<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SURPRISE: SALMON LOVES HITTING IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Tex. _ Tim Salmon has no explanation for it, nor does
he care to have one. But Salmon, whether he's in a slump or not,
kills the Rangers in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   No opposing player in the majors has a higher batting average
(.432) or more RBI (43) at The Ballpark in Arlington than the
Anaheim Angels' Salmon. He entered the series slumping but went 6
for 13 with three homers and seven RBI in the three games,
including a three-run homer Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to Texas for the series, Salmon said he was
looking for something . . . anything . . . to get him going. Was
this it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope,'' said Salmon, who is now hitting .269 with 21 homers
and 57 RBI. ``I'm looking for anything to give me some confidence.
. . . I don't really have an answer for it (his success in Texas).
All I can think of is that this ballpark has one of the best
hitter's backgrounds. You see the ball well here. Also, the
matchups. Guys I face here, I see them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, though, doesn't like to talk much about his success in
Texas. He doesn't want to jinx himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's like, 'Why bring it up?' '' he said. ``It's like
when a guy has a no-hitter going. You don't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Record tied: Third baseman Troy Glaus homered in his first
at-bat Wednesday, his team-leading 30th of the season, which tied
Doug DeCinces' 1982 mark for single-season homers by an Angels
third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the homer, Glaus has struggled this month. He is hitting
only .188 (15 for 80) in July, and just .095 (2 for 21) on the road
trip, his season average dipping to .278.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia said some might have become spoiled by
Glaus' hot start and expected too much. Glaus himself might be one
who expected too much, as he often slams his helmet and bat after a
strikeout or missed opportunity. But Scioscia said he doesn't think
Glaus is putting any undue pressure on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's anything inside of Troy other than the
natural disappointment of not coming through in situations,''
Scioscia said. ``I don't think he's reached a level of frustration
to become concerned about. He's able to turn the page. It's why I
have the utmost confidence he'll be a key part of our run in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia added that he doesn't think pitchers are pitching Glaus
much differently than early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think he's getting pitches to hit,'' he said. ``Some
he's missed. We're not trying to reinvent the wheel here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
