r s BC-RAC-DELMAR-LADN-(SLAN     07-27 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DELMAR-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS READY FOR COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ Hall of Fame jockey Gary Stevens said
Wednesday morning he hoped to announce ``in the next 24 hours''
that he is coming out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who limped away from his career seven months ago at
Santa Anita, citing the pain in his arthritic right knee, had
declined recently to discuss indications he is preparing for a
comeback. But a few hours before Del Mar opened its 61st summer
season, Stevens sat on a bench outside the backstretch racing
office and spoke as if the decision to return to the saddle is all
but final.
</P>
<P>
   Before making it official, he said, he wants to put the knee
through some final rigorous tests in morning workouts. He has been
working out horses for several top trainers for about two months,
and said he took a leave from his job as assistant to Thoroughbred
Corp. trainer Alex Hassinger last weekend to concentrate on riding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly up to me,'' Stevens said. ``I want to make sure
_ 100 percent sure _ the knee is going to hold up to race riding.''
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't want to do is launch a comeback only to call it
off after a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are going to be skeptics,'' he said. ``I want the
fans to know they're going to get their money's worth when I go out
there. I want to be 110 percent (healthy).''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said he is generally fit, weighing 115 or 116 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 37 years old, and with the exception of the knee, I'm in
perfectly good health,'' he said. ``I'm going to have to change my
routine a little bit (if he returns to riding). There's going to
have to be a break in the middle of the year. Everybody needs a
break anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell people I'm cured of arthritis. It's
still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said the availability of insurance is not a factor in
his decision, as has been speculated.
</P>
<P>
   The three-time Kentucky Derby winner, elected to the Racing Hall
of Fame in 1997, has made no secret of his struggle to cope with
the premature end of his 20-year riding career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably took three months to where I accepted the
situation that I had a new future,'' said Stevens, who announced
his retirement abruptly in the middle of Santa Anita's opening-day
card Dec. 26, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had accepted it was over with. But then I noticed that doing
little menial things around the house, it wasn't having the same
(painful) effect as the last couple years. My ears perked up and I
thought, 'There's something going on here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that if I could return to riding even at the same level
I was at the last couple of years, it would be a waste for me to be
sitting around at age 37.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who visited specialists last winter in hopes of finding
a remedy for his pain, said he thinks the knee has simply improved
with rest. Sitting on the bench Wednesday, he demonstrated he can
flex the knee fully, placing his right foot on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   He has had his name, and that of agent Harry Hacek, listed in
the first Del Mar condition book of the meet. He said he worked
five horses Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens wouldn't say when he might appear in a race. He has a
personal commitment out of town this weekend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, in the next 24 hours I'll have something to say,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar's 43-day season began under an increasingly overcast
coastal sky with Corey Nakatani riding three winners and Bob
Baffert saddling three in front of a bigger-than-expected crowd of
31,494. Baffert is shooting for his fourth consecutive Del Mar
training title.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert won the last three races, including the $86,400 second
division of the Oceanside Stakes ($14.60) for 3-year-olds with
California-bred Stormy Jack and jockey Victor Espinoza.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and Nakatani teamed up with Flame Thrower to win the
afternoon's closely watched 2-year-old maiden race over High Tech
Exec and Godolphin Racing-owned Matta.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the faster, $86,900 first division of the Oceanside, a
1- mile turf race, went to favored Duke of Green ($5) and Chris
McCarron. Ron McAnally saddled the winner for owners Bob and
Beverly Lewis, who have given five horses to the Hall of Fame
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Duke of Green ran like a 2-3 shot should. That _ 2-3 _ is how
his odds appeared on the Del Mar tote board that showed signs of
dyslexia all day.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the only problem with the tote board: Its new beige
background made the numbers hard to read, and the installation of a
video screen left fans near the finish line without a payoffs
display.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was the third-largest in the history of the San Diego
County track founded by Bing Crosby and Pat O'Brien in 1937. It
trailed the 44,181 who watched Dare and Go end Cigar's winning
streak at 16 in 1996, and the 34,697 who responded to a hats
giveaway on opening day in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
