<SLUG> BC-UTIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILICORP UNITED ONE STEP CLOSER TO ACQUIRING TWO UTILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ UtiliCorp United Inc. cleared a huge hurdle in its
bid to buy two regional utilities Wednesday when it got the green
light from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission to move ahead
with the acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted unanimously to allow UtiliCorp to move
ahead on its bids to buy Empire District Electric Co. for about
$800 million in stock, cash and assumed debt, and St. Joseph Light
&AMP; Power Co. for about $190 million.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said UtiliCorp must submit a revised competitive
analysis six months before joint operations can begin.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp still must gain regulatory approval from the
Securities and Exchange Commission, the Federal Trade Commission
and Missouri utility regulators for both acquisitions. Also, the
Empire acquisition will require approval from utility regulators in
Oklahoma, Arkansas and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Empire, based in Joplin, Mo., sells electric power to about
145,000 customers in Missouri, Kansas, Arkansas and Oklahoma. St.
Joseph Light &AMP; Power, based in St. Joseph, sells electric service
to about 66,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   Once UtiliCorp completes the mergers, it will have about 460,000
electric customers and gas customers.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp spokesman George Minter said the company hopes to
complete both acquisitions by the end of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
