r f BC-STAFF-KAN &LR;      07-27 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLEST WAY OFTEN IS THE BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ Pretend you just went the extra mile at work. It'd
be nice if someone noticed, you mutter to your bedroom ceiling at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Then, what's this? The next day at work your boss walks up and _
pick one:
</P>
<P>
   Hands you a check for $100.
</P>
<P>
   Tells you to take tomorrow off.
</P>
<P>
   Leads a kazoo chorus of co-workers humming ``For He's a Jolly
Good Fellow'' and leaves a balloon bouquet at your desk.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly slips you a handwritten thank-you note.
</P>
<P>
   Enters your name in the company's monthly drawing for a
Caribbean cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Gives you a $100 gift certificate to spend at the regional
shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Proclaims over the loudspeaker that it's Your Day and gives you
a nice golf shirt with the company logo discreetly embroidered on
the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Which would you prefer?
</P>
<P>
   Survey after workplace survey finds different preferences among
employees. Some, often because of cultural differences or just
plain shyness, would rather sink through the floor than be publicly
recognized. For others, moments of public recognition become the
highlights of their work lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers crave a freebie day off. Others moan that they'd
just go home and catch up on housework and lawn mowing _ and what
kind of a reward is that?
</P>
<P>
   Some would grab the $100 and enjoy a surprise shopping spree for
something special. Others say a cash prize is here today and gone
tomorrow in the bill-paying rush, and there's no lasting memory of
the job well done.
</P>
<P>
   Some wouldn't mind taking the chance for delayed gratification
on a company-sponsored cruise. Others think that it falls short if
the reward isn't here and now, especially if there's a chance
they'll never get it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Some like company merchandise because of the camaraderie it
fosters. Others would rather pass on the logo stuff for a lot of
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One reward that doesn't always show up on incentive preference
surveys _ possibly because many of the surveys are sponsored by
companies that have some /{thing/} to sell _ is the handwritten
thank-you note. But rewards and recognition gurus say it's the best
thank-you tool there is.
</P>
<P>
   There's an old saw on the management training and motivational
circuit that says employees join companies but leave managers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if workers don't feel appreciated by the people
they report to, they're unhappy and likely to leave (or, at the
very least, spend a lot of time grousing).
</P>
<P>
   A simple thank-you note from the boss (or bosses) is, time and
again, the most appreciated reward. Simple, yet in some ways the
hardest thing to get on the laundry list of possible rewards. A lot
of bosses can't and won't take the time.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that some workers couldn't care less about a
thank-you note from their managers. So how does anyone know what
the right, best reward is?
</P>
<P>
   There's another old saw on the management training and
motivational circuit that says if you want to know what your
employees want, all you have to do is ask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0007 </DOCNO>
