<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SCOTUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT: SUPREME COURT SHOULDN'T REVIEW CASE  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft asked the U.S. Supreme Court Wednesday to step aside
and let an appellate court that once ruled in its favor hear its
appeal of a court-ordered breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief filed with the high court, the world's No. 1 software
maker said the ``morass'' of factual, legal and procedural issues
in the case necessitate a review by the Washington, D.C., Circuit
Court of Appeals, rather than the Supreme Court, which usually does
not like to delve into factual analysis of any given case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case in which the court should exercise its
discretion to hear a direct appeal, thereby undertaking the onerous
task of sifting through a large and complex record and forgoing the
many benefits of intermediate appellate review,'' the brief said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company's appeal of a federal judge's breakup order
normally would proceed to the appellate court, the Department of
Justice and 19 states that sued the company for violations of the
Sherman Antitrust Act are employing a rarely used 1974 law that
allows cases of national importance to skip that step.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the measure would expedite the process, but
most legal scholars believe the government is trying to leapfrog a
court potentially friendly to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, a panel of three judges from the federal appellate
court in Washington overturned Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
order that had required Microsoft to give computer manufacturers
the option of installing a version of the company's Windows
operating system stripped of its Internet Explorer Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said its response to Wednesday's brief
will be contained in its filing, which is not due until August 15.
The Supreme Court could decide whether or not to take the case as
early as September.
</P>
<P>
   The round of legal filings is the latest in a pitched, two-year
battle between Microsoft and the federal government, which accused
Microsoft of using its monopoly in the operating systems market to
crush its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, Jackson ordered the company carved in two.
</P>
<P>
   The order also called for curbs on the company's business
practices and required the company to reveal parts of the Windows
``source code.''
</P>
<P>
   In its brief, Microsoft insists Jackson made numerous errors in
the case and said it would be proper for the appellate court to
hear it first.
</P>
<P>
   And the appeals court appears eager to comply. Less than an hour
after Microsoft filed its notice of appeal, the court said seven
jurists would immediately hear the case, rather than the
traditional three-member review panel.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies Microsoft's biggest advantage, said one lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court doesn't usually explore the nitty gritty
aspects of the cases it hears. Since the appellate court does, and
has experience with Microsoft, some believe the justices will defer
on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing scares the Supreme Court more than factual analysis,''
said Chicago antitrust lawyer Hillard Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   One of the weaker arguments contained in Microsoft's brief,
according to another lawyer, centers on Jackson's behavior outside
the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Several times within the 30-page filing, Microsoft cited
Jackson's interviews with the media as an example of one of the
many issues it would explore in its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In a Wall Street Journal article, Jackson explained why he
didn't allow for more than one day of hearings on the breakup plan:
``(I)t is procedurally unusual to do what Microsoft is proposing _
are you aware of very many cases in which the defendant can argue
with the jury about what an appropriate sanction should be? Were
the Japanese allowed to propose the terms of their surrender? The
government won the case.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Microsoft's brief, ``the district court's blunt
comments to the press raise serious questions about its
impartiality and betray a misguided belief that apellees were
entitled to the remedy of their choice, no matter how extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Silicon Valley antitrust lawyer Rich Gray said
attacking Jackson may backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Supreme Court agrees with Microsoft (about Jackson's
behavior), they might want to take the case immediately,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
