A4292 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OBSERVE-DEATHPENALTY-     07-27 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBSERVE-DEATHPENALTY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES CALIFORNIA PRESS, PUBLIC ENTITLED TO WITNESS
ALL  STAGES OF LETHAL INJECTION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BILL WALLACE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a victory for the media, a federal judge has ruled that the
press and public in California are entitled to witness the entire
process of executing a condemned inmate by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling filed Friday and made public Wednesday, District
Court Judge Vaughn Walker issued an injunction that effectively
forces the state Department of Corrections to allow public
witnesses to watch from the time the injection equipment is
attached to the inmate until a doctor pronounces death.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said prison officials had exaggerated potential security
problems when they adopted regulations to keep curtains drawn while
an inmate is being prepared and the needle inserted.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Terhune, director of the California Department of
Corrections, could not be reached last night for comment on
Walker's ruling, and the department issued no official statement
about the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The California First Amendment Coalition, which, along with the
Society of Professional Journalists, sued the department over its
restrictive regulation, called the judge's decision ``gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very good news,'' said Terry Francke, general
counsel for the coalition, a Sacramento-based nonprofit that
monitors governmental incursions on freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that Judge Walker not only responded to the
arguments that our attorneys made, but even took them a step
further ... by finding that there is an affirmative constitutional
interest in having the media able to view an entire execution as
witnesses on behalf of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Schlosser, an attorney for the American Civil Liberties
Union who argued against the prison department's rules during the
trial before Walker, also hailed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Walker not only found that the department had
exaggerated the potential security risks involved in allowing the
injection procedure to be witnessed, but that one of the
department's motivations was its concern that the public might have
an adverse reaction to the use of violent force to restrain an
inmate for injection,'' Schlosser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ruled, in essence, that part of the reason for the
regulation was nothing but censorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's ruling came in response to a lawsuit filed after prison
officials instituted their restrictive regulation before the
execution of ``Freeway Killer'' William Bonin in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The rule _ Regulation 770, as it is known _ allowed prison
staffers to strap Bonin to a gurney and begin the flow of lethal
drugs before they opened a curtain that allowed him to be seen by
the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials justified the restriction by saying that media
descriptions of the beginning of the executions would make it
possible for other prisoners to identify and retaliate against
prison staffers involved in the preparations.
</P>
<P>
   The Society of Professional Journalists sued, arguing that the
rule was unconstitutional, as it prevented the press, acting as a
surrogate for the general public, from witnessing the entirety of
the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Walker issued a summary judgment for the society in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His original ruling was overturned after the department appealed
to the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco. In
reversing Walker, the appellate court found that prison officials'
security needs outweighed the First Amendment right of public
access.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment Coalition joined with the society in asking
the Ninth Circuit for a rehearing of the case. After reviewing its
earlier findings, the appellate panel sent the case back to Walker
for trial on the narrow issue of whether the Department of
Corrections had accurately portrayed the security risks.
</P>
<P>
   In the ruling, Walker concluded the department had clearly
overstated the risks in order to justify barring press access to
executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ensuring staff safety is a legitimate safety concern,'' Walker
wrote in his opinion, ``(but) execution team members' identities
have not in the past ever been revealed by the media, nor have
there been any acts of retaliation or threats against any execution
workers. ... The court concludes that defendants' practice of
limiting witness observation during lethal injection executions is
an exaggerated response to defendants' security concerns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
