<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOUSE OKS CONTINUED FUNDS FOR AIDS CARE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted unanimously Wednesday to renew the
Ryan White Comprehensive AIDS Resources Emergency (CARE) Act,
including a funding formula change that promises to reduce San
Francisco's share of the $1.6 billion now spent on the program.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, co-sponsored by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., and Rep.
Henry Waxman, D-Los Angeles, calls for a gradual shift over five
years to focus on HIV infections rather than full-blown AIDS cases.
The bill also would change the funding formula in an attempt to
shift funds to areas where the disease is rising. The current AIDS
CARE act will expire on September 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also passed, by unanimous consent, legislation that
would increase spending to combat international AIDS and
tuberculosis epidemics. It was sponsored by Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current Ryan White formula, San Francisco receives
approximately twice as much money per AIDS case, roughly $5,000 a
year, as other cities, including Oakland, even as the path of the
epidemic has spread across the country and shifted to heterosexual
demographic groups, particularly women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS groups in San Francisco warned that the formula shift could
slash San Francisco's Ryan White funds by as much as 25 percent in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., voted for the overall bill, but
strongly objected to the formula change.
</P>
<P>
   ``As advocates for people living with the disease, we should be
emphasizing that the solution to the continuing AIDS crisis is to
increase overall funding rather than to redistribute existing
dollars,'' Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn predicted that rapidly rising federal funding for the
Ryan White money that goes to cities _ which has increased by an
annual average rate of 24 percent since 1991 _ will continue, so
that San Francisco could wind up with no absolute cut in funds,
even as its share of the total falls.
</P>
<P>
   Local AIDS groups sharply disagreed, saying funding would have
to double over the next five years for San Francisco to stay even.
</P>
<P>
   Many AIDS activists applauded some of the changes in the House
bill, particularly the focus on tracking HIV rather than AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Dison, spokesman for AIDS Action, said his group's policy
committee ``said some years ago that we want to see a shift to HIV
data rather than AIDS data.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Driscoll, national AIDS policy adviser for the Log Cabin
Republicans, a gay group, said the House measure would ``upgrade
prevention, improve accountability and attempts to make Ryan White
programs more responsive to minorities and women as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll said that when the Ryan White law was enacted a decade
ago, San Francisco was the center of the AIDS epidemic, so the law
``was written in a way that was very favorable to San Francisco.
That becomes very difficult to maintain as a broader and broader
constituency nationally has to be served by the program.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version of the bill contains a smaller formula change
that would have less of an effect on San Francisco's funding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4294 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CONVENTIONS-STAKES-SF     07-27 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-STAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THRILL IS GONE, YET CONVENTIONS CARRY ON  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a time, not so many years ago, when
political nominating conventions could be thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Democrats meeting in Chicago went to a third ballot
before settling on Adlai Stevenson as their nominee. In 1968,
Hubert Humphrey captured the nomination in the same city without
having entered a primary. In 1988, Vice President George Bush
stunned delegates in New Orleans with his mid-convention selection
of Dan Quayle as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, as Republicans meet in Philadelphia, the biggest
uncertainty is whether Monday Night Football's 49ers-Patriots
exhibition game will end in time for retired Gen. Colin Powell's
opening night address.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned suspense that once made the conventions a
rewarding _ if not riveting _ summertime tradition is now gone. But
the stakes are no different for George W. Bush in Philadelphia, or
Al Gore in Los Angeles two weeks later, than they were for
Stevenson, Humphrey or Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   To have a shot at becoming president, the candidates still must
rally their party's faithful and capture the imagination of the
nation during a fleeting moment when it is paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, that means taking command of his father's party and
displaying the substance behind his rallying cry of ``compassionate
conservatism.'' For Gore, it means unifying the pro-trade and
pro-labor wings of his party and stepping out from the shadow of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For both parties, it is the single best time _ even if voters
only catch snatches of headlines or glimpses in between turning
channels _ to show off their candidates and define what they stand
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions provide a focal point for the campaign,'' said
Allan Lichtman, professor of political history at American
University in Washington, D.C. ``It awakens people to the fact that
there is a campaign going on _ and it may be the candidate's last
free shot to define himself.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a task made more challenging by the lack of drama and the
growing apathy of the viewing public. Convention planners find
themselves in a Catch-22; the more they package their events for
television, the less spontaneous they become, and the less TV is
interested in covering them.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that a political version of ``Survivor,'' where
candidates are left on a rat-infested island and voted off one by
one, or a return to the old days of discord and uncertainty, would
draw higher ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does anyone dispute that the modern system of primaries and
caucuses _ which relegate the conventions to a ceremonial role of
rubber-stamping the voters' choices _ produce a more democratic
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The most anticipated moment will come on the final nights, when
Bush and Gore deliver their acceptance speeches. Each of the major
networks, reluctant to give up more than an hour of prime time
during the previous three nights, is committed to showing the
speeches in their entirety, making them almost certainly the most
widely viewed addresses of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches are generally months in the making, and often leave
lasting impressions.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1992 that Clinton defined his modern populism,
concluding his speech by saying he ``still believes in a place
called Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Bush's father gave a speech that most acknowledge as
the turning point in his crusade to be seen as more than President
Ronald Reagan's vice president, in which he declared that the
nation needed someone experienced and able in the Oval Office, then
thundered: ``I am that man.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1964 acceptance speech given by Barry Goldwater at the GOP
convention in the Cow Palace included his most memorable line:
``Extremism in defense of liberty is no vice. Moderation in the
pursuit of justice is no virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties will do what they can to lure viewers for the first
three nights. In 1996, Democrats scheduled a prime time speech by
paralyzed actor Christopher Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   This Republicans are looking to accommodate shorter attention
spans, replacing many speeches with fast-paced video clips, live
bands and an array of nonpolitical speakers ranging from breast
cancer survivors to a blind mountain climber. Prime-time speaking
slots will go only to top names such as Arizona Sen. John McCain
and Powell.
</P>
<P>
   GOP convention planners have given each night a theme aimed at
promoting Bush. But the titles ``Opportunity with a Purpose: Leave
no Child Behind,'' and ``Strength and Security with a Purpose: Safe
in our Homes and in the World,'' among others, will probably do
little to interest viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, if you want the most exciting conventions, those
days have passed us by,'' said Leslie Goodman, a spokeswoman for
the GOP affair. ``The idea is to share our energy and enthusiasm,
and to try to energize the grassroots.''
</P>
<P>
   The aura of excitement that once surrounded conventions has
diminished every four years since 1972, when primaries and caucuses
replaced party bosses and backroom maneuvering as the way nominees
got elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an age of action and drama, and there is precious little
action and drama,'' Lichtman said. ``TV stations are less
interested in crafted events.''
</P>
<P>
   From a high of 50 hours of coverage in the 1952 conventions _
the first covered by television _ networks are scaling back to
about an hour per night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my work cut out for me,'' said J.C. Watts, the
Republican representative from Oklahoma who once enjoyed millions
of followers during his career as a quarterback at Oklahoma
University and in Canada, but now will be lucky to be seen during
the halftime of Monday night's NFL exhibition opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in San Francisco and you want to see a `Seinfeld'
rerun or Andy Griffith, or J.C. Watts emceeing the opening night of
the GOP convention, it's probably not close,'' Watts said. ``Hey,
if I wasn't in Philadelphia, I'd probably be watching Andy
Griffith.''
</P>
<P>
   The army of journalists at next week's convention _ there will
be more than seven for each of the GOP's 2,066 delegates _ make it
inevitable that at least some of the party's message gets out.
</P>
<P>
   But what if they threw a convention and no one watched?
</P>
<P>
   The surprising answer is that the speeches would still be
delivered, the delegates would still hoot and holler, and the
balloons would still drop from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious attempts by both parties to brainwash the
public into supporting their candidate, the quadrennial affairs are
also intended to fire up their own loyalists. ``There is an
audience that you absolutely must reach, and those are the members
of the party,'' said California Sen. Barbara Boxer, who along with
Sen. Dianne Feinstein has been named co-chair of the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions rev up the grassroots,'' she said. ``They fire up
the people who are already paying attention and signal the
beginning of the campaign to everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most faithful cable-television devotees will only catch
a small glimpse of the politicking, caucusing, schmoozing and
partying that goes on in Philadelphia and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Most state delegations will hold daily meetings to discuss party
business, debate disagreements and hear from rising party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conventions offer a way to solidify support behind the nominee
and hopefully emerge as a unified party,'' said Gerry Parsky, chair
of the California delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Solidifying our Republican base is important,'' Parsky said.
``One way to do it is to gather all supporters and the nominee
together. If we leave the convention energized, we return to
California with enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez Democrat Tim Farley, who has been a delegate to three
conventions, said the events ``may not be thrilling like they used
to be, but they energize the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Farley remembers no one seemed to be paying attention to the
1992 election before the Democrats met in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speeches were made, the balloons came down, and everyone
went home believing we have a purpose,'' Farley said. ``And
suddenly Clinton/Gore buttons started popping up on people in the
supermarket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
