<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-BREAKOUT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE ATTEMPT BREAKOUT AT SAN QUENTIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANGELICA PENCE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN QUENTIN _ Three Death Row inmates broke through a chain link
fence at San Quentin Prison last week and threatened several guards
before they were subdued, an incident that correctional officers
said poses serious safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   The guards, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
deteriorating security at San Quentin has put their lives in
danger, and they accused state corrections officials of doing
little about it.
</P>
<P>
   San Quentin officials briefly discussed the incident only after
being contacted by The Chronicle and, even then, played it down.
</P>
<P>
   At San Quentin, spokeswoman Patricia Blanson said the prison is
not classifying it as an escape attempt and said it was not deemed
worthy of publicizing after it happened.
</P>
<P>
   However, several San Quentin guards interviewed by The
Chronicle, along with a representative of the powerful California
Correctional Peace Officers Association, said the July 18 incident
was the most serious of its kind since so-called ``Soledad
Brother'' George Jackson's fatal attempt to flee the prison in
August 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, six inmates were eventually tried for killing
three guards. Last week's incident happened in the same part of the
prison as the 1971 escape attempt involving Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Even though last week's prisoners were eventually subdued, the
incident highlighted guards' growing complaints that the state
Department of Corrections is failing to give them the kind of
security they say they need in dealing with an increasingly violent
criminal population.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one just came too close,'' one San Quentin guard said of
the midday incident. ``It's got us all shook up. We have serious
security problems here, and they're just not being addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the time, our officers labor under a correctional
management oppression rather than support,'' said Jeffrey Thompson,
a lobbyist for the Peace Officers Association. ``If you ask
soldiers to volunteer for the war, you don't ignore their needs for
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sacramento, Department of Corrections spokeswoman Margot Bach
said she could not comment on the incident or on the union's
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Much of last week's escape attempt was detailed in a two-page
Department of Corrections incident report, a copy of which was
obtained by The Chronicle. Blanson confirmed the existence of the
report, but did not offer any more details than it contained.
</P>
<P>
   The incident happened shortly after noon on July 18, when a
group of condemned inmates, identified as gang members, unraveled a
four-foot section of a chain link fence along the so-called ``Crip
Yard,'' an exercise yard named for the prison gang. It is located
near the Adjustment Center, which houses more than 100 of the
prison's most dangerous and criminals.
</P>
<P>
   An officer named D. Cordona noticed the gash in the fence around
12:30 p.m., according to the prison report. The opening gave the
inmates access to a walkway guards use to escort handcuffed inmates
to and from the Adjustment Center, correctional sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Frank Cerecedes immediately ordered Cordona to sound the
portable alarm guards carry for just this purpose, summoning about
60 officers from throughout the prison. But those officers were far
away.
</P>
<P>
   A second guard, Sgt. Ken McLean, grabbed a 37mm gun that fires
wooden blocks, each one about 1.5 inches thick. He aimed it at the
inmates from a nearby building, Blanson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lt. Cerecedes ran to the back door of the unit,'' the report
said, while McLean, his stun gun at the ready, ``took a defensive
stance.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerecedes then ordered that part of the prison locked down,
trapping the inmates inside the walkway and away from most of the
prison staff. But it was still not over.
</P>
<P>
   To the guards' astonishment, the three inmates _ convicted
murderers Paul Tuilaepa, Tiequon Cox and Noel Jackson all cq &LR; _
rushed through the hole in the fence, several feet away from them
and lunged toward Officer Marcie Mann and Officer W. Whitlow.
</P>
<P>
   While Tuilaepa closed in on Mann, McLean fired a volley of
wooden bullets and hit him in the left shoulder blade. The
remaining inmates stumbled over Tuilaepa, who had collapsed
facedown on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lt. Cerecedes and Sgt. McLean shouted commands for the ...
inmates to remain on the ground,'' the report said, ``and for the
inmates to back up to the breach in the fence line and return back
onto Yard No. 3, where they could be secured and observed in a
controlled area.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one was killed in last week's near break,
correctional officers said in interviews that waning safety
standards, budget constraints and fear of lawsuits are endangering
the lives of the more than 1,500 correctional officers, support
staff and volunteers who work at the infamous Northern California
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of thing shouldn't be happening,'' said the officer.
The inmates ``came very, very close to holding one of us hostage.
They're condemned men. They have zero to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers said the incident probably could have been avoided if
the damaged fence had been replaced _ something San Quentin
corrections officers say they have repeatedly requested. Workers
were called out to San Quentin this week to measure for a new fence
only after the escape attempt, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Blanson said late Wednesday that San Quentin's warden was
notified of the staff's requests to fix the aging fence and had
just received funding approval from Sacramento to make the repairs
when the incident took place.
</P>
<P>
   And late Wednesday, Blanson confirmed that there had been a
recent escape attempt by two Russian prisoners who were caught by
guards. The inmates were carrying a map of the Bay Area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
