<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY SHAW WANTS JOB BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ There's been no declaration, but after his sixth
scoreless appearance since returning from the disabled list Jeff
Shaw said he should be the closer of the Los Angeles Dodgers again.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he's pitching as he did in his most successful years,
and the shoulder weakness and elbow tendinitis that plagued him
during his rocky spell are no longer concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he's gained confidence after throwing 1 innings for a
save July 17 against Pittsburgh, recording the save in a 5-4 win
Friday against San Francisco and with the save in Tuesday's 6-4 win
against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's enough to say that I'm throwing the ball well
enough to earn my job back,'' said Shaw, who has 148 career saves.
``It's not like I've been a closer only for a couple of years. I've
been doing this for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson has gone with a
closer-by-committee system since late May, when Shaw was at the
height of his difficulties and the low point of his health. He went
on the disabled list June 28 and was activated after the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Shaw has three saves and Mike Fetters has two saves.
Shaw has allowed four hits in 5 innings and hasn't yielded a run.
Fetters has allowed three hits in five innings with yielding a run.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hasn't said either way if Shaw has his closer's role
back or if he'll go with a combination of Shaw and Fetters. But
he's maintained all along the Dodgers need Shaw to return to form
if they're going to remain in playoff contention. Shaw blew seven
of his first 19 saves chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of a weak shoulder, a bad elbow that time
was giving me a lack of command,'' Shaw said. ``It all goes back to
having arm strength, confidence and being out there on a regular
basis. I've told (Johnson) to just use me. (Reds manager) Jack
(McKeon) did the same thing. Jack would use me and use me and use
me until I told him, `That's enough, I can't do it any more.'
Davey's been very good about giving me time off. I told him I feel
better when I pitch more.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Being Curt: The long-term ramifications of the Arizona
Diamondbacks trading for right-hander Curt Schilling could be
catastrophic to the Dodgers' playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't over yet,'' Johnson said. ``I know it's a good move
for them. Schilling is starting to throw the ball like he did
(before the surgery).''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers should benefit from the trade in the short term.
Schilling, regaining his form after missing the first few months of
the season because of shoulder surgery, was supposed to start when
the Dodgers opened a three-game series in Philadelphia. Instead, it
will be lefty Omar Daal, one of the four players the Phillies
acquired for Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Daal is 2-10 with a 7.22 ERA and was bumped out of the
Diamondbacks rotation. He hasn't started since July 2. Daal's last
three appearances were in relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
