<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-TE     07-27 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATALANOTTO'S PINCH HIT, GREER'S RBI SAVE DAY FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ From the dugout, Frank Catalanotto watches
the game like a manager, anticipating his chance.
</P>
<P>
   Innings pass, pitchers come and go, the lineups turn over.
Catalanotto thinks ahead, two or three moves ahead, because to him,
there's no such thing as going to the plate without a plan _
especially when you're a pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Called on again in that role last night, the Rangers' reserve
second baseman tripled with one out in the ninth inning and scored
on Rusty Greer's two-out single to left as Texas defeated Anaheim,
6-5, at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The victory didn't do much for the Rangers' position in the
American League West, as they remain 101/2 games out of first place
and don't play another AL West game until September. But it
bolstered Catalanotto's pinch-hit reputation.
</P>
<P>
   He's 9-for-20 as a pinch hitter this season and is hitting .380
overall. Rangers manager Johnny Oates said a strong mind and a
short swing help account for Catalanotto's pinch-hitting success,
but Catalanotto said that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've done my whole career is watch the game like I'm a
big part of it,'' he said. ``The veterans I've been around have
always told me to think about a game, figure out where you might
fit in, look ahead and just be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, with the Rangers trying to avoid extra innings
after the Angels' one-run rally in the top of the frame against
closer John Wetteland, Oates was prepared, too. He didn't hesitate
to send Catalanotto to the plate for Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Facing reliever Al Levine, Catalanotto followed his plan. He
swung at the first strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing about pinch hitting is being prepared and
studying the pitcher, knowing what pitch he may feature,''
Catalanotto said. ``What I like to do in those situations is swing
at the first strike. He threw a slider; it didn't break much, and I
was able to catch up to it and drive it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer's game-winning hit made a winner of Wetteland, who gave up
the tying run in the top of the ninth as Orlando Palmeiro singled,
stole second, moved to third on a groundout and scored on pinch
hitter Chris Spiezio's single to center.
</P>
<P>
   The blown save cost Matt Perisho his first victory as a starter
this season. The left-hander, who allowed four hits in six innings
and absorbed Tim Salmon's three-run homer in the sixth, hasn't won
since a June 4 relief appearance against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   His performance was clearly better than his last start, a
one-third-inning outing in which he gave up seven runs. But last
night's start and the one against Arizona each featured an inning
loaded with walks. Against Arizona, it was three in the first
inning. Last night, it was two to lead off the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was much like what we've seen overall, but we're looking
for consistency,'' Oates said. ``Right now, he's walking too many
people. The other night against Arizona, he gave up three hits off
the end of the bat. That happens. What hurt him was that he gave up
three walks in the inning, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon followed the sixth-inning walks with a home run, bringing
the Angels within 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Then Perisho reappeared. He struck out Garret Anderson and Troy
Glaus swinging, and retired Matt Walbeck on an easy grounder to
short.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored three times with no outs in the fourth inning
to take a 5-1 lead. The lineup immediately behind the cleanup spot
produced the inning.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 hitter Chad Curtis doubled, Gabe Kapler looped a single
over third, and Bill Haselman followed with a run-scoring double
that sent Kapler to third. With Mike Lamb at the plate, Scott
Schoeneweis threw a wild pitch that scored Kapler. Luis Alicea's
two-out single scored Haselman.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored first, taking a 1-0 lead on Troy Glaus'
420-foot solo home run in the second inning. But Perisho settled
in, retiring 11 of the next 14 batters before the troublesome
sixth. In that stretch from the second inning to the sixth, he
induced four fly balls, two pop-ups and a double play that stunted
a first-and-second, no-out opportunity in the fourth. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
