<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL AT FINISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Anaheim Angels returned home late
Wednesday night, down but not out. Their 6-5 loss to the Texas
Rangers before 27,858 at The Ballpark in Arlington completed a road
trip that began in Oakland and ended with four losses in six games.
</P>
<P>
   They began the trip four games behind first-place Seattle and
returned five out. They are only two games behind Oakland in the
wild-card race. They lost Wednesday on Rusty Greer's two-out RBI
single in the ninth off Angels reliever Al Levine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we played good baseball, but you don't get points for
being in the game,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We've
played a lot of close ballgames and won more than our share all
year. But the ball didn't bounce our way in this series or in
Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got Troy Glaus' 30th home run of the season and a
three-run homer from Tim Salmon (No. 21). But the homers were all
but forgotten by the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the ninth featured the Angels using their five-man
infield for the sixth time this year. It has become more common
lately, as they've used it four times since the All-Star break,
including twice in the last three nights against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had tied the game at 5 in the ninth on Scott
Spiezio's pinch RBI single off Rangers closer John Wetteland but
found themselves on the brink of defeat after Rangers pinch-hitter
Frank Catalanotto tripled with one out in the bottom of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Darin Erstad has been used as the fifth infielder
in the previous games, but Wednesday he was the DH. So Scioscia
brought in center fielder Garret Anderson and put him at first
base. Anderson played first in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Mo Vaughn borrowed Scott Spiezio's infield glove
and moved to the second-base spot, and the Angels were set to pitch
to Luis Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told O (left fielder Orlando Palmeiro) to tell (Scioscia) he
played second base in the minor leagues,'' Salmon said. ``I
wouldn't go in (to play infield). I've lost too many teeth
already.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro found the ball anyway, as Alicea hit a blooper to
shallow left that Palmeiro caught charging toward the infield,
giving Catalanotto no chance to tag and score. With two outs,
Anderson returned to center, Vaughn to first and the Angels were
almost out of it.
</P>
<P>
   But Greer spoiled the Angels' plans by slapping a 3-1 pitch from
Levine the other way to left to drive in Catalanotto for a Rangers
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six times the Angels have used the five-man infield,
they've recorded the important second out four times. But only once
did they get the third out. That was Monday, when they went on to
win the game in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the other games, they lost to the Dodgers on Jim Leyritz's
two-out RBI single, to the Padres on Eric Owens' two-out bunt that
Levine booted for an error, and on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your backs are against the wall,'' Scioscia said of getting
the second out. ``But it's third-down-and-goal, not
fourth-down-and-goal. You've got to get the last out. We did it
earlier in the series, but tonight we couldn't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels might have felt fortunate to be in that position at
all, since they fell behind early for the second night in a row.
Scott Schoeneweis was making his first start for the Angels since
June 16, when he went to the disabled list with a strained rib-cage
muscle.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared a little rusty, but he managed to go seven innings,
allowing five runs and 10 hits. He gave up a two-run homer to Gabe
Kapler in the second inning but wasn't bothered by that.
</P>
<P>
   What bothered him were the bloops and bleeders in the fourth
inning that led to three Texas runs. Kapler had a blooper just over
the infield dirt behind third for a key hit in the inning, and
Alicea had a swinging bunt that rolled up the third-base line for
an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Haselman doubled in a run in the inning and another run
scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I gave up five runs, it wasn't a loud five runs,''
Schoeneweis said.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis is a ground-ball pitcher who relies on his defense.
But sometimes the balls find holes and Schoeneweis is left
scrambling to keep the team in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like hit or miss for me,'' he said. ``Whether (the balls)
go to people or not, I look at the chart and see I got 18 ground
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Matt Perisho, a former Angel and a teammate of
Schoeneweis' at Double-A Midland a few years ago, held the Angels
to one run on three hits through the first five innings, but in the
sixth he lost the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   He walked Kevin Stocker and Vaughn to begin the inning. He was
behind in the count, 3-1, to Salmon when Salmon hit his three-run
homer to put the Angels back in it at 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   It remained that way until the ninth when the Rangers brought in
closer Wetteland. It was the fourth consecutive game Wetteland
appeared in, marking the second time this season and the fifth time
in his career Wetteland has pitched in four straight games.
</P>
</TEXT>
