<SLUG> BC-BBN-TRADE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS REACQUIRE VALDES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ If the Los Angeles Dodgers can fire the team president
and rehire him two months later _ a la Bob Graziano last fall _
reacquiring a pitcher the organization spent a year bad-mouthing
for a playoff push is doable.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers answered Arizona's acquisition of Curt Schilling by
getting right-hander Ismael Valdes and cash Wednesday from the
Chicago Cubs for minor-leaguers Jamie Arnold and Jorge Piedra.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, 26, spent the first six seasons of his career with the
Dodgers before being traded with Eric Young to the Cubs for pitcher
Terry Adams and two minor-leaguers in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers questioned Valdes' toughness and heart last season,
and Cubs management quickly did the same. Valdes opened the season
on the disabled list with soreness in his a shoulder and has missed
starts with a hamstring injury and a recurring blister problem, but
he's been healthy for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think in this environment, with the bullpen we've got now
and the offense we've got, he's in position to succeed,'' Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``I think last year it seemed
like he didn't get the run support. He should have won more than
nine games last year. We didn't trade him because he wasn't
effective. It was a financial move that enabled us to go out and
get some other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we felt like the acquisition didn't mortgage the future.
It kept the future intact and we got a guy to help us down the
stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes was 2-4 with a 5.37 ERA in 12 starts for the Cubs, but
his reputation lowered the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hope Valdes pitches more like the guy who went 61-54
with a 3.38 ERA in 176 games in Los Angeles _ but with a more
team-oriented approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is different than it was before because now the players
get involved,'' Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield said. ``I want
some Christmas money (from the playoffs). To have a guy that has
great stuff and the potential to be a 20-game winner is not a bad
deal. It's a matter of him going out and putting it on the line for
his teammates. You have to put it on the line for your teammates
and forget about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes is owed approximately $2 million of the $5.8 million
contract he signed before the season, but the Cubs will pay
$500,000 of that. Valdes is a free agent after the season, and
though he said he would think about re-signing with the Dodgers,
it's not on his mind now. The Dodgers won't discuss a contract
extension now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be back home with my old teammates,'' Valdes
said. ``They have the power hitters, a good lineup, a good bullpen.
They have everything a championship team needs. It's a great team.
I'm very excited to be part of the pennant race.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Dodgers said otherwise publicly, they were concerned
about using rookie Eric Gagne during the pennant race. He'll be
sent to Triple-A Albuquerque after he starts today in Colorado, a
team source said. He's 1-6 with a 5.59 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Cubs are in Philadelphia, Valdes will join the Dodgers
when they arrive there to open a three-game series Friday. Manager
Davey Johnson said he hasn't decided when Valdes will start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a pennant race,'' Johnson said. ``To me, it's a lot
tougher to pitch when you're not in one than when you're in one. I
know how (Valdes) can turn it up a notch. I've seen it, and when he
does that, there aren't many better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tried to get involved in the Schilling sweepstakes
late Tuesday, but they couldn't compete with the package the
Diamondbacks put together (pitchers Omar Daal, Nelson Figueroa and
Vicente Padilla and first baseman/outfielder Travis Lee). Also,
Schilling didn't want to play in Los Angeles and could reject a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Team sources said Malone talked briefly to Cubs president and
general manager Andy MacPhail on Tuesday, but discussions didn't
heat up until Wednesday afternoon. The trade went quickly because
the Dodgers are familiar with Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, a 26-year-old right-hander, was 4-7 with a 5.07 ERA in
13 starts for Triple-A Albuquerque and he appeared in two games for
the Dodgers with a 4.05 ERA. Piedra, 21, is an outfielder who was
batting .283 with six homers and 52 RBI in 92 games at Class A Vero
Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
