<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAD DOESN'T LAST AS PEREZ GETS ROCKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; DENVER _ On a day when the Los Angeles Dodgers acquired
right-hander Ismael Valdes from the Chicago Cubs to, in all
likelihood, replace rookie Eric Gagne in the rotation, they sure
could have used a substitute for lefty Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez matched career highs by allowing nine runs and eight
earned runs, which is quite remarkable considering the way Perez's
season went a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Dodgers gave Perez a three-run lead before
he took the mound, he was hammered as the team's winning streak was
snapped at three games with an 11-4 loss to Colorado at Coors Field
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers remain 2 games out first in the National League
West. Arizona and San Francisco are tied for first. The Dodgers can
win the four-game series with a victory this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got back from the break, we got together and said
let's stop making it so hard on ourselves and concentrate on
winning series,'' Dodgers shortstop Kevin Elster said. ``We've won
every one since, and that's what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez (4-5) hasn't won since May 20, but he had pitched well
most of the season. That was hardly the case as he, and the
Dodgers, suffered through his second shortest start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez lasted just 1 innings in May 14 at St. Louis when he
allowed seven runs. It's the fourth time Perez allowed eight earned
runs in a game, the latest being June 11, 1999 at Oakland. Perez
allowed nine runs Aug. 23, 1998, at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't find my spot, and that's why I got hit,'' Perez said.
``Sometimes when you don't have much power in your arm, you pitch
great. Today, I had more velocity, and sometimes I tried to go with
a breaking ball, but it gave me a hard time. I'm not going to be
scared to throw my breaking ball. I'm going to keep using it, but
probably the next time I'm going to use my fastball more.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Dodgers took a 3-0 lead on a two-run double by Eric
Karros and an RBI fielder's choice by Adrian Beltre in the top of
the first, the Rockies, who had lost 17 of 20, had a 5-3 lead
before Perez recorded an out.
</P>
<P>
   The final three of those came on Jeffrey Hammonds' homer to
left-center field, but Johnson argued that a fan reached over the
railing and caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got a good call yet on a guy leaning over the damn
fence,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson, who managed Baltimore
when youngster Jeff Maier reached over and caught Derek Jeter's
homer at Yankee Stadium in the 1996 playoffs. ``How come I'm the
only one who could see it?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies built their lead to 6-3 when Colorado pitcher Brian
Bohanon, but that's not what did in Perez. The Dodgers cut the
deficit to 6-4 in the third on another Beltre ground out, but Perez
got himself in more trouble in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   And it began with a walk to Bohanon. Brian Hunter singled and
Neifi Perez sacrificed. But instead of letting Beltre field it at
third, Perez grabbed it, whirled and threw off target to Eric
Karros at first. Matt Herges relieved, but allowed all three
inherited runners to score and then gave up his own run-scoring
single to Butch Huskey as Colorado went ahead 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first one he hasn't kept us in the ballgame in
quite a while,'' Johnson said. ``He's really been very good, but it
didn't happen. He wasn't very sharp. He was just up and out, and
that was about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
