<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-27 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S GO QUIETLY AS OAKLAND CUTS WEST DEFICIT TO THREE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You don't need the roar of the crowd to gauge a team's
success.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   All you need is ears. All you have to do is listen. The postgame
clubhouse will tell you all you need to know.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners clubhouse Wednesday was as quiet as a library at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The A's clubhouse was as loud as the engine testing room at
Boeing. There was enough music cranked up to simulate a battle of
the bands.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who won?
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hudson pitched the A's to a 6-1 victory over the Mariners,
moving Oakland to within three games of Seattle in the American
League West.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred games into the 2000 season, the Mariners have had
their share of raucous clubhouse moments as Seattle has zoomed to
the top of the charts in the West. Wednesday's no-noise zone was a
reminder of the fleeting nature of baseball, of how quickly things
can change in the 62 remaining games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that they could come into our house and do
this,'' shortstop Alex Rodriguez said of the A's, who won two of
three games. ``But it may be good. Maybe this will serve as a
wakeup call for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also serve as a call to arms. Seattle general manager Pat
Gillick has until Monday to get a non-waiver deal put together, and
the loss served notice that the Mariners, while good, are not as
good as they could be.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle loaded the bases with one out in the first and scored
just one run. John Olerud smoked a line drive, a ball run down in
the gap by center fielder Terrence Long. Olerud's drive produced a
1-0 lead, but that was the end of Hudson's vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners left two men on in the first, the second and the
fifth, and they had two on when the A's turned an inning-ending
double play in the fourth. Opportunity was there repeatedly, but
success was not. It's not a new story. The Mariners rank last in
the AL in hits and last in runners left on base.
</P>
<P>
   Normally that combination will leave a team dead in the water,
but the Mariners have been able to skirt the problem by pitching
well, playing steady defense and getting just enough offense to go
around.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Mariners may well depend on if Gillick is
able to bridge the hits/runners-left-on conundrum. A left-handed
bat would be ideal, and names like Jeromy Burnitz (Milwaukee), Al
Martin (San Diego) and Johnny Damon (Kansas City) are being thrown
around as potential additions to the Mariners arsenal. The
throwing-around part is easy. It's the catching part that's hard.
</P>
<P>
   And right now, the A's are looking at ways to catch Seattle
while the Mariners look at ways to improve their roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two months to go, and a lot of the guys who are here
have done the job before,'' losing pitcher Paul Abbott said. ``With
all the time still to go, we should get as strong as we can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's sent a loud, emphatic message, in winning two of three,
that the Mariners had better improve, because Oakland isn't about
to go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was essential that we beat these guys, and beat them on
their own turf,'' second baseman Randy Velarde said. ``This
definitely sends a message, not only for the postseason, but that
we're able to beat teams in our own division, because it's getting
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, in just his second year in the big leagues but already
pitching like an All-Star _ which he was, two weeks ago in Atlanta
_ ran his record to 11-3 by shaking off the rocky first inning. He
gave up a bullet to Olerud with the bases loaded, to be sure, but
Long ran it down, keeping the damage to a sacrifice fly. And after
Hudson struck out John Mabry, the worst was over _ for Hudson. For
the Mariners, the worst was yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Hernandez got the first hit off Abbott in the third
inning, a two-run homer. Oakland scored two more runs in the fifth,
on a couple of bloop singles with men in scoring position. Then
Jason Giambi hit a two-run homer in the eighth off Brett Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners out-hit the A's 8-5, but went 1-for-10 with men in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not all of their hits were pretty,'' outfielder Jay
Buhner said. ``But they got hits with men on base. We didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner wasn't in the lineup Wednesday. Neither was Rickey
Henderson. As a general rule, neither veteran plays day games after
having played the night before. The Mariners had good role players
in place of both, but Raul Ibanez and John Mabry have just one
homer each. That's not enough for players hitting sixth and seventh
in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the push to add another bat to the lineup, a thought that
will be on the Mariners' minds as they prepare for four games
against Toronto beginning Thursday night, a game that will be
closely monitored by the A's, who host Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only hope we didn't tick off the Mariners so much that they
go out and kick Toronto's behinds,'' A's designated hitter Matt
Stairs said.
</P>
<P>
   The A's and the Jays will have the answer to that momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
