u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-27 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD MARKS 25TH BIRTHDAY BUT PARTY TIME REMAINS ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Alex Rodriguez turns 25 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Not that every day isn't like a birthday.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the Mariners have showered gifts on the young
shortstop: John Olerud, Aaron Sele, Arthur Rhodes, Mark McLemore,
Stan Javier, Rickey Henderson ... and the trading deadline is just
around the corner. The yawning wood in the Mariners' batting order
during Wednesday's 6-1 loss to the A's only reinforced the need to
bring in some extra bash.
</P>
<P>
   Since last November, when the mating dance with Rodriguez began
in earnest, the Mariners have built a winning team that is also
supposed to double as proof to Rodriguez that they mean business.
</P>
<P>
   If he is gloating about his lofty station in life, Rodriguez
never shows it.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, if he is impressed by the Mariners' effort, it
has done nothing to change his mind about testing the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard Lincoln (Mariners part-owner and CEO) doesn't try and
score any points with me, which I appreciate. I really like him,
but he knows it would do more harm than good to bring up the
contract, especially now,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's glamour free-agent-to-be, Rodriguez has the world by
the tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in demand,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 25, I was on top of my game, too. It made the game a lot
easier. But you learn it's not about how much money you can make.
It's about what he wants to get out of this game. You can go
somewhere and get what you deserve, and that's all gravy. The
important thing is to play the game, accomplish what you set out to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said that like Henderson, he has goals _ but he will
not reveal them. Rodriguez knows he's in the catbird seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys kid me that I have a silver spoon since I was young,
especially since I signed (his first contract with a million-dollar
bonus) so early. But I think they're saying that facetiously. I
think they realize how hard I work. I try not to take things for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   As birthdays go, Rodriguez said his summertime gig has never
been anything special. There's always a game, business to take care
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best birthday, though, was when I turned 21, because I
signed a contract extension that day and hit a home run to win the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has often said that the contract extension he signed
with the Mariners in 1996 was for his family. The $12 million deal
was the security he wanted to make sure his mother, sister and
brother were forever going to be OK.
</P>
<P>
   The next one he signs will be for him. No matter how much fun he
is having, Rodriguez refuses to determine his future now.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Lincoln stopped by the shortstop's locker and whisked
him off for a private meeting. Rodriguez said no offers were
tendered, no overtures made.
</P>
<P>
   This quashed any vague, flickering hope that Rodriguez would
celebrate his birthday by taking the $100-million-plus deal the
Mariners are prepared to give him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't make an emotional decision because the team is
winning now and we're having fun. Look at Alex Fernandez,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marlins won the World Series, he signed a contract, and
the next year, they started tearing the team apart.''
</P>
<P>
   As much of interest to Rodriguez Wednesday was talk about what
the Mets might do, now that Reds shortstop Barry Larkin isn't
heading to Shea Stadium. Did the Mets call the Mariners? What deal
would the Mets make for Rodriguez?
</P>
<P>
   The promise was to not trade Rodriguez this season, but no one
said anything about listening to offers.
</P>
<P>
   As Rodriguez gets older, he gets more shrewd. If he rebuked
agent Scott Boras when he was 18 and signed with the Mariners, and
if he defied Boras again at 21 when he signed the extension,
Rodriguez is extremely cautious about sticking to his guns this
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What direction are the (Mariners) going? That's what I'm
interested in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Half of a promising season has not swayed Rodriguez. Nothing
alters the bigger picture. Boras wants him in L.A. or New York,
maybe Chicago, for marketing reasons. Rodriguez says the decision
is ultimately his.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, the 41-year-old Henderson has climbed past Hall
of Famers every time he steals another base, scores another run,
gets another hit or draws another walk.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, 36-year-old Jay Buhner hit home run No. 300, good
for No. 86 on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez, enjoying his most productive year as one of the
game's best hitters, leads the league in RBI.
</P>
<P>
   At 25, the advancing age of the Mariners roster has got to be a
concern for Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie Moyer, Aaron Sele, Ole (John Olerud), Edgar, (Tom)
Lampkin, (Joe) Oliver; a lot of guys here have a lot of questions
about what happens next. Not negative questions, just who's going
to be here, who's coming back?''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a demand. It's a question. But even if the Mariners
have an answer, it really doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   As he turns 25, Rodriguez is not going to celebrate with the
richest contract in baseball history. His party comes later, time
and location still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
