<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 07:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i PM-CONCORDE-CRASH-0727-C     07-27 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-CONCORDE-CRASH-0727-COX &HT;    PROBE IN CONCORDE CRASH TURNS TO 'BLACK BOXES'; EXPERT FINGERS
ILL-FATED FLIGHT'S TURBINE DISCS
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ Investigators have fully extracted the data
from the ``black box'' recorders aboard the Air France Concorde
that crashed Tuesday, and have begun analyzing cockpit
conversations and engine readings made during the supersonic
aircraft's doomed two-minute flight, the French government said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The government agency that investigates aviation accidents said
it was unclear how soon the
</P>
<P>
   information contained on the flight data and cockpit voice
records would yield clues about what caused the crash that killed
113 when the Concorde slammed into a small hotel near Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope to learn more about the readings from the No.
2 engine, which burst into flames as the aircraft was taxiing down
the runway. The same engine was repaired by mechanics just before
the Concorde departed.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also intend to study the amateur video aired Wednesday
on TV news reporters to determine if for example, the color and
size of the flames can held determine the temperature and source of
the flames, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-fated Concorde was carrying 100 passengers _ 96 Germans,
two Danes, an American and an Austrian _ and nine French
crewmembers. The American was identified as retired Air France
employee Christopher Behrens. Two Polish women were among those
killed on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Six members of one German family died in the crash, including a
10-year-old boy and a seven-year-old girl, the newspaper France
Soir reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service has been scheduled here in Gonesse for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A French aviation engineer who serves as an official adviser to
French courts told La Croix newspaper that evidence and
observations suggest that a turbine disc in the jet engine may have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Auffray told the newspaper that investigators should
focus on turbine discs inside
</P>
<P>
   both Rolls-Royce engines under the left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Auffray said the pilots' loss of control indicates that a
ruptured turbine disc may have caused the engine to break up
inside. However, because it is so unlikely that a disc would have
spontaneously failed, he said it was also possible that the engine
was damaged by ``intruding objects.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot reported engine trouble seconds after take-off and was
apparently making a frantic attempt to fly the crippled aircraft to
a nearby airport, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Elisabeth Senot, a French jurist conducting a judicial enquiry
into the crash, said tower controllers at Charles de Gaulle
International Airport radioed the Concorde's crew that they could
see flames at the back of the aircraft 56 seconds after it took
off. Air France identified the pilot as Capt. Christian Marty,
known for skill and prudence as a pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captain replied, 'fault in engine number two,''' Senot
said at a news conference Wednesday. ``After that, it seems the
flames became extremely large because (the fire) was once again
signaled by the control tower, and the crew replied that they were
no longer in a position to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew told the tower that they were heading for Le Bourget
Airport, four miles southwest of Charles de Gaulle. This would have
required a half-turn rather than a full-turn by the damaged
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was during this turning maneuver that it crashed on the
hotel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The supersonic transport lost power and altitude as the flames
poured from engines under its left wing and crashed into a small
hotel. All 109 passengers and crewmembers aboard the Concorde were
killed, as well as four people at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The plane struck the hotel and earth near fields of wheat and
corn near the suburb of Gonesse, about nine miles from central
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Air France reported that Marty asked mechanics to make a repair
to the engine that began spewing flames moments before take-off.
Mechanics repaired a thrust-reverser in one of the two portside
engines before the Concorde took off.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the airline said engine No. 2 _ the interior
engine on the left wing _ was inspected and repaired at the pilot's
insistence even though the repair was not required for take-off.
The problem with the thrust-reverser, which is used to slow an
aircraft on landing, was detected after the plane arrived from New
York on Monday, Air France said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the pilot was told that the repair wasn't required,
he asked mechanics to make it anyway, the airline said. ``The piece
w's survivors on the ground told reporters that she was spared only
because she had been assigned a room at the front of Hotelissimo,
which was engulfed in the blaze fed by the aircraft's 100 tons of
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Brooking, 21, a Cambridge student, jumped out of a window
on the hotel's second floor to safety seconds after the accident.
She had been on the phone with her sister in England. She said that
flames and smoke moved quickly through the hotel. ``It was like
being in an oven,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Gonesse, a town of 20,000 brought unhappily to the
world stage by the crash, expressed a mix of sadness and gratitude
about what had happened. Coming out of a Toys ``R'' Us at a nearby
mall, Marie Hetru said she could not get over the crash, and the
prospect that it could have crashed into the center of Gonesse a
half-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would the number of dead be then _ maybe including me and
my children,'' she
</P>
<P>
   said. ``Of course it is terrible _ 113 people _ but if it wasn't
for the pilot, it may have been much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonesse Mayor Jean-Pierre Blazy said the crash reflected the
miseries of the town's living near one of the world's busiest
airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying for a long time that air traffic is
increasing too fast, that
</P>
<P>
   even with four runways, you can't safely manage this amount of
air traffic around Paris,'' Blazy said at a press conference
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lived with planes for several decades and we don't
live in
</P>
<P>
   daily fear of a crash, but it's on our minds.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
