<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX     07-27 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Another chance for Mideast peace squandered
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following a consistent 52-year pattern, the Palestinians have
managed again to make the least of an opportunity. This time, at
President Clinton's Camp David negotiations, they dodged the
creation of a substantial, internationally recognized Palestinian
state with significant authority in the Muslim quarter of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   And consistent with this dismal history, too, Yasser Arafat,
chairman of the Palestinian Authority, is being hailed as a hero by
his allies and even some of his enemies _ the extremist Hammas _
for resisting the best opportunity for a lasting peace since the
Palestinians and their backers in Arab capitals blew off Israel's
tenders after the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat now goes ahead with his threatened unilateral
declaration of a Palestinian state September 13, he will likely
lose for his people more than just an opportunity. Such a reckless
move would all but require unilateral Israeli counters, probably
including full annexation of some Jewish-occupied sections of the
West Bank and hardened barriers to Palestinian interests in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   That, and a likely turn in Israeli domestic politics to the
uncompromising right. After all, what point would there be, then,
in Israelis continuing with a peace-minded government?
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak had prepared Israelis for painful
compromise by all but formally ceding substantial concessions even
before the Camp David talks. By common account, he proved
additionally flexible in the negotiations, even in hard-nut
Jerusalem issues.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat had not prepared his people for substantial compromise,
holding out even as he enplaned for Washington a fantasy of
Palestinian triumph. And by equally common account _ except, of
course, from Palestinian spin _ he was unbending in demanding that
Jerusalem be partitioned, which isn't going to happen and
shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that Arafat's stubbornness on Jerusalem is being
cheered in Palestinian and Arab precincts as a negotiating success.
</P>
<P>
   A long string of successes like this one has brought the
Palestinians to their current pass, on ever-shrinking patches of
land in an unfavorable status quo increasingly sanctioned by the
calcification of time and practice.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has three choices. He can begin finally prepare his
people for the kinds of concessions that the Camp David talks, if
they did nothing else, made clear will be necessary for peace. That
might still allow for a final-status agreement before
mid-September, thought that's a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   He can settle for the current ad hoc, unstable and muddled
relationship with Israel and hope it does not come unstuck in any
but manageable ways,
</P>
<P>
   Or, as he foolishly has done in the past, he can stir up the
volatile Palestinian street in a reckless gamble that more gain
than loss will come of the turmoil, a model increasingly
discredited in practice but not in Palestinian theory.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with peace, Arafat ran. Right into a nasty bind of his own
making.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
