r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0728-CO     07-27 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some literary selections to keep your mind off the heat
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   SUMMERTIME, AND THE READING IS EASY
</P>
<P>
   At least it's easy to come up with an excuse for staying out of
the heat and under the air-conditioning, or curling up with a book
under a back-porch ceiling fan once that infernal sun has finally
sunk below the horizon. A night-time climate of 90 degrees with a
bit of shade and some air stirring seems fairly tolerable after a
full day of 103-degree weather in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   I've been on a reading tear since the solstice, so I picked an
armload of my favorite recent reads to offer for your
consideration. It's an eclectic mix of heavy and light, fiction and
fact, so maybe you'll discover something that tickles your fancy.
Here goes:'
</P>
<P>
   ``Gates of the Alamo,'' by Stephen Harrigan (Knopf, 581 pp. $25
list.). Just when you thought the last thing the world needed was
yet another book about the Alamo _ fact or fiction _ Texas Monthly
writer Stephen Harrigan publishes a fine historical novel of the
state's seminal event. Harrigan was meticulous in his research, and
the few completely fictionalized characters are entirely
believable. His portraits of the main players in the Texas
revolution: Sam Houston, Gen. Santa Anna, and the three
larger-than-life characters who died at the San Antonio mission _
Crockett, Bowie and Travis _ are well drawn and as faithful to
history as a novelist can get.
</P>
<P>
   The subplot involves a mother chasing after a son who runs off
to join the Texian forces at the Alamo. The son is sent out to get
reinforcements just before the battle, and the mother, pinned
inside, manages to survive. (Santa Anna allowed women and children
to live.)
</P>
<P>
   There's no line drawn in the sand, which might disappoint some
who are enamored of that historical chestnut, but as Harrigan
points out in the afterword, there's little or no proof that
actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gates of the Alamo'' takes readers through the rest of the war
and Houston's eventual triumph at San Jacinto. Even non-Texans
should find it a fascinating read.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fine Green Line,'' by John Paul Newport. (Broadway, 312
pp. $24 list). OK, you probably have to be golfer to enjoy this
account of a free-lance writer's attempt to raise his game to a
professional level , survive qualifying school and make it to the
PGA Tour. Newport was a better-than-average golfer who shot a
miraculous three-under-par 69 one day and decided to take a year
off to see just how good he could get.
</P>
<P>
   The answer? Not nearly good enough, but the tale is at times
hilarious and insightful _ especially for us hackers upon whom the
golf gods occasionally smile and bless us with a low round and
string of birdies. And Newport is a very good writer. Golf widows
(and widowers) might enjoy an articulate explanation of why their
spouses devote endless hours baking in the sun, hitting a little
white ball over and over. Golf nuts will love this book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midwives,'' by Chris Bohjalian. (Vintage paperbacks, 372 pp.
$13 list). Oprah picked this book, and that's reason enough for me
to give it a shot. It turned out to be one of the better novels
I've read in some time. The story centers around an experienced
midwife in rural Vermont who runs into trouble during a delivery in
which the mother apparently dies of a stroke. In desperation, she
performs a Caesarian section to save the baby. After, the father
and her assistant claim the woman actually was alive, and the
impromptu surgery is what killed her. Sibyl, the midwife, is
indicted for involuntary manslaughter, a charge pushed by the
medical establishment long critical of home births by non-doctors.
The trial is the centerpiece of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midwives'' is a page-turner from the beginning with a unique
plot and no real villains or heroes. Once gain, Oprah was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duty: A Father, His Son, and the Man Who Won the War,'' by Bob
Greene. (Morrow, 295 pp., $25 list). Chicago Tribune columnist Bob
Greene tells the story of his recently deceased father and his
World War II experiences, as well as those of a fellow hometown
veteran, Paul Tibbets, who piloted the Enola Gay and dropped the
atomic bomb on Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
   This is an amazing memoir of two ordinary men who served our
country gallantly, one in relative anonymity, the other whose name
is forever linked to one of the most momentous events of the 20th
century. Both remained self-effacing and modest to a fault. Tibbets
never granted an interview until Greene contacted him more than a
half-century after the event. Greene's dad had little to say about
the war until close to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duty'' is a fine piece of journalism, and few will be able to
finish it with dry eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy, and stay out of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
