<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How am I? I'm barely making it
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ If it walks like pneumonia and quacks like
pneumonia, there's a good chance it is. Even though my doctor never
used the ``p'' word in describing my illness, I know _ despite my
lack of any formal training in the medical field _ the walking
pneumonia had me.
</P>
<P>
   The very fact I went to the doctor is proof enough I had
symptoms that couldn't be sloughed off with Nyquil and Tylenol.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing gets your attention quicker than a temperature of 102
followed by sheet-soaking sweats and topped off by teeth-chattering
chills. Then the roller coaster ride would start over. Oh, did I
mention the uncontrollable coughing fits that would nearly leave me
for dead?
</P>
<P>
   It's been a month now and I'm finishing up the last of five or
six rounds of antibiotics that have been working night and day to
rid my lungs of what looked like cumulus clouds on the X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   My brush with mortality has given me a chance to reflect on a
number of topics:
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't say I have been insensitive to others who might come
down with the sniffles, but when someone would start telling me
their medical problems, I would offer my best advice. ``The best
thing for what ails you,'' I would say, patting their shoulder as I
guided them back to the their desk,'' is hard work and lots of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   My doctor told me he was prescribing the ``best antibiotic known
to medical science.'' Seven pills cost $50. For that amount, I at
least expected it to be laced with Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   My illness was not nearly as interesting to others as it was to
me. Even my wife, who made some sort of vow dealing with sickness
and health, was growing weary of what she described as ``my
constant moaning.'' The combination of pills and cough syrup made
my tired and I will admit it may have made me slightly edgy. But
she had no call to crank the lawn mower and leave it running next
to the bedroom window when I was trying to take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my condition, I kept up my duties as a fourth-grade
Sunday school teacher. Some might say I was placing young children
at risk of infection. I say their immune systems are much better
than mine at fighting disease. I remember one recent Sunday when I
was telling a Bible story, I had their undivided attention. They
sat there, eyes as big as saucers and mouths open, as I hacked and
wheezed through the story. I was amazed how _ even in my worsened
condition _ I still had their rapt attention. I mentioned this to
my daughter who's in the class, to which she replied, ``Daddy, we
all thought you were going to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't like it when co-workers pat me on the shoulder and tell
me the best thing for what ails me is hard work and lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Website: www.coxnews.com/newsservice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
