</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Untermeyer on why a Bush-Cheney ticket works
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Chase Untermeyer of Houston, a trusted ally of
both former President Bush and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, thinks
Dick Cheney will be a great running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was chief of staff for President Gerald Ford when Bush
headed the Central Intelligence Agency. Brent Scowcroft was
national security adviser, and Jim Baker, the undersecretary of
commerce, was Ford's campaign manager in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Their close relationship then made for great cooperation later
when President Bush had Scowcroft as national security adviser,
Baker as secretary of state and Cheney as secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer, director of White House personnel for President Bush
and appointed in 1999 by Gov. Bush to the politically sensitive
chairmanship of the Texas State Board of Education, recalled
bringing presidential historian Dr. Richard Neustadt, to visit the
president in 1989. The meeting ended when the national security
team came into the Oval Office, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer said Neustadt told him that previous defense and
foreign policy advisers usually had their sabers drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time the secretary of state and national security
adviser got along as well before was when Henry Kissinger held both
jobs,'' Untermeyer said. ``They could sublimate their rivalries or
jealousies or territorial turf battles because they started off
with a great degree of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've got to believe that that is one of the traits of
Cheney Bush values,'' Untermeyer said. ``He is a strong man and
highly capable, but he gets along with people.''
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer thinks that's because Cheney ``was so young when he
was chief of staff to the president. There he was in this very
important job where he had to work with all these important people.
He had authority, but he worked quietly with everybody to get
cooperation, rather than to force it.''
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer recalled a story the normally staid Cheney once told
about campaigning for re-election in Wyoming. He was running late
for an interview at a radio station in a town he'd visited often,
but not recently. Cheney remembered the station was in a house
trailer at the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney told the driver `turn left, turn right' _ and he burst
into the trailer to find a mother and two kids cooking supper, and
realized that this radio station had moved,'' Untermeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, Untermeyer recalled, turned to the woman as he was
leaving ``and said, `You have just been visited by your United
States senator _ Alan Simpson.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's 10 years in the U.S. House of Representatives, part of
them fairly high in the Republican leadership, will serve the
younger Bush well, Untermeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president, Cheney would preside over the U.S. Senate.
That, coupled with his roots in the House, ``can be of immense
value on Capitol Hill, totally apart from his national security
considerations,'' Untermeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cheney choice would give Bush something that modern
presidents who are former governors (without congressional
experience) really need. And that is a vice president who can be
the administration's most senior ambassador to Capitol Hill, who
has roots in Capitol Hill, and who can speak to the members there
as a former colleague in a way that someone who doesn't have those
ties cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's what Mondale did for Carter and Bush did for Reagan
and Gore has done for Clinton,'' Untermeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
