<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDIES0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oldies but goodies
 &HT;    By Carol Simmons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In the cult action movie ``Escape From New
York,'' our hero, played by Kurt Russell, finds that every time he
meets up with someone new, the character's first line is: ``I
thought you were dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it seems appropriate to compare one pop cultural form with
another, especially when considering musical acts you may have
thought were dead. Maybe not in the literal sense of having left
this mortal plane, but certainly in the notion that their time in
the spotlight has passed.
</P>
<P>
   The list of acts touring the country this summer is dominated by
groups whose biggest successes appear to be behind them _ way
behind them.
</P>
<P>
   But to paraphrase a line from another movie, Monty Python's
``Holy Grail'': They're not dead yet. At least not to their fans,
who are happy to spend their dollars to hear songs they never
stopped loving.
</P>
<P>
   In the next week plus a day, several acts whose careers started
_ and might have seemed to have ended _ in the '70s and '80s will
be making their way through the Dayton area. Some groups, such as
KC and The Sunshine Band, are banking solely on past glories, while
other acts, such as Rick Springfield, and Michael McDonald, are
pushing forward with new material and recording projects.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's the old hits most people will go to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The nonfans may think of an evening with one of these groups in
terms of yet another movie: ``Night of the Living Dead.'' But for
longtime fans, the music is eternal.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Wayne Casey, better known as ``KC'' of KC and The Sunshine
Band, rose to the top of the music charts in the 1970s with such
dance hits as Shake Your Booty, Get Down Tonight and That's The Way
(I Like It).
</P>
<P>
   During the peak years of the band's career, the group's
brass-heavy disco feel garnered nine Grammy nominations and three
Grammy awards, two of which were for work on the Satuday Night
Fever soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Opening act War formed almost 30 years ago in South Central Los
Angeles to spread a message of brotherhood and harmony. Fusing
rock, jazz, Latin and rhythm and blues, the multi-ethnic ensemble
had major hits with Why Can't We Be Friends?, Low Rider and The
Cisco Kid.
</P>
<P>
   To fans of the smooth-voiced Paul Anka, he's a living legend.
With more than 40 years in show business behind him, Anka has
written hundreds of chart-topping favorites, including Put Your
Head on My Shoulder, My Way and You Are My Destiny. He also can
boast having a record on Billboard's Top-50 chart for five
consecutive decades.
</P>
<P>
   A wunderkind when he started out, Anka was only 16 when his
first hit, ``Diana,'' launched his career. Through the years, his
music has been recorded by such entertainers as Elvis Presley,
Barbra Streisand, Tom Jones, the Doobie Brothers and, of course,
Frank Sinatra, who made Anka's ``My Way `` his signature song.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield, the subject of one of the most interesting VH-1
``Behind the Music'' programs, brought us such '80s hits as
``Jesse's Girl,'' ``Don't Talk to Strangers'' and ``Affair of the
Heart, `` while playing the heart-breaking Dr. Noah Drake on the
daytime soap opera ``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade away from recording and touring,
Springfield released the introspective album ``Karma'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   The first rock band to give the flute a prominent role in its
instrumental mix, Jethro Tull has sold more than 60 million albums
since the group's formation in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Named for an 18th century English agricultural pioneer, Jethro
Tull has given the world such songs as ``Aqualung,'' ``Bungle in
the Jungle,'' ``Teacher `` and ``Living in the Past.'' And after
30-some years, flutist and vocalist Ian Anderson and guitarist
Martin Barre remain at the heart of the band.
</P>
<P>
   Singer-songwriter Michael McDonald _ creator of such hits as
``Takin' It to the Streets,'' ``What a Fool Believes'' and ``I Keep
Forgettin' `` _ followed well-known stints with Steely Dan and the
Doobie Brothers by launching an initially successful solo career in
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But we hadn't heard much out of the blue-eyed-soul stylist in a
while, until his recently released ``Blue Obsession `` ended what
turned into a seven-year-long span since his last album of new
material.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
