<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0728-COX     07-27 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's choice frames distinctions between major parties
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Judging by the rhetoric of the times there are
three major political factions in our land: the Republicans, the
Democrats and the ``not a dime's worth of difference'' faction.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``not a dime's difference between the Ds and the Rs.
They're all the same.'' Red ketchup. Green ketchup. Same condiment.
</P>
<P>
   Some who pay attention will note that at times the prevailing
power structures indeed seem to merge _ as in trade and
globalization issues, military pork, or finding ways to avoid
dealing holistically with health-care issues.
</P>
<P>
   But put those aside, look at the record, and one wonders if the
``not a dime's difference'' crowd has sand in its eye from too many
nights on ``Survivor'' island.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Dick Cheney as George Bush's running mate is a
powerful reminder of the differences between the Ds and the Rs. If
Bush has been been able to fuzz matters of ideology while building
centrist poll numbers, his running-mate choice gives voters, at
least those who look, something definitive.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: anti-gun control at every turn, even against the ban on
cop-killer bullets; hard-line anti-abortion, even in instances of
rape and incest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush-Cheney: a ticket that may be more beholden to a single
industry than any ticket in history. Sure, everyone has his bread
buttered somewhere. But admit it: This is Big Oil's dream team.
</P>
<P>
   Were we talking dimes? We should be talking silver dollars, gold
doubloons.
</P>
<P>
   OF MATTERS GREEN
</P>
<P>
   On no subject is the difference between Rs and Ds more striking
than on the environment. Though the Clinton administration could be
accused of seeking half-a-loaf solutions, let the record show that
if an R had been in Clinton's seat the last eight years the loaf
would be reduced to post-ash hydrocarbons.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important things Clinton did was blunt the Newt
Gingrich-led quest to gut summarily the Environmental Protection
Agency budget.
</P>
<P>
   The criticisms of Bush as a callous despoiler of the environment
are hyperbole. But it's no overstatement that Rs in Congress like
Majority Whip Tom DeLay would dance a jig if Bush were in the White
House, license to surgically poke, prod and possibly lobotomize the
EPA.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the Sierra Club last week endorsed Gore and not the
the Green Party's Ralph Nader. The club's Green-at-heart types know
the best thing for the environment at this stage is for Clinton to
hand the veto-pen baton to Gore to continue to counter
congressional mischief.
</P>
<P>
   Among that mischief is to block at every turn any federal
initiative that acknowledges man-caused global warming or acts on
the meticulously bargained Kyoto accords aimed at a world reduction
in the use of fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Um, excuse me. Did someone say oil?
</P>
<P>
   YES, A DIFFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   More power to the Greens as a voice about globalization, the
environment and health care. Welcome to the argument, zany
Buchananites. Libertarians? At least you know where you want to go,
even if we don't dare accompany you.
</P>
<P>
   However, for those who insist ``not a dime's worth'' I am
holding up an optical chart three inches from your nose. Let me
help you. That's an E at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Differences between R and D? On reproductive rights. On gun
control. On whether to empty the bank for a missile defense rather
than seek a limited version. On returning regressivity to tax laws
and putting tax cuts as the No. 1 fiscal priority, even with a
national debt to resolve. On vouchers that would undermine public
schools and subsidize religion. On government-imposed religion. On
the impulse to declare racial disparities suddenly all fair and
square.
</P>
<P>
   We could go on. How many dimes will do?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
