<HEADER>
A4428 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SHARP-DRIVING0728-COX     07-27 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driving in France always means a race to finish
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Test driving a station wagon is not normally something
that would make my heart skip a beat. But I was driving through the
scenic rolling mountains of southern France. The vehicle was
Volvo's V70 wagon. My drive partner was He Drove/She Drove's Paul
Lienert.
</P>
<P>
   Paul tossed me the keys and assumed the duties of navigator.
Volvo's new turbo wagon is an S80 luxury sedan with a knapsack.
Only the cargo space behind the rear seat distinguishes it from its
five-passenger counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Not far out of Nice, an avocado green ``box'' whizzed past. Paul
noted, ``A Honda Hr-V. It's an SUV that they don't bring into the
states.''
</P>
<P>
   I charged off in hot pursuit. I wanted to get a better look at
this unfamiliar Honda.
</P>
<P>
   I am embarrassed to admit it, but I was having no luck in my
pursuit of the Honda. Don't the French know that SUVs are not
supposed to be driven quickly on twisting, mountain roads? With the
right shoulder nothing more than a craggy mountainside, my
navigator's tense grip on the V-70 door handle was a welcome excuse
to ``let the Honda go.''
</P>
<P>
   On we traveled into rolling farmland. While Paul and I were
solving all the woes of the automotive world, I heard this annoying
little ``beep, beep'' from behind. A quick glance in my rearview
mirror revealed the presence of a Peugeot 106 GTI.
</P>
<P>
   Paul explained that the 106, which is not available in the
United States, is a small puddle jumper with a big 118-horsepower
motor. Then he roars with laughter, ``Doesn't the driver know who
he she is messing with?''
</P>
<P>
   I have a reputation as being a ``driver.'' Paul's comment had
thrown down the challenge. Now, I was not only duty bound, but
obligated to ``dust'' the Peugeot. I clamped down on the V70's
powerful turbocharged six-cylinder, and the Peugeot soon
disappeared. Keeping up my accelerated pace for about five minutes,
I smugly thought to myself, ``Well, I guess we showed them,'' which
also made me feel better about that Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, there again in the rearview mirror was that
aggravating Peugeot. Enough was enough; it was time to concede the
road. As the black 106 pulled alongside, its driver, a young French
girl, sat with both hands planted firmly on the wheel, eyes fixed
straight ahead. Paul and I both waved. There was no acknowledgment.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, we both blurted out, ``She must drive this road
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul politely added, ``Perhaps, she's late for work?'' ``Or
school?''
</P>
<P>
   It could be the reason that race car drivers like Nelson Piquet
or Alain Prost are national heroes. It seems that just about every
French man or woman fancies himself or herself as a future Formula
One racer. Or then again, it could just be that station wagon
thing; no one really wants to get blown away by one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
