<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4430 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TESTDRIVE0728-COX     07-27 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Red alert_ 2001 Corvette Z06 ready to zoooom
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you think the Chevrolet Corvette Z06 isn't one hot
item, consider this: Somewhere between its manufacture and initial
drives by magazine writers at the proving grounds in Michigan and
Atlanta, the brilliant red car lost the ``Z06'' emblem off its
right front fender _ and chip marks indicated it didn't just fall
off.
</P>
<P>
   But while some may view the insignia as collectible Corvette
memorabilia _ press kits for some models sell for hundreds of
dollars _ Chevrolet insists that the 2001 Z06 isn't going to be a
seldom-seen collector's car. General Motors plans to build 5,000 to
6,000 of the sophisticated beasts, meaning they should account for
about one-fifth of Corvette's projected sales this model year.
</P>
<P>
   Some, no doubt, will wind up on blocks while their owners wait
for them to appreciate from the $47,500 price, but the Z06 is such
fun to drive that it would take a truly mercenary person to just
let one sit.
</P>
<P>
   The Z06 loves to go _ and go it will. This being a time when
manufacturers no longer act coy about the performance potential of
their cars _ cases in point being the Dodge Viper and Ford Mustang
Cobra R _ Chevy blithely tosses out numbers that say, yes, the Z06
is a world-class sports car. It may lack the cachet of a Ferrari or
a Lamborghini, but take it to race or test track, and the Z06 will
hold its own.
</P>
<P>
   Zero to 60 mph happens in about four seconds. Top speed is
estimated at about 170 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its ultra-high performance predecessor, the ZR-1, known
as the ``King of the Hill,'' the Z06 is eminently tractable. The
clutch is a bit heavier than those of most cars, but anyone who can
work a manual shift will have little trouble driving the Z06. The
shifter has a fluidly mechanical feel, and it isn't necessary to do
much more than rest a foot on the brake pedal for the Z06 to say
``Whoa, Nelly'' and stop (60 mph to zero in about 125 feet with
little nose dive).
</P>
<P>
   The Z06 has some distinctive exterior features _ including
five-spoke wheels that show off red brake calipers, mesh-covered
air ducts and four round tail pipes jutting out from under the
center of the squared-off, muscular rear end. But the most
significant difference between the Z06 and ordinary Corvettes is
under the long, flared-fender front end.
</P>
<P>
   Raise the Z06's front-hinged hood and _ yee-ha _ there's a
red-trimmed V-8 that can't wait to rumble and grumble through its
weight-saving, half-titanium exhaust system. Regular Corvette
engines make 345 horsepower, but the Z06 powerplant cranks out 385
hp at 6,000 rpm (it redlines at 6,500 rpm) and 385 pounds-feet of
torque at 4,800 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   As its zero-to-60 mph time indicates, the Z06 launches like a
catapulted airplane with special-made 17-inch Goodyear F1 Supercar
tires up front and 18-inchers at the rear (no spare tire _ just a
pressurized can of sealant). Even with the traction control turned
off, the Z06 has such grip that inducing serious tire spin is
somewhat of an achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off for the flat, high-traction ride isn't as severe
as might be expected. The Z06 ride is appropriately firm, but not
uncomfortable so. Perhaps more of an aggravation _ well,
conversation inhibitor _ is the road and engine noise permeating
the cabin (GM uses thinner window glass and less insulation to keep
curb weight down to about 3,100 pounds, 100 or so below that of
other 'Vettes).
</P>
<P>
   The cabin is not without its pleasures, though. The seats are
very accommodating, and the height-adjustable power driver's seat,
in tandem with the tilt steering wheel, enables virtually all
drivers to find a correct/comfortable driving position easily.
Visibility is fairly good with blind spots, as expected, at the
rear quadrants.
</P>
<P>
   Those seats are real eye-poppers, though, trimmed in
red-and-black leather with Z06 insignia at the headrests. The full
and very legible instrumentation is distinguished by italicized
numbers on the 200 mph speedometer and 7,500 rpm tachometer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the impressive performance, which is what makes the Z06
so desirable, there is this to remember: There'll always be another
king of the hill, and anyone who thinks the Corvette engineers
can't wring more muscle out of the 5.7-liter V-8 isn't giving them
their due. To some, the Z06 may seem too good to be true, but it's
not too good to be topped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
