<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, July 27, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER (San Francisco) _ Attention Napster users: You have
until midnight Friday to download all the free, copyrighted music
your hard drive can handle. After that, the controversial,
music-swapping Web site will most likely be out of business. By
ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIONS-PRESS (San Francisco) _ Criticizing state prison
officials for trying to limit press access to executions, a federal
judge says reporters must be allowed to watch the entire lethal
injection process, from the time the shackled prisoner is led into
the chamber until death is pronounced. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CONVENTION-PROTESTS (Undated) _ Tens of thousands of
protesters are expected to converge on the conventions at which
Republican Gov. George W. Bush and Democratic Vice President Al
Gore formally will accept their parties' presidential nominations.
The demonstrators hope to capitalize on the high-profile political
events to bring attention to their causes. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ENGINE (Undated) _ Are you 8 years old or younger?
Are you fond of trains? Do you harbor a keen interest in the
serpentine career path of Alec Baldwin? Then have we got a film for
you. ``Thomas and the Magic Engine,'' which opened amid very little
hoopla _ certainly none of the hoopla attending ``Pokemon 2000'' _
has to be the gentlest, most unassuming and most quietly charming
children's film to be released this summer. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you're a worker, one of the
greatest places in the world to be right now is Paris. Late July
offers the anticipation of what comes in August: An entire month of
vacation. Certainly not every Parisian takes August off, but French
law requires employers to give workers more than four weeks of
vacation a year. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Wichita Falls, Texas) _ Compare the feeling to Ed
McMahon unexpectedly ringing your doorbell with a million-dollar
greeting. For Tim Seder, such a moment came one afternoon this
spring when he arrived home from his high school coaching job to
find a message on his answering machine from Dallas Cowboys kicking
coach Steve Hoffman. Seder, three years removed from tiny Ashland
(Ohio) University, is fighting fellow rookie Rian Lindell of
Washington State for just such an opportunity _ to kick field goals
for the Cowboys. By BRENT ZWERNEMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ After the Air France Concorde
fell in flames from the sky, an American musician who witnessed the
crash told reporters, ``It looked just like virtual reality.'' We
all know what he meant. It's not that the crash was any less
horrific to this young man, or that his mind is controlled by an
unholy alliance of Sega and Industrial Light and Magic. Like many
of us, he simply sees the world as if through a cathode ray tube.
That's the way we're used to seeing things, and the way we talk is
with the language of the media. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Emergency room nurse Mary Comber
was succinct and direct in her open letter to the mayor and Board
of Supervisors: ``The situation is bad and getting worse . . . Will
the city step up and do the right thing?'' The situation is that an
unholy number of drunk or drugged-out indigent San Franciscans are
adding a dangerous load to the city's already-burdened emergency
medical services network. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
