<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-GLASS-COLUMN-0730-COX     07-27 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-0730-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: HISTORY'S MOBILE MOMENTS
 &HT;    Moving in the commentary (k) and national (a) categories.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 30.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a summer day 32 years ago, the late Jacob Javits,
seeking to catch a shuttle to Washington for a key Senate vote, got
a ride to New York's LaGuardia Airport in his law partner's plush
limo.
</P>
<P>
   The car came with a radio telephone which accessed the 30
channels then available throughout New York City for public use. On
Javits' behest, I waited until one of 30 red lights finally turned
green and then asked the mobile operator to connect us with an
airline dispatcher. They held the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Those overburdened 30 channels came to mind the other day while
I stood in front of the Yale Club of New York, around the corner
from the old Hotel Roosevelt, where I had served as Javits'
campaign press secretary in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Before pulling up, I called a Manhattan garage from the Lincoln
Tunnel on my car's mobile phone. In waiting some five minutes for
the valet attendant to show up, 45 people had walked by on that
busy sidewalk talking on their cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, it's become common at congressional hearings to ask
folks to turn off their pagers before paging the first witness.
Some trendy Manhattan eateries have taken to asking patrons for
their cell phone preference _ on or off. No longer does the maitre
d' come by to plug in celebrity diners.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile phone scene has changed since 1984, when an attorney
friend told me that he would be getting a car phone in return for
having done legal work for a pioneering telecom provider. In time,
he passed up that swap. But I bought a phone, to the surprise of
dinner hosts who directed us into their unmarked cul-de-sacs.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year or so, that single-antenna firm had gone belly up
because, as it turned out, cell phones were the way to go. So I
switched to a $950 Motorola model, becoming one of the first
200,000 subscribers in the country to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association announced the anonymous arrival of the nation's 100
millionth wireless subscriber. This rapid mobile growth, the
industry trade group reported, isn't expected to stop, or even slow
down, anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   With 36 percent of the U.S. population already gone wireless,
usage continues to grow at the rate of 67,082 new subscribers each
day, which works out to a new subscriber every 1.3 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It took 16 years to get to 100 million mobile users. By
contrast, it took 54 years for TV sets to reach 100 million
households; it took cars 68 years to reach 100 million parking
spaces, and it took 91 years for telephone land lines to reach 100
million customers.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten to where cell phones even provide column fodder for
such renowned pundits as William Safire of The New York Times.
Safire recently keyboarded a column on behalf of beleaguered folks
who do not ``wish to hear any of their tidbits or their stock
trading results that they discuss over their little wireless
phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Safire rarely employs e-mail and never uses his cell phone while
crossing the street. But I rather suspect that Jacob Javits,
Safire's onetime friend and my former boss, whose centennial falls
due soon, might have been known to his admirers as the Mobile
Senator.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
