<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-PARTIES28-COX     07-27 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PARTIES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IT'LL BE A GRAND OLD PARTY IN PHILLY
 &HT;    Moving in (p) politics and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The thought of Republicans convening in the City
of Brotherly Love doesn't exactly inspire boogie-down images of
``Animal House.''
</P>
<P>
   But convention planners swear it's gonna be a grand old party.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there will be scads of parties for the 5,000 or so
delegates and alternates, 15,000 journalists and media technicians,
and uncounted legions of lobbyists, campaign contributors and
assorted political groupies already assembling for the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not counting Sunday's parade featuring Corpzilla, a
giant paper-mache multi-national financial monster, an anti-death
penalty Executioners Ball, and other activities planned by the
20,000 protesters who aim to crash the scene.
</P>
<P>
   W.C. Fields wasn't praising his home town's party-hearty
attitude when he suggested that his epitaph say: ``On the whole,
I'd rather be in Philadelphia.'' But this historic city founded by
Quakers is likely to be a lively place starting Saturday and
continuing through Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   From the protesters pounding on plastic buckets in the streets
to delegate gatherings featuring musicians ranging from Blues
Traveler to Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Philly will throb with beats you can
dance to.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Clark is returning to the birthplace of ``American
Bandstand'' to emcee two GOP shindigs.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., recruited Clark _
along with Bobby Vee, the Shirelles and the Four Tops _ for a
Sunday night oldies show at the Pennsylvania National Guard Armory.
</P>
<P>
   The following night, Clark will be watching dancers bop and
twist at a ``Bandstand'' reunion of sorts at the Enterprise Center,
which was the TV studio when the show was produced in Philadelphia.
The singers this time will be aging home boys Chubby Checker, Bobby
Rydell and Frankie Avalon. This affair was arranged by Rep. Michael
Oxley, R-Ohio, whose wife, Pat, grew up in Philadelphia and danced
on ``Bandstand'' as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley, who would like to become chairman of the House Commerce
Committee, is in a let-the-good-times-roll competition with Rep.
Billy Tauzin, R-La., who has similar ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin is wooing committee colleagues with crawfish rather than
cheese steaks. On Tuesday night, he's hosting a huge Mardi
Gras-flavored party at the Naval Business Center's cruise ship
terminal. This time, the dancing will be to Bayou fiddles and
guests will feast on jambalaya and other Cajun fare prepared by
chef Jimmy Gravois, the congressman's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the salsa beat, Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., predicts
the ``premiere party'' will be the Wednesday night fiesta featuring
Latin music at the Shampoo Night Club. Jon Secada, a Cuban-born
singer from Miami, will perform at the event honoring the House
Entertainment Industry Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these events have corporate backing. For instance,
sponsors of the Latin music party include the Recording Industry
Association of America, the Motion Picture Association of America,
Time Warner, the Walt Disney Corp., Viacom and Seagram/Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for the sake of equal political opportunism, many of
the same corporations and trade associations will be sponsoring
parties for the Democrats when they convene in Los Angeles in a
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Other political parties of note: the Temptations will sing at
tribute for Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., on Sunday at the Reading
Terminal train shed. Michael J. Fox and Heather Locklear will
mingle at George Magazine's benefit for Parkinson's Disease
research on Wednesday at a Kenneth Cole store. Blues Traveler will
perform at a Monday night concert hosted by House Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas. Boxers Joe Frazier, Michael Spinks, Larry Holmes and Roy
Jones Jr. will mix it up _ socially that is _ with guests of the
National Republican Senatorial Committee's ``Fight Night'' party at
the cruise ship terminal.
</P>
<P>
   And it'll all climax with Brooks &AMP; Dunn starring at a
boot-scootin' boogie for George W. and Laura Bush after Thursday
night's acceptance speech by the Texas governor and Republican
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, though, Philadelphia will have thrown a few parties
itself.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, the city will welcome delegates with a parade
of lighted boats and fireworks on the Delaware River and a
``Stately Dessert'' at the Camden Waterfront. The desserts include
Philadelphia water ice, Pennsylvania shoofly pie, New York
cheesecake, Florida key lime pie and ``Texas Brown Sugar Cookies''
made from Laura Bush's recipe.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a summer Mummer's Parade and Wawa Hoagie Day will
give the delegates a taste of two Philadelphia traditions. The
costumed Mummers will give a rendition of the parade they have
performed every New Year's Day since 1901. Wawa _ a local chain of
convenience stores _ will break its own hoagie record by
constructing a 6,700 foot sandwich. Willard Scott will get to eat
the first slice.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of sandwiches, on Wednesday, delegates will be bused to
South Philly's open-air Italian Market for a ``Carnevale'' with
cheese steaks, sausage-and-pepper subs and pasta.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mega-events, there will be scores of cocktail
parties, brunches, lunches (including a huge one for Laura Bush
hosted by the National Federation of Republican Women on Wednesday)
and assorted other activities. For instance, House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., is taking some campaign contributors fly-fishing,
and there will be golf outings and a fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said DeLay has made elaborate efforts as a ``thank you''
to Republican House members. A train has been parked near the First
Union Center stocked with food and drink and computers and news
wires and TVs. Members of Congress can ride over on golf carts if
they need a break from the convention _ or its parties.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.gophila.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
