<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4512 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-QUESTION-COLUM     07-27 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-QUESTION-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ONE QUESTION ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, July 27, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least once a week I'm hit with the question: ``How long does
it take you to write one of those columns of yours?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when I would give a long, self-indulgent,
it's-not-as-easy-as-it-looks kind of answer, something along the
lines of:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well of course, it all depends on the subject matter. It can
take a few hours, or it can take days or even weeks to put together
a single column, which is why I work on several of them
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, I might have to make phone calls, interview people,
attend events or press conferences, do library and Internet
research _ all sorts of things like that. And then sometimes I do
all that legwork, only to come to the hard conclusion that what I
have isn't a column at all, so I have to start from scratch and
come up with something before my deadline ...''
</P>
<P>
   And that's when I'd start to see the glazed look in their eyes.
Nobody cares that much, unless it's another columnist who wants to
be reassured that it's not any easier for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   So now when people ask me how long it takes to write a column, I
affect a slightly British accent and say, ``Exactly three hours and
16 minutes, every time. Quite odd, actually, but I don't question
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems to satisfy folks.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what you do for a living, there seems to be that one
question you'll hear again and again _ and the inquisitor is
inevitably under the mistaken impression that you've never heard
such an insightful and marvelously curious piece of interrogation
in your lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the theory that was advanced in a recent
conversation among colleagues, and the more I thought about it, the
more I believed this theory. Every job has its built-in question.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a cop, people want to know if you've ever had to fire
your gun.
</P>
<P>
   If you fought in a war, the question, of course, is, ``Did you
kill anyone?''
</P>
<P>
   If you work with someone famous, everyone wants to know:
``What's the celebrity really like?''
</P>
<P>
   (The answer to this question is usually, ``Oh, he's so nice!''
But let's be honest, it's much more interesting to hear, ``Oh, he's
an incredible jackass!'' For instance, when I was working in radio
... ah, just kidding.)
</P>
<P>
   Pizza parlor employees, I'll wager, are always asked if they're
sick of America's favorite food, what with making it and smelling
it and delivering it for eight hours at a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Bartenders are asked if they water down the drinks. Or maybe
it's: ``Do you get to drink for free?''
</P>
<P>
   Toll booth workers? We want to know when and where they go to
the bathroom!
</P>
<P>
   And if you're a gynecologist, the boor who's had three martinis
at the party probably gives you a nudge and asks ...
</P>
<P>
   Well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at a party, I never tell people I work for a
prestigious Wall Street investment company,'' says a friend of
mine. ``If I do, I'm swarmed with questions about stocks. So I just
say I sell insurance; nobody corners you to ask a million questions
about insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but there's probably some query that insurance brokers are
sick of hearing. Probably something along the lines of, ``Why do my
rates keep going up if I haven't been in an accident in 14 years?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me how much of a discount I get on
clothes,'' says a friend who works at an upscale store. ``Isn't
that kind of rude when you think about it? I mean, I don't ask
about the perks or benefits of their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure is rude. So anyway, how much of a discount do you get?
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty percent. Sweet deal, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   What's the one question about work that you always hear? And
what's your response? I'd like to test my theory, with your help.
Drop me a line at 401 N. Wabash, Chicago, 60611; or e-mail me at
rroeper &LR; suntimes.com with a brief description of your job, the
question you're sick of and your response.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps you've got a job that doesn't lend itself to any kind
of one-question curiosity. I'd like to hear about that too.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, hardly anybody ever asks the real question that pops
into mind, no matter what the profession _ the question that would
fly out of all of our mouths if we were injected with truth serum:
</P>
<P>
   ``So how much do you make doing that?''
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the ROEPER
COLUMN and other features. &QL;
</P>
