anytime thereafter:
</P>
<P>
   BANKS ARE SLOW TO MOVE ONLINE, BUT SO ARE THEIR CUSTOMERS
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECOM-ONLINE-BANKING-NYTSF _ Unlike online stock trading,
online banking has not, so far, taken off. Why? ``The advent of
Net-only banks seems so exciting,'' says Bruce Zimmerman, a senior
vice president of Chase Manhattan Bank. ``But the reality is, there
aren't many customers who want to do everything only over the Net.
That's why you've seen that Net-only models haven't been
successful.'' By Patrick McGeehan. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   ASSESSING ONLINE EXCHANGES: FROM ONE EXPERT, A MIXED GRADE
</P>
<P>
   BC-ECOM-ONLINE-EXCHANGES-NYTSF _ The frenzy to find
business-to-business uses of the Internet is prompting people to
create online exchanges where companies will be able to trade
everything from sheet steel to hotel sheets. Eric K. Clemons, a
professor in the Information Strategy, Systems and Economics group
at the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania in
Philadelphia, says that many of them are doomed to repeat the
mistakes of their financial predecessors. A Q&AMP;A. By Saul Hansell.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
