<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4527 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-ONLINE-EXCHANGES     07-27 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-ONLINE-EXCHANGES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING ONLINE EXCHANGES: FROM ONE EXPERT, A MIXED GRADE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: One B&AMP;W photo is available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By SAUL HANSELL  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   The bull market has not just been on the stock exchange but in
exchanges themselves. The frenzy to find business-to-business uses
of the Internet is prompting people to create online exchanges
where companies will be able to trade everything from sheet steel
to hotel sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Eric K. Clemons, a professor in the Information Strategy,
Systems and Economics group at the Wharton School of the University
of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia, says that many of them are doomed
to repeat the mistakes of their financial predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   He discussed the lessons from the financial markets in a recent
series of e-mail messages. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Electronic-trading exchanges first began opening in financial
markets 15 years ago, amid great skepticism by traditional traders
that they would work. Why did some work and others not?
</P>
<P>
   CLEMONS: I guess the biggest difference between success and
failure continues to be liquidity. When there are enough buyers and
sellers to determine an effective price, then online trading can
occur.
</P>
<P>
   If buyers and sellers are widely separated in time, and if there
is little information on ``comparables'' to help buyers or sellers
determine fair prices, then intermediaries will continue to serve
an essential function. Thus, I would not expect to see real-estate
agents disappear anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, exchanges didn't help instruments that no one
understands or no one wants to trade, such as contracts tied to
hurricanes in Florida, the cost of cellular air time in August in
midtown Manhattan or other forms of catastrophic risk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But online exchanges also failed in the United States in some
very liquid markets, such as futures.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMONS: It's hard to get market participants to leave a
structure that's liquid and working well, even if it is not working
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, online trading has captured markets abroad where there had
been no previous exchange or where the existing stock market had
been less efficient and more expensive than its U.S. equivalents.
Online trading in the U.S. continues principally to provide
lower-cost access to existing exchanges, rather than replacing
these existing exchanges, in general because they have been doing
such a good job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what sort of industrial markets will be most suited to
online exchanges?
</P>
<P>
   CLEMONS: The invisible hand of the marketplace does the best job
when buyers and sellers are fragmented and thousands of small
orders interact simultaneously. This is true whether I want to buy
1,000 shares of IBM at the current price on a stock exchange or if
I want to buy 1,000 standard memory chips in one of the emerging
industrial exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The guiding principle here is that the random flow of small
orders is sufficient to assure that the market finds the right
price.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what about the proposed exchanges in industries like auto
parts, where there are a handful of buyers and not all that many
sellers of each type of item?
</P>
<P>
   CLEMONS: If the order flow is heavily concentrated in a small
number of buyers or a small number of sellers, or if delivery must
be carefully coordinated and scheduled between buyer and seller,
then an exchange is likely to be less effective.
</P>
<P>
   If I need several million fuel injectors or pistons, an
exchange-based market will not be my best alternative. If my
pistons arrive too late, my production line will shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In business environments such as these, I will want to carefully
negotiate order quantities and delivery schedules, quality levels
and purchase prices.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A lot of people say the real value of the exchanges in the
long run won't be the lower transaction costs or even the lower
prices, but the efficiencies throughout the production stream that
would flow from the instant, universal, transparent demand
information being shared. I take it you don't completely agree.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMONS: That's right. For some industries full transparency
will indeed produce allocative efficiency _ by setting the right
prices, based on aggregating supply and demand, the product will
end up in the hands of the customers who value it most highly. In
industries with rapidly evolving products _ personal computers _
this might indeed be a new and optimal design.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases the key issue is not determining the right price,
but scheduling delivery of the right quantity at the right time.
Ford or GM might be more concerned with assuring that spark plugs
and fuel injectors arrive in the right-sized batches at precisely
the right times to avoid disrupting their assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the right quantity of products at the right time is
closer to traditional supply-chain optimization than it is to the
design of trading mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some people argue that one benefit of these new exchanges is
that they open up world markets, allowing a small steelmaker in
Thailand to find a buyer in Peru. Does that make sense?
</P>
<P>
   CLEMONS: Globalization of markets and exchanges, likewise, will
be important only if buyers and sellers have a real need for global
access. But when they do, geographical separation appears to be no
longer relevant as a barrier to trading, as long as the item's
description is clear enough to be described online without too much
ambiguity, and its value is sufficient to justify shipping costs.
</P>
<P>
   I will admit that the online trading of Beanie Babies through
eBay caught me pretty much by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
