<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IS IT REAL OR IS IT VIRTUAL? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After the Air France Concorde fell in flames
from the sky, an American musician who witnessed the crash told
reporters, ``It looked just like virtual reality.''
</P>
<P>
   We all know what he meant. It's not that the crash was any less
horrific to this young man, or that his mind is controlled by an
unholy alliance of Sega and Industrial Light and Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of us, he simply sees the world as if through a
cathode ray tube. That's the way we're used to seeing things, and
the way we talk is with the language of the media.
</P>
<P>
   Reality is almost as realistic as computerized special effects.
A hurricane is imperfectly horrendous, unlike George Clooney's
perfect storm. Kids shoot down their classmates as if they were
playing a video game, or so some witnesses said at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   After a plane crash, a hurricane or a mass shooting, the scene
is invariably described by someone who never went to war but
watched a lot of war movies as looking ``like a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The trenches of the First World War were described as looking
like slaughterhouses, but that term has lost literal meaning. Most
Americans have never seen an animal slaughtered, except for that
rat on ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene was a little too realistic and caused an uproar, even
among those who hire mercenaries from Orkin to slaughter rodents en
masse.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual reality, big deal, big cliche. Virtual unreality is the
order of the day, and ``Survivor'' is the summer's leading example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' is a bomb because the idea of locking a dozen
boring people in a house together is too close to a certain
reality. It's like college, all talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' in contrast, offers fake jungle escapism for
viewers trapped in the virtual real life of cell phones, beepers,
Palm Pilots and personal computers. Lords of the computer files get
to watch people just like them playing Lord of the Flies.
</P>
<P>
   And now all kinds of things once considered reality are
described in ``Survivor'' terms.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because politicians are so close to virtual unreality to
begin with, every political commentator in America has used
``Survivor'' metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   You have to admit, the idea of stranding George W. Bush and Al
Gore on an island not named Martha's Vineyard is a very appealing
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Political conventions are a prime example of virtual unreality.
But unlike ``Survivor,'' this summer no one will be watching
because the conventions are rigged, rehearsed and we know who the
winners will be.
</P>
<P>
   Political strategists are talking about the ``story line'' each
convention will present on behalf of the candidates, but we're too
media-wise to buy that kind of stuff. We want real virtual
unreality. Yuppies showing off tattoos and jungle rot with skimpy
bathing suits is as virtually unreal as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   We won't be watching those conventions. Besides, the only bare
flesh and tattoos will be outside the convention halls among the
anarchists.
</P>
<P>
   The more I think about it, the more it makes sense that an
airhead nonentity named George W. Bush stands a very good chance of
being elected president of the United States. After 50 years of
television, vacuity makes us feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Who cares if Bush has a brain? He has the best of advisers, and
a very serious running mate, to take its place.
</P>
<P>
   The proof that the nation has become virtually unreal is the
polling that says voters agree with Gore's position on the major
issues, but prefer to elect Bush as president.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't even a matter of style over substance, since Bush
doesn't have any more style than Gore. It's the comfort of his
nothingness. He's as unreal as America feels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
