<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4538 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-27 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NO ROOM AT THE ER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Emergency room nurse Mary Comber was succinct
and direct in her open letter to the mayor of San Francisco and
Board of Supervisors:
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is bad and getting worse . . . Will the city
step up and do the right thing?''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is that an unholy number of drunk or drugged-out
indigent San Franciscans are adding a dangerous load to the city's
already-burdened emergency medical services network.
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it?
</P>
<P>
   Comber's letter was signed by 345 nurses, doctors, paramedics
and other employees of every emergency room in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As the size of the city's drunk and drug-addicted population has
increased over the past few years, a 1997 change in police
department policy has added to the problem of dealing with and
caring for them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of automatically arresting a drunk or out-of-it addict
and letting him or her ``sleep it off'' in jail, cops are required
to take all but the most pulled-together to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, if a person is found lying or sitting in a public
place, with altered mental status and unable to walk, he/she is
taken to a city ER for evaluation,'' wrote Comber.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . The result is that the city emergency rooms have to
devote much-needed beds to patients who are inebriated and
generally have no other medical problem.''
</P>
<P>
   At Davies Medical Center, where Comber is a nurse, that can mean
almost half the ER's 11 beds are filled with people whose only
physical problem is being loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Comber and her colleagues say many of the city's strung-out may
be unable to stay clean and sober, but they have grown very
sophisticated about the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``People apprehended in the commission of a crime, or for public
intoxication, know they need only state that they have chest pain
or are unable to walk or are going to have a seizure, and an
ambulance will be called,'' Comber wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these patients refuse to leave the hospital after
being medically screened, and become verbally or physically
abusive, requiring hospital security to become involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, ``It is not unusual to see the same inebriated
individuals more than once in the same day.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one upside to habitual ER patients _ or ``frequent
flyers,'' as they are nicknamed by paramedics: ER staffs have a
clue about their medical history.
</P>
<P>
   The city's ERs are at or over capacity and thus spend more time
than ever on divert. Ambulance drivers spend more time roving the
streets and working the radio, trying to find an ER with an open
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the medical records of a drunk or drugged-out
patient may be in one of several hospitals; more time and energy
must be expended locating them.
</P>
<P>
   Once the patient has sobered up or come down, a companion ordeal
begins for ER staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually the shelters fill up by early evening and the Central
Referral line is no longer available to hospital personnel,''
Comber wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The only option is for a nurse or other employee to call ``every
shelter in town hoping for a bed or a chair. If none can be found
and the patient is discharged to the street, they very often come
right back again or end up at another ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Comber and her colleagues say that the hole created by closure
of the 500-bed Mission Rock Emergency Shelter _ to make way for a
parking lot at the new baseball park _ has never been repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ER staffers at Davies have even taken to donating clean clothes
for sobered-up patients who need them. But they ``simply cannot
keep up with the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Comber's letter begs city officials to understand the severity
of the problem and to do something concrete to help alleviate it _
like create a dry-out facility where the drug and alcohol-impaired
can be taken by cops and watched by medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is to do nothing until ``the situation'' gets so
bad that someone in need of real emergency medical care dies for
want of attention or bed space.
</P>
<P>
   As Comber warned in her letter:
</P>
<P>
   ``On a recent day in June, with no earthquake, no major trauma
incident and cool temperatures, six of the 10 ERs in San Francisco
were closed to ambulance traffic by 7 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   To repeat her question: Will the city step up and do the right
thing?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
