<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYT-WORLD-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for &UR; FRIDAY,
July 28,  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH (Paris) _ Developments in the investigation of
the crash Tuesday of an Air France Concorde. Investigators are
analyzing the contents of the plane's black boxes. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ The government has dropped the fraud
case against Vladimir Gusinsky, the anti-Kremlin media mogul whose
prosecution raised fears of a crackdown on the press. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Developments in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace efforts. (Staff byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CARDINAL-MURDER (Mexico City) _ An investigation of the
1993 murder of a cardinal in the Roman Catholic Church has been
inconclusive. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category or as noted)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DNA-TESTS (Los Angeles) _ Prosecutors in southern
California plan to offer free DNA tests to some inmates which may
overturn their convictions. San Diego County prosecutors have been
reviewing the cases of about 560 inmates to determine whether DNA
tests developed since their convictions can link biological
evidence from a crime scene to someone other than the person
convicted. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-GRASSHOPPERS (Hamilton, Texas) _ It is not quite the
biblical plague of locusts, but grasshoppers are chewing up East
Texas at a rate not seen in years. By Ross W. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ Statistics released by the New York
Police Department show a marked increase in disciplinary actions
against police officers over the past three years, which the police
department says demonstrates increased vigilance in punishing
misconduct. Critics contend that the department has manipulated the
numbers to avoid federal oversight. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CONFIDENTIAL-SALARIES (Undated) _ The U.S. job market may be
extraordinarily employee-friendly these days, but that does not
necessarily mean you get to talk about your expanding paycheck and
bonuses. Some managers still warn employees not to discuss pay,
under penalty of dismissal. Now, pay-confidentiality policies are
being attacked by working-women's groups with the argument that the
policies perpetuate wage discrimination. By Mary Williams Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-RULING (Undated) _ On a judge's order Wednesday that
barred Napster from allowing the exchange of copyrighted music over
the Internet. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-RULING-REACT (Undated) _ What users of Napster are saying
about the judge's decision. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   TELEKOM-VOICESTREAM (Undated) _ On how Deutsche Telekom plans to
overcome resistance to its proposed $50.7 billion acquisition of
VoiceStream. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-VIETNAM-TRADE (Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam) _ On the
prospects for increased commercial ties between Vietnam and the
United States once the agreement to normalize trade relations is
ratified. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   NY-OUTDOOR-SCULPTURE (New York) _ When it comes to outdoor
sculpture in New York City this summer, the animal kingdom seems to
have walked off with the main prizes. For quality and sheer size
there is Jeff Koons' ``Puppy,'' a 43-foot-tall flower-covered
sculpture in the shape of a West Highland terrier. For quantity,
ubiquity, relentless aw-shucks hokeyness and stupidity at toxic
levels, the prize goes hoofs down to ``Cow Parade,'' a herd of
nearly 500 life-size fiberglass heifers. Even without these two
unusual occurrences, the summer's outdoor sculpture offerings cover
a great range, especially if you stretch your definition of public
sculpture. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   MONGOLIA-RELIGIOUS-ART (New York) _ Mongolia, the land of
Genghis Khan, windswept steppes and tough ponies, is seldom
associated with religious art. Yet such art always thrived there,
in the expressive ritual forms of a native shamanism and in gilded
icons produced in Buddhist monasteries. ``Dancing Demons:
Ceremonial Masks of Mongolia'' at the Asia Society presents masks
and other objects. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   MONNIER-DANCE-REVIEW (New York) _ On the French avant-garde
Mathilde Monnier dance troupe at the Lincoln Center Festival. By
Anna Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   GIRL-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Girl on the Bridge,'' a
soap-bubble of romantic attitude and second-hand glamour, Patrice
Leconte succeeds by discovering something sexier than sex, at once
a perfect metaphor and a convincing substitute for it. By A.O.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   WIND-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Iranian director Abbas Kiarostami's
absorption in the wide emptiness of the rural Iranian landscape, in
a remote corner of which ``The Wind Will Carry Us'' takes place,
yields views that seem almost otherworldly in their clarity and
depth. By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Michael Winterbottom's
``Wonderland'' could be called ``The Three Sisters'': a modern-day
London turn on Chekhov, it deals with the anguish of three women
whose lives are in varying stages of disintegration. Reviewed by
Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
