<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4564 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-EMMY-RULES-1000(2Take     07-27 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-RULES-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER NEW RULES, EMMY VOTERS CAN VIEW AND CHOOSE WINNERS FROM THEIR
HOMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Every year or so someone has a problem with
the Emmy Awards, whether it's an overabundance of nominations,
apples-and-oranges categories, astonishing lapses in logic, or the
telecast itself, which moves along with all the grace of a garbage
barge.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Marshall, chairman and CEO of the Academy of Television
Arts &AMP; Sciences (ATAS), has heard the complaints and logged them
accordingly. She admits that, in a 200-channel universe, trying to
locate the gems of TV programming scattered over networks, cable
and syndication can be a tiresome, thankless task, certainly one
that invites second-guessing.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason alone, Marshall appears to be holding firm on
the latest tweaking of how shows are selected for Emmy
consideration. It's a change that could drastically alter which
stars, producers and writers we see trot out to the podium at the
Los Angeles Shrine Auditorium, and because of Emmy's power to lift
a series out of the ratings gutter, it may even alter what kind of
shows we see in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now in existence for 52 years, the Emmys has long relied on an
arcane procedure in which final winners are chosen by ``judging
panels'' _ actors, directors, producers and the like herded into
hotel rooms and ballrooms over a selected weekend to spend hours
screening one Emmy candidate after another.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the academy decided to amend that process,
partly because only between 1,000 to 1,500 of the 9,000 ATAS
members would show up, participate on panels and vote. That means a
category like, say, best drama series could have fewer than 100
people determining who wins. For technical areas it could be as
many as 70 _ or as few as seven.
</P>
<P>
   Now cassettes of every contending show are mailed directly to
voters, allowing panelists to watch tapes at home at their leisure.
The goal is to include more voters in the judging and therefore
produce a broader sampling of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   It also lets those most active and busy in the TV industry
participate, because the criticism has been that most of the judges
are retirees more than happy to escape to the Beverly Hilton Hotel
_ but a group less likely to embrace risk-taking fare on cable, or
even younger-skewing network series such as ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' an often-praised drama that has never even been nominated
during its four seasons on the WB.
</P>
<P>
   ATAS claims this new process has already tripled the number of
people agreeing to participate as judges from last year _ about
4,000 so far.
</P>
<P>
   Although an adjustment in how tapes are seen had long been
discussed (members have always considered it a pain to be holed up
at a hotel watching TV practically all day long, except for lunch
and potty breaks), it finally happened after what's known here as
``The Sopranos'' Effect. When the HBO series, thought by critics to
be the best thing they'd seen in years, was denied last year's Emmy
for best drama (it went to ``The Practice''), critics mercilessly
scolded the academy for its oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall says the change had little to do with the ``Sopranos''
defeat per se. Instead, Marshall says, most significant was the
sense of the room (at the Emmys) last year. ``I looked around the
room and realized that there were a number of extremely qualified
people who were active members in the academy who had not
participated in the judging. And the sense was that we had to
figure out why and we had to make sure that they did.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's hardly the way to go about doing it, says Tom O'Neil,
a journalist who has made a career out of tracking awards shows. He
has authored beefy, everything-you-wanted-to-know books on the
Emmys and the Grammys and is currently working on a project that
combines all award shows.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil is convinced that ATAS members won't watch without
supervision and that the Emmys will be awarded based on the
opinions of their families, friends _ even waiters at their
favorite bistros.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when people don't watch a show is that they tend
to ask those around them what ``they'' think about such and such,''
says O'Neil. ``There are persistent allegations that shows in some
categories aren't watched in their entirety due to the absence of
supervisors at a particular panel session. So imagine if they're at
home with their everyday distractions. If voters don't watch the
tapes, they'll probably just vote for what's hip. That means not
only are underdog shows at risk, but underdog networks, too.''
</P>
<P>
   By underdogs O'Neil means shows liked by TV critics but
invisible to viewers and therefore susceptible to cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Cagney &AMP; Lacey,'' a one-hour drama considered unconventional
because it centered on two female detectives, was canceled during
the 1982-83 season after failing to get a sizable enough audience
to earn a renewal. Loyal viewers inundated CBS with letters, but
the network refused to change its stand. It wasn't until the series
won an Emmy that September as best drama that the network relented,
bringing the cop drama back in the spring of 1984 for what would
turn out to be a five-year run and, now, a legacy as a
groundbreaking series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hill Street Blues,'' the cop drama considered by some the best
hour-long series ever, and ``Cheers,'' certainly one of the
medium's best sitcoms, were also low-rated programs that parlayed
their Emmy wins into higher viewership at a time when their
survival was far from a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil has a point that the new method could suffer from an
age-old problem _ namely, people voting based on reputation instead
of watching and deciding who's most deserving. He cites Chris
Rock's 1997 expletive-laden comedy special on HBO as an example,
saying unsupervised voters likely would have bailed on the viewing
early on. Instead, they were compelled to sit down, give it a
chance and find humor and poignancy through the four-letter words.
That Emmy virtually changed the direction of Rock's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we're working on an honor system here _ we give voters
the tape and expect them to watch it,'' says James B. Chabin, ATAS
president. ``Are we worried they won't? You know, the reason people
volunteer to do this is because they care about the shows and they
care about the Emmy and they want to make sure that the right
program succeeds in receiving it. For that alone, we think they'll
take the time to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Emmys' perception problem is endemic to television,
where series continue year after year, with only the occasional
intriguing newcomers _ such as ``The Sopranos'' and ``Sex and the
City'' last year or ``The West Wing'' this time around, shaking
things up.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison's sake, the Oscars are presented an entirely new
round of candidates every year, but even there the tendency is to
return to familiar faces. How many people still shake their heads
over the nomination last year of Meryl Streep?
</P>
<P>
   As for the Golden Globes, perceived to be more ``with it'' (it
named ``Sex and the City'' as top comedy), the 80 or so members of
the Hollywood Press Association seem to select their nominees based
on who they think are kinda cool, which isn't much different from
the way MTV does its back-patting shows.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil considers the Emmys the most accurate and fair prize
because it not only guarantees all nominees that their work will be
seen by voters, but in addition, unlike the Oscars or Grammys,
politics and sympathy voting rarely play a part in the selection
process.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Hartman, who was fatally shot by his wife, didn't get an
Emmy after his death, and even though the Golden Globes named
three-time Emmy winner (for ``Family Ties'') Michael J. Fox best
comedic actor for his work in ``Spin City,'' O'Neil doesn't expect
the same from the Emmy voters despite his current battle with
Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   If sentiment figured into voting, Angela Lansbury, who starred
in ``Murder, She Wrote,'' would not be the biggest Emmy loser, with
16 losses, and Jackie Gleason wouldn't have ended his career
Emmyless.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil may think that the Emmy Awards is the last ``pure''
bastion of awards shows, but aren't awards ceremonies by their very
nature political? I can't pick up a trade magazine here like
Variety or The Hollywood Reporter without seeing page after page of
``For your consideration'' ads, even for series and performers who
shouldn't even be on the air, let alone given television's top
prize. (Even O'Neil talks about nominations being ``bought.'')
</P>
<P>
   But studios now spend a combined $15 million placing print ads
to get the attention of voters (like for ``Biography'' on A&AMP;E,
which took out a full-page advertisement in Variety in hopes it
could land a nomination in the Outstanding Nonfiction Series
category).
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they realize they're not winning Emmys, they'll do
exactly what ABC and CBS did in 1965 when winners were still
determined by popular vote,'' O'Neil predicts. ``They'll quit the
Emmy race altogether. What saved the Emmys then was the
introduction of the judging panels. Now they want to kill the
panels, which, again, shows that television will forever be a
medium that simply can't learn from its past mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0086 </DOCNO>
