<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NAPSTER ON HOLD AFTER MIDNIGHT FRIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Attention Napster users: You have until midnight
Friday to download all the free, copyrighted music your hard drive
can handle.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the controversial, music-swapping Web site will most
likely be out of business.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Napster lawyers said after a federal judge
enjoined the Internet company from enabling the ``duplication of
all copyrighted songs, musical compositions of which the plaintiffs
hold rights,'' effective midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary injunction stems from a lawsuit filed against
Napster by the Recording Industry Association of America alleging
the Web site's file-sharing software is costing the music business
millions, if not billions of dollars, in royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Napster users can log onto the company's Web site
(www.napster.com) and then swap digital music files with one
another, including copyrighted tunes ranging from Johnny Cash to
Limp Bizkit.
</P>
<P>
   Music industry professionals hope Wednesday's ruling will set a
precedent, helping to shut myriad other sites that allow similar
downloading, including the popular Gnutella and FreeNet sites.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel handed down the
injunction after a spirited, three-hour court hearing that
highlighted the intellectual property debate that has raged on the
Internet for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Napster has countered the charges by saying it has nothing to do
with the swapping of copyrighted material.
</P>
<P>
   It simply created software that enables the swapping of digital
music, or MP3, files over the Internet. According to Napster's
all-star legal team, any illegal swapping going on is not the
company's problem.
</P>
<P>
   Patel did not buy Napster's song.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of Napster users use the service to download and
upload copyrighted material,'' the judge said. ``This should be no
surprise to Napster. The defendant had actual or constructive
knowledge that third parties engaged in direct copyright
infringement by downloading files using the Napster service.''
</P>
<P>
   In her ruling, Patel repeatedly said the RIAA, on behalf of its
member record companies, had proved ``a strong likelihood of
success on the merits'' of their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Barry, the chief executive of Napster, based in San Mateo,
Calif., said the company would appeal the ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
