<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FACE TEST IN CROSS-CONTINENTAL JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Off they went, 24 players (and a suspendee) in search of their
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, rained out of Wednesday's game against Minnesota at
Fenway, sloshed westward on an 18-day, 16-game transcontinental
odyssey that could determine how their first season of the century
shakes out.
</P>
<P>
   With their star slugger, Carl Everett, watching from the
sideline, the Sox begin their bicoastal challenge with four games
against Oakland, which leads the American League wild-card race by
2 games over Anaheim and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Sox play three in Seattle against the top team in the
AL West before they red-eye home for three more against Kansas
City, only to dart away after that for six games in Anaheim and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the test we're going to have to pass if we're
going to make it,'' said Pedro Martinez, who is scheduled to pitch
Friday against the Athletics. ``This might be the trip that
dictates where we end up.''
</P>
<P>
   On a similar journey last year _ a 12-game, 14-day swing through
Seattle, Oakland, New York, and Cleveland _ the Red Sox surged to a
9-3 record, effectively blazing their wild-card path to the
playoffs. Martinez won his 20th and 21st games during the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go through hard times if you're going to make the
playoffs,'' said All-Star closer Derek Lowe. ``Last year, we played
extremely well on that September road trip. Hopefully, this one
will be a character-builder, too.''
</P>
<P>
   If not character building, the Sox are grasping for something to
solve their schizophrenia. This year, they burst into first place
in May, only to squander the top spot with a disastrous June. They
appeared on track to rebound in July, starting 13-7, but then they
lost two straight to Minnesota, the worst team in the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to be said for continuity, and we just don't
seem to have it right now,'' said catcher Scott Hatteberg. ``It's
tough to mesh together when things are as volatile as they have
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Most volatile has been Everett, whose head-butt of umpire Ronald
Kulpa July 15 brought a 10-day suspension, which he began serving
Monday. Though Everett is hitting only .194 since the All-Star
Game, the Red Sox face the prospect of trying to break out of a
run-scoring drought (five runs in their last three games) without
him. He is not eligible to play until Aug. 4, the opener of the
Kansas City series.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Boston is about to play two teams (Oakland and Seattle)
that have produced far more runs than the Sox (502 runs). Oakland,
led by Jason Giambi (.334, 26 home runs, 91 RBIs), has scored 599
runs, and Seattle, faring just fine without Ken Griffey, has scored
572.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland, they're a nightmare because they are so free-swinging
and score so many runs,'' Hatteberg said. ``We really have to go in
and shut them down because they have good pitching, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, whose staff's ERA of 4.35 is second in the American
League to Boston's 4.19, also has the league's best home record
(33-16). The Sox are 24-23 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're going out there to beat up on some
mediocre teams,'' said Sox reliever Bryce Florie, who won a key
game in Seattle last year during the September trip. ``We have our
work cut out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After all their fits and starts, the Sox are hoping the
resurgence of Troy O'Leary (.400, 4 home runs, and 22 RBIs since
returning from the disabled list July 3) and the return of several
other key players will help them gain some stability.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among the recent returnees are right fielder Trot Nixon,
who missed a month with a strained hamstring, and reliever Rod
Beck, who had been plagued most of the season with a pinched nerve
in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bret Saberhagen, the two-time Cy Young Award winner
who is inching back from surgery for a torn rotator cuff.
Saberhagen, 36, could be back in the rotation in August, a
remarkable 13 years after he was first named the AL Comeback Player
of the Year (he repeated the feat in 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Beck said the team's prospects on the West Coast _ and the rest
of the season _ may hinge on the players' health.
</P>
<P>
   ``These West Coast teams we're playing, they're not exactly a
walk in the park,'' Beck said. ``But if everyone can stay out of
the training room, we can be good enough the rest of way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
