<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PEEP-BOS &LR;      07-27 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PEEP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEDIA COVERAGE, THE PERSONAL IS POLITICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
PEEP SHOW 
Media and Politics in an Age of Scandal 
By Larry J. Sabato, Mark Stencel, and S. Robert Lichter 
Rowman &AMP; Littlefield, 177 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did The Boston Globe err in writing about former mayor Raymond
Flynn's drinking habits? Did the media give Newt Gingrich a pass on
his less-than-conservative lifestyle? Is coverage of George W.
Bush's ``young and irresponsible'' past excessive?
</P>
<P>
   These are the ethical quandaries that Larry Sabato and two
colleagues bravely tackle in the aptly named ``Peep Show: Media and
Politics In The Age Of Scandal.'' In doing so, they try to answer
the question that has bedeviled the nation's news industry ever
since presidential hopeful Gary Hart was caught trysting the night
away with Donna Rice in 1987. What is fair game when it comes to
the private lives of public figures?
</P>
<P>
   In Sabato's 1991 book, ``Feeding Frenzy: How Attack Journalism
Has Transformed American Politics,'' the University of Virginia
professor of government tried to promulgate ground rules, most of
them sensible, for determining when reporters ought to rattle pols'
closets for skeletons. Though ``Feeding Frenzy'' turned Sabato into
an oft-quoted pundit on media malfeasance, its actual impact on
journalism is debatable.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics might say that in trying to codify a set of media
ethics, Sabato is trying to regulate the ungovernable. Indeed, the
effort is messy but still worthwhile. Perhaps feeling more needed
than ever, he is back in the post-Monica era with ``Peep Show,''
coauthored by Washingtonpost.com politics editor Mark Stencel and
S. Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media and Public
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line political reporters draw between private and public
life is perhaps more blurry than ever before. With increasing
regularity, that blurry line is the smudged chalk outline of an
ambitious politician,'' quip the authors.
</P>
<P>
   Point well taken. In an election season during which vaporous
tales of Bush's supposed partying habits and Al Gore's alleged
cannabis cravings have brought more disrepute to journalism than to
the candidates, the news industry is again thrashing clumsily
around the ``character issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peep Show'' is an earnest attempt to diagnose the problem,
restate Sabato's guidelines, and offer a scorecard on how various
media outlets have handled a variety of ``scandals.'' The diagnosis
is the book's least interesting aspect because many of the maladies
_ poor sourcing, lowest-common-denominator journalism (in which
less reputable media outlets drive the news), and the vagaries of
Internet reporting _ are tired staples of media criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The authors do come up with the intriguing notion that the
influx of women into the newsroom has spurred more reporting on
politicians' personal foibles, arguing that it ``demolished old-boy
networks that allowed reporters to wink and ignore certain behavior
among politicians, as they did among their colleagues.'' And they
make an intelligent argument that pols who ``humanize'' themselves
by yukking it up on the couch next to Jay Leno ``turn themselves
into human-interest stories'' who invite tabloid-style treatment.
(Although Bill Clinton's 1992 shades-n'-saxophone appearance on
Arsenio Hall's show may go down as one of the great PR coups in
campaign history.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Peep Show'' wisely encourages news executives, in their own
enlightened self-interest, to do a better job of explaining their
decisions to the public because ``readers and viewers rarely
appreciate just how much most journalists anguish over decisions to
publish damaging or embarassing details about a politician's
personal behavior.'' Translation: Unless journalists provide an
alternative theory, the public tends to ascribe to them the worst
possible motives.
</P>
<P>
   The book provides exemplary examples by reprinting Washington
Post executive editor Leonard Downie's 1992 explanation of why the
paper chose to publish allegations of sexual misconduct by Senator
Robert Packwood and Idaho Statesman editor Karen Baker's 1998
editorial detailing why her paper exposed a relationship between a
Congresswomen and a married man.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the eagerly awaited scoreboard. The authors give the
Globe a B for its coverage of Flynn's drinking by arguing that it
was ``ongoing private behavior . . . that was potentially
debilitating'' in the public arena. They give the press an F ``for
showing too much discretion'' in not aggressively pursuing the Newt
Gingrich infidelity story, arguing that the former House speaker's
personal conduct at the time when the president was enmeshed in a
sex scandal ``is potentially reckless behavior.'' (The authors
aren't prudes. They believe there are a number of circumstances
that justify media scrutiny of a misbehaving pol.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the media get a middling C for their attention to
Bush's partying. On one hand, Bush's ``admitted alcohol abuse
extended well into his adult years,'' which makes it significant.
On the other, journalists recklessly aired ``unproven rumors''
about his alleged drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The C might be a passing grade, but as ``Peep Show'' takes pains
to insist, it's sure no Gentlemen's C.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
