<HEADER>
A4576 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-27 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FBI'S PRIVACY PREDATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ever see an old movie called ``The FBI Story''?
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a masterpiece. Jimmy Stewart, tapering off from his
daring 1950s work with Hitchcock and Preminger, here plays a dull
and stolid G-guy, solemnly hunting down Ku Kluxers, gangsters, and
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   So why do I like this movie so much? Because I'd like to believe
that the nation's cops are all like Jimmy Stewart _ brave, decent
folk who defend the rights of the law-abiding, rather than run
around violating them.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this movie was made in 1959, and as the cameras were
rolling, so were the FBI's tape recorders. Head G-man J. Edgar
Hoover cheerfully used wiretaps, burglaries, and other police-state
tactics against thousands of law-abiding citizens whose political
views didn't suit him. Nowadays, Hollywood's idea of an FBI agent
is David Duchovny of ``The X Files,'' a good man swimming upstream
in a sewer.
</P>
<P>
   So you can understand why this Carnivore business has me
squirming. The FBI has admitted using a system that scans millions
of e-mails in search of messages from criminal suspects. Some
public-relations mastermind named the system Carnivore. I hope he
enjoys his new job as special agent in charge of Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
   Carnivore is software that runs on a computer using the Windows
NT operating system. When the FBI needs to see what a suspect is
pumping out over the Net, the agency gets a court order to install
a Carnivore computer at the suspect's Internet service provider.
Carnivore sits on the line, constantly scanning for data packets
with the suspect's e-mail address. All such packets are recorded.
</P>
<P>
   A high-tech wiretap? Almost, but not quite. With a traditional
telephone wiretap, the cops can only listen in to traffic on one
particular phone line. You can't do that with the Internet, because
data is chopped up in packets that can travel to their destination
any old way. The solution is to intercept all of the packets, and
then figure out which ones you actually need. So when Carnivore is
installed at an Internet provider, it's rummaging through the
messages of every customer in the joint.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union is predictably appalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no precedent for this in domestic surveillance,''
says its associate director, Barry Steinhardt. ``They're collecting
a lot of information about third parties, and no third party is
ever going to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to Carnivore sweeps right across the political
spectrum. During a congressional hearing on Monday, Republicans and
Democrats took turns teeing off on FBI officials.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows I sympathize with the libertarians. But what should
the cops do while criminals plan their nastiness online? Take up
needlepoint?
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as there are pedophiles and hackers and terrorists, we
need to talk about them, too,'' says Amitai Etzioni, author of
``The Limits of Privacy'' and professor at George Washington
University in Washington, D.C. Etzioni is a rarity among
intellectuals _ a guy who frankly supports a certain amount of
government snooping on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly because Etzioni trusts the FBI. Bureau officials
say Carnivore only captures data when an e-mail address matches
that of the suspect. The Carnivore computer screens out all other
data; no human eye ever sees it. For innocent bystanders, Carnivore
would be no more intrusive than any Internet router _ they scan
addresses too, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Denning, professor of computer science at Georgetown
University, has nothing but contempt for those who think the FBI
will use Carnivore to spy on people willy-nilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's totally stupid,'' says Denning. ``They can't do
that. It's against the law.'' Specifically, says Denning, it would
violate existing wiretap statutes.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI spokesman told me the agency plans next week to turn over
the source code of Carnivore to an independent agency. This unnamed
agency will have to promise not to reveal the details of how it
works, but will be allowed to describe in general terms what the
program can and cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU has also requested a copy of the Carnivore code under
the Freedom of Information Act, and Steinhardt told me that he's
willing to keep the code secret if the FBI hands it over for
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   An independent report showing that Carnivore isn't a privacy
predator would make me feel a lot better about it. So would a new
law strictly limiting how it could be used. I'd want all Carnivore
cases assigned to Jimmy Stewart _ or at least David Duchovny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
