<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-27 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAGIARISM'S MANY SHADES OF GRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like an infectious disease, a plagiarism-related virus rampaged
through newsrooms this month. The most notable case was The Boston
Globe's four-month suspension of columnist Jeff Jacoby for
``serious journalistic misconduct'' in borrowing elements of a
column on the signers of the Declaration of Independence. And
suddenly, the floodgates opened.
</P>
<P>
   In an editor's note, The New York Times admitted that parts of
an obituary ``closely reflected the phrasing of an obituary in The
Times of London.'' The sports editor of the San Antonio
Express-News apologized to readers for lifting several paragraphs
from another paper in a story he wrote. The reader advocate at the
St. Louis Post-Dispatch detailed how a columnist there failed to
attribute material from an Associated Press story. There was a
brief dust-up when a Salon.com staffer felt that a Colorado Springs
Gazette story was too reliant on a piece he had written.
</P>
<P>
   Was it coincidence that all this occurred around the time of the
Jacoby situation, which sparked debate over whether he was guilty
of plagiarism or just laziness? Or is heightened scrutiny of the
media leading to stricter enforcement amid surprisingly routine
violations? Does the news industry even have an agreed-upon set of
standards for recognizing the problem?
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the p-word, a number of observers echo Supreme
Court Justice Potter Stewart's musings on pornography. It may be
hard to define, but ``I know it when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a piece he wrote back in 1983, Roy Peter Clark, a journalism
instructor at the Poynter Center for Media Studies, called
plagiarism ``the skeleton in journalism's closet,'' adding that
`most newspapers have no rules'' and ``editors seem loath to define
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, changing technology has greatly compounded the
problem. Citing pressure for ``globalized reporting,''
computer-assisted journalism, and the Internet, Express-News editor
Robert Rivard says ``everybody is thrashing around'' to ``make sure
our management policies catch up to the technologies.'' Often,
today's plagiarism is ``not malice aforethought,'' he says. ``It's
the merging of data.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a common understanding of what
plagiarism is,'' adds Jerry Ceppos, president of the Associated
Press Managing Editors organization. ``It's like everything else in
life. There's a lot of grays there.''
</P>
<P>
   In examining ethical codes at 33 newspapers, Poynter Center
ethics program director Bob Steele found that only 13 of them
addressed plagiarism. And those that do may not offer much
guidance. The Society of Professional Journalists' Code of Ethics
deals with the subject in two terse words: ``Never Plagiarize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we wanted to simplify things,'' says SPJ ethics
chairman Fred Brown. ``I think we wanted to be very blunt . . . I
think it's impossible to quantify (plagiarism). Ultimately, it
rests with the editor, and the editor has to trust the writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe general policy guidelines, which acknowledge those shades
of gray, say that ``whenever a writer intentionally uses the
creative phrasing or ideas of another without crediting that
person, the result is plagiarism . . . If the words or ideas are
not original, but rather those of another person, we must, in an
appropriate place, give credit to him or her.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many media ethicists, Clark sees plagiarism as varying in
degrees and intensity. ``Pure plagiarism, I think, always has
intent as its sort of dark soul,'' he says, but ``plagiarism is not
like pregnancy. You can be a little bit plagiaristic . . . I've
never talked to an editor who didn't have a case he could cite.''
(During his 18 years at the San Jose Mercury News, Ceppos recalls
only one case, but then adds: ``I want to believe there was only
one case, but definitions vary.'')
</P>
<P>
   Take the divergent views of the Jacoby case, in which he relied
on several source materials for the signers' story and did
additional research. Globe editorial page editor Renee Loth calls
it a violation of Globe attribution policy, saying that Jacoby
``didn't just borrow a few phrases, but the whole concept of this
column has been borrowed.'' Globe ombudsman Jack Thomas called it
``plagiarism.'' Jacoby, who could not be reached for comment
Wednesday, called it ``an oversight'' in an earlier interview.
</P>
<P>
   In dueling columns in The Wall Street Journal, one writer argued
that Jacoby was guilty only of ``an error of judgment'' while
another skewered him for ``taking anonymous crud from the Internet
and throwing it into the paper'' with his name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Punishment for the unacceptable borrowing of others' work varies
dramatically as well. Express-News editor Rivard, who fired a
writer for ``wholesale plagiarism'' in 1997, says wayward sports
editor Mitchell Krugel was given a reprimand and the task of
apologizing to readers, calling that punishment ``appropriate to
the mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Times managing editor Bill Keller declined to discuss
the matter of punishment for obit writer Douglas Martin, but ``he
knows very well what he did was wrong . . . I won't pussyfoot
around the word. I'd call it plagiarism . . . our basic policy is
there are degrees'' of plagiarism and ``there's certainly a
difference in how you treat them.''
</P>
<P>
   In his article, Clark detailed a wide range of punishment for
various forms of plagiarism. In one 1982 case, a writer who had
lifted pieces for a story that ultimately won an American Society
of Newspaper Editors prize was allowed to keep both the prize and
his job. Two years ago, when Globe editors learned that columnist
Mike Barnicle had borrowed jokes from George Carlin _ and Barnicle
argued that he was unaware of their origin _ the original decision
was to suspend him for a month without pay. But after a videotape
of Barnicle recommending the book surfaced, he was asked to resign.
When he produced evidence that the material had been in wide use on
the Internet, the penalty was reduced to a two-month suspension.
Later, Barnicle was forced to resign, but over other issues
regarding a 1995 column.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts are wary of any attempt to codify the definitions
and penalties for plagiarism. ``We're pretty good at
self-policing,'' says Rivard. But ``we're not like the welders
where we're going to sign off on a new set of engineered
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark says that the challenge is for journalism to rethink the
question of ``what does it mean to be in the public domain.'' Media
outlets, he adds, should ``revisit all the important standards
cyclically (and) be willing to adjust them in the light . . . of
the complex and overwhelming development of new media
technologies.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
JACOBY VS. HARVEY: A COMPARISON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing Jacoby's July 3 column on the fate of the signers
of the Declaration of Independence, Globe managers found
similarities between numerous unattributed passages in the column
and other sources, most notably a 1975 copyrighted book by Paul
Harvey called ``Our Lives, Our Fortunes, Our Sacred Honor.'' What
follows are some examples cited by Globe managers.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey: ``They had learned that liberty is so much more
important than security that they pledged their lives . . . their
fortunes . . . and their sacred honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby: ``They were men of means and social standing, but for
the sake of liberty, they pledged it all _ their lives, their
fortunes, and their sacred honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey: ``His fields and gristmill were laid waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby: ``His fields and mill laid waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey: ``Fifty-six men knew _ when they signed _ that they were
risking everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby: ``They were risking everything and they knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey: ``And Thomas Nelson Jr., of Virginia, raised two million
dollars on his own signature to provision our allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby: ``Thomas Nelson Jr. of Virginia raised $2 million for
the patriots' cause on his own personal credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey: ``He died bankrupt and was buried in an unmarked
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby: ``He died bankrupt and was buried in an unmarked
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey: ``For more than a year, he lived in forests and caves
and returned home after the war to find his wife dead, his children
gone, his property gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby: ``While he hid in forests and caves, his home was
demolished. . . . When it was finally safe for him to return, he
found his wife dead, his children missing, and his property
decimated.''
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to friends written by Jacoby, he said that
``since all of the sources I relied on had in turn relied on even
earlier recitations, I assumed that all the material in my column
was in the public domain.''
</P>
<P>
   Editorial page editor Renee Loth says that regardless of the
history or distribution of material, ``readers have the right to
believe that material appearing under a reporter's byline
(including columnists) is original.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jurkowitz covers media issues for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     07-27 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUBU WORKS ONLINE MAGIC IN YOUR MUSICAL EAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you describe the sound of music?
</P>
<P>
   No, no, no, not ``The Sound of Music,'' as in the one with nuns
and Nazis and kids dressed in curtains. We are talking here about
the actual sound of music, that intangible essence that can stir
the emotions and caress the eardrums. How do you define that in
quantifiable terms? How do you write a mathematical equation for
something as elusive as taste?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are some folks in San Francisco who think they've
figured it all out, and _ guess what? _ they've started an Internet
company. These folks are convinced they can quickly surmise your
musical taste and instantly select a handful of albums you are
certain to adore. How do they do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the MuBu magic,'' says John Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? MuBu who?
</P>
<P>
   MuBu, it turns out, is short for Music Buddha, Inc., the company
Adams founded to create a sound-based music recommendation service.
Admittedly, the name doesn't exactly roll off your tongue, but
let's forget about that for now. The concept itself is actually
pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and his scientists have identified hundreds of
characteristics for thousands of songs, defining things like
instrumentation, tempo, feel, and mood for each track. They apply
these defining criteria (or data points) to each song, creating a
sort of musical DNA for the music. Users then listen to a handful
of sample songs and express their preferences; the system then
makes recommendations based on the individual's musical
``fingerprint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a friend who knows what kind of music you
like,'' says Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Right. A friend who makes tapes and burns CDs for you and
doesn't make you do something in return. And a computer does this?
We tried it (at www.mubu.com). The bad news: It requires you to
download a media player, which is always a pain, and the user
interface is clunky and slow. The good news: It actually makes
great recommendations _ most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works. You choose from a variety of narrow music
categories such as Anarchy or Ambient, Gospel or Evil, Tattoos and
Pool Cues or Lite Rock and EZ Pop. You then rate a series of song
clips, click on a Buddha that says ``Enlighten Me,'' and the system
recommends albums. In our unscientific study, three out of three
resident music experts here at the Globe approved of the
selections.
</P>
<P>
   It works much better than other Internet collaborative filtering
systems. For instance, if you ever order a book from Amazon about,
say, antique radios, they insist on trying to sell you books about
furniture for the rest of your life. The MuBu system offers things
you might consider buying _ but that's all it does. It doesn't
offer playlists or ways to store music. It simply links you to
places where you can buy CDs online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be the consumer's best friend,'' says Adams.
``We're not going to push Metallica at a jazz fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if they could only do something about that silly name. Oh,
they won't mind the advice: That's what friends are for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems like everyone wants to be our best friend these days _
at least when it comes to buying stuff online. First, there are the
experts at Contentville.com, the new site for voracious readers
launched by publisher Steven Brill. Apart from the fact that it
classifies all forms of the printed word with that annoying term
``content,'' the site is intriguing. Owners of small bookstores
offer recommendations about the latest novel or biography, and
authors share their reading lists. From afar, you can compare notes
with Wendy Wasserstein or Wendy Kaminer.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can purchase the dissertation written by your favorite
academic or celebrity. For instance, you can pick up Dr. Ruth
Westheimer's tome, ``An Investigation of the Effectiveness of
Paraprofessionals in Increasing the Use of Postpartum and Family
Planning Services By Women from Lower Socio-Economic Backgrounds in
an Urban Setting.'' It was obviously penned before she took on such
topics as ``The Art of Arousal.''
</P>
<P>
   Another site, www.moodlogic.com wants to be your best friend,
regardless of your mood. The site, which launched last month,
purports to categorize songs for every special moment, from upbeat
and happy to brooding and aggressive. We asked it to find some
brooding, raspy jazz by a female vocalist: Alas, it came up blank.
The system, it seems, was having a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group named Artists Against Piracy placed full-page
ads in several newspapers on the day that folks from the music
industry were testifying about digital music distribution in
Congress. The ad, signed by artists ranging from Aimee Mann to
Vince Gill, supported Metallica in its lawsuit against Napster.
</P>
<P>
   So who is funding this new organization? Think hard. Did you say
the Recording Industry Association of America, the trade group that
represents the major record labels? Two points! The ads didn't note
that point, but the group's founder, singer-songwriter Noah Stone,
says that his group received ``a little chunk of change'' from the
industry, as well as from a few technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a group of independent artists launched a lobbying
group called the Coalition for the Future of Music, which aims to
speak up for the rights of artists without aligning itself with big
business interests. Its cofounder, activist and musician Jenny
Toomey, says she supports the other group's high-profile advocacy
campaign. Stone, however, says he hopes the two groups can join
forces. ``The more groups we have, the more confused this gets,''
he notes. But Toomey is adamant. She won't take money from the
industry. Period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send e-mail to hartigan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
