<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-27 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD SMASHES TAURUS EGGS, BUILDS A RIG THAT WON'T CRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere in the rooms where they cook up the design recipes for
Fords, somebody must have decided to make an omelet. Smash the
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Ford Taurus is almost totally lacking (except for the
Ford badge itself) those oval/egg-shaped patterns that ran through
windows, door panels, pillars, body panels, even the dashboard
control panel. In its last incarnation, it was easy to spot a
Taurus on the street. But it's also easy to spot a squeegee man.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, we can say the new Taurus is devoid of the ovoid.
</P>
<P>
   It is more square _ yet somehow sleeker _ and almost Focus-like
with its gently wedged hood, squinted-eye headlights, smooth rise
through the roof, and chopped back-end.
</P>
<P>
   But looks, vastly improved that they are, do not comprise the
essence of the new Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk safety.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only car sold in America with a base price under
$20,000 (you'll pay more for top-end versions) to win the
government's five-star crash rating for both the driver and
front-seat passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The Advanced Restraints System is the answer. In a crash,
most people don't know what is happening to them and many don't
remember much after it is over. ARS knows. It is made up of a batch
of sensors that can tell if the front seat belts are being used;
how close to the dash the driver is sitting; how hard the crash is.
It uses this information to decide whether or not to tighten the
seat belts _ in a lower-speed crash _ or to relax them just a bit,
and thus avoid belt-caused injuries, in a harsher crash.
</P>
<P>
   Air bag deployment is softer in a lesser crash, more forceful in
a harder crash.
</P>
<P>
   Even before leaving the driveway, with the optional ($120)
adjustable pedals, shorter drivers can position themselves farther
back from the wheel and air bag by moving the pedal back as much as
three inches.
</P>
<P>
   Add optional side air bags and you are swathed in safety. Toss
in the glow-in-the-dark interior trunk handle meant to keep kids
from locking themselves in that cavern and you've got one very
safety-oriented automobile.
</P>
<P>
   Downside? Even with the redesign, it suffers from the plague of
so many midsize sedans _ Nissan Maxima, Honda Accord, Buick
Century, and Toyota Camry among them: This is America's nondescript
rental fleet. You won't turn a head driving any of them. But since
the Accord and Camry are the top sellers in this segment, there
must be a lot of folks who don't care.
</P>
<P>
   New for the front-wheel-drive Taurus this year is a 3.0-liter,
24-valve, V6 engine that puts out 200 horses. I would not buy this
3,000-pound-plus car without this option. Buy the SE model as
tested, at a base price of just under $21,000 and you get the
engine standard. Toss in traction control _ which should become
standard on every car _ a leather package, and upgraded sound, and
you're up to $24,000.
</P>
<P>
   The four-speed automatic transmission is one of the better I've
seen in a while. Better in that it understands what you, the
driver, are attempting. It senses your driving style and comes to
learn that when you stomp the pedal, you are probably passing
someone, so it lets the RPMs roam instead of shifting up
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   The steering is solid, interior noise is minimal, and the thing
seems darn near European in its handling. Maybe Ford's ownership of
Volvo is slopping over here. It's not tight like a Volvo and still
has a sense of that distinct American tendency to float at the
front, but Ford is getting this ride down.
</P>
<P>
   The only real fault I find with this car is its brakes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a heavy midsize sedan and Ford should have moved past the
days of mixed brakes _ discs up front, drums in the rear _ by now.
With traction control and ABS (other features that ought to be
mandated as combined and standard), this car handles the way
today's cars should handle.
</P>
<P>
   Taking away from that handling, and to me, braking is an
essential element of handling, by clinging to an old system, does
not make sense.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The giant taillights with their big turn signals. They really
let that jerk who is tailgating you know what you are up to.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --Skinny outside mirrors. I found myself crouching in my seat at
times to aid rear vision. Hey, we're not trying to shave hundreds
of a second off our quarter-mile times with this rig. Give us
bigger mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $20,895 &QL; 
Price as tested: $24,205 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 200/200 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 108.5 inches/197.7 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 73.0 inches/56.1 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 3,340 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
