<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4582 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-PROPHET-OF-PROFIT-NYT     07-27 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROPHET-OF-PROFIT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET FAITHFUL FLOCK TO JIM CLARK, PROPHET OF PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Financial Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from TheStreet.com, the
authoritative business and finance Web site, is available from the
New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By TISH WILLIAMS  
 c.2000 TheStreet.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ Women with tear-stained faces passed their
babies forward, entrusting them to the hands of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Clark gazed at each and waved his hand in blessing. Palm by
palm, Internet start-up ideas were brought to the outstretched arms
of the holy man.
</P>
<P>
   As celebratory M80s were fired off outside the high-tech
cathedral, the sweat-soaked, tightly packed start-up pilgrims
surged toward the stage. They were here to see the man who
communicates directly with the alternately cruel and benevolent god
of Internet success.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire didn't disappoint the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The brains behind Silicon Graphics, Netscape, Healtheon/WebMD,
MyCFO and now the divine chairman of Shutterfly, Clark enraptured a
throng of technology faithful Monday night in Silicon Valley at a
Q&AMP;A session hosted by Santa Clara's Churchill Club.
</P>
<P>
   More salt-of-the-earth than not-of-this-world, Clark showed the
several hundred gathered that it doesn't take a thick layer of
polish to attain capitalist enlightenment. His jokes weren't
canned. His image wasn't tailored. His rough edges had only been
slightly smoothed by life in the pagan festival of the media
bacchanal and as the subject of ``The New New Thing: A Silicon
Valley Story,'' a biography by Michael Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Clark is as close to the pure Internet entrepreneurial
religion as you're going to get these days.
</P>
<P>
   He offers no apology for acts that seem devoid of the airbrushed
faith we expect from our Internet moguls. In truth, no amount of
escorting the elderly through the crosswalks of four-lane
thoroughfares will change the fact that capitalism is cutthroat.
Clark didn't offer up false hope _ rather, his fearless,
straightforward opinions on startups and the Internet boom set
stomachs churning all evening.
</P>
<P>
   First, the mile-long queue of pilgrims waiting in line for the
Q&AMP;A session microphones was quickly damned. Clark explained that he
only invests in ventures shown to him by friends he's worked with,
``and maybe not even then do I invest.'' Madre de dios! His good
sense of comedic timing softened the pain for those who'd crawled
on their knees from San Jose with an extra-thick stack of business
cards in their slacks.
</P>
<P>
   And sure, if you want to know, he did sell a sinful amount of
his AOL stock, which he received after it bought Netscape. Does he
care?
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad I didn't sell it when it was at $90,'' Clark laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has gone from being AOL's largest single shareholder to
claiming ownership of only 1 million shares. Why did he liquidate
millions upon millions of shares when he could've had some sort of
greater relationship with the leading new media power? ``I think
AOL is at some substantial risk still from Microsoft as a site. And
I don't fundamentally believe in the way AOL works, and I
especially don't like it combined with Time Warner. ... I prefer
the opposite model: Don't own the content,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A ringing endorsement from a million-share man.
</P>
<P>
   What did he do with that money? For starters, he bought a little
of the aforementioned threat Microsoft ``once the judge issued the
decree and the stock went down.''
</P>
<P>
   For the love of god, doesn't the founder of Netscape have one
iota of malicious competitive hatred? ``Microsoft has enormous
power. I'm sure they'll learn how to use it,'' he wisecracked.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the bliss of apolitical investment. You stab my back,
I'll scratch yours _ if it makes me a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   Clark didn't hesitate when moderator and New Yorker scribe John
Heileman asked him to offer a buy, sell or hold rating on some
popular stocks. Yahoo!? Hold, Clark fired off. Microsoft? Buy,
obviously. Amazon.com? A buy, ``at this price,'' Clark quipped.
Excite(at)Home? Clark smiled and lowered his gaze. ``I think
everyone should buy (at)Home. No ... I own that, and I'm currently
underwater.'' Ah, the guilty conscience got the better of him.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a little dirt was kicked on the divine one: ``What
about SGI, which now trades for all of 4 1/2?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh god,'' Clark groaned as the crowd whooped its amusement. He
paused for a moment with a cautious smile. ``I think its patent
portfolio is worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems and Cisco? ``Overpriced,'' Clark said. Not that
he doesn't own them, mind you. ``I like to own round numbers, one
million shares,'' Clark joked with the wealth-ogling crowd.
Finally, Intel got a Clark buy rating.
</P>
<P>
   To finish off the evening, Clark sent his followers out with a
heartwarming message of Silicon Valley compassion. When asked
whether he plans to give away his money, Clark offered in his same
no-nonsense yet thoughtful tone, ``I grew up poor. I didn't have
any money. You could say I had a negative net worth,'' he
emphasized. He detailed how he has set aside chunks of his net
worth for his children and grandchildren. Clark also gave Stanford
University $150 million to fund a new biotech department.
</P>
<P>
   As for a Bill Gates-like approach to giving, don't hold your
breath. ``I'll give away what I don't spend. And I don't really
think I can spend it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Say it with him, congregation, ``Amen.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Tish Williams is a senior writer for TheStreet.com. Her column
takes at look at the people who make Silicon Valley tick. In
keeping with TSC's editorial policy, she doesn't own or short
individual stocks, although she does own stock options in
TheStreet.com. She also doesn't invest in hedge funds or other
private investment partnerships. She awaits your feedback at
twilliams(at)thestreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Distributed by New York Times Special Features
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
