<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-0728     07-27 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAN'T SETTLE JERUSALEM? LEAVE IN GOD'S HANDS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When low-level negotiators can't settle a dispute,
they usually ``bump it upstairs'' for a decision.
</P>
<P>
   So, why not turn to The Man Upstairs(CQ) to settle the dispute
over the holy city of Jerusalem?
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli academics suggest Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators break their deadlock over the city by giving God
sovereignty over the most sacred _ and disputed _ areas.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that Jordan's late King Hussein repeatedly
advocated. The intent is to break the stalemate on a largely
symbolic issue with a symbolic solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful idea,'' said Ruth Lapidoth, one of several
scholars who advise Israeli negotiators. ``Sovereignty is an
abstract notion that makes people's feelings very strong. It's a
symbolic notion that makes it very difficult to compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the issue of sovereignty, which means ``supreme
power,'' in Webster's New Collegiate Dictionary, should be set
aside for 20 or 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that time, either you say sovereignty belongs to God or you
say each side shares sovereignty,'' said Lapidoth, who is a law
professor at Jerusalem's Hebrew University and a researcher at the
Jerusalem Institute for Israel Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem was the biggest snag in the recently failed, 15-day,
Camp David summit. Negotiators announced Thursday that they would
start low-level meetings in the region on Sunday and the talks are
sure to turn to the city once again.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has controlled the entire city since capturing its
eastern areas in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree that sovereignty has little impact on daily life.
Israeli negotiators, in broad terms, already appear willing to give
Palestinians near-total control their own neighborhoods. There are
a number of ideas, including joint police forces or a city borough
system, that could lead to practical solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israelis refuse to cede sovereignty, and Palestinians won't
take a deal without it.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reports from the summit that the negotiators
discussed placing sovereignty with God. But, the suggestion was
noted Thursday in Israel's Ha'aretz daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Lapidoth said she does not know what kind of reception
Palestinian and Israeli leaders might give it.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For daily news from Israel see:
</P>
<P>
   www.haaretzdaily.com.il
</P>
<P>
   For The Jerusalem Institute for Israel Studies see
</P>
<P>
   www.jiis.org.il
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
