<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACTOR WILL SAVE RENOVATION HEADACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Our bathroom needs to be brought into the 21st century. When
I had a half-bath installed not long ago, a plumber and carpenter
did the work. For the redo of the big bathroom, should I hire
individuals to do each step or hire a contractor who would
coordinate all the workers?
</P>
<P>
   FRANCES McKAY, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Coordinating all the workers _ and there will be more than
just a plumber and a carpenter _ is the key to the success of the
project. I think hiring a contractor to do it all is your best bet.
It will save you lots of headaches. If you plan on doing some of
the work yourself, you can hire each individual and have him or her
work around your part of the project.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am painting inside my house. The living room and dining
room have popcorn ceilings. What is the best way to remove that
popcorn when there is asbestos underneath? Can the popcorn be
removed without disturbing the asbestos? If asbestos needs to be
removed, how is it done?
</P>
<P>
   MANUEL SILVA, San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. If there is asbestos on your ceiling, you should not remove
any finish that is on top of it, including the popcorn ceiling. You
can buy popcorn patching material that you can apply to the
ceiling, but don't try to remove the old popcorn before
establishing whether it contains asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Besides popcorn, the only other type of asbestos ceiling used in
a home is made of mineral-fiber tile. To find out if your ceiling
contains asbestos, break off a small piece of the tile, or whatever
is under the popcorn ceiling, and a piece of the popcorn; put them
in sealed plastic envelopes and take them to an asbestos abatement
company.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are listed in the Yellow Pages under ``Asbestos
abatement.'' They can also remove the asbestos safely, though not
inexpensively.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no asbestos, you can scrape, sand, and wash off the
popcorn and paint what's under it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is insulated with foam, installed back in the 1970s.
Would I have trouble if I were to put the house up for sale?
</P>
<P>
   P. N., Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That foam in your walls is probably urea formaldehyde foam
insulation, popular in the 1970s. It is an excellent insulator, and
properly installed, is safe.
</P>
<P>
   However, some installations were defective because the
formaldehyde did not foam up properly, resulting in illnesses among
people allergic to formaldedyde. So it was banned in Massachusetts
and later the whole country. It was removed from some houses, but
not all.
</P>
<P>
   Your insulation sounds as if it was properly installed and is
causing no harm. If you put the house up for sale, you must declare
that the house is treated this way. Some buyers may not be
concerned, others might. If you find a buyer who would like to buy
the house but objects to the foam, and you accept his offer, then
it must be removed by the seller. That's expensive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My sink overflowed and very hot water dissolved the finish on
my new linoleum. The luster or shine is all gone. What can I apply
to it to help seal the finish and restore the shine?
</P>
<P>
   FLORENCE HELLAND, Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Call the manufacturer of the linoleum, which is sheet vinyl,
to see what he recommends. He might have something to restore the
shine. The dealer might know, too, but I think you are better off
going directly to the manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   If no success there, you could treat the dull spot with Future,
an acrylic finish. I have done this on sheet vinyl with pretty good
results. But nevertheless, caveat emptor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am redoing my bathroom, and putting in an exhaust fan. I
also would like to paint the walls and ceiling with a mildew-proof
paint. Is there such a thing, and does it work?
</P>
<P>
   M. A. F., Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, there is such a thing. The Zinsser company calls its
Perma-White a mildew-proof interior paint, and guarantees it for
five years. It is sold in paint stores that carry the Zinsser
brand.
</P>
<P>
   Since you are putting in an exhaust fan, make sure it vents
outdoors. The fan will help keep an ordinary painted wall and
ceiling free of mildew for longer than five years, so you may not
need the mildew-proof paint. Turn the fan on during showers and
keep it on for half an hour afterward to exhaust any remaining
water vapor. That should do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
