<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-27 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AMERICAN WORKERS CAN LEARN A LESSON FROM THE FRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you are a worker, one of the greatest places
in the world to be right now is Paris. It's always wonderful, of
course, but what makes Paris particularly special at this time of
the year has nothing to do with the Eiffel Tower, the
Champs-Elysees or the Arc de Triomphe.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you could be seeing all those wonderful sites and gorging
on wonderful food, but late July also offers the anticipation of
what comes in August: An entire month of vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the next time you're staring at the back of a
bumper during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not every Parisian takes August off, but French law
requires employers to give workers more than four weeks of vacation
a year, according to a study by Hewitt Associates. So a lot of
Paris simply shuts down in August.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt reports that similar laws mandate at least four weeks of
vacation for workers in such countries as Australia and Brazil and
almost all of Western Europe. These are not rewards for years of
service; they are legally required for employees who have been with
a company at least one year.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Hewitt says, typical workers get about two
weeks of vacation after their first year. You may eventually get up
to four weeks, but often that comes after 15 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture? The Eiffel Tower is missing, and
so is a lot of sanity.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is going through one of the greatest economic
booms in its history, yet a lot of workers from the middle class on
down are progressing like a hamster on a wheel.
</P>
<P>
   If you're frustrated because your portion of the boom has been
more of a fizzle, there are a lot of people you can blame, like
politicians, for favoring the rich and not having better labor
laws, or your employer, for being greedy and insensitive. But if
you want to meet face to face with the person who deserves most of
the blame, find a mirror.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a good worker and you haven't managed to squeeze more
than a cost of living raise out of your employer in the last three
years, what exactly are you waiting for? Being an unrewarded worker
these days is sort of like keeping your virginity during the Summer
of Love; you are passing up an opportunity you may never see again.
</P>
<P>
   It's not news anymore when an industry is struggling for
workers. High-tech companies want to relax immigration laws so they
can get more engineers, police departments are advertising like
crazy for officers, restaurateurs are begging for good waiters.
</P>
<P>
   You have a lot more leverage than you think you do. Employers
are finally realizing how hard it is for them to replace a good
employee, especially in this market.
</P>
<P>
   And getting an extra week or three of vacation is one of the
easiest concessions you can get. Yes, companies have to scramble
when workers are on vacation, but it allows the businesses to get
by without the out-of-pocket costs they face with pay raises or
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask for more vacation and get turned down, it can mean
one of several things:
</P>
<P>
   You're not as good as you think you are.
</P>
<P>
   You're in a weak company or industry.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't make a good case for the extra vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The company doesn't believe it will lose you.
</P>
<P>
   Your boss is an unappreciative dolt.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you negotiate anything, point out how it makes sense
from a business standpoint. Explain how the extra vacation will
allow you to be more creative or less distracted by family events
or whatever else you can come up with from a business standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of negotiating, mention anything you can about
competing companies' pay and benefits if it helps your case. That
gives a subtle message that you are thinking about leaving, or at
least considering your options.
</P>
<P>
   Stop short of threatening to leave. Once those words have left
your mouth, there will be an extra layer of tension between you and
your boss. Any smart boss with a smart worker will realize that
you're perfectly capable of leaving. Keep the threat unspoken.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not overestimating your own value and you still get
turned down, that means either that your boss is an unappreciative
dolt or you're in a weak company or industry. (Certainly successful
small businesses might have a legitimate argument against long
vacations, but make sure your other benefits make up for that.) Do
you have any reason to believe the circumstances will be better a
year from now?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, if your boss is new and simply needs to get to know you
better. Or your industry is in a typical down cycle. Or your
company suffered a setback, but you have a good reason _ other than
blind faith _ to believe the situation will turn around.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, though, you should take the rejection as a warning
signal. Something is seriously wrong _ with your performance, with
your relationship with your boss, with your company or with your
industry. And if things are sour at this point, what makes you
think they will get any better when the economy inevitably hits a
downturn?
</P>
<P>
   Unless you come up with a good answer, you next long vacation
may be one you never asked for.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
