<HEADLINE>
AMITYVILLE KILLER STILL SERVING TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Is the Amityville Horror killer still in prison?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.M., Hurst, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Ronald DeFeo Jr. is serving six consecutive 25-year prison
terms at the Green Haven Correctional Facility in Stormville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 13, 1974, DeFeo was 23 when he shot and killed his
parents and four younger siblings with a rifle at their Amityville,
N.Y., home. He made an unsuccessful bid for a new trial in 1993,
claiming his sister Dawn murdered the family before he killed her
in a fit of rage.
</P>
<P>
   The next owners of the home, George and Kathy Lutz, claimed it
was haunted by demons, floating pig heads and meat-eating flies,
inspiring a bestselling 1977 book, 1979 movie and eight subsequent
films and TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Lutzes' claims encouraged ``ghost-busters'' and others from
around the world to visit the house, Newsday columnist Ed Lowe
wrote in 1998. ``Amityville saw the entire country, and later
emissaries from the world, through a prism of mass hysteria and
unfathomable stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the bugle call Taps?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.W., Granbury, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Taps was written by Union Gen. Daniel Adams Butterfield and
first performed in July 1862 in memory of the men who died in the
Seven Days battles.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional bugle call at day's end was Light's Out, but
Adams thought it was too formal, according to the White House's
National Moment of Remembrance Web site at
www.whitehouse.gov//remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music was beautiful on that still summer night and was
heard far beyond the limits of our brigade,'' the first Taps
bugler, Oliver Wilcox Norton, is quoted as saying. ``The next day,
I was visited by several buglers from neighboring brigades, asking
for copies of the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Taps is played during the National Moment of Remembrance, which
occurs for one minute at 3 p.m. local time each Memorial Day. The
ceremony honors Americans who died serving their country.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the mailing address of Coretta Scott King?
</P>
<P>
   _ L.J., Bakersfield, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to her in care of the Martin Luther King Jr. Center for
Social Change, 449 Auburn Ave., N.E., Atlanta, GA 30312.
</P>
<P>
   King, 73, helped persuade the Justice Department to conduct a
new inquiry into the April 4, 1968, murder of her husband. James
Earl Ray pleaded guilty in 1969 to shooting King as the civil
rights leader stood on a balcony at the Lorraine Motel in Memphis,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Justice Department concluded after an 18-month
investigation that there was no credible evidence to indicate a
conspiracy in King's murder.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
