<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR NATIONS NEED SOME RELIEF IF THEY'RE TO TRY TO LEAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Developments at the recently concluded G-8 summit summon to mind
thoughts of Jim Smiley and his frog, Daniel Webster.
</P>
<P>
   Such an association may seem like a bit of stretch to some. But
others may find the comparison not overly farfetched, because the
richer nations of the world pledged at the summit to help the
poorest make a great leap forward.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Smiley helped Daniel Webster do. Those who still
fancy Mark Twain's way of telling tall tales remember Smiley as the
leading human character of Twain's short story ``The Celebrated
Jumping Frog of Calaveras County.'' Smiley trained Daniel Webster
to be the best broad-jumper of his species in that neck of the
woods. For his troubles, he won significant sums of money by
betting that his frog could outjump anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   But he lost a $40 bet to a stranger who stuffed Daniel Webster
full of quail shot while Smiley was off in the marsh capturing
another frog for the stranger to pit against his amphibian athlete.
</P>
<P>
   When the two nudged their frogs to start the contest, the
stranger's sprang an impressive distance, but old Daniel Webster
couldn't move. The stranger got away before Smiley realized that he
had been had.
</P>
<P>
   The poorest countries in the world face predicaments similar to
Daniel Webster's. They are weighed down by problems that prevent
them from rising out of poverty and fecklessness to compete
effectively in the new global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the figurative birdshot that holds them down is the
legacy of European colonial domination. That is particularly true
in Africa, where the European colonists established national
boundaries without regard to tribal territorial claims and set the
stage for recurring strife in the continent after those colonies
achieved independence.
</P>
<P>
   The colonial powers also handicapped those countries
economically in many instances by transforming them into producers
of one or two exportable commodities, undermining their subsistence
farming and making many of them into net importers of food and
other basic materials.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that weigh them down include inadequate health
care, lack of educational opportunities, poor transportation
infrastructure, and venal politicians and bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Add to those loads the heavy indebtedness of many poor nations
to the governments and lending institutions of the G-8 countries,
and it becomes as impossible for them to rise as it was for Daniel
Webster to levitate with a belly full of BBs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the primary criticisms of the G-8 summit is that the rich
nations did not go far enough in promising debt relief. Such
criticism is justified because some the poorer nations must make
such heavy payments on their debts to other governments and private
banks that they have nothing left with which to address crying
fundamental needs.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the richer nations need to offer more debt relief if
the poorer nations are to evolve into significant markets for their
goods and services. Such debt relief, however, must be provided
only on conditions that the resources freed up will go to
education, health care and other fundamental needs instead of
lining the pockets of politicians and bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Some criticism has been leveled at the G-8 nations for their
emphasis on closing the ``digital divide.'' The richer countries
promised to launch a public-private sector program to help the poor
get more access to computers and the benefits of the rapidly
evolving technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of that promise made at the Okinawa summit labeled
it a ``let-them-eat-chips'' response to the plight of the world's
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is true, as one critic pointed out, that ``You can't
eat laptops,'' it is a serious mistake to underestimate the
importance of expanding access to computer technology to poorer
inhabitants of the poorest countries. It is just as crucial as debt
relief to getting them to where they need to be to compete in the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the poorer nations need help in addressing fundamental
needs, that alone will not enable them to catch up. The poorer
nations really don't have time to build the infrastructure that has
been developed over generations in the rich countries.
</P>
<P>
   But the kind of digital help that was pledged at the G-8 summit
could be just the nudge to get the birdshot out of them and allow
them to leap-frog over several of the stages of economic, social
and political advancement through which the more affluent nations
had to pass.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
