<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARTHBROOKS-AUSTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTH GAINES FEW FANS WITH PART 2 OF HIS ROCK/POP ACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was during Garth Brooks' marathon two-hours-plus taping for
``Austin City Limits'' one night last fall that word came down that
a few people had ``actually walked out'' as Brooks did a short set
from his new rock/pop CD, ``Garth Brooks In ... The Life of Chris
Gaines.''
</P>
<P>
   Understand, this was Brooks, stadium-filling superstar, playing
before fewer than 500 devoted fans; someone in the last row could
have tossed a tennis ball underhanded and hit the stage. And still
there were those that were so put off by his foray into pop/R&AMP;B/rap
that they turned their backs on their hero.
</P>
<P>
   There were 12 songs spread over an hour in the second edition of
the Brooks taping. Most of the show _ and most of the event _
centered on the country hits, and all were capably performed by
Brooks and his band; sandwiched between all those favorites, he and
a second band (younger, multiracial) did only four songs from the
Gaines CD.
</P>
<P>
   Two, ``Main Street'' and ``Way of the Girl'' are here, and
months later it's pretty easy to see why the Gaines project was a
colossal boondoggle. Coming just after Brooks does two solo
acoustic numbers, ``Unanswered Prayers'' and Bob Dylan's ``To Make
You Feel My Love,'' ``Main'' and ``Way'' arrive like a stink bomb
at a Saturday-night beer bash.
</P>
<P>
   These two songs _ the first a slice of faux-Midwest rock, the
latter unappetizing pop/funk _ show exactly why the Gaines project
was a relative failure and why the Brooks camp has been very quiet
about it and the scheduled Gaines-themed movie ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaines project _ and this show _ underscore that Brooks has
always been a singer with one foot solidly in the pop-rock camp.
Check how much ``Rodeo'' or ``Ain't Going Down (Til the Sun Comes
Up'' are informed by solid, meat-and-potatoes rock, the nods to the
Eagles that lurk just under the surfaces of several tunes, and the
obvious Jimmy Buffett rip-off that is ``Two Pina Coladas.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this mixture of rock and country that allowed Brooks to
capture a larger audience than any country artist _ although he was
familiar and easy on the ears to mainstream country fans, he also
roped a whole bunch of aging rock fans into his camp, people who at
the dawn of the '90s felt left behind by grunge and rap.
</P>
<P>
   His mainstream inclinations _ and slice-of-life stories _ have
always been his greatest strengths. They certainly were that
November night in Austin, and they will be again, now that Brooks
is putting this whole Chris Gaines thing behind him.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin City Limits: Garth Brooks No. 2''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: 9 p.m. CDT on PBS. The first half of the taped
performance will be shown at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
