<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL-LIFE LESSONS ON MAKING ASSUMPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looks can be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   That's a hard lesson to teach and an even harder lesson to
learn. I thought I had mastered the concept, and then last weekend
I realized that I haven't.
</P>
<P>
   We were at my mom's family reunion, and all 13 of my mother's
siblings along with about a hundred of my cousins were there. We
were doing the little drawing thing for the person who had come the
farthest and the person with the fattest baby when my Aunt Lola
announced that someone named Robert had recently gotten married.
</P>
<P>
   Well, we were all quite puzzled because we've had several
relatives tie the knot this summer but none of them is named
Robert.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the back of the room, my cousin Snooky slowly stood up
with this big cheese-eating grin on his face. I'm Robert, he said.
A collective gasp rose like a cloud of dust. We've called this man
Snooky since he was born. Everyone thought his real name was
Snooky. His mother even looked a bit surprised. I think she had
forgotten his real name, too.
</P>
<P>
   We have a cousin named Sweetmeat, so Snooky seemed almost tame
in comparison. I suppose Sweetmeat's real name is Arthur or Kyle.
But never in a million years would you guess that Snooky is really
a Robert. He looks nothing like a Robert.
</P>
<P>
   All the Roberts look alike, you know. No hair on their necks.
Good posture. Long fingers. So anyway, as I said, looks can be
deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to make this point to my boys a few days ago. We were
sitting in the car waiting for my husband to return from the store.
It was a little after nine and the air in the car was as hot as a
sauna. My husband always takes the keys, as if we are going to
leave him or something.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, most of the stores in this little strip center were
closed, and only a few cars were in the parking lot. A noise
attracted our attention, and that's when we noticed a gentleman
slowly walking along the sidewalk in front of the stores. He was
checking the locks on the doors, causing the rattling sound we'd
heard. He shuffled along as if each step was more painful than the
last. The few, isolated strands of white hair on his head were
plastered to his scalp. The gun at his side was almost bigger than
he was.
</P>
<P>
   I turned to my two sons and said, ``What do you think about that
security guard? What do you think his background is?''
</P>
<P>
   My youngest son suggested, ``I don't think he likes his job, but
maybe he doesn't know how to do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior shook his head and said: ``Well, he probably didn't save
up for his retirement, because he doesn't need to be doing this
job. He can hardly walk and it's way too hot out here.''
</P>
<P>
   You're both wrong, I said. ``His name is Bill and he's been a
millionaire since he was 20 years old. He has a master's degree in
sociology and a law degree, although he never practiced law because
he started his own company right out of law school. He's a
second-degree black belt in karate. He usually runs six miles every
morning, but right now he's recovering from knee surgery. He's
doing this job because walking is part of his physical therapy and
one of his employees is out sick. The security company is one of
four companies that he owns.''
</P>
<P>
   My children looked at Bill with heightened respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he really a second-degree black belt?'' my oldest son
asked.
</P>
<P>
   I smiled and said, ``I don't know. Actually, I made the whole
thing up. But what I guessed could be correct, just like what you
guessed might be right. On the other hand, we could both be wrong.
All we know for sure is that that fellow is an adult male with a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, why do you do stuff like that?,'' my baby boy whined.
``Why would you make all of that up?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Son,'' I replied, ``what I did was make an assumption, and
it's the same thing that a lot of people will do when they look at
you and see a young, African-American male. They may think good
things or bad things, but they are going to form an opinion about
you before you even open your mouth. But that doesn't change what
you truly are, does it? We can guess about that guard all day but
it doesn't change a thing about who he really is and what he can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   They still looked puzzled so I added, ``All I'm saying is, don't
let other people determine your value.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, we just sat in silence waiting for my husband _ or a
breeze _ to emerge from the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Anderson is a dentist, TV talk-show host and author in
Arlington, Texas. Her latest book, ``Mom, Are We There Yet?,'' is a
collection of her favorite columns. Contact her online at
www.moeanderson.com or call (817) 548-5564. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
