   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER SAN DIEGO _ Napster has been enjoined from helping
people share music files after mindight Friday, but will the move
stem the digital tide? Other, less enforceable methods already
exist for exchanging MP3 files on the Internet. Experts analyze the
injuction and look at what's likely to happen next. (Keefe, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER-SIDE _ In the wake of the Napster meltdown, where are
fans going to get their downloads? What alternatives exist and how
busy are they today _ and how busy is Napster for that matter? What
are fans saying, doing as the court deadline looms? (Fernandez,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)STEVENS _ As expected, WestPoint
Stevens said earnings were hurt by a large restructuring charge.
The West Point sheet and towel maker reported a second-quarter loss
of $89.8 million, or $1.81 a share, compared with a profit of $19.6
million, or 34 cents a share, in the prior period. The results
included a one-time pretax charge of $168.2 million. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS _ The outlook for profits has suddenly dimmed, thanks to
the Federal Reserve's year-long series of interest rate hikes. Most
economists now think the usual second-half rebound will not occur
this year, and analysts are worried that 3rd and 4th quarter profit
growth will slow. This casts a cloud over the outlook for the stock
market. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EARTHLINK _ EarthLink Inc. on Thursday reported booming
revenues, a shrinking loss and strong customer growth as it
continued its pursuit of America Online.
</P>
<P>
   In reporting its second quarter earnings, the company also
acknowledged some service problems during the earlier part of the
year _ blaming them largely on the awkardness of merging EarthLink
and MindSpring. The company also promised more acquisitions as it
grows. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
