<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-PROTES     07-27 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-PROTESTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROTESTERS GEAR UP FOR PARTY CONVENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of protesters are expected to converge on the
conventions at which Republican Gov. George W. Bush and Democratic
Vice President Al Gore formally will accept their parties'
presidential nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators hope to capitalize on the showy political
events to bring attention to their causes.
</P>
<P>
   Connected by Web sites, mass e-mailings, organizing meetings and
civil disobedience training, the activists are building on the
World Trade Organization protests in Seattle last fall and the
World Bank demonstrations in Washington in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   The police in Los Angeles and Philadelphia, and the
demonstrators, are bracing for the same types of confrontations at
the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated convention protests have more targets than the
turbulent anti-Vietnam War demonstrations during the 1968
Democratic National Convention in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   This time, activists hope to move beyond largely white
participation. They have been organizing in inner cities around
such issues as wages, police relations, high housing costs and
health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't issues that will be raised on the floors of
either the Democratic or Republican conventions,'' said Van Jones,
31, executive director of the Ella Baker Center for Human Rights in
San Francisco. ``If we don't go and raise these issues _ these
survival issues, that affect people every day in very real ways _
then they won't be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   The activists are not pitching their message at politicians and
delegates at the conventions. ``I think the audience is the people
at home channel surfing,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jones, Leticia Arellano does not expect to sway the
delegates or ``change their consciences. But I hope we can push
them, to at least look at the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Arellano wants to build a long-term, anti-death penalty
movement. A goal is to convince California lawmakers to impose a
moratorium on executions, as did the governor of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Arellano, saying that the majority of prisoners are behind bars
for drug-related offenses, said the government should focus on
treatment and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people can change,'' she said. ``Their lives can be
reformed. Everybody has an opportunity to pursue a satisfying
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention begins Monday in Philadelphia. The
Democratic event starts two weeks later in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
