<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH (Paris) _ Developments in the investigation of
the Air France Concorde crash. After deciphering information from
the airliner's black boxes, crash experts hoped to form an initial
verdict Thursday of the causes of the crash. But they now say that
it may be several days before they complete their analysis. The
French have started several different investigations, and warfare
between them is now breaking out. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (Caracas, Venezuela) _ He promised a
revolution, and he has kept his word. Since being swept into power
here 18 months ago, Hugo Chavez has uprooted every institution,
assaulted every elite group and derided every orthodoxy with the
unrelenting combativeness of the army paratrooper he used to be. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ The government has dropped the fraud
case against Vladimir Gusinsky, the anti-Kremlin media mogul whose
prosecution raised fears of a crackdown on the press. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Developments in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace efforts. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   PRISONERS-INTERNET (Chicago) _ Around the nation, thousands of
prisoners now advertise themselves on the Internet, sometimes
pleading that they were wrongfully convicted, sometimes looking for
money, sometimes looking for pen pals. While no American prison
allows inmates to have access to the Internet behind bars, these
prisoners use third-party services, usually for a fee, to reach out
to a potentially huge audience. Victims' rights groups have
expressed outrage over prisoners' popping up on Web sites, saying
that it inflicts more pain on the families of people who have been
harmed, and often distorts the truth. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DNA-TESTS (Los Angeles) _ Prosecutors in southern
California plan to offer free DNA tests to some inmates, which may
overturn their convictions. San Diego County prosecutors have been
reviewing the cases of about 560 inmates to determine whether DNA
tests developed since their convictions can link biological
evidence from a crime scene to someone other than the person
convicted. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ Statistics released by the New York City
Police Department show a marked increase in disciplinary actions
against police officers over the past three years, which the
department says demonstrates increased vigilance in punishing
misconduct. Critics contend that the department has manipulated the
numbers to avoid federal oversight. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARINES-CRASH (Washington) _ The Marine Corps was expected to
announce the cause of the latest V-22 Osprey crash, reportedly
pinning the blame on pilot error, not the aircraft's design. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ The House was expected to pass the
last of its tax bills, this one repealing a 1993 tax on Social
Security benefits. Also, possible developments concerning a veto by
President Clinton of the marriage penalty legislation. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SENATOR (Washington) _ Zell Miller was to be sworn in as the
new senator from Georgia, and was to give his first speech from the
floor. He gives the Democrats one more vote. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Undated) _ A detailed look at how Dick Cheney came
to be George W. Bush's running mate. By Frank Bruni and Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   WASH-PA-CONGRESS (Seattle) _ A look at the two House districts
in the United States that swing frequently back and forth between
Republicans and Democrats, in Washington state and Pennsylvania. By
Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-VOTE-VOICES (Evanston, Ill.) _ Interviews with voters in
this diverse, middle-class suburb in a swing state show that people
are still skeptical and wary of the presidential candidates. In the
absence of a single urgent issue, voters are sizing up candidates
as managers, stewards and leaders worthy, or not, of respect. By
Pam Belluck.
</P>
