<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYBRID AUTOS BRING FUTURE TO YOUR DRIVEWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 HYBRIDCAR KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JAMES A. FUSSELL  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so gas prices have dropped. You no longer have to hock the
good silver just to drive to work. Still, a buck fifty a gallon is
no bargain, considering you were paying a scant 80 cents just over
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an alternative to car pooling, canceling family
vacations and weeping silently behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   It's the new gasoline-electric hybrid cars, which despite some
consumer misconceptions _ no, they won't electrocute you if you
drive through a puddle _ might be in your driveway sooner than you
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we know what you're thinking. Electric cars are gimmicky
little eco-pods that get dented in a stiff breeze and have to be
plugged in every night, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not when it comes to the first two high-tech hybrids to hit
American shores. Thanks to groundbreaking technology that blends
gasoline engines with batteries and electric motors, both Honda
Insight and the Toyota Prius (Latin for ``to go before'') are more
capable and less needy than you might imagine. They drive easily in
traffic, can reach speeds greater than 100 mph and don't need to be
plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the best part. In addition to extremely low
emissions, a competitive price tag of $20,000 and the comforts
Americans have come to expect, the cars still get 50 to 70 miles
per gallon _ two to three times that of most regular cars.
</P>
<P>
   Both cars are available locally now. The Insight has been out
for several months. The Prius came out late last week.
</P>
<P>
   So what are they like?
</P>
<P>
   We drove the cars, interviewed retailers and owners and
consulted the director of the auto testing facility for Consumer
Reports. Here's what we learned.
</P>
<P>
   The Prius, almost a mid-size sedan, is larger and more powerful
than the Insight. It's designed to hold five adults. It has a
trunk, traditional gauges and a soft-riding suspension. The
Insight, a futuristic looking two-seater with a sweep of sheet
metal covering the back wheel wells, looks sportier and achieves
higher mileage.
</P>
<P>
   John Lewis of Leavenworth recently bought an Insight for his
daily commute to work at the Sprint campus. He used to drive a
large Ford pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gas bill has gone from $50 per week to $7.50 a week,'' said
Lewis, who got his car several months ago from O'Neill Honda in
Overland Park. ``That feels pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   It should. The savings add up to $217 per month, or more than
$2,500 per year. After his down payment, the savings easily make
his monthly payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of my criteria in determining whether it was
worth the investment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis expected some quirks from the new engineering but didn't
find any.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of things written that it is slow to
accelerate,'' he said. ``But how fast are you trying to drive? It
will easily cruise at 70 to 75 mph. The thing that will surprise
you is how responsive it really is. It has far exceeded my
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   To Lewis, the Insight is part car, part video game. While
driving, he constantly monitors a bar graph that displays the car's
current and lifetime miles per gallon (the Prius also has this
feature). Then he tailors his driving habits to maximize his
mileage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he said on a recent drive. ``I'm going 62 and getting
over 100 miles per gallon!''
</P>
<P>
   To date he's getting 72 miles per gallon on the highway and
close to 60 in the city. With practice, he thinks he can do even
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to go on a long trip with it,'' Lewis said. ``I
should be able to get to Florida for about $15 bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   David Champion, director of the Consumer Reports auto test
facility, has driven both the Insight and the Prius. And while he
appreciates the ingenious technology in the Insight, on balance he
prefers the Prius.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prius seems to be a much more usable car,'' he said. ``We
were impressed by how flawless it worked. It was just like driving
any other car. Unless you're a single person, or a couple who don't
need the rear seat and are quite satisfied with a stick shift (the
only transmission available in the Insight), the Prius is going to
be a better bet. Much more in keeping with what most people in the
U.S. want.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the Insight?
</P>
<P>
   The aerodynamics are outstanding, Champion said, and so is the
technology and, of course, the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the magnificent mileage, he said, his Insight suffered
from a stiff ride, road noise and a five-speed transmission that
could be fatiguing to drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard work to drive around,'' he said. ``You're always
changing gears.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners say that discomfort quickly fades. Many owners report
learning to shift quickly from second to fifth gear. Lewis, of
Leavenworth, reports his car is quiet, easy to drive and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Champion predicts the Insight's long-term popularity will
be limited. ``I think this car will mostly appeal to the die-hard
environmentalists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are similarities, though, too. The electric motor in both
cars turns into a generator that charges the car's batteries when
coasting or braking. The batteries do not need routine replacement.
And both cars come with alloy wheels, anti-lock brakes, dual air
bags, power windows, mirrors and door locks, remote entry,
theft-deterrent systems and more.
</P>
<P>
   .MDBO/.MDNM/One note: If you break down in a hybrid vehicle,
don't expect Joe's garage to be able to fix it. Because the
Insight's small gasoline engine runs all the time, even if the
electric boost fails, you will still be able to drive, albeit not
nearly as well. If you break down in a Prius, it's more
complicated, because the car uses its electric motor to get going.
</P>
<P>
   To reassure buyers, Toyota provides an eight-year, 100,000-mile
warranty on all hybrid components and a three-year, 36,000-mile
bumper-to-bumper warranty that includes all your routine
maintenance for free, such as oil and filter changes. The Prius
also comes with free 24-hour roadside assistance and free towing
anywhere in the country, plus a free loaner car brought to your
location.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want any customer to be afraid of the technology,''
said Michael Davenport, a Toyota field training specialist.
</P>
<P>
   So even as technology marches forward, questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Will hybrids capture our imagination and in the coming decade
spread to virtually every make and model, like cruise control and
air bags? Or will it be a fad and fizzle out, like eight-tracks and
the rotary engine?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had the answer to that, I'd be a rich woman,'' said
Samantha Patton, a sociological historian in New York. ``If I had
to venture a guess, I'd say as long as these are viable products,
people will accept the change but do it slowly. Of course, there
are a lot of factors that can change that. Let's say the price of
gas goes to $3 or $4 a gallon by next year, and a lot more
companies come out with similar (high-mileage) cars. The pace might
quicken considerably. On the other hand, if gas prices go back
under a dollar, you may not have many people willing to make a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically it's been difficult to get people to leave the
status quo and embrace new technology, said Don Smith, director of
the economic development center at Carnegie Mellon University.
Especially when they perceive a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain segment of the population who will buy the
new things no matter what. But most people are risk-averse.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, that may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the whole we have seen new technology embraced much more
quickly than in the past. It took almost two decades for a million
black-and-white televisions to be sold. And yet DVD players sold a
million units in the first year. So the pace of new technology
acceptance, or technology diffusion, has picked up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity endorsement could speed up the pace of acceptance,
Smith said. So are car commercials featuring Sting and Robert
Redford endorsing the more environmentally friendly electric
hybrids in our future?
</P>
<P>
   Don't rule it out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
