<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4635 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MUSICCROWSKANSAS-KAN &LR;      07-27 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING CROWS, CASTING SHADOWS ON THE WINTER SKY 
</HEADLINE>
 CROWS KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 TIMOTHY FINN  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The verse that was stuck in his head for a few days recently
comes from a sad Richard Buckner tune called ``4am'', and Adam
Duritz, songwriter and lead singer for Counting Crows, couldn't get
enough of the ache in Buckner's shattered heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a part where he's completely abandoned the rhyme
scheme,'' Duritz said last week, ``and he sings, `Oh, my one, my
one, you've broken me ...,' and there's this catch in his voice.
It's a moment of complete honesty. I kept rewinding to that part,
for the devastation in his voice ... I look for those kinds of
moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Counting Crows have been around since late 1993, and from the
start, Duritz has been willing to share his sad, desperate moments
with anyone who wanted a whiff of the gunk in his heart and the
stuff ``crawling around inside my brain,'' to borrow a line from
one of his own songs.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Crows' first record, ``August and Everything
After,'' became a commercial hit, the music landscape was changing
underneath them: Nirvana was kaput, Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish were
huge, and other shiny pop-rock acts like matchbox twenty, Third Eye
Blind and the Wallflowers were throwing hard in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Duritz, though, never stopped dining with his demons and ghosts.
Nearly eight years and two albums later, he and his band are
setting his baroque, melancholy poems to some infectious folk-rock
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray is my favorite color,'' Duritz sang on ``Mr. Jones,'' his
band's first big hit, an ironic declaration for a guy whose music
is so autumnal and blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's sorrow in our music, but there's hope, too,''
Duritz said. ``But our songs are about people who still have hope,
and I think people miss that. That's where the yearning comes from:
They're in pain, but they still believe.''
</P>
<P>
   The sorrow that Duritz writes about isn't the heavy,
pathological kind that tormented, say, John Lennon, who never got
over the departure and loss of his mother; nor the physical and
mental anguish that drove Kurt Cobain to suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Duritz's comes more from the bad weather that rolls in and out
of our lives and sometimes stays for too long: those long
Decembers, and the rain, which has been a redundant device in every
Crows' album.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Amy Hit the Atmosphere,'' a song about a lady who ``feels a
lot better'' when it rains, he sings: There has to be a change, I'm
sure//Today was just another day fading into another//And that
can't be what life is for ... In some ways, Duritz is Morrissey
after a few Tony Robbins seminars: a recovering melancholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of being an adult,'' said Duritz, who turns 36 on
Tuesday, ``is appreciating the flaws in your work and life and
getting through them. Even if you end up doing what you always
dreamed of doing, you have problems. Nothing can be pure and easy,
except being a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Duritz writes about love, too, but rarely about the one he's in
love with. Instead he remembers those he's lost or left, and even
then he explores and relives the consequences of the departure _
the solitary spaces, the unfilled time, those stark 4 a.m. moments
_ and not the women who created them. And he apparently forgets no
one.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mrs. Potter's Lullaby'' from the Crows' latest record, he
sings without a catch in his voice: ``There's a piece of Maria in
every song that I sing.'' And then, in trademark fashion, he
overwrites: ``And the price of the memory is the memory of the
sorrow it brings.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria is one of several women who have reappeared in Duritz's
songs during the course of three records. (She also shows up in the
first song on ``August.'') But his most famous heroine may be
Elisabeth//Elizabeth, who is the star of the melodrama ``Goodnight,
Elisabeth'' and who gets a postcard from Adam in the new song ``I
Wish I Was a Girl'': ``Hey, Elizabeth, you know I'm doing all right
these days ...''
</P>
<P>
   A guy who talks about his feelings and who doesn't fear
commitment _ even if it's only to the memories of his many
ex-girlfriends _ will never have trouble drawing women into his
life.
</P>
<P>
   So in chatrooms all over the Internet, Duritz has stirred up
plenty of interest in his exes and his love life (which reportedly
included a ``Friends'' actress), something that shouldn't surprise
a guy who writes ambiguously daring lines like : ``I'll wait for
you while she slips in something comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started,'' Duritz said, ``I thought we were a
great band. But I thought the songs were so personal that not many
people would relate to them. Obviously, people are relating. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing is personal, but it isn't necessarily cathartic for
me. I don't think it simply makes everything better. If I'm having
a bad day, usually I'll write. Does it resolve what was wrong? No.
But if I write something, at least the mood hasn't been wasted. A
lot of getting older is about trying to fix things. Songwriting
fits into that somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove that some of the issues crawling around in his
brain are trivial, he admits his latest project: ``I'm trying to
learn to like pumpernickel bread. I love food, so it bothers me
that I don't like this bread. So I bought some pastrami, and I'm
gonna sit down and try this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
