<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4644 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      07-27 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SMALL-TOWN STAR GETS BIG CHANCE WITH DALLAS COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Ohio, Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENT ZWERNEMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Compare the feeling to Ed McMahon
unexpectedly ringing your doorbell with a million-dollar greeting
or Halliburton Co. suddenly calling about an opening to replace
Dick Cheney as its chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   For Tim Seder, such a moment came one afternoon this past spring
when he arrived home from his high school coaching job to find a
message on his answering machine from Dallas Cowboys kicking coach
Steve Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up, you always see yourself as a little kid being
successful as a professional athlete, but at the end of college I
had moved on to being a teacher,'' Seder said. ``I didn't think I'd
have this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder, three years removed from tiny Ashland (Ohio) University,
is fighting fellow rookie Rian Lindell of Washington State for just
such an opportunity _ to kick field goals for the Cowboys. And,
Seder is slightly ahead in the competition heading into the second
week of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Both likely will get opportunities to kick when the Cowboys face
the Pittsburgh Steelers on Sunday at 7 p.m. in the teams' preseason
opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's made a few more field goals than Rian,'' Hoffman said,
``but it's certainly not cut and dried with one guy jumping ahead
of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, everyone can't help but smile at Seder's sudden
Cinderella showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's a unique individual,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said.
``He was out there teaching and coaching, and now he's got the
opportunity to kick in the NFL. There's no question he could be a
tremendous success story.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, former Ashland offensive line coach Dave
Jaumotte, an assistant with the Detroit Lions, mentioned to Hoffman
at the Indianapolis scouting combine that he knew of a good kicker
out of the school, located in central Ohio. As a result, Hoffman
asked for Seder to send a tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just in this high school gym without much light and
just a net hanging down,'' Hoffman said, grinning, of the resulting
video shot indoors because of a harsh Ohio winter. ``But he still
looked pretty good. I just kept the tape in my desk, because we
weren't looking for a kicker at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But 12 games into last season, the Cowboys replaced a struggling
Richie Cunningham with veteran Eddie Murray, who remains a
possibility this season should the rookies falter. Following the
season, the Cowboys started searching for a young kicker, one who
might save them money under the salary cap, instead of re-signing
Murray or the likes of Chris Boniol or Jeff Jaeger, who are still
available free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the hunt was on, all of these tapes were coming in, from
All-Americans to guys in Germany,'' Hoffman said. ``And every time
I looked at one, I kept going back and looking at Tim's tape.''
</P>
<P>
   So in early April, Hoffman called Seder, who was helping coach
basketball while getting ready for the baseball season at Lucas
High in Ashland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call came as such a surprise,'' said Tim's mother, Soni
Seder. ``We just felt like the good Lord must have worked this out
somehow, and he was determined to give it everything he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and Seder quickly agreed to a tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he came down to Texas Stadium and he was just kicking in
this old pair of indoor soccer sneakers, but he kicked it great,''
Hoffman said. ``Once you find a guy who has that athletic ability,
you've got to look deeper into it and find the guy who can handle
the pressures of the NFL. You want a guy who's mature, steady and
humble, and one who keeps his mouth shut and just does his job.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Hoffman had found the perfect candidate in Seder,
who's married and signs autographs with a scripture (Proverbs
3:5-6) attached. The player has attended the same church, Grace
Brethren in Ashland, his whole life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky to be here and I thank the Lord every day for the
chance,'' Seder said. ``There's a lot of people who love to just go
in the back yard and kick, let alone come out here and play with
the Dallas Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt that Seder, 25, had stayed strong and active by
training with the boys he was coaching at Lucas High.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working out with the kids was important,'' he said. ``Because
how could I tell them to do something if I couldn't? So if we got
up at 6:30 a.m. to lift weights, I would go and lift, and they
would also see me run and do those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seder's numbers weren't spectacular at Ashland, where he made 27
of 39 field goals and 37 of 40 extra points over his junior and
senior seasons in 1996 and '97. But Hoffman said he looks at a
kicker's form, not his statistics, when evaluating the player
because of all the intangibles that come with kicking in college,
including playing surface.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said Seder, who is 5-feet-9-inches and 180 pounds, has a
classic delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits the ball straight, gets the ball up and pushes it
through the goalposts,'' Campo said. ``But the kicking situation
(will be determined) by what happens in games and critical
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Seder also knows guys like Murray and Jaeger can show up on a
day's notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the NFL is,'' he said. ``They want the best people
out there, and that's what pushes you every day. I've said this
myself as a coach: If you don't have somebody to compete against,
then you're not going to get any better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his high school kids, imagine their reaction to learning
Coach Seder had earned a tryout with the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were happy for me,'' Seder said, smiling. ``I like to
think that I had pushed them in the weight room and all of those
things, but they were pushing me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Brent Zwerneman by e-mail at
bzwerneman(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-IVOR-STOCKARD-CHANNIN     07-27 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-STOCKARD-CHANNING-IN-THE-TRUTH-ABOUT-JANE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH ABOUT STOCKARD CHANNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Stockard
Channing in scenes from ``The West Wing'' and ``The Truth About
Jane.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Third time's the charm, or so it seems.
 &HT;    At any rate, it's a pretty remarkable achievement for Stockard
Channing to have been nominated for an Emmy Award as best
supporting actress in a dramatic series _ despite the fact that her
performance has included only three episodes.
 &HT;    Perhaps it isn't so surprising, however _ as far back as her
performance as the wisecracking Rizzo in ``Grease'' (1978), it's
been hard to look at anyone else when Channing is on stage or
screen. No wonder that she can steal scenes even from so seasoned a
veteran as Martin Sheen, who plays President Josiah Bartlet to
Channing's First Lady Abby Bartlet in the hit NBC series.
 &HT;    If Channing cops the Emmy it will be her second, to go with a
Tony Award and an Oscar nomination for ``Six Degrees of
Separation'' (1993).
 &HT;    At 56, Channing is as busy as she's ever been. She's recently
wrapped not one but two independent films: the Canadian production
``Piano Man's Daughter'' and ``Business of Strangers,'' filmed in
New York. She has the first two episodes of the new season of
``West Wing'' in the can, as well as ``It's a Girl Thing,'' a
four-hour Showtime miniseries in which she plays a psychiatrist
whose patients include Kate Capshaw, Elle Macpherson, Rebecca
DeMornay, Mia Farrow, Linda Hamilton, Glenne Hedley, Lynn
Whitfield, Camryn Manheim and Channing's ``West Wing'' colleague
Allison Janney.
 &HT;    Then there's ``The Truth About Jane,'' a controversial
television movie airing Aug. 7 on Lifetime. Set in a quiet,
middle-class suburb, it's about a family shaken to its core when
the 15-year-old daughter reveals to her parents that she's gay.
 &HT;    Producer Orly Adelson says that Channing was essential to the
cast, since as the mother, Janice, she has a role that's in many
ways more difficult than the title character. The part demands an
actress who can be hostile and without understanding for most of
the story without completely losing the audience _ who can be
realistic while at the same time retaining some connection even
when the character is at her most unsympathetic.
 &HT;    ``You're willing to invest your emotion with an actress like
her,'' Adelson says. ``It works because she represents most mothers
in America who have a dream of what their kid should be, vs. who
they really are. She represents all of us.''
 &HT;    Struggling with a nasty cold, Channing admits that Janice wasn't
an easy role to get a handle on. The character thinks of herself as
liberal in thought, word and deed _ why, her best friend is an
openly gay man (RuPaul Charles) _ but she can't handle it when her
baby falls in love with the new girl in town.
 &HT;    ``She's in violent denial,'' Channing says. ``I wanted to make
her as human as possible. I didn't totally agree with the way she
was behaving, but one of the points of the piece is we all behave
this way all the time, especially when the mother/teen-age daughter
conflict is all tied up with it.''
 &HT;    Jane's father (James Naughton) is more understanding and
accepting. He is appalled at his wife's completely out-of-character
reaction _ but, Channing says, that doesn't make him automatically
the good guy.
 &HT;    ``Let's face it,'' the actress says, ``children are usually
raised by their mothers. What happens to this family is not just a
bolt of lightning _ there's an attrition involved, as there is in
any kind of conflict. The husband becomes good cop to her bad cop.
There's an isolation of this woman, and I found that very moving.''
 &HT;    Although the story is in part taken from the life of Lee Rose,
its writer/director, Channing says she too can identify with Jane's
situation.
 &HT;    ``I didn't make the best life choices when I was 15,'' she says,
``and when at 19 I told my mother I wanted to be an actress, I
thought she was going to shoot me.''
 &HT;    Jane accuses her mother of being concerned only with what her
friends will think. Janice insists that she's only thinking of her
daughter _ ``You don't understand how cruel the world can be,'' she
says.
 &HT;    Channing sees some truth in Janice's protestations.
 &HT;    ``She's not wrong,'' she says. ``Even today there are too many
stories still out there of persecution of kids in school who choose
alternative lifestyles in any way. High school is hell.''
 &HT;    As part of her research for the film, Channing _ a child of
affluent parents who studied at the Madeira School in McLean, Va.,
and then Radcliffe College in Cambridge, Mass. _ attended a meeting
of Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays, one of several
national organizations which offered support for the movie.
 &HT;    ``I walked into a huge ballroom in Washington, D.C., and
listened to these people testifying,'' the actress recalls. ``It
was incredibly moving. These were not particularly sophisticated
people, and they had no idea how to cope when this happened to
them. What they all had in common was figuring out how to keep
their family relationships together.''
 &HT;    Given the amount of preparation she likes to bring to a role,
it's astonishing that Channing can survive so busy a schedule.
 &HT;    ``I'm a little tired,'' she admits, ``but I like all the
juggling. I like a lot of variety in my life _ it enables me to
refresh myself.''
 &HT;    Still, she adds that she wouldn't mind cutting back on her
schedule to free up more time for ``The West Wing,'' if
writer/creator Aaron Sorkin were to expand her character.
 &HT;    Channing was taken with the show from its very first episode,
which she happened to see while unpacking her suitcase in yet
another hotel room.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `What a great show,''' she recalls. ``And a week
later I had a call from Aaron Sorkin to tell me they wanted me for
first lady. I really responded to the great actors, the writing and
the direction. I took three days off from the film I was shooting
and went to L.A. to talk to them.''
 &HT;    So far, however, the first lady has made only intermittent
appearances on the show, partly in deference to Channing's
jampacked schedule and partly because of the basic concept of the
series, which after all focuses on the West Wing, where the
president works, rather than on the East Wing, where he lives.
 &HT;    ``It's tricky to give her much to do,'' Channing says, ``because
she's really tangential to the West Wing action. Also, there are
seven or eight fabulous characters to be fleshed out.
 &HT;    ``But she's got a great, non-dysfunctional relationship with her
husband, and that's unusual in this era, particularly for a first
lady,'' she adds with a laugh. ``If Aaron wants to integrate me
more into the action, he'll figure out a way to do it. I'd just
love it _ but it's up to him.''
 &HT;    Offscreen, the actress has a non-dysfunctional relationship of
her own with cinematographer Daniel Gillham, with whom the
four-times-married Channing has lived for 14 years.
 &HT;    ``Maybe,'' she says, laughing, ``it's the not getting married
that is the charm!''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
