<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN EDINBURGH 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By SARAH LYALL  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    August may be the best month of all to visit Edinburgh, the most
regal of Scottish cities. Not only are the northern days still
delightfully long, but it is also the month for the Edinburgh
International Festival, a world-renowned feast of music, dance and
theater.
 &HT;    Most of Edinburgh is given over to the festival, as
international companies, including the New York City Ballet, Czech
Philharmonic Orchestra and Royal Dramatic Theater in Stockholm,
take over theaters and concert halls, leaving the visitor
thoroughly spoiled for choice.
 &HT;    It has been a year since Scotland embarked on a bold democratic
experiment, swearing in its first England-free Parliament in almost
300 years and getting to run its own affairs when it comes to
things such as education and health.
 &HT;    The new legislators have yet to move into their custom-made
building at Holyrood, but construction can be observed in the Old
City, on Edinburgh's south side. When Parliament is in session, the
legislators themselves can be seen building Scotland's new
political order in their temporary headquarters, near the George IV
Bridge.
 &HT;    One caveat: it is normal, while visiting Edinburgh, to become
unduly obsessed with the vicissitudes of Scottish weather. It can
be cold; it can be hot; rain is generally lurking somewhere on the
horizon. The best course is to plan for the worst, but hope for the
best.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    From Aug. 13 to Sept. 2, Edinburgh will feast on the dizzyingly
eclectic smorgasbord that is the Edinburgh International Festival.
For tickets and a full list of events, call the festival office at
(44-131) 473-2000 (www.eif.co.uk) or Globaltickets at (800)
223-6108 in the United States.
 &HT;    Tickets can also be purchased at the Hub, the festival's
handsome new headquarters _ a prime spot for eating and shopping,
too _ on the Royal Mile in the Old City. Here are some highlights:
 &HT;    On Sept. 1, the Czech Philharmonic Orchestra will be performing
Janacek's Sinfonietta and Mahler's ``Das Lied von der Erde,'' a
lyrical meditation on death and nature. Curtain time is 8 p.m. at
Usher Hall on Lothian Road. Tickets from $7.50 to $58.50
(calculated at $1.50 to the pound).
 &HT;    The pianist Christian Zacharias will direct and accompany the
Scottish Chamber Orchestra in a rendering of the complete cycle of
Mozart's piano concertos, over seven nights between Aug. 14 and 27
at Usher Hall. Tickets $7.50 to $46.50.
 &HT;    Another of the festival's delights is seeing a play in a foreign
language. This year's possibilities include a German ``Hamlet'' and
a Spanish play called ``One thousand five hundred meters above the
level of Jack,'' about a deep-sea diver teetering on the edge of
madness. All have English supertitles. On various dates; tickets
from $9 to $33.75.
 &HT;    The Netherlands Dance Theater _ really three companies in one,
with each made up of dancers at different points in their careers _
is presenting a program of bold, sexy dancing over five nights,
from Aug. 29 to Sept. 2. And on Aug. 30 and 31, dancers from NDT1,
the main company, will dance to music played by the Czech
Philharmonic Orchestra, with Sir Charles Mackerras conducting.
Performances are at 7:30 p.m. at various sites; tickets, $7.50 to
$55.50.
 &HT;    There also is the well-known but much less formalized Edinburgh
Fringe Festival, which features stand-up comedy, theater, skits,
dance, music and mime in halls, parks, clubs and on the streets.
Performances run Aug. 6 to 28; (44-131) 226-5138; www.edfringe.com.
Admission to some performances is free; tickets range up to $22.50.
 &HT;    From Aug. 4 to 26, Edinburgh is also celebrating the 50th
anniversary of the Edinburgh Military Tattoo, an extravaganza of
pipes and drums and well-turned calves peeking out from beneath
kilts. It takes place at night, beside Edinburgh Castle, which adds
to the pageantry; (44-131) 225-1188, www.edintattoo.co.uk. Shows
are Monday to Friday at 9 p.m., and Saturday at 7:30 and 10:30 p.m.
Tickets: $12.75 to $36.75.
 &HT;    Devoted to Dadaists and Surrealists such as Ernst, Magritte and
Man Ray, the Dean Gallery, 73 Belford Road, is a beautifully
organized new museum in a grand, neo-Classical former orphanage in
north Edinburgh. An exhibition from Saturday through Oct. 1 will
feature Salvador Dali. Open Monday to Saturday 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.,
Sunday 2 to 5 p.m.; (44-131) 624-6200. The regular collection is
free; the Dali exhibition is $6.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    If the day is spectacularly sunny (it happens sometimes),
celebrate at the Royal Botanic Garden, 70 acres of beautiful
gardens and greenhouses that feature a display of herbaceous
borders during August. Tucked amid all the greenery are a cafe and
shop. The Garden, 20A Inverleith Row, (44-131) 552-7171, is open
daily 9:30 a.m. to 7 p.m. (6 p.m. in September). Free admission.
 &HT;    The former royal yacht Britannia is docked on Ocean Drive in
Leith, and you can pay $11.55 ($8.95 ages 60 and older, $5.60 ages
5 to 17) to stride its four decks in a monarchical manner. Open
10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. Monday to Thursday, and until 7:30 p.m.
Friday and Saturday; (44-131) 555-5566. Reservations are advised.
 &HT;    It cost hundreds of millions of dollars less than the Millennium
Dome in Greenwich, but Dynamic Earth, a new museum not far from the
royal Palace of Holyroodhouse, is far more successful. This
minidome offers nothing less than the story of Earth in all its
diversity.
 &HT;    Visitors can experience icebergs, volcanoes and tropical rain
forests, among other things, in 11 galleries with stunning special
effects. Open daily 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. in summer, with last entry at
4:45. Information: (44-131) 550-7800; admission is $10.40, $5.90
ages 5 to 15.
 &HT;    The Museum of Scotland, on Chambers Street, presents a whirlwind
tour of Scottish history. Attractions include an authentic
18th-century guillotine. The top floor is a crazy quilt of objects
_ from golf balls and hairdryers to a Saab convertible to the Queen
song ``Bohemian Rhapsody'' _ that ordinary Scots have identified as
essential to their very being. Open daily. Admission (which also
gets you into the Royal Museum next door) is $4.50, $2.25 for
students and those 60 and older. Free for people under 19, and on
Tuesdays after 4:30 p.m.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Rooms are scarce during the festival. For 11th-hour help, try
www.edinburgh.org, which has a listing of hotels, or (44-131)
473-3800. For rooms in private homes at festival time, call
(44-131) 225-1101.
 &HT;    Just 10 minutes by car from the center of town and easily
reachable by bus, the Malmaison stands in modern splendor in Leith,
a lively and much-revived waterfront neighborhood east of central
Edinburgh.
 &HT;    The hotel, one in an admired British chain, is decorated in cool
earth tones, with clean lines and geometric motifs. The 60 rooms
include five suites. Doubles from $165, with tax. One Tower Place,
Leith; (44-131) 468-5000, fax (44-131) 468-5002.
 &HT;    The recently refurbished Edinburgh Royal Circus Hotel, 19-21
Royal Circus, in a handsome Georgian building in central Edinburgh,
offers 30 rooms, friendly service, garden views and easy access to
major attractions. Doubles are $144, tax and breakfast included;
(44-131) 220-5000, fax (44-131) 220-2020.
 &HT;    Budget: The Ashlyn Guest House, 42 Inverleith Row near the
Botanic Garden, is one of scores of small family-run hotels that
offer all the comforts of someone else's home at reasonable prices.
Five of the eight bedrooms have private baths. No smoking. Doubles
start at $45 a person, breakfast included. Telephone and fax
(44-131) 552-2954.
 &HT;    The Borthwick Guest House, at 23 Mayfield Gardens on the city's
south side, offers 11 bedrooms, all with private baths. Doubles
from $45 per person, breakfast included; (44-131) 667-8475, fax
(44-131) 667-6763.
 &HT;    Luxury: The Bonham, 35 Drumsleugh Gardens, Edinburgh's newest
hip hotel, epitomizes the city's seemingly effortless ability to
combine the old and the new. Constructed from three adjoining town
houses, the hotel has a stately Victorian facade that belies a
thoroughly modern interior, with brash contemporary furniture and
modern art. There are 48 rooms; doubles from $247.50, with tax and
breakfast. If the Bonham is full, its owners will gladly recommend
their other two hotels, the Howard and Channings, which are cozy
and Old World; (800) 323-5463 from the United States, fax (44-131)
226-6080.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Tucked away off the Royal Mile, Dubh Prais, 123B High Street,
offers Scottish dishes lovingly prepared with traditional recipes.
Try collops in the pan, steak medallions in a
port-and-pickled-walnut sauce; for dessert, there's atholl brose
parfait, an unusually tasty ice cream made with toasted oatmeal,
honey and Drambuie. A typical dinner for two, plus wine, costs
about $90. Reservations are essential _ there are only nine tables;
(44-131) 557-5732.
 &HT;    The Tower, at the top of the Museum of Scotland on Chambers
Street, is one of Edinburgh's hottest new restaurants. Appetizers
include sauteed mushrooms with spinach, poached egg and toasted
brioche; for the main course, portions of steak and roast beef come
in three sizes: 8, 12, and 16 ounces. Dinner for two, with wine,
generally comes to about $150. A two-course pre-theater dinner for
$18 is available from 4 to 6 p.m.; (44-131) 225-3003.
 &HT;    Most of Scotland's art galleries and museums feature smart cafes
with tasty dishes. One that stands out is Cafe Newton in the Dean
Gallery, 73 Belford Road. It is open the same hours as the gallery
and offers a small selection of light entrees, like smoked salmon
with creme fraiche, and an eggplant, feta, pesto and olive sandwich
on a choice of bread. A sculpture of Isaac Newton looks down from
the center of the room. Sandwiches average $6.35; daily hot
specials range from $6.75 to $8.25; brownies and other treats cost
from $1.20 to $4.35; no alcohol served.
 &HT;    Tucked into a corner of Hunter Square, not far from the bustle
of the Royal Mile, Bann's vegetarian cafe provides healthful food.
At dinner, appetizers include Thai phyllo parcels with stir-fried
vegetables on wilted bok choy, with a sweet sesame-seed oil
dressing; main courses include tarte tatin made of
 &HT;    layers of roasted sweet pepper, zucchini and cheddar cheese, and
an all-vegetable haggis _ no animal innards to speak of. Dinner for
two, with wine, costs about $60. Open daily 10 a.m. to 11 p.m.;
(44-131) 226-1112.
 &HT;    In the last few years, George Street has overtaken the
increasingly tacky Princes Street nearby as the city's choice
shopping and eating street. One of the nicest restaurants here is
the Dome, in a vast, high-ceilinged building that used to be a
mortuary, then a bank.
 &HT;    At the outside Garden Cafe, enjoy pizza and pasta (weather
permitting) for about $24 for two, wine included; in the Grill
Room, expect to pay from $60 to $75 for two, including wine, at
dinner for dishes that include pheasant and apricot terrine with
red currant dressing. They can both be found under one dome at 14
George Street; (44-131) 624-8624. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Sarah Lyall is a reporter in the London bureau of The Times.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Sarah Lyall 
