<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: VETERANS GET VIP TREATMENT IN BRANSON, MO.  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    When the Osmond Brothers ask all the veterans of war who attend
their showcase in Branson, Mo., to stand up, nearly one-third of
the crowd rises while the rest of the audience gives a thunderous
round of applause.
 &HT;    This show of respect is a common occurrence at the Osmond
production, one of many in Branson that run daily from breakfast to
bedtime to satisfy the more than 7 million visitors who come to
town each year.
 &HT;    Of those visitors, 2.3 million are veterans who, along with
their families, are treated like VIPs in this heartland town in
south-central Missouri. Some 250 military reunions are held there
annually, and there is even a hotline to help people organize
gatherings of all sorts, including military events. (For more
information, call 21st Century Tours at 877-349-3378.)
 &HT;    Branson's 5,000 residents and performers work hard to welcome
veterans with special treats. One that shouldn't be missed is the
six-day Veterans Homecoming, which takes place each November to
celebrate Veteran's Day. This year's celebration will include an 8K
race in which participants will walk or run _ even roll in
wheelchairs _ and special tributes to those who were bestowed the
Congressional Medal of Honor. In addition, several of the area
shows will be free to the public _ or heavily discounted _ to honor
our country's veterans.
 &HT;    For a schedule of events, write to the Branson Veterans Task
Force, P.O. Box 1726, Branson, MO 65615; or call (417) 337-8387.
 &HT;    
 THE BOOK THAT STARTED IT ALL  
 &HT;    The book ``Shepherd of the Hills,'' a tale about the lives,
loves and deceptions of the Ozark mountain people in the early
1900s, sold more than 1 million copies when it was first published
back in 1907. Its overwhelming popularity played a large part in
putting Branson on the map. Suddenly, people from across the
country wanted to see for themselves some of the ``hillbillies''
described on its pages. Eventually, the book was adapted for the
stage, and today that show is still performed nightly from April
through October.
 &HT;    As part of festivities, audience members who pay an additional
board an open-air train that takes them on an historical tour of
the area. Highlights include passing by the home of Old Matt, one
of the show's primary characters, and the 230-foot Inspiration
Tower, a landmark on the pageant grounds. The tour also includes
special events, such as a bluegrass festival.
 &HT;    The production is great fun, and during intermission the actors
welcome spectators to make their way down to the stage, take part
in a square dance and chat with the cast.
 &HT;    A combination adult ticket for the tour and play costs $27;
admission to the play alone is $21. For more information, call
(800) 653-6288 or visit www.old-matt.com. Please note: Those with
mobility problems should discuss their needs when purchasing
tickets.
 &HT;    Another way to see Branson is to buy a ticket for the Branson
Scenic Railway, (800) 287-2462, a 40-mile round-trip tour onboard a
vintage-car train. Knowledgeable guides give riders a taste of the
local history. Except for mid-December to mid-March, the train runs
daily, including a dinner run Saturday nights from May to December.
The train leaves from the Main Street depot in downtown Branson. An
adult ticket costs $19.35 plus tax.
 &HT;    
 CRAFTSMAN COLLEGE  
 &HT;    Any trip to Branson wouldn't be complete without a stop in
Silver Dollar City _ (800) 952-6626 or www.silverdollarcity.com _
an historically recreated town that takes visitors back in time to
the turn of the century in Ozark country. Here, employees dressed
in period costumes man the rides, restaurants and shops, and many
of the booths show how common goods were once created.
 &HT;    Last fall, Dr. Jack Gillispie of Kimberling City, Mo., spent a
day in Silver Dollar City _ a day that would ultimately lead him to
discover a new hobby. Because of his fascination with metalwork, it
wasn't long before the family practitioner found himself hanging
around the blacksmith's shop. By watching the smithy work and
speaking with the ``locals,'' he learned that he could enroll in a
``Craftsman for a Day'' seminar, which would teach him the basic
skills of forging. Other craft seminars offer instruction in the
finer points of dipping candles and weaving baskets, much like the
locals did years ago, before the dawn of the Industrial Revolution.
 &HT;    On his second visit to Silver Dollar this past April, Gillispie
once again visited the blacksmith shop, but this time he was
immediately handed a costume that helped him blend in with the
other villagers. Then, after a lesson in safety procedures, the
doctor was put to work to the delight of the watching crowd.
 &HT;    Being more adept with a stethoscope than a hammer and anvil,
Gillispie started with a small task _ making a little nail. He then
moved on to crafting a metal hook to hang a flower pot from and,
eventually, a rose that was constructed step by step. ``Mine looked
more like a dandelion,'' he confesses, ``but I really got into it.
It was a blast.''
 &HT;    In fact, Gillispie was so inspired by the class that herecently
ordered his own coal forge and anvil for his home, where he plans
to start tinkering with metalwork and reading a few books on the
subject before returning to Silver Dollar City for more lessons.
 &HT;    The day-long programs range in price from $30 to $125, depending
on the craft. For more information, call (800) 695-1353.
 &HT;    
 MORE TRAINING  
 &HT;    In addition to day-long craft seminars, Silver Dollar City also
offers three- to five-day seminars in specific craft skills. For
example, a pottery seminar with Master Craftsman Todd Nelson is
slated for Sept. 8 to 10, and five woodcarving seminars will be
held March 5 to 9. The longer seminars vary in price from $75 to
$275, depending on the instructor.
 &HT;    For more information about Branson _ including road information
_ call (800) 214-3661, or visit www.branson.tripusa.com on the Web.
You can also visit the city's Web site at www.bransonchamber.com.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
