<HEADLINE>
BE STRONG, YOU HAVEN'T SEEN THE LAST OF KATHIE LEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects 6th graf, ``The Star has her on the cover...'', sted
Enquirer.   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frankly, friends, it's a miracle I'm able to sit up and write
this, but thanks to the inventiveness of modern pharmacology and
the support of my grief therapy group I have managed to make it
half way through Kathie Lee's Farewell Week with only one or two
minor breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   I confess I lost it Tuesday morning when Kathie Lee's buddy
Diane Sawyer presented the discount diva with a set of human-size
butterfly wings and fondly urged, ``Soar!'' Kathie Lee donned the
wings and capered about the stage. Really, I said to myself, there
won't be many moments like this on TV from now on, say what you
will about the possibilities of ``reality'' programming. What will
we do without her?
</P>
<P>
   During this period of national mourning I have tried to tell
myself that Kathie Lee isn't really going away permanently, she's
just changing her career path and exploring hitherto unplumbed
depths of her talent. Stretching, as they say in show business.
Still, it's difficult to live with the knowledge that Kathie Lee
will no longer be sitting there with Regis every weekday morning
doing what she does so well, whatever it is. Let others speculate
about who will get her job. Who cares. No one can replace her.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee occupies a unique place in our culture. She's our
bipolar celebrity. We either love her or loathe her. She's a
wholesome, all-American girl, a down-to-earth mother of two
adorable children who is struggling to save her marriage. Or she's
a self-obsessed no-talent who's built a career on making a public
spectacle of herself, her husband, her children.
</P>
<P>
   This stark divide in public opinion is cleverly exploited by the
current issues of two supermarket tabloids, the Star and the
National Enquirer. Both publications are owned by the same company,
American Media Inc., and both have a history of covering Kathie
Lee's every move as it really mattered.
</P>
<P>
   What will Kathie Lee do when she leaves ``Live!''? Take your
pick of stories. The Star has her on the cover, with the headline,
``Kathie Lee Gets Even'' and the line, ``Regis is history, Frank's
next.'' According to anonymous ``friends,'' she's quitting the show
to minimize bad publicity when she dumps aging philanderer Frank
Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like the Star's version, the Enquirer's is more
upbeat, quoting another anonymous ``friend'' who has the
not-so-happy couple repairing to some secret destination to work on
saving their marriage. ``The talk show queen is determined to lay
the groundwork for a long and happy future with Frank,'' the
Enquirer states.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that seems absolutely certain is that Kathie Lee
is determined to lay the groundwork for a very happy future for
Kathie Lee. She's said to have a sitcom in development, she's been
angling for a starring role in a Broadway musical, and she's
determined to become a successful singer-songwriter. On ``Live!''
earlier this week she announced that she's been busily creating new
songs with producers Ernie Lake and Bobby Guy. She insisted on
playing a sample. I don't recall the exact words, but it was
something along the lines of (I'm paraphrasing): I've had it up to
here with you, you bum, and I've found somebody better.
</P>
<P>
   I got the feeling that Regis was not the inspiration for this
song, although he was sitting there with an expression that seemed
to say, ``Only three more days! Give me strength!''
</P>
<P>
   It may be Kathie Lee's Farewell Week on ``Live!,'' but not in
any larger sense. I have the feeling that this is just the first of
many farewells, and that like Barbra Streisand, the Judds, and so
many others, Kathie Lee will be saying goodbye to us again and
again, for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
