<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAT POETS REMIND READERS THAT THE MOVEMENT WAS AS MUCH LITERARY
BRAIN AS EMOTIONAL BRAWN 
</HEADLINE>
 BEATPOETS KANSAS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN MARK EBERHART  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Integral Years: Poems 1966-1994 (Vol. III of The Crooked
Lines of God: A Life Trilogy) by William Everson (372 pages; Black
Sparrow Press; $30 hardcover, $17.50 paperback) America: A History
in Verse, Vol. I, 1900-1939 by Edward Sanders (391 pages; Black
Sparrow Press; $27.50 hardcover, $16 paperback)
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kerouac On the Road, William Burroughs as a Junkie, Allen
Ginsberg making his poetry Howl: They and other Beat writers
challenged literary traditions and life's conventions by
questioning America's cultural ethos and exploring their own
tortured psyches.
</P>
<P>
   Beats were the 20th century's Romantics, the artists who tried
everything, who championed freedom of spirit and expression even if
it meant paying what William Blake called ``the price of
experience.'' They have always been valued for their visceral
impact but at times underappreciated for their intellect.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg's Howl, for example, reads more like a wail than an
epic poem, and yet it is both, a keening lament for the destruction
of the ``best minds'' of a generation but also a keenly wrought
observation of how American life in the 1950s could cease to make
sense even to the sanest of spirits.
</P>
<P>
   So now come two books to remind us again that the Beats go on,
and that the substance of their thoughts remains as important as
the style in which they render them.
</P>
<P>
   One poet here delves into the universal soul of a nation while
the other finds Wordsworthian inspiration in the personal _ but
both of them arrive, strangely, at the same place: a place of
peace.  &LR; brk:America the bountiful
</P>
<P>
   Edward Sanders was born in Kansas City in 1939. Now the man who
founded the Fugs (a satiric poetry rock group) and wrote a 1971
book on Charles Manson and his followers called The Family is
living in Woodstock, N.Y. (where else?) and still writes fine
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   America: A History in Verse is the first in a projected
multivolume work, and Sanders is off to a marvelous start: This may
be history, but it is also poetic exuberance, a remarkable blend of
information dissemination and the sheer joy of word-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way my nation seethes,'' Sanders writes in his
Introduction, and continues:
</P>
<P>
   I love its creativity
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; the flow of its wild needs
</P>
<P>
   to build itself
</P>
<P>
   on a tiny place
</P>
<P>
   in a spiral galaxy
</P>
<P>
   called the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   As for his credentials to write such a thing (a history in
verse?), Sanders quickly answers his own rhetorical question:
</P>
<P>
   And who am I, someone could ask, to write
</P>
<P>
   a history of America?
</P>
<P>
   I am a bard
</P>
<P>
   trained with my every breath
</P>
<P>
   for 41 years
</P>
<P>
   to chant &AMP; sing, whisper, shout, keen, dance with joy
</P>
<P>
   &AMP; try to trace with grace
</P>
<P>
   what the Fates &AMP; Human Mammals have wrought
</P>
<P>
   in the Time-Track of America
</P>
<P>
   ``To chant &AMP; sing,'' indeed: Sanders' work is so surprisingly
mirthful that it fairly dances on the page. We are not used to
history rendered as poetry, and yet in centuries past, it was more
common. Perhaps it is silly to imagine the historians of 2000
tossing out their tomes and producing verse instead, but Sanders'
effort is gloriously refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   His fascination with his country is impossible to resist, from
Sanders' bouncy accounts of the arrival of Halley's comet and
departure of Mark Twain in 1910 to the bluster of Teddy Roosevelt,
president from 1901 to 1909, to the strife of workers' movement
groups such as the Wobblies.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the events turn grim, such as the recounting of the
Lindbergh baby kidnapping in 1932, Sanders' lines keep their
buoyancy and vitality. Life may not always be pleasant, but the
poet never descends into the maudlin or lurid:
</P>
<P>
   In the night
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morrow &AMP; Charles Lindbergh's 19-month-old son
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jr.
</P>
<P>
   was snatched from their just-completed
</P>
<P>
   grand style house near Princeton, New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   The perp left a homemade ladder under the bedroom
</P>
<P>
   window and a ransom note in ``broken English''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' depictions of harrowing events always retain a dignity
while managing a poetic resonance. This is journalism with a beat.
</P>
<P>
   The year 1939 was not an easy one for America, with war looming
and the Depression lingering, and yet at the end of this volume,
the poet delivers a near-song of good people and good things: Bela
Bartok's music, Grandma Moses' paintings and a roll-call of
literary greats ranging from John Steinbeck to James Thurber to
Henry Miller to Raymond Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, in short, smiles throughout these verses, even when
America doesn't seem to have something to smile about. For him, the
rhythm of life is enough. ``Seething Nation!'' he exults at the
end. ``Vast &AMP; Flowing! Day &AMP; Night &AMP; Dawn!''
</P>
<P>
   Bring on Vol. II.  &LR; brk:Prelude to a poet
</P>
<P>
   Black Sparrow, a small press in Santa Rosa, Calif., also has
released a fine new volume, this one by William Everson.
</P>
<P>
   Everson, who once was known as Brother Antoninus of the
Dominican Order, made no secret of the model for his epic
autobiography in verse, Dust Shall Be the Serpent's Food. His
prototype was no less than William Wordsworth's The Prelude or
Growth of a Poet's Mind, as Everson told his friend Allen Campo as
early as 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Everson never finished his epic. And yet the five of Everson's
10 planned cantos are extraordinary on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Wordsworth's greatest moments involved solitude or
near-solitude _ rowing on a still lake, crossing a mountain pass,
communing with whatever rock he had befriended for a day _
Everson's epiphanies involve people.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken by the death of his mother only five years before, he
explodes in anger and grief at his father's funeral, as told in
Canto One, ``In Medias Res'':
</P>
<P>
   I had stood dry-eyed, but when the lid was closed
</P>
<P>
   Something snapped in my skull. In a choking
</P>
<P>
   Rage, twisted by unreckonable guilt,
</P>
<P>
   I pounded my fists on the coffin,
</P>
<P>
   Sobbing: ``Why! Why!'' and slumped to my knees,
</P>
<P>
   Jarring the bier.
</P>
<P>
   Everson may wear his feelings on his sleeve, but these are
feelings of universal loss. And in the tradition of Wordsworth and
other great Romantics, those feelings are held under tight artistic
control in the poem. Critics sometimes forget that the rage and
pain of Romanticism was reflected through a prism of rewriting and
hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Dust Shall Be the Serpent's Food, which also owes much to the
Book of Isaiah, is only one pleasure of this volume, the last
installment of Everson's collected poems. Shorter works, from
``Dark Waters'' to ``Steelhead,'' show a poet at ease with both the
natural world and human mind.
</P>
<P>
   But the images in Dust, from adulterous wives to traveling by
rail to visions of spiritual redemption, are perhaps the most
arresting of all the works here. In the final Canto, Everson
reaches a soulful crescendo that every poet must yearn for:
</P>
<P>
   But the ills of the world,
</P>
<P>
   By God's clear injunction, are to be reckoned
</P>
<P>
   Implicitly benign. His vivid signature, dazzlingly
</P>
<P>
   Calligraphed on trees, rivers, rocks, buttes and benchlands,
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal of life is the measure of its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Perdurably opportune, the hostages of pain
</P>
<P>
   Never fail to evince the quantification of value
</P>
<P>
   In the substance of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Everson, a native of Sacramento, Calif., died in 1994 at age 81
in Kingfisher Flat, Calif. This volume proves that, almost to the
very end, he continued to write _ and to write well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
