<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-HOTSPRINGS-GETAWAY-12     07-27 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTSPRINGS-GETAWAY-1200(2Take)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARKANSAS TOWN RENOWNED FOR ITS `CURATIVE WATERS' BECKONS ANEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOT SPRINGS, Ark. _ My mental image of Hot Springs is based
largely on secondhand memories, stemming from my childhood way back
in the '60s, when my grandmother would travel down to Arkansas from
her home in Missouri to ``take the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   She was old and weak and afflicted by arthritis; my aunt, who
was a nurse, thought the natural hot springs piped into the town's
many bathhouses might work some kind of miracle. I was only 4 or 5,
too young to go on these trips, but I formed a strong picture of
the resort town as some kind of magical hospital in the mountains,
a series of quiet, vast institutions where old people went to get
well.
</P>
<P>
   And so, even after a couple of brief visits within the past
decade, I am, on this July visit, having a hard time reconciling my
recollections with reality.
</P>
<P>
   We have already driven along the town's main drag _ past the
lovely horse track that was my other main childhood impression of
the place, past the row of majestic bathhouses that sit maintained
but empty, no longer used by bathers and not yet converted to new
uses, and down to the 75-year-old Arlington Hotel, across from the
tree-shaded trails of Hot Springs National Park.
</P>
<P>
   And now we are sitting in a shabby-chic, Mediterranean-flavored
restaurant called Pompeii, enjoying wine with our prosciutto-topped
pizza and rich Greek salads. As we try to decide where to head next
_ one of the galleries showcasing regional artists? the high school
attended by President Clinton, being turned into an artists'
colony? the row of charming boutiques and home-decor shops we'd
spotted down the street? _ an ebullient restaurateur is making
plans for us to visit his friend's trendy restaurant-slash-cigar
lounge down the street for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Hot Springs of 15 years ago, or even five
years ago,'' Mark Johnston, executive director of the soon-to-open
Clinton Cultural Campus, would tell me later. ``We have a thriving
arts community, which we did not have, and a very active and
restored downtown area, and incredible growth in the lakes area.
The number of tourists has just increased incredibly over the last
five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The bathhouses, most of which are out of business, are no longer
the city's main draw; more visitors probably associate Hot Springs
first and foremost with the spring racing season at Oaklawn, the
stately track where thoroughbreds have run for nearly a century.
Today's Hot Springs is also more a family resort than a health
sanitarium, with attractions including a child-friendly science
museum, watersports at the nearby lakes, a new amusement and water
park, and an excursion train.
</P>
<P>
   But separating Hot Springs from its past as a healing center is
like trying to imagine Fort Worth without cattle. Bathhouse Row may
no longer be Hot Springs' reason for being, but people do realize
there would be no Hot Springs without it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   An uncomplicated five-hour drive from Dallas-Fort Worth _
basically, it's a straight shot east on Interstate 30 _ Hot Springs
is nestled in the low-lying Zig Zag Mountains, on the edge of the
Ouachita Range, between Lake Hamilton and Lake Catherine. The city,
home to about 32,000, is built around the national park, which
includes both the historic bathhouses and the trails and
campgrounds carved into the surrounding mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surviving eight major bathhouses, lined up next to
one another on Central Avenue in the heart of downtown, date from
around 1920, but the legend of the hot springs is rooted far
earlier than that.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans may have seen the springs as early as 1541, when
Spanish explorer Hernando De Soto and his troops are rumored to
have stumbled across them. But American Indians had known about the
natural hot springs for at least 10,000 years, calling it Manataka,
the place of peace.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, Indian tribes used the valley as a neutral
gathering place for prayer, rituals and peace councils, says Lee
Standing Bear Moore, secretary of the Manataka American Indian
Council in Hot Springs. They were attracted not only by the hot
springs that flowed from the mountain, but also by the area's
beauty. The Indians believed the valleys, covered in lush forests
and draped in mist from the springs, had a special power, and not
just as a source of healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it; if you have a bad leg, are you going to walk
1,000 miles just to soak it in a spring?'' says Moore, who also
works at the Cherokee Longhouse, which sells American Indian gifts,
books, music, food and herbs in addition to housing a spa offering
baths and body treatments.''No, they came here for some other
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   But European settlers came in larger numbers to the springs
after French trappers used it in the late 1700s. In 1832, the U.S.
government set aside the land around the springs as the first U.S.
reservation, a precursor to the national park system, and formal
bathhouses began springing up.
</P>
<P>
   The first ones were crude wooden-and-canvas structures, little
more than tents, prone to fire, collapse and even rot from the
steam of the springs. As the area prospered, bigger and more
elaborate bathhouses were built, with marble floors, stained-glass
skylights, bubbling fountains, and the latest in exercise equipment
and treatment rooms. By 1921, the area had been named our 18th
national park, and Hot Springs considered itself the pre-eminent
health spa in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
