<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4755 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-HOTSPRINGS-GETAWAY-2n     07-27 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTSPRINGS-GETAWAY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
HOT SPRINGS, Ark.: spa in the nation. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, you can get a glimpse of this history at the Fordyce
Bathhouse, opened in 1989 as the park's visitor center, restored to
its glory days of the 1920s. The majority of the city's bathhouses
closed in the '60s and '70s, as the area declined. Today, only the
Buckstaff still operates along the row, though several hotels have
their own full bathhouses.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Fordyce, you can walk through the same rooms used by
the ill people who came to Hot Springs seeking a cure 50 or 80
years ago; they are outfitted with the same porcelain tubs, white
metal cots and steam cabinets used then.
</P>
<P>
   Here you can also learn the fascinating history of the city's
entirely separate set of bathhouses for African-Americans, who were
prohibited until the early 1960s from using white-only spas, though
they formed the bulk of their work force.
</P>
<P>
   The only one of these African-American bathhouses to remain
standing is the old National Baptist Hotel, and it is not included
on the maps of the other bathhouses. I found it, finally, a few
blocks away from the main row. Especially compared with the
manicured lawns and well-kept facades on Bathhouse Row, the
once-prominent resort looks sad and abandoned, its windows boarded
over with plywood and weeds creeping through cracks in the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, vague rumors have circulated that a company
intends to renovate the building, adding a new wing for a hotel and
turning the existing building into a museum. But nothing has come
of it, though residents still hope the building will someday be
used again.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, little has come of long-rumored plans to convert the
six empty bathhouses on Bathhouse Row into galleries or other
businesses. Though the entire row is listed on the National
Register of Historic Places, and restoration has been ongoing, no
businesses have been attracted to the space. Insiders say that's
partly because of the stringent regulations attached to the use of
historic buildings; a lack of parking has also hurt development,
though a planned parking garage may alleviate that.
</P>
<P>
   Another boost may come from the soon-to-open Clinton Cultural
Campus, the town's celebration of native son Bill Clinton, who was
born in the famously monikered Hope just down the road, but who
went to school in Hot Springs.
</P>
<P>
   A display in the Hot Springs National Park visitor center
chronicles his youth, but the town has grander plans. In October,
it will open the first phase of the Clinton Cultural Campus, a
complex of 38 loft-style apartments that will be leased at
affordable rates to artists, musicians, writers and actors from all
over the nation. The apartments were carved out of classrooms and
the gymnasium of the former 76-year-old junior high, adjacent to
the 1915-era high school that Clinton attended.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of years, the gothic-style high school will be
converted into an administration building, housing art galleries, a
Clinton museum and meeting rooms, director Johnston says. He also
hopes city arts groups, like the city's respected documentary film
festival, will move their offices there.
</P>
<P>
   The city's reinvention as an arts colony is still far from
complete. The area is still full of the typical mass-market
attractions endemic to any town dependent on tourist trade _ an
alligator farm, T-shirt shops, miniature golf courses, fast-food
stands, and something called Tiny Town, filled with moving
miniature scenes that reportedly took one family 50 years to
create. And I stood a long while outside the somewhat
alarming-looking Josephine Tussaud Wax Museum on the main strip,
listening to a couple argue about whether a wax bust was supposed
to be Barbara Bush. (It was actually a likeness of the museum's
namesake, though it bore a passing resemblance to the former first
lady.)
</P>
<P>
   But there are also surprises. Like an after-hours,
industrial-looking nightspot called Diva, where revelers dance
until dawn. And a cluster of hip restaurants, such as the one where
our attentive servers, including a former Miss Gay Arkansas, served
up eyebrow-grooming tips along with our glasses of cabernet and
pancetta-wrapped shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   And at the heart of it all is still the springs.
</P>
<P>
   My first afternoon in town, I sat in the park with a bottle of
cold spring water, watching local residents pull up to city
fountains dispensing free spring water. (Unlike that of many other
natural springs, the water here has no odd odor or strange taste.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a bath and be sure to drink a lot of the water,'' one
older man told me as he filled four plastic gallon jugs from the
spigot, his drinking water for the week. ``Yes, it's good for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   I took his advice. Indeed, it may no longer be the legendary
curing spa, but there's still something magical about water that
bubbles from the ground at 143 degrees, so hot that it must be
cooled down before you can bathe in it.
</P>
<P>
   On my way up to the hiking trails on Hot Springs Mountain early
one morning, I leaned over a grate, catching the rising steam and
getting an instant facial. Later, I went to the only remaining true
bathhouse, the Buckstaff, for a relaxing, old-fashioned spring
bath. It was a leisurely 90 minutes of soaking in an oversized
porcelain tub, lying on a metal cot wrapped in steaming hot towels,
then taking a shower of spring water afterward to cool down before
resting again in a quiet, institutionlike cooling room.
</P>
<P>
   It was, I imagined, the same routine my grandmother had followed
all those years ago, one that had been in place since long before I
was born. And if we're lucky, it will never completely die out.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
