<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WONDERLAND-FILM-NYT &LR;      07-27 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDERLAND-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WONDERLAND': THREE SISTERS IN LONDON, WITH LIVES WORTH MOURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Winterbottom's uneven ``Wonderland'' could be
called ``The Three Sisters'': a modern-day London turn on Chekhov,
it deals with the anguish of three women whose existences are in
varying stages of disintegration. The director is out to catch life
on the fly, and the movie feels real and unrehearsed, especially in
the relationships between the sisters, who could be the same woman
at different stages of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia (Gina McKee), a waitress, wants an attachment of some sort
_ any sort, actually _ and slinks from one bad entanglement to the
next. In one of the most riveting scenes in a movie this year, she
rides alone on a double-decker bus filled with loud, happy
revelers, and her face, normally a mask of dispassion, slowly
crumples into a teary mess.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie (Shirley Henderson), a hairdresser and single mother,
runs out to grab a pint and a few more moments of irresponsible fun
while her 11-year-old son raises himself. She is angry with the
boy's father (Ian Hart, who has come a long way from the
quick-witted cruelty of the John Lennon he played in ``Backbeat'').
</P>
<P>
   The pregnant Molly (Molly Parker) wants domestic simplicity,
though there are clear rumblings that her partner, Eddie (John
Simm), isn't ready for the family responsibilities that are days
away from changing his life forever.
</P>
<P>
   In following these characters through five days, Winterbottom
doesn't make the expectant mother the source of optimism. The one
person in the family whose life is happy is the women's brother,
Darren (Enzo Cilenti), the only son. He left home years before to
get away from the incessant grousing of his bitter mother (Kika
Markham), who sits in her row house and makes as much noise as the
neighbor's constantly barking dog.
</P>
<P>
   In the way Winterbottom deals with working-class life,
``Wonderland'' bears a stylistic similarity to the work of the
British social realist directors Ken Loach and Mike Leigh. There is
nothing pretty about the way the sisters get through a day. The sun
never breaks through, even at the end, when there is a small gleam
of hope in one of the women's futures.
</P>
<P>
   Winterbottom doesn't rest on making social observations. Rather,
he moves in with this family and catches its members in the moments
of existential dread when they collectively seem to have no place
to go. Even the wiser and more calloused Debbie, who has found a
way to detach herself from the chill of her life, has a harrowing
moment or two.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is flush with color and sometimes jerks into
accelerated motion, leaving viewers with whiplash while it briefly
tracks one of the characters. Michael Nyman's score is like a
tonier version of the music Stewart Copeland composed for
``Rumblefish''; the rhythms are like a clock ticking, bringing to
mind lost lives and wasted time.
</P>
<P>
   McKee, who played Hugh Grant's wise, wheelchair-bound friend in
``Notting Hill,'' doesn't fall back on her dimples and charm. Done
up in the accouterments of a techno-music lover, she is shy, with a
backpack and her hair in girlish twists, but all her style is on
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   You could come to the same conclusion about ``Wonderland,''
which flits from one life to the next. Essentially an anthology
movie, it needs the actors to bring it to life _ ``Coronation
Street'' with a hand-held camera.
</P>
<P>
   McKee and David Fahm are intriguing performers who do much with
what they have. Fahm's Franklin, an oversensitive guy who has
turned his bedroom into a bunker and listens to music that Nadia
might be a fan of, seems to have music videos of a much more
glamorous life playing in his head.
</P>
<P>
   Some sections are gripping. Yet as well done as it is,
``Wonderland'' feels predictable. There is no sad turn in these
characters' lives that you cannot see coming about an hour before.
It's an odd fix for the man who directed the ace British television
mystery series ``Cracker'' to find himself in. Relying on a more
realistic setting than he used in his films ``Welcome to Sarajevo''
and ``Jude'' doesn't alleviate the movie's grim inevitability.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WONDERLAND'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Winterbottom; written by Laurence Coriat;
director of photography, Sean Bobbitt; edited by Trevor Waite;
music by Michael Nyman; production designer, Mark Tildesley;
produced by Michele Camarda and Andrew Eaton; released by USA
Films.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Kika Markham (Eileen), Jack Shepherd (Bill), Enzo Cilenti
(Darren), Shirley Henderson (Debbie), Ian Hart (Dan), Peter
Marfleet (Jack), Gina McKee (Nadia), Stuart Townsend (Tim), Molly
Parker (Molly), John Simm (Eddie) and David Fahm (Franklin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 108 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It includes profanity, drinking, sexual
situations and a childbirth scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
