<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-GLWNT-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNING SAYS TALKS BREAK DOWN WITH NORTEL ON MERGER OF OPTICAL
UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service) (Eds: Stock
figures are not up to the minute.) 
 By STEVEN VAMES   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corning(GLW:NYSE) confirmed Thursday that talks have broken down
with Nortel Networks(NT:NYSE) over a potential merger between the
companies' optical components businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Corning, the world's largest maker of optical fiber and cable,
had been rumored to be in talks with Nortel earlier this week.
Corning's announcement Thursday confirmed the rumors, but said the
talks had been terminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have and will continue to have a close working relationship
with Nortel. We are committed to working together to create
value-added solutions for our customers,'' said Roger G. Ackerman,
chairman and chief executive at Corning, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, New York-based Corning added that it expects sales
in some of its optical technologies to grow 100 percent this year
and that it has been investing heavily in expansions to meet
growing demand.
</P>
<P>
   The talks with Nortel had centered around a stock swap that
would give Ontario-based Nortel more than 50 percent of Corning,
with Corning maintaining its independence and owning the optical
parts unit.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would have been the second major deal in the
fiber-optic arena. Recently, competitor JDS Uniphase(JDSU:Nasdaq),
the world's largest maker of fiber optics components, agreed to buy
SDL(SDLI:Nasdaq) in a deal valued at the time at close to $41
billion. Corning had reportedly lost out in the bidding for SDL.
</P>
<P>
   Corning traded up 9 1/8, or 3.5 percent, to 267 1/4 in late
morning trading. Meanwhile, Nortel is down 4 5/8, or 5.5 percent,
at 79 5/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ENERGY-PSUNTX-STREET &LR;      07-27 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-PSUNTX-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXACO, SUNOCO AND PHILLIPS PETROLEUM MORE THAN DOUBLE EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service.) (Eds:
Stock figures are not up to the minute.) 
 By JENNIFER BARRETT   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surging oil and natural gas prices and consistently strong
consumer demand helped boost second-quarter earnings at three of
the country's major oil companies, with Texaco (TX:NYSE) more than
doubling its quarterly income.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco, the second-largest U.S. oil company, reported income
before special items of $641 million, or $1.17 a share, up from
$286 million, or 52 cents, in the same period a year ago. Despite
the sharp increase, however, Texaco's earnings per-share fell a
penny short of the consensus estimate among analysts surveyed by
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco's net income, including special charges, was $625 million
in the second quarter, or $1.14 per share. Revenue at the White
Plains, NY-based company rose to $12.1 billion from $8.3 billion in
the same year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Thursday's trading session, shares of Texaco moved up
2.7 percent, to 49 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Sunoco (SUN:NYSE), the third-largest independent oil refiner and
marketer, easily beat Wall Street estimates, reporting
second-quarter earnings of $132 million or $1.50 per share,
excluding special items. The figures are significantly higher than
the $10 million, or 11 cents per share, earned in the same period a
year ago. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had
forecast earnings per share of $1.37.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue at the Philadelphia-based oil company grew to $3.6
billion from $2.4 billion in the same period a year ago. Sunoco's
stock was trading up 1/2, or 2.1 percent, to 24 7/8 Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Petroleum (P:NYSE) also surpassed analysts' estimates,
with second-quarter net income of $442 million, or $1.73 per
diluted share. That's 17 cents higher than the consensus estimate
among Wall Street analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial. The Bartlesville, Okla.-based company earned $68
million, or 27 cents per share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Total second-quarter revenue at Phillips Petroleum were $5.4
billion, up sharply from $3.2 billion a year ago. Phillips is one
of the country's largest integrated oil companies, with oil and
natural gas exploration, production, refining, and marketing
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, shares of Phillips were trading up 1 5/16, or
2.8 percent, to 48 11/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
