a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     07-27 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK TWICE BEFORE WASHING THOSE HANDS
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This just in from the Department of Contradictory Health News:
Americans, who are doing less housework than ever before, are
putting themselves at risk by being obsessively clean.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Tufts University geneticist said American's
excessive use of anti-bacterial cleaning products has the potential
to weaken our immune systems and make us susceptible to infections
and diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, USA Today reported that the average time
married couples spend doing housework has dropped from 36 hours a
week in 1965 to 29 hours a week now.
</P>
<P>
   I think I can explain.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Levy, the geneticist, is operating under the mistaken
assumption that the people who buy these anti-bacterial soaps and
cleaning products are actually using them.
</P>
<P>
   My 14-year-old son, for example, has had the same bottle of
anti-bacterial hand soap in his bathroom for the past five years.
Like most Americans, I think he believes that germs will be
frightened away by the mere presence of the soap dispenser. To
actually apply the soap to his hands would be overkill.
</P>
<P>
   If Stuart Levy wants to do some truly useful research, he should
determine whether germs can read. When they see the word
``anti-bacterial'' on the side of an unused bottle of liquid soap,
do they scuttle away in fear or do they roll around on the counter
of the sink, slapping their little microscopic bacterial sides and
laughing till they get the hiccups?
</P>
<P>
   A quick visual examination of my son's bathroom suggests the
latter, but I could be wrong. It is possible, I suppose, that the
fossilized chunks of Crest adhering to the basin of the sink and
the black fuzzy stuff in his shower are not filth, but rather wads
of dead bacteria, brought down by invisible cleansing rays
emanating from an unopened 5-year-old bottle of soap.
</P>
<P>
   If Levy is right _ and I sincerely hope that he is _ then the
fact that we are doing less housework than ever before is both
understandable and justifiable. Indeed, it may be necessary for us
to stop doing housework altogether or, if our homes are overstocked
with anti-bacterial soaps and cleansers, actually pay someone to
haul in more dirt.
</P>
<P>
   This would not appear to be good news for maids and professional
house cleaners, but I'm betting they could adjust. Instead of
hauling around all those buckets and mops and vacuum cleaners,
they'd simply roll in a wheelbarrow-full of dirt and spread it
around the rooms. They would have to leave the house quickly, of
course, before they are blinded by all the anti-bacterial soap rays
beaming around the house, but then again maybe a good pair of
reflective sunglasses would offer adequate protection. (Another
possible research project for Stuart Levy and his cronies at
Tufts.)
</P>
<P>
   My suggestions seem to dovetail nicely with Levy's contention
that children who wallow around in the dirt have stronger immune
systems than those who don't. Perhaps all the diseases that kids
pick up at day-care centers could be avoided if caretakers would
simply wave a bottle of anti-bacterial soap over the swing set and
sandbox. (You parents of young children may want to continue
keeping a spare bottle of ear-infection antibiotics in the
refrigerator, just in case I'm wrong about this.)
</P>
<P>
   I am supposed to clean the garage today, but I'm thinking I may
put it off. I understand that Mr. Clean has come out with some
anti-bacterial towelettes.
</P>
<P>
   If I fling a few around on the floor, the place will be as
sterile as an operating room.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
