<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: GROUPING ART BY DATE; GETTING THE HOLZER MESSAGE IN
PHILADELPHIA; FILLING A CURATORIAL HOLE IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Britain)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christie's is once again grappling with the way it
packages the art it sells, reorganizing its important fall evening
sales in New York and London. Each time, executives say, the change
is to ``reflect current collecting patterns,'' meaning Christie's
is trying to match the art with the right buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In November Christie's plans to hold three evening sales in New
York: Impressionist and modern paintings, drawings and sculptures;
postwar art, with classic contemporary masters dating from 1945 to
1970; and contemporary art, made from 1970 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally both Christie's and Sotheby's had two categories
for their big sales: Impressionist and modern art in one auction,
contemporary art in another. Works made before the 1860s went into
19th-century day sales. Impressionist paintings, drawings and
sculptures, though executed in the late 19th century, were grouped
with 20th-century art made before 1945. Auctions of contemporary
art consisted of works dating from 1945 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago Christie's made what was then considered a
radical change by putting works by 19th-century artists like
Delacroix and Ingres in the same sales as masters like van Gogh and
Monet in an auction labeled ``Impressionist and 19th-century art.''
</P>
<P>
   But the early 19th-century art tended to bog down the sales and
failed to bring the high prices experts had hoped for by placing
those works alongside the big-ticket Impressionist paintings. Last
year, Christie's quietly renamed its Impressionist and 19th-century
sale ``Impressionist and post-Impressionist art'' and auctioned the
early 19th-century art in day sales.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the auction house also lumped artists like Picasso and
Matisse with modern figures like Jackson Pollock and Robert
Rauschenberg in sales of 20th-century art. Art dating from the
1970s to the present went into a separate evening sale of
contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   At the time everyone waited to see if Sotheby's would follow
suit. It didn't. After several weeks of internal discussions,
executives there announced that the company would stick to the old
categories: Impressionist and modern art, and contemporary art,
which it continued to define as work dating from 1945 to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's is also changing the dates of its important London
sales. Instead of December, they will now take place at the end of
January and the beginning of February. The reason, Christie's
experts said, is that December is too close to the New York sales
in November; buyers won't have time to pay for their New York
purchases before they are bombarded with more works in London. But
in London there will be only two evening sales: Impressionist,
modern and postwar art in one sale on Jan. 31 and contemporary art
the following evening.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has also held its important London sales in December.
Executives there said Thursday that they had not yet decided if
they would follow Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we're going back, but rather that we're
tailoring our sales to different markets: London and New York,''
said Franck Giraud, head of 19th- and 20th-century art for
Christie's worldwide. ``We've re-evaluated the 19th- and
20th-century picture market and examined some areas that were
successful and others that were not.
</P>
<P>
   ``But still, we have to be flexible,'' Giraud added. ``Top-end
works by artists like Corot or Courbet will be included in our
Impressionist evening sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's will continue selling works dating from 1970 to the
present in their own sale. ``We created a market that didn't exist
at auction before,'' Giraud said. By offering works that used to be
sold almost exclusively at galleries, Christie's was making works
by younger artists with long waiting lists _ names like Jeff Koons
or Andreas Gursky or Damien Hirst _ more accessible to a wider
public. Often, contemporary-art dealers give new works by these
artists only to their best customers or to museums. But as soon as
they hit the auction market, prices soared, often far exceeding
those charged in galleries.
</P>
<P>
   HOLZER MESSAGES
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of charisma can be fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Use what is dominant in culture to change it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   These are two of the messages being flashed on a giant
electronic billboard at the construction site of the Kimmel Center
for the Performing Arts at Broad and Spruce Streets in Philadelphia
near the First Union Center, where the Republican National
Convention is to be held next week.
</P>
<P>
   Not the typical political messages, they are a site-specific
artwork created by Jenny Holzer, the American artist known for her
signature ``Truisms'' that have been shown everywhere from the
Guggenheim Museum in New York to the Reichstag in Berlin and the
Pompidou Center in Paris. When officials from the Kimmel Center
approached Holzer, she agreed to create the installation for no
fee. The center has only paid her expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important statement about the importance of art in our
society that is appropriate to this city and to this time,'' said
Stephanie W. Naidoff, president of the center.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimmel Center, a $225 million public-private project, is to
open on Dec. 14, 2001. The 130,000-square-foot complex, which
includes a 2,500-seat concert hall for the Philadelphia Orchestra
and a 650-seat recital theater, has been designed by the Manhattan
architect Rafael Vinoly. Holzer's work, which went up Thursday
night, will run continuously through Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   A COAST CURATOR
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art has had a gaping hole in
its curatorial staff since its chief curator, Gary Garrels,
resigned in December to become the chief curator of drawings and a
curator of painting and sculpture at the Museum of Modern Art in
New York. This week the San Francisco museum announced that
Madeleine Grynsztejn, the curator of contemporary art at the
Carnegie Museum of Art in Pittsburgh since 1997, has joined it as
senior curator of painting and sculpture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
