<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-TVADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV AD MAKERS CITE TEAMSTERS PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN AND SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the same time that it has flexed its muscle to
maintain its grip on the filmmaking industry in New England,
Teamsters Local 25 has used similarly aggressive tactics to secure
jobs for its members with makers of television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the film industry, companies involved in making TV
commercials in most states, including Massachusetts, are not under
contract with the Teamsters to hire their members as drivers.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives of several production studios, however,
the Teamsters have regularly tried to disrupt television commercial
shoots because the studios refused to hire Teamsters for
transportation jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes like a hit-and-run situation,'' said one executive,
who asked not to be identified. ``They hear we're shooting at a
certain location and converge on us. Thankfully, commercials take a
lot less time to make than films so we can work around the
problem.'' In one instance in 1993 a member of a Boston production
team, hired by the state Department of Public Health to shoot an
antismoking commercial in Quincy, just outside Boston, got into a
fight with a group of Teamsters after he resisted their attempts to
shut down the set.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for local Teamster chief George Cashman said Cashman
has instituted reforms at the union to attract movies to the
region, but federal investigators are looking into whether
filmmakers were forced to hire a local trailer-rental firm
controlled by union member James Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a federal grand jury in Boston subpoenaed contracts
between Local 25 and the producers of several major Hollywood films
shot in Massachusetts and the three northern New England states.
Agents from the US Department of Labor's Division of Labor and
Racketeering seized records from Flynn's Weymouth home.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci said he would speak with Cashman, Local
25 president, whom Cellucci recently reappointed to another term on
the Massachusetts Port Authority's board of directors, about the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci acknowledged that he has been asked in the past by
Hollywood studios to intervene with Cashman when they were having
problems with the local union.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that when I have been involved, when I call the
Teamsters at the request of the Hollywood studios, they have always
been very responsive,'' Cellucci said. ``So I was very surprised to
see these (newspaper) reports.'' Cashman, who defended the
Teamsters' negotiating tactics with the film industry on Monday,
has not returned phone calls in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   However, Boston lawyer John Pappalardo, who is representing the
Teamster president, denied that Cashman was either a target or
subject of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, he said, had implemented many reforms, including
``policies designed to attract the movie industry to
Massachusetts,'' since taking over as president of Local 25 nine
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``His efforts in this regard have been repeatedly praised by
industry officials,'' Pappalardo said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Weisman, who is now directing the $53 million MGM movie
``What's the Worst That Could Happen?'', around Massachusetts,
praised the work of the Teamsters. Weisman said there are at least
35 Teamsters a day on the set being supervised by Flynn and William
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   He also defended Flynn as a professional who has kept things
running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he go by the book? Yes,'' Weisman said. ``Is he
unreasonable? No.'' However, several film industry executives
interviewed by the Globe said that Local 25 is so difficult in
negotiations on such issues as the number of drivers assigned to a
set, overtime, and fringe benefits that they have decided to shoot
their movies elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some independent film makers said they felt intimidated by local
Teamsters while negotiating contracts or trying to resolve
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Local 25 has employed its share of tough guys on film crews over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn himself was acquitted in the 1982 gangland slaying of
Brian Halloran, a Winter Hill gang member who was gunned down on
Boston's waterfront after cooperating with the FBI against James
``Whitey'' Bulger. Patrick McGonagle, a Teamster who worked on the
set of ``The Good Son'' when it was filmed in Massachusetts in
1993, was later convicted of a series of armored car robberies --
including a 1984 heist in Hudson, N.H., in which two guards died.
</P>
<P>
   McGonagle, of Charlestown, is serving 30 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
