<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAYREUTH-MUSIC-GERMAN     07-27 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYREUTH-MUSIC-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: THE CITADEL WAGNER BUILT, UNDER SIEGE INSIDE AND
OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYREUTH, Germany _ Richard Wagner had in mind that all things
low and vulgar would be left behind at the bottom of the green hill
on which he built his opera house. Listeners and artists alike
would make the short climb between rows of sheltering trees and
find in the theater he dedicated to himself refreshment and
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   After 124 years, the trees have grown and the myth of the
Bayreuth Festival with them. The annual summer event is with us
again. ``Parsifal'' was played on Tuesday night, raising its hand
in a kind of preliminary blessing toward the work to come. The
first performances of a newly produced ``Ring des Niebelungen''
with ``Das Rheingold'' runs through the week. The staging is by
Juergen Flimm; Giuseppe Sinopoli conducts.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner might be alarmed to find how near to his citadel of
purity the coarseness of the world has encroached. The high street
leading to his house, Wahnfried, is a merchandiser's gantlet of
cheap-looking clothes, fast food and expensive watches.
</P>
<P>
   Vulgarity has even made its way up the hill. The opening night
audience, with only a smattering of foreigners, preened itself with
displays of elegance and material good fortune. Inside Wagner's
plain but dignified Festspielhaus were intermittent hacks, coughs
and unidentified bumps and bangs, intruding on this temple of
silence. It took the final scene of ``Parsifal,'' a moment of
extraordinary and reverential beauty, to put a less-than-perfect
world in its place. Wolfgang Wagner's 11-year-old production was
not helpful. It is a homely, slightly awkward affair to begin with
and has not aged gracefully. Movable pillars shaped in jumbles of
solid geometry reverse themselves to form interior walls. Klingsor
(Hartmut Welker) comes and goes on a kind of slow-moving elevator.
Costumes are modest to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's collection of singers was mixed in quality, but then
what international Wagner cast is not? Bayreuth at least has a
radiant Kundry, Lithuania's Violeta Urmana, and in Andreas Schmidt
an earnest and devoted Armfortas. Matthias Holle sang Gurnemanz
with touching dignity, although his appearance in the part came as
a late-hour surprise. Hans Sotin, with 29 seasons at Bayreuth
behind him, withdrew (or was asked to withdraw, depending on whom
you ask) because of ``unbridgeable differences'' with the
conductor, Christoph Eschenbach.
</P>
<P>
   As Parsifal, Poul Elming has a clear heldentenor voice of
unusual health. He is a tall, youthful presence onstage and works
hard at his part, so it is a shame he is not a more compelling
musical personality. Titurel, Holle's original role, was taken by
Alfred Reiter
</P>
<P>
   Top billing in the end belonged to the Festspielhaus itself.
``Parsifal'' is the only opera Wagner wrote with the sound of its
unusual acoustics already in his ears. Contrary to later Wagnerian
trends, the great man's priorities tilted toward words and acting.
The house's wood surfaces disperse voices with unusual clarity. The
covered orchestra pit subdues the big ensemble to such an extent
that the first rising trumpet figure, a dominant voice in most
opera houses, blends sedately into the rolling string figures. Such
a space tends to flatter even a mediocre orchestra, although this
one was better than that. Bayreuth's splendid chorus, crucial to
any ``Parsifal,'' needed no flattery at all.
</P>
<P>
   Eschenbach took the prelude so slowly that the line between the
stately and the moribund was sometimes confused. Klingsor's scene,
on the other hand, went at a furious speed. The final act was
deeply moving, rising to the level of religious piety and ancient
barbarism to which Wagner's crypto-Christian world of holy relics
and holy bloodshed aspires.
</P>
<P>
   The composer, who wrote a lot of heavenly music, found time in
his leisure hours to produce a family from hell, and today his
descendants squabble and intrigue as they always have about the
festival's future. Arguments for and against tradition are
slippery. Wolfgang, Wagner's 80-year-old grandson, has the upper
hand now, but family agitators for new ideas and artistic
renovation are closing in.
</P>
<P>
   The Festspielhaus reeks of atmosphere and history, and its
rituals (no applause after Act I of ``Parsifal''; doors opened,
shut and locked by a rigid observance of the clock) are followed as
by a congregation in church. Yet the staging is traditional in the
questionable sense of the word. Its self-conscious gesturing and
choreography address a set of audience expectations long since
superseded.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative and conservation are words with the same root, and
who knows, maybe the workmanlike simplicity of Tuesday's
``Parsifal'' would have appealed to its composer. He would have
been less pleased, I think, with those sitting in the theater,
whose aura of vanity and public display was precisely what the
Bayreuth Festival was intended to do away with.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the rich, the powerful and the politically connected
need as much enlightenment as anybody else, maybe more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
