<SLUG> BC-TV-GEENADAVIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR-WINNING ACTRESS GOES TO THE SMALL SCREEN THIS FALL IN ABC
SITCOM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Each year, TV executives greenlight a
plethora of improbable concepts that they hope will captivate
audiences and seduce potential advertisers. Sometimes they succeed.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of Geena Davis' new self-titled ABC sitcom is both
improbable and immoral. Her character, a glamorous New York career
woman named Teddie Cochran, falls in love at first sight, gets
engaged at first bite and is next seen packing up the SUV and
heading to the burbs to live in premarital bliss with her fiance
Max (Peter Horton) and his two kids (John Francis Daley and
Makenzie Vega).
</P>
<P>
   The chance of something like this happening to a hip millennium
diva in a city where women outnumber men is about as likely as
Rosie O'Donnell, or anyone else in America for that matter, passing
up a hot Krispy Kreme doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you love TV? You can just do anything and get away with
it!
</P>
<P>
   According to Davis, however, there's a method to this madness.
``It's meant to be clear that this is a once-in-a-lifetime thing
for both of us,'' Davis, who is also one of five executive
producers, told a group of TV critics last week. ``My character's
never had this kind of thing happen. It just hit us both over the
head and something we impulsively decided to go with. I think
that's part of what we're going to take advantage of _ that we
don't really know each other that well.''
</P>
<P>
   For the folks in the Bible Belt who might be a bit miffed that
Teddie and Max are shacking up with his kids, hold off on the
e-mail and letter-writing campaigns for a minute. The producers
plan to have Teddie and Max tie the knot real soon.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking February sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two people who have made a very serious commitment
to one another, and there are children involved,'' says executive
producer Nina Wass. ``And they are engaged, so we are definitely
going to get them married in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about (having them live together) a lot and what we
thought would be interesting is, it is a contemporary family and
these people are very responsible. We thought it would be sort of
fun to explore, because we hadn't seen it explored before.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality and the lack thereof, however, is not the problem with
``The Geena Davis Show.'' The problem is that Davis, who has an
Academy Award sitting on her mantel, deserves something better. The
writing in the pilot episode is uneven, uninspired and derivative.
At one point, we see Davis and her three single girlfriends (Mimi
Rogers, Cindy Lu and Wendy McKenna) sitting in a bar drinking
cosmopolitans and exhaling over Teddie's domestic dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   Remind you of another show featuring four single women?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it just so happens that the show's creator, Terri Minsky,
also used to write for HBO's ``Sex and the City.'' However, when
Minsky discovered that she was repeating herself, she quickly
changed the dynamic of Teddie's inner circle by replacing McKenna
and Lu with actress Kim Coles of ``Living Single.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the substitution of Coles might not be a fix-all, Davis
says she's not really concerned about the negative buzz from
critics who panned the pilot episode. Why should she worry? If
``The Geena Davis Show'' tanks, it's not like Davis will have to
trade in her Prada pumps for a pair of
Payless kicks. She'll have several other options to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   A. She is an established movie star.
</P>
<P>
   B. She can always shop the show to cable.
</P>
<P>
   C. She's also pretty darn handy with her bow and arrows. Davis'
competitive archery career is no joke. At the 1996 Olympic trials,
she finished 24th out of 300 and is currently ranked 10th in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who conceded that she doesn't get stage fright, didn't
appear nervous when she met the press at the Ritz-Carlton last
week. Dressed in a clingy black dress with 3-inch black sandals
that she removed during the ABC outdoor soiree later that evening,
she said she wouldn't take it personally if the show bombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't control everything,'' Davis, 41, said emphatically.
``If I controlled all the aspects of the universe I would take it
to heart, but since I can only control my limited contribution . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   You ought to be applauded for sticking your long neck out there.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy launching a show when you're fully aware that more
than 80 percent of all new fall series fail within the first 13
weeks. And it must be rather disconcerting when some people assume
that the only reason an A-List actor would condescend to do
television is because his or her career is in the
toilet.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not really the case with Davis, a Massachusetts-born
actress who made her film debut in ``Tootsie,'' won the 1989 Best
Supporting Actress Oscar for ``The Accidental Tourist'' and has
appeared in 14 other memorable films, including ``Thelma &AMP;
Louise,'' ``A League of Their Own,'' ``Speechless,'' and most
recently, ``Stuart Little.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've certainly never been a snob about mediums,'' said Davis,
who previously starred in two other sitcoms, ``Buffalo Bill'' and
``Sara.'' ``It wasn't a conscious plan to pursue television at this
moment. It purely was this material. I saw this pilot and fell in
love with the writing and the concept. It was really about the
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrice-married and divorced actress also added that she
could identify with Teddie. ``Actors bring parts of themselves to
everything they do. A fun part of acting is exploring different
facets of your personality. I can certainly relate to her
enthusiasm and optimism and drive. I sort of look at the world that
way, too. There's nothing I can't do if I don't really apply
myself. The funny thing about Teddie is that that doesn't always
work _ especially in this new role as a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   What has worked for Davis throughout her career is her
versatility. She's as adept at drama as she is at comedy. Her
dramatic performance in ``The Fly'' with ex-husband Jeff Goldblum
was impressive. Conversely, her natural comedic timing was apparent
in ``Beetlejuice.'' And from a purely physical standpoint, Davis, a
former model, is pretty enough to play the ingenue as she did in
``Angie,'' tough enough to play an action star as she did in
ex-husband Renny Harlin's ``The Long Kiss Goodnight'' and subtle
enough to play a girl-next-door type as she did in ``A League of
Their Own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, from the beginning I was offered many different
types of parts,'' said Davis, whose next feature film will be
``Stuart Little II.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been pretty fussy about what I choose to do, which
is sometimes why I take a year or two off between film roles. I've
always wanted to play a variety of things. I've been so lucky that
I've been in so many different genres in my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not anything I can put my finger on, but when I read
something and start to picture myself in it, saying, `I want to say
that, I want to do that,
I want to be that person,' then I know it's probably be something
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her good instincts will help her overcome what now
appears to be an improbable dream.
</P>
<P>
   (Miki Turner is entertainment critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
