</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JANEKACZMAREK-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KACZMAREK'S PORTRAYAL OF MOM IN `MALCOLM' REDEFINES ROLE OF TV MOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKI TURNER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When Jane Kaczmarek _ who plays Lois, the
unconventional mother on Fox's irreverent family sitcom ``Malcolm
in the Middle'' _ bared her breasts and shaved off her nude
husband's body hair in the kitchen during the series' premiere
episode last January, she not only altered our perceptions of the
perfect television family (you know the kind, where problems are
always solved in 22 minutes or less), but redefined the role of the
sainted television mom as well.
</P>
<P>
   The very second Lois screamed, ``Chop-chop'' at her kids, June
Cleaver died. Claire Huxtable left the room. Carol Brady covered
her eyes and ears, and Donna Reed called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Their saccharine images have been mercifully destroyed by a
mother who does things outside of the kitchen _ such as taking a
bath, making love to her husband and plotting revenge against pesky
neighbors. Lois also has that uncanny God-given ability to see all
and hear all while creating one of her infamous mystery-meat
casseroles. These are the things real moms _ those wonderfully
flawed, funny and multidimensional people who rub our tummies when
we're sick and warm our bottoms when we're bad _ do.
</P>
<P>
   This is why we love Lois. She's one bad mama.
</P>
<P>
   This also is why ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' which stars the
brilliantly talented Frankie Muniz as Malcolm, a regular kid with a
high IQ _ along with Bryan Cranston as the sometimes clueless
father; and Christopher Kennedy Masterson, Justin Berfield and Erik
Per Sullivan as Malcolm's precocious brothers _ was the breakout
comedy hit of last season. Last week the show received five Emmy
nominations, including best actress in a comedy series for
Kaczmarek, who recently was honored by the Television Critics
Association for best individual performance in a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarek's glee over her first Emmy nomination, however, was
bittersweet because her husband, actor Bradley Whitford, who stars
on ``The West Wing'' _ the other most-talked-about show of last
season _ didn't get a nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very disappointing because my husband wasn't
nominated,'' Kaczmarek, 44, told a group of television critics,
with her voice cracking. ``I was much more upset than he. He's a
gracious, big-hearted guy. He was very happy for me. But if you
watch `The West Wing,' my husband is the quarterback of that show.
He worked so hard and he loves it so much. He's just spectacular
and it was really disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarek and Whitford met on a blind date arranged by
Kaczmarek's roommate at Yale Drama School, Kate Burton (daughter of
Richard Burton) in 1992. Two years later they married, and in 1998
Kaczmarek gave birth to the couple's first child, Frances, who is
now 2 1/2. Their son, George, is 7 months old.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Kaczmarek _ whose television credits include
co-starring roles on ``Equal Justice,'' ``Big Wave Dave's,''
``Hometown'' and ``Paper Chase: The Second Year'' and recurring
roles on ``Felicity,'' ``Party of Five,'' ``Frasier,'' ``The
Practice,'' ``Cybill'' and ``Hill Street Blues'' _ nearly missed
out on the role that has made her one of America's most popular TV
moms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd taken a year off and had been studying classical music at
UCLA and found that there was this wonderful life out there that
had nothing to do with acting,'' the veteran stage and screen
actress said. ``And when the phone rang you didn't wonder if it was
an agent. Then I got pregnant. I had a glorious year not working
and had my daughter (Frances) and thought `do I really want to go
back into this?' It was pretty great. Brad was working all the
time, I continued taking the music classes and was doing a little
bit on `Felicity' (playing Julie's long-lost mother). That was all
I did and that was terrific. I love that show.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   When the Whitfords decided to have a second child, Kaczmarek
instructed her agents not to send her on any auditions. But at the
end of pilot season, Mary Fox, the casting director for ``Malcolm
in the Middle,'' persuaded Kaczmarek's agents to send the actress a
script about an unusual family seen through the eyes of a young
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still didn't want to do it, but then you think, `Wow, they
really love me,''' Kaczmarek said. ``Maybe I should read this. I
did and found that there was something undeniably quirky and
endearing about Lois.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Kaczmarek, she didn't have to avoid the
inevitable comparisons to other television moms. Lois was and is an
original.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TV mom I identify most with is Donna Reed, because I grew
up in that era. What I really like about Lois is that she has
depth. Mothers on television tend to not grow. They tend to be kind
of wise, nodding, influencing kind of funny ma'ams. Lois isn't
that. She yells and is kind of the mouthpiece for the family. She's
just kind of normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarek's perception of her character is why she takes
exception to the ``D'' word that's often used to describe the hit
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Dysfunctional?''' This is one of the most highly
functioning families,'' says the Milwaukee native, who is the
oldest of four kids born to Edward and Evelyn Kaczmarek. ``They
have dinner together every night, which I think is impressive in
this day and age. And they don't get away with anything. They try,
and I think that's why their mischief is as clever as it is. I
think the parents are aware of everything. And I think there's
great love expressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they have one bathroom is a testimony to huge
function. Do you know how organized you have to be to have one
bathroom? I grew up in a house with one bathroom and boy, you have
to work together as a family and forgive, forgive, forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Kaczmarek has been finding that the lines between Lois
and Jane are becoming increasingly blurred. For example, the phrase
``Chop-chop'' that Lois uses to whip her boys into shape on the
show has become part of Jane's parental vernacular as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if life is imitating art or the other way around,''
Kaczmarek says with a laugh. ``My children are becoming a little
more mobile. And I guess I've never been fond of people who dawdle.
I'm very fond of the phrase `Chop-chop.' It's kind of, `Let's go,
let's go now and let's do it the way I want you to do it.' So I
don't know if I'm learning some good techniques for playing Lois
that I'm going to incorporate into my technique as Jane the mom,
but Lois is pretty good at keeping things going. And so far,
`Chop-chop' has worked very well around the house, too.''
</P>
<P>
   And like most TV mothers, she has to pull rank sometimes
on-screen and off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I have a family at home that I really want to go home
to, when (her TV kids) sometime goof around too much or come in
unprepared _ which they really don't do, they're just having fun _
I'm usually the one who kind of tells everyone to knock it off,
concentrate and let's go,'' Kaczmarek said. ``I try not to be too
harsh, but it kind of does the trick. It got them more focused and
I got to go home a little earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Muniz says he doesn't mind Kaczmarek's gentle nudging at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not me, anyway, she gets after,'' Muniz says with a
devilish grin. ``No, Jane is great. She's really like all of our
moms. She keeps us in line when she has to, but she's always there
for us, too. She's really smart and funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Kaczmarek can apply some of that wisdom and good
humor to potty training Frances. The actress said that she spent
the better part of her hiatus trying to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to trust that they are finally going to do it on
their own time,'' Kaczmarek said. ``It's hard to accept that you
are not more clever than they are. I thought, `I'm a 44-year-old
woman with a master's degree from Yale and I can outsmart this kid,
but you can't. It was a very humbling experience. I remember the
first time she took my hand and said she didn't want to wear
diapers anymore. She wanted to go `potty.' We went into the
bathroom and you hear that little (makes tinkling noises) and I
thought I'd just won a prize. I was so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Frances has learned to chop-chop, too.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
