<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, July 28. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH (Paris) _ Flight recorders show that the pilot
of the Air France Concorde that crashed on Tuesday had problems
with both engines on the plane's left side and reported that he
could not retract his landing gear, investigators said Thursday.
The recorders make clear that the plane was too far down the runway
to abort the flight when the control tower told the pilot that they
could see flames at the back of his plane. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
prepared Thursday to resume talks this weekend following the
failure of the U.S.-mediated summit meeting, with each side looking
for crucial support and staking out bargaining positions. Saeb
Erekat, a top aide to Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, was to meet
Sunday with Israeli negotiator Oded Eran. (Summary from wires.) By
John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (Caracas, Venezuela) _ He promised a
revolution, and he has kept his word. Since being swept into power
here 18 months ago, Hugo Chavez has uprooted every institution,
assaulted every elite group and derided every orthodoxy with the
unrelenting combativeness of the army paratrooper he used to be. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Austin, Texas) _ Even as Dick Cheney was screening
other possible vice presidential choices for Gov. George W. Bush,
his own candidacy was moving along a track so secret that the other
politicians on the list had no idea that Cheney was their most
serious rival. And that unusual development has stirred concern and
befuddlement among some Republicans, who wonder whether the man in
charge of screening other candidates could possibly have received
as thorough a screening himself. By Frank Bruni and Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-VOTE-VOICES (Evanston, Ill.) _ Interviews with voters in
this diverse, middle-class suburb in a swing state show that people
are still skeptical and wary of the presidential candidates. In the
absence of a single urgent issue, voters are sizing up candidates
as managers, stewards and leaders worthy, or not, of respect. By
Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ The House passed legislation
Thursday that would reduce taxes on some Social Security benefits,
giving Republicans another victory in their effort to make tax cuts
a defining election-year issue. Democrats were expected to break
ranks in substantial numbers to support the bill, which White House
officials said President Clinton would veto should it reach his
desk. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ Statistics released by the New York City
Police Department show a marked increase in disciplinary actions
against police officers over the past three years, which the
department says demonstrates increased vigilance in punishing
misconduct. Critics contend that the department has manipulated the
numbers to avoid federal oversight. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-RULING-REACT (Undated) _ What users of Napster are saying
following a judge's order Wednesday that barred Napster from
allowing the exchange of copyrighted music over the Internet. By
Amy Harmon.
</P>
