<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-     07-27 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-5TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLISHING NASHVILLE'S TWANG 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ I wouldn't know a Gibson from a Stratocaster.
My favorite guitarists are Django Reinhardt, Eddie Lang and Andres
Segovia, and none of them, as far as I know, ever played a single
note at the Grand Ole Opry.
</P>
<P>
   That could cast a rather long shadow, I suppose, over my
qualifications as a guide to Music City, U.S.A., except that there
is a lot more than picking and fiddling, a lot more than ballads of
love and loss, in Nashville's past, present and future _ especially
its future. Which is no bad thing for the city, since country
music, which rang up sales of tapes and records of almost $2
billion two years ago, is suffering through a bit of a slump at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Convention and Visitors Bureau here has set aside $4 million
to play down the city's hillbilly image and emphasize its
developing cosmopolitanism. It should not prove too hard a sell;
like Charlotte, N.C.; Jacksonville, Fla.; and a number of other
second-tier Southern cities, this one is rapidly acquiring big-time
accouterments, including a National Football League team called the
Titans. With a brand-new $292 million stadium, a bruiser of a
running back named Eddie George and a formidable defensive end
named Jevon ``the Freak'' Kearse, the Titans went to the Super Bowl
last year and made the city swagger a little.
</P>
<P>
   Already in business or on the way are a zoo, a new Country Music
Hall of Fame, an enormous shopping complex on the scale of the Mall
of America near Minneapolis, a new library designed by Robert A.M.
Stern, an arena to house the Nashville Predators of the National
Hockey League and the ambitious new Frist Center for the Visual
Arts, about which a few more words later.
</P>
<P>
   What interests me most about Nashville, however, is its past,
notably its often neglected role as an agent of political and
intellectual change.
</P>
<P>
   It was from Nashville _ or rather from the Hermitage, his home
just east of town _ that rugged old Andrew Jackson set off for
Washington in 1829, having ousted the aristocratic John Quincy
Adams in the pivotal election of 1828. A frontiersman, a general,
the first president from west of the Alleghenies, the first
self-made man to take up residence in the White House, Jackson
shaped modern American democracy in the image of his own
egalitarianism. He fostered government by the masses instead of the
propertied classes.
</P>
<P>
   The muddy boots of Jackson's followers spoiled the carpets at
the post-inaugural party, and his opponents derided him as ``some
kind of border savage,'' in the words of Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr.
But he proved them wrong, taking a new, more aggressive style of
leadership to Washington and blazing a path for a fresh tramontane
dynasty that included James K. Polk and Abraham Lincoln, a
Kentuckian before he moved to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, in the early 1920s, a group of writers at
Vanderbilt University, just west of downtown Nashville, coalesced
around a journal they called The Fugitive. They railed against both
the industrialization of the South and what they called the
``moonlight and magnolia'' distortion of traditional agrarian
values.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Tate and John Crowe Ransom, two of the most important
modern American critics, were members of the group, but its star
was Robert Penn Warren. His biographer, Joseph Blotner, called him
this country's greatest 20th-century man of letters, which seems
reasonable enough given his achievements as a poet, critic,
novelist, playwright, essayist and biographer. Warren wrote what
for me is the greatest of political novels, ``All the King's Men,''
whose protagonist, Willie Stark, was a ringer for Huey P. Long, and
he was the only person to win Pulitzer Prizes for both poetry and
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years, the Fugitives became the Agrarians, and most
members drifted away from Vanderbilt, but not before they had
helped to ignite the Southern Literary Renaissance. Eventually,
those fevered nights in Nashville helped to mold publications like
The Kenyon Review and The Sewanee Review and writers like Randall
Jarrell, James Dickey and Cleanth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMIC ACHIEVEMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt may well be entering a bright new era. Founded in
1872 and endowed by Cornelius Vanderbilt, it has evolved from
Methodist and regional origins into an institution of national
repute with 10,000 students. Already among the 20 wealthiest
colleges and universities in the nation, it has found a new
champion in Martha R. Ingram, whose family controls Nashville-based
Ingram Industries, one of the nation's dozen largest privately held
companies. Among many other things, Ingram is the largest book
wholesaler in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 Ingram gave Vanderbilt $300 million in Ingram stock _
the second-largest donation ever made to any American university _
and this year she played a leading role in persuading E. Gordon Gee
to come here as chancellor. A former president of Ohio State
University, Gee staggered the educational world by leaving Brown
University, where he had only recently been installed as president,
to move to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the region say Ingram, who was also the prime mover in
establishing the Tennessee Performing Arts Center, has ambitions to
make Vanderbilt into a southern Stanford or Harvard, or at least to
put it on an academic par with Duke and the University of Virginia.
Not so, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Culturally, we were a little deprived, but we've begun to
remedy that,'' Ingram told me. ``Education has always been taken
seriously here. Now it's time to try to take Vanderbilt up a notch
or two, but we don't want it to be a Southern equivalent of
something else. Not at all. We want to be the best we can be on our
own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's early settlers hiked through the Cumberland Gap, a
natural opening in the Appalachian barrier near the point where
Virginia, Tennessee and Kentucky meet. They settled along the
Cumberland River, which cuts through lovely limestone hills in this
region, and quickly established Nashborough, as it was called, as a
staging point to the west. From here, the Natchez Trace, a crude
forest track, linked the interior South to the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   For many generations, Nashville's banks and insurance companies
formed the basis of its prosperity. They gave Union Street a modest
reputation as ``the Wall Street of the South,'' but in recent years
they have been sold to out-of-town interests, along with The
Tennessean, long the city's dominant newspaper, and a number of the
more important radio and television stations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-     07-27 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-2NDAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE: television stations.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Great hunks of once humble, now glittering Music Row now belong
to big foreign conglomerates like Bertelsmann of Germany and Sony
of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nashville used to be a home-owned, home-operated kind of
city,'' said John Egerton, a social historian who has lived here
for 35 years. ``But for a long time, it has had an aspiration to
celebrity, and by this point it is quite clearly a city on the
make. It's a money culture. But that's the New South, I guess. The
new world.''
</P>
<P>
   As the state capital, Nashville remains a cockpit of political
drama. Closely divided between the two parties, Tennessee has
produced prominent Democrats like Cordell Hull, who was Franklin D.
Roosevelt's secretary of state; Sen. Estes Kefauver, the 1956
Democratic vice presidential nominee; and Sen. Albert Gore Sr. It
has produced powerful Republicans like Sen. Howard H. Baker Jr. and
Gov. Lamar Alexander, who both aspired to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   They play the game for keeps here, and they don't forget; in
casual conversation six years after he lost his seat, former Sen.
Jim Sasser bitterly condemned those who had denied him a third term
as ``reactionary know-nothings.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, politics sometimes looks like Nashville's growth
industry. Vice President Al Gore, soon to be the Democratic nominee
for President, is a native son, sort of; born in Washington, he
spent summers in Carthage, one of many nearby towns with names
drawn from antiquity, then graduated from Harvard and studied for a
year at Vanderbilt's divinity school. He moved his headquarters
here when his primary campaign was floundering, and Yankee staff
members have learned more than they wanted to know about biscuits
with cream gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, a Republican, was promoted for a time this
year as a candidate for vice president, and there were even a few
mentions of Tennessee's other senator, William H. Frist.
</P>
<P>
   IMPORTANCE OF HEALTH CARE
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though, Middle Tennessee, the region anchored by
Nashville, has found more reliable ways to make a living. The most
important is health care. Nashville has a string of important
hospitals, and it is the headquarters of HCA, the largest hospital
management company in the country. HCA was founded by Frist's
father, and after many corporate tribulations, Thomas F. Frist Jr.,
the senator's brother, returned as chief executive to turn it
around.
</P>
<P>
   The city's economy benefits as well from a Nissan auto plant at
Smyrna and the Saturn factory at Spring Hill, both south of here.
Bridgestone/Firestone produces tires here, too. And Dell has just
begun shipping computers from a vast new Nashville factory.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1980s, this has been one of the boom towns of
the South, growing more rapidly than any other metropolitan area
between Atlanta and Dallas-Fort Worth. Employment is so full that
stores and airlines have trouble filling jobs. Metropolitan
Nashville's population now exceeds a million, and it has recently
overtaken Memphis as the largest city in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The swells of Nashville live in Belle Meade, a suburb of
enormous houses beneath lofty shade trees on even more enormous
lawns. They don't mix much with the denim-clad country crowd, and
this is more and more their city.
</P>
<P>
   But the two groups have a few things in common. The whole town
assuages its sweet tooth with a locally produced candy called
Goo-Goo Clusters, a highly caloric confection of peanuts,
chocolate, caramel and marshmallow. Ronald Reagan took jelly beans
to the White House; if Al Gore wins the presidency this year, look
for him to stock the Oval Office with Goo-Goo Clusters.
</P>
<P>
   RHINESTONE COWBOYS
</P>
<P>
   As for country music, my wife, Betsey, and I are learning.
</P>
<P>
   We were prepared for the army of musicians and would-be
musicians looking for a break, waiting on tables and strumming
their guitars everywhere _ in rundown bars, on street corners, in
legendary dives like Tootsie's Orchid Lounge and Robert's Western
World. We were ready for the rhinestones, too.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Altman saw to that in ``Nashville,'' his brilliant,
Chaucerian film about the princes and princesses of country music,
with egos the size of cathedrals, as well as the no-hopers. Now the
French photographer Michel Arnaud has brought the picture up to
date in a handsome new book, ``Nashville: Pilgrims of Guitar
Town,'' soon to be published by Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang.
</P>
<P>
   But this is one of those places that you have to see to believe.
</P>
<P>
   You could do a lot worse than start at the Country Music Hall of
Fame, which reminded even a country-music philistine like me how
much good stuff has flowed from Nashville into the American
pop-culture mainstream. A fan of Benny Goodman, Artie Shaw et al.,
I was intrigued to learn more about Bob Wills, who made ``San
Antonio Rose'' popular and more or less invented the wonderfully
rhythmic music called Western Swing. Apparently he never performed
without a 5-cent cigar in his mouth. I had not known that Lester
Flatt and Earl Scruggs played that captivating banjo tune (it's
called ``Foggy Mountain Breakdown'') on the soundtrack of ``Bonnie
and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   And I ask you, for sheer gaudy glory, what could match the
hall's prize possession, Elvis Presley's ``solid gold'' Cadillac, a
perfect totem of American excess?
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers remember the days when Music Row consisted of ratty
houses used as music publishers' headquarters. The Opry played in
the pre-renovation Ryman Auditorium, whose roof sometimes leaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any air-conditioning,'' recalled Tricia Frist,
Thomas Frist's wife, ``so you stuck to the back of the seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Music Row is lined with multistory office buildings, and the
Opry has moved to a riverside site on the edge of town. Today's
Grand Ole Opry House has air-conditioning, a light board and sound
system that would do credit to Las Vegas and more seats than the
Metropolitan Opera House: 4,400, versus 3,800. Nearby stand the
kitschy Opryland Hotel and a sprawling mall called Opry Mills. An
expanded Country Music Hall of Fame is to open in the area in May.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-     07-27 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NASHVILLE: in May.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   Its fans treat the Opry with tremendous seriousness, according
it a place in their hearts alongside stock-car racing and
evangelical Christianity. (One car in the immense parking lot bore
the license plate ``SAVED 67.'') An Opry performance feels a little
like a secular church service. The audience is, in fact, seated in
pews, not individual seats. Everyone listened raptly and
respectfully the Saturday night we were there, munching their
popcorn and slurping Big Drinks, with none of the hubbub of a rock
concert.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from another perspective, this is vaudeville for
hayseeds, with a carefully calibrated blend of corny jokes, spangly
costumes, bottle blondes and a surprising range of music _ not just
country and bluegrass, but also honky-tonk, western, rockabilly,
gospel and quasi-Cajun. A lot of the lyrics may be banal and the
emotional range may be severely limited, but there are big voices
up there onstage, and the songs are sung with unmistakable skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd need a heart of steel not to like this stuff,'' said
Betsey, charmed by Porter Wagoner, the gold-booted MC who joined
the company 43 years ago and helped to advance the career of a
buxom thrush named Dolly Parton.
</P>
<P>
   But we realized what aliens we were in this culture when the
crowd lustily cheered an explicitly sexist, rabidly homophobic,
stunningly anti-government ditty called ``We Want America Back.''
The Supreme Court, one of the song's milder verses suggested, hands
out free condoms while frowning on the distribution of Gideon
Bibles. Rush Limbaugh would have been enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   There are other art forms in Nashville, but sometimes you have
to look around a bit to find them.
</P>
<P>
   You might despair about the city's contemporary architecture if
all you saw was its skyline, dominated by the Bell South building.
From one angle, I thought, it looked like some misbegotten
postmodern Mont St.-Michel; from another, a mooring mast for
dirigibles. As usual, the word on the street was more apt;
Nashville folk call it the Batcave or the Batman Building.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Joseph B. Ledbetter, a Nashville businessman of broad
interests, set me right. The concrete span bridge on the Natchez
Trace Parkway south of town, he said, ``is perhaps the most
beautiful sight in all of Nashville.'' So it is: a broad, lean,
handsome arch across a verdant valley, an architectural engineering
gem as graceful as the soaring Sunshine Skyway in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   `GOOD TO THE LAST DROP'
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for pictures. Nashville's showplace is Cheekwood,
the limestone mansion built in the 1930s by Leslie Cheek, who made
a pile from Maxwell House Coffee (named after the Nashville hotel
where Theodore Roosevelt supposedly proclaimed it ``Good to the
Last Drop''). While we greatly admired the English silver, some of
it by Hester Bateman and Matthew Boulton, we found the paintings
disappointing and the gardens, with the exception of the extensive
boxwood hedges, beaten down by Nashville's unforgiving midsummer
heat.
</P>
<P>
   But at Fisk University, in a far less leafy part of town, we
found an utterly unheralded trove of early American modernism.
Founded by missionaries and freedmen in 1866, only a year after
Appomattox, Fisk may be the oldest historically black institution
of higher education in the country. A statue of W.E.B. DuBois, the
school's most famous alumnus, stands on the campus. After the death
of the pioneering photographer and art dealer Alfred Stieglitz in
1946, his widow, Georgia O'Keeffe, divided his art collection five
ways, giving most of the paintings to big urban museums but sending
101 others to Fisk, where they hang today in a modest little
red-brick building.
</P>
<P>
   A few are by European masters, including Severini and Renoir and
Signac. There is an arrestingly caustic portrait of a dandy in
pince-nez and his companion, swathed in pearls and furs, done by
the German George Grosz while he was living in New York during
World War II. Three or four less well-known artists are included
here, among them Abraham Walkowitz, whose vaguely Cezanne-like work
was represented in the famous Armory Show in Manhattan in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   The treasures of the Fisk collection, to my mind, are the large
groups of works by Marsden Hartley, Arthur G. Dove, Charles Demuth
(especially a precise, curiously touching little watercolor of an
eggplant and some bell peppers) and John Marin. There are more than
a dozen Marins, watercolors and dry-point etchings, ranging from
Venice to Manhattan to the Maine coast.
</P>
<P>
   These same artists are shown to no better advantage in
Washington's Phillips Collection, which owes part of its renown to
them. It is a pity that no corporation or government body has
stepped forward to underwrite improvements to the galleries at Fisk
or to help publish a catalog. Chronically short of cash for
decades, the university desperately needs every cent of help.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITING ART
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one day the Stieglitz collection will be shown at the
$45 million Frist Center, now being carved out of the old Nashville
Post Office, a good-looking New Deal building guarded by stone
eagles outside and decorated with elegant Art Deco aluminum screens
inside. When it opens next year, it will give Nashville 24,000
square feet of gallery space to house major traveling exhibitions
as well as temporary exhibitions of locally owned art.
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, the center will have no collection of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're rather late to the party,'' said Chase W. Rynd, the
center's executive director, who came here from Tacoma, Wash.
``Good art is very expensive these days, so we are concentrating
our resources on the building, on education and on holding the
prices down. Kids 18 and under will pay nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The center is scheduled to open on April 8, with a show from the
Art Gallery of Ontario. Nashville will hit another cultural
milestone this fall when the Nashville Symphony Orchestra, for the
first time in its history, plays in Carnegie Hall on Sept. 25. More
than 1,000 local residents have booked trips to New York to cheer
their musicians in a program featuring the violin virtuoso Nadja
Salerno-Sonnenberg.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
