<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-     07-27 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE: Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will be a triumphal moment for Kenneth Schermerhorn, the
orchestra's music director since 1983. Earlier in a long career, he
conducted both the Milwaukee Symphony and the orchestra of the
American Ballet Theater in New York.
</P>
<P>
   WITH CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Classical music seems somehow appropriate for a city that has so
much classical architecture, notably timeless houses like Belle
Meade Plantation. This is the kind of Southern mansion, in the
words of the critic Roger G. Kennedy, that seems to be ``sleeping
away the centuries, its white columns composing a kind of cage to
keep what lies within from being touched by time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hermitage is another such house, set next to a garden ablaze
with hollyhocks and crape myrtle in high summer. Its most
impressive exterior feature is its portico, with six two-story
columns painted, then sprayed with sand to simulate stone. They are
topped with what were apparently meant to be acanthus leaves, but
no botanist would recognize them as such. Inside, the furniture,
though largely original, is outshone by the textiles and
wallpapers, especially the exceptional scenes of Telemachus on his
travels, made in Paris in 1837, which hang in the foyer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the work of William Strickland, who came to
Nashville from Philadelphia after designing the magnificent Second
Bank of the United States. Here, he produced the Downtown
Presbyterian Church (1851), perhaps the finest Egyptian Revival
building in the nation, a real Thebes on the Cumberland, and the
State Capitol (1859), finished by his son. He is buried there.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the Parthenon _ Nashville's Parthenon, the only
full-size replica in the world, first built of wood and plaster in
1897, and then, 25 years later, when it had started to melt like
ice cream in the sun, replaced with a copy in brownish concrete.
Like the original, it is sometimes covered with scaffolding, but
the little museum inside is open, occupied by a Winslow Homer
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   What to say about this apparition, which John Seigenthaler, the
publisher emeritus of The Tennessean, calls ``a phenomenal
monstrosity?'' Betsey said this: ``The Elgin marbles seem to be in
place, so what's the fuss about?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU GO: BEYOND RED-EYE GRAVY, GIZZARDS AND THAT COUNTRY
SOUND &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By R.W. APPLE Jr. &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of attractions as well as travel information follows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where to Stay &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HERMITAGE SUITE HOTEL, 231 Sixth Ave. North, (615) 244-3121.
Minnesota Fats, the legendary pool hustler, passed his last days
here, and Dinah Shore began her career here with Francis Craig's
orchestra. But the magnificent, richly marbled lobby reeked of
disinfectant when we checked in, and the dated though spacious
guest rooms had dirty windows. Keener management and a less
lackadaisical staff could work wonders at this Beaux-Arts landmark.
Double room rates: $99 to $209.
</P>
<P>
   LOEWS VANDERBILT, 2100 West End Ave., (615) 320-1700. Without
doubt the best address in a city with a chronic dearth of
first-class hotels. A sparkling travertine lobby, a plugged-in
young staff (including car parkers working their way through the
university just across the street) and a convenient location more
than compensate for the somewhat anonymous, run-of-the-mill rooms.
A Ruth's Chris Steak House on the site caters to itinerant
carnivores. Double room rates: midweek, $149 to $269; weekend, $109
to $269.
</P>
<P>
   OPRYLAND HOTEL, 2800 Opryland Dr., (615) 889-1000. This is the
capitol of the Kingdom of Schlock, a maze of 2,883 guest rooms, 15
restaurants, 27 shops, 600,000 square feet of meeting and
exhibition space, three pools and nine acres of interior gardens,
hard by the Grand Ole Opry and its adjacent outlet mall.
``Shoppertainment,'' they call it. Take your hiking boots; Yogi
Berra said he crossed three time zones between the front desk and
his room. Double room rates: room with balcony and terrace that
overlooks nine and a half acres of gardens, $245; traditional room
with view of the hotel exterior, $195.
</P>
<P>
   RENAISSANCE NASHVILLE, 611 Commerce St., (615) 255-8400. Linked
to the city's convention center and arena by covered passageways,
this is Nashville's leading convention hotel. With 673 rooms in a
shiny modern tower, it meets contemporary standards of service and
amenity, but don't look for the personal touch in a place this big.
For country-music enthusiasts, the honky-tonks of Lower Broadway
and the Ryman Auditorium are within easy walking distance. Double
room rates: weekends, $99 to $109; midweek, $149 to $169.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Where to Eat  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOVELESS CAFE, 8400 Highway 100, (615) 646-0067. Local foodies
complain that tourists have taken over, and they insist that the
salty country ham is not quite as authentic as it once was. Maybe
so. But the fried chicken, scratch biscuits, sweet shoepeg corn and
red-eye gravy still have that down-home flavor, and the fabulous
peach and blackberry preserves are still made in big kettles right
on the spot. You eat it all at tables with red-checkered cloths.
</P>
<P>
   ROTIER'S, 2413 Elliston Place, (615) 327-9892. This beloved hole
in the wall near Vanderbilt University has been serving things like
buttermilk and chicken-gizzard dinners since 1945. Evelyn Rotier,
who founded it with her late husband, still comes to work three
days a week. What keeps the place full are a list of 50 beers and
the truly exceptional grilled hamburgers, served on toast.
</P>
<P>
   SASSO, 1400 Woodland St., (615) 226-7942. Corey Griffith, who
cooks in this agreeable little East Nashville hot spot, says he's
shooting for quality ``without glitter or glare.'' He does well by
salmon: salmon cakes remoulade at lunch, a fillet in a Szechuan
peanut crust at dinner. There's wit at work, too; the menu offers
``roasted airline chicken breast'' as well as ``swine-whine''
barbecue. Fish and chips come wrapped in The Tennessean, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
