<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLES-NASHVILLE-ART-5THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHVILLE: Tennessean, naturally.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUNSET GRILL, 2001 Belcourt Ave., (615) 386-3663. A lot of
music-industry executives eat at this glossy, relaxed restaurant,
with a good, mostly modestly priced wine list. Pastas, salads,
stir-fries and grills dominate the menu. You'll probably encounter
the odd bit of weirdness, like swordfish stuffed with Brie,
together with a lot of imagination, like shrimp with a brisk
roasted-cumin salsa and a boffo butterscotch-habanero bread
pudding.
</P>
<P>
   WILD BOAR, 2014 Broadway, (615) 329-1313. The atmosphere is
rather sepulchral, but there is nothing gloomy about the food. Tiny
bouchot mussels in a light curry sauce, perfectly roasted quail and
a fruit extravaganza (peach ice cream served in a tuile, alongside
delectably ripe peaches on a peach bavarois) all showed solid
craftsmanship. Seafood, from scallops to grouper, is bought from
day boats. The wine list astonished us: 15,000 bottles, from $35 to
$5,000, many of them old vintages of a sort rare in this country
(and in France).
</P>
<P>
   ZOLA, 3001 West End Ave., (615) 320-7778. Debra Paquette scores
some successes, like a stacked salad of yellow and red tomatoes,
with herbed goat cheese, avocado and a topknot of mango chutney,
which seemed a definition of good midsummer eating. I also liked
the ice cream flavored with Moroccan spices. But many of the dishes
of Greek, Turkish and Italian inspiration tasted as if every
ingredient in the souk had gone into them. Closed Sundays and at
lunchtime except for special functions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Attractions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BELLE MEADE PLANTATION, 5025 Harding Rd., (615) 356-0501. A
restored historic site. ``Civilians Under Siege: Nashville,
1862-1870,'' an exhibition on view through Sept. 4. Hours: Mondays
through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Admission: $10; $8.50 for the elderly; $4 for children 6 to 12;
under 6 free.
</P>
<P>
   BELL SOUTH BUILDING, nicknamed the Batman Building. Commerce and
Third Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   CHEEKWOOD, Nashville's Home of Art and Gardens, Forrest Park
Drive, (615) 356-8000. Botanical gardens and museums. ``The Forbes
Magazine Collection of Victorian Narrative Paintings,'' through
Aug. 6. Hours: 9:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., Mondays through Saturdays;
11 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., Sundays. Admission: $10; $8 for the elderly;
$5 for ages 6 to 17 and for college students with identification;
free for children under 6.
</P>
<P>
   DOWNTOWN PRESBYTERIAN CHURCH, 154 Fifth Ave., at Church Street,
(615) 254-7584. Sunday service is at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   FISK UNIVERSITY, 1000 17th Ave. North, (615) 329-8500.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND OLE OPRY HOUSE, 2804 Opryland Dr., (615) 889-3060. Call
for tours. Tickets: $8.65; free for children 3 and under. The Grand
Ole Opry itself is still performed as a live radio broadcast on
Fridays at 7:30 p.m. and Saturdays at 6:30 and 9:30 p.m. It
features more than 20 acts, which are announced on the Wednesday of
the preceding week. Tonight's lineup includes Asleep at the Wheel.
Tickets: $22.50; free for children 3 and under.
</P>
<P>
   HERMITAGE, 4580 Rachel's Lane, Hermitage, (615) 889-2941. Guided
tours available. Hours: daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $10; $9
for the elderly; $5 for children 6 to 12; free for children 5 and
under.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC ROW. The entire area of about eight blocks is a short trip
from downtown by car. The 55 Country Music Hall of Fame circulator
trolley stops in front of the Country Music Hall of Fame, 4 Music
Square East; (615) 416-2001. Hours: daily, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Admission: $10.75; $5.75 for children 6 to 11; free for children 5
and under). Metro Transit Authority information: (615) 862-5950.
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE CONVENTION AND VISITORS BUREAU, 211 Commerce St.,
Suite 100, Nashville, Tenn. 37201; (615) 259-4700.
</P>
<P>
   PARTHENON, in Centennial Park, (615) 862-8431 The centerpiece of
the Tennessee Centennial Exposition of 1897 and a full-scale copy
of the ancient Greek temple in concrete. Inside is a 42-foot statue
of Athena made by Alan LeQuire, a local sculptor. ``Winslow Homer:
An American Genius,'' through Sept. 24. Hours through Sept. 24:
Tuesdays, 9 a.m. to 8 p.m.; Wednesdays through Fridays, 9 a.m. to
4:30 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 4:30 p.m.; closed Mondays. Admission:
$6; $3.50 for children under 18 and the elderly; free for children
under 4.
</P>
<P>
   STATE CAPITOL, Capitol Boulevard, a little north of the downtown
district, (615) 741-1621. Tours: (615) 741-0830.
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE PERFORMING ARTS CENTER, James K. Polk Cultural Center,
505 Deaderick St., (615) 255-2787. Saturday at 3:30 p.m., America's
Music Festival, a national singing competition. Tickets: $10. Sept.
26 to Oct. 1, ``Les Miserables.''
</P>
<P>
   VANDERBILT UNIVERSITY, campus entrance at 1211 22nd Ave. South,
off West End Avenue, (615) 322-7311.
</P>
