<HEADER>
A4804 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COMPUTER-ANIMATION-NY     07-27 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-ANIMATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FESTIVAL OF ANIMATION, ANIMATEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ An army of samurai come roaring on horseback down
a medieval hillside in a driving rain, kicking up mud and water.
Several of them dismount, swords and spears spinning, and break
into a brutal ballet of combat and impalings. One of them takes an
arrow through the throat, an image lifted directly from Akira
Kurosawa's ``Throne of Blood'' and given a fresh twist in this
bleak, computer-generated landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Onimusha,'' the opening movie for a video game to be used in
the soon-to-be-released Sony Play Station 2, won best-of-show
honors at the computer animation festival at this year's Siggraph
convention in the humid funk of a Louisiana July.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Siggraph brings together the leading artists,
companies, researchers, animators and visionaries from the worlds
of computer animation, virtual reality and interactive technology _
and each year, one of the highlights is a computer animation
festival featuring the best of the submissions that come in from
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   More than 650 entries were received this year; 135 were chosen
to be part of the festival. They were shown in four screening rooms
at the New Orleans convention center, just upstairs from the vast
cacophonous trade show floor where companies like Adobe, Nvidia,
NewTek, SGI and Discreet were showing off their latest high-tech
gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, at the ornate, refurbished Saenger Theater, a
two-hour ``Electronic Festival'' of the year's short-film
highlights was shown each night.
</P>
<P>
   The event is seen in the world of computer graphics as a kind of
annual assessment of the state of the art in computer-generated
special effects and computer animation _ both of which are
increasingly important in Hollywood, in video games and on the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   It was at such festivals over the last two decades that many
breakthroughs in computer animation were first given a public
viewing, as artists in the highly competitive field showed off for
one another with the geek equivalent of a cocky swagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significant trend this year was the advance of game
animation with a more cinematic feel,'' said Joe Takai, an animator
for Industrial Light and Magic who served as chairman of this
year's festival committee. ``Game developers are paying more
attention to story development and styles in the way that feature
films have done for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Takai said the committee was particularly impressed with the
number of foreign entries _ about 48 percent of those submitted _
as well as the unusual number of high-quality entries from
students, an indication of how a new generation of cheaper
animation software is allowing even beginners to produce pieces
good enough to compete with the the offerings of the biggest
animation companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stationen,'' from a German animator named Christian
Sawade-Meyer, was just such a piece, and it won the festival's jury
award, its second prize. In the short film, a man drags a box
filled with withering plants across an apocalyptic wasteland,
occasionally pausing to try to plant some in the arid soil only to
watch them wither and die. Eventually, he discovers a glistening
spring, but it is too late: the plants are dead.
</P>
<P>
   The top award to ``Onimusha'' also highlights the high number of
festival selections from the video gaming world. These have been
made possible by advances in photo-real animation, in
motion-capture techniques (which allow actors whose bodies are
covered with computer sensors to act out complex movements that can
later be transferred to animated characters) and by a new
generation of video game consoles like Sony's Play Station 2 and
Microsoft's X-Machine, on which the games will eventually be
played.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood was here, too, of course. Industrial Light and Magic
had a short film about the computer-generated water effects it
created for ``The Perfect Storm.'' Digital Domain showed the credit
sequence from ``The Fight Club,'' which begins inside a person's
head and follows a thought as it rushes through his brain and out
his eyeball. Sony Pictures' Digital Human Project showed some bits
of the intricate computer-generated skeleton and muscle work that
made possible its forthcoming invisible-man thriller, ``The Hollow
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Academic researchers, at the heart of Siggraph from the
beginning, contributed pieces that highlighted advances in the use
of virtual light and three-dimensional graphics.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Light of Mies van der Rohe,'' Henrik Wann Jensen of
Stanford University showed the interplay of natural light over an
entire day as it splashes across a computer-generated architectural
model. In ``The Last Drawing of Canaletto,'' Cameron McNall of the
University of California at Los Angeles brings to three-dimensional
life a final sketch by the artist and takes the audience on a
virtual ride through the painting, seeing the figures from various
angles inside the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Young and relatively inexperienced animators also made an
impressive showing. In the film that probably got the festival's
biggest laughs, Robert Rioux did a version of a light-saber duel
between Darth Vader and Luke Skywalker from ``Star Wars'' in which
they are made of Lego blocks and in which Vader ends up berating
his son for being a slacker and needing a haircut.
</P>
</TEXT>
