<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MONGOLIAN-RELIGIOUS-A     07-27 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONGOLIAN-RELIGIOUS-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: MASKS OFFER AN EXOTIC TASTE OF MONGOLIAN MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mongolia, the land of Genghis Khan, windswept steppes
and tough ponies, is seldom associated with religious art. Yet such
art always thrived there, in the form of gilded Buddhist icons and
in the expressive images of a native shamanism.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most of that work has vanished. Buddhism worked
hard for centuries to put shamanism out of business, and to a large
degree succeeded. In the 1930s, Stalinist purges destroyed
practically all of the Buddhist monasteries _ more than 700 _ along
with everything in them.
</P>
<P>
   Some precious objects were hidden away and have since reappeared
in the national museum collections of an independent Mongolia. And
in 1995, a remarkable cache of this material visited the United
States in an exhibition that was put together by the Asian Art
Museum in San Francisco and traveled to the Denver Art Museum and
the National Geographic Society in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The installation in Washington, in a choppy string of lobby
galleries, was something of a bust. But much of the art, sacred and
secular and mostly dating from the late 19th and 20th centuries,
was spectacular. And nothing made a stronger impression than a
handful of sculptural masks, larger than life, vividly painted and
made to be worn in epic-scale religious dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the outstanding masks from that show, along with others
visiting America for the first time, are at Asia House in ``Dancing
Demons: Ceremonial Masks of Mongolia,'' an exhibition that is
itself a slice of a larger Mongolian survey organized by the art
historian Jan Fontein at the Nieuwe Kerk in Amsterdam last year.
</P>
<P>
   With Asia Society in temporary quarters these days _ its main
plant, farther north on Park Avenue, is under renovation _ its
gallery space is tight, and Fontein had to edit his original show
down. No harm done. The result is a usefully focused look at one
aspect of a complex hybrid culture in which Buddhism and shamanism
alternately duked it out and worked together.
</P>
<P>
   Asian shamanism remains little studied in the West, particularly
in exhibitions. But in Mongolia, as in Tibet, it was the primary
religion of a nomadic people who viewed the natural world as a
cosmic mechanism of checks and balances, controlled by ancestral
spirits, sensitive to disturbance, always threatening to tip toward
disaster. By means of ritual implements and trance-induced visions,
shamans intervened in crises and appealed to the powers that be for
relief.
</P>
<P>
   If shamanism was a grass-roots religion, Buddhism was a movable
feast. Wherever it touched down outside its birthplace in India, it
was an import item, a foreign body that aroused suspicion as well
as devotion. Perhaps for this reason it learned to be diplomatic
about making its presence felt. Rather than replace local religious
traditions outright, it borrowed from them, then gradually absorbed
them in a passive-aggressive mix of preservation and suppression.
</P>
<P>
   But traditions are traditions for a reason. They're tenacious
and resilient, and even when paved over, they keep pushing up,
blending into the new order here, standing out from it there. And
that is the organic story _ it's the ABC of cultural history _ told
in the objects at Asia Society.
</P>
<P>
   True, some of those objects seem, at least at a glance,
religiously specific, like the 19th-century shaman costumes on loan
from the National Museum of Mongolian History or items made for a
New Year celebration honoring the Buddha of the future, Maitreya.
For that occasion, a statue of Maitreya was displayed on a wooden
chariot to which the head of a magical green horse was attached.
Such a head, a velvet-covered wood carving attributed to the
artist-monk Damdinsuren (1868-1938), is in the show.
</P>
<P>
   But the horse was an emblem important to Buddhism and shamanism
alike. And both religions were thoroughly intertwined in another
grand monastic festival known as the Tsam. A combination of
morality play, circus, shoot-em-up action film and public exorcism,
it involved an eclectic cast of symbolic characters, with the god
of death _ the Buddhist Yama, the shamanist Erlik Khan _ in the
starring role.
</P>
<P>
   The event was staged in a mandala pattern. The outdoor playing
area was divided into a series of concentric circles, at the center
of which stood a doll-like form molded from a lump of fast-rising
dough. Throughout the long performance, characters attacked the
doll with knives, and its yeasty form slowly swelled as if
poisoned. (Symbolically, it was absorbing evil, including sins of
the community.) In the end, it was hacked to pieces and burned,
leaving the path to collective enlightenment clear.
</P>
<P>
   All of the roles in the pageant were acted by monks wearing
elaborate masks of the kind seen at Asia Society. A pair of
skeletal figures called Citipati, with sources in the Tibetan
Buddhist tradition, opened the proceedings with a shivery flourish.
They were followed by the pudgy, grinning Kashin Kahn and his eight
sons, characters with complicated links to Chinese Buddhism, who
served as both orchestra and receiving line, greeting new players
as they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Shamanist figures joined the festivities at various points. Some
were powerfully exotic: a mask of the Hindu deity Garuda, a horned
bird carrying a cotton serpent in its beak, embodied the spirit of
a revered holy man from the past who had ``converted'' to Buddhism.
The main shaman character, however, named the White Old Man, was a
burlesque, a doddering, bearded buffoon. Intended to provide comic
relief, he was relegated to the fringes of the central activity.
But, significantly, he was an audience favorite.
</P>
<P>
   As in many dramas, the villains were the most dynamic figures of
all, and although Yama/Erlik Khan is not directly represented in
the exhibition, several of his frightful henchmen are, among them
the ghoulish Citipati and a dancing deer with a lolling red velvet
tongue. Also on hand are snarling, bug-eyed characters known as
dharmapalas, or protectors of the Buddhist law. Indebted, like so
much Mongolian art, to Tibetan prototypes, they look demonic but
are actually agents of divine protection, meant to scare evil away.
</P>
<P>
   The show is fleshed out with interesting smaller items. One, a
brocade ritual apron stitched with the face of the Buddhist god
Mahakala, represents a kind of pictorial applique at which
Mongolian artists excelled. Another is a two-stringed violin, its
slender neck ending with green-painted horse heads, which was
designed to accompany recitations of heroic Mongolian tales passed
on through oral tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition catalog _ a more modest effort by far, at least
in its English version, than the one produced by the Asian Art
Museum _ suggests that such recitations are still occasionally
performed. And apparently, the grand festivals are being revived,
and art surviving in museums and monasteries is being restored.
</P>
<P>
   It would certainly be good to see more of this work, including
the glorious sculptures of the renowned artist-lama Zanabazar
(1635-1723), in New York, where enthusiasm for things Buddhist runs
high and cultural hybridity is well understood. Perhaps ``Dancing
Demons'' will inspire one of the big museums to get into the
festive groove.
</P>
<P>
   (``Dancing Demons: Ceremonial Masks of Mongolia'' remains at
Asia Society at Midtown, 502 Park Ave. (at 59th Street), through
Sept. 17).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
