<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER LOPEZ STEPS INTO `THE CELL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Jennifer
Lopez in a scene from ``The Cell.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    ``The Cell'' is a film like no other.
 &HT;    Gorgeous and disturbing in its imagery, brutal yet ultimately
hopeful in its storytelling, it will surely revolt as many people
as it entertains.
 &HT;    And make no mistake, ``The Cell'' is an A-list, mainstream
production starring Jennifer Lopez, Vince Vaughn and Vincent
D'Onofrio, directed by video auteur Tarsem and set for wide release
on Aug. 18 by New Line Cinema.
 &HT;    ``It is all those things,'' says Lopez, the freshly minted
Latina superstar. ``There were times when I said, `This is really
out there,' but when I choose a role or a film I don't think about
whether or not it will piss people off. If it's a story I feel I
want to tell or a character I can relate to, I just go with that.
 &HT;    ```The Cell' was in development for years,'' she says. ``When I
went to New Line for a meeting with Mike DeLuca, that was on the
roster. I remembered it from years ago, when nobody would make a
movie with me.
 &HT;    ``When I saw it on their list of projects they owned, I was
like, `Oh wow, I'd love to do this,''' Lopez recalls. ``Mike said,
`Fine, let's just get a director.' That was it. It was great.''
 &HT;    The film's story involves Carl Stargher (Vincent D'Onofrio), a
deeply disturbed serial killer who lapses into a coma soon after
imprisoning his latest victim in a hidden cell rigged first to
torment her and then, within two days, to kill her. On the case and
at his wits' end, FBI Agent Peter Novak (Vince Vaughn) is open to
anything.
 &HT;    Anything takes the form of Catherine Deane (Lopez), a
psychologist working on a radical, chemically and electrically
stimulated therapy that enables her to link her mind to a patient's
and probe that person's dreams, fears and desires. Though skittish,
Deane accepts the challenge of entering Stargher's demented mind in
an effort to confront him and uncover the location of the imperiled
victim.
 &HT;    Deane and eventually Novak take the plunge and stumble into a
maelstrom of unbridled ego, repressed rage, childhood innocence,
gruesome torture and sick sexual fantasy, not to mention outlandish
outfits, masks and furnishings. It's a harrowing world from which
they may never escape, even if they do get out alive.
 &HT;    ``The whole dream world gave me so much room to be creative, to
go wherever as an actress,'' Lopez says by telephone from a New
York recording studio, where she's working on her next dance-music
album, due out in October. ``The costumes were (Oscar-winning
Japanese designer) Eiko Ishioka's, the sets were Tarsem's vision
and I just brought to it my aspect, which is the realness of the
character, who's this woman trying to save a little boy in a coma
and also the woman who is missing.
 &HT;    ``I tried to focus on my acting, on the character, and all this
other stuff was going on,'' she says. ``I definitely thought, `Oh
my God, I hope this works.' I had that thought every once in a
while. I was standing there in this long, white outfit with a red
scarf, like I was in a Ti-D-Bowl commercial _ but on film it looks
incredible.''
 &HT;    Lopez admits that sci-fi and horror films aren't exactly her cup
of tea _ never were and never will be. The initial concept of ``The
Cell'' called for it to be far less of a genre piece than it turned
out to be, she says.
 &HT;    ``Tarsem really brought that aspect to it,'' says Lopez, who's
due next in the comedy ``The Wedding Planner'' and the romantic
drama ``Angel Eyes.'' ``The script was really more about trying to
get into the mind of a serial killer.
 &HT;    ``I didn't know it would take that surrealistic, sci-fi type of
approach,'' she says. ``It originally didn't have that flavor in
the script. That was something that was totally Tarsem's idea and
vision and creativity.''
 &HT;    Not that she's complaining, of course.
 &HT;    ``I think it was an incredible way to go,'' Lopez says. ```The
Cell' is different. It's new. It looks great. It's wonderful.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Cell,'' consult the
official Web site at www.thecellmovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
