<HEADLINE>
$ADV01 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, AUG. 1, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard.  
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second night of the Republican convention should be
highlighted by Sen. John McCain's speech. On ABC, you'll find
coverage at 10 p.m. PBS will be on the air from 8 to 11. But the
other networks will be running regular programs _ although CBS will
look in on the convention during ''60 Minutes II.'' Even NBC might
drop by during ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   On cable, you'll find complete coverage on C-Span as well as
extensive time on CNN, Fox New Channel and MSNBC, although C-Span
has the advantage _ no shouting pundits. Your best bet may be the
irreverent comedy and commentary on Comedy Central's ``The Daily
Show with Jon Stewart,'' whose guests include Bob Dole and Robert
Reich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS at 8: Live coverage of the soap opera
developments inside a house filled with some of the most annoying
people you'll ever want to met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' ABC at 8: No, this isn't
ABC's convention coverage. In fact, it may be a little less
show-bizzy. Regis Philbin hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' WB at 8: Caustic punk vampire
Spike (James Marsters) returns to Sunnydale looking for a relic.
Buffy (Sarah Michelle Gellar) is less than thrilled to see him.
Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show,'' Fox at 8: Jackie, depressed from her breakup
with Kelso, finally agrees to dinner with Fez, but she seems more
interested in the entree. And the appetizer. And the rolls. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier,'' NBC at 9: One of this season's truly sparkling
episodes, as Oprah and Star Jones take it on the chin. Kim Coles of
``In Living Color'' guests as a vacation fill-in for Roz who starts
taking over the radio show from Frasier (Kelsey Grammer) and
becomes a Seattle sensation. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judging Amy,'' CBS at 9: Amy must decide a custody case
involving the child of a mentally handicapped woman. Amy Brenneman
stars. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angel,'' WB at 9: Picking up where tonight's ``Buffy'' left
off, Angel finds himself up against Spike when Oz brings a certain
relic to L.A. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Full Circle,'' some PBS stations at 8: The marathon continues.
The latest sojourn with globe-trotting ex-Monty Pythoner Michael
Palin as he circles the Pacific Rim. Additional episodes air at 9
and 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Reel Models: The First Women on Film,'' American Movie
Classics at 8: A surprising hour-plus documentary hosted by Barbra
Streisand uncovers some amazing stories of women making it in the
very early days of Hollywood, and the prices they paid for stardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking Apart: Families Under the Influence,'' HBO at 8: A
look at how addiction affects everyone in the drinker's orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilligan's Island'' marathon, Nick at Nite at 9: If you can't
wait till Wednesday for ``Survivor,'' a dose of this ought to tide
you over. I'd like to see Richard and Susan build a radio out of
coconuts and palm fronds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultraviolet,'' Sci Fi at 9: Part two of the three-part British
miniseries about a cop investigating vampires and worldwide
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''100 Greatest Rock 'n' Roll Moments on TV,'' VH1 at 10: Moments
80-61. This is as goofy and random an exercise as any 100 greatest
list, but there's enough terrific footage here to make it worth
watching. The show airs at 10 all week, working toward No. 1. (At 9
tonight, moments 100-81 are repeated.)
</P>
<P>
   Marx Brothers movie marathon, Turner Classic Movies at 8:
Beginning with ``A Night at the Opera,'' followed by ``A Day at the
Races,'' ``At the Circus,'' ``Go West'' and ``The Big Store.'' It
doesn't get any better than this.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Nathan Lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Clint Eastwood,
Tommy Lee Jones, James Garner and Donald Sutherland, who are the
stars of the movie ``Space Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: Arsenio
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.:
Actress Brenda Blethyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Frankie Muniz
of ``Malcolm in the Middle.'' Rerun. &QL; 
