<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NUTTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY DELIVERS IN GROSS-OUT FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C+  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say what you will about Eddie Murphy, the man works hard for his
money.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps,'' he plays not just the
300-pound Sherman Klump and his sleek alter ego Buddy Love but the
character's father (in two stages of his life), mother, grandmother
and two other significant roles.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike ``Nutty I,'' the extended family members are not just
brief cameos but full-blown performances. As the movie's subtitle
indicates, the focus is less on the split personality of the title
character and more on the elder Klumps. Murphy spends 90 percent of
the running time buried under Rick Baker's Oscar-worthy makeup
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Murphy is remarkably convincing _ even endearing _ as
each of the characters. His Sherman Klump is not just Murphy in a
fat suit but a touching, finely drawn characterization. His Granny
Klump is not just Murphy in drag but an extraordinary piece of
acting. It's a tour de force (and, to be sure, a tour de ego).
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the movie itself is a scattered mess that really
doesn't add up to anything that's particularly satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   There's also something galling about the fact that it reportedly
cost $90 million _ making it the highest-budget comedy ever _ and
yet it aims so mind-bogglingly low.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' and ``Scary
Movie,'' it also seems to be part of a disturbing new Hollywood
trend this summer to outdo the competition by plumbing the absolute
depths of gross-out comedy. It's undeniably funny in spots, but it
has the sensibility of a dirty-minded eighth-grader and the soul of
a whoopee cushion.
</P>
<P>
   The story finds the professor in love with an academic colleague
(Janet Jackson), in possession of a fountain-of-youth formula and
worried about recent intrusions by his suppressed alter ego, Buddy.
Complications ensue when one of the lab experiments goes awry, and
Buddy finds a way to come to life independent of Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   But the struggle of Sherman and Buddy _ mostly over the formula
that's worth $150 million to one company _ is this time only a slim
pretext, and the film is actually more about Sherman's stumbling
efforts to get married, the dysfunctional sex life of his parents
and the romantic aspirations of his 80-year-old Granny.
</P>
<P>
   The gags are basically just more of the same of what we got in
the 1996 first installment, except that the concentration of the
humor is less on cruel fat jokes and more on geriatric sex _ which,
in the adolescent mentality of the script, is viewed as being so
unnatural and repulsive that when Granny comes on to Buddy Love, he
has no recourse but to run to the bushes and throw up.
</P>
<P>
   Part II also outdoes Part I in flatulence jokes (quite a feat,
since Leonard Maltin's review of the original claims it has
``enough flatulence jokes to last 10 lifetimes''). Here we get
Sherman in a ``2001''-like dream sequence flatulating ``The Blue
Danube'' waltz, and Father Klump half destroying a buffet
restaurant with one deadly explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty II's'' biggest gag, however, involves a laboratory
hamster that suddenly takes on the proportions of the Monster Who
Devoured Cleveland, then devastates a press conference with his
excrement and sodomizes the heavy (Larry Miller). Murphy's films
are often criticized for being unoriginal, but that's a sequence we
definitely haven't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   NUTTY PROFESSOR II: THE KLUMPS
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Peter Segal
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS: Barry W. Blaustein, David Sheffield, Paula Weitz, Chris
Weitz
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Eddie Murphy, Janet Jackson, Larry Miller, John Ales
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 98 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for gross humor and geriatric sex jokes
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
