<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTIONS-PRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE CLEARS WAY FOR REPORTERS TO WATCH EXECUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Criticizing state prison officials for trying to
limit press access to executions, a federal judge says reporters
must be allowed to watch the entire lethal injection process, from
the time the shackled prisoner is led into the chamber until death
is pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyewitness testimony is crucial to the public's evaluation of
how this extreme punishment is performed,'' U.S. District Judge
Vaughn Walker said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   His ruling restored and broadened the unprecedented order he
issued in 1996, requiring the San Quentin warden to lift the
curtain that had shielded the early stages of the execution process
from reporters and other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   That order was in effect for only one execution before it was
set aside by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which said
Walker had given too much weight to the media's access rights and
not enough to the safety of prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling allowed prison officials to close the viewing area
until after the prisoner had been strapped to the gurney, needles
and tubes had been inserted, and all guards had left the chamber.
Reporters had to rely on official descriptions of events while the
curtain was closed.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeals court said Walker could consider another claim
by news organizations that filed the lawsuit: that the restrictions
were an exaggerated response to the prison's security concerns. The
judge agreed with that claim Wednesday, citing evidence from a
two-day non-jury trial in February.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of executions in California, none of the guards
who volunteer for the execution team has ever been identified by
news reports or suffered retaliation or threats by prisoners,
Walker said. He said there was no evidence of any such incidents in
other states.
</P>
<P>
   Walker also said guards could wear surgical masks to conceal
their identities. And he said the state's current restrictions
appeared to have been prompted in part by public relations.
</P>
<P>
   The rules were ``motivated, at least in part, by a concern that
the strapping of a condemned inmate, the injection of intravenous
lines or other aspects of a lethal injection execution would be
perceived as brutal by the public,'' a consideration that is
separate from ``legitimate concerns for prison personnel safety,''
Walker wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a memo from Arthur Calderon, the warden of San Quentin
when the restrictions were drafted, in which he said that witnesses
might draw the wrong conclusions if guards were seen subduing a
prisoner who resisted while being strapped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we are perceived as using only the
minimal amount of force necessary to accomplish the task,''
Calderon wrote. He said using a great deal of force ``would most
certainly be misinterpreted by the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials ``have a history of resistance to media
presence at executions,'' Walker said, and tried in the mid-1990s
to stop reporters from taking pencils and paper to the viewing
chamber. Those efforts run contrary to the historic right of the
public and press to have access to executions, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The last prisoner executed in California was Darrell Rich, a
convicted serial killer who was put to death by injection in March.
No executions are scheduled for the rest of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
