<HEADER>
A4819 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-SHATTUCK-TRAVEL-HNS &LR;      07-27 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHATTUCK-TRAVEL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Travel Commentary. For release Sunday, July 30.
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASEBALL TOUR VISITS ALL 30 MAJOR LEAGUE STADIUMS IN 32 DAYS
</P>
<P>
   By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   I've managed some creative trip scheduling over the years, but
probably my wackiest idea _ and proudest accomplishment from an
endurance standpoint _ was visiting 26 baseball spring training
camps.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 days.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm being trumped. By a school librarian, two college
freshmen-to-be, a grandmother-grandson tandem, a retired petroleum
engineer, a video-store owner and _ gulp! _ a Brit.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a ``Millennium Tour'' organized by
Massachusetts-based Sports Travel, these eight individuals and a
coordinator/escort are in undertaking a cross-continent adventure
that is taking them to regular-season games at 30 stadiums in 32
days. Plus a closing stop at the National Baseball Hall of Fame in
Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   I had it easy. The major leagues have added four teams since my
mid-'80s odyssey. And spring camps are limited to Florida and
Arizona; these warriors are visiting 17 states and two Canadian
provinces _ traveling by airplane (13 flights), bus, train, van and
taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend was a doozy. The Sports Travel team _ a designation
participants proudly accept _ spent Friday night at the Coliseum in
Oakland, Calif., Saturday afternoon at Seattle's Safeco Field and
Sunday afternoon at Houston's Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   And the airlines lost only one suitcase en route.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about dedication: Following overnight flights, the team
arrived at Bush Intercontinental Airport Sunday at 9:30 a.m. and
proceeded to the stadium to watch batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were treated royally,'' says Floridian Red McGarry, a
former executive with 3M and Polaroid who is coordinating this
marathon _ and adding to the 16 parks he'd already visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Astros invited us onto the field for batting practice,''
McGarry says. ``And they upgraded our seats so that we watched the
game from the front row of the club level just behind the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie London, a teacher and librarian for 28 years in the
Milwaukee public school system, even got to chat with one of her
favorite players _ Astros infielder Bill Spiers, who previously
toiled with the Brewers in her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   London, a baseball loyalist since age 4, won't admit to being a
hitting coach, but Spiers followed with two home runs, including a
grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Travel Industry Association of America
found that 75.3 million U.S. adults have traveled 50 or more miles
to attend or watch a sports event over the past five years.
Participants on this tour come from diverse backgrounds and
geographical locations but possess two common bonds: a love of
baseball and a thirst for travel.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Troy and Michael Tomsky, both 18, have been best buddies
for 10 years in Stamford, Conn. They will attend different
universities, and this excursion _ high school graduation presents
_ is an opportunity to spend one last month together.
</P>
<P>
   Marcella Early, from Louisville, Ky., relishes any chance to
travel with 14-year-old grandson Scott. Visiting every baseball
stadium is her lifelong dream, and Scott already is an avid
memorabilia collector.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Short, 39, who hails from New Athens, Ill., says that he,
too, has ``fantasized about this kind of trip. I especially enjoy
seeing the contrast between the older and younger parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Westgate, 53, lives in Irving, Texas. During the '70s, he
traveled to every stadium then in existence. But that journey took
four years, not 32 days.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Hook, a 30-year-old accountant, is the most unlikely
participant, having been raised in England's ``Forest of Dean,'' a
hotbed of rugby near the Welsh border.
</P>
<P>
   Hook got hooked on baseball in the early '90s. He religiously
tapes live telecasts from the United States (shown twice weekly in
the middle of the night in England), collects videocassettes of
historic games and has participated in three shorter Sports Travel
tours.
</P>
<P>
   Hook admits that his rugby-oriented chums don't share his
passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends understand five weeks in America,'' he says. ``They
don't understand five weeks of baseball. They don't understand one
day of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me, `Why don't you go see the Grand Canyon
instead?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sightseeing isn't included in the tour price ($5,995 per person,
double occupancy; $7,662 single, covering game tickets,
transportation and escort but not meals), but during Week 1 some
team members visited Disneyland in Anaheim, Calif., San Francisco's
Fisherman's Wharf and Seattle's Pike Place Market. Two nights each
in Chicago and New York loom promising, and the schedule may allow
a stop in Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Most spare time, though, is reserved for sleeping, eating and
frequenting hotels' self-service laundries.
</P>
<P>
   And for evaluations. Participants use a 1-to-5 point system to
grade each park on 18 criteria _ friendliness, safety, acoustics,
seat comfort and view, restroom cleanliness, food quality and
merchandise pricing among them.
</P>
<P>
   Early results haven't been tabulated, but those surveyed rank
Enron Field at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   As for San Francisco's new Pacific Bell Park?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm collecting postcards at every stadium,'' Hook says. ``A
postcard at Pac Bell costs $2; at Enron it's 35 cents. And it's a
nicer postcard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hook also is collecting T-shirts while fellow travelers save
programs and ticket stubs and purchase pins and other souvenirs.
``Several teams have given us goody bags,'' McGarry says, ``and the
Astros gave us Enron Field inaugural game programs, which was
especially nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make frequent trips to post offices to ship things home,''
McGarry says.
</P>
<P>
   Successful completion of the journey brings a coveted reward:
induction into Sports Travel's Stadium Hall of Fame in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Travel plans a similar tour for next year and offers
shorter packages for baseball and other sports (with prices
starting at $500 per person). Customized tours can be arranged.
Call 800-662-4424 to request a brochure. Or access
www.sportstravelandtours.com.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
