</P>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Oscar-winning actress Geena Davis goes to the
small screen this fall with her new self-titled ABC sitcom, which
has an improbable _ and some would say _ immoral premise. The
initial buzz on the show isn't very good, but Davis is far from
worried. By MIKI TURNER. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-JANE KACZMAREK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Jane Kaczmarek had a new baby and was
studying music and didn't want a TV show but found something quirky
and endearing about the character of Lois, the mother in ``Malcolm
in the Middle.'' Kaczmarek's portrayal of the unconventional mom
redefined the role of the sainted television mother _ and earned
the actress her first Emmy nomination last week. By MIKI TURNER.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ADS-POP CULTURE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Whassup with the way certain commercials filter their
way into the entertainment world and the public consciousness? We
look at a few campaigns that have inspired parodies, expanded
trends or rediscovered obscure music and try to find out what
separates them from their more humble brethren. By ROBERT PHILPOT.
Story will move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EMMY-RULES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Amending the process of how stars and shows
are selected for Emmy honors may alter what we see in the future,
or it may simply give us exactly what we always get: the same shows
and the same familiar faces trotting up to the podium. TV critic
Ken Parish Perkins examines the Emmy rules change and the criticism
that's following it. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
