<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4823 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-NUTTY28-COX     07-27 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-NUTTY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murphy large, but not in charge
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big problem in ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' is the
nutty professor. This sequel to the 1996 hit seems designed for
video: You want to fast-forward through all the parts focused on
tubby scientist Sherman (Eddie Murphy) so you can get back to the
rest of his family (played by Murphy, Murphy, Murphy and Murphy,
plus a fat kid).
</P>
<P>
   The first ``Professor'' put a delirious spin on the Jerry Lewis
original, transforming Sherman from a nerd to a lovably obese
sweetheart whose genetic formula unleashed his thinner, meaner id,
Buddy Love, as he tried to win his lab assistant's heart. She was
played by Jada Pinkett. This time Janet Jackson is the romantic
interest, a fellow scientist who has nothing to do but be lovely;
she's wasted.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Sherman gets rid of Buddy _ who has a habit of popping out
of him at awkward moments _ by extracting the rogue's DNA from his
own. Naturally, Buddy manages to regenerate in the flesh, with the
help of some dog DNA. This nonsensical science is a pretty good
indication of the script as a whole. It's slapdash and episodic,
and hard to care about.
</P>
<P>
   Director Peter Segal and the handful of screenwriters involved
should have just ditched it and found a way to focus entirely on
the family, once again the movie's real comic glory.
</P>
<P>
   Submerged in Rick Baker's amazing fat suits and makeup, and
aided by terrific visual tricks that let him share the screen with
himselves, Murphy continues to be jaw-droppingly funny as Sherman's
parents, brother and grandmother. The crotchety and oversexed
granny steals the movie, especially when the arrival of the
unsuspecting Buddy Love gets her libido burning.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the movie flips back to the piecemeal plot about
Sherman and Buddy's battle to sell a youth serum to the highest
corporate bidder, it loses steam.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's moments of splendor deserve a screenplay that's as good
as he is. Maybe a sharper script is too much to ask for these days,
when comedies are becoming just a series of comic set pieces and
gross-out scenes, barely held together by a plot. ``Nutty II''
follows that pattern: bad movie, hilarious bits.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next time, the Klumps will leave Sherman at the lab, and
go visit their cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty Professor II:
</P>
<P>
   The Klumps''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy and Janet Jackson. Rated PG-13 for crude
humor and sex-related material. 1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Not nutty enough.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
