<P>
   These business stories for release Friday, July 28, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER _ SAN DIEGO _ Industry leaders and observers said
Thursday that a federal judge's injunction that would shut down
Napster significantly increases the chances of government
regulation of the online music industry. Surprisingly, some say
they welcome regulatory intervention. In any case, the court ruling
is little more than a temporary setback in the online entertainment
world, they say. And don't count Napster out of it just yet.
Company attorneys, backed by some of the heaviest hitters in
Silicon Valley, were preparing an appeal Thursday and are showing
no signs of turning down the noise in their camp anytime soon.
(Keefe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER-SIDE _ In the wake of the Napster meltdown, where are
fans going to get their downloads? What alternatives exist and how
busy are they today _ and how busy is Napster for that matter? What
are fans saying, doing as the court deadline looms? (Fernandez,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)STEVENS _ As expected, WestPoint
Stevens said earnings were hurt by a large restructuring charge.
The West Point sheet and towel maker reported a second-quarter loss
of $89.8 million, or $1.81 a share, compared with a profit of $19.6
million, or 34 cents a share, in the prior period. The results
included a one-time pretax charge of $168.2 million. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UTILITY-BIAS _ Lawyers file a major class action lawsuit against
Georgia Power Co. and the parent Southern Co. alleging racial
discrimination against 2,100 employees. The lawsuit , filed by the
same law firm that represented plaintiffs in the Coca-Cola case,
alleges an ``extraordinarily hostile racial environment'' at the
utility. Georgia Power's president is addressing employees this
afternoon to issue a defense against the charges. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS _ The outlook for profits has suddenly dimmed, thanks to
the Federal Reserve's year-long series of interest rate hikes. Most
economists now think the usual second-half rebound will not occur
this year, and analysts are worried that 3rd and 4th quarter profit
growth will slow. This casts a cloud over the outlook for the stock
market. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EARTHLINK _ EarthLink Inc. on Thursday reported booming
revenues, a shrinking loss and strong customer growth as it
continued its pursuit of America Online. In reporting its second
quarter earnings, the company also acknowledged some service
problems during the earlier part of the year _ blaming them largely
on the awkardness of merging EarthLink and MindSpring. The company
also promised more acquisitions as it grows. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COX _ Cox Communications releases its earnings. (Brister,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM _ WorldCom earnings; WorldCom considers tracking stock.
Continued speculation on merger(s) (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0725 _ A truly massive vehicle and one that's
ultra-sophisticated in some ways, the 2000 Lincoln Town Car also is
as retro as the 2001 Chrysler PT cruiser or any other vehicle
harkening to the good ol' days of cheap fuel and big-engined luxury
cars (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a
3-column color photo of the 2000 Lincoln Town Car and a 2-column
color photo of the car's leather seats.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Lincoln Town
Car.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC _ Harkening back to the Paul Simon song, here
are 50 ways to kill your catalytic converter. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color photograph of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ ATLANTA _ Test driving a station wagon is not
normally something that would make my heart skip a beat. But I was
driving through the scenic rolling mountains of southern France.
The vehicle was Volvo's V70 wagon. My drive partner was He
Drove/She Drove's Paul Lienert. Paul tossed me the keys and assumed
the duties of navigator. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE _ ATLANTA _ If you think the Chevrolet Corvette Z06
isn't one hot item, consider this: Somewhere between its
manufacture and initial drives by magazine writers at the proving
grounds in Michigan and Atlanta, the brilliant red car lost the
``Z06'' emblem off its right front fender _ and chip marks
indicated it didn't just fall off. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
