<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0728-COX     07-27 3006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Miller seated in senate
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democratic former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller was sworn in today to
temporarily fill the U.S. Senate seat left vacant by the death of
Republican Paul Coverdell. The popular Miller, a two-term governor
of Georgia, will run in a November special election to fill the
four remaining years of Coverdell's term, giving Democrats high
hope of snatching the Senate majority from Republicans. Miller
thanked senators for their tributes to Coverdell in the past week
and added his own voice to the chorus of praise. ``Paul Coverdell
had a powerful faith in bipartisan progress,'' Miller said, ``and I
intend to keep that faith.'' Miller was sworn in by Senate
President Pro Tem Strom Thurmond of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY, IN DEFENSE OF HIS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, newly picked this week to be George W. Bush's
running mate, defended his conservative record in interviews on
three network morning TV programs today. On CBS' ``Early Show'': He
voted against the Equal Rights Amendment as a congressman because
he feared it would require the drafting of women into the military.
On ABC's ``Good Morning America'': He was one of only four
lawmakers voting against banning plastic guns and armor-piercing
``cop-killer'' bullets because he's ``a great believer in ... the
right of the citizens to keep and bear arms.'' And on NBC's
``Today'': His vote not to impose economic sanctions against the
segregationist government of South Africa did not mean he opposed
freeing the imprisoned Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S THAT DRAFT QUESTION AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Nominated to be secretary of defense in 1989, Dick Cheney came
under close questioning about how he had managed to avoid the draft
and Vietnam. The issue is likely to arise again now that he's
George W. Bush's running mate. But while George W. Bush, Bill
Clinton and Dan Quayle _ vice president under Bush's father _ all
have had to answer suggestions that they pulled strings to avoid
the draft, there's not been any such suggestion about Cheney. His
father, local administrator for the U.S. Soil Conservation Service,
hardly had major political influence. ``He was not very well known
at that time,'' said Joe Meyer, who roomed with Cheney in college
and now is Wyoming's secretary of state. Meyer said Vietnam ``was
not a subject on our mind'' at the time.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT TIME TO GET AWAY
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican Party set to open its national convention in
a few days, Al Gore has veered away from the campaign trail to
``clear his head'' with a family vacation before launching a blitz
taking him into his own Democratic convention. The Gore clan was at
the family home in Tennessee before heading later today to the
North Carolina seashore for some sun and relaxation. Aides wouldn't
rule out an occasional political discussion or phone call, but made
it clear that this was not intended to be a working vacation.
</P>
<P>
   LOW PROFILE, BUT WATCHING
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, as well, intends to keep a low profile while
the Republican Party holds its convention next week. Clinton is to
attend Democratic fund-raisers in Florida on Monday, but otherwise
will have ``a pretty low-key week,'' said White House press
secretary Joe Lockhart. That's in keeping with the tradition to
avoid the spotlight while the opposing party nominates its
presidential candidate. Lockhart, however, said Clinton might be
available to comment on some aspects of the GOP gathering ``if they
do something really dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE LIKES CHENEY CHOICE, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Despite the teasing pleas of a Chicago radio show host, Al Gore
wouldn't reveal whom he'll choose as his running mate. Not just
yet, Gore said. But then he added, with obvious pleasure, an
unsolicited reminder. ``Dick Cheney has been selected on the
Republican side,'' he said, his smile growing. In the days since
the Cheney announcement, Gore's campaign has publicly rejoiced. And
there's also a quieter, more private celebration going on at Gore's
Nashville headquarters, where the Cheney selection brings a level
of freedom to Gore's own high-pressure search for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T FORGET, HIS INITIALS ARE JFK
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Sen. John F. Kerry has kept mum about his
prospects of becoming Al Gore's running mate, but the Gore campaign
has asked Kerry for his tax records, according to the Washington
Times, a new signals that Kerry has moved up the shrinking list of
names in running. Others still prominently mentioned as possibles
are ex-Sen. George Mitchell of Maine, Sens. Bob Graham of Florida,
Tom Harkin of Iowa and Evan Bayh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   GULF WAR WAS GOOD TRAINING
</P>
<P>
   Four years after helping to win the Persian Gulf War and
liberating the oil fields of Kuwait, Dick Cheney went from fighting
for oil to running a Dallas-based outfit that he's helped transform
into the world's largest oil field services company. As chairman
and CEO of Halliburton since 1995, Cheney has been able to rely
heavily on the high-level contacts in the Middle East he made as
secretary of defense to win business in the roughneck world of
international oil. Much of Halliburton's business is done with Arab
governments, and almost 70 percent of the company's nearly $15
billion in annual sales come from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   PARTING WORDS FOR HALLIBURTON
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, who is resigning as chairman and CEO of Halliburton
Co. to join the Republican ticket, told shareholders and industry
analysts that his decision to leave the oil services company was
not an easy one. ``I did not seek the job that was proffered to me.
But I concluded after the governor talked to me a number of times I
did have an obligation to return to public service if in fact I was
asked. That's obviously what has transpired,'' Cheney said. He
added that he'll be watching the company very closely since he's a
major shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   TIME TO FALL IN AND MARCH IN STEP
</P>
<P>
   Offering closure to a bitter primary fight, John McCain is
preparing a prime-time convention speech in which he praises George
W. Bush and declares ``it is my time to serve'' his former rival.
In a draft of his speech being reviewed by convention planners and
Bush advisers, McCain calls for ``government reform'' in general,
but avoids direct mention of his bid to overhaul election finance
laws _ the issue that divides McCain from Bush and other GOP
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   NOTHING LIKE A BATTLESHIP FOR DRAMATIC EFFECT
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf will address the Republican
convention next Tuesday _ from the battleship New Jersey.
Schwarzkopf is to join John McCain, Bob and Elizabeth Dole, and
George W. Bush's international affairs adviser, Condoleezza Rice,
in discussing the night's theme: national security. Schwarzkopf was
commander of U.S. and allied troops in the Persian Gulf War. The
887-foot New Jersey is to be towed from the Philadelphia Naval
Yard, where it was launched in 1942, to its new permanent home at a
pier across the Delaware River in Camden, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   OLDER CITIZENS READY TO BITE BACK
</P>
<P>
   During his decade in Congress, Dick Cheney compiled a record of
voting against elderly interests on Social Security, Medicare and
assistance programs. ``His voting record on senior issues was a
disaster,'' said Bette Cooper of the National Council of Senior
Citizens. ``I haven't found one point where he could be viewed as a
friend of senior citizens.'' John Rother of the non-ideological
AARP, said the votes by George W. Bush's new running mate on a
variety of senior issues ``could be one of his biggest liabilities
as a candidate.'' Rother noted that Cheney was one of the few in
Congress to vote against the Older Americans Act and restoring
minimum benefits to Social Security recipients.
</P>
<P>
   DECK STACKED ON ANTI-ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over the Republican Party's position on abortion is
shaping up as one-sided, a blow to GOP abortion-rights activists
already disappointed in George W. Bush's choice of a running mate.
The group of platform committee members chosen to take up the issue
in pre-convention meetings Friday is led and dominated by
anti-abortion Republicans. The panel is ``overloaded with those who
disagree with us,'' said Susan Cullman, head of the Republican
Pro-Choice Coalition. ``It will be very hard to get a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP PRIMARY PLAN GAINS A STEP
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party moved a step closer to adopting a
presidential nominating plan in which small states would vote first
and big states last. The party's rules committee reaffirmed its
support of the plan, intended to forestall a drift to a national
primary, encourage more candidates to stay in the race longer, and
ensure that more votes matter. This year, the nominations were
settled in early March. But big states that fear irrelevance from
going last, and traditional opponents of giving party leaders more
power, are joining to fight the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE EXTRA, JUST TO MAKE SURE
</P>
<P>
   Even without heavyweight competition, Rep. Patrick Kennedy of
Rhode Island is still pulling in big bucks. In the three-month
period ending June 30, Kennedy banked $112,325 in campaign
contributions from organized labor, the hospital and nursing-home
industry, and scores of other out-of-state benefactors. His
Republican opponent, boiler operator Stephen Cabral, couldn't
compete. The political newcomer raised $1,360 and spent $828.13
over the same three-month stretch, most of it on campaign supplies
from Staples and Copy N Print.
</P>
<P>
   BUT THERE'S NO LINCOLN BEDROOM IN THE PENTAGON
</P>
<P>
   Long before there were White House coffees for Democratic
donors, Dick Cheney entertained major Republican contributors at
private meetings at the Pentagon, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics, which investigates congressional fund-raising.
Cheney was host for at least two GOP donor gatherings inside the
Defense Department in 1991 and in 1992, the records show. As
defense secretary under President Bush during the Persian Gulf War,
Cheney's popularity was then at its height. Republican National
Committee spokesman Bill Pasco declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   GORE LEADING IN JERSEY
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, which both parties view as a crucial electoral
battleground, Al Gore continues to hold a slight lead over George
W. Bush, according to the latest Quinnipiac University poll. The
survey (3 percentage point margin of error) shows Gore with a lead
of 46-41 percent lead in a one-on-one race. When small-party
candidates are included, Gore's lead is 42-38 over Bush, with 7
percent for Ralph Nader and 2 percent for Pat Buchanan. The survey
was taken before Bush's V.P. choice of Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   LAME DUCK MAKES PARTY SWITCH
</P>
<P>
   In his 18 years in Congress, Rep. Matthew Martinez has gone
about his job in relative obscurity. But the lame-duck Californian
became the talk of Capitol Hill as he switched from the Democrats
to the Republicans. Martinez, 71, was denied renomination in the
March Democratic primary. In the closely divided House _
Republicans now will have a seven-vote margin in the chamber _ GOP
leaders sought to play up the defection to the hilt. But House
Democrats scoffed, calling the switch nothing more than a parting
shot by a bitter lame duck.
</P>
<P>
   WHOOPS, SOME OTHER BUSINESS BEFORE LAZIO
</P>
<P>
   Not many people know Hillary Clinton has a Democratic opponent
in the New York Senate race, but he challenged the first lady to a
series of debates Wednesday. Mark McMahon, a 39-year-old Manhattan
surgeon who is largely considered a nuisance opponent by the
Clinton campaign, gathered more than enough signatures to assure
himself a spot on the ballot in the Sept. 12 Democratic primary.
McMahon said he'd be a better candidate against Republican Rick
Lazio because he doesn't ``carry any of the negative baggage that
Hillary does.''
</P>
<P>
   GET THAT CANDIDATE A GOOD MAP
</P>
<P>
   New York Senate candidate Hillary Clinton, who proudly proclaims
she has visited all 62 of the state's counties, made a wrong turn
last week when she appeared on a radio station in Erie County, Pa.
She apparently believed she was on the air in New York. ``Last
week, I was up your way talking about my upstate economic agenda,''
Clinton told her befuddled radio host during a 10-minute interview
on 1,000-watt WLKK, which is located about 20 miles from the New
York border. The signal almost reaches the state line.
</P>
<P>
   SANTA CLAUS WITH PAC MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Expanding quickly beyond his local fortresses of support in Long
Island, Rick Lazio went on something of a philanthropic binge this
month, giving a total of $72,500 on the same day to all 62
Republican county committees in the state. And for good measure, he
sent an additional $4,000 to four Conservative Party county
committees. The donations, though, didn't put a dent in Lazio's
Senate campaign treasury. The money came from an obscure state
political action committee that effectively allows him to get
around strict federal fund-raising limits.
</P>
<P>
   PAC-MAN ACCOUNTABILITY?
</P>
<P>
   Congressional supporters of a new law requiring tax-exempt
political organizations to reveal who's paying for their
campaign-style activities urged the IRS to make it also apply to
lawmakers' political action committees. The leadership PACs are all
registered with the Federal Election Commission and disclose the
contributions they receive under federal law, which can be used to
directly aid candidates. But at least a dozen lawmakers, including
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) and Rep. Patrick
Kennedy (D-R.I.), chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee, also have set up nonfederal entities _ which do not have
to report to the FEC.
</P>
<P>
   COMMON GROUND IN SAME CHURCH
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the Rev. Charles Rush in Summit, N.J., found
both U.S. Senate candidates facing each other across the aisle to
receive Communion. Jon Corzine and Rep. Bob Franks may spar with
each other day in and day out on the campaign trail, but they say
their prayers together at the end of the week. Corzine, a Democrat,
lives in Summit and has been at Christ Church, an
interdenominational mix of Baptist and United Church of Christ, for
more than 20 years. Franks, a Republican who lives the next town
over in Berkeley Heights, has been going to the church for more
than two years.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE CAUSE OF A BIG UMBRELLA
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell (R-Calif.) said he'll go to the Republican
convention to speak out on behalf of abortion rights, a position
sure to put him at odds with the convention's majority. Campbell is
facing an uphill fight to unseat Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
and California voters are heavily pro-choice. But Campbell insists
that he isn't being guided by politics. ``Truly, my purpose is to
make sure that people see the Republican Party as diverse as it
really is,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   AND IT SOUNDS JUST LIKE A FREIGHT TRAIN
</P>
<P>
   Using videotape of the violent protests during the World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle to make their point, Los Angeles
police warned downtown businesses to prepare for the worst during
the Democratic convention. Business owners should consider boarding
up glass walls and windows, hiring additional security, and
stocking up on emergency provisions like flashlights, food and
water, police suggested. ``It's almost like a tornado,'' said
Detective Darryl Butler, who has been giving up to four
presentations a day to downtown workers. ``You can see it coming,
but you don't know where it's going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   BOXER GEORGE FOREMAN NAMED HIS FIVE SONS GEORGE
</P>
<P>
   All three Georges are coming, and the rest of the Bush clan too.
The father, George Herbert Walker Bush, will be saluted as a former
president. ``I'll be there proudly,'' he said. His eldest grandson,
George Prescott Bush, is just as thrilled, though somewhat startled
over his own, newfound fame. Coming out of the sandwich generation,
George W. Bush will be nominated for president.
</P>
<P>
   AREN'T JOURNALIST USED TO LEAKS?
</P>
<P>
   Four giant pavilions that will serve as workplaces for more than
10,000 members of the media outside the First Union Center in
Philadelphia leaked all day Wednesday as more than an inch of rain
fell on the city. Water also came in where the structures' fabric
walls meet the ground. In the months leading up to the Republican
convention, organizers have insisted the structures _ made of PVC
fabric stretched across huge aluminum arches _ should not be called
tents because of their resistance to the elements. Media critics
suggested there should have been more testing.
</P>
<P>
   HAVE YOUR CREDIT CARD READY
</P>
<P>
   The QVC cable shopping channel is getting election fever. The
cable TV marketer of housewares, jewelry and exercise gear will put
on a special show from the Republican convention to hawk campaign
buttons and other mementoes. Souvenirs will range from the
inexpensive buttons to a collection of lapel pins representing all
the states and the District of Columbia, valued at more than $250.
In addition to vendors selling official souvenirs at the convention
and around the city, the GOP said it was naming QVC the official
national retailer to try to reach a wider market.
</P>
<P>
   CRACKED LIBERTY BELL, AND THEN SOME
</P>
<P>
   Each state was supposed to send a version of the Liberty Bell to
Philadelphia for the Republican convention next week. But South
Dakota's won't make the trip. ``It exploded in the kiln,'' said
potter Ken Russell of Arlington, S.D. The bell was about 2 feet
tall and 22 inches in diameter, with a grain pattern carved on it
to represent South Dakota's farmland. ``It would have been
pretty,'' Russell said glumly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
