<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      07-27 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A HOUSE DIVIDED': A PLANTATION WITH A FAMILY SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sam Waterston plays a complicated hero in ``A House Divided.''
He's a slave owner who rapes his house servant, a black teen-ager,
and then _ many years later _ hires a lawyer to make sure their
daughter isn't denied her inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   This Showtime movie is what Hollywood agents call, with deadly
reduction, an ``issue-driven narrative.'' But, thanks to a careful,
hard-nosed script and fine performances, it sidesteps many hazards
of the genre. Love for his mixed-race child doesn't suddenly
politicize the Waterston character, David Dickson, or make him
endearing, or even worse, drive him to speechmaking. His motives
for doing the right thing are selfish and dramatically interesting:
He adores his only child, wants her to have whatever he can give
her and seems determinedly oblivious to the hostility that her
black genes might arouse in the slave-owning South.
</P>
<P>
   When he discovers that Julia, the girl he raped, tried to abort
her pregnancy (graphically depicted on screen), he goes to her room
and says, ``Just go on and have that baby, and we'll all forget
about it.'' While he acknowledges he may have behaved
inappropriately (by raping her), he doesn't apologize. He simply
wants her to understand that his lust had already been converted
into parental pride, even before his daughter was born, and that
Julia shouldn't interfere with his newfound feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Waterston has to play Dickson across several decades, so he
seems a little too old to be living with his mother, as he did at
the times of his daughter's violent conception and throughout her
upbringing. But he uses his wrinkles and a mop of stringy, untamed
hair _ and his trademark perplexity _ to emphasize Dickson's
eccentricity. Dickson is far more interested in improving his farm
(experimenting with bat dung as fertilizer) than politics. He owns
slaves and supports the Confederacy during the Civil War, but isn't
cruel _ apart from the inherent cruelty of the institution and his
complicity in it.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, he keeps his relationship with Julia
businesslike. Once he discovers her skill in mathematics and sense
of logic, he gives her increasing responsibility for management of
the farm. So even after slavery ends, she remains there _ but not
there in her rightful place, as her child's mother. Her daughter
Amanda loves her _ as a servant _ but thinks her real mother died
in childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   She is able to believe this fiction because she looks white. The
filmmakers don't exactly explain how the other slaves on the farm _
who must have noticed what was happening in the big house _ didn't
spill the beans. We are only shown what happens when Amanda grows
up. These household secrets erupt to call into question her happy
childhood, and indeed, her place in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   This improbable family drama might have been imagined by
Tennessee Williams, and then who knows what would have transpired.
Instead it was inspired by, of all things, actual events as
described in a doctoral thesis, ``Woman of Color, Daughter of
Privilege,'' by Kent Anderson Leslie, and published in 1995 by the
University of Georgia Press. Leslie based much of her research on
records of the real-life trial that determined whether Amanda
America Dickson was her father's rightful heir.
</P>
<P>
   The film's director, John Kent Harrison, and its screenwriter,
Paris Qualles, have conventionally structured this psychologically
fraught drama. They use the trial as the centerpiece for their
story, which unfolds in a series of explanatory flashbacks. The
segues to the past are purely functional. ``Where did it start?''
Dickson's lawyer asks, for example, to instigate one memory trip.
The music, too, feels familiar _ sorrowful wails to let us know
that slavery was sad and evil, as if we didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   But the characterizations and acting rise above the stylistic
platitudes. Jennifer Beals conveys Amanda's hurt _ and charm and
sturdiness _ with a credible combination of hesitation and
fortitude. Tim Daly is suitably bland and earnest as Charles
Dubose, the young lawyer Dickson entrusted with the job of drafting
his will and having its provisions honored. Since the will was read
after Dickson's death in 1874, in the Reconstruction era, the issue
wasn't whether a slave could inherit property. Rather, his brother
(who wanted the land) argued that Dickson hadn't been competent
when he drafted the will. But, of course, race still was the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Dubose never existed but is a fictionalized composite of the
many lawyers who actually argued the case. He was evidently created
to represent the post-Civil War New South, where one form of
selfish interest (the protection of individual rights) supersedes
another (sentimental bigotry). The filmmakers have him hail,
appropriately, from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The film's most subtle and lovely portrait captures the alliance
_ resembling a certain kind of postsexual marital arrangement _
that develops between Dickson and Julia, who is elegantly played by
Lisa Gay Hamilton of the television series ``The Practice.'' She
convincingly portrays Julia's development from a surprisingly
innocent girl (considering her uprooted childhood, even before the
rape) to a stoical but uncompromising adult. Julia is wise, but not
annoying. You believe in her as a hurt woman who has carved herself
a dignified path through hardship.
</P>
<P>
   When Dickson is old (and Waterston's hair is gray as well as
ratty), taking account of his life and their relationship, he
describes their partnership as ``pretty good.'' The look Julia
sends him transmits every layer of text and subtext he has had to
ignore to reach that conclusion. Then she says, ``Yes, Master
David,'' because she knows there's no point in saying anything
else. It's a powerful moment, capturing a lifetime of hypocrisy,
devotion and habit.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A HOUSE DIVIDED'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Based on the book ``Woman of Color, Daughter of Privilege:
Amanda Dickson,'' by Kent Anderson Leslie. John Kent Harrison,
director; Jordan Kerner and Jon Avnet, executive producers; Beth
Colt and Sam Waterston, producers; Stephen J. Turnbull, line
producer and unit production manager; Kees Van Oostrum, director of
photography; Susan Longmire, production designer; Henk Van Eeghen,
editor; Resa McConaghy, costume designer; Phyllis Rossheim-Pierce,
co-executive producer; screenplay by Paris Qualles; music by
Lawrence Shragge.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Sam Waterston (David Dickson), Jennifer Beals (Amanda
Dickson), Lisa Gay Hamilton (Julia), Tim Daly (Charles Dubose) and
Kayla Perlmutter (Amanda at 5).
</P>
</TEXT>
