   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER _ SAN DIEGO _ Industry leaders and observers said
Thursday that a federal judge's injunction that would shut down
Napster significantly increases the chances of government
regulation of the online music industry. Surprisingly, some say
they welcome regulatory intervention. In any case, the court ruling
is little more than a temporary setback in the online entertainment
world, they say. And don't count Napster out of it just yet.
Company attorneys, backed by some of the heaviest hitters in
Silicon Valley, were preparing an appeal Thursday and are showing
no signs of turning down the noise in their camp anytime soon.
(Keefe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER-SIDE _ In the wake of the Napster meltdown, where are
fans going to get their downloads? What alternatives exist and how
busy are they today _ and how busy is Napster for that matter? What
are fans saying, doing as the court deadline looms? (Fernandez,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)STEVENS _ As expected, WestPoint
Stevens said earnings were hurt by a large restructuring charge.
The West Point sheet and towel maker reported a second-quarter loss
of $89.8 million, or $1.81 a share, compared with a profit of $19.6
million, or 34 cents a share, in the prior period. The results
included a one-time pretax charge of $168.2 million. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UTILITY-BIAS _ Lawyers file a major class action lawsuit against
Georgia Power Co. and the parent Southern Co. alleging racial
discrimination against 2,100 employees. The lawsuit , filed by the
same law firm that represented plaintiffs in the Coca-Cola case,
alleges an ``extraordinarily hostile racial environment'' at the
utility. Georgia Power's president is addressing employees this
afternoon to issue a defense against the charges. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS _ The outlook for profits has suddenly dimmed, thanks to
the Federal Reserve's year-long series of interest rate hikes. Most
economists now think the usual second-half rebound will not occur
this year, and analysts are worried that 3rd and 4th quarter profit
growth will slow. This casts a cloud over the outlook for the stock
market. (Walker, Atlarter earnings, the company also acknowledged
some service problems during the earlier part of the year _ blaming
them largely on the awkardness of merging EarthLink and MindSpring.
The company also promised more acquisitions as it grows. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COX _ Cox Communications releases its earnings. (Brister,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM _ WorldCom earnings; WorldCom considers tracking stock.
Continued speculation on merger(s) (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
