<SLUG> BC-FILM-KLUMPS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAT-ACCEPTANCE GROUP BLASTS `NUTTY PROFESSOR II: THE KLUMPS' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSE FRANCO   
 Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTANBURG, S.C. _ ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' is
expected to be a summer blockbuster when it opens in theaters
Friday. But the National Association to Advance Fat Acceptance in
Sacramento, Calif., says the film is sending the wrong message
about overweight people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deplore movies like this which continue to foster the myth
that we are all stupid, lazy and are constantly overeating,'' said
Frances White, spokeswoman for the group in San Francisco. The
group, with an estimated 3,000 members nationwide, provides
education on size-discrimination issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Klumps'' is a PG-13 rated sequel to the $270 million, 1996
box office hit ``The Nutty Professor'' starring Eddie Murphy. In
both films, Murphy portrays several overweight characters who
overeat, use foul language and are plagued with gastrointestinal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene in the new movie, the overweight Klumps go to an
all-you-can-eat restaurant and wipe out the place except for an
avocado pit. The youngest Klump, Ernie Jr., gobbles ice cream
straight from the dispenser. Then Papa Klump ends the meal by
passing gas and setting the restaurant's curtains on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Several derogatory terms for overweight people are used in the
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that this is billed as a family movie because that
means that folks will take their children to see this movie and fat
hatred will be expressed to the next generation,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the group does not advocate a boycott, it does alert
members about what it considers offensive material.
</P>
<P>
   Should people feel bad about going to the movie and having a
good laugh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you laugh at a Step-n-Fetchit movie?'' White asked,
referring to the comedy team that had negative stereotypes of black
people.
</P>
<P>
   But Connie Easler, a group leader for a Weight Watchers group in
Spartanburg, said she had no problems with the previous ``Nutty
Professor'' film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the other movie was real cute. I don't think people
get offended by portrayals of fat people. It's just part of the
movie. It's just a part of Eddie Murphy. It's just a part of
Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's defense, the 400-pound Sherman Klump is an
intelligent, caring scientist with a heart of gold. While his alter
ego, Buddy Love, is physically fit and considered attractive but is
cruel, greedy and vindictive.
</P>
<P>
   In a touching moment, the Sherman Klump character says ``I am
used to being overweight. I am used to people making fun of me. But
I never got used to being alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Sherman isn't really alone. According to the federal
Centers for Disease Control, an estimated 55 percent of the
population is overweight; 22 percent are considered obese.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Universal was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   (Jose Franco writes for The Herald-Journal, Spartanburg, S.C.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
