<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-NURSING-HOMES-FIRST-L     07-27 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-FIRST-LEDE-0728- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORT CALLED 'DISTURBING' BUT ACTION UNCERTAIN
 &HT;    First Lede
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the wake of major new findings that
understaffing in nursing homes leads to bedsores, malnutrition and
avoidable infections, lawmakers and the Clinton administration
Thursday took turns prodding each other to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study is disturbing,'' Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said
as his Special Committee on Aging examined a U.S. Health and Human
Services Department report, which concludes that 54 percent of
nursing homes fall below the minimum staffing level for safe care.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley said he wants to require that the facilities hire more
staff when Congress considers increasing their Medicaid and
Medicare reimbursements this fall. However, the senator expressed
doubts that Congress would enact federal staffing standards any
time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could do it more quickly,'' Grassley told Nancy-Ann
DeParle, head of the Health Care Financing Administration at HHS.
``Would you have that authority?''
</P>
<P>
   DeParle said she would have to check with her legal counsel on
how far her agency can go in enforcing current laws.
</P>
<P>
   Existing statutes have only a vague requirement for ``sufficient
nursing staff'' that includes requiring one full-time registered
nurse a day and round-the-clock coverage by a licensed practical
nurse at each facility.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle said her department would need more money from Congress
to begin policing the staffing levels of the nation's 16,500
nursing homes. Moreover, she said that her department was not
prepared to set minimum standards without further research
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The latest staffing study, which was first ordered by Congress
in 1990 to be completed in 1992, focused on 1,800 nursing homes in
Texas, Ohio and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The report documents the effects of low staffing and is ``the
largest and most rigorous study of the relationship between
staffing and quality of care conducted to date,'' said Andrew
Kramer, a geriatric medicine professor at the University of
Colorado, who helped conduct the research.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer told the committee that among facilities where each
resident received at least two hours of nurse's aide attention a
day, only 2 percent had a high rate of ``avoidable''
hospitalizations for ailments such as pneumonia, urinary tract
infections and dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Among homes that offer less than two hours of nursing, 22
percent had a high rate of hospitalizations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Kramer said a single national standard would not be
practical because nursing homes with sicker residents need more
staff than those where the population is relatively healthy.
</P>
<P>
   That finding was applauded by Charles H. Roadman II, head of the
American Health Care Association, the largest nursing home trade
group, who opposes any attempt to mandate what he called a ``magic
ratio'' for patients and staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly none of us are happy with pressure ulcers or falls or
dehydration or malnutrition,'' Roadman said, but he said the ``core
cause'' is the labor shortage and inadequate government
reimbursements through Medicare and Medicaid, which together
finance most nursing home costs.
</P>
<P>
   (trim line)
</P>
<P>
   Certified nursing assistants, who do most of the work of nursing
home care, receive low pay, have a high rate of turnover and often
suffer from on-the-job injuries as they move and lift patients.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these workers described to federal researchers the
conditions in nursing homes when they are short-staffed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Showers are the first things to go,'' one worker said.
``Eating is also affected. Food is put in front of sleeping
residents and taken away before it's eaten. Residents are also left
in urine and feces for a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Another worker said that residents who are supposed to get
showers two times a week ``might get one once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another: ``There is a lot of weight loss because of not
feeding residents. Dehydration. Some residents just don't eat. Some
aides take the tray in and don't even try to feed, even if it says
'feeder.' It makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that nationwide, staffing levels at nursing
homes have remained about steady from 1997-1999, averaging about
3.25 nursing hours per day for each resident. Non-profit and
government facilities had more staff hours per resident than
for-profit nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the report showed that Alaska, with 4.92 nursing hours
per resident, ranked highest. Oklahoma was lowest at 2.61.
</P>
<P>
   Staff hour ratios for other states include: 3.41 for Ohio, 3.11
for Texas, 3.10 for Georgia, 3.70 for North Carolina, 3.59 for
Florida and 3.30 for Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone can be reached by e-mail at jmalone(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
</P>
