<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-OUTCOMES-NAT     07-27 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-OUTCOMES-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PHILANTHROPIST BACKS EVIDENCE-BASED MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Anand Giridharadas  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service   WASHINGTON (July 26) - Imagine
<TEXT>
walking into the doctor's office and entering into a computer your
symptoms, prior ailments and family history. Then the doctor,
tapping information from the database you just used, prescribes a
cure that appears to have worked in thousands of similar cases.
<P>
   That is what a wealthy Miami developer and philanthropist with a
history of grandiose plans is imagining these days. And he has
entered into a unique partnership with the federal government to
get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a fifty-year-old white male with prostate cancer,
and you're told you have three options,'' said Joseph H. Kanter,
75, in an interview, ``what are you going to do? You need to know
the outcomes of those three choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanter's quest is to build a database of so-called ``outcomes
research'' and place it on the Internet. The database would track
the experiences of millions of patients - from the detection of
symptoms to the course of treatment and, ultimately, to the end
result - and combine them in a user-friendly package.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter says that package would allow doctors to make more
informed medical judgments. Rather than basing decisions on
personal anecdotes and journal articles, he argues, a doctor could
quickly call up a history of similar patients with similar
troubles, and select the treatment that seemed to serve them best.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the collective clinical experiences of millions of
people all over the world, just like you - and what worked with
them,'' Kanter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enrolls every physician permanently in an ongoing,
24-hour-a-day medical school,'' said Kanter's communications
director, Read Scott Martin.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, gathering and organizing the records of millions of
patients is a Herculean task. For one thing, in all the reams of
medical records, there is little data on the outcomes of
treatments. And even where records do exist - symptoms, diagnosis,
prescription - putting them in electronic form will be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   But Kanter is not unfamiliar with big undertakings. He began his
career in a rural Alabama general store and rose to make millions
as a builder and developer, erecting entire townships across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, he bought property in Miami, and went on to become one
of the largest landowners in South Florida, with 20,000 acres on
the Dade-Broward border. He was in banking for several years, as
chairman of the National Bank of Florida and later the Bank of
Florida. He has also produced an Oscar-winning film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love a challenge,'' he said of his new task. ``It's not our
job to finish this project. But we must start.''
</P>
<P>
   In this latest bid to transform medicine, Kanter has struck an
unusual deal with the federal government. His organization, the
Kanter Family Foundation, and the federal Agency for Healthcare
Research and Quality are jointly funding a project to design and
eventually build the world's first outcomes database.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership - known as HELP - is currently assessing what it
would take to build the system. HELP plans this year to build two
pilot models, focusing solely on breast and prostate cancer. Their
idea is to showcase the niche databases and use them as
steppingstones to build a register for all illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On October 30, HELP participants will convene for an all-day
conference in Washington, where experts and project leaders will
gather to cement a vision for the project and set a plan to move
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter acknowledges a few potential obstacles to building the
database - aside from the shear scope of it.
</P>
<P>
   The largest hurdle, he said, is to inform the public and
persuade people to volunteer their medical records. The system's
effectiveness is linked directly with the number of patients whose
records it contains.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with a detailed digest of patients' histories and
treatments available on the Internet, there may be concerns about
insurers tapping into the system to decide whether patients are
healthy enough to cover.
</P>
<P>
   But Kanter and his collaborators insist the database would be
anonymous - tracking cases, not people.
</P>
<P>
   Also, doctors might resent the system if they view it as a
fancy, new-age substitute for their judgment.
</P>
<P>
   But Kanter said doctors, who often call this type of research
``cookbook medicine,'' should embrace the technology. He said the
database would drastically improve the quality of care and reduce
the risk of malpractice claims, by giving doctors a uniform
standard to apply in cases where they are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors should resent this to the extent that a professional
resents having an encyclopedia,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Kanter, who himself has been diagnosed with prostate cancer,
pointed out that the notion of using data to make an informed
choice is not a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you buy a stock today, you can punch a button or call a
broker and get ten years of prices, dividends, earnings,'' he said.
``But you go to the doctor, and it might involve you not going back
to work or losing your leg, and you get much less information than
if you're buying a stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laurence B. Gardner, chairman of the University of Miami
department of medicine, seemed to agree. ``The new world of
medicine is going to require that there be evidence for what we
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
