   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONCORDE-CRASH _ GONESSE, France _ Investigators have fully
extracted the data from the ``black box'' recorders aboard the Air
France Concorde that crashed Tuesday, and have begun analyzing
cockpit conversations and engine readings made during the
supersonic aircraft's doomed two-minute flight, the French
government said Thursday. The government agency that investigates
aviation accidents said it was unclear how soon the information
contained on the flight data and cockpit voice records would yield
clues about what caused the crash that killed 113 when
</P>
<P>
   the Concorde slammed into a small hotel near Paris. A memorial
service has been scheduled here in Gonesse for Thursday. Meanwhile,
a French aviation engineer who serves as an official adviser to
French courts told La Croix newspaper that evidence and
observations suggest that a turbine disc in the jet engine may have
</P>
<P>
   failed. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service). Expected to
move by 4 p.m. (ET) on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-JERUSALEM _ JERUSALEM _ When low-level negotiators can't
settle a dispute, they usually ``bump it upstairs'' for a decision.
When it comes to the Holy City of Jerusalem, maybe The Man upstairs
should settle the dispute. An Israeli academic, who consults with
negotiators in the peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians,
suggests they break their deadlock by giving God sovereignty over
the holiest parts of the city. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED on the NYT Wire in both International and Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MURDER _ MEXICO CITY _ When Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo,
the Cardinal of Guadalajara, was machine-gunned to death in his car
outside the city's airport seven years ago, distraught Mexicans
wondered if their country was headed for hellish Colombia-style
violence. On Thursday, authorities here reveal the conclusions of a
years-long investigation into the shocking murder of the Cardinal,
who was riddled with bullets while wearing his vestments and
crucifix. An initial theory was that the Cardinal was a mistaken
target caught in the crossfire of two vicious international
drug-trafficking gangs, one of which is still on the FBI's most
wanted list. The current Cardinal of Guadalajara, a sharp critic of
Mexican authorities' efforts to investigate the crime, has said he
fears the cardinal was murdered in a conspiracy. (Ferriss).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by 6:30 p.m. (ET) on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANTS _ WASHINGTON _ With an eye on the potentially crucial
Hispanic vote in this fall's elections, Democratic leaders Thursday
called for passage of a bill to ease certain immigration
restrictions. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY _ When Dick Cheney came to the cloistered, good-ol' boy
world of the oil business five years ago as chief executive of
Halliburton Co., many wondered whether he could make the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   He'd spent his entire working life in Washington as either a
White House staffer, Congressman or cabinet member. It was a little
hard to see how a life inside the Beltway would play in the oil
patch of West Texas, the oil fields of the Middle East or the North
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney proved surprisingly well suited to running a global
business, those who observed him from inside and outside the
company say. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-MERGER _ WASHINGTON _ The Federal Communications Commission
meets to consider the merger of America Online Inc. and Time
Warner. The merger is opposed by companies ranging from giant
Disney to startup Tribal Voice, who say AOL/TW will be an arrogant
abuser of consumers. (Geewax, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-MERGERS _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Commerce Committee
holds a hearing on the impact that mergers and consolidations in
the airline industry might have on competition, focusing on airline
hubs, and the possibility that a single carrier could control the
overwhelming majority of flights into and out of certain airports.
(Garcia, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NURSING-HOMES _ WASHINGTON _ More than half of the nation's
nursing homes fail to meet federal standards for staffing. Lower
staffing leads to more infections, bed sores and other preventable
ailments, a researcher will testify in Senate testimony Thursday on
an extensive new national survey. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ The House is scheduled to vote late
Thursday on a bill to reduce the percentage of Social Security
benefits subject to federal income taxes. The percentage was raised
from 50 percent to 85 percent as part of the 1993 deficit-reduction
bill. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GOP-PARTIES PHILADELPHIA _ GOP stands for Grand Old Party, and
that's what Republican convention delegates and visitors are
looking forward to having before and after the sessions. (Dart, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (p) politics and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MILLER _ WASHINGTON _ Zell Miller sworn in on Thursday as
Georgia's newest senator. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JAKES-RALLY _ The Rev. T.D. Jakes opens his ``Women Thou Art
Loosed!'' conference at the Georgia Dome, part of a week-long blitz
of the city that includes the premier of a values-based play and
book-signing. We capture some of the color. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GASTRUCK-ACCIDENT _ A gasoline truck driver apparently fell
asleep at the wheel, veered into the center median, then
overcorrected, clipping a pickup before the tanker overturned,
engulfing the driver in 2,000-degree flames about 3/8 mile north of
the Yamato overpass. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _Following a consistent 52-year pattern, the
Palestinians have managed again to make the least of an
opportunity. This time, at President Clinton's Camp David
negotiations, they dodged the creation of a substantial,
internationally recognized Palestinian state with significant
authority in the Muslim quarter of Jerusalem. (Teepen, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ If it walks like pneumonia
and quacks like pneumonia, there's a good chance it is. Even though
my doctor never used the ``p'' word in describing my illness, I
know _ despite my lack of any formal training in the medical field
_ the walking pneumonia had me. (Ernest Murray is managing editor
of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ At least it's easy to come up with an excuse
for staying out of the heat and under the air-conditioning, or
curling up with a book under a back-porch ceiling fan once that
infernal sun has finally sunk below the horizon. A night-time
climate of 90 degrees with a bit of shade and some air stirring
seems fairly tolerable after a full day of 103-degree weather in
the sun. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches
Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Chase Untermeyer of Houston, a
trusted ally of both former President Bush and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, thinks Dick Cheney will be a great running mate. Cheney was
chief of staff for President Gerald Ford when Bush headed the
Central Intelligence Agency. Brent Scowcroft was national security
adviser, and Jim Baker, the undersecretary of commerce, was Ford's
campaign manager in 1976. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Judging by the rhetoric of the
times there are three major political factions in our land: the
Republicans, the Democrats and the ``not a dime's worth of
difference'' faction. As in ``not a dime's difference between the
Ds and the Rs. They're all the same.'' Red ketchup. Green ketchup.
Same condiment. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   NAPSTER _ SAN DIEGO _ Industry leaders and observers said
Thursday that a federal judge's injunction that would shut down
Napster significantly increases the chances of government
regulation of the online music industry. Surprisingly, some say
they welcome regulatory intervention. In any case, the court ruling
is little more than a temporary setback in the online entertainment
world, they say. And don't count Napster out of it just yet.
Compatution)
</P>
<P>
   UTILITY-BIAS _ Lawyers file a major class action lawsuit against
Georgia Power Co. and the parent Southern Co. alleging racial
discrimination against 2,100 employees. The lawsuit , filed by the
same law firm that represented plaintiffs in the Coca-Cola case,
alleges an ``extraordinarily hostile racial environment'' at the
utility. Georgia Power's president is addressing employees this
afternoon to issue a defense against the charges. (Quinn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS _ The outlook for profits has suddenly dimmed, thanks to
the Federal Reserve's year-long series of interest rate hikes. Most
economists now think the usual second-half rebound will not occur
this year, and analysts are worried that 3rd and 4th quarter profit
growth will slow. This casts a cloud over the outlook for the stock
market. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EARTHLINK _ EarthLink Inc. on Thursday reported booming
revenues, a shrinking loss and strong customer growth as it
continued its pursuit of America Online. In reporting its second
quarter earnings, the company also acknowledged some service
problems during the earlier part of the year _ blaming them largely
on the awkardness of merging EarthLink and MindSpring. The company
also promised more acquisitions as it grows. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COX _ Cox Communications releases its earnings. (Brister,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM _ WorldCom earnings; WorldCom considers tracking stock.
Continued speculation on merger(s) (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
