<P>
   REVIEW-CHEERLEADER _ Movie review: ``But I'm A Cheerleader.''
Grade: C- (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CHEER _ Bubbly, bouncy Megan is a red-blooded,
all-American high school cheerleader. But her parents are
distressed about her affinity for tofu and her attachment to her
Melissa Etheridge poster. And for such a little girl, she sure has
a husky voice. You don't suppose she's a . . . Megan's perplexed
parents don't ask, they just call in the staff of True Directions,
a ``gay rehab camp,'' to stage an intervention and cure her of this
lesbian thing. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHEER-PETERSON _ Long before his first script ever went before
the cameras, Brian Wayne Peterson's career was heating up. Based
solely on his spoof of gay rehabilitation camps But I'm A
Cheerleader, Variety named him one of ``10 Screenwriters to Watch''
in 1999. Now after a rocky road of production delays, a distributor
pullout and a temporary NC-17 rating, the 28-year-old gay writer
from Montana is waiting to see whether moviegoers are ready to
watch. In South Florida last month to attend a Pride FilmFest
screening, Peterson's spirits were buoyed by the reaction of the
predominantly gay audience. Still, he knows his satirical film must
attract a wider audience to succeed. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   GROSSE-POINTE_ PASADENA, Calif. _ Aaron Spelling may be 148
years old, but he still has clout in this town. ``Grosse Pointe''
is a new WB comedy that satirizes what goes on behind the scenes of
a fictitious prime-time soap. The series is an obvious shot at such
campy Spelling soaps as ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' In fact, the
``Grosse Pointe'' characters look a lot like Shannen Doherty, Jason
Priestley, Luke Perry and Tori Spelling. Ah, Tori Spelling. Aaron's
no-talent daughter. In ``Grosse Pointe,'' actress Lindsay Sloane
plays Marcy Sternfeld, a Tori look-alike who also happens to be the
producer's daughter. Aaron, however, was not amused. And he let the
network know it. Reportedly, Spelling was so upset, he ordered
Jamie Kellner, the WB's CEO, to his house. Not true. Fall TV Tour,
no art. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-NUTTY _ ``Nutty Professor 2.'' Grade: C+ (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-NUTTYPROF _ ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps.'' 2 stars.
Eddie Murphy returns in all his many Klump guises in a boon for
lovers of flatulence jokes. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-PROFESSOR _ The key to a successful movie sequel is
figuring out what made the original such a hit and repeating it.
Leave it to anthropologists to explain why bodily function jokes,
crude humor, plus some clever makeup and two handfuls of
performances by Eddie Murphy sucked $270 million out of the global
economy in 1996 with The Nutty Professor. Just be content _ or
shake your head in distress _ knowing that Murphy and compm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   OLDIES _ DAYTON, Ohio _ In the cult action movie ``Escape From
New York,'' our hero, played by Kurt Russell, finds that every time
he meets up with someone new, the character's first line is: ``I
thought you were dead.'' Well, it seems appropriate to compare one
pop cultural form with another, especially when considering musical
acts you may have thought were dead. Maybe not in the literal sense
of having left this mortal plane, but certainly in the notion that
their time in the spotlight has passed. (Simmons, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KATHIE-LEE _ Ways to keep Kathie in your life now that she won't
be on ``Regis and Kathie Lee'' anymore. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   E-BOOKS _ Here we go again with another concept that 15 years
ago wasn't even in the subconscious of mainstream society. The
assumption was that books as we've known them have always been and
would always just be...books. Not. Technology has wrapped it's
cold, sinewy fingers around the whole genre of bookreading.
Hardcover is taking on a whole other meaning that we will introduce
in this story. We'll make no vast, arguable statements about the
future success or failure of the technology; rather we will discuss
the evolution of books with a local bookclub and flip through the
advantages, disadvantages, pros, cons, eases and hassles of this
new literary tool. (Moore, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   STALKING _ Nearly 15 percent of American women say they have
been stalked at least once, in their lives, according to a new CDC
survey out Thursday. The results, which Atlanta women's rights
advocates say are startling, show that 2 percent were being stalked
at the time they were interviewed, one-third were injured as a
result of being stalked and more than half were so stressed that
their lives were disrupted for more than a month afterward. More
than four-fifths knew the person stalking them. Because two-thirds
of women were not injured, and one-third never reported the
stalking to police, traditional means of figuring out whether
violence against women is occurring (police reports, ER charts)
haven't found numbers like this, CDC says. The numbers come from a
survey of the female population of Louisiana but are broadly
applicable, CDC says. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
