<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE CHILDREN: MUTANTS? TALONS? TRYING TO THINK COMIC-BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   X-Men
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Jackman, Patrick Stewart, Ian McKellen, Anna Paquin, Famke
Janssen, James Marsden, Halle Berry, Bruce Davison
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bryan Singer
</P>
<P>
   PG-13
</P>
<P>
   105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Their strength is revealed when a little boy shreds a chain-link
fence in a Nazi camp. Mutants from the X-Men comic book. Over the
decades their numbers grow and ``sometime in the near future'' they
are upsetting ordinary people on a regular basis. We meet a few
examples. Wolverine ( Jackman) has Freddy Krueger-style talons that
spring from his knuckles. Storm ( Berry) is a walking hurricane and
electrical power plant. Rogue ( Paquin) sucks energy from human
bodies. Cyclops ( Marsden) can destroy a city block with a stare.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise they seem all-right sorts who would mind their own
business if others let them. The problem, of course, is that they
are different. Congress is turning McCarthyesque. A U.N. group
gathers on Ellis Island to address the perceived threat. Among the
mutants themselves there are two reactions. Professor Charles
Xavier (Stewart), who can read minds and affect thoughts, would try
to reason with normally endowed humans. Magneto (McKellen), a
mutant rebel and former colleague of Xavier's, would destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   While the authorities dither, these two wage a high-voltage
comic-book zap fest for control of their breed. The professor runs
a kind of prep school for talented young mutants, and from gleaming
laboratories and battle stations beneath the ivied halls he and his
proteges struggle to outwit Magneto, whose powers seem
insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Soon they all end up in a wild electrostatic battle at the
Statue of Liberty. (With those talons, Wolverine could shut down
local power company for a week.) Magneto ends up in a plastic box
but vows to return. Think there'll be a sequel?
</P>
<P>
   Violence: Behind all those sparks and lightning bolts mutants
fling one another around like basketballs and they and regular
people get a little blood-flecked. But this is supposed to be the
comics.
</P>
<P>
   Sex: None.
</P>
<P>
   Profanity: Some profane exclamations.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 3-7: A common situation for the very young: too complicated
and too loud and intense. Not that attendance would necessarily
turn into a rout or have other damaging consequences, but this
isn't their movie.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 8 and up: The clouds lift. Discretion is advised, however.
Parents know their children.
</P>
<P>
   Scary Movie
</P>
<P>
   Jon Abrahams, Carmen Electra, Anna Faris, Shannon Elizabeth,
Dave Sheridan, Marlon Wayans, Shawn Wayans, Cheri Oteri
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans
</P>
<P>
   R
</P>
<P>
   88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   To lampoon the ``Scream'' movies, Wayans' film borrows from
several other teen-age slasher shows, not to mention ``The Matrix''
and ``The Usual Suspects.'' But let's not get ahead of ourselves.
Late one night a pretty, vacant high school miss answers the
telephone and with a nervous titter indicates to the caller that
she is not quite dumb enough to tell him all about herself. He then
tells her he wants to look at her insides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scream,'' right? Remember, though, this is a spoof. On the
stove popcorn swells suggestively in its foil tent. Time for the
first blast of flatulence. On the lawn the familiar maniac in black
robe and Edvard Munch mask flashes his long knife. But this is a
killer prone to tripping on porch steps, botching garage slashings
and getting as stoned as his potential victims.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the blade he wields a gleaming cargo hook.
Actually he is the victim of a teen-age hit-and-run incident and he
wants revenge because he knows what they did. They ran him over.
``We hit a boot, but where's the foot?'' one teen-ager asks.
Finding a body they strip it of credit cards and toss it into the
harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a year later _ ``one year after, you know, we killed
that guy,'' says Cindy (Faris, stepping into the Neve Campbell
``Scream'' role). The television personality and author Gail
Hailstorm (Oteri) swoops down in an imitation of Gale Weathers from
the ``Scream'' adventures. Doofy (Sheridan) is the imbecilic
security man. There is a ``Blair Witch'' rush through the woods.
More flatulence and much bloodshed. You know, that Doofy is smarter
than he looks.
</P>
<P>
   Violence: One beheading, many stabbings and a sleet of gore.
(Where's your sense of humor?)
</P>
<P>
   Sex: The sex act is continually flaunted and discussed and
partially performed. Genitals are on view.
</P>
<P>
   Profanity: Any obscenity you've ever heard (or most).
</P>
<P>
   Footnote: On the LCD (lowest common denominator) scale, the film
rates a 9, saved from a 10 by a passing attempt at wit now and
then. Vulgarity is celebrated in all forms, from the sexual to the
intestinal, with an emphasis on bowels. Drugs are heavily in use,
and there are leaden racial jibes and stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   Under Age 14: If they haven't seen it already, resist.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 14 and Up: Unless uninterested or dissuaded, they have
definitely seen it already.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon the Movie 2000
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Ikue Otani, Veronica Taylor, Rachael Lillis,
Eric Stuart, Addie Blaustein
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kunihiko Yuyama and Michael Haigney
</P>
<P>
   G
</P>
<P>
   85 minutes
</P>
<P>
   To warm up the very little ones the presentation starts with a
short subject. The concept is ``rescue'' and involves a young
fellow who gets hung up by his backpack on a branch over a towering
waterfall. In the leafy glades below, the Pokemon (creatures
spawned by Japanese television) frolic obliviously and
unintelligibly until a few of them suddenly pop up and free the
backpacker.
</P>
<P>
   The screen goes dark, and after a good look at the Nintendo logo
we open on the main subject: a not altogether uninvolving story
about rejiggering the elements. Aboard a quite grand flying
whirligig a smug evildoer called the Collector plots to capture
three large and major Pokemon who control fire, ice and lightning.
Next he will seize the most important Pokemon, who oversees the
oceans.
</P>
<P>
   It falls to Ash, the human Pokemon trainer, and his little
yellow Pokemon pal, Pikachu, to save the environment. On
storm-tossed seas, he and his adolescent friends wreck a few
expensive powerboats and scramble around the Orange Islands in
weather conditions that, depending on which major Pokemon is in the
clutches of the Collector, vary from monsoonish to icebound. Will
pluck prevail?
</P>
<P>
   Violence: Some very mild rough and tumble.
</P>
<P>
   Sex: None.
</P>
<P>
   Profanity: Presumably none, but Pokemon babble is hard to
decipher.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 3-8: Attention may wander, but they will be entertained.
</P>
</TEXT>
