<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 28, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sizzling heat will expand across the West on Friday as a very
warm ridge of high pressure several thousand feet above the ground
intensifies. With residual moisture trapped under the sprawling
ridge, afternoon and evening thunderstorms will erupt in response
to the uneven heating of mountains and valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will erupt near a cool front stalled
over the southern Plains. Though downpours are likely in spots, the
threat of severe weather will be limited, given the lack of wind
shear in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the recent rains along the Northeast Seaboard,
low clouds will shroud much of the region this morning, but the sun
will break through the clouds over some areas. The resulting
warming, in combination with gradually rising humidity, will make
the air feel more summerlike.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: RADAR RAIN GAUGE
</P>
<P>
   While official rain gauges are many miles apart, radar can act
as a giant rain gauge blanketing a large area. When microwaves
emitted by radar encounter raindrops, the amount of energy returned
to the radar site provides an estimate of the rainfall rate. The
relationship between the reflected energy and the rainfall is a
complex one that depends in part upon the size and density of
droplets in the clouds. On Wednesday, the radar site near Boston
switched to tropical mode to provide better estimates of rainfall
from clouds streaming north from the tropical Atlantic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
