<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS SEE PERIL FOR CONSUMERS IN WAVE OF AIRLINE MERGERS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of the Senate Commerce Committee expressed
concern Thursday that mergers in the airline industry could leave
passengers facing reduced service and higher prices from a handful
of giant carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can not think of any marketplace that works better for
consumers with fewer competitors,'' warned Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., the panel's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposed merger of United Airlines, the nation's largest
carrier, with US Airways is approved, some predict that its market
power would force the creation of two other mega-carriers,
American-Northwest and Delta-Continental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional mergers in this industry will further erode airline
service to rural states, and I want the U.S. Justice Department and
the Department of Transportation to put the brakes on additional
mergers,'' said Sen. Bryon Dorgan, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Senators also said they were concerned about high ticket prices
for short trips on lesser-traveled routes. Some said they can fly
to Europe for less than they to some U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joel Klein, head of the Justice
Department's antitrust division, said this was a result of the hub
system that evolved after the deregulation of airlines in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The hub system provides more flights and a variety of routes,
but a few airlines control airport hubs and tend to drive out the
competition, Klein said. With little competition, airlines can then
charge higher fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The underserved population is due to predatory practices by
the big companies that keep low-cost carriers out of their hub,''
Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question they have predatory practices, said Sen.
Fritz Hollings, D-S.C. ``You have to immediately break up the
hubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to high ticket prices, Klein told the
senators, is that ``airlines use computer modeling techniques and
ticketing restrictions to identify passengers to whom they can
charge higher fares.''
</P>
<P>
   But only about 6 percent of flyers pay the full price of the
ticket, said Alfred Kahn, a Cornell University emeritus professor
of political economy often called the ``father of airline
deregulation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the government could not successfully regulate the industry,
said Kahn. Instead, government should provide adequate
infrastructure and make competition more effective. The shortage of
airports and inadequate air traffic control system is the basis of
the problem with today's air transportation system, Kahn added.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings and other committee members agreed that government
agencies should serve as ``caution lights'' for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Klein did not discuss the US Airways-United merger because it is
under review by his department.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
