<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NUTTY-FILM-REVIEW-2TA     07-27 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTTY-FILM-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NUTTY PROFESSOR II': TREMENDOUSLY FUNNY, IN PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Eddie Murphy. He gave the performance of a lifetime in
``The Nutty Professor,'' with the kind of professional breakthrough
that showed he had become an actor with serious chops, and yet Jim
Carrey gets all the reviews. In ``The Nutty Professor II: The
Klumps,'' Murphy again displays enough agility to show that he
deserves to be taken seriously. We probably shouldn't feel too bad
for his being overlooked; after all, the first ``Professor'' was a
big hit. And this one will be, too.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the film are tremendously funny. Every single scene in
which Murphy, hidden away under millions of dollars' worth of
transformative makeup, plays all the members of the Klump family _
all of them together in some scenes _ will knock the blues right
out of you. But some of the cheap laughs to which the picture
stoops will give you the blues. This makes ``Nutty Professor II''
half a movie at best. The broad humor at times derails Murphy's
performances, but the movie provides a vehicle for him to display
his reach.
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Nutty Professor,'' made in 1963, was an update of
``Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde'' starring Jerry Lewis as Dr. Julius
Kelp, a mega-nerd college professor crippled by his shyness. Kelp
invented a formula to unleash his inner hipster, Buddy Love. The
1996 remake starring Murphy did the same thing, with the actor
playing an overweight professor, Sherman Klump, who spent time with
his family _ mother, father, elder brother and grandmother, all
played by Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   In portraying Buddy Love, Lewis was shockingly good. He burrowed
deep to come up with a dexterous, shaped performance that was both
sublime and a murderously hostile star turn: a full-blooded parody
of his former partner, Dean Martin. Lewis' impersonation came
complete with a satyr's cosmic boredom and an ability to read
people that functioned as a dry Vegas version of Sherlock Holmesian
ratiocination. For Murphy, Buddy Love is a sketch character, with
condescension for this loud-mouthed player manque built-in. Murphy
can't play this guy straight; he's too busy scoring off Love's
loutishness.
</P>
<P>
   The main crisis is that Buddy Love still exists inside Sherman,
and he erupts from Sherman's subconscious with awful frequency.
Buddy finds a way out when Sherman withdraws the aberrant gene that
created his slim but ravenous Id; the extracted gene looks like
irradiated Windex.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, performers wearing layers of makeup strain to show
off. Murphy uses the prosthetics as a tool, as they should be used;
he has worked out all of the emotional details from the inside.
(Method actors study for years to achieve this kind of
understanding.) His Sherman Klump has reserves of modesty and
charm, with a mellow bass chuckle that radiates contentment. Murphy
could play the character for cheap pathos _ the sad, heavy-set
clown who demands sympathy _ but he doesn't. Instead, Sherman is a
man who has settled into his place in the world; he has got a
jaunty, graceful gait for such a big man. It's his infatuations
that get him into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the first ``Professor,'' Jada Pinkett got his pheromones
going. This time it's Janet Jackson, and the biggest special effect
in the movie is her playing a genetics scientist. The names of the
chemical compounds don't come trippingly off her tongue; it's as if
they trip off her tongue. ``The Klumps'' screeches to a halt a
number of times as we get lengthy scientific explanations, leaving
skid marks and unintended comedy. And there's a lot to explain.
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   There's also straight-talking, libidinous Grandma, who brings
down the house; some of her material is unbelievably crude and
shocks a laugh out of you. She's clearly based on the gruff, dirty
comedian Moms Mabley, and her behavior shows where Buddy Love comes
from, especially when the two meet and she sizes him up like a
prime cut. Even he is put off by her audacity. ``You look just like
Ken Norton in that movie `Mandingo,''' she says, running her tongue
across her gums.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also has enough toilet humor to show that Murphy can
compete with Carrey and the Farrelly brothers. There are flatulence
flambe and projectile pellets from a giant hamster, among other
touches.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough for ``The Klumps'' to work as well as its predecessor
because there is no novelty left in Murphy's prodigious multiple
performances. (In addition, some of the characters sound similar to
Murphy's voice-over as the gruff super on the Claymation series
``The PJ's'' on Fox.) Still, he shows the discordant nimbleness of
Thelonious Monk, the brilliant jazz pianist whose hands found chord
voicings so distinctive it was as if each had a mind of its own.
How else could Murphy keep all these characters straight and still
riff in the way he does? The essentials are all worked out, and a
scene in which the Klumps gather around the television set to watch
Sherman at a news conference is a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Tribute should be paid, too, to the makeup artist, Rick Baker,
who won an Oscar for the first Murphy ``Professor.'' Care has been
taken to make all the Klump men look like family; their heads are
the same shape and the plain-spoken father, Cletus, and Sherman's
brother, Ernie, are balding. Sherman has all his hair, perhaps
because he is closer in looks and temperament to his big-hearted
mother. But each of the characters has an individual and
well-defined mouth. The differentiations in Baker's workmanship
almost deserve their own movie.
</P>
<P>
   The Farrellys have been applauded for the genius
African-American triplets in ``Me, Myself and Irene,'' hip-hop
gunslingers who have filtered the chaos theory through Chris Rock
and Richard Pryor. But it's Murphy who has made the daring move:
the large, courtly Sherman Klump, with his countrified enunciation
and courtly manner _ the kind of black man who would probably be
taken for a preacher, like many other African-Americans in suits _
is a prodigy, a man who takes pride and refuge in his understanding
of science. It's subversive on a level that many African-Americans
will know, and love.
</P>
<P>
   `NUTTY PROFESSOR II'
</P>
<P>
   The Klumps
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Peter Segal; written by Barry W. Blaustein, David
Sheffield, Paul Weitz and Chris Weitz, based on a story by Steve
Oedekerk, Blaustein and Sheffield; director of photography, Dean
Semler; edited by William Kerr; music by David Newman; production
designer, William Elliott; produced by Brian Grazer; released by
Universal Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Eddie Murphy (Sherman Klump, Buddy Love, Granny Klump,
Mama Klump, Papa Klump, Young Papa Klump and Ernie Klump), Janet
Jackson (Denise Gaines), Larry Miller (Dean Richmond) and John Ales
(Jason). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutty Professor II'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes plentiful toilet humor and broad sexual
jokes.
</P>
