<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-MAZE-BOS &LR;      07-27 1473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-MAZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RELEASE OF SOME MAZE PRISONERS VIEWED WITH CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAZE, Northern Ireland _ Bobby Sands died here, starving himself
to death. Billy Wright, the loyalist assassin, died here, too,
gunned down by Irish republican enemies who somehow smuggled a gun
into the most secure prison in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1970s and 1980s, the sprawling Maze prison
outside Belfast was the cauldron in which Northern Ireland boiled.
Prisoners demanded political status and refused to wear prison
clothes, wrapping themselves in blankets and smearing their cells
with excrement.
</P>
<P>
   When those protests failed, the hunger strikes began in 1981.
Sands and nine other republican prisoners fasted to the death in an
extraordinary show of defiance.
</P>
<P>
   But by the early 1990s, after the British government acceded to
the demands for which the hunger strikers died, the prison went
from being part of the problem to part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Using their cellblocks as a forum for debate, Irish Republican
Army prisoners and their loyalist counterparts threw their
intellectual weight behind the 1994 cease-fires and the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   And so by Friday, the Maze will become what few ever believed
possible: virtually empty.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, only about 15 political prisoners will remain in
Northern Ireland, a place that produced more of them per capita
than any place in the world over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the last of some 400 paramilitary prisoners, a
cornerstone of the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, is aimed at
making Northern Ireland a safer place in the long run, as it is
meant to cement the cease-fires that the major paramilitary groups,
with some murderous exceptions, have been observing since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Freeing some of these prisoners has made Northern Ireland a more
dangerous place in the short run, according to British and Irish
security sources. It has also tested the willingness of people to
swallow the disgust of watching some of Northern Ireland's most
ruthless, remorseless killers walk free.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Protestant loyalist extremists who are among the
last released will inevitably be caught up in an internecine feud
in which loyalists have been killing each other as one group tries
to keep a minority of hardliners from breaking the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   On the republican side, it is also inevitable, according to
security sources, that some IRA and republican splinter group
prisoners, especially those who have served relatively short
sentences, will drift in with dissidents trying to wreck the peace
process by placing bombs in Northern Ireland and London.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hope for the future is that an empty Maze prison will
undermine the cult of victimhood which runs deep in both the
Catholic nationalist and Protestant unionist communities.
</P>
<P>
   While this week is a momentous one in Northern Ireland's
tortuous road to peace, it is one of outrage for people like
Michelle Williamson and Sally McErlean.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, whose parents were killed with seven other
Protestant civilians by a botched IRA bombing meant for loyalist
paramilitary leaders in 1993, tried futilely in the courts to keep
the IRA bomber, Sean Kelly, from walking free this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British government has given in to the terrorists,'' a
disconsolate Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   McErlean's son Thomas was slain in 1988 as he tried to stop
loyalist assassin Michael Stone from shooting and throwing grenades
at Catholic mourners at the funerals of three IRA guerrillas gunned
down by British commandos in Gibraltar. McErlean said seeing Stone
walk free Monday to a hero's welcome ``made me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   But others did not even get the limited satisfaction of knowing
their loved one's killer spent time behind bars. Jim McCabe's wife,
Nora, was killed in 1981 by a plastic bullet fired by a police
officer who was never charged. The Royal Ulster Constabulary and
the British army used plastic bullets against civilians, mostly
Catholics, while their use was outlawed in the rest of the United
Kingdom. Of the 17 people killed by plastic and rubber bullets,
nine were under age 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say they are outraged watching these men leave prison.
They at least had the luxury of seeing these people brought before
a court and face justice. I never had that luxury,'' said Jim
McCabe, who was left with three children under age 6 after his wife
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 400 people were killed by the security forces in Northern
Ireland, and only four cases resulted in convictions against
British soldiers and police. All of the security force members were
subsequently released after brief incarcerations, and the soldiers
were allowed to rejoin their regiments.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last 30 years, the prison near Lisburn was both
a cause and a byproduct of the Troubles, as the Irish in their
penchant for understatement call the political and sectarian
conflict that has killed more than 3,500 in a place the size of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The prison also underscored how Protestant loyalists, who fought
so that Northern Ireland would remain part of the United Kingdom,
and Irish republicans, who fought for unity with the Irish Republic
to the south, hold polar opposite views.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans still refer to the prison as Long Kesh, the original
detention camp where they were sent in the early days of the
Troubles, especially after internment, a disastrous British policy
aimed at stamping out the IRA. Because so many innocent Catholics
were caught in the dragnet, internment radicalized a whole
generation of nationalists, ensuring the IRA a steady stream of
recruits.
</P>
<P>
   For republicans, especially, prison was a political education,
``just another part of the struggle,'' according to Gerry Adams,
the leader of Sinn Fein, which is allied with the IRA. Adams, an
IRA commander in the early 1970s, was held without charge like
hundreds of other nationalists during the failed policy of
internment. And like hundreds of other young IRA volunteers, Adams
became radically politicized in prison, where IRA prisoners read
Mao and debated how they could persuade the Irish people to embrace
their vision of a 32-county socialist republic.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalists, meanwhile, were disillusioned by being imprisoned by
the very government to which they swore loyalty. But eventually
they, too, used prison to see their crimes, and their future, in
political terms.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hutchinson, jailed for killing two Catholics, came to
believe that he and a generation of young Protestants had been used
as cannon fodder by fundamentalists such as the Rev. Ian Paisley,
who whipped up anti-Catholic sentiment, ``but considered us scum
when young loyalists followed Paisley's rhetoric to its inevitable
conclusion and killed Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson came out of prison determined to improve the lives of
working-class Protestants and Catholics, who bore the brunt of the
suffering during the Troubles. Upon his release from prison, he
worked with Pat McGeown, a former IRA prisoner who nearly died on
hunger strike. When McGeown eventually died from complications
related to his fast, Hutchinson publicly praised him as ``a good
man,'' an unprecedented tribute from a loyalist to a republican.
</P>
<P>
   While most like Hutchinson and McGeown came out of prison better
educated, and few were sent back after doing their ``whack,'' as
they call prison time here, there is also the cautionary tale of
Billy Giles, who found that while prisoners could leave the Maze,
walking through its creaky metal turnstiles, some could never fully
escape the demons sharing their cells.
</P>
<P>
   When a Globe reporter toured the loyalist wings of the Maze in
1991, Giles was commanding the fellow Ulster Volunteer Force
prisoners. He proudly pointed out the differences between his men
and the IRA men on the other side of the H-blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stress individualism,'' Giles said. ``The IRA force their
men to live in a socialist collective.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1998, after Giles had been freed, this reporter bumped
into him at a prisoners' rehabilitation center in East Belfast.
Over coffee, he talked of how he had never gotten over murdering
Michael Fay in 1982. Fay was an innocent Catholic, on his way to
visit his daughter in the hospital, when he was abducted and killed
by Giles and a loyalist gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a man,'' Giles said, tears brimming but never
quite falling from his eyes. ``He was just a man with a wee family
and we killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Billy Giles hanged himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a victim, too,'' he wrote in the note he left behind.
``Please let our next generation live normal lives, tell them of
our mistakes and admit to them our regrets. I've decided to bring
this to an end now. I'm tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
