<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-27 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A CLEAR CHOICE NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush's selection of a doctrinaire
ultraconservative as his running mate may alleviate one campaign
problem: voter apathy born of a feeling that there isn't much
difference between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Bush has dropped his cloak of moderation to identify
firmly with the right wing, Vice President Al Gore is free to
respond in reverse. He let it be known he is looking seriously at
potential veeps from his party's left wing. The names of three
undeniably liberal Democrats immediately popped up: Massachusetts
Sen. John Kerry, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt and Iowa
Sen. Tom Harkin.
</P>
<P>
   Moderation in all things, including politics, is customarily a
wise course. But it also confuses voters accustomed to the clang
and bang of sharp-edged partisan warfare. Elections are all about
choosing between two philosophies of governing. To make the right
choice, voters need information, not soft soap.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Pew Research Center poll suggested that voter turnout
this fall may be even lower than in 1996, when only 49 percent of
eligible citizens cast ballots. The biggest reasons: boredom and
cynicism about politics and a sense that it doesn't matter much who
is elected president anyway. Thirty-three percent of those surveyed
said Bush and Gore hold similar positions.
</P>
<P>
   The two have nobody to blame but themselves for this sorry state
of affairs. They both have been trying to appeal to independent and
moderate voters by softening the ideological outlines, speaking in
soothing generalities meant to reach beyond their party base and
their core beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   On important issues, Bush is actually more vague than Gore, but
Gore is no paragon of clarity either.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew poll, however, indicated that this muddled picture was
beginning to shift even before Bush selected Dick Cheney as his
running mate. The public impression of Bush's ideology, once
equally divided between moderate and conservative, was already
tilting toward conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was seen as becoming more moderate and less liberal.
This image would certainly shift to the left, solidifying the
contrast with Bush, if Gore picks a liberal running mate.
</P>
<P>
   It is still early. The two conventions and first national
impressions of the veeps-in-waiting should stimulate fresh interest
and reshape some issues. The Pew survey reported that the
presidential race is still wide open, subject to changing voter
opinions as the campaign wears on. There was no such voter
flexibility four years ago. President Clinton held a consistent
lead over Dole in the post-primary surveys, and nothing Dole could
do changed it.
</P>
<P>
   It is fair to ask if Bush is really as far to the right as the
opinions reflected in Cheney's congressional voting record from
1979 to 1989. After all, papa George Bush abandoned some
firmly-held positions, most notably opposition to supply-side
economics and support of abortion rights, when he joined Ronald
Reagan on the 1980 GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush the younger in effect answered yes to the question. ``I
obviously thought about the (Cheney) record,'' he said. ``This is a
conservative man. So am I.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's voting record, however, is not just conservative. It
wears high-button shoes and squeaks when it walks. ``I'm proud of
it,'' he said after Bush named him.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney consistently voted against abortion rights, with no
exceptions for the life or health of the mother; against all
gun-control legislation, even a bill to outlaw cop-killer bullets;
against funds for Head Start and federal aid to college students;
against the continued existence of the Department of Education;
against strengthening laws banning discrimination in housing;
against extending the clean water act. There's more, but you get
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   On all those issues, Gore was on the opposite side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there can be absolutely no doubt when the American people
go to the polls this November they will be choosing between two
very different visions for our future,'' Gore declared. If his own
running mate is one of the three liberals whose names now seem to
top his list, the present ideological ravine that separates the
presidential tickets will look like a canyon. There's a difference,
all right.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was voting on these issues a decade ago. Since then he
has been a prosperous corporate executive, his views still
conservative and pro-business but held privately. He promptly
indicated he might have second thoughts today about some of those
votes, cast during a period of federal deficits rather than an era
of Treasury surplus.
</P>
<P>
   But his heart was clearly with big defense spending and not with
support for domestic programs like education, environmental
protection or social justice. The ``compassionate'' element in
conservatism that Bush claimed to want is missing. And hearts and
minds are hard to change.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
