<HEADER>
A4874 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-CHEER0728-COX     07-27 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CHEER0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    But `Cheerleader' comedy is too obvious
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bubbly, bouncy Megan is a red-blooded,
all-American high school cheerleader. But her parents are
distressed about her affinity for tofu and her attachment to her
Melissa Etheridge poster. And for such a little girl, she sure has
a husky voice. You don't suppose she's a . . .
</P>
<P>
   Megan's perplexed parents don't ask, they just call in the staff
of True Directions, a ``gay rehab camp,'' to stage an intervention
and cure her of this lesbian thing.
</P>
<P>
   As Megan, Natasha Lyonne (''American Pie'') is as surprised as
anyone to learn of her sexual orientation. Sure, whenever her
boyfriend stuck his tongue in her mouth, her mind would
distractedly wander to the torsos of her cheerleading colleagues.
But maybe he's just not a very good kisser, she figured.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of Jamie Babbit's feature debut, ``But I'm A
Cheerleader,'' is considerably better than its execution. It goes
about its pastel-colored satire so toothlessly that audiences will
probably be way ahead of the joke. In its playful way, it traffics
in homosexual stereotypes, showing how society has defined gay
orientations for its own convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Babbit both mocks such stereotyping and wallows in it, an
indulgence she justifies because her movie eventually will come
down squarely in favor of romance in all its permutations. Since
the hypocrisy and wrong-headedness of True Directions is a given as
soon as we get a look at the camp's Chanel-suited, sadistic,
right-wing head mistress, Mary Brown (Cathy Moriarty, giving every
indication of being a transvestite herself), the picture takes an
awfully long time arriving at its pro-gay message. Sexual politics
clearly take precedence over comedy here, but the film remains an
amiable fable for our times.
</P>
<P>
   Surely production designer Rachel Kamerman had fun decorating
True Directions headquarters, with its behavior modification color
scheme _ bubble-gum pink for the girls' quarters and baby blue for
the guys. The deprogramming process is patterned after the
confessionals of Alcoholics Anonymous, plus some positive
reinforcement _ vacuum cleaning classes for her, wood chopping
lessons for him.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, it dawns on Megan that her parents' suspicions were
well-founded, a realization hastened by encountering sullen, bad
girl Graham (Clea DuVall, in a comic variation of her ``Girl,
Interrupted'' role). Despite the best efforts of the program, love
blooms and their sexual bent prevails, leading to a last minute
rescue of Graham, an intervention by Megan that brings to mind the
fade-out of ``The Graduate. ``
</P>
<P>
   Lyonne and DuVall play their parts straight, if you'll pardon
the expression, while the rest of the eclectic cast winks its way
through the movie. Surely Moriarty must have had Faye Dunaway as
Joan Crawford in ``Mommie Dearest'' in mind as she butches it up.
</P>
<P>
   As Mike, the ``ex-gay'' camp counselor for the guys, RuPaul
Charles appears in a rare macho role, but still infuses the
proceedings with camp. While they don't have much to do after the
opening scenes, ``Harold and Maude's'' Bud Cort and John Waters
favorite Mink Stole add a refreshingly offbeat touch as Megan's
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The exaggerated reality of a Waters movie wafts throughout ``But
I'm A Cheerleader,'' but it it would have been more effective had
Brian Wayne Peterson's screenplay gone further out on a satirical
limb.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has an elbow-nudging, self-congratulatory tone that
makes its comedy more obvious than necessary. The movie amuses,
without leaving us something to truly cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
