u a BC-SMOKING-GUN-NYTR &LR;      07-27 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-GUN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERESTING ARTIFACTS TO BE FOUND ON SMOKING GUN WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK HUGHES COBB   
 Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging by the box office, pretty much everyone rushed out to
see the movie ``Titanic.'' Believe it or not, there's more to the
story of the 1912 tragedy, and some of the more interesting
artifacts can be found on The Smoking Gun Web site.
</P>
<P>
   You can see actual SOS telegrams, printed in mimeograph purple
so ripe you can almost smell it, dashed from the doomed ship:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have struck iceberg sinking fast come to our assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Another follows:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sinking fast passengers being put into boats.''
</P>
<P>
   Those blunt words still send a chill through Danny Green, an
editor and co-founder of The Smoking Gun.
</P>
<P>
   Also featured are various true-crime quirks, ramblings from J.
Edgar Hoover and a hand-scrawled missive from Elvis Presley to
Richard Nixon requesting an audience to discuss the drug, hippie
and communist threats.
</P>
<P>
   The site _ www.thesmokinggun.com _ also has lighter fare
highlighting the absurdities of modern life, such as the Victoria's
Secret dress code booklet (store employees better be big on black)
and vintage whines of the American celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Curious about Jim Morrison's somewhat sober testimony from his
Florida obscenity trial? Interested in the lush lives of former
love bunnies Kirstie Alley and Parker Stevenson, divvying up goods
in an ugly divorce? Need proof that Billy Bob Thornton and Angelina
Jolie are indeed legally wed?
</P>
<P>
   It's all the news they can fit on a server.
</P>
<P>
   Green and co-founder Bill Bastone, both writers and
investigative reporters in New York City, kept stumbling across
``cool and interesting'' documents from courtrooms, law enforcement
agencies and elsewhere. Words this good cry out to be shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the New Yorker didn't have the space to print a three-page
FBI file,'' Green said. ``And some of it was not what some would
deem newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   So back in 1996 they began investigating Internet capabilities.
After about a year of study, they went online with The Smoking Gun.
Response was immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 36 hours of getting things up, we were getting e-mails
from Japan,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist, ``it's not like you get flooded with letters
about every story you write. In my whole career, I've gotten maybe
two dozen letters. But all of a sudden we were getting 20 to 30
e-mails a day, saying we love your site, we hate your site, why
don't you look into this case? It was really a thrilling thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom of Information Act is their friend _ and weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to write one Freedom of Information Act request a
day,'' said Green, although the site's only a part-time occupation
for the co-editors at present.
</P>
<P>
   Readers also leak documents, such as the Victoria's Secret dress
code, which raised a fuss after it went up on the site this summer.
The lacy lawyers came out gunning.
</P>
<P>
   The rather stringent code insists employees wear ``predominantly
(95 percent) black'' while covering all that skin: hosiery a must,
and bare bellies, backs and shoulders a no-no, ironic in a store
selling skimpy underwear.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of columnists, including famed gossip Liz Smith, took
note of the Secret-Gun ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is Victoria's Secret thought we were some kind of
rinky-dink site, and we'd cave easily and take it down,'' Green
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position remains: If Tyra Banks wants to call me, I'll
talk, but until then, it stays up. And she hasn't called,'' Green
said, referring to the lingerie model.
</P>
<P>
   Green and Bastone stand on the doctrine of fair use _
established by The New York Times' legal battle to publish the
Pentagon Papers _ which protects the use of newsworthy information.
</P>
<P>
   The Smoking Gun helped crack a TV farce back in February, by
publishing a judge's restraining order against Rick Rockwell, the
titular dude of the much-hyped Fox TV special ``Who Wants to Marry
a Multi-Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the genesis of a big story,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, scrupulous attention to detail reveals fun facts.
Basketball star Shaquille O'Neal sued a custom car plant for not
delivering his specialized Mercedes. In the paperwork, among
details of a $10,000 stereo and initialized grill work were orders
for a ``secret compartment'' in the car, which only O'Neal would be
able to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assumed it was for, of course, his championship rings,''
Green laughed.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the archive gives some impression of the whimsical,
tabloid-like style and dizzying breadth of the document collection:
</P>
<P>
   _ I See Dead People _ Being Groped (about perverted shenanigans
in a funeral home)
</P>
<P>
   _ Backed Into a Coroner (autopsies and death certificates of
famous people _ Elvis, JFK, Malcolm X, Frank Sinatra, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   _ The Unabomber Quiz (test your sanity the way the courts tested
Ted Kaczynski's)
</P>
<P>
   Because of low overhead _ two employees, with main expenses
being copying, mailing and phoning _ the site is paying for itself.
Sales of T-shirts and other paraphernalia, along with banner ads,
account for much of the revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no fat in our organization,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Green works three days a week at another site, and Bastone
continues to report for other publications. But the future looks
bright: They've just signed a two-book deal with Little, Brown for
further Smoking Gun adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our first chance to really move towards making a very
good profit,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of potential Web site mergers are in the offing, which
might change The Smoking Gun to a full-time proposition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to be putting new stuff on five or six days a week.
There's plenty of stuff out there.''
</P>
<P>
   (The News in Tuscaloosa, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
