<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4876 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-HNS &LR;      07-27 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH-CHENEY WILL COURT FIVE SWING STATES EN ROUTE TO
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Republican partners George W. Bush and Dick
Cheney made plans Thursday to campaign in five swing states as they
travel to the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. All
five states _ Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio and West Virginia
_ have rejected Republican presidential candidates in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he and his freshly-minted running mate ``are excited
about the tour and the opportunity to spread my message of
improving schools, cutting taxes, preserving Social Security and
strengthening our national defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush broke away from preparations for his pre-convention march
to Philadelphia to conduct a dress rehearsal of his scheduled
acceptance address on Aug. 3 in the comfortable surroundings of the
Texas governor's mansion that he has called home since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cheney continued to defend his conservative voting
record as a Wyoming congressman during 10 years in Congress that
ended in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In a round of television interviews, Cheney responded to
criticism from Democrats that he had opposed the Equal Rights
Amendment, fought legislation to outlaw plastic handguns favored by
terrorists to evade airport security, opposed legislation to ban
so-called ``cop killer'' bullets capable of penetrating body armor
and had opposed U.S. sanctions against the white racist regime
governing South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I came from a conservative state and did, in fact,
vote that way,'' Cheney said. ``But I don't have any apologies to
make for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney worked in Dallas on Thursday, wrapping up his affairs as
the multimillionaire chief executive of Halliburton, a worldwide
oil-services conglomerate where Cheney worked for the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's campaign spokeswoman, joined in Cheney's
defensive efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney ``cast thousands of votes in his career'' in Congress,''
she said, adding ``If Al Gore wants to talk about each one _ let
him.'' Hughes noted that Gore, as a senator from Tennessee, had
voted in the Senate to confirm Cheney as defense secretary in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney scoffed at Democrats' criticism of his voting record.
</P>
<P>
   ``So whatever the Democrats want to say about me now, the fact
of the matter was many Democrats, as well as all of the
Republicans, thought I was a reasonably respectable fellow in the
1980s,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign pressed its effort to define Cheney in the
eyes of voters before the Bush-Cheney ticket could gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a deputy campaign manager for Gore, called Cheney
``a card-carrying member of the `old guard,''' adding: ``Some of
his past votes are hard to explain away in any era.''
</P>
<P>
   Fabiani, who helped handle public relations for President
Clinton during his impeachment struggle, said the Gore campaign
would ``keep the focus on what Cheney's selection says about Bush's
decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   The five states being visited by the Republicans en route to the
convention, plus Pennsylvania where the convention is located,
offer 74 of the 270 electoral votes that a presidential candidate
needs to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six states last voted for a Republican presidential
candidate in 1988; West Virginia last went Republican in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney planned to travel with Bush to Arkansas and Missouri
before returning to Dallas on Saturday to prepare for his
convention appearance on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In his interviews, Cheney explained that his opposition to the
ERA had stemmed from concern that the constitutional amendment
would require that women be drafted into the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   Women in the armed forces currently are permitted to serve in
near-combat positions but not in front-line ground assault units.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said on CBS News' ``The Early Show'' that he ``didn't
think that (drafting women) was a very good idea'' and had tried to
revise the proposed amendment to stipulate that women need not be
drafted. But Cheney, who oversaw the deeper integration of women
into near-combat positions during his four years as defense
secretary, said the House rules at the time would not permit such
revisions and so he voted against the ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney told ABC News' ``Good Morning America'' that he joined
only three other House members in 1988 to vote against a ban on
plastic guns and a ban on body armor-piercing bullets because he
remains ``a great believer'' in protecting Americans'
constitutional right to ``keep and bear arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney added: ``The solution to our gun problems really lies in
enforcing existing regulations and laws that prohibit felons, for
example, from owning guns, rather than imposing new requirements on
law-abiding citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney lambasted suggestions by critics that his vote against
imposing economic sanctions on the white racist regime of South
Africa signaled opposition to freeing Nelson Mandela, the jailed
African National Congress black nationalist. Mandela was freed in
1990 and went on to lead South Africa's black majority to a largely
peaceful takeover of the nation's government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This notion that somehow I was opposed to freeing Nelson
Mandela is a typical distortion by Al Gore,'' Cheney told NBC News'
``Today'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney signaled during his maiden campaign trip with Bush to
Wyoming on Wednesday that many of his conservative votes in the
1980s as a member of the House GOP leadership stemmed from concern
over soaring federal budget deficits. Cheney said he was
``generally proud'' of his voting record but added: ``I'm sure if I
were to go back and look at the individual votes, I could probably
find some that I might tweak and do a bit differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney asked voters to look at his voting decisions ``based upon
the time at which they occurred,'' adding: ``I'm happy to talk
about basic fundamental principles; I think those have been
generally consistent over time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, best known for helping to orchestrate the U.S.-led
ouster of Iraqi occupation forces from Kuwait during the Persian
Gulf War in 1991, defended his conduct as defense secretary when he
took part in two GOP fund-raisers at the Pentagon. Donors received
policy briefings at the Pentagon from top officials, including
Cheney. ``That's a far cry from the abuses we have seen out of the
Clinton-Gore administration _ White House coffees and selling the
Lincoln bedroom,'' said Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also tried to allay any concerns about his personal
health, after suffering three heart attacks in the 1980s and
undergoing quadruple bypass surgery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he was in fine health. ``I mean, the fact of the
matter is, I wouldn't have taken on this assignment if the doctors
hadn't signed off on it and approved it,'' Cheney said on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
