<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ADS-POPCULTURE-1100(2     07-27 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADS-POPCULTURE-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERICALS AREN'T JUST SELLING PRODUCTS; THEY'RE INFLUENCING POP
CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wayans brothers' hit comedy ``Scary Movie'' wields a big
parodic scythe, slicing through such targets as ``Scream,'' ``The
Sixth Sense'' and ``The Matrix.'' Those were all box-office hits,
movies that had comic bull's eyes painted on them _ and to the
Wayanses, mocking is the sincerest form of flattery.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Scary Movie'' also spoofs a much briefer form of
entertainment. Actually, it lampoons a sales tool: Budweiser's
``Whassup!'' TV commercials, which feature a bunch of
couch-sitting, phone-talking friends ``Watchin' the game, havin' a
Bud.'' ``Scary Movie'' isn't the only summer film to riff on the ad
campaign; the previews for ``The Adventures of Rocky and
Bullwinkle'' featured the lovable moose saying ``Whassup!?'' as
well. In fact, a brief article in the July 21 issue of
Entertainment Weekly notes that the commercial campaign has
inspired at least a half-dozen other parodies, including ones
featuring the Super Friends, the ``South Park'' characters, and a
briefly circulated one with Elian Gonzalez and Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even need to have seen the original commercial to know
whassup with that. The ads, which debuted during this year's Super
Bowl, created a catchphrase that has proved so ubiquitous, you're
probably weary of the clown at the next cubicle opening his mouth
as wide as he can and bleating the words. And it's only one example
of an ad that's filtered out to become a bigger part of the
entertainment world _ and everyday life. But not everyone goes
around quoting, say, Mountain Dew commercials, and it's not always
easy to define the quality that makes an ad outgrow its humble
beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really got to do with whether it hits a chord
with consumers,'' says Peter Beckman, founder and chief executive
officer of AdCritic.com, a Web site that displays TV commercials _
including the original ``Whassup'' ad, as well as its spinoffs and
several parodies. ``It's something that can be used in everyday
life, like (Wendy's) `Where's the beef' was in the '80s. I actually
had a teacher write on one of my papers, `Where's the beef?''' Not
to mention that Walter Mondale co-opted it for his 1984 campaign
for the Democratic presidential nomination, and that the slogan
remains so memorable, everyone contacted for this story mentioned
it.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to influential ads than catchphrases. The Gap's
``Khakis swing'' ads, which first appeared in 1998, helped expand
an incipient swing movement (and unlike that short-lived movement,
the ads learned to adapt). Volkswagen's series of music-accompanied
spots have boosted the sales of such cult artists as Trio, Nick
Drake and Spiritualized. MasterCard's ``For everything else,
there's MasterCard'' campaign has been spoofed on ``Saturday Night
Live,'' imitated in a ``Will &AMP; Grace'' promo, and borrowed for an
amusing promo for ``The Tom and Steve Show'' on Fort Worth's
KTCU/88.7 FM. The just-canned ``Yo quiero Taco Bell'' Chihuahua
also inspired an Elian Gonzalez ``drop the chalupa'' parody, as
well as a ``Yo quiero Pachelbel'' billboard for Dallas
classical-music station WRR/101.1 FM.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see these commercials,'' says Bob Garfield, ad
critic for Advertising Age, putting it simply. ``That's the answer.
A lot of people see them. So if it's the music of Nick Drake that
gets people's attention 30 years after he died, or if it's the
swing movement moving into the mainstream, or if it's a talking dog
that people think is just so darn cute, the answer is the same: If
you show the same images enough times, something's going to
click.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a recent phenomenon _ AdCritic's Beckman reminds us
that Coca-Cola's ``I'd Like To Teach the World To Sing'' spun off a
hit song in the early '70s, and anyone who was a kid in the late
'60s probably mouthed Alka-Seltzer's ``I can't believe I ate the
whole thing'' slogan at least once _ but our media-drenched world
makes commercials' influence on what we say, listen to and watch
seem even more powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is important,'' says Justin Reardon, art director
for DDB Chicago, the ``Whassup'' ad agency. ``Think of `Where's the
beef?' Imagine if the Internet was around back then.'' Or, he
suggests, imagine if the World Wide Web weren't around now. The
``Whassup'' ads and parodies might not be nearly as popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first parody, the Super Friends, wouldn't have had any
impact if it weren't for the Internet,'' he says. ``There's a
snowball effect. People see it online and think, `That's funny,
maybe I could do one of my own.' And then the entertainment
industry sees those, and realizes that it can do its own parodies.
I think the Internet has had a huge impact on this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also affected the campaign is that, in a way, anyone can
do it. Reardon says that not only has he heard radio ``Whassup''
contests, but thanks to the Web, he has heard the spot imitated in
Europe. In advertising, simplicity can be powerful, and Reardon's
not the only person to point that out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracts parodies and spoofs are ads with a very, very
identifiable creative template,'' says Nat Puccio, creative
director for New York-based ad agency McCaan Erickson, which
created the MasterCard campaign. ``It has to be very simple, so it
can be repeated over and over, almost the way telling a great joke
is repeated over and over. Great comedians have a template for
their jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   All the ads mentioned here have that trait _ in fact, except for
the MasterCard campaign, they're so simple that they hardly have
any words. Although Volkswagen's ads occasionally contain dialogue,
more often they're just music and cars _ and sometimes, the car
isn't even moving. Many of the ``Whassup'' parodies simply place
someone else in the same positions as the original ad, and have
them mouth the same words. For the past couple of years, the Gap's
campaign has either featured production numbers or young
Gap-dressed people singing baby-boom era pop songs.
</P>
<P>
   Puccio and Reardon both say that the simplicity not only helps
keep the ads in people's minds, it helps them connect emotionally,
which keeps the ads in the public consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Whassup' stuff is so simple, but it'll still hit viewers
on many levels,'' Reardon says. ``It starts off with friends just
hanging out, and it builds into something with a connection. It
reminds us that some of the strangest and most original moments
we've had have been with our own friends.'' Friendship was key to
the execution of the ads as well; Reardon says that DDB auditioned
comedians and actors for days and days before deciding to cast the
commercial with director Charles Stone III's buddies, because they
gave the spot the proper relaxed mood.
</P>
<P>
   But Garfield adds that sometimes, simplicity doesn't work, and
he's not sure that it's the key. ``I think a better word is
`resonance,''' Garfield says. ``The mechanism is that the
recognition creates a resonance. This gets back to how powerful and
ubiquitous some of these ads are.''
</P>
<P>
   That resonance goes beyond simple emotional connections. The Gap
and Volkswagen commercials, for the most part, are a little bit
chillier than the ``Whassup'' campaign, especially Gap's series of
ads with stone-faced youths singing classic rock and R&AMP;B. But
they're influential for other reasons. Actually, in the case of the
Gap's ``Khakis swing'' ad, it was a matter of being influential by
being influenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gap didn't start the swing trend, but it noticed it and
amplified it,'' says Puccio, the McCaan Erickson spokesman. ``You
have to be where the action is. One of the reasons we pay a lot of
money for office space in Manhattan is that we need to have a bunch
of young creative kids who live in SoHo and are on the edge of
what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   By being on that edge, creative teams can come up with ads that
appeal to people of similar ages and tastes. But the appeal of the
Gap and VW ads is more widespread. Older demographics might feel
shut out by a busy, noisy dot-com commercial or one of Nike's
ethereal, jock-driven spots. But the music in the Gap and
especially the VW commercials often crosses generational lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Volkswagen stuff, I think, is brilliant,'' Reardon says.
``Music can be personal, like when you're sitting by yourself or
singing along with it in your car. It can evoke emotions, make you
feel a certain way.'' And VW often chooses music that hasn't
completely saturated the culture, which makes people curious about
the recordings as well as the car, and gives them a subtle
connection to the product being advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the music wasn't invented for the VW commercials _ it
was discovered and/or uncovered for them, much like the nascent
swing trend was put to use for the Gap. Reardon points out that the
``Whassup'' commercials didn't invent the catchphrase, they simply
took advantage of it and popularized it (and also added new
inflections and an over-the-top, tongue-hanging-out way of saying
it).
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the culture fuels the commercials, which then
affect the culture. ``It's completely cyclical,'' Puccio says.
``We're all living in the same culture. In many ways, a good
commercial is like a good 30-second movie. It has to tell the
entire story in one image.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all their entertainment value, and all their influence
on other entertainment, it's still hard to determine how effective
many of these ads are as sales tools. You may chortle at the sight
of a bunch of slackers saying ``Whassup'' and ``True, very true,''
but if your tastes run to imported beers, is the ``Whassup''
campaign gonna make you run down to the 7-Eleven and grab a
six-pack of Bud? Puccio gets a kick out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always reminds me of people in nightclubs who say that they
can't be hypnotized, and 10 minutes later they're acting like a
chicken,'' he says. ``At least you have to consciously decide not
to have a Bud. You can't buy what you don't know, and now the idea
has been implanted in your brain. A key rule in advertising is that
you have to be remembered before you can be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   All advertising psychology aside, one fact remains _ many of
these commercials, to use Garfield's word, resonate just because
they're so entertaining. Sometimes, they can be too much of a good
thing (last week's news of the Taco Bell Chihuahua's retirement
wasn't exactly heartbreaking), but often, they're more entertaining
than the shows they support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started (AdCritic.com) almost a year and a half ago, almost
as a hobby,'' Beckman says. ``Now we've been written about in
several magazines. AdWeek contacted us; we've been featured in
Newsweek, People, Time and Vanity Fair. We've actually had guys in
the military thank us for the service we're providing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
