<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-TYCOON-BOS &LR;      07-27 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TYCOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES DROPPED AGAINST MEDIA MOGUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian prosecutors dropped criminal charges Thursday
against media mogul and Kremlin opponent Vladimir Gusinsky, ending
a case that provoked concerns here and abroad that President
Vladimir V. Putin was cracking down on the press.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were dropped on the eve of a meeting between Putin
and Russia's leading businessmen, leading some analysts to suggest
that Putin was switching tactics in his dealings with Russia's most
powerful industrialists.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky, who owns Russia's only private television station, was
arrested last month and accused of defrauding the Russian
government of $10 million. Gusinsky spent four days in jail before
being released on condition he not leave Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The travel ban was lifted on Wednesday, and Thursday,
prosecutors unexpectedly announced that there was a ``lack of
evidence that a crime had been committed,'' and dropped the
charges. Gusinsky was informed of the impending decision late
Wednesday night and left immediately for Spain where his family was
staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin understands that the Gusinsky case was harming his image
in the West,'' said Yevgeny Volk, a political analyst with the
Heritage Foundation in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's case provoked outrage in Russia and abroad. Free
speech advocates said it showed that Putin, a former KGB spy, was
intent on stifling the press and exerting authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks before the arrest, masked security police raided
Gusinsky's Media-Most company, which controls the popular NTV
television station, Ekho Moskvy radio and several newspapers and
magazines. Gusinsky's media outlets had harshly criticized Putin,
reported on Kremlin corruption and questioned the war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton raised the issue of press freedom in Russia at
a meeting with Putin during last week's Group of Eight summit in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin maintained that Gusinsky's case was about fighting
corruption, not muzzling the media.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky is one of Russia's so-called oligarchs,
politically-connected tycoons who used their government connections
to amass fortunes and wield enormous political power under former
president Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Putin pledged during his election campaign to establish a level
playing field for business and to rein in the oligarchs. In
addition to Gusinsky's case, law-enforcement bodies have opened
investigations into several other leading business moguls.
</P>
<P>
   Russian prosecutors have sought to reverse the 1997
privatization of giant metals concern Norilsk Nickel, saying it was
sold at an unfairly low price to a well-connected businessman.
Prosecutors have also launched investigations into Russia's largest
car maker, Avtovaz, oil giant Lukoil and the natural gas giant
Gazprom.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, media and oil baron Boris Berezovsky, widely
considered to be the most influential of Russia's tycoons, resigned
his seat in parliament to protest what he called Putin's
heavy-handed tactics. Days before his resignation, prosecutors had
questioned Berezovsky about an estimated $600 million allegedly
embezzled from Russia's national airline Aeroflot.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here said the dropping of Gusinsky's case and Friday's
scheduled meeting in the Kremlin, are signals that Putin has
decided to use more subtle tactics to rein in the moguls.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Markov, a Moscow-based political analyst, said, ``A
message is being sent to the oligarchs that on one hand they don't
have to worry about being arrested, but on the other hand, they
will now need to play by new rules of the game with the Kremlin in
charge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
