<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MAKING-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKING-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: NOVELS THAT SELL, WITHOUT THE HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: this column appeared in Thursday's New York Times) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To chew over The New York Times' fiction best-seller list is to
be reminded that an author doesn't necessarily need media
anointment or a splendid critical sendoff or an otherwise powerful
launching to be a striking commercial success. Often all it takes
is the gradual accumulation of popularity, the gathering together
of heaps of devotees for the writer's books, one after another,
until there is a critical mass of ardent fans.
</P>
<P>
   This is about commercial, not literary, fiction, and the writers
are not literary celebrities or sensations; rather, they are
first-class practitioners of the art of telling good yarns, mostly
about relationships. There will be three such books on the Aug. 6
best-seller list by authors whose careers have been built not only
on their storytelling, but also largely by careful, nurturing
publishing and word-of-mouth enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The most startling is ``Not a Day Goes By'' (Doubleday) by E.
Lynn Harris, which enters at No. 2 on The Times' list and No. 1 on
the Barnes &AMP; Noble fiction list (and No. 3 on the chain's overall
list). But there was also ``Hot Six'' (St. Martin's Press) by Janet
Evanovich, which opened on The Times' list at No. 1 and is now No.
9; and ``Liar's Game'' (Dutton) by Eric Jerome Dickey, which is No.
14. Harris and Dickey write about relationships; Evanovich writes
steamy crime thrillers featuring the lusty bounty hunter from
Jersey City, Stephanie Plum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a Day Goes By,'' Harris' sixth novel, had a first printing
of 152,000 copies. There are now 212,000 in print. Harris, 42, is
African-American and gay and writes about love and friendship. His
characters are generally young, successful, attractive and black
and gay or bisexual. This is not his first best-selling novel, but
it is his fastest start out of the carton and its success puts him
into a more rarefied category of best-selling authors.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just good writing that goes into the creation of a
blastoff like Harris'. His editor, Janet Hill, said, ``We wanted a
smaller book at an attractive price to be out in time for July, to
be a beach read.'' So the novel is 271 pages, printed in a smaller
format than most hardcovers, and has a list price of $19.95. Which
means that in the doorways of the chain bookstores it can be
purchased for $11.97.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' first novel, ``Invisible Life,'' was self-published (but
later reissued by Doubleday), so the writer is rather sophisticated
about self-promotion. At book signings, he said, ``I spend lots of
time writing long autographs, and I urge people to tell their
friends, and I tell them if they don't like the book bring it back
and I'll give them back their money.'' He also buys blank journals
and fills them with the names and addresses of the fans he meets on
tour _ already more than 7,000 _ and sends them Christmas and
Valentine cards and mass e-mails. (His Web site is
www.elynnharris.com.) Harris also does a lot of interviewing on
black radio programs and goes to nearly every black-oriented
exposition he can.
</P>
<P>
   Do his numbers reflect a large cross-over of white readers? His
publisher, Stephen Rubin, and his agent, John Hawkins, say the
answer is yes, but it's inferential. ``A large number of white
women come up and tell him how much they enjoy his books,'' Rubin
said. ``Probably because his books are first and foremost very
human, the kind of stories people can relate to, whatever their
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-help is the key to the other successes. Evanovich, besides
having a state-of-the-art formula for sexy thrillers, also has a
state-of-the-art Web site (www.evanovich.com), which has the
freshest information available on her books. Generally, she puts
the first chapter of her latest book on the Web site as a teaser
leading up to the publication date; then a week or two later the
second chapter goes on the Web site. After that, it's buy the book!
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Shear, publisher of the paperback and reference group of
St. Martin's Press, said, ``If you know what you are doing in your
marketing and with the right timing and with the author pushing and
pushing, you can make it happen.'' It also sends out only a small
number of galleys of Evanovich's books for reviewers only, and not
the usual thousands of advance reading copies.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton published ``Sister, Sister,'' the first novel of Dickey,
who is African-American, in October 1996, and it did so in
hardcover. His editor, Audrey LaFehr, said: ``We started him off
modestly, with no advertising and a small public relations budget,
but in hardcover because we did know that African-Americans buy
hardcover.'' We printed 18,000 copies, rather a large printing for
a first novel, but ended up grossing 40,000 copies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the next one we had a first printing of a little more, in
the low 20,000's, and we sent him on a small tour,'' she added.
``Now he tours for two months and more. He has a huge word-of-mouth
following.'' There are 140,000 copies of ``Liar's Game,'' his fifth
book, in print and that number will probably increase.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the patient, step-by-step creation of nonliterary
fiction best sellers appears so easy, particularly when reviewed
through a publisher's retrospectivescope. Nonetheless, next week we
will find out whether another writer whose novels sold
exponentially better, from a clutter of paperback originals to
hardcover, will jump out of the box to near the top of the lists.
On Tuesday Tami Hoag's fifth hardcover thriller, ``Dust to Dust''
(Bantam Books),'' will be in the marketplace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
