<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-EBOOKS28-COX     07-27 1847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBOOKS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-books: Bedtime for binderies?
 &HT;    By Charlotte Moore,
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead. Turn it on.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there you go. Push its little ``Power'' button right there,
then sit back. Relax. Let it tell you a story _ heck, it'll tell
you several stories if you'll open your mind and let it.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, you say?
</P>
<P>
   Sure. Inspect it. Dissect it. Measure its girth and consider how
it feels in your hands. Test it out. Marvel at all the amazing
things it can do. Be excited by the fact that it can store multiple
documents in its memory.
</P>
<P>
   Show it off to your friends. One by one, let them ``oooh'' and
``aaah'' at its countless capabilities. Let them compare it to the
omnipotent computer, its ancestral patron, then pontificate
expertly on its technical innards and how it must operate. Use it
to read your little ones to sleep by the light of lamp, take it
with you when you travel abroad and, first thing in the morning,
use it out on the veranda to read your local daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Take all the time you need. Soon enough the techni-green glow of
its backlight will easily lull you into the anti-climactic
realization of what it is.
</P>
<P>
   For, beneath its obdurate exterior and various buttons, beyond
the magical powers of its stylus wand, it is merely a device for
reading.
</P>
<P>
   It is a book. And all it wants is to tell you a story.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Sullivan is very much a bathtub reader. In fact, she does
some of her best reading and thinking while wrinkling in her
bubble-filled vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take this into the bathtub,'' Sullivan said,
gesturing toward the electronic device before her, as if to ward
off its vile existence.
</P>
<P>
   The device is an electronic book, or e-book as we're commonly
calling them now. E-books are pieces of hardware about the size of
a typical paperback novel that store digital text and graphics,
much like a computer. The term e-book is also used to refer to the
actual data downloaded from a computer and then uploaded into the
e-book hardware. It's difficult to pinpoint the exact year that
e-books were introduced; they've evolved over the past five years
to become a specialized version of a portable computer, much like
laptops and personal digital assistants. While the concept of
e-books is not terribly novel, the buzz of interest within
publishing, author and reader circles across the country has just
begun, likely as an effect of the March release of Stephen King's
66-page novella ``Riding the Bullet.'' Bullet was published online
and downloaded by more than half a million people at little or no
cost. Yet, for all their recent popularity, e-books fall way short
of their conventional counterparts in some areas of functionality.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamental differences in reading style
</P>
<P>
   You can't take an e-book device, bend its cover back and palm it
the way you would a paperback novel. You can't turn its pages with
your saliva-smeared finger. You can't use a Bic pen to jot down
notes in the margins of an e-book. You can't absentmindedly toss it
on the coffee table, and you wouldn't willingly relinquish your
pricey device to a friend when you know it'll be years before you
get it back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for many practical _ and even for some slightly impractical
_ purposes, electronic books are more than the intimidating
nonsensical gadgets that some traditional book-loving critics have
written them off as being.
</P>
<P>
   By now you familiar with the more popular e-books; NuvoMedia
Inc.'s Rocket eBook, Softbook Press Inc.'s SoftBook Reader and
Microsoft Corp.'s Microsoft Reader. There are a handful of other,
less popular devices produced by companies like Glassbook Inc. and
Everybook Inc. In general, they all come with memory, touch screen
capabilities, a rechargeable battery and built-in modem. With
minimal instruction, anyone with a credit card and an ounce of
technical skill could easily master the process of downloading
books from various Web sites. Presently, the devices cost anywhere
from $200 to $600 but come with upgrade options and can store
literally thousands of pages of text.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not so much the technology; we've proven
ourselves to be forward-thinkers with a willingness to welcome
easier, more efficient methods of operation. The problem seems to
be getting avid readers to do away with traditional perceptions of
what is and is not a book.
</P>
<P>
   Who better to estimate the value of e-books than two
self-prescribed bibliomaniacs? Sullivan and her colleague Shannon
Robertson, employees at Book People, weren't the least bit
intimidated by the Rocket eBook they examined for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh ... but wait. They weren't all that impressed, either.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the handful of locals at this month's Book People
Contemporary Fiction book club, led by Sullivan and Robertson. They
were a comfortable cluster of Austin intellectuals seated snugly
around an antique coffee table in plush vintage high-backed chairs.
They were all equipped with weathered paperback copies of Roddy
Doyle's novel ``Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha'' and all were prepared to
delve into deep conversation _ a serious verbal deconstruction of
the month's featured reading.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a brief, haughty chat about e-books, ``that new
technology'' they'd seen on television or heard about on National
Public Radio. While a couple of them admitted to frequently using
their desktop or laptop computers to read excerpts of books or
other snippets of information, none had actually purchased, or even
considered purchasing, a dedicated e-book reading device.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be really low down on the list of toys I'd like to
have,'' said one member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading is very important to me,'' said another. ``There is
definitely a sensual component to reading a book that's not
available with that thing. I don't think I'd want to take that to
bed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feature for taking notes but it's not the same as
keeping your pencil behind your ear,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Luddite,'' Sullivan said. ``I just kind of got tired of
looking at it and there's no cover to flip to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan thinks the e-book will appeal most to those people
already predisposed to a technical pursuit of knowledge. ``Most of
the people that are looking at the computer books aren't
necessarily reading massive amounts of theory and the kind of stuff
that we read for fun _ hey, it's a sick world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   These are the types of raw _ petty, even _ concerns that arise
when ordinary folks ponder our evolving world of literature.
Bookworms are a proud people who are incited when their senses are
stimulated; they enjoy being attracted by a book's cover, the woody
smell of the pages, the way a bookshelf creaks when it's
overwhelmed by thick, heavy classics.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic books, they say, are asking them to make a mental
transition _ to veer from their ingrained appreciation for the
printed books that fill our nation's more than 120,000 public,
academic and special interest libraries _ to depend on a neoteric
gizmo that disrupts the sacred union between man and book.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the changing world of publishing
</P>
<P>
   Industry players are not as critical. In fact, they appear to be
fastidiously making room for the whole idea of e-books on their
corporate shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-books are just another way of supplying books to people,''
said Patricia Wynn Ricks, local author and owner of Pemberley
Press, which plans to publish two e-books in March 2001. ``The
electronic book will just be one way of delivering a standard book.
It will be convenient for people who travel a lot, people who enjoy
reading off their screen, people who don't have a lot of room to
store books. E-books will be cheaper than traditional books and
they will allow us to reach people at greater distances who don't
have large bookstores near them.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, electronic books are steir embryonic phase.
According to a recent report released by the Association of
American Publishers, only 10 percent of the total 2005 consumer
book market will consist of electronic content publications. But
turn those numbers into actual dollars and the $2.3 billion figure
is a projection publishers cannot easily ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 'Riding the Bullet' event was an anomaly,'' said Adam
Rothberg, director of corporate communications for publisher Simon
&AMP; Schuster. ``It was one of those experiences from which we learned
absolutely everything and absolutely nothing. It was on the one
hand an event that was waiting to happen; on the other hand there
were so many variables to it that we cannot make a general
statement from it. The fact that more than 500,000 people were
willing to try the e-book experience was a big positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even small publishing companies are getting in on the digital
action. Eakin Press, an 11-person company in the Central Texas Hill
Country that publishes about 60 titles a year, has sent more than
200 of its books to be digitized by netLibrary, a Colorado-based
outfit that sells collections of digital books to libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get 50 percent of what netLibrary gets and the author gets
50 percent of what we get,'' said Ed Eakin, president of Eakin
Press. ``E-books are just another part of publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects are huge in areas of academics. In keeping with
its tradition of striving to offer a competitive education, the
University of Texas is fortifying its libraries with e-book-related
material. Under the UT System Academic Library Collection
Enhancement Program, $1 million a year, for the last three years,
has been allocated by the UT System Board of Regents for the
purpose of purchasing various library aids including 5,000
Web-based e-books currently available to all UT students and
faculty from El Paso to Brownsville. Plans are to purchase another
5,000 to 10,000 e-books next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it as easy as possible for our students to be
able to do high-quality research wherever they are and whenever
they can find time,'' said Dennis Dillon, UT's head of information
resources. ``We have purchased books that are not generally read
from cover to cover or pondered at length. Most of our e-books are
purchased with the expectation that they will be used primarily to
look up quick facts or relevant chapters; or the books are
scholarly in nature and of a type where we expect that the reader
might want to quickly sample several titles on the same subject or
to examine specific chapters. We expect that UT-Austin students
will have access to a minimum of 25,000 Web-based e-books within 12
months.''
</P>
<P>
   The Book People Contemporary Fiction book club members could
certainly appreciate the advantages electronic books might offer in
schools and public libraries. But as for regular old
reading-for-the-simple-pleasure-of reading purposes, they've
already pulled the plug on electronic devices and digital text.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to play with,'' Robertson said. ``But they're up
against a thousand year-old tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REVIEW-NUTTYPROF-COX     07-27 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-NUTTYPROF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eddie Murphy dishes out crude humor
 &HT;    `Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'
 &HT;    2 stars
 &HT;    Starring: Eddie Murphy, Janet Jackson
 &HT;    Director: Peter Segal
 &HT;    Screenwriters: Barry W. Blaustein, David Sheffield, Paul and
Chris Weitz
 &HT;    MPAA rating: PG-13 for crude sexual humor, language, unbridled
flatulence jokes
 &HT;    Running time: 1 hour, 45 minutes
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only funny parts of Eddie Murphy's 1996 ``The Nutty
Professor'' were the scenes of Professor Sherman Klump's family
rioting at the dinner table like ravenous Teamsters. Between
dripping swallows of barbecue, Sherman, Granny, Mama, Papa and
Ernie _ all played by Murphy upholstered in pillowy pounds of
makeup _ loosed cross-fires of acid banter and gales of gas. There
was a call-of-nature pride to the intestinal expulsions that gave
viewers a liberating glee, and a blush.
</P>
<P>
   The bloated sequel, ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps,'' extracts
and magnifies those bawdy interludes, elevating the Klump clan to
bona fide stars, each with a subplot to call their own.
</P>
<P>
   The ambition is admirable, but it's too much on top of the main
plot, a many-tentacled mess unsure if it wants to be a
Farrelly-style gross-out or a sweet romantic comedy. It involves
Sherman's jerky alter ego Buddy Love re-emerging in order to steal
a lucrative youth serum Sherman has invented.
</P>
<P>
   There are all manner of crude gags, as well as tender longueurs
about Sherman and his girlfriend Denise (a blandly pleasant Janet
Jackson in the blank and reactive love interest role). Oddly,
there's not a whisper about Ms. Purdy, Sherman's paramour in part
one.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, a lurching series of elaborate comic situations
peppered with funny lines, is overburdened and wild-eyed. It works
every angle, but the funniest bits, again, are the basest: the
Klumps at the dinner table cussing and cutting. It's worth noting
that our bulbous hero Sherman is the apologetic straight man in
these scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Klumps'' is sweeter and smarter than its formulaic
predecessor. The movie's big-budget, high-concept overload and
juggling of multiple themes recalls, if never attains, the comic
grandeur of ``Ghostbusters,'' and it jitters with almost as many
special effects. Yet for all its ambition, the Murphy vehicle is
curiously routine, never veering outside the
lowest-common-denominator lines.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Love still lurks in Sherman, a courtly scientific genius
barred from social success by his 400-pound girth. He's a globular,
jiggly mensch with turkey-sausage fingers.
</P>
<P>
   As the embodiment of Sherman's sexually repressed id, Love pops
out with testosteronic vengeance, a spray of noxious virility on
the prowl. He emerges in Sherman with Tourette's syndrome-like
outbursts that threaten to sabotage his relationship with Denise.
</P>
<P>
   In the film's Disney-inspired scientific world, Sherman
undergoes a gene-removal procedure to expel Love once and for all.
It backfires with dire results. And through a freak accident far
too complicated to describe _ it concerns a dog hair and a jar of
the bad Buddy gene _ Buddy springs to life in the form of Eddie
Murphy's unadorned body.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1963 Jerry Lewis original and Murphy's '96 knockoff,
Love's motivation was to score with the ladies. This time he's a
standard-issue villain after a standard-issue potion. Love is the
only role Murphy plays in his own skin, and he's amped him up
several ratchets into a shrill and diabolical maniac, running
around screaming with his mouth wide open. Sometimes he acts like a
dog.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a dog. You're excused if you're lost. A quartet of
screenwriters, including ``American Pie'' gross-mongers Chris Weitz
and Paul Weitz, keep piling layers to the story. There's Granny
Klump cavorting like an oversexed vixen and Papa Klump guzzling the
youth serum to up his sex life. Much of it is very funny; much more
of it is lame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Klumps'' has a big heart that miraculously renders the
foul family sympathetic, even genial. But attempts at real
emotional resonance _ the movie can be downright maudlin _ are
thinly contrived. Sorrows are short-lived and quickly reversed. We
never make an investment we're afraid of losing.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's a comic wonder as the cantankerous Klumps. He etches
the characters with perceptive realism into people we might know.
But the film has no center of gravity. Rapid-fire gags and deft
editing sustain a zippy pace, but it starts to blur in the heedless
pattern of a spinning top. When a hamster grows to a ferocious
20-feet-tall and sodomizes a character, the movie glances a wall,
sputters, and falls on its side.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
