<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-MURDER-0728-CO     07-27 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MURDER-0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROBE INTO VICIOUS KILLING OF MEXICAN CLERIC ENDS AS IT BEGAN -
IN CONTROVERSY
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ It was a spectacularly brutal assassination that
ushered in a new era of drug-related violence in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Assailants wielding automatic weapons blasted away at a Mexican
Catholic cardinal _ who was dressed in his vestments and crucifix _
as his car was entering the parking lot of Guadalajara's
international airport.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a special commission that probed the seven-year-old
murder of Cardinal Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo ended as it began _
with divided opinions over whether Posadas was killed accidentally
or on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   In a painstaking presentation, Mexico's Attorney General's
Office described testimony by numerous jailed participants who said
Posadas was killed ``out of confusion, an error over vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   The official story, which has been on the record for years, is
that Posadas was probably shot in his white Grand Marquis car by
hired guns working for Mexico's notorious Arellano Felix brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The Tijuana-based drug traffickers' leader, Ramon, is on the
FBI's ``10 Most-Wanted'' list. At the time of the killing, the
Arellanos were engaged in a vicious fight to control
cocaine-smuggling routes into the United States. Some of the
alleged killers were recruited from San Diego, Calif., just over
the border from Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Their target on May 23, 1993, was trafficker Joaquin Guzman,
whose wife also reportedly drove a white Grand Marquis, the
Attorney General's report said.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic Church representatives and members of the state
government of Jalisco, where the killing took place, disagreed with
the conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not the product of an accident,'' said Fernando
Guzman, a high-ranking aide in the Jalisco state government. He is
not related to Joaquin Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   State and church officials participated in the commission, which
met 23 times to discuss the case. But they remain convinced that
Posadas was the specific target of a conspiracy that killed his
driver and others in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The initial investigation, which quickly pointed toward the
Arellano Felix brothers, was ``deficient and manipulated,'' Guzman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects were coerced and their testimony was suspicious because
some was identical, down to ``commas and periods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials since proved to be corrupt were involved in the case.
Some of the assailants were able to board a plane to Tijuana and
escape the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But assistant Attorney General Jose Luis Ramos said federal
officials had exhausted other leads and that alleged witnesses with
alternative information had failed lie detector tests.
</P>
<P>
   The killing was the product of hired guns that were paid
$15,000, and in a ``burst of adrenaline'' attackd the cardinal's
white car from the rear, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   Thugs with nicknames like ``the white crab'' and ``the black
marshal'' told officials they thought they were killing Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cardinal Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo was an extraordinarily kind
man, with no enemies, and no reason existed for a group of drug
traffickers to take his life,'' Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
