u a BC-KUWAIT-CULTURE-NEWHOU     07-27 1990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-CULTURE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN CULTURE TRANSFORMING KUWAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, July 27, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of Samira Omar (NNS6) and teachers
at American Creativity Academy in Kuwait (NNS7) 
 By PAM LOUWAGIE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   She looks every bit New York, dressed smartly in a gray
pantsuit, a flower-printed scarf fashionably flung around her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Scientist Samira Omar, the head honcho of a research institute,
supervises dozens of environmental research projects every year.
From her book-filled office, she directs a staff that includes
several men.
</P>
<P>
   But as a woman in a still-traditional Arab society, Omar doesn't
have the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Women ``do have influence at the professional level,'' said
Omar, who has a doctorate. ``But the most important thing, they
deprive us from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the living oxymoron that is Kuwait. In a modern
Middle Eastern country where Western ideas are infiltrating much of
society, balancing the Westernization with traditional Arab values
is proving a difficult juggling act.
</P>
<P>
   It's evident everywhere: Stores in elaborate new malls are
filled with tank tops and miniskirts that the culture says women
are not allowed to wear. Satellite dishes adorn nearly every house,
but Islam condemns their provocative content. Kuwaiti women have
outpaced men in attendance at Kuwait University, but they're not
allowed to vote.
</P>
<P>
   As in many societies, Kuwaitis say change is coming through its
young people and its women, with teen-agers rebelling against Arab
traditions such as wearing robes and women becoming more educated
and taking on bigger jobs. At the same time, religious
fundamentalists are working to push the society back to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait is ``a mixture of everything,'' political scientist
Masoumah Al-Mubarak said. ``Change is everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   On the seaside edge of Kuwait City, change has hit like a
tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   It's where the younger generations hang out, driving their
Mercedes and BMWs to sleek shopping centers, watching each other
parade around Starbucks in snug-fitting outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Ali Eslami, 20, strode into an Internet cafe wearing
bluejeans and a skateboarding T-shirt, and carrying an e-mail
address containing the words ``boyz2men.''
</P>
<P>
   He often goes to the cafe to chat in person or online, he said.
And he dresses in the traditional male attire, white robes called
dishdashas, only when his father asks him to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was a kid, I never liked traditional wear. For two to
three hours, I will wear it ... when (Father) wants to visit one of
his friends and he says, `You've got to respect that guy,''' said
Eslami, twiddling the cord of his cell phone's earpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the new generation is really Westernized,'' said Hamed
Al-Azemi, taking his two children to the Internet cafe to do
research for a school project because their home computer had
broken. ``Whatever they see, they want to bring it into Kuwait.''
</P>
<P>
   What they see is part of the problem, some Kuwaitis say.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a country wealthy from oil money, Kuwaitis are
frequent travelers, taking long vacations in the summer to escape
the desert heat that often nears 130 degrees. Technology such as
satellite dishes and Internet connections is everywhere. Cellular
phones have become such an important part of the Kuwaiti attire
that people pay extra for an easy-to-remember number.
</P>
<P>
   Such access to images of the world has opened a market in Kuwait
for Western restaurants, products and movies. Some believe it also
has created more problems in the country, encouraging the use of
alcohol and illegal drugs, which Islam forbids, and increasing the
number of violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   So the Kuwaiti government has tried to mitigate Western culture.
Outside a theater, a movie poster with a man and woman kissing has
a magazine cut-out of a face covering their lips. Inside a TGI
Friday's restaurant, the bar menu is filled with nonalcoholic
daiquiris.
</P>
<P>
   But some say the infiltration of Western values is proving
impossible to control. Though Islamic culture forbids
American-style dating, teen-age boys now zip down a waterfront road
on motorcycles, carrying girlfriends who hug them from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would never see this before,'' Khaled Al-Ghanem, 36, said
with disgust as a motorcycle whizzed by. ``A guy with a girl on his
bike!''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaiti society has even become more accepting of homosexuality,
said a 38-year-old biomedical engineer who is gay. ``It's more
Westernized. They accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonalcoholic beer made its way onto store shelves recently, but
officials considered banning it when they found it contained a
trace of alcohol. That apparently hasn't stopped the demand for
black-market alcohol, often available at underground parties,
Kuwaitis say.
</P>
<P>
   Even drugs are smuggled into the country. And violence has
turned more serious, with Kuwaitis retaining some of the weapons
they acquired for defense during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you scratch a car now, they will fight you without saying
anything,'' Eslami said.
</P>
<P>
   Many traditional laws still apply, though.
</P>
<P>
   A famous Kuwaiti singer made newspaper headlines this spring
after police caught him in a compromising position with another
man's wife.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the young people, women are most responsible for shaking
social change in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait historically has been more progressive than its Islamic
neighbors. Kuwaiti women have been allowed to seek high-level
professional jobs and now hold positions such as Kuwait University
president, ambassador and planning ministry head.
</P>
<P>
   But women still aren't allowed to vote or hold elected political
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have influence at the professional level. And as
housewives, women decide everything in the home. ... But the most
important thing, they deprive them from it,'' said Omar, who became
a women's activist while studying at the University of California
at Berkeley. ``It bothers me a lot. I don't want to feel I'm less
intelligent or less important than my colleagues just because they
are male.''
</P>
<P>
   Some traditionalists say Islam prohibits women's involvement in
politics, though women in other Middle Eastern countries where the
religion predominates, such as Iran, are allowed to participate.
</P>
<P>
   At the behest of Kuwait's emir, the parliament took a vote on
women's suffrage in 1999. The motion failed 32-30, but many Kuwaiti
women say the narrow margin is a good sign of change to come.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the changes would be much slower if it weren't for the
Gulf War, which raised political awareness among all Kuwaitis and
made women take more active roles in providing for their families.
Though Iraqi soldiers often took Kuwaiti men prisoner, women
typically were allowed to go freely about their business. So, many
women went out to get parts to repair things in their homes or buy
supplies for their families. Some were part of an underground
resistance, transporting weapons and hiding foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women felt that if they can do it during the invasion,
they can do it after liberation,'' said Lubna Al-Qadi, a Kuwait
University sociologist.
</P>
<P>
   For petroleum engineer Sara Akbar, the war was an opportunity to
show heroism, and she is considered a leader in the women's
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Akbar, an employee of Kuwait Oil Co., organized one of the first
teams to extinguish oil wells torched by retreating Iraqi soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew all the fields by heart,'' Akbar said modestly.
</P>
<P>
   When she and a team surveyed some of the oil wells and found one
gushing, she had someone simply turn off its valve. The rest
started from there.
</P>
<P>
   After putting out 42 well fires in 45 days -- a world record,
Akbar is quick to mention -- she is now pictured in films and
brochures about the fires.
</P>
<P>
   She said many other women helped during and after the war, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw these women have something strong in them,'' Akbar said.
``But they're not in positions where they would be because of ...
male dominating'' society.
</P>
<P>
   Though women have been making political strides in the past
decade, ``the tide of Islam is trying to push it back,'' Al-Mubarak
said.
</P>
<P>
   The women are divided, too. Many want to embrace their heritage
and choose to dress traditionally and hold traditional roles in
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Mubarak said many women agree with the women's rights
movement but are afraid to show it. Some quietly applaud suffrage
leaders when they meet at a function or in a store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call them the silent majority,'' she said. ``Some don't
have the time (to join the women's movement), or some fear what
their husbands will say.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   For the dozens of Americans living here, Kuwait is slowly
looking more like home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are definitely not stuck out in the desert somewhere,''
said school Principal Lisa Al-Ramly, who grew up in Kokomo, Ind.
``But it hasn't always been like this.''
</P>
<P>
   American items such as chocolate chips used to be rarities in
grocery stores, but now Americans say they can find almost
anything. American restaurants are plentiful, though they're
modified to work in Arab culture: They contain no pork or alcohol.
Even A&AMP;W advertises ``root drink'' instead of root beer.
</P>
<P>
   Movie theaters have become more common, though films and even
movie posters are edited for content deemed too immodest. And as
modern and wealthy as Kuwait is, some primitive ways of doing
business persist, Americans there say.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners spending time in the country quickly notice a few
things: Kuwaiti nationals live in elaborate villas -- the
apartments are for the workers -- and only they can enjoy certain
benefits such as owning property.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a social status. Kuwaitis are at the top of the food
chain, then the Westerners, and the Americans are at the top of
that,'' said Jesse Ruiz, 31, who has a civilian job at a military
base.
</P>
<P>
   As in America, getting things done requires influence and
connections. Mail is often slow and isn't sorted by machine, but by
laborers. Some infrastructure, such as water systems, is not on par
with that in the Western world.
</P>
<P>
   ``For as much money as they have ... they could go a lot further
with it,'' said Brenda Gange-Murad, who grew up in Seattle and has
lived in Kuwait for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Americans say they have seen Kuwait change quickly in the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more open, a lot more Western,'' said Fatema Lynn,
who grew up in Kalamazoo, Mich., and has lived in Kuwait for 13
years. ``It probably would have happened anyway. It probably
happened faster because there are more Americans here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaitis are split on that subject.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the country has changed quickly because so many
Kuwaitis fled during the Iraqi invasion and spent seven months out
of the country, where they picked up Western habits.
</P>
<P>
   Others laugh at that suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way to connect this issue with seven months of
being out of the country,'' Al-Mubarak said, pointing out that
Kuwaitis have long had the money to travel the world.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, many in Kuwait say they expect society will
keep battling and adjusting. As Omar says, conflict in social
change is inevitable: ``It happens in every society when it moves
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Pam Louwagie is a staff writer with The Times-Picayune of New
Orleans)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
