<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-MISSING-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES STILL SEARCH FOR THOSE LOST IN WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, July 27, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With photo of Abdul Hameed Al-Attar (NNS5) 
 By PAM LOUWAGIE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He hears the muffled, pleading shouts replay in his mind every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father, I'm in here! I'm in here!''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, Abdul Hameed Al-Attar has lived with the
chilling memories of his 26-year-old son Jamal's cries, the last
words of a young man taken prisoner in his own neighborhood by
Iraqi soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He's heard the horrific stories about the torture Kuwaiti
prisoners endured during the Persian Gulf War, cooped up in cement
cellars without food, forced to do unfathomable acts such as drink
their own urine, enduring Iraqi soldiers zapping them with
electricity or cutting off their genitals.
</P>
<P>
   Imagining his son dead is almost easier than imagining the
torture. ``I always see him in my eyes as insane, out of his mind
from the torture,'' Al-Attar said, his hazel eyes shiny with welled
tears.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after Iraqi soldiers consumed the oil-rich emirate and
allied forces drove them back, Kuwait is still missing 605 of its
own, quite a lot given there are only about 650,000 Kuwaiti
nationals in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most Kuwaiti families are missing a relative or friend. And
that's why accounting for the missing is still a major issue.
Yellow ribbons and the slogan ``Remember our POWs'' adorn
everything from private business cards to billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows somebody. ... Those things keep reminding
us,'' said Sara Akbar, a petroleum engineer with three missing
co-workers and a neighbor who was abducted while fetching food for
his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very important to us,'' Al-Attar said indignantly.
``The Iraqis refuse to give us answers about any of them. They
refuse to give us information.''
</P>
<P>
   A nagging guilt drives Al-Attar to volunteer every night at a
center for the missing, where other parents like him are still
wondering about their children. He can't rest until he knows for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   At the center, formally called the Council for Missing and POW
Affairs, pictures of the missing are tacked neatly on a wall to
form a memorial behind iron bars and barbed wire: A smiling
14-year-old boy was taken away as he scrawled ``Long live Kuwait''
on a building; a relative of a member of the Kuwaiti Parliament who
once supported Saddam Hussein but spit in an Iraqi soldier's face
during the invasion disappeared; and there's Al-Attar's son.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Attar often cries when he speaks to groups about his son. He
carries extra copies of the photo with him to remind people of the
horrors that came at the hands of Iraqis and to tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   Under the watch of enemy soldiers, Al-Attar happened to see his
son while Jamal was out with members of a small resistance
movement, an activity that made a protective father nervous. They
hugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Take care of yourself.' He said, `Don't worry,
Father, I am OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Jamal was snatched by Iraqi soldiers. As Al-Attar
pleaded with guards at the police station, Jamal heard his father's
voice and shouted to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in here!''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last the two heard from each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I blame myself,'' Al-Attar said. ``Was I followed
by the Iraqi police? That's the only explanation I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq denies that it has any Kuwaiti prisoners, but Kuwaitis say
they know otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Until each missing person is accounted for, Kuwaitis have vowed
they will not stop searching.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot help checking and asking,'' Al-Attar said. ``These
are our people.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Pam Louwagie is a staff writer with The Times-Picayune of New
Orleans)
</P>
</TEXT>
