<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4893 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-KUWAIT-RECOVERY-NEWHO     07-27 2107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUWAIT-RECOVERY-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN YEARS AFTER GULF WAR, KUWAIT REMAINS WARY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, July 27, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With two photos, of restaurants (NNS3) and Hazem
Jaber Ahmad (NNS4)
 By PAM LOUWAGIE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the weekend, time for Fozan Muhammed and his wife to
abandon their large house in the city, load their two children into
the Jeep, hitch up their boat and head for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The date was Aug. 1, 1990. Soldiers from neighboring Iraq were
threatening their tiny Persian Gulf emirate, disputing borders and
control over oil, but many Kuwaitis weren't fretting. Political
leaders were talking and many figured it would be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was thinking that things were getting cleared up,''
Muhammed said. ``There were no worries.''
</P>
<P>
   So he and his family hit the highway for a 45-minute drive to
their seaside ``chalet'' for a reprieve from the ovenlike heat.
They slept peacefully that night.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, their country was gone.
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of hours, Iraqi soldiers had occupied all 6,900
square miles of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We slept as Kuwaitis and woke up as Iraqis,'' said Sara Akbar,
a petroleum engineer. ``We lost our identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mass confusion filled the road back to Kuwait City. People drove
the wrong way on streets, desperate to escape Iraqi checkpoints.
Desert-beige tanks lined some roads. Muhammed and his family heard
bombing and shooting nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Panic blanketed the country for nearly seven months, as Iraqi
soldiers ransacked houses, raped women and gathered families to
witness the execution of a husband or father.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy Kuwaitis used to traveling the world suddenly felt a
trip across town was too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out of money, out of everything, out of country,''
Muhammed said. ``It's a strange feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Months of economic sanctions and intense negotiations by the
United Nations and the United States failed to persuade Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein to withdraw his troops and release his
choke hold on the world's oil supply and thousands of Westerners
trapped in Kuwait. So on Jan. 16, 1991, the United States and its
allies simultaneously started bombing the Iraqi capital of Baghdad
and parts of Kuwait to drive out Iraqi troops. When Operation
Desert Storm ended 42 days later, more than 500,000 American troops
had left home, families, friends and careers to answer the call.
</P>
<P>
   As the anniversary of the Iraqi invasion approaches, Kuwaitis
speak matter-of-factly about the conflict that changed their lives,
the rebuilding process and the unease they still feel about Iraq.
Most of the physical signs of war are gone. Roads torn up by tanks
have been paved smooth. Buildings once pockmarked from artillery
have been restored, and yards are cheery with blooming flowers.
Downtown, fancy cars buzz between tall buildings. Men in
traditional white robes carry briefcases into posh offices.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Kuwait looks like a modern, prosperous place
where locals have rebuilt their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Memories aren't cleaned up so easily, though.
</P>
<P>
   While many Westerners dismiss the Gulf War as a tidy conflict
that America dominated, Kuwaitis are still haunted by the gruesome
memories and by doubt about the country's own defenses and its role
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cleaned our houses, but our insides are still affected. You
feel the fear,'' said Masoumah Al-Mubarak, a political scientist at
Kuwait University. ``There's fear inside every Kuwaiti.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear has turned Hazem Jaber Ahmad into a war machine.
</P>
<P>
   A resistance organizer during the Gulf War, Ahmad has nightmares
about the day he watched his friends die.
</P>
<P>
   He and 18 other resisters knew the war was coming to an end, so
they gathered in a house in the middle of a neatly kept subdivision
to planfor the country's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the conversation in detail,'' Ahmad said through an
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted after nearly seven months of secretly plotting against
Iraqi occupiers, they sat on the home's pink carpet and
wide-striped couch, where they dared to think about life returning
to normal, joking and envisioning a peaceful vacation Ahmad and two
others planned to take in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, a knock at the door changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   An Iraqi soldier stood outside, and the Kuwaiti resisters
grabbed their guns to defend themselves. A first shot launched a
10-hour battle that eventually included about 700 Iraqi soldiers
laying siege to the house with tanks and guns.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ahmad's friends was killed when shrapnel ripped into his
arm and side. Several others were shot when Iraqis stormed the
house. The two he planned to vacation with died.
</P>
<P>
   When the battle became too much, Ahmad climbed into a ceiling
crawl space and hid, listening for hours to the horrors of war
around him.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of only seven survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Now called the Al-Quarain House, the building stands untouched
as a museumlike memorial. Shattered plaster littering the floor and
dried blood spattered on the wall serve as reminders of the human
price of war.
</P>
<P>
   The memories have driven Ahmad to prepare his mind and body for
future battles. He has spent the past decade studying weapons and
resistance methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Iraqis come again, I want to do more,'' said Ahmad, a
33-year-old policeman. ``Now I have the ability to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   It's memories like Ahmad's -- the nightmares, the stress of
knowing the enemy's leader is still in power just miles away --
that nag at Kuwaitis and keep the society strapped with tension.
</P>
<P>
   Horrific war crimes were reported during and after the war.
Amnesty International said Iraqi forces killed and tortured
hundreds of Kuwaitis, sometimes gouging out eyes or cutting off
tongues, ears or genitals; raping women; and leaving a dead Kuwaiti
hanging from a crane for others to see. One report said Iraqis left
more than 300 premature babies to die after stealing their
incubators from hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more cautious now,'' Akbar said. ``It's like when a
person gets bit by a snake: Every time he sees a rope moving, he
thinks it's a snake.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever there is a hint of trouble along the Iraq-Kuwait
border, people flock to grocery stores as if preparing for a
hurricane. Most families own a sport-utility vehicle capable of
plowing through desert sand in case they need to flee another
invasion. More are stashing money in foreign banks where they can
reach it if their country is invaded again, Kuwaitis said.
</P>
<P>
   Violent-crime rates have risen in the country, where citizens
possess weapons left over from the war.
</P>
<P>
   They live every day knowing their comforts can slip out from
under them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother used to keep her china only for the guests,'' one
Kuwaiti said. ``Then the Iraqis took it. She said she wished she
had enjoyed it more with her family.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the anger is directed at Saddam, who continues to
resurrect threats as he rules Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he's there, we can never be safe,'' said Khaled
Al-Ghanem, a Kuwaiti insurance broker.
</P>
<P>
   The only sense of safety comes from the U.S. soldiers and other
troops standing guard at Camp Doha, a permanent base about 20 miles
from Kuwait City.
</P>
<P>
   Financed mostly by the Kuwaiti government, the troops stand to
ward off aggression from Iraq's army. Nobody knows for sure how
long they will be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy kilometers from here are 1 million Iraqi soldiers
waiting to kill you,'' Lt. Col. Robert Costello of the Army
Reserve's 377th Theater Support Command in New Orleans told the
group during a recent training mission. Although considered a war
game by some, ``we don't play games here,'' Costello said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kuwaitis are grateful to have the troops there, they also
worry that America's presence has caused Kuwait to lose its status
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing they appear to be a puppet of the superpower, they
wonder whether the United States is quietly playing one country
against another for its own advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you guys,'' said investment manager Khalid Al-Habib,
while relaxing at a ``diwaniyah,'' a weekly Kuwaiti social
gathering where men in white robes drink tea and discuss politics.
``But ... you don't know how embarrassed we are when other states
say we are agents of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Tension between Kuwait and Iraq had existed for 30 years, by
some estimates. Kuwait often bought off Iraqi aggression, even
supporting Iraq to the tune of billions of dollars during the
Iran-Iraq War of the 1980s. But in 1990, Iraq claimed Kuwait had
stolen billions from Iraq's oil fields by drilling slanted wells
across the border. A decade later, bombings often still occur after
Iraqis try to shoot down U.S. planes patroling a no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
   And with Saddam still in power, the United Nations continues to
closely monitor Iraq's activities. Banned from most international
trade because of its invasion of Kuwait, Iraq is allowed to sell
oil to buy food and medicine for its people, and spare parts to
rebuild its oil industry, destroyed in Operation Desert Storm. But
U.N. inspectors fear Iraq also might restart the nuclear weapons
program it was forced to dismantle after the war.
</P>
<P>
   For Kuwait, that could mean that their Western defenders will be
with them for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Kuwaitis realize their country was rescued because of the oil
flowing under it. ``We like the fact that they (America) said from
the beginning they were here to take care of their own interests as
well as take care of Kuwait,'' Al-Ghanem said. ``We used to joke,
`Why do we have to worry? Why don't we just ask the States to make
it 51 states?'''
</P>
<P>
   American business came into the country en masse to help
extinguish more than 700 oil-well fires that retreating Iraqi
soldiers had set ablaze. Smoke covered the country for months,
turning daylight into dusk even at high noon.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, American influence on the culture has become
evident; in the past 10 years, Chili's, TGI Friday's, Fuddrucker's,
McDonald's and Applebee's have built restaurants near Kuwait City's
beaches and have become hot spots for teens. Calvin Klein jeans and
other U.S. goods fill fancy malls.
</P>
<P>
   In a traditionally conservative Islamic society, that's not
necessarily the kind of influence the locals want.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trendy food and clothes, ``teach me about technology,
hospitals, cars, education,'' Al-Habib said, ``not burritos.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kuwait's physical recovery was swift, the government
still is working on healing the emotional scars the war brought. In
an emirate rich with social welfare, the programs for emotional
healing are plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after the war ended, the emir created a special
government agency to coddle families of the ``Martyrs,'' the 589
Kuwaitis killed during the Gulf War. A social agency helps take
care of their children, following each child's school progress.
Psychologists help all family members deal with their emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to replace the father,'' said Torky Al-Anboy, a
manager at the agency. ``Especially for the kids who saw their
fathers being killed before their eyes, we need to break the hate
inside them. ... Instead of being aggressive, we need to bring them
back to normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   But as some Kuwaitis can attest, with war memories still fresh
in their hearts and an enemy leader still in power next door, life
as they knew it before the war might never return. As reminders,
war monuments dot the country, and yellow ribbons adorn signs,
business cards and bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Faiyza Al-Shubaiki, another worker at the government agency,
pulled out a thick photo album filled with photographs of dead
Kuwaitis, their bodies bruised, singed from acid or charred from
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know what happened,'' Al-Shubaiki said.
``Some people don't know about the torture. All they know was that
Kuwait was invaded and liberated.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Pam Louwagie is a staff writer with The Times-Picayune of New
Orleans)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
