<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACK-REPUBLICAN _ After nearly a decade as Islip, N.Y.'s,
elected town clerk, Joan Johnson, 66, is the Republican Party's
anointed choice to succeed Rick Lazio as New York's 2nd District
representative in Congress. That makes her at least even money to
become the first black Republican woman ever elected to Congress,
and from a district only about 10 percent black. Photos, map. About
2,100
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ROADTRIP _ The Bush campaign takes to the road Friday for a
pre-convention swing that targets six states carried by Clinton in
1996 with a prize of 74 electoral votes. About 900
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-RECOVERY _ Ten Years After Gulf War, Kuwait Remains Wary
(First of two articles; with sidebar, `KUWAIT-MISSING') (KUWAIT
CITY, Kuwait) On the surface, Kuwait looks like a modern,
prosperous place where locals have rebuilt their lives. Memories
aren't cleaned up so easily, though. As the 10th anniversary of the
Iraqi invasion approaches, Kuwaitis are still haunted by the
gruesome memories of war and by doubt about the country's own
defenses and its role in the Middle East. By Pam Louwagie. With
photos. About 2,000
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-MISSING _ Families Still Search for Those Absent Since
War (With ``KUWAIT-RECOVERY'') (KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait) Ten years the
Iraqi invasion, Kuwait is still missing 605 of its own -- quite a
lot given there are only about 650,000 Kuwaiti nationals in the
country. Most Kuwaiti families are missing a relative or friend.
And that's why accounting for the missing is still a major issue.
Yellow ribbons and the slogan ``Remember our POWs'' adorn
everything from private business cards to billboards. By Pam
Louwagie, 2nd story. About 600
</P>
<P>
   KUWAIT-CULTURE _ Western Culture Transforming Country (Second of
two articles) (KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait) Kuwait is a living oxymoron. In
a modern Middle Eastern country where Western ideas are
infiltrating much of society, balancing the Westernization with
traditional Arab values is proving a difficult juggling act. As in
many societies, Kuwaitis say change is coming through its young
people and its women, with teen-agers rebelling against Arab
traditions such as wearing robes and women becoming more educated
and taking on bigger jobs. At the same time, religious
fundamentalists are working to push the society back to tradition.
By Pam Louwagie, 3rd story. With photos. About 1,800
</P>
</TEXT>
