<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-BLACK-REPUBLICAN-NEWH     07-27 2352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-REPUBLICAN-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN CLERK IN SUBURBAN NEW YORK STANDS ON THE LIP OF POLITICAL
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, July 27, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With graphic showing map and demographics of New
York's 2nd Congressional District, and two photos of Joan Johnson
(NNS1 and NNS2) 
 By JONATHAN TILOVE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   House slaves, says Joan Johnson, were often misjudged.
</P>
<P>
   They were viewed as docile and loyal, she says, when, in fact,
``they were spitting in their (masters') food, urinating in their
food to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What you don't do is the upfront thing,'' the 66-year-old
suburban public official says, describing that as a lesson
hard-learned by black Americans in slavery and segregation. ``It
has helped me to get where I am today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand on the edge of history because I learned survival
skills as a child growing up in the South, that when I hear racist
and bigoted stuff in the North that I thought didn't exist, I just
simply bide my time and say, `I'll have my opportunity someday.'''
</P>
<P>
   That day is now, and Johnson's perch on the lip of history is
more than a rhetorical flourish.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a decade as the elected town clerk of Islip, N.Y.,
Johnson is the Republican Party's anointed choice to succeed Rick
Lazio as New York's 2nd District representative in Congress. That
makes her at least even money to become the first black Republican
women ever elected to Congress. She would also double black
Republican representation on Capitol Hill, joining J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma, at a time when the Republican Party is desperate to
demonstrate greater appeal to black and brown Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's candidacy is, of course, thrilling to folks like
Ronald Radford Sr., president of Suffolk County's 35-year-old
Afro-American Republican Club.
</P>
<P>
   But her selection also delights more than a few black Democrats
in her Long Island district, who are instantly better situated to
make demands on their own party now that it's not the only one
seriously contending for black votes. It's a scenario that the
nation's small cadre of black Republicans has promoted for years,
but one that seldom had the benefit of a compelling and concrete
example.
</P>
<P>
   And while her prospective opponents dismiss her as a well-worn
cog in the Republican machine whose experience best qualifies her
to continue issuing peddler's permits and marriage licenses, the
Joan Johnson who emerges from an interview in her campaign office
along quaint Main Street is the anti-clerk, a black woman liberated
and on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to black people across this country is you should
divorce the Democratic Party for non-support,'' she declares.
``Look at your lives. Individuals have benefited, but they don't
seem to be able to translate that back to your community. Why
haven't they been bartering their votes to bring things to their
communities? ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not one group in the country that gives 85 percent of
its vote to one party. No group. No group,'' she roars. ``People
just getting off the boat don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's healthy,'' said Paul Johnson, past president of the
Suffolk County Council of Black Democrats, of his unrelated
namesake's selection by the rival party.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a retired public relations executive with the Long
Island Lighting Co., is supporting Steve Israel, a councilman in
his hometown of Huntington, who is seeking the Democratic
nomination for Lazio's seat. But, he said, ``This is a wake-up call
for everybody. Generally we're given a chance to run for something
we can't win, just to bring out the black vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, in addition to Joan Johnson, there are only two other
black elected officials in Suffolk County -- a Democratic town
clerk in Babylon and a Republican judge from Islip.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was, we just got outflanked,'' said Leonard
F. Canton Jr., one of those black Democrats who has run and lost in
Suffolk.
</P>
<P>
   But Canton's second reaction was to join an effort by
like-minded black Democrats in the town of Babylon to field a
29-year-old black woman lawyer, Ghenya Grant, for the Democratic
nomination for Congress. Canton and his allies are angered at what
they consider a long history of being taken for granted and
double-dealed by the Democratic powers-that-be locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They betrayed us. They are going to feel our rage,'' said
Eugene Burnett, who chairs the Babylon Town Caucus of Black
Democrats and is mentoring Grant's candidacy. ``It would be
interesting, two African-American women running for Congress on
Long Island. I'd love that.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of one African-American woman running for Congress
on Long Island has proved plenty interesting as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shocker; it took everybody by surprise,'' said Delano
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who was Jesse Jackson's Long Island campaign
coordinator in 1984, publishes Point of View, a monthly
African-American newspaper in Suffolk. When Suffolk Republicans
announced the choice of Johnson, Stewart wrote that it was, to some
observers, ``a stroke of genius.''
</P>
<P>
   The district is only about 10 percent black, and another 10
percent Hispanic. But if, as he believes, Johnson can pull up to
half the black vote -- which usually votes more than 90 percent
Democratic -- it could make the difference in a district that
overwhelmingly re-elected Lazio yet also decisively voted for
President Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson notes that she has outpolled white running mates in town
elections, even providing some crossover coattails. But others
wonder whether these mostly white Republican suburbs are really
prepared to send a black woman like Johnson to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will the white Republicans vote for Joan Johnson?'' Canton
asked. Not, he suspects, in sufficient numbers.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson faces a Republican primary in September against Robert
T. Walsh, who works as the United Nations representative of a
humanitarian agency that cares for orphans, cancer victims and the
homeless and who will also run in November as the Right-to-Life
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said he has heard from many loyal Republicans upset with
the party's choice. ``Party leaders chose her, with all due
respect, because of her race, her gender and her (abortion rights)
position on life,'' said Walsh. ``I tell you they've blown it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also faces a primary for the Conservative Party line, on
which Republicans depend for a crucial lift in close elections. But
the Suffolk Conservative Party chairman predicted that Johnson will
easily prevail.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Grant and Israel, 42, will face David
Bishop, 35, a county legislator from Babylon.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the very fact that Johnson was picked by a powerful
machine that never shows the slightest attraction to lost causes is
evidence she can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting move,'' said Jeff Garrett, who runs a
beauty supply store in the heart of Wyandanch, the district's most
concentrated black community. But, he concluded, ``The Republicans
in Islip know what they are doing. They have a stranglehold on the
town.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the choice of state Sen. Caesar Trunzo, the boss in
Islip, which makes up half the district, and the new Suffolk County
Republican Chairman Anthony Apollaro. With control of Congress in
the balance, loss of this seat would look very bad.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is not the only black Republican candidate for Congress
this year.
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, an expert on black politics at the Joint Center
for Political and Economic Studies in Washington, said that when
the dust settles from the last primaries, they will probably number
18 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bositis said, Johnson is the only one with a really good
chance of winning. Two others -- Jennifer Carroll in Florida and
Dylan Glenn in Georgia -- are running formidable campaigns against
black Democratic incumbents but remain very long shots, in his
view.
</P>
<P>
   Bositis said Johnson struck him as a ``good fit and wise pick''
for New York Republicans. He thinks she will be a tough target for
Democrats because ``she comes across as authentically black. She
doesn't sound like a white guy who works for the Republican
National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson grew up ensconced in the warmth of a large and
successful extended family in segregated West Palm Beach, Fla. Her
clan had their own compound, their own water tower. ``We owned the
service station, beauty shop and general store,'' she recalled. Her
father was a butler and chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   Racism intruded when she would venture outside ``colored town,''
or, most vividly, the time when she was 12 or 13 and a white police
officer, who had apparently just beaten up a neighbor boy, saw her
point him out to a girlfriend as he drove by where she lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `If I ever see you point a finger at a white man
again, you see this revolver, I'll blow your brains out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although her father was out of sight but close by, she did not
call out to him. ``I remember that in that split moment I thought
that if I called my father, my father could be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came to New York City to pursue a career as a jazz
singer (she imagines Congress as ``another opening, another
show''), but in the 1960s moved to Suffolk with her husband, a New
York City police officer, to raise a family. She became a
Republican because that was what you did to ``move around out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Her choice of party was confirmed when, not long after, as an
official of the local NAACP, she sought to persuade Democratic
candidates in Islip to take on open housing as an issue. She was
told it was political suicide because ``you people don't vote.''
She reported back to the NAACP that, ``if I closed my eyes I was at
a Klan meeting in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Republicans who ran Islip, where her husband
was by then the housing administrator, enacted what she describes
as a very strong open housing law. By 1969, her husband was Islip's
deputy supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   A social worker by training, she has served over the years as a
school board member, Head Start director, affirmative action
officer and deputy commissioner of human services for the town.
</P>
<P>
   When she was sworn in as Islip town clerk in 1991, she said,
``I'm hoping this will do for politics (on Long Island) what Jackie
Robinson did for baseball.'' (Robinson himself was a Rockefeller
Republican.) She said upfront and out loud that it was a
steppingstone to higher office.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has officiated at 2,500 weddings. She won the
title Ms. Senior New York, performing ``My Funny Valentine.'' This
year she sang the national anthem at the opening day of the new
local baseball franchise, the Long Island Ducks. She teaches a
local college course on urban minorities for criminal justice
majors, some of whom, she said, ``come from the antiseptic
communities of Long Island, have never had to deal with black
people and live in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was that.
</P>
<P>
   But then New York Mayor Giuliani bowed out of the Senate race
against Hillary Rodham Clinton, Lazio jumped in, and Pete McGowan,
the Islip town supervisor and obvious successor to Lazio, stood
aside. Johnson wanted it, and Apollaro and Trunzo gave her the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they were going to be so smart,'' Johnson said,
adding that she thought her biggest political obstacle would not be
her race but her gender.
</P>
<P>
   On the issues, Johnson is a shade more liberal than Lazio, an
old ally, who compiled a moderate record in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   She supports abortion rights, and partial birth abortion if the
mother's life is at stake. She supports gun registration. She
helped persuade Lazio to defy Republican efforts to gut the
National Endowment for the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The one issue where she is most at odds with most blacks is that
she believes President Clinton should have been impeached, an issue
over which Lazio agonized. ``He put his hand on the Bible and he
lied,'' Johnson said of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   She has already been to GOP candidate school in Washington, and
dined with Majority Leader Dick Armey and top party fund-raisers at
the Capitol Grill. She has been given time to speak on the opening
morning of the national convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But Howard University political scientist Lorenzo Morris said
that
</P>
<P>
   if she wants to raise the money she will need, she will have to
toe the national Republican line to a degree that will make it
impossible for her to claim half the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   (THIRD OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   There are now 38 black Democrats in the House, and with
Democratic control they would gain the chairmanships of some of the
most powerful committees, beginning with Harlem's Charlie Rangel at
Ways and Means.
</P>
<P>
   (FOURTH OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think African-American voters will realize that a Democratic
Congress is critical to the future of African-Americans in this
country,'' said David Bishop, the primary contender.
</P>
<P>
   (FOURTH OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Says Johnson, ``Charlie Rangel's party had the damn majority for
40 years and there has been no appreciable change in the lives of
black people in Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thinks she can win this argument, and that when she
does, she can sell it to black voters elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to transport it,'' she said. ``I am going to be the
Harriet Tubman, I am going to take them through the underground and
out of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
