<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CHEER-PETERSON0728-CO     07-27 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEER-PETERSON0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Being stereotyped not a concern for gay scriptwriter
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Long before his first script ever went before
the cameras, Brian Wayne Peterson's career was heating up.
</P>
<P>
   Based solely on his spoof of gay rehabilitation camps ``But I'm
A Cheerleader,'' Variety named him one of ``10 Screenwriters to
Watch'' in 1999. Now after a rocky road of production delays, a
distributor pullout and a temporary NC-17 rating, the 28-year-old
gay writer from Montana is waiting to see whether moviegoers are
ready to watch.
</P>
<P>
   In South Florida last month to attend a Pride FilmFest
screening, Peterson's spirits were buoyed by the reaction of the
predominantly gay audience. Still, he knows his satirical film must
attract a wider audience to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do definitely think this has crossover appeal,'' he said,
sitting at a Fort Lauderdale bookstore cafe. ``At worst, it's going
to capture the gay market.'' But that is hardly a demographic that
needs to hear the message of tolerance. ``I don't think a movie can
ever change someone's mind, but it can become a catalyst for
dialogue,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``Cheerleader `` came from first-time feature
director Jamie Babbit, who grew up around an alcohol rehab facility
where her mother worked. It led her to lampoon gay deprogramming
camps, which are proliferating. ``They're everywhere,'' reports
Peterson. Many are ``around Orange County, Calif., and other
rabidly conservative areas. But anywhere you are in the country you
can find them.''
</P>
<P>
   As ridiculous as he tried to make the camp, it is not far from
the truth, Peterson says. ``The funny thing is I don't think we
could make it any more absurd than it is. That's why we pushed it
even further, because otherwise it would have been reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Peterson actually visited a gay rehab to research his
script. ``No, I'm a very angry person and I wouldn't have lasted
long in one,'' he concedes. ``I probably would have gotten
arrested.'' At college in Oregon, while several anti-gay voter
initiatives were pending, he obtained a propaganda video that
depicted the rehab process. ``I would go around to fraternities
doing like this Homo 101 program, explaining that we are not like
the video says we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he make any progress? ``I got a really good date out of one
of them,'' he reports with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson came to Babbit's attention because of his unproduced
University of Southern California master's thesis script about a
gay rodeo. Yes, they do exist. ``I just think it's the greatest
world for a film, because of the juxtaposition of two different
things you would never expect,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he is not worried about being stereotyped as a gay
screenwriter. ``Everything that anyone's ever told me has been
`Write what you know, write what you like,' '' explains Peterson.
``Every time I have not been very successful has been when I do
stray from that, doing something because I think it will be
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself at the beginning, if possible I would always
have a positive representation of a gay or lesbian in my movies.
Even if it's a minor character, it can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   From this low-budget independent picture, Peterson learned that
making movies is about rewriting and waiting. He began writing
around Christmas 1997, completing the first draft in a month.
Babbit liked what she read, a production company called Ignite
bought it and Peterson spent the next year revising the screenplay.
At one point, Fine Line signed to distribute ``Cheerleader,'' then
dropped out. ``I honestly don't know what happened with the
negotiations,'' says Peterson. ``I was wearing a Fine Line shirt at
Sundance and now I have a Lion's Gate T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   He does know what happened with the movie's rating and feels
certain a double standard was at work. ``Cheerleader'' was
initially slapped with a deadly NC-17 rating because it dealt with
gay teen sex and was made outside the Hollywood system, Peterson
says. His view was confirmed for him when he saw the R-rated
``Election,'' which covers similar territory. ``But it was with a
big studio that had the clout and because it was a straight
situation, not a gay situation,'' he charges. Cuts were made to
gain an R-rating, though ``I can't even really tell where the scene
is different. That's how minuscule the change is.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson has other film scripts he is trying to peddle and he
has been taking developmental meetings about some television work.
</P>
<P>
   His fate now largely rests with the box office response to
``Cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ifmed Lance Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is very good at keeping these characters distinct and
vivid, but the real star is five-time Oscar-winning makeup wizard
Rick Baker. Frankly, the only reason I am sure Murphy is under all
that latex is that the credits say so. With enough makeup, you can
hide anyone these days, as ``Big Momma's House'' with Martin
Lawrence proved.
</P>
<P>
   The problem _ and the preview audience that was convulsed in
laughter showed no evidence of minding _ is that director Peter
Segal (''Naked Gun 33-1/3'') and his committee of writers from ``In
Living Color,'' ``Saturday Night Live'' and ``American Pie'' have
no idea what to do with all these characters beyond flatulence and
bodily fluid jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The Klumps, as you may recall, are robust eaters, so early on
they head to a buffet to chow down with gusto and break wind with
equal satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   If Sherman took a weight-reduction potion last time that turned
him into lean, mean Buddy, this time he comes up with a youth
serum. Having made sufficient fun of fat people, the sequel targets
old folks, taking particular amusement in the effects of age and
gravity on the human body.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy is back and, for the sake of a few strained laughs, he
occasionally thinks he is a dog. Muddying the plot _ which never
manages to feel like a sustained story _ is Sherman's tampering
with his DNA, which causes him to gradually lose brain cells. And
the rest of the Klumps prattle on, led by randy Granny, grouchy
Papa and upbeat Mama.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the sketch comedy writing is an odd detour for a
parody of ``Star Wars,'' whose reason for existing seems to be the
revelation that the force behind The Force is _ what else? _
flatulence.
</P>
<P>
   Plugged into the Jada Pinkett role as Sherman's romantic
interest is Janet Jackson, playing a professorial colleague who
also doesn't miss many meals. She is the movie's lone straight man,
which means looking teary-eyed as Sherman's brain turns to mush.
</P>
<P>
   Listed again as one of the movie's executive producers is Jerry
Lewis, an acknowledgement that all this began with his 1963 Jekyll
and Hyde update. At the risk of siding with the French, that
kinder, gentler, no-less-silly comic style seems a remnant of a
golden age, compared with what Murphy hath wrought.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he is not alone, as the popularity of ``Scary Movie''
and ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' demonstrate. One day, dumb and gross
comedies will fall out of favor, but it doesn't look like it will
happen anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
