u w BC-ELDERLY-TAX28-COX     07-27 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-TAX28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PASSES BILL TO EASE TAX ON SOME SOCIAL SECURITY BENEFITS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Passing yet another tax cut bill before beginning a
long summer recess, the House voted Thursday to reduce the amount
of Social Security benefits for higher-income retirees that would
be subject to federal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 265-159. Fifty-two Democrats crossed party lines to
join all but four Republicans in supporting the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was the latest in a series of tax cut bills, the
product of a strategy to win in small pieces what GOP leaders
failed to achieve last year, when President Clinton vetoed a
comprehensive tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the leaders offered a proposed repeal of the
3 percent federal telephone excise tax, a phase-out of the estate
tax, and adjustments to the so-called ``marriage penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has threatened to veto all the measures,
claiming the bills favor the rich, spend the projected budget
surplus, and place Social Security and Medicare at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Senate action is not likely until Congress returns in September.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would reduce from 85 percent to 50 percent the
amount of Social Security benefits subject to the federal income
tax for elderly individuals who earn more than $34,000, and couples
earning more than $44,000 who file jointly. That was the level
subject to taxation before the law was changed in 1993 as part of
the Clinton deficit reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would reduce the amount of taxes credited to Medicare
by $117 billion over 10 years and replace that with money from the
projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton would veto the
bill ``unless they can come up with a way of doing this that does
not threaten the Medicare trust fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., who managed the bill on the House
floor, said it was immoral to tax Social Security recipients on
benefits for which they already have paid taxes when they were
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wrong to tax people on getting their own money back,''
Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the tax rate was increased at a time when the
federal government faced a $255 billion deficit, House Ways and
Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, argued that it was
no longer necessary because the federal surplus this year is $233
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats warned that rolling back the Social Security tax could
jeopardize Medicare because the increased rate is earmarked for the
Medicare trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose the speculated surplus doesn't show up?'' asked Rep.
Charles Rangel of New York, the ranking Democrat on the Ways and
Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., argued that the GOP plan was ``a gift
to the very rich,'' because it would not affect 80 percent of the
Social Security recipients who do not pay the highest rate.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw argued that ``to say we're ... helping our rich friends is
absolutely ludicrous, unless you think people making $34,000 are
rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that the GOP plan would further endanger
efforts to provide a Medicare prescription drug benefit.
Republicans responded that reducing the Social Security rate would
not affect Medicare and would not prohibit adoption of a
prescription drug plan.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic alternative that would have raised the threshold on
those eligible for the maximum tax liability from $34,000 to
$80,000 for individuals and from $44,000 to $100,000 for couples
was rejected, 256-169.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress legislative action: thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
