<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE NAPSTER RULING, EXPERTS SAY ONLINE SHARING WILL SURVIVE
 &HT;    Moving in (l) lifestyle and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB KEEFE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Distraught music fans jammed Napster on Thursday, a
day after a federal judge ordered the leading Internet
music-swapping site to close in order to protect copyrighted
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my god they killed Napster,'' wailed a visitor to a Napster
online forum who went by the name ``born-4-music.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Napster may be off line, at least temporarily, after
midnight Friday, industry observer said they don't expect the
burgeoning business of delivering music and other entertainment
over the Internet to miss more than a beat or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to the law, technology and the human
appetite for something free continues to stay ahead of the law,''
said Gary Arlen, a Bethesda, Md., Internet industry consultant.
``This might slow it down, but it's not going to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Delivering music, movies and software over the Web is one of the
hottest areas of the Internet these days. Industry researchers
predict that will only grow as more households gain high-speed
access.
</P>
<P>
   So far, online music has been dominated by a few companies such
as Napster that make no money from the songs listed on their
directories, but sell advertising from companies that want to tap
into the thousands of visitors they get each day. Napster, for
instance, claims 20 million visitors since it got started a little
more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies _ including Napster _ aren't likely to let
the potential profits from that business pass them by because of
disagreements like the one between Napster and the Recording
Industry Association of America (RIAA).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this spells the death knell at all of music or
entertainment on the Internet,'' said Larry Waks, an Austin, Texas,
attorney who specializes in music and copyright issues. ``It's just
the age-old story about the law trying to keep up with
technological inventions.''
</P>
<P>
   There are many other companies using the Napster model for
sharing music files, but the recording industry's biggest nightmare
might be a program called Gnutella, which allows individuals with
music on their personal computers to quickly make connections with
large numbers of other fans.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Napster, there is no central server with a directory of
songs that the industry can target with a lawsuit or a court
injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Napster were busy Thursday preparing an appeal of
Wednesday's ruling, and the company showed no signs of giving up.
</P>
<P>
   Napster has some heavy hitters on its side.
</P>
<P>
   The lead attorney representing the San Mateo, Calif.-based
company is David Boies, who recently led the successful efforts to
win a federal antitrust ruling against Microsoft Corp. Its chief
executive is Hank Barry, a former entertainment industry attorney
turned venture capitalist. And the money behind Napster comes from
Hummer Winblad Venture Partners, a powerful Silicon Valley venture
capital firm that pumped $15 million into the company in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``There some very smart people there, and I would suspect they
will emerge with some sort of product and technology which is more
viable,'' said Vincent Grosso, a former vice president of NBC
Interactive who now is chief executive of Into Networks Inc., which
rents software over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some Internet music companies have changed the way they
do
</P>
<P>
   business. After it was sued by the RIAA earlier this year, San
Diego-based MP3.com Inc., for instance, struck a deal in which it
gives record labels a small payment each time one of its visitors
downloads a piece of copyrighted music.
</P>
<P>
   What Wednesday's ruling will do is force the question of who
owns what on the Internet to the forefront, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inevitable that the legislators are going to get
involved,'' said MP3.com executive vice president Billy Pitts, just
hired by the company as its chief lobbyist in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Pitts and MP3.com _ named after the highly
compressed format that made music transmission over the Internet
viable at dial-up speeds _ are planning a nationwide drive to get
online music aficionados to contact their representatives. Their
goal is to get legislation or regulation on their terms and to keep
the battle out of the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts said he envisions an ``e-bill of rights'' that would
determine what is and isn't off-limits in sharing files over the
Internet, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet should not be ruled by a small cadre of
hand-picked judges who are trying to interpret what the law
means,'' Pitts said.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that one of the industry's biggest
challenges is explaining to Congress how online music works.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say MP3 on the Hill, they say ``Oh, it's down the hall
on the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Keefe's e-mail address is bkeefe(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
