<SLUG> BC-STEVENS0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WestPoint Stevens has expected loss, blamed on large
restructuring charge
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As expected, WestPoint Stevens said earnings were hurt
by a large restructuring charge.
</P>
<P>
   The West Point-based sheet and towel maker reported a
second-quarter loss of $89.8 million, or $1.81 a share, compared
with a profit of $19.6 million, or 34 cents a share, in the same
quarter last year. The results included a one-time pretax charge of
$168.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   WestPoint Stevens announced a major restructuring last month.
Another $27 million in one-time charges will come later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the quarter rose slightly to $462 million, compared
with $453.5 million one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, WestPoint Stevens recorded a loss of $74.2
million, or $1.50 a share, compared with profit of $35.2 million,
or 61 cents a share. Those results include the one-time charge.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, WestPoint Stevens said it will close some old mills
and get rid of certain support and administrative jobs as it tries
to pay off debt. The company hasn't identified the operations that
will go.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring, which follows a derailed plan to take
WestPoint Stevens private, is expected to save the company $5
million this year and $15 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
