<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-WORLDCOM0728-COX     07-27 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDCOM0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WorldCom hints at spinoff as profits rise
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WorldCom Thursday reported a solid quarter of growth,
while hinting at a spinoff or tracking stock for its business in
consumer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, Miss.-based WorldCom's revenue rose to $10.2 billion
during the second quarter, compared to $9.1 billion during the same
period of 1999. The company reported earnings of $1.3 billion,
representing 46 cents per share, up from $865 million, or 30 cents
a share, one year earlier. Those results matched a consensus of
analyst expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Those results did not include a $55 million charge taken by the
company as part of the failed deal with Sprint _ an agreement
blocked by regulators on both sides of the Atlantic largely because
the merged company would share long-distance domination with AT&AMP;T.
WorldCom Chief Executive Bernard Ebbers bitterly criticized the
regulators, arguing that price wars and competition make profits
increasingly hard to come by in consumer long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   A former Wall Street highflier, WorldCom has seen its stock
languish of late, weighed down by investor disdain for slow growth
and iffy profits. WorldCom stock this year has dropped about 25
percent, compared to a 12 percent decline for SBC Communications
and a 16 percent dip for BellSouth. However, AT&AMP;T has fallen 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rumors continue to fly about WorldCom's next move.
The company has ached to go wireless, an urge that may not have
died along with the Sprint deal. But few enticing _ and affordable
_ targets remain. WorldCom could bid against Deutsche Telekom,
which has a $50 billion pact to buy VoiceStream. It could return to
Nextel, now much more costly than when WorldCom passed up a
purchase. There are other players, like Alltel and Powertel, that
are attractive, if not national.
</P>
<P>
   And WorldCom might still find a way to purchase Sprint's
wireless unit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
