<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PROSECUTORS SUDDENLY DROP PROBE OF MEDIA BARON 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian prosecutors Thursday abruptly dropped their
high-profile criminal inquiry into Vladimir V. Gusinsky, the
Russian press tycoon whose Media-Most empire has been among the
Kremlin's sharpest critics.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not explain why had they abandoned the
investigation, which began with a spectacular May raid by
ski-masked policemen and climaxed in June with Gusinsky's brief
imprisonment on embezzlement charges. As recently as three weeks
ago, prosecutors insisted to Parliament that Gusinsky had defrauded
the government of at least $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was notable that the inquiry was halted virtually on the eve
of a Kremlin meeting between many of the country's wealthiest
tycoons and President Vladimir Putin, whose government has moved
against several of them in tax and criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called round table is widely viewed as an attempt to win
concessions from the tycoons _ including, perhaps, promises to
surrender their deep-rooted influence over government agencies and
leaders _ in exchange for an end to federal hectoring.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky was not invited to that meeting. But like other
tycoons, he in effect stood accused of building his empire _ a
collection of print and broadcast outlets _ through corruption and
influence-peddling in the early days of Russian independence, and
the other had lined up to support him.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gusinsky insisted that the charges were a sham,
designed to punish Media-Most for its criticism of Putin's handling
of the war in Chechnya and of corruption in the administration of
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky's counterattack proved so adroit that even the U.S.
White House offered him its tacit support, sending President
Clinton to an interview at a Media-Most radio station during the
recent summit meeting in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Gusinsky's spokesman and his lawyer said simply that
the charges had been dropped for lack of evidence to support them.
A letter from the prosecutor's office was published Thursday on the
Media-Most Web site (www.mediamost.ru) stating only that the
proceedings had been canceled and that assets seized during its
course had been unfrozen.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's office refused to confirm that the letter was
genuine. But an unidentified official in the agency's
public-relations office told the Interfax news service that
Gusinsky had been cleared as a suspect in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Since the day in mid-May that the federal police swooped into
the headquarters of Media-Most, toting automatic rifles and wearing
camouflage and black ski masks, the object of the investigation has
never been completely clear.
</P>
<P>
   Gusinsky apparently was accused of swindling $10 million or more
from the Yeltsin government in 1997, during a deal involving the
privatization of a bankrupt St. Petersburg television station. But
details of that accusation never became public.
</P>
<P>
   At other times, investigators seized records of hundreds of
millions of dollars in loans or guarantees given Media-Most by
Gazprom, the state-controlled natural-gas monopoly, which has
called the aid a simple business investment. And at one point, the
prosecutors seized a souvenir gun that Yeltsin had once given
Gusinsky, saying he had no permit to own it.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the anonymous spokesman for the prosecutors told
Interfax that the inquiry into the St. Petersburg television deal
would continue, but that its focus had shifted from Gusinsky and
Media-Most.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gusinsky, freed from the prosecutors' ban on his travel outside
Russia, had flown to Spain on Wednesday evening to see his family
and was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the investigation, in mid-June, officials
jailed Gusinsky, a multimillionaire with citizenship in both Russia
and Israel, for three days in Butyrskaya detention center, a
notoriously decrepit and dangerous holding pen for Moscow street
criminals. The resulting outcry led even government officials to
say the investigators might have pushed the boundaries of
propriety.
</P>
<P>
   Putin at times seemed to mildly rebuke the prosecutors for their
conduct, but maintained that the prosecutor's office was an
independent agency beyond his control. More than once, he has
suggested that the tycoons built their riches on corruption and
that they have no grounds to complain when that corruption comes
under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But it was never quite clear how much Putin was involved in the
campaign against Gusinsky. And today, it was still not clear how
much he was involved in its apparent end.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, I'd say this has a certain rough
correspondence with the way the rule of law is supposed to work _
they investigated him, didn't find anything, and closed the case,''
said Alan E. Rousso, the director of the Moscow Center of the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. ``But the reality is a
little more nuanced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact he's been cleared of all charges doesn't exonerate
the government for the way this was done,'' Rousso said. ``And it
doesn't answer the question about whether this is some sort of
witch hunt and exertion of presidential power, or a true clearing
of the Augean stables. That remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   One tycoon, Anatoly Chubais, who got his start as Yeltsin's
economic expert and deputy prime minister, called on Putin on
Thursday in an interview in the business newspaper Kommersant to
show his hand and either wave the prosecutors off, or let
corruption inquiries go forward with his explicit blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was implying that the prosecutor's office was
not independent, as Putin says, Chubais was succinct. ``Never has
been, is not, and won't be for some time,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
