<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-JFK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MAN AT JFK LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy was an ardent internationalist. Had he lived, it
is safe to say he would now be deeply fascinated and involved with
the complex forces of globalization, and especially the
strengthening of democracy and human rights around the world.
</P>
<P>
   So the appointment announced Thursday of John Shattuck, now US
ambassador to the Czech Republic, to be the new chief executive
officer of the Kennedy Library and Foundation, is both appropriate
and hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck's selection signals significant changes. For one thing,
he will be the first leader of the Library and Foundation who did
not know Kennedy personally. He succeeds Charles U. Daly, who was
in Larry O'Brien's legislative office in the Kennedy White House.
This transition, too, is fitting, for most of the people who visit
the Library now have no personal memory of JFK.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the success of Shattuck's tenure at the Library will
likely depend on his ability to marshal the institution's abundant
resources not in response to people's memories, but in support of
their desires _ especially for public service.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck, a former executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union office in Washington, was also a vice president of
Harvard; in Cambridge he was active in supporting improvements in
public education.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy said Thursday a key to Shattuck's
appointment was his note expressing ``a real vision for the Library
for the next 20 years,'' including strengthened programs to inspire
young people and promote civic action.
</P>
<P>
   This is crucial. People, young or old, cannot be shamed into
public service; they will participate enthusiastically when they
believe their efforts will bear fruit. Shattuck has laid out an
impressive agenda including human rights, public education, the
Peace Corps, and the promotion of political debate around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Library and Foundation has always been more than a
museum. Shattuck will serve his neighbors in Boston and the global
community well if he can further strengthen its substantive work
and its clout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
