<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER'S LAST DAYS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of free music on the Internet are swamping the Napster Web
site to complain about a judge's ruling against the music service _
while also snatching a few last downloads. But Judge Marilyn Patel
was correct: Napster facilitates copyright infringement and should
not operate in its present form.
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry, which brought the suit, would be wise
not to blindly oppose downloading of popular songs, however.
Instead it should adapt this useful technology so that industry and
artists get a fair return. Otherwise, music fans will seek out
alternative free sources of music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than keep fighting this case through the courts, music
companies would be better off buying or allying themselves with
Napster, which has the most popular music search program on the
Net. Many of the 20 million people who have downloaded the program
would pay reasonable monthly fees for an improved Napster.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a long legal struggle is likely. Napster lawyers went
before the US appeals court in San Francisco in hopes of staving
off compliance with the decision, which was to take effect this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Napster argues that it does not encourage the sharing of
copyrighted works. That argument is disingenuous. Unlike other
music services on the Web, Napster does not focus on new artists
who make their work freely available. Instead it encourages users
to search for performers they know, almost invariably famous acts
who have not given approval for the use of their copyrighted tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Patel did not order Napster shut down, but her decision would
force it to prevent the sharing of copyrighted songs, a practical
impossibility. She considered the evidence so overwhelming that she
took action before the lawsuit went to trial. Napster's case is
weak as it pursues legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is an easy-to-use program, which would benefit from
improvements to track specific songs and encourage connecting links
so users could sample new artists and learn more about favorite
performers. If it abandons its resistance-at-any-cost strategy, the
recording industry could make beautiful music with this powerful
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
