<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MIDEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING PEACE ANOTHER CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The announcement that Palestinian and Israeli negotiators will
meet Sunday to renew their search for a comprehensive agreement
suggests a shared realization that there is no tolerable
alternative to a negotiated peace.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the triumphal welcome for Yasser Arafat orchestrated by
his Fatah faction, the reality is that, in the wake of his failure
to get to yes at Camp David, his people have to go on living under
the thumb of Israel _ without jobs, without proper public services,
and deprived of the conditions for genuine self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one crucial reason why Arafat was not able to engage in
the give-and-take required for a compromise on the key issue of
Jerusalem is that his corrupt and incompetent governance of
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza the last few years has
eroded his popularity, his credibility, and his margin for
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   For different reasons, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel has
also suffered attrition in his political standing. Because of
defections from his governing coalition, Barak arrived at Camp
David without the optimal flexibility for striking a historic
compromise with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   It is encouraging that both sides are saying that the missed
opportunity at Camp David marks not a dead-end but a stepping stone
on the path to an agreement. For this rosy rhetoric to become a
reality, certain decisive actions must be taken:
</P>
<P>
   Barak will have to reconstitute a coalition that backs the
difficult concessions required for peace. Arafat will have to
refrain from unilaterally declaring an independent Palestinian
state on Sept. 13 if there is no accord by that date. President
Clinton will need to call in some chits with the Saudis and the
Egyptians, pressing them to give Arafat the cover he needs to
accept partial rather than complete Palestinian sovereignty in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that Arab regimes have a long history of giving
the Palestinians nothing but lip service. Now they have to give
Arafat the leeway to strike a realistic bargain with Israel, for
the sake of his people and their future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
