<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4921 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MOVIES-BOS &LR;      07-27 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MOVIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVING AWAY MOVIEMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grand jury probe of the contracts between Teamsters Local 25
and major Hollywood movie producers will cast some needed light on
the featherbedding and strong-arm tactics that undercut moviemaking
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Cellucci, a big fan of both movies and Teamsters, needs
to focus on reality. He is the chief executive of a state where the
shakedown of movie producers is apparently an art form. The hiring
of no-show drivers is just part of it. The grand jury is also
investigating allegations that Teamster officials pressure
producers to hire the Location Connection, an equipment rental
company with suspected links to organized crime in Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   Producers of low-budget movies or commercials who are not
required to hire Teamsters also face the prospect of disruptions on
the set. They learn quickly that Teamsters leaning on their horns
don't do much to enhance a boudoir scene. Slashed tires are a sign
to roll with the Teamsters or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   Local 25 Teamster chief George Cashman and Cellucci
administration officials have been promoting the construction of a
sound stage complex in Boston to give the region a better chance to
attract large-scale movie productions. Cashman had pledged to put
an end to Teamster turmoil on the set. But he didn't deliver. It
now appears that any sound stage with Teamster involvement will be
nothing more than a snare for movie producers who will later be
devoured by the movie unit of Local 25.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor in New England cannot be pleased by the
performance of their Teamster brothers. Union carpenters, painters,
electricians, actors, and others lose work when wary movie
producers shun New England. Teamsters President James P. Hoffa
can't be happy, either. His Boston operation is becoming a magnet
for federal agents precisely when he is promising to find and sever
links to organized crime in order to end federal supervision of the
union.
</P>
<P>
   The movie unit of Local 25 needs to be brought under control.
It's driving away good business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AOL-MERGER-0728-COX     07-27 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MERGER-0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WRITE HEADLINE HERE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - If America Online Inc. and Time Warner Inc. are
allowed to merge, consumers will see the Internet taken ``to the
next level - connecting, informing and entertaining people around
the world as never before,'' AOL chairman Steve Case assured
federal regulators Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But corporate competitors and consumer advocates warned the
Federal Communications Commission that the combined company could
put ``choke holds'' on the Internet, restricting consumer choices
by controlling both the cable ``pipes'' and the content flowing
through them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the unprecedented concentration of market power that
would be created by this merger, there is a clear threat to
consumer choice,'' said Preston Padden, a lobbyist for Walt Disney
Co.
</P>
<P>
   Though shareholders of the world's No. 1 online service company
have approved the merger with the No. 2 U.S. cable-TV operator, the
companies still need approval from the FCC, as well as the Federal
Trade Commission and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Time Warner executives argue their proposed merger
raises no serious anti-trust issues because their companies operate
in different markets. AOL has 23 million online subscribers. Time
Warner owns cable TV operations and media companies that generate
news and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   By combining their strengths, ``AOL and Time Warner will drive
the Internet's development - helping to spur a new era of
innovation and robust competition,'' Case said during the four-hour
FCC hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney, General Electric Co.'s NBC and a host of other
companies have been filing objections to the merger. Disney is
asking the FCC to separate AOL Time Warner's cable distribution
system from the content-providing operations, saying neither
company can be by trusted to look out for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Case and Time Warner Chief Executive Gerald Levin promised their
merged company would provide competitors with access to their
high-speed connections, but declined to provide a definite date.
However, Levin said he ``remained quite confident we can make that
happen faster than anyone else in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Padden objected to such reassurances. ``This massive aggregation
of market power cannot be left to voluntary promises of good
behavior,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Corp. executive William Reddersen said his company
believes the FCC should bar any relationship between AT&AMP;T and Time
Warner, warning that any deals between those two giants in the
cable industry could limit the ability of rivals, such as
BellSouth, to compete in offering Internet service, instant
messaging and cable service.
</P>
<P>
   While phone and media companies are primarily concerned about
the combination of content and cable lines, others are worried
about AOL's control over Internet services, especially instant
messaging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from history that those who unfairly exploit a market
dominance don't get nicer as they get bigger,'' Tribal Voice Chief
Executive Ross Bagully said in prepared testimony. Tribal Voice
developed Internet messaging technology used by some AOL
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger would ``give AOL-Time Warner plenty of
opportunities to bundle its extraordinary media properties with its
stranglehold over instant messaging to favor its content and
prevent innovations that might threaten its dominance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One witness for consumers, Barry Orton of the University of
Wisconsin, said the FCC should give local cable franchising
authorities the power to force AOL to meet minimal customer service
standards for cable Internet service. He noted that local
authorities already can make such demands on traditional cable
companies, and that AOL ought to be held to similar service
standards.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Chairman William Kennard summarized the issues before the
regulators: ``Will the merger deliver on the promises that have
been made, including accelerated broadband deployment, innovative
services and a continued commitment to multiple broadband
platforms?
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it usher in the anticipated convergence of the Internet
with television, and unleash all of the intriguing possibilities
therein? Or will it instead, as others contend, potentially impair
the competitive, consumer-driven evolution of these technologies?''
</P>
<P>
   On the web: Federal Communications Commission at
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
