<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4928 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ECONOMY-GROWS-BOS &LR;      07-27 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-GROWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY ROARS ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government's index of American workers' wages continued to
rise at a steady clip this spring, confirming that the labor force
is reaping the fruits of their growing productivity and
unprecedented strength in the job market.
</P>
<P>
   The employment cost index, closely watched by the Federal
Reserve Board as a signal of future inflation, increased 1 percent
in the April through June period, the US Bureau of Labor Statistics
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This was slightly below the 1.4 percent rise in wages in the
first three months of this year, and matched a 1 percent increase
in the final three months of last year. The index is a tally of
employers' costs for both wages and benefits, such as health
insurance and vacations.
</P>
<P>
   The gains, offset by increasing productivity, were seen as
encouraging by some investors, who pushed the Dow Jones industrial
average up 69.65 points, or 0.7 percent, Thursday to 10,586.13. The
Nasdaq Composite index, however, dropped 145.46 points, or 3.6
percent, to 3842.26, reacting to poor financial results by
Amazon.com and other technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Strong and persistent wage gains have protected workers'
paychecks from being eroded by inflation. For the year, the wage
index gained 4.4 percent, well above the inflation rate of 3.7
percent. That was not the case during most of the 1990s: Household
incomes, adjusted for inflation, did not begin to expand until
1997, according to a Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But, with the nation's unemployment rate at 4 percent, a 30-year
low, employees are apparently becoming increasingly adept at using
their leverage in a job market desperate for talent to win raises
and beef up their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are ahead of the game,'' said Denis McSweeney,
regional commissioner of the US Bureau of Labor Statistics, which
released the ECI data Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While workers are slightly better off, there was some concern
among economists that another surge in wages would add to price
pressures that may be building in a still-hot US economy. Labor
costs account for two-thirds of all business costs.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication of strong economic growth, the federal
government also reported Thursday that orders for manufactured
durable goods rose 10 percent in June. That was the biggest monthly
increase since July 1991, when orders jumped nearly 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times during
the past year in an attempt to cool the economy and hold inflation
in check. Fed chairman Alan Greenspan, testifying before the House
Banking Committee on Tuesday, said he would be watching the
economic data closely for signs of inflation during the weeks
leading up to the Fed's next meeting on interest-rate policy,
scheduled for August 22.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan also said he believed the current data, such as
slowing retail and home sales, show that interest-rate increase
were beginning to temper the economy and reduce the risk of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the new employment cost index data did not
contradict Greenspan. The gains, though robust, were not enough to
cause concern because workers are also producing more goods. If
productivity keeps pace with wage gains, as it has month after
month, then manufacturers do not have to raise their prices to
cover the costs of higher output.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers aren't good, but they're not a disaster,'' said
Steve Ricchiuto, chief economist at ABN AMRO, a financial firm.
``They confirm an upward trend, but it's not horrible enough for a
rate hike in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers' productivity grew at a 3.7 percent pace in the first
quarter, and Oscar Gonzalez, economist for John Hancock Financial
Services Inc. in Boston, forecast that productivity would exceed 3
percent again in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Rising wages are ``a natural consequence of the ability of
workers to be more productive,'' Gonzalez said. ``That's really the
key to the whole puzzle. If you don't have those productivity
gains, things would start to fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Bureau of Labor Statistics also included
in its employment cost index calculation the cost to employers of
referral and hiring bonuses, which are becoming increasingly
popular as a way of attracting workers. But the addition had little
effect on the overall numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Gonzalez added, the 1 percent gain in wages and
benefits was ``a big number.'' The government breakdown of the
index found that wages and salaries rose 1 percent during the
April-to-June quarter, while benefits increased 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northeast, wage gains were roughly even with the national
trend, preliminary data showed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
