<HEADER>
A4938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUDITORS-NORRIS-COLUM     07-27 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDITORS-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: AUDITORS' INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt, the chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, wants to end his term by enacting new rules to increase
the independence of auditors from their corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is,'' Levitt said near the end of a long day of public
hearings, ``a cultural change we are talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Auditors are the only profession enshrined in our nation's
securities laws. If you want to sell stock to the public, you don't
have to hire a lawyer or an investment banker, but you do need an
independent accountant. Levitt fears that auditors are not
sufficiently concerned with assuring that they are seen as
independent.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the accounting industry bitterly resent Levitt's latest
moves, which would force the accounting firms to stop providing
some consulting services they now provide to companies whose books
they audit. They say those services make them more familiar with
the company, and thus able to do better audits. And, they say,
there is no evidence that such relationships have led to bad
audits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the rules say we must be independent in fact,'' said
James Copeland, the chief executive of Deloitte &AMP; Touche, in an
interview. Levitt is pushing rules that demand ``independence in
appearance,'' he said, adding that ``this Caesar's wife quote is
absurd.'' That's the one that says some people must be above
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   There probably never was a golden age of accounting
independence. Back in 1957, Leonard Spacek, the legendary managing
partner of Arthur Andersen, was warning that ``the profession's
existence is in peril'' because it was not showing enough
independence. He complained that the accounting principle-setters
of that era ``yielded quickly'' when companies complained that a
new standard would cut their profits. ``Proper accounting
principles in this case were not even discussed,'' he moaned. He
warned that it was dangerous for auditors to be perceived as
advocates for their clients, rather than impartial fact finders.
</P>
<P>
   Many things have changed for the better since then. The
Financial Accounting Standards Board now sets accounting rules and
has exhibited backbone.
</P>
<P>
   But accounting chief executives talk a different language than
Spacek did. They are very confident that the public has confidence
in them, and point to high stock prices as evidence that investors
trust the financial statements they certify. To the extent there is
a perception that they lack independence, they blame the SEC for
raising the issue. You get the impression everything would be fine
if Levitt would just shut up or go away.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the major accounting firms _ Andersen, Deloitte and
KPMG _ are determined to fight the new SEC proposal. They are
lining up allies in Congress and preparing to go to court. They
hope to delay action until a new president can appoint a new SEC
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   They may win that fight. But such a victory would be pyrrhic.
Highly publicized resistance to rules that are described as seeking
to promote auditor independence will be remembered when _ as will
surely happen _ there is another case of an audit gone awry,
particularly if the auditing firm got far more money from
consulting relationships than it did for doing the audit.
</P>
<P>
   The industry should seek a compromise, perhaps one that lets
auditors continue to do more information technology consulting than
the SEC seems to want, but with safeguards and fuller disclosures.
But for now, there may be too much anger to allow such talks to
even get under way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4939 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ARCHDIOCESE-DEBT-BOS &LR;      07-27 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDIOCESE-DEBT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL FORGIVES $28 MILLION OWED TO BOSTON ARCHDIOCESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Citing an ancient biblical tradition of forgiving debts
every 50 years, Cardinal Bernard F. Law has decided to write off
$28 million owed to the Archdiocese of Boston by 104 Eastern
Massachusetts parishes.
</P>
<P>
   The debts, owed by nearly one-third of the parishes in the
archdiocese for items such as building renovations and insurance
premiums, have been a financial and psychological burden for many
of the poorest parishes.
</P>
<P>
   Many parishes with the highest levels of debt are urban parishes
that now minister to immigrant populations unable to pay the costs
of sprawling physical plants constructed by earlier, more affluent
generations of Catholics who have since migrated to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could never stand on our own two feet because we always had
this debt hanging over us,'' said the Rev. William C. Francis,
pastor of Holy Family in Boston's Dorchester section, which will
have $700,000 in debts wiped away. ``Plus you always wonder if you
owe so much money and are not able to pay it, if they ever have to
come to a crunch, are you going to be the one that's crunched? This
will be one less worry to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Family is typical of the parishes that will be granted debt
relief. On the one hand, the parish is doing what parishes are
supposed to do: ministering to immigrants from Latin America and
the Caribbean as well as providing a school, a homeless shelter,
and a summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   But the parish could never hope to pay off the money it spent to
repair its church and its school _ weekly collections at Mass run
$1,000, and without a regular subsidy from the archdiocese the
church couldn't even stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Some parishes are also struggling to support schools once
attended predominanly by Catholic children and staffed at low cost
by priests and nuns but now attended by numerous non-Catholics
whose families are not parishoners and staffed by laypeople who
expect higher salaries than clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Law declined a request for an interview, but a top diocesan
official said the cardinal was moved not only by the moral
imperative of the jubilee year, but also by the desire to complete
a long-term effort at consolidating and strengthening parishes by
restoring them to financial health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these are inner city parishes that can't support the
old structures -- in a sense they educated themselves out of
existence, with fine Catholic schools that gave immigrant kids a
good Catholic education but now those kids live in Wellesley and
Weston and Sudbury,'' said the Rev. Thomas Groome, a Boston College
theologian. ``But society owes them a debt, and the cardinal's
forgiveness is...an extraordinary gesture of generosity in a
jubilee year in which the cardinal is clearly practicing what he
preaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Christian leaders, including Pope John Paul II, have made
debt forgiveness a theme this year, saying that a passage in
Leviticus requires debt forgiveness in jubilee years, which occur
every 50 years. Christians are celebrating a jubilee year this year
to mark the 2,000th anniversary of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Most religious leaders have focused their debt forgiveness
efforts on pushing the United States and other wealthy governments
to forgive debt owed by poorer nations.
</P>
<P>
   But the US Catholic hierarchy has been taking a more direct
approach to debt forgiveness. A number of Catholic bishops have
forgiven debts owed by parishes, although Law's action appears to
be the largest to date. Among the dioceses that have previously
acted are Camden, NJ, which forgave $12 million; St. Petersburg, $7
million; Buffalo, $5.5 million; and Pittsburgh, $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the $28 million in debt forgiveness will be granted
to 104 of the 372 parishes in the archdiocese. About 60 percent of
the aid will eliminate the debt of the 28 poorest parishes; the
balance will used to help reduce the debt of other parishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to stabilize and position these parishes to move
forward into the new millennium without dealing with debts that
were insurmountable,'' said David W. Smith, the archdiocese's vice
chancellor for financial affairs. ``We are taking care of each
other, as we are supposed to do. Now these parishes can go forward
and implement their own individual missions without having to face
financial burdens that are beyond their ability to handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual parishes in the Boston area are not incorporated, so
they can not borrow money from banks. Instead, they borrow money
from a revolving fund maintained by the archdiocese. Wealthy
parishes deposit savings into the account, earning 5.5 percent
interest; that money is loaned to poorer parishes, at an annual
rate of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese also provides a variety of types of insurance
coverage and employee benefits for parishes, and charges them fees
for those services.
</P>
<P>
   The debts are incurred when parishes can not afford to pay back
the money they owe to the archdiocese. Failure to repay debt does
not result in parish closings or other Draconian steps, but pastors
and parishes often find high levels of debt hurt morale and
distract parishes from other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The $28 million forgiven will have to be made up through
fundraising, Smith said. That amount is a fairly large sum for the
archdiocese -- by way of comparison, Law raises about $17 million a
year through contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
