<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CHENEY0728-COX     07-27 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney successful in politics and business By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Dick Cheney came to the cloistered,
good-ol' boy world of the oil business five years ago as chief
executive of Halliburton Co., many wondered whether he could make
the transition.
</P>
<P>
   He'd spent his entire working life in Washington as either a
White House staffer, Congressman or cabinet member. It was hard for
some to see how a life inside the Beltway would play in the oil
patch of West Texas, the oil fields of the Middle East or the North
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney proved surprisingly well suited to running a global
business, those who observed him from inside and outside the
company say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a mixed bag initially because he didn't have any
business experience,'' industry analyst Gary Russell, who worked at
Halliburton from 1990 to 1997, said of the reaction within the
company to Cheney's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney quickly put any worries to rest by recognizing his lack
of industry experience and submerging himself into the grit of oil
and gas production.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to the well site and technology labs,'' said Dale
Jones, former vice chairman at Halliburton who retired in late
1998. ``He got up to speed in the first six to nine months. He
really focused on that and made everyone in the company who may
have been concerned about that aspect of his background more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is said to have caught the eye of former Halliburton
Chief Executive Tom Cruikshank on a fishing trip with several CEO's
in 1994 when Cruikshank was contemplating retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Cruikshank were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had about a week together,'' said Kent Hance, a former
Texas Railroad Commission chairman and attorney specializing in oil
and gas, who talked to Cruikshank about it later. ``He said he was
impressed with (Cheney's) depth and understanding of world
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was hired because he knew the right people in the right
places to be an asset to the oil industry. He worked in one White
House that suffered through an oil crisis _ as chief of staff under
former President Ford _ and directed a war over oil for another _
the elder Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: Cheney possessed star power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who knew people all over the world. He could get
audience with them and get Halliburton's foot in the door,'' said
Hance.
</P>
<P>
   He and Cheney entered Congress the same year, 1979. Cheney
represented Wyoming, and Hance represented Lubbock, Midland and
Odessa.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the former secretary of defense wants to meet with CEO and
president of Shell Oil in Amsterdam, they're going to see him,''
Hance said. ``If he wants to meet with King Fahd in Saudi Arabia,
they're going to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of Cheney's draw was impressive, said Jones, who
accompanied Cheney on several trips overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of customers and potential customers who we
could see with him. They recognized him and wanted to meet him.
These were people used to meeting with CEOs. Here was a person who
had name recognition all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers say Cheney's contacts and name recognition paid off in
contracts such as the $2.5 billion deal Halliburton recently won
with Petrobas, Brazil's state-owned oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's other contributions are harder to gauge. The company is
more than double the size it was when Cheney took over, but it's
had to struggle with one of the industry's worst recessions.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue climbed to $14.9 billion from $5.9 billion between 1995
and 1999. Market capitalization _ the value of all shareholders'
stock _ rose to $18.5 billion from about $6.2 billion. Employment
nearly doubled during the same time, rising to 103,000 from 57,300.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've definitely taken steps in right direction,'' said
Russell, who follows Halliburton for Frost Securities in Dallas.
``I don't know how much can be attributed to him; but while he's
been there, a lot of good things happened with the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney demonstrated a command of the art of compromise and
negotiation two years ago in orchestrating the merger with Dresser
Industries Inc., Halliburton's cross-town rival in the
oilfield-services business.
</P>
<P>
   Such a merger had been probed extensively just a few years
before by Cheney's predecessor but was abandoned because of
Halliburton's weak stock price at the time, said Jones, who worked
on the merger with both Cheney and Cruikshank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did the deal,'' Jones said of Cheney. ``Some deals can can
get done in an amicable way, and some can't. When this was
finished, Dick and Bill Bradford (Dresser's chief executive) were
good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's years of experience negotiating delicate matters, such
as the multinational coalition that made the Gulf War possible,
were evident from the start at Halliburton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he comes into a meeting, you don't get the sense he's
going to railroad you. He doesn't pound the table,'' Jones said.
``I never saw the guy blow up or come close to it. He doesn't use
foul language of any type. He's got such a vocabulary that he
doesn't have to resort to that.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all easy: As he did with the military while secretary
of defense, Cheney had to make painful cuts. Just months after the
Dresser acquisition, Cheney had to lay off about 9,500 people when
an industry recession set in.
</P>
<P>
   It's uncertain how Cheney's tenure ultimately will be viewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, his tenure coincided with a recession in the
energy business,'' said Tom Escott, managing director,
Robinson-Humphrey Co. in Atlanta, who follows Halliburton.
``There's nothing he could have done to prevent a worldwide
downturn in drilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's management style was forged by running a White House
under siege in the mid-70s and a Pentagon at war in the early
1990s. He was unlike his predecessor at Halliburton, who would meet
several times with executives before making a major decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick was more used to people coming in (once), giving a
presentation, offering alternatives and then making a decision
right then and there. It's a pattern he'd become accustomed to as
secretary of defense. It wasn't a bad pattern, just different.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney didn't drop names or play up his involvement in the
Persian Gulf War around the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pretty humble guy,'' Jones said. ``He didn't tell war
stories. It's not his character. He felt it would wear pretty
thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was comfortable making big decisions himself, but he kept
his options open and didn't burn bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say he sought consensus, but I would say he sought
input,'' Jones sa$5.6 million. He still holds stock options today
worth $8.4 million more than what he'd have to pay to exercise
them.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton became a more Republican environment during the past
five years. Since Cheney took over, Halliburton has given around
$400,000 each election cycle, totaling $1.2 million over six years.
All but $40,000 of it has gone to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cheney's arrival, its political contributions were much
smaller and somewhat more evenly split between the parties. In the
1992 cycle, the company gave $67,000, 25 percent of which went to
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, two people with long ties to the Bushes and the
Republican party, joined the board:
</P>
<P>
   Ray Hunt, chief executive of Dallas-based Hunt Oil Co., is
national finance chairman for Victory 2000, the Republican National
Committee's voter-participation arm.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Eagleburger, an adviser to a Washington, D.C., law
firm, was deputy secretary of state for President Bush. Hance said
he wasn't surprised by Cheney's return to politics and said he's a
good choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured for some time he'd be in Bush's cabinet if he wanted
to,'' Hance said. ``More surprising is he got in the oil business
in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
