<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC investigates stalking as issue of public health
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than one in every six American women may have been stalked
at least once in her life, according to a study released Thursday
by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, one-third of women who have been stalked have been
injured as a result, and more than half experienced profound stress
because they were forced to disrupt their lives for more than a
month to avoid their stalkers, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   The study, one of the first to look at stalking from a public
health perspective rather than through law enforcement records, was
based on telephone interviews with 1,171 women in Louisiana.
However, it is applicable beyond that state, CDC said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to recognize that this level of violence is so
endemic that it constitutes an actual threat to public health,''
said Tina Trent, who researches violence against women at Emory
University and is the former director of Georgians for Choice.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, four out of five women who were stalked said that
they knew the stalker; in half of stalking cases, the person
threatening them was a former spouse or boyfriend. Three-fourths of
the women believed their lives were in danger from the stalker,
even though most escaped injury.
</P>
<P>
   Members of law enforcement who work on violence against women
said the CDC's findings were reliable, possibly even an
underestimate. The CDC found, for instance, that two-thirds of
women who had been stalked had reported the crime to law
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect not-reporting to be much higher,'' said Gerald
Blaney of Gwinnett County's State Court Solicitor's Office. His
caseload includes 100 instances of stalking a year, prosecuted
under a Georgia law that went into effect three years ago.
Successful prosecution requires ``an enthusiastic, cooperative,
observant victim,'' he said. ``It is not the kind of crime that an
officer can be patrolling on the street and see occur. It has to be
reported.''
</P>
<P>
   Because two-thirds of women who were stalked were not injured,
and one-third never reported the stalking to police, traditional
means of uncovering violence against women such as police reports
and medical records may not be a reliable guide to the problem, CDC
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blaney agreed that many cases never reach the justice system,
despite their severe impact on people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that it is disruptive of lives is a gross
understatement,'' he said. ``It's just horrible for people. It's a
relief that our society has recognized it as a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
