A4952 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-PELOSI-WHIP-HNS &LR;      07-27 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-WHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI CONFIDENT OF HOUSE LEADERSHIP POST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Rep. Nancy Pelosi said Thursday she has
enough support from fellow Democrats to become majority whip, the
No. 3 position in the House leadership, if the party wins control
of the chamber in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   In her most confident statement yet about her prospects for
capturing the post, Pelosi said that if Democratic lawmakers were
to vote today, she would defeat her rival, Rep. Steny H. Hoyer of
Maryland. The whip acts as the chief vote counter and works to
rally party members to support the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a clear majority,'' Pelosi said. ``It's undeniable that
I have the commitments. I am very confident about the numbers that
I have.''
</P>
<P>
   She said more than 80 Democratic representatives were supporting
her. But her quest for the leadership job hinges on whether the
party achieves its goal of regaining a majority in the House, six
years after the Republicans won control of both the House and
Senate in a humiliating defeat for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The whip contest heated up last week after Georgia Rep. John
Lewis announced that he was dropping out of consideration after
concluding ``the votes are simply not there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis then endorsed Hoyer, setting off a feverish scramble by
the remaining two candidates to capture commitments from his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer said he won commitments from about half of Lewis' 30
supporters, while Pelosi said Lewis' exit gave her enough new
supporters to put her over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic of John getting out of the race added to my
numbers,'' Pelosi said. ``The boost I received from Lewis leaving
the race has solidified it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer said Pelosi's claim of victory is premature and that it is
``a tactic to try to stampede people into thinking it's a done
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Any candidate would need a majority of votes from the Democratic
Caucus, which now has 210 members. There are 223 Republicans and
two independents in the House.
</P>
<P>
   If the Democrats gain control of the House, Richard A. Gephardt
of Missouri, now the minority leader, would become speaker. David
E. Bonior of Michigan, now the minority whip, would become majority
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer said between 90 and 95 House colleagues were supporting
his candidacy for the No. 3 post.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't have it locked up and I believe I have more votes
than she does,'' Hoyer said of Pelosi. ``They wouldn't be trying so
hard if they had it locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer said a majority of members have told him they think he
would be a better whip, but that some have said they are supporting
Pelosi ``because they think we need gender diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer, now in his 10th term, is more senior than Pelosi, who is
serving her 7th two-year term in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer added that he hasn't pressured anyone to publicly declare
support for him because the whip's race is hypothetical unless
Democrats win control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a reason to trot out a bunch of lists,'' Hoyer
said. ``If there was a real race, that's a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
judy(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
