<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EarthLink has strong growth, lower losses
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ EarthLink Inc. on Thursday reported booming revenue, a
shrinking loss and strong customer growth as it continued its
pursuit of America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The company also acknowledged that quality of service _ on which
it pegs its reputation _ suffered at least in the first few months
of the merger between EarthLink and MindSpring Enterprises as the
companies melded network and customer service operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had some rocky times in the first quarter,'' said
company President Michael McQuary. ``I think we will continue to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company offers Internet access _ including
high-speed connections _ as well as Web hosting services. The
company says recent troubles have been temporary and limited, and
that customers should check its Web site or _ if they cannot get
online _ call customer support.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever problems there have been, EarthLink has not shed
customers more rapidly than before. In fact, during the first
quarter, 5 percent of customers broke their EarthLink connection, a
``churn'' rate that dipped to 4.2 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink reported revenue of $230.9 million for the quarter
ended June 30, up 41 percent from revenue of $163.7 million in the
year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a net loss for the quarter of $35.2
million, or 29 cents per share, not including acquisition and
merger-related costs. EarthLink had net income of $5.3 million, or
5 cents per share, during the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But growth matters more right now than short-term profits, in
EarthLink's view, and the company finished the quarter with 3.7
million subscribers. With ``organic'' growth and the completion of
a deal to acquire OneMain.com, EarthLink will reach 5 million
subscribers by year's end, McQuary said.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of EarthLink's growth comes from former AOL members,
he said. ``We are in the second inning, not the seventh inning. We
will continue to close the gap with AOL.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has more than 23 million members, in addition to its massive
deal to buy Time Warner. If that merger is completed, AOL will
increasingly become a media company, owning content like the shows
that run on Time Warner's cable service, McQuary said. ``We are in
a different business. We don't compete against Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   The consumer dial-up represents a declining portion of the
business _ about 85 percent of revenues. Meanwhile, the company
increasingly looks elsewhere for future profits. For instance,
high-speed lines are increasingly seen as the preferred connection
to the Net. EarthLink now has 80,000 customers with that
``broadband'' link. The company expects to have 150,000 broadband
customers by year's end using digital subscriber lines (DSL), cable
modems and wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
