<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMSOFT0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American Software fighting for Wall Street attention
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ American Software's performance is anything but
monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been up. We've been down. We've been up. We've been
down. And at this particular point in time, we're in a down
cycle,'' said James Edenfield, chief executive officer and
co-founder of the Atlanta-based company.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Barron's last month called American Software ``a busted
technology play.'' But the financial weekly also said the stock,
selling at about $4, was a potential bargain. For that price,
buyers could pick up a company with $2 per share in cash and 85
percent ownership in Logility, another software company with nearly
as much cash per share, Barron's noted.
</P>
<P>
   American Software stock had been trading at more than $8 in
mid-May, when the company issued an earnings warning. It posted a
fourth-quarter loss of $2.7 million, or 12 cents a share, on $23.3
million in revenue. For the fiscal year it lost $1.2 million, or 6
cents a share, on revenue of $105.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old company now hopes to repair its image with Wall
Street and reward shareholders by taking at least one, and maybe
more, of its subsidiaries public.
</P>
<P>
   First up will be AmQuest, which provides computer services,
including a home for Web sites. American Software had hoped to take
the unit public earlier this year, until the IPO market fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield predicts that AmQuest on its own will be worth more
than American Software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think the market, at the present time, really
understands it. And maybe if it does understand it, doesn't quite
believe it, but we're going to bring this off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, American Software announced it was considering an
IPO for AmQuest, a unit on track to produce about $25 million in
annual revenue and operating at about break even, according to
Edenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Edenfield sold 237,262 Class A shares of
American Software. Chairman Thomas Newberry, the other founder,
sold 80,000 ``A'' shares.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams of Jefferies &AMP; Co., the only analyst following
American Software, likened the selling to ``shooting yourself in
the foot ahead of the offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield doesn't quite see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I kind of believe it's better to sell when the
stock is high than when it's low,'' he said. ``So it was a little
bit of that. And then I had a need to diversify my holdings for
estate planning purposes. And we had never entered the registration
process with AmQuest, nor have we yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield holds only 72,000 ``A'' shares, plus options to buy
another 53,000, according to American Software. But he still owns
just over 2.1 million ``B'' shares, which can be converted to ``A''
shares on a one-to-one basis and which carry 10 times the voting
power of an ``A'' share. Only he and Newberry own ``B'' shares.
</P>
<P>
   American Software plans to sell less than 20 percent of AmQuest
to the public, making it possible to distribute the rest of the
stock tax-free to American Software shareholders. That would be a
change from the Logility IPO in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   American Software sold about 16 percent of Logility to the
public and has held on to the rest, although a distribution of the
stock has not been ruled out, Edenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest possible offering of AmQuest would be in the fall,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has a ``buy'' rating on American Software,
recently estimated AmQuest's potential market value at between $286
million and $418 million. American Software's market value is about
$130 million.
</P>
<P>
   American Software is also looking at the possibility of an IPO
for Intellimedia Commerce, which builds and manages Web sites _
AirTran Airways is a client _ and invests in start-up companies
through a venture capital partnership with Cordova Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Forgetting for a minute the IPO possibilities, the issue at
American Software and Logility is not their productstion, he says,
plus general weakness in the enterprise resource planning market.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, American Software, which sells software to control
manufacturing, ordering, distribution and other processes, has
added an Internet-based version of its products.
</P>
<P>
   Logility, headed by Michael Edenfield, James' son, has doubled
its sales force over the last year and a half and reached deals
with IBM and Great Plains Software to expand distribution channels.
Logility's software is used to improve the efficiency of
manufacturing, distribution and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   American Software's products fare well against those of larger
competitors, and service and support scores are above the industry
average, according to Jim Lebinski, vice president and research
director of Gartner Decision Drivers Interactive in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Two areas that could use improvement, he said, have nothing to
do with the products and everything to do with assuring potential
customers about what to expect in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Software must consistently improve on, and show
positive financial results, in order to assure future viability,''
he said. Also, he added, the company needs to gain market share and
``aggressively'' tell potential customers where the company is
headed on product development.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
