u i BC-PERU-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS BUILD AS INAUGURATION IN PERU NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ In this capital on Thursday, women were washing
Peruvian flags they say have been sullied by President Alberto K.
Fujimori, vendors were selling crude gas masks and riot police were
taking up positions.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori is to begin his third five-year term on Friday, having
resisted pressures for democratic reforms. It promises to be a
raucous inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Through a mix of economic populism, political repression and
deal making in Congress, he has tightened his grip on power since
his re-election eight weeks ago, which was roundly criticized for
vote tampering and campaign dirty tricks.
</P>
<P>
   After the voting, Fujimori promised to work with the
Organization of American States to strengthen the independence of
the judiciary, to revamp electoral agencies and to expand freedom
of the press. He has, however, reduced the influence of officials
in his government who have most advocated reform.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition, led by Alejandro Toledo, the business professor
who dropped out of the presidential race a week before the May 28
runoff, has organized more than 100,000 people across the country
to march in an attempt to blemish the inauguration. But efforts to
block the ceremony have been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has appeared oblivious to criticism from the United
States and many Latin American and European governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinions of other countries are not important to us,'' he
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Using the large majority he controlled in the lame-duck
Congress, Fujimori pushed through legislation that gives the agency
regulating telecommunications more power to monitor private phone
conversations and to obtain access to computer and telephone
records without court order.
</P>
<P>
   He also has broken with his usual free-market policies, through
a new law that removes tax benefits for foreign mining companies
that reinvest profits in the country. He has blocked several
privatizations in order to maintain control over gas and water
prices as well as to shore up a government pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   The moves have upset businessmen and Wall Street analysts, who
express concerns that Fujimori will use populist economic policies
to buttress his political position.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Congress acted not only to clear high-level
Fujimori campaign officials of charges that they led an effort to
forge a million signatures to put the president on the ballot, but
also voted to make four whistle-blowers who exposed the forgery
criminally liable.
</P>
<P>
   The charges of forged signatures, substantiated by the newspaper
El Comercio, badly damaged Fujimori during the campaign and were a
large factor in his failure to win a first-round victory.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS is continuing to press for a democratic opening, but
Fujimori has refused to follow a demand that he fire his
intelligence chief, Vladimiro Montesinos, for campaign abuses.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Fujimori has not faced international sanctions, aside
from a few mostly symbolic actions by the U.S. Congress, which
delayed delivery of $42 million in foreign aid and excluded Peru
from a recent $1.3 billion anti-narcotics package that primarily
helps Colombia, but also Ecuador and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has signaled that it will continue to
work with Fujimori, particularly on anti-narcotics programs. Still,
it expressed strong comments about Fujimori when Ambassador John
Hamilton told a July 4 gathering in Lima that ``cosmetic or
superficial changes will not resolve the crisis of credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton will lead a spare U.S. delegation to the inauguration.
The only foreign presidents to attend will be Hugo Banzer of
Bolivia and Gustavo Noboa of Ecuador. Nine Latin American
presidents attended Fujimori's last inauguration in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has tried to head off a chilling of relations with
Washington by ordering the air force to deploy 18 Sukhoi-25
tactical fighter jets, formerly used as a deterrent against
Ecuador, to fight the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition had placed its hopes on international influence,
believing that the United States and the Organization of American
States might even prevail on Peru to hold new elections. But now
Toledo and other opposition leaders are expressing bitter
disappointment, going so far as to accuse the regional group of
complicity in Fujimori's election victory.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen or so opposition legislators have changed sides in the
last two months, so Toledo's ability to pressure Fujimori has
decreased. In one case, a former Toledo ally in the new Congress
changed his allegiances after judges friendly to Fujimori reversed
an embezzlement conviction against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4988 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-GREENHOUSE-GAS-AR     07-27 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GREENHOUSE-GAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS KEEP A WARY EYE ON POWERFUL, NEWLY IDENTIFIED GREENHOUSE
GAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Colo., Ore.)   (Eds.: The numerals 6, 5 and 3 in the formulas SF6, SF5 and CF3
should appear as subscripts for those with such typesetting
capacity.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have found rising concentrations of a newly
identified gas in the air that traps heat more effectively than all
other known greenhouse gases, the dozens of compounds released by
industry and the burning of fuels that act like a greenhouse roof
and may be warming the global climate.
</P>
<P>
   The synthetic gas is extremely rare, so far reaching
concentrations just over one-tenth of one part per trillion of air,
according to a paper being published Friday in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   But it still poses potential problems, the paper's authors say,
because concentrations of the gas are rising quickly, the gas
probably takes more than 1,000 years to break down and its source _
although certainly from human activities _ is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, there is far too small a quantity to be of concern,''
said William T. Sturges, an atmospheric chemist at the University
of East Anglia in Norwich, England, and the study's principal
author. ``But I wouldn't want to see it enormously increased.''
</P>
<P>
   The study provides the latest evidence of the global reach of
pollution and the sometimes unintended consequences of industrial
activity, said many chemists familiar with the report. Advance
copies of the paper circulated this week by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Some chemists said Thursday that it was possible that the gas
was being used secretly in military equipment. A similar gas,
sulfur hexafluoride, or SF6, is on lists of chemicals used in
electronics and in weapons and for other military purposes. But
they added that the new gas might also be used secretly by some
industry or it could simply be an unintentional byproduct of some
manufacturing process somewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The gas was found in samples taken by instrument-laden balloons
21 miles up in the stratosphere and in air trapped under layers of
Antarctic snow. Its name, trifluoromethyl sulfur pentafluoride, is
enough of a tongue twister that chemists prefer to talk about it
using its chemical formula, SF5 CF3.
</P>
<P>
   Its discoverers found no evidence of the gas in the air before
the 1950s, with only a scattering of molecules appearing in the
1960s and then a steady rise, with concentrations now rising about
6 percent a year. Altogether, the scientists calculated, about
4,000 tons have been released so far, with another 270 tons emitted
each year.
</P>
<P>
   That still has resulted in an overall concentration of only
about 0.12 parts per trillion in air, making the gas exceedingly
rare, Sturges said.
</P>
<P>
   But because SF5 CF3 is such a potent, and nearly permanent,
heat-trapping gas, he and his colleagues said, they hope the
finding will serve as a call to industry and governments to find
its source.
</P>
<P>
   Molecule for molecule, it is 18,000 times as effective at
trapping heat in the atmosphere as carbon dioxide, the most
familiar greenhouse gas, Sturges said. And, like the durable
chlorofluorocarbon chemicals, or CFCs, that can erode the earth's
protective ozone layer, the gas is extremely long-lived, with
molecules probably persisting for 1,000 years or more once they are
lofted in the air, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several chemists who work with similar compounds
said that they were astonished to learn that thousands of tons of
the chemical had infiltrated the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I nearly fell off my chair,'' said Gary A. Gard, a chemistry
professor at Portland State University in Oregon, who is a leading
expert in the properties of compounds containing fluorine, a
versatile element that has helped scientists produce the atom bomb,
prevent tooth decay and make products like Teflon coatings and
refrigerants.
</P>
<P>
   Gard recalled how SF5 CF3 had first been synthesized more than
40 years ago by one of his mentors, George H. Cady, at the
University of Washington, but had never found much use beyond pure
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the best of my knowledge, no one is using it on an
industrial scale,'' Gard said. ``It's the kind of research chemical
where you'd buy 100 grams or 50 grams, but you wouldn't buy a ton
of this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chemists said that SF5 CF3 was briefly employed about 30
years ago as a kind of chemical tag to track the flow of pollution
from smokestacks. The advantages were that it was inert and stood
out clearly in samples taken downwind, said Edward A. Tyczkowski, a
fluorine chemist in Newport, Tenn., who once manufactured about 100
pounds of the material for government scientists. But he said only
a few pounds were used in such tests and he knew of no large-scale
production of the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Gard agreed with a theory proposed by Sturges that the traces of
the chemical in the air could be some unnoticed byproduct of
industrial processes using fluorine. He also agreed that a search
should be made for the source.
</P>
<P>
   F. Sherwood Rowland, an atmospheric chemist at the University of
California at Irvine, who shared a Nobel Prize in 1995 for
discovering the link between CFCs and the ozone layer, noted that
other greenhouse gases containing fluorine were unintended
industrial byproducts.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said the new finding was important because it
underscored the need to give serious consideration to even the
atmosphere's most minor constituents.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, he said, the new gas is similar to CFCs, which
prompted an international treaty to protect the ozone layer but
have never existed in concentrations higher than 550 parts per
trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Gard said the newly discovered atmospheric gas also served as a
reminder that the atmosphere is not some boundless expanse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too long ago people thought, We can dump anything we want
in the ocean because it's so vast,'' he said. ``It's the same thing
with the atmosphere. It's just been seen as this huge sink. Now we
see it's not an infinite reservoir. People should realize that and
start taking better care of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
