<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SENATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GEORGIA GOVERNOR SWORN IN AS U.S. SENATOR, SHAVING GOP
MAJORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaving behind the tranquility of the Georgia
mountains to come to the Capitol, Zell Miller, a Democrat and
former Georgia governor, came out of retirement Thursday to be
sworn in as a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the oath of office, Miller spoke eloquently on the
Senate floor of the man whose seat he is filling, Paul Coverdell,
the mild-mannered but dogged 61-year-old Republican leader who died
of a brain hemorrhage on July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who is 68 and one of the state's most popular
politicians, agreed only reluctantly to take the job offered him by
the current governor of Georgia, Roy Barnes. He will run in a
special election on Nov. 7 to fill the remainder of Coverdell's
term, which ends in 2005, a decision that has buoyed Democratic
hopes for reclaiming control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A two-term governor who retired just last year, Miller arrives
in the Senate amidst partisan discord; just this week Democrats
virtually shut down the Senate, objecting to the way Republicans
are handling federal judicial nominations.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Miller, a centrist, made it clear that he hopes to
honor Coverdell by trying to leap beyond the restraints of party.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to what he accomplished, Paul will always be
remembered for how he accomplished it,'' Miller said on the Senate
floor. ``He was as committed a Republican as I am a dedicated
Democrat. And yet, he was always looking for ways to get things
done across party lines. He did so not by abandoning his
principles, but by heeding and listening to the proverb, `a soft
answer turneth away wrath. With grievous words stir up anger.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me repeat the pledge I made to my governor and to the
people of Georgia when I accepted this mission,'' Miller added. ``I
will serve no single political party, but rather 7.5 million
Georgians.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were gleeful about Miller's decision to accept the
Senate seat and compete in the November election, and said that his
potential victory might tilt the balance of power in their favor.
Republicans now hold 54 seats to the Democrats' 46.
</P>
<P>
   When he left office in 1999, Miller had an approval rating in
the state of 80 percent, and Democrats say he is one of the few
candidates who can, on short notice, assemble a campaign and raise
the money needed to get elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in a while, there is a real feeling we can
capture the Senate,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican challenger has yet stepped forward, but a
potential candidate emerged Thursday: Lewis Jordan, the wealthy
former chief executive of ValueJet. Aides said that Republican
leaders were pleased with the prospect because Jordan is wealthy
enough to help finance his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., is also considering a run for the Senate
seat, but the rest of the state's delegation has withdrawn from
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 7 election is a quirky one; it is officially
nonpartisan, and the winning candidate requires 50 percent of the
vote in order to avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts say a change in party control of the Senate is
unlikely, but they do not rule it out. Democrats have fewer
vulnerable incumbents than Republicans and are well-positioned in
several races for open seats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans acknowledged Miller's popularity in his home state
and said that Democrats had chosen wisely. ``They shrewdly picked
the one person in Georgia that gives them any chance of taking the
seat back from Republicans,'' said Chuck Clay, the state Republican
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the Senate was not the statehouse, no matter how
many times Thursday Democrats evoked Coverdell's name and the
spirit of cooperation. ``You cannot say you are going to vote on
and implement the Paul Coverdell view of things and be a
Democrat,'' Clay said. ``You can't do that in Washington. You are
on one team or on the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Miller's showcase accomplishment was establishing a
state lottery and using the money to create a college scholarship
fund for Georgia students.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, lauded
the former governor's ability to transcend partisanship. ``In
deciding public policy,'' Daschle recounted, ``he has said, `the
most important question is not: How will this affect my chances in
the next election? The proper question is: What will this mean for
my grandchildren?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
