u i BC-MEXICO-CARDINAL-MURDE     07-27 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CARDINAL-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS DISAGREE ON 1993 MURDER OF MEXICAN CARDINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After years of investigations, federal, state and
church authorities said Thursday they had agreed to disagree about
the events that led to the 1993 murder of one of Mexico's two Roman
Catholic cardinals during a shootout at an airport.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on the latest review of evidence, which itself took
two years, federal prosecutors ridiculed suggestions that the
prelate was the target of a conspiracy, and they stood by the
conclusion of the initial investigation. They said that the
cardinal, Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo, was shot to death during an
afternoon of gunfire and mayhem at the Guadalajara airport by
narcotics traffickers who mistook him for a rival drug lord
</P>
<P>
   But top officials from Jalisco state where the murder occurred,
and church leaders who participated in the review, cast doubts,
noting that the first investigation was secretly led by an army
general later found to be working for the narcotics cartels. The
Jalisco officials also cited signs of evidence tampering, the
pressuring of witnesses and other irregularities in the course of
the full investigation that spanned seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent conclusions mean that a cloud of public doubt will
linger about the murder, which served as a wake-up call to many
Mexicans about the reckless arrogance of the drug lords and the
power they had accumulated as Mexico's marijuana and opium crops
proliferated and its importance grew as a smuggling route for
Colombian cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The final report Thursday by a committee that included
representatives of Mexico's attorney general, the Jalisco
government and the Catholic Church brings the lengthy inquiry to a
close.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first months of the investigation in 1993, the
authorities discovered that Posadas had approached the Guadalajara
airport on May 24, 1993, just at the moment in which gunmen led by
Ramon Arellano Felix, a leader of the main cocaine smuggling
organization in the Mexican state that borders California, had
opened fire with automatic rifles on members of a rival drug cartel
based in the states south of Arizona, commanded by Joaquin Guzman
Loera and Hector Palma Salazar.
</P>
<P>
   For months, members of the rival gangs had been assassinating
each other in wild shootouts at discos and restaurants. The
Guadalajara airport became an inferno as the two drug gangs
exchanged automatic rifle fire. Posadas, who was 66 at the time,
had gone to the airport to pick up the papal nuncio, who was
arriving in Guadalajara for a visit. As he sat in his car outside
the terminal, Posadas was shot 14 times at close range. At least
six other bystanders were also killed.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first weeks after the crime, Guzman Loera and dozens
of gunmen who participated in the shooting, including several
federal and Jalisco state police found to be working for him, were
arrested and put on trial for drug crimes and for their involvement
in the airport violence. Palma Salazar was also jailed two years
later. Arellano has never been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terrible killing that occurred by accident,'' Jose
Luis Ramos, a top federal prosecutor concluded Thursday in a news
conference, as Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar listened.
</P>
<P>
   But officials from the government of Jalisco state, led by Gov.
Alberto Cardenas Jimenez, a member of president-elect Vicente Fox's
center-right party, disputed the federal government's conclusion,
and two bishops representing the Catholic Church's episcopal
conference said they shared the doubts of the Jalisco officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a premeditated homicide,'' said Fernando Guzman
Perez, the Jalisco government's No. 2 official. ``This was no
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   To explain the Jalisco government's skeptical view, Guzman noted
that federal prosecutors had originally argued that Posadas had
been killed in crossfire until ballistic tests showed he had been
shot at point-blank range. He also noted that prosecutors had
changed the testimony of several witnesses, and that official
documents and videotapes from the investigation had gone missing
during the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   An especially troubling aspect of the official investigation,
Guzman said, was that Gen. Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo, the general in
charge of the Guadalajara region, rather than civilian prosecutors,
had led the original investigation, in which suspects were
interrogated and evidence stored at an army base.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez was later arrested and is still on trial for drug
crimes, accused as a long-time associate of Mexico's largest drug
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the church, this case is not closed,'' said Juan Cardinal
Sandoval Iniguez, Posadas' successor at the Guadalajara
archdiocese, who participated in the review.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
