<SLUG> BC-TELEKOM-VOICESTREAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM MAY DILUTE GERMAN GOVERNMENT STAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom is considering ways to reduce the German
government's stake in the company as it prepares to wage a
behind-the-scenes political battle to win approval of its plan to
buy VoiceStream Wireless Corp., the company's chief executive said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. lawmakers have opposed the acquisition of an American
telecommunications company by a corporation controlled by a foreign
government, throwing up a significant hurdle to the expansion of
Deutsche Telekom, Europe's largest phone company. Existing law
generally puts the limit of foreign government ownership at 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   One option, which illustrates how Deutsche Telekom's $50.7
billion offer for VoiceStream is unlikely to satisfy the company's
appetite for expansion, would be to acquire one or more additional
telecommunications companies, either in the United States or
elsewhere, worth as much as $100 billion, which would lower the
German government's overall stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to buy today a company about the size of Deutsche
Telekom, that would dilute the government's stake down to about 22
percent, it's that simple,'' Ron Sommer, Deutsche Telekom's
chairman, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, few companies rival the size of Deutsche Telekom, the
second-largest telephone company after Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone of Japan. That is why the German company is expected to
pursue several acquisitions at once, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Another option, seemingly less predictable, would be the sale of
Germany's shares in the company. The German government owns about
58 percent of Deutsche Telekom's stock but has pledged to decrease
its holdings. If Deutsche Telekom succeeds in buying VoiceStream,
based in Bellevue, Wash., the German government's stake would fall
to 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other European countries like France, Germany does not
have legislation that prevents the government from reducing its
stake in its national telecommunications company. Nor are there
rules that give the government a ``golden share,'' allowing it to
veto certain management decisions, as there are in Spain and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sale of the government's stake would depend on the
price. ``We always said the government would sell according to
market conditions,'' Sommer said.
</P>
<P>
   Given political opposition to Deutsche Telekom's expansion in
the United States, it is important for Sommer to underscore the
German government's intent to decrease its ownership. In Europe,
Deutsche Telekom could try to buy Telefonica SA of Spain, whose
chairman, Juan Villalonga, resigned on Wednesday, or make another
bid for Telecom Italia, said Bob House, a vice president in the
London office of Renaissance Strategy, a telecommunications
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, a handful of large telecommunications
companies have been mentioned as potential takeover targets for
Deutsche Telekom, including WorldCom Inc., which recently failed in
its bid to acquire Sprint Corp., and Global Crossing, based in
Hamilton, Bermuda, which has a growing global fiber optic network.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are political complexities in these moves, but Deutsche
Telekom knows that they are all in play,'' House said.
</P>
<P>
   As the company debates its options, Sommer said that much of
Deutsche Telekom's energy in the United States would be focused on
securing approval in Washington to buy VoiceStream. To do so,
Deutsche Telekom has hired several lobbying and law firms.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying is expected to focus on thwarting legislation sponsored
by Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and supported by several
congressional leaders, which would block Deutsche Telekom's
takeover of VoiceStream.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer's comments came after Deutsche Telekom released results
Thursday showing that its second-quarter profit declined by nearly
half, to 200 million euros, or about $188 million, after the
company spent heavily to expand its mobile phone operations, most
recently in Britain and Austria. Shares of Deutsche Telekom fell
1.17 euros, or 2.3 percent, to 49.50 euros. The stock has declined
more than 34 percent since June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire what Deutsche Telekom is doing to expand, but I
prefer smaller, faster-growing companies,'' said Michael Eggly,
co-manager of the Northern Global Communications Fund in Chicago.
``The former national telephone company of Germany isn't attractive
to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
