<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MARKETS0728-COX     07-27 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slower profits expected as Fed action takes hold
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has done
his job too well. Wall Street thinks so, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst a flurry of second-quarter corporate profit reports that
are upbeat by any standard, the market refuses to break out of a
four-month trading range. Some strategists see the best of the year
behind us already.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly spoiled by a decade of stellar earnings growth,
investors are focusing on the disappointments of companies that are
not living up to analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, the outlook for stocks in the second half is
not very good since by all accounts profit growth in 2000 has
probably peaked.
</P>
<P>
   First Call/Thomson Financial, a research firm that tracks
earnings forecasts, said that with two-thirds of the companies in
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index already reporting, overall
second-quarter earnings growth is ``in the 22 percent to 23 percent
range.''
</P>
<P>
   That's close to the S&AMP;P-500's first-quarter earnings growth of
23.6 percent, year-over-year. One or the other of these quarters is
likely to be the earnings peak for the year, according to a report
by First Call research analyst Anthony Crooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, it's been all down hill for the second half,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts are projecting third-quarter profit growth of
just over 18 percent, just over 16 percent for the fourth quarter
and just under 16 percent for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious villain in this scenario is the Federal Reserve,
which has raised short-term interest rates for the past year to put
the brakes on an economy whose growth rate it regards as
inflationary. And, apparently, the strategy is working.
</P>
<P>
   The government is expected to report today that the economy
expanded at a 3.8 percent annual rate in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Though brisk by historical standards, that would be down from
the 5.1 percent annual growth in the first quarter and 4.6 percent
in the final quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. economic performance is shifting from the truly
spectacular to the merely good,'' Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. chief
economist Bruce Steinberg told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed would like to see annual economic growth of less than 3
percent, but even Greenspan has said that's not likely in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to economists, is that the Fed's goal of
an economic ``soft landing'' _ growth of less than 3 percent with
inflation under control _ is a difficult assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed succeeded in engineering such a soft landing in 1994 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts at Ned Davis Research found that most of the Fed's
attempts to slow the economy by raising interest rates have
resulted in recessions or shorter economic dips.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the Fed reads the economic news, the slowing
that already has occurred in the economy may be enough to persuade
Greenspan and colleagues to stop raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   That would almost certainly result in a stock market rally.
Thursday produced a good news/bad news situation for the market.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that the government's second-quarter
Employment Cost Index, a measure of change in wages, rose only 1.0
percent from the first quarter, in line with expectations. This is
nothing that would push the Fed to raise rates at its Aug. 22
policy meeting, First Union economist David Orr said.
</P>
<P>
   But June orders for durable goods _ big-ticket items not
frequently purchased _ surged 10 percent compared to analysts'
projections of only a 0.2 percent increase. But most of the
increase was for commercial airplanes and not consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's trading on Wall Street, investors were less
interested in economic news than in disappointing earnings reports
from Amazon.com, WorldCom and Nokia, which sparked a technology
selloff that depressed the Nasdaq composite index by 145.49 points
to 3,842.23.
</P>
<P>
   But buying in blue chips gave the Dow Jones industrial average a
boost of 69.65 points to 10,586.13.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
