<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS AND PALESTINIANS SAY NEGOTIATIONS WILL RESUME NEXT WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Amid a flurry of political and diplomatic moves on
both sides, Israel and the Palestinians made plain on Thursday that
they are eager to put the failed Camp David talks behind them and
move forward with a renewed peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides confirmed that negotiators would meet on Sunday at
the border of the Gaza Strip, and said that ideas floated at Camp
David by President Clinton _ including proposals that the
Palestinians rejected on the future of East Jerusalem _ have
carried the peace process further than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours after completing their long flights home,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, laid out new travel plans suggesting that both
believe that some form of agreement _ perhaps only partial,
officials said, and possibly excluding the deal-breaking issue of
Jerusalem _ may yet be possible in the weeks and months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After a hectic round of consultations with Israeli ministers and
opposition leaders who will decide the fate of Barak's beleaguered
coalition government in a series of parliamentary votes next week,
the prime minister announced he would fly to Egypt on Friday to
meet with President Hosni Mubarak. Arafat had stopped in Alexandria
on his way back from Camp David on Wednesday to brief Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   The Egyptian leader, a key player in Middle East peace moves for
two decades, is seen by both sides as crucial to the shape of any
eventual agreement _ especially on Jerusalem, the issue on which
the Camp David negotiations reportedly foundered on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for his part, announced he would leave before the
weekend for a whistle-stop tour that will include talks with
President Jacques Chirac of France, long regarded as one of the
Western nations most sympathetic to the Palestinian cause, and on
to meetings with a succession of unspecified Arab leaders. Arafat
has usually made such tours in the wake of major negotiating
sessions, but with the issue of Jerusalem now squarely on the
table, these briefings were certain to be more critical and
intense.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the various trips and meetings reflected a sense that
something substantial, even historic, had occurred even though
Barak and Arafat came down out of Camp David seemingly
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, commentators said, the decision to return so rapidly
to the negotiating table reflected a recognition that the talks, in
particular the American ideas for a settlement in Jerusalem, have
swept the historic rivals into new political terrain that they must
now explore, and from which neither can easily retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The plan put forward by Clinton, as outlined by Israeli and
Palestinian officials who have spoken with reporters here, would
have established a complex mosaic of jurisdictions in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Gilead Sher, one of Barak's top aides at Camp David, said the
president had proposed that Arafat have a presidential office in
the Muslim quarter of the walled Old City of Jerusalem, a move that
according to Israeli commentators would allow the Palestinians to
claim that they had fulfilled their pledge to establish the capital
of their new state in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Other Israeli officials said that the American proposals had
provided for some of East Jerusalem's Arab quarters annexed to
other Palestinian territories outside the city and expanded to
establish a new city to be known as Al Quds, the historic Arabic
name for Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, these officials said, the Palestinians would have
been given vaguely defined authority, short of sovereignty, over
the Muslim and Christian quarters in the Old City, control of the
Dome of the Rock and other Muslim holy places, and a new bridge
allowing Palestinians unhindered access to the Muslim holy places
from areas under their control to the east of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Sher told Israel radio that the talks with Clinton opened a new
horizon in the peace effort, even if the Jerusalem proposals were
rejected by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that definitely yes, it's possible to finish the
conflict and reach a reasonable settlement in not too long a time
as long as there is talk between the sides,'' Sher said.
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, a senior Arafat aide at Camp David who has taken a
positive stance from the day the talks concluded, confirmed that he
would meet with Oded Eran, a senior Israeli negotiator, to renew
peace talks on Sunday at Erez, on the border between Israel and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating remarks that he made Wednesday on the ABC News program
``Nightline,'' Erekat told reporters in the West Bank city of
Jericho that ``many taboo subjects'' had been discussed at Camp
David for the first time, including Jerusalem, and that the two
sides were now ``closer than ever'' to ending their 52-year-old
conflict. ``I don't think our negotiations will ever be the same
after Camp David,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Erez meeting will follow one held there on Wednesday between
Israel's deputy defense minister, Ephraim Sneh, and Tayeb Abdel
Rahim, a senior aide to Arafat, at which the two men discussed
joint efforts to prevent outbreaks of violence by Israelis or
Palestinians discontented by the events at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On both sides, officials pointed to the Wednesday talks as a
mark of how far the peace effort has come since the days when
orchestration of violent protests was a ready tactic for
Palestinian officials seeking to wring concessions from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   (START OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Marwan Barghouti, a top Arafat official on the West Bank, told
reporters that neither side could gain from violence. ``We must
keep things quiet and wait until September,'' he said, referring to
the Sept. 13 date Arafat has set as the deadline for unilaterally
declaring an independent Palestinian state in Gaza and the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The change of mood was not without its darker notes. Both Barak
and Arafat, in statements and through aides, continued to stake out
what in the parlance of the region are known as ``red lines'' _ the
limits of what the two sides publicly claim they can accept in any
final settlement on Jerusalem, on Jewish settlements, on the return
of Palestinian refugees and on other issues that have been left
unresolved in the stuttering process that began with the Oslo
agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for example, continued to insist at a sparsely attended
ally in the Palestinian-controlled town of Ramallah on the West
Bank that ``there is not one among us who can give up a grain of
soil of noble Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Barak, since returning home, has been emphasizing
that Israel, by accepting key parts of the Clinton plan involving
Jerusalem, has escaped ever having to compromise sovereignty over
the city in any comprehensive way, and, in addition, has
established the principle of Israeli sovereignty over most of the
145 Jewish settlements in Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Barak's immediate challenge was to shore up his political
position at home, and the signs as he prepared for his journey to
Egypt were that his fractious, 14-month-old government would
survive a battery of three no-confidence votes in the Parliament on
Monday, as well as a separate vote on Wednesday in which opposition
groups will seek the dissolution of the parliament and a new
election.
</P>
<P>
   Head counts of voting intentions among more than a dozen
political parties and factions, combined with intensive new
contacts between Barak and two coalition parties that left the
government on the eve of the Camp David talks _ the religious Shas
party and the left-wing Meretz party _ suggested that Barak's
coalition, led by his One Israel movement, would survive by at
least a narrow majority.
</P>
<P>
   After the votes, the parliament will adjourn for its summer
recess, giving Barak, if he survives, a respite from the constant
political challenges. Barak is also likely to elude an option that
some conservatives in the ruling coalition have urged on him in the
wake of the Camp David talks, the formation of a ``national unity
government'' with Likud, the right-wing opposition party led by
Ariel Sharon. That option appeared to be as good as dead on
Thursday after leading officials of One Israel and Likud pronounced
it unacceptable because of the harshly opposed stands the two
parties have taken on the peace effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
