<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EG-GUINEA-OIL-ART-NYT     07-27 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EG-GUINEA-OIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP OF EQUATORIAL GUINEA MOVES TO DEVELOP COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBA, Equatorial Guinea _ Not counting the yapping cocker
spaniel that was terrifying some men who were practicing witchcraft
in the jungle the night before and now feared being found out by
the sharp-eyed dog, this town was pretty much dead on a recent
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A drizzle from the clouds on this side of the volcanic island of
Bioko had kept most people indoors. A handful of children splashed
in the murky canal that snakes through this town. A large monkey
lay dead on a front porch, waiting only for the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   A knock on the governor's temporary house (the longtime
president of this tiny Central African nation, Teodoro Obiang
Nguema Mbasogo, has grown so fond of the governor's house that he
has appropriated it for his visits here) found the man in question,
Deogracias Miguel Olomo, looking relaxed in sweats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a couple of years ago, there was absolutely nothing
here,'' Olomo told an unexpected visitor. ``Now Luba can be, well,
not the capital. But it can be the economic capital.''
</P>
<P>
   If Luba, population 3,000, is thinking big these days, it is
merely a reflection of the national mood. Equatorial Guinea, once
the penniless neighbor in a region awash with oil, has finally hit
the jackpot. With perhaps 120,000 barrels a day of crude, and much
more to come, forgotten towns are now daring to dream of El Dorado.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spanish colonialists left in 1968, Luba, despite being
the second town on this island after the national capital, Malabo,
sank into darkness. With nothing going on here, people stepped back
into the jungle to hunt and grow crops. The roads linking Luba to
Malabo to the north and Riaba to the east became virtually
impassable.
</P>
<P>
   Today, while much of the road to Riaba remains hidden under
overgrown trees and bush, workers are digging up and paving over
the way to Malabo. A new port for the oil companies is being built
here.
</P>
<P>
   As for Equatorial Guinea's government, it says it wants to
develop every town in the country. And to that effect, it has
adopted a novel strategy: in June it moved the entire government,
or most of it, off this island and onto the mainland in the city of
Bata.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Nguema Lima, the secretary of state at the Ministry of
Mines and Energy and a son of Obiang, explained that the move would
perhaps last six months. After that, the government will keep
moving to other towns, returning to Malabo after an indefinite
journey, Nguema added.
</P>
<P>
   In Malabo, the move caught most people unawares. That was hardly
a surprise in a country with no daily newspapers and a history of
authoritarian, corrupt governments.
</P>
<P>
   At El Sabroson, a restaurant on Avenida de la Independencia, a
couple of days before he was scheduled to join his colleagues in
Bata, the information minister, Lucas Nguema Esono Mbang, was
having lunch with a ponytailed Spanish businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``By moving the government away from here,'' the information
minister said, picking at his plate of antipasto, ``we can
redevelop the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish businessman, who was awarded a government contract
earlier that day, nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' the information minister went on, ``Spain should
follow our example by moving the government to Barcelona or the
Basque country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactamente,'' the Spanish businessman said, looking down at
his plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, he is a great admirer of Franco,'' the minister said
of the businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' the businessman said. ``Authority is good! That's
why this country is good. You can leave 100,000 francs on this
table,'' or about $150, he went on, ``and no one will take it.
Liberty! What is liberty if you cannot leave 100,000 francs on this
table without worrying?''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, at the headquarters of the Union Popular, an
opposition party, people ascribed different motives to the
government's move to Bata.
</P>
<P>
   Fabian Nsue Nguema, the party's secretary general, brought up
the point that in the final months of the administration of
Francisco Macias Nguema, the country's first president, the
government was also moved to the mainland. Macias, a brutal
dictator, eventually placed the government in his hometown,
Mongomo, at the country's easternmost point. Shortly after that, he
was toppled and then executed by his nephew, the current president,
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dictatorship,'' Nsue said of the government. ``What
distinguishes dictatorships is that they are afraid. So they are
afraid and want to move from place to place.''
</P>
<P>
   Agapito Ona Nguema, another party officer, added: ``Why do they
have to move from place to place to develop the country? Your
government in Washington, does it have to move to New York or Los
Angeles to develop them? And yet they are developed, right?''
</P>
<P>
   The president's family, a subclan of the Fang ethnic group, has
controlled the country since independence. Though they come from
the mainland, they have governed from Malabo, the capital
established by the Spaniards. An ethnic group known as the Bubi
makes up the indigenous people of Malabo and the rest of the island
of Bioko.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, enough resentment toward the mainland
rulers had built up that some Bubi rebels killed two soldiers here
in Luba and marched north toward Malabo. They were stopped near the
capital by soldiers, who are believed to have carried out reprisal
attacks in and around Luba.
</P>
<P>
   These days, things seemed to have settled down. Filiberto
Estrada, 27, a mason, is one of the many people who have gravitated
here after hearing of job opportunities. He has not found one yet,
complaining, as do many other jobless young men, that the jobs go
to those with connections to the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   He did not understand why the government was packing up and
going to Bata.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time I've heard of it,'' Estrada said. He
added, with a smile: ``Each country has its own way of doing
things. And here in Equatorial Guinea, we have our own way of doing
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
