<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MUSIC-EXCHANGE SERVICE FIGHTS INJUNCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MUSIC-RULING-REACT) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lawyers for Napster asked a federal court here
Thursday to stay a preliminary injunction issued by a judge on
Wednesday, asserting that the injunction would effectively put the
Internet service, which permits computer users to freely exchange
music, out of business.
</P>
<P>
   In their brief, filed in the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ,
Napster lawyers argued that Chief Judge Marilyn Patel of the U.S.
District Court overstepped her authority by seeking to extend
copyright law to a new technology. The brief also argued that
Patel, in the 90-minute hearing, did not consider all of the
evidence, including studies that contend that Napster helps, rather
than hinders, record sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing the same reasoning at Court of Appeals they
tried at the judge,'' said Hilary Rosen, president of the Recording
Industry Association of America, the industry group that had sought
the injunction. ``The judge's reasoning was solid and this won't be
successful,'' she said of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction, which is to take effect on Friday at midnight,
precludes Napster from allowing its users to exchange copyrighted
music owned by the major record labels, pending a trial. Napster
says the injunction effectively will put it out of business since
it cannot distinguish legal from illegal songs. No trial date has
yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   Although the record industry praised the judge's action on
Wednesday, its celebration was tempered by what analysts say is an
imposing challenge: putting their own businesses online to meet a
demand for music that Napster so clearly demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have got to fill the vacuum,'' said Michael B. Nathanson,
a record industry analyst with Sanford C. Bernstein, the securities
firm. ``They just can't keep stopping these things. They've got to
be aggressive over the next six to 12 months'' in making their
music available online.
</P>
<P>
   But Nathanson and industry executives have been speaking with
such urgent tones for the last two years, and, in some cases by
their own admission, they have little to show for it. The major
record labels have begun selling some music, mostly singles, for
download, and are exploring subscription-based sites in which
visitors could pay a fee to download music.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, for instance, has roughly 50 songs available for download,
selling them for $2.49 each. The company has a partnership with
Universal Music Group to develop a subscription-based model.
Meanwhile, EMI, another major record label, has begun making
downloads available, and will soon sell singles for $3.49 and full
albums for $17.95 on a site called musicmaker.com.
</P>
<P>
   The labels say they have aggressively pursued strategies for
distributing music online, striking business deals with music
sites, working to develop secure technology, and exploring new
business models. But the challenge is daunting because they want to
create encryption technology that will prevent their music from
being freely exchanged. They assert that Napster makes online music
distribution look deceivingly easy because it facilitates the free
exchange of songs; the service claims that 20 million users
downloaded its free file-sharing software, and recording industry
lawyers say that 14,000 songs change hands each minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to be realistic. We're not going to re-create
Napster overnight,'' said Rosen of the Recording Industry
Association. ``It's a lot harder to get people to come to a party
than to a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   But they might eventually re-create a service similar to
Napster, or even purchase Napster itself, people within the record
industry say. A person at one of the major record labels said that
most, if not all, of the labels have considered purchasing Napster
and finding a way to license the content exchanged by users. But
that person said that the labels appear not to be able to find a
way to make the service profitable while permitting the wide
exchange of content that has made it so popular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
