<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-EARTHLINK0728-1STLEDE     07-27 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHLINK0728-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Change in wording in 1st graf.
 &HT;    EarthLink has strong growth, lower losses
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ EarthLink Inc. on Thursday reported booming revenue, a
smaller than expected loss and strong customer growth as it
continued its pursuit of America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The company also acknowledged that quality of service _ on which
it pegs its reputation _ suffered at least in the first few months
of the merger between EarthLink and MindSpring Enterprises as the
companies melded network and customer service operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had some rocky times in the first quarter,'' said
company President Michael McQuary. ``I think we will continue to
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company offers Internet access _ including
high-speed connections _ as well as Web hosting services. The
company says recent troubles have been temporary and limited, and
that customers should check its Web site or _ if they cannot get
online _ call customer support.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever problems there have been, EarthLink has not shed
customers more rapidly than before. In fact, during the first
quarter, 5 percent of customers broke their EarthLink connection, a
``churn'' rate that dipped to 4.2 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink reported revenue of $230.9 million for the quarter
ended June 30, up 41 percent from revenue of $163.7 million in the
year-earlier period.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a net loss for the quarter of $35.2
million, or 29 cents per share, not including acquisition and
merger-related costs. EarthLink had net income of $5.3 million, or
5 cents per share, during the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But growth matters more right now than short-term profits, in
EarthLink's view, and the company finished the quarter with 3.7
million subscribers. With ``organic'' growth and the completion of
a deal to acquire OneMain.com, EarthLink will reach 5 million
subscribers by year's end, McQuary said.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of EarthLink's growth comes from former AOL members,
he said. ``We are in the second inning, not the seventh inning. We
will continue to close the gap with AOL.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has more than 23 million members, in addition to its massive
deal to buy Time Warner. If that merger is completed, AOL will
increasingly become a media company, owning content like the shows
that run on Time Warner's cable service, McQuary said. ``We are in
a different business. We don't compete against Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   The consumer dial-up represents a declining portion of the
business _ about 85 percent of revenues. Meanwhile, the company
increasingly looks elsewhere for future profits. For instance,
high-speed lines are increasingly seen as the preferred connection
to the Net. EarthLink now has 80,000 customers with that
``broadband'' link. The company expects to have 150,000 broadband
customers by year's end using digital subscriber lines (DSL), cable
modems and wireless.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-ILL-VOTE-VOICES-2TAKE     07-27 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-VOTE-VOICES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ILLINOIS SUBURB, LITTLE ENTHUSIASM FOR BUSH AND GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   by PAM BELLUCK  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ It is a puzzling political season for George
Gauthier.
</P>
<P>
   Although the major presidential candidates were identified
months ago, Gauthier, a builder, has no idea whom he will vote for.
</P>
<P>
   He knows where he stands on the issues and has thoughtful,
nuanced ideas about what a president should be. But so far, no
candidate has given him enough to go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush doesn't have the strengths in foreign and national
politics that his father did,'' said Gauthier, 59, who also runs an
organization to help lower-income people obtain homes, ``and
there's been good and bad state governors as presidents, so he
comes into it having to answer why he should be executive of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Gore, my fear is that his programs would be too big, too
expensive,'' said Gauthier, who voted for Republicans in the last
four presidential elections, Democrats in the previous three and
knows only that he will not vote for a third-party candidate this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both of them show leadership potential, an ability to
project their vision of the future,'' he said. ``Neither is going
to effect major radical change. It's a question of how they would
lean, which bias they have. It's hard to find the best candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican and Democratic conventions coming up,
Gauthier is hardly in the minority, interviews with voters suggest.
In dozens of discussions in Evanston, a diverse, middle-class
suburb just north of Chicago in a critical swing-vote state, people
were studiously skeptical, waiting for answers, and wary of the
campaign games politicians play.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a single urgent issue like war or economic
crisis, voters were sizing up candidates as managers, stewards and
respect-worthy leaders rather than as rallying, agenda-driven
politicians. Voters were more interested in what kind of cabinet
officials and Supreme Court justices the candidates would appoint
and in how they would work with Congress, than in where they stood
on every issue.
</P>
<P>
   And while most said they wanted a president with consistency and
integrity, someone unlikely to be swayed by interest-group
pressure, they doubted whether any candidate had those qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see a leader who's not captive of special
interests, but it may be impossible,'' said Edith Eisner, a
75-year-old retired English teacher who said she would vote for
Vice President Al Gore. ``I think both the candidates now can be
pushed around.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Butkus, the president of an engineering firm who said he
would vote for Gov. George W. Bush, said: ``My big concern about
presidential politics is once you get to be able to run for
president you've had to make so many promises and compromises that
you've compromised yourself coming through the system. Gore got his
hand caught in the cookie jar in fund-raising, but really the
system made him do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Evanston, home of Northwestern University and one of the few
racially diverse communities in the Illinois suburbs, more people
vote for Democrats. But the interviews focused on people across the
political spectrum. All except one of those interviewed said they
had ruled out voting for the third-party candidates, Ralph Nader of
the Green Party and Patrick J. Buchanan of the Reform Party. Most
considered them extreme or narrowly focused, although some said
they found Nader appealing but unelectable.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, among people who said they would support Gore or
Bush, there was frequently little passion about the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Wilson, a 40-year-old civil rights lawyer, said she had
always voted Democratic and would again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said: ``I think Gore is questionable. I don't think
he tells the truth all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, with two children and a husband who is also a lawyer,
said she was fairly certain that Gore agreed with her on education,
the environment, affirmative action and other issues, but had
reservations about ``him as a person.'' She said she believed, for
example, that he was ``pandering'' when he said that Elian Gonzalez
and his father should be given permanent residency status, and she
said his ethics on campaign financing were ``a little loose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to always say what people want to hear,'' she said.
``I can't get excited about him and trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   Butkus, 48, who typically backs Republicans for president, said
of Governor Bush: ``I believe that his political background is
wanting. He doesn't have a lot of political experience. There's
just not a big book on him to let you now how he'd act in
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was ``not happy'' with Bush's vague response about
whether he had used cocaine, but added, ``There's abuses on the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I'm impressed with Bush about is that he has
been picking good people and they're sticking by him,'' Butkus
said. ``It hasn't been a revolving door.''
</P>
<P>
   People seem well aware of what presidential power can and cannot
do these days. Their priorities included Supreme Court appointments
and keeping Alan Greenspan as chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board. Some would like a foreign policy leader to help resolve the
Middle East conflict, deal firmly with Russia and either scrap or
build a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Some mentioned health care that would be affordable for all
citizens and progress in race relations. Most said they believed
the economy would continue strongly under either candidate. And no
one linked his or her vote to a single issue, like school vouchers
or the death penalty _ indeed, a few said such issues should be
left to the states.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Butkus' wife, Ellen, 47, said she strongly opposed abortion, but
would not make that a litmus test. ``The check mark in the little
box just doesn't give you a sense of all the different ways that
this candidate could affect things,'' said Mrs. Butkus, a nurse who
works with the homebound elderly through her Mennonite church.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Mrs. Butkus, who is undecided and would not rule out
Nader, is more concerned about how candidates would deal with
racial issues and what impact they would have on things like the
death penalty and school choice. ``I think a president is in a
position to raise people's awareness of how the country behaves as
a whole, of what the injustices are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several people seemed to favor both the pro-business,
smaller-government approach historically associated with
Republicans and the sense of social justice and inclusiveness
typically linked to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want someone who's going to have a balance in being
generally businesslike in the management of government,'' said Don
Colleton, a 58-year-old lawyer leaning toward Bush. ``But I'm not
one to play around with some of these social issues. I want folks
to behave in a way that is just resolute in acknowledging the
intrinsic equal dignity of members of the human race, whatever
color or size they come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier exemplifies the sense of wanting to borrow from both
Republicans and Democrats. He says that the federal government
should deal with social problems by financing private nonprofit
agencies like his housing coalition, which he contends are more
cost-effective than government agencies. He says he thinks a
prescription drug plan should include means-testing so that those
people most in need will benefit, and that eventually, there will
have to be means tests for Social Security and Medicare. He also
contends school vouchers are unworkable, and that the government
should take some of the money now being spent on the military and
battling illegal drugs and put it into drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gauthier is so concerned with balance that he said he
might vote for the candidate whose party appeared that it would not
have a majority in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Several people expressed concern that Bush might be influenced
by radical right-wing voices in the Republican Party, but none
seemed concerned that Gore would be similarly pulled from the
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bush's heart is one place and his head is another,''
said the Rev. Larry Bullock, an African Methodist Episcopal
minister who also owns construction businesses. ``I think he is a
compassionate conservative, but I think he's too beholden to
certain wings of his party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock said he would probably vote for Gore, but wanted the
Democratic candidate to ``show a freshness and a newness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really got to rattle those bones,'' Bullock said.
``Clinton gave us the bridge to the 21st century. Gore needs to
tell us what's on the other side of the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those interviewed said their view of President Clinton
would not affect their vote. Supporters and critics said Gore was
appropriately loyal in defending the president in the Monica
Lewinsky matter. And most said that he deserved neither credit nor
criticism for Clinton administration policies.
</P>
<P>
   One exception was Lorraine Morton, the Democratic mayor of
Evanston, who said she did not have ``great enthusiasm'' for Gore,
but ``Clinton did a fantastic job,'' and if elected, ``Gore can
pick up the telephone and say, `Bill. what do you think about so
and so.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although most people said Bush made a good choice in Dick Cheney
as his running mate, those interviewed said it would not affect
their views.
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign heats up, the candidates might do well to listen
to the likes of Barry Slotnick.
</P>
<P>
   Slotnick, 28, who works in his family's travel business and owns
a fitness equipment company, considers himself ``fiscally
conservative and socially liberal,'' pro-entrepreneur and
pro-abortion rights. He voted Republican in 1992 and 1996, but
started this campaign admiring Bill Bradley, especially his
progressive views on race relations. ``As Bradley's situation
started to fade,'' he said, ``I really took an interest in John
McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Slotnick is ``very much on the fence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Republican platform when it comes to small
government,'' he said, but he said he was worried about ``some very
frightening people in the far reaches of the Republican Party, the
far right.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bush, he said, he is unsure ``how much has been attained
because he's daddy's boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that Gore brings more
experience, having been vice president for eight years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Slotnick said he believed that Bush ``could probably get
a good cabinet together.'' And while ``Bush seems to me like a
grown-up frat boy,'' Slotnick said, he also ``seems like a more
approachable, more normal guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems less political,'' Slotnick said. ``Gore, everything
he does seems a little rehearsed.''
</P>
<P>
   Slotnick said he thinks ``both Gore and Bush can keep the
momentum in the economy going,'' adding: ``So this year I'm really
looking more at the person. At the end of the day you look for
someone who really you can look up to and trust. Are they a good
representation of the country?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
