<SLUG> BC-CARS-AUDI-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS AND CLASS AND CASH ($68,425) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 (Editors: Also see CARS-PORSCHE-BOXSTER . )  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What do Americans want? More, always more, it
seems, and automakers are happy to comply, cramming six pistons
into cars that run nicely on four and shoehorning V-8s into engine
bays where V-6s are a tight fit. Not often does a redesigned car or
truck end up smaller than the one it replaces.
</P>
<P>
   Already large automobiles are not exempt from size creep.
Mercedes-Benz once offered both long- and longer-wheelbase versions
of its biggest sedan, but Americans showed a strong preference for
the first-class cabin, rendering business-class accommodations
unnecessary. BMW has the 740iL and 750iL, with rear seats that come
closer to meeting the bottom-line needs of well-fed customers.
Jaguar, whose charms have included famously cozy rear quarters,
added the commodious XJ8 L and Vanden Plas. A slightly stretched
Lincoln now accounts for 8 percent of Town Car sales.
</P>
<P>
   So who should be surprised that for 2000, Audi has the A8L, a
five-inch-longer version of its all-aluminum luxury liner. Only
those, perhaps, who recall that when the A8 made its debut, less
than four years ago, Audi mocked competitors by summarizing its
car's virtues as ``excellence without excess, class without mass.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still excellence in the A8s advanced space frame, a
rigid skeleton of lightweight aluminum, and in its unobtrusive
Quattro all-wheel drive. There is class, too, in the understated
but sumptuous cabin, which has gained nearly 3 inches of rear
legroom and a bit of extra space for heads and elbows.
</P>
<P>
   As for mass, the A8L is hardly lacking, since even with all
those aluminum pieces it tips the scales at 4,156 pounds, a bit
more than the steel-body Mercedes S500. The A8L measures 203.3
inches long, about the same as the Mercedes and a bit longer than
the BMW 740iL.
</P>
<P>
   The pluses and minuses of this outsized Audi were evident on a
1,500-mile trip through Northern California and Nevada, given that
the car was saddled with four adults, six sizable bags and a few
bottles of cabernet sauvignon picked up during stops in wine
country. The $72,525 test car (base price, $68,425) proved an
excellent choice for luxurious grand touring, pampering passengers
with a ride that was practically serene.
</P>
<P>
   Its climate control was put to the test, since we visited wine
country during a heat wave. After a memorable hot lunch in a
restaurant whose air conditioner had failed, the Audi's external
thermometer registered 120 degrees. Given what it was up against,
the climate system coped admirably.
</P>
<P>
   The backseat is the big news here, and it got rave reviews from
its occupants. There were firm but cosseting seats covered in
perforated leather, power-adjusted headrests and lumbar support and
no lack of space. Two 70-something passengers could quibble only
about the backrest (raked a little too steeply) and the sunscreens
(ineffective against a blazing California sun). But they
appreciated how the wider doors aided entrances and exits,
particularly when noontime placed them at their fourth wine tasting
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   From the driver's seat, though, the Audi reminds one about the
march of progress. While the A8 seemed so innovative in 1996 _ it
was called ``the first luxury car of the 21st century'' on this
page _ it competes in a segment that changed radically a year ago
with the arrival of an all-new S-Class. While the Audi has bulked
up, the Mercedes trimmed down and learned to dance.
</P>
<P>
   In our travels, the A8L never faltered, whether tracing
switchbacks in the Sierra Nevada or negotiating jagged ocean-view
turns on Highway 1. If it had, a new stability control could step
in to save the day. Yet a touch of body roll on turns, and steering
that didn't feel as crisp as it actually proved to be, made it
clear that this is a luxury cruiser, not an overgrown sport sedan.
Its luxurious size also made for tight maneuvers in cramped public
garages. On sharp descents, the five-speed Tiptronic transmission
resolutely refused to engage first gear except for an instant after
a standing stop, forcing overuse of the brake pedal.
</P>
<P>
   This is a brisk car for its size, capable of 0-to-60 dashes in
well under 7 seconds, yet the test car felt leaden in a range of
1,200 to 1,800 rpm. The horsepower of the dual-cam 4.2-liter V-8
has been raised to 310. There is 302 foot-pounds of peak torque for
Autobahn zoom at cruising speeds. Yet the A8L managed to feel a bit
sluggish when merging into traffic at 45 mph or climbing a steep
grade in high elevations.
</P>
<P>
   A long car trip turns little annoyances into oversized
irritations. In the A8L, these included a touchy throttle that
works against smooth starts; one-touch window switches that never
performed as expected; and overcomplicated audio and climate
controls. I did not use the standard-equipment navigation system,
for lack of a map disk, and I eventually switched off the acoustic
parking sensors (a $700 option), which detect obstacles as you try
to dock this zeppelin. The system is calibrated so sensitively that
it beeps long before you're close to another car's bumper, and it
makes a terrible racket, too.
</P>
<P>
   At night, the cabin is a little Las Vegas of red lights, with
more than 100 switches, knobs and buttons. Aside from being a bit
overwhelming, the controls are not particularly intuitive, but they
do put one in the mood to visit a casino. No wonder that when we
pulled up to Harrah's on Lake Tahoe in our impressively oversized
Audi, friendly people greeted us as if we were high rollers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
