<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-PAIN-NYT &LR;      07-27 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SUGGEST PAIN IN INFANCY MAY CAUSE LIFELONG PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mass.)   By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A study showing that pain administered in infancy can
permanently rewire the nervous system in rats may have implications
for human infants undergoing painful medical procedures,
researchers are reporting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Animals given sore feet for a few days as infants ended up
hypersensitive to pain as adults, according to the researchers'
report appearing in the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   They said the finding could be worrisome for babies and
premature infants in intensive care units who are repeatedly stuck
with needles and subjected to other painful tests and treatments.
</P>
<P>
   If the findings in animals are confirmed in people, they will
provide strong evidence that even the smallest premature babies
need careful treatment for pain. In the past, it was thought that
newborns and premature infants had little pain sensitivity, and
circumcisions and even major operations were often done without
anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   It is now known that infants are quite sensitive to pain, and
they are no longer subjected to surgery without anesthesia. But
they do still undergo other painful procedures, like repeated blood
tests without the use of painkilling creams that numb the skin.
</P>
<P>
   In the rats, hypersensitivity apparently occurred because their
nervous systems were still developing and reacted to the foot
irritation by sprouting extra pain nerves in the spinal cord,
according to a report by Dr. Maryann Ruda and other researchers
from the National Institute of Dental and Craniofacial Research &UR;  &LR; in
Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear how much bearing the findings have on
people, even though baby rats and human infants behave similarly in
response to pain, and the pain pathways in their nervous systems
develop in much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Berde, a professor of pediatrics and anesthesiology
at Harvard Medical School, who did not take part in the new study,
said some research in human infants had also suggested that lasting
hypersensitivity could result from pain in infancy. But, he said,
the findings are highly controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very emotionally charged area,'' Berde said.
</P>
<P>
   At one extreme, he said, are researchers who argue that babies
are highly resilient and recover from all manner of noxious
experiences. At the other extreme are those who take the view that
injury and pain will damage a child for life. The truth may fall
somewhere in between, he said, but good data about long-term
effects are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly true that injury in early life causes changes
in the pattern of connections and nerve organization,'' Berde said.
``That has good and bad aspects. There may be persistent
oversensitivity to pain, but there may also be more capacity to
recover from it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that premature babies in intensive care units often did
become hypersensitive to pain, but that it was not known how long
the condition lasted. Paradoxically, in some cases where children
might be expected to become hypersensitive, they do not, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he added, babies with shoulder injuries resulting
from difficult births rarely show signs of pain, even during
physical therapy. But adults with similar injuries from motorcycle
accidents frequently have long-term pain.
</P>
<P>
   Ruda and her colleagues injected an irritating substance to
create a sore and swollen hind foot for five to seven days in
newborn rats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let them mature like normal rats would, and when they were
adults we looked at the anatomical organization of the nerves
innervating the hind paw, going from the foot to the spinal cord,''
she said. The researchers found that extra nerve endings had
sprouted and had also branched into new areas of the spinal cord
where they would not normally be found.
</P>
<P>
   The adult animals also showed a greater than normal response to
pain, Ruda said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that rats were generally considered good models for
studying pain in humans, but that a study in people would be needed
to determine whether they suffered similar long-term consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's needed now is to get a population of individuals that
did have treatments that caused significant pain and tissue injury
as neonates and do careful pain measures on them now and see if
there are differences and to what extent they occur,'' Ruda said.
</P>
</TEXT>
