<HEADER>
A5026 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CARS-PORSCHE-BOXSTER-     07-27 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-PORSCHE-BOXSTER-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLASH AND CASH ($49,000) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 (Editors: Also see CARS-AUDI . )  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New! Improved! Few products deserve those exclamation points,
but the Porsche Boxster S is an exception. What began as a fun
roadster has been transformed into a serious sports car, at the
added expense of a relatively modest $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   The plain-vanilla Porsche Boxster came to America in 1997, just
as Mercedes-Benz and BMW were landing their own pricey little
roadsters. All three found enthusiastic, if somewhat different,
customers. The Mercedes SLK230, with its soft ride, automatic
transmission, retractable hardtop and candy colors, attracted women
buyers. The BMW Z3, with its elegant retro looks and initially tame
engine, picked up a preppier suburban crowd. Meanwhile, the
Boxster, with its swoopy futuristic sheet metal and austere ride,
was slotted as the roadster for real drivers _ those who craved an
entry-level sports car rather than a touring vehicle for weekends
in Napa or the Hamptons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I fit myself in the last category, but was a bit frustrated by
the original Boxster's elusive hints of greatness. And $40,000-plus
seemed high for a roadster of modest comfort, whose performance was
so overshadowed by the muscular Porsche 911. The company did not
have any trouble selling the cars, and still doesn't, but it went
back and finished the job. The Boxster S is everything I wanted the
first time around.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How did Porsche accomplish this transformation? The engineers
started with the same horizontally opposed six-cylinder engine that
sits just forward of the rear wheels in both models. But they
increased the engine's displacement from 2.5 liters (in the 1999
Boxster) to 3.2 liters, giving it 250 horsepower as compared with
201 horsepower. (For 2000, the standard-issue Boxster has 217
horsepower.) The greater displacement, complemented by improvements
in both the air-intake system and the electronics, also raised the
maximum torque by 25 percent, to a hefty 225 foot-pounds. Most of
that torque, by the way, is available at relatively low engine
speeds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it takes a lot more than muscle to make a sports car.
A perfectly adequate five-speed manual transmission has been
replaced by the mechanically tougher six-speed gearbox from the
911. The 16-inch wheels were replaced by 17-inch wheels that carry
wider, lower profile speed-rated rubber. The big disc brakes were
replaced with even bigger disc brakes (again, from the 911 parts
bin). And the suspension was beefed up to improve high-speed
cornering stability. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The visual cues distinguishing the Boxster S are, to say the
least, discreet: a third air intake located at the front bumper,
twin tailpipe outlets, different wheels to show off the big brake
calipers painted red. The interior plastic and leather are
highlighted with aluminum trim.
</P>
<P>
   The ergonomics are excellent, with comfortable, supportive
bucket seats and a mix of dials, digital readouts and idiot lights
that minimizes distractions from the road. But Porsche made some
improvements for the S version, notably a height adjustment for the
seats and a steering wheel that telescopes as well as tilts. The
power softtops on the two models are nearly identical, but Porsche
added padding to the inside of the top on the Boxster S, which
provides significant sound insulation to an already nicely fitted
top. A removable aluminum roof is an option on both Boxsters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All this amounts to preface. What counts in deciding whether the
S is worth the extra bucks is how the new version compares on the
road. And here, there's just no contest. The engine on the ordinary
Boxster still feels a touch sluggish in hard acceleration. The
Boxster S may be less than a second faster to 60 miles per hour
(5.7 seconds versus 6.4 seconds) but feels much stronger at engine
speeds below 4,000 r.p.m. Indeed, the S engine offers so much
torque across so wide a band that its feels fine in third gear
anywhere between 20 and 80 miles an hour _ a flexibility that pays
off in heavy traffic where frequent shifting can be a big bore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The differences in steering and handling are yet more
impressive. While both Boxsters offer marvelous road manners and
both have rear spoilers that extend automatically at 75 mph to
offset the tendency of the body to take off, the S is more the
master in a variety of driving situations. It stays heavier and
more stable on rough roads, yet takes corners at higher speeds
without a hint of roll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Boxsters come with an optional traction control system that
uses both the brakes and the engine to prevent the rear wheels from
sliding on slippery surfaces. Those who want to corner using
controlled oversteer can shut off the system with a button. But the
fat tires on the S are so grippy that aggressive
``throttle-steering,'' pushing the car hard enough so that the rear
wheels slide, would probably not be practical in real world
situations for any but the most skilled drivers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gripes? Just a few. The interior seems a bit cheesy for a
$50,000 car: in my otherwise delightful week of driving the Boxster
S, two pieces of interior plastic trim self-destructed and one
idiot light refused to go off. This shouldn't surprise; the
original Boxster proved to be far from 100 percent reliable in
long-term tests conducted by several magazines.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, too many things that should be standard on a
car this expensive are options: cruise control, premium sound,
leather, wind deflector and cassette and CD storage units for the
dash. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
