<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GIRL ON THE BRIDGE': EXPLORING THE KNIFE'S EDGE OF DESIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last two decades or so, sex in movies _ even French
movies _ has become demystified, conventional and, well, unsexy.
Even the most artfully directed writhing, the most ardently
counterfeited sighs and moans can seem a bit pro forma. And so
ambitious filmmakers _ especially French ones _ are faced with the
challenge of how to bring genuine erotic heat to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Girl on the Bridge,'' a soap-bubble of romantic attitude
and second-hand glamour, Patrice Leconte succeeds by discovering
something sexier than sex, at once a perfect metaphor and a
convincing substitute for it. That something is knifethrowing, an
obscure music-hall attraction that Leconte dusts off and places at
the center of this giddy sendup of (and tribute to) European cinema
in its heady postwar golden age.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in sumptuous black and white, replete with dizzy, swooping
camera effects and gorgeous shots of Paris, Monaco, Athens and
Istanbul, ``Girl on the Bridge'' is like a pocket anthology of your
favorite foreign movies (or mine, anyway), a meticulous
cut-and-paste collage of a half-dozen half-remembered, dreamed-up
movies by Godard, Truffaut and, above all, Fellini. The story is
``La Strada'' without the poverty and fatalism: It follows the
sadomasochistic, symbiotic relationship between a knocked-around
carnival performer and his assistant. The homage to Fellini is far
from subtle: there is the parade of clowns, dwarves and
contortionists, big luxury cruise ships and garish casinos,
pore-tight close-ups and careening crane shots.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the knife throwing. Adele (Vanessa Paradis) is a
young woman who has drifted through a life of aimless, passive
promiscuity (``I believe every promise I hear'') that has led her
to the brink of suicide. Standing on a chilly Paris bridge she
meets Gabor (Daniel Auteuil), a profane, philosophical knife
thrower out recruiting new talent. After saving her life, he
persuades her to risk it, and they set out to conquer the cabarets
and casinos of Europe with their act. He seems a bit uncertain of
his own skill, but that, he assures her, is a secondary
consideration. The secret to knife throwing is to find a fortunate
target.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Gabor briefs Adele on the finer points of his
worldview, a kind of gambler's mysticism based on the cosmology of
luck. He also instructs her in the cultivation of her gifts. ``The
audience must fall in love with you,'' he instructs. It isn't
difficult. The coltish, gap-toothed Paradis, heretofore best known
in France as a pop singer, has the effortless gamine appeal of Jean
Seberg in ``Breathless'' or Audrey Hepburn in ``Funny Face.''
Gabor, needless to say, falls hard, but the only consummation he
needs is to stand and hurl the tools of his trade, with their long,
symmetrical, rounded blades, at her trembling form.
</P>
<P>
   The first time they do this for an audience, she's hidden behind
a sheet, and it's one of the most sexually charged sequences ever
filmed, full of danger and audacity. But as the film pursues the
metaphoric link between cutlery and concupiscence, with its
overtones of risk and domination, it loses some of its insouciant
accuracy. By the time Gabor and Adele perform in private, in an
empty warehouse, for the sole purpose of satisfying their own
desires, the scene has a cheap, heavy-breathing staginess. They
might as well be doing it the old-fashioned way, between the
sheets, without any sharp objects on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl on the Bridge'' is most entertaining when it takes itself
least seriously, when it forsakes melancholy romanticism for the
gaudy, extravagant kind. The chemistry between Auteuil, with his
craggy, unshaven sensuality, and Paradis, with her sexual
incandescence, is so perfect that it undermines the movie's attempt
to generate conflict and distance between them.
</P>
<P>
   Adele is supposedly still drawn to her old, man-crazy life, but
her intoxication with Gabor and his blades is so evident that we
don't understand why she would want anything else. The targets of
her lust seem so pretty and callow that they can't be serious
rivals, and the film's last third, during which the couple's luck
turns bad, is so predictable and lacking in dramatic force that not
even the glories of the Acropolis at dusk or the shimmering lights
of the Bosphorus can save the movie. The final scene is such a
heavy dose of Hollywood schmaltz that you half expect Auteuil and
Paradis to be replaced by Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Watching this film, with its brightly underscored themes of luck
and risk, is like watching a high-stakes gambler amass a big pile
of chips and then fritter it away on a series of small, pointless
bets. Leconte's visual instincts are so impressive that they
outstrip his story, leaving us flushed and bedazzled, but also, as
after a long night of champagne and baccarat (to say nothing of
other irresponsible pleasures) hungry, tired, and homesick.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GIRL ON THE BRIDGE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Patrice Leconte; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Serge Frydman; director of photography, Jean-Marie
Dreujou; edited by Joelle Hache; produced by Christian Fechner;
released by Paramount Classics.
</P>
<P>
   With: Daniel Auteuil (Gabor), Vanessa Paradis (Adele), Bertie
Cortez (Kusak), Giorgios Gatzios (Barker), Demetre Georgalas
(Takis), Luc Palun (Stage Manager), Isabelle Petit-Jacques (Bride),
Frederic Pfluger (Contortionist) and Natascha Solignac (Nurse).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 92 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl on the Bridge'' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes sexual
situations and obvious sexual metaphors.
</P>
</TEXT>
