<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: HEALTH SERVICE REFORM
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair proposed the biggest reform of the
beleaguered National Health Service in its 52 years, with promises
of more doctors and nurses, improved patient care, reduced waiting
times and spending increases of 6.1 percent above inflation over
the next four years to bring the service in line with European
averages. The erosion in health services has hurt Blair's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: EXPLOSION IN DUESSELDORF
</P>
<P>
   An explosion in a pedestrian tunnel leading into a commuter
railway station injured nine people, two of them seriously, and the
police said a bomb was suspected. No claims of responsibility were
made. Bomb attacks have been rare in Germany in recent years. A
grenade attack on a Hamburg disco this year has been linked to the
city's drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: NO THREEPENNY OPERA
</P>
<P>
   Luciano Pavarotti has agreed to pay more than $12 million in
back taxes, ending one of the more operatic tax disputes in Italian
fiscal history. The government maintained that the tenor had
falsely listed a house in the tax haven of Monte Carlo as his
primary residence. In a letter to the Turin newspaper, La Stampa,
Pavarotti wrote that ``it is very difficult to explain the life of
one who travels the world and who visits 50 cities every year.''
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: POWER FAILURES
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of the port town of Nakhodka in Russia's Far East,
Viktor Gnezdilov, has appealed to Moscow for help in preventing
chronic electricity blackouts, Interfax reported. Earlier in the
week, protesters in Nakhodka blockaded a highway to protest
electricity reductions and the Defense Ministry warned about
shortages on military bases.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: OVERTURE TO OPPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Vicente Fox met with Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the
leftist former Mexico City mayor who finished a distant third in
July 2 presidential balloting. Fox said he apologized for harsh
criticisms he may have made during the campaign and expressed hopes
that some of Cardenas' associates would take part in his
government. Cardenas remained noncommital, saying his party
intended to act as a ``constructive opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: JAILED AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   An American who fled to Canada in 1971 to escape a four-year
prison term for a minor drug offense will have to spend at least
eight more months in a New York State jail before being eligible
for parole, state parole officials say. Allen Richardson, 50,
surrendered to American authorities last month to clear up his
status after serving only a few months of a four-year sentence for
selling $20 worth of LSD to an undercover police officer three
decades ago. Richardson, who worked until June at a physics
laboratory at the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, said
he fled a low security work camp to avoid being transferred to the
state prison in Attica.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: FARMERS APPEAL TO COURT
</P>
<P>
   The Commercial Farmers Union, which represents the country's
4,000 white commercial farmers, asked the High Court to hold the
national police chief in contempt for failing to remove black
squatters who still occupy more than 1,000 white-owned farms. The
police chief and others have flouted a March court order requiring
the squatters to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA: ILLEGAL DIAMONDS
</P>
<P>
   Britain accused the Angolan rebel movement led by Jonas Savimbi
of continuing to break a United Nations embargo on the sale of
diamonds to finance its long-running war against the government.
The Foreign Office said the sales had been conducted in Libreville,
the capital of Gabon. The United Nations sought to impose a ban on
diamond sales by the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
