<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5037 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-NAPSTER-GOLDSTEI     07-27 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-NAPSTER-GOLDSTEIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC WON'T LEAVE THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Friday, July 28, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By PAUL GOLDSTEIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ Here's an adage for the Internet age: New
technology has a way of making itself indispensable _ even to those
who are at first wary of it.
</P>
<P>
   This will be true even for the big music labels, which won an
important battle against Napster, an online music bazaar that
allows computer users to exchange music without paying a penny for
the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the music companies are naturally gratified that a
federal district judge has ruled that Napster violated copyright
law and has ordered the online service to stop permitting the
exchange of music, effectively shutting it down.
</P>
<P>
   In the industry's mind, its music and its artists have been
protected from digital piracy. But a year or two down the road,
these same companies may find that some comparable online service
could be their indispensable friend.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 years ago, music publishers filed a copyright lawsuit
to stop the manufacture of piano rolls, on the ground that they
would undercut sales of sheet music. The publishers lost their case
in the Supreme Court but soon got Congress to amend the copyright
act in their favor, requiring manufacturers of music rolls, as well
as the newly popular phonograph records, to pay lucrative royalty
fees.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, when radio stations broadcast musical works
without paying royalties, the publishers sued again. The stations
contended that their broadcasts were free and, in any case,
increased the sales of sheet music _ virtually the same arguments
Napster made two weeks ago in Senate hearings, when it claimed that
its service was free and that it boosted record companies' sales.
As in the case of Napster, the argument of the radio stations did
not succeed in court. Because of this, radio stations today pay to
broadcast music _ and music publishers and record companies depend
on these stations to promote their products.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every confrontation between the entertainment industry
and new technology ends in the same way: four or five years after
the litigation and legislation end, the new technology _ once the
industry's fearsome enemy _ becomes its staunchest ally. Indeed,
the technology ends up generating abundant new revenue for the
owners of copyrights.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon is not confined to music. In the late 1970s,
motion picture companies sued to stop the sale of VCRs, arguing
that the industry lost money anytime viewers copied movies from
television broadcasts. Also, in the early '80s, the movie companies
went to Congress to ask for legislation requiring video stores to
pay a royalty each time they rented a cassette. The companies lost
in court and in Congress. Yet, without either of the legal rights
they sought, the industry developed a fresh source of revenue
through the expanded sale of videocassettes.
</P>
<P>
   According to Napster's lawyer, the company could be forced to
shut down if it loses its appeal. Napster may no longer exist, but
the technology will likely live on and thrive on the Internet. It's
not hard to see how music companies could benefit from online
services. Already, some companies are licensed to distribute music
on the Web. With modest levels of encryption and reasonable
pricing, music companies could make hundreds of millions of dollars
by offering their products online.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, music companies will adapt to these new services.
The industry may be able to shut down Napster, but it can't stop
the advance of technology.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Goldstein, a law professor at Stanford University, is the
author of ``Copyright's Highway: From Gutenberg to the Celestial
Jukebox.'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
