<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5038 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WACO-HNS &LR;      07-27 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    FBI wants to learn from Waco mistakes
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno, cleared of wrongdoing
in the deadly 1993 Branch Davidian siege, said Thursday that her
agency would learn from its mistakes and move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``One doesn't think in terms of exoneration when you look at
something like that,'' Reno said, referring to the fatal fire at
the cult compound near Waco. ``That was a terrible tragedy and . .
. we've got to look to the future to see what we can learn about
human behavior to avoid tragedies like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's comments followed last Friday's release of investigator
John Danforth's preliminary report, in which he concluded that
Branch Davidian leader David Koresh started the blaze that killed
81 cult members at their compound as FBI agents moved in.
</P>
<P>
   But Danforth, a former U.S. senator from Missouri, faulted FBI
agents for failing to tell senior officials for six years that
federal lawmen used pyrotechnic tear-gas devices four hours before
the final fire April 19, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   That failure led Reno to tell Congress that pyrotechnic devices
weren't used at the cult's compound, scene of a lengthy siege by
federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Public confidence in federal law enforcement fell when the FBI
belatedly disclosed last year that the devices might have been
used, Danforth said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Danforth's preliminary report excused Reno of blame, the
attorney general said the bad end to the siege not only remains a
painful memory but also a motivation to improve law enforcement
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion that it weighs heavily in terms of dragging me
down, I don't let things like that do that,'' Reno said at her
regular Thursday briefing with reporters. ``I just try to look to
the future and say, what can we do when another David Koresh or
somebody like him appears? Make sure that we know as much as we can
about human behavior and what we can do to prevent such a
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a Democrat, has said it was her desire to restore public
confidence in the Justice Department that led her in September to
name Danforth, a Republican, to conduct the independent inquiry
into the assault after the government's possible use of
pyrotechnics came to light.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's initial report found that the devices were used, but
cleared the government of any wrongdoing or cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary study, completed after 10 months and $12
million, left unanswered why federal agents concealed the use of
pyrotechnic devices. Danforth said he plans to answer that question
in his final report this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Danforth's investigation is incomplete, Reno said,
``There will come a time when it's appropriate for me to comment
and I think that Senator Danforth, since he has indicated he has
additional matters that he wants to pursue, should be able to
pursue them without comment from me.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
