<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-NAPSTER-SIDE0728-COX     07-27 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-SIDE0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Napster feeding frenzy
 &HT;    By Don Fernandez and Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pop music potluck is far from finished; the
party's just moving to another house.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites with alternative file-sharing software were gridlocked
Thursday as music lovers soon-to-be-evicted from Napster Inc.
sought fertile pastures where the downloads remain free.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary injunction issued Wednesday against Napster could
force the MP3 file-sharing giant to cease operations at 3 a.m.
Saturday. Anxious Napster clients converged on the company's
central servers for a final free-for-all mission to nab toll-free
music. Close to 1 million members on one of more than 100 Napster
servers were scouring each other's hard drives for tunes Thursday
afternoon, almost twice the normal traffic.
</P>
<P>
   And while the company appeals, it appears the phenomenon of
downloading free music won't stall, no matter what the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a million other sites out there,'' says Kelly Watts,
22, an employee at Tower Records in Atlanta who has more than 3,000
Napster song files on his home computer. ``If you try to stop it,
it's only going to encourage it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more popular sites heating up was iMesh based in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Downloads of the iMesh software _ which allow users to share
MP3s, JPEGs and other files in the same manner Napster does _
doubled from a daily average of 8,000 to 16,000 in just a few
hours, says Uri Rotshpein, iMesh vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In a mere 10 minutes Thursday, 160 new members were registered,
adding to the more than 1 million existing iMesh members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is we're very similar (to Napster),'' Rotshpein
says.
</P>
<P>
   Gnutella and Scour Exchange software also can hunt for songs as
well as video and image files. At Scour Exchange, more than 31,000
people had used Scour Exchange to share more than 2 million songs
by midday Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But GlobalSCAPE Inc., which manufactures CuteMX file-sharing
software, isn't eager to take in Napster's nomads. The company late
Thursday decided to embargo its software from being downloaded
until legal issues are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there may be 20 million people who need somewhere to
go, we don't necessarily want them here,'' said Sandra
Poole-Christal, president of San Antonio-based GlobalSCAPE Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Watts is among those who already has Gnutella file-sharing
software on his computer, and he prefers it in some ways to
Napster. It can search for everything from a video clip to a
recipe. ``Download time is quicker,'' he said, comparing Gnutella
to Napster. ``There's another site called webradio.com that will
probably do better than Napster because you don't have to download
any software.''
</P>
<P>
   He sheds no tears for Napster, noting the army of software
makers lining up to take its place. But Watts lamented the
shortsightedness of the music industry for failing to realize that
Napster and similar programs actually draw listeners turned on by
downloaded music into record stores to lay down cash for their
tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had a value; it informed the customers,'' he said. ``But
they're still going to be able to use other software. The record
companies need to work it out. If they produced quality albums, it
wouldn't be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Han, 21, of Atlanta, who has been a Napster member since
the software became available last year, also questioned the ruling
and the logic behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends are upset about it,'' she says. ``I
understand the record industry's case, but if they think people are
burning CDs, how can they prove that? Napster as a program doesn't
force the person to copy it. We listen to the radio and hear music
for free and can tape it. Is that different from Napster? Are you
going to ban radio?''
</P>
<P>
   Rapper Chuck D of the group Public Enemy had partnered with
Napster for a promotion on his website, www.rapstation.com, and
unabashedly celebrated the software's potential to promote new
musical acts. He says the ruling was a victory for record industry
executives, not artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am kind of salty about it,'' he says. ``The bigger issue at
hand is they can't stop file sharing. Thousands of start up
companies are going to do the same thing. It's funny how the power
is never in the people's hands, no matter what they say. Typical of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Napster's emergence hasn't necessarily hurt sales at music
stores. It's even spawned demand for the equipment needed to burn
MP3 files on recordable CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 50 percent of my customers use Napster and a lot could
care less,'' says John Montez, store manager of one of Atlanta's
Tower Records stores. He called the recordable CD format a growing
sales niche ``and it's not just because of Napster but because of
the technology. It's become the new blank tape.''
</P>
<P>
   And the evolution of such technology, and its use by consumers,
is among the bigger issues in the Napster fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect to the law, technology and the human
appetite for something free continues to stay ahead of the law,''
said Gary Arlen, a Bethesda, Md., Internet industry consultant.
``This might slow it down, but it's not going to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies _ including Napster _ aren't likely to let
the potential profits from that business pass them by because of
disagreements such as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this spells the death knell at all of music or
entertainment on the Internet,'' said Larry Waks, an Austin, Texas,
attorney who specializes in music and copyright issues. ``It's just
the age-old story about the law trying to keep up with
technological inventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Internet music companies have changed the way they
do business.
</P>
<P>
   After it was sued by the Recording Industry Association of
America earlier this year, San Diego-based MP3.com Inc. struck a
deal in which it gives record labels a small payment each time one
of its visitors downloads a piece of copyrighted music.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday's ruling likely will force the question of who
owns what on the Internet to the forefront, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inevitable that the legislators are going to get
involved,'' said MP3.com executive vice president Billy Pitts, just
hired by the company as its chief lobbyist in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Pitts and MP3.com _ named after the highly
compressed format that made music transmission over the Internet
viable at dial-up speeds _ are planning a nationwide drive to get
online music aficionados to contact their representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal is to get legislation or regulation on their terms
and to keep the battle out of the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts says he envisions an ``e-bill of rights'' that would
determine what is and isn't off-limits in sharing files over the
Internet, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet should not be ruled by a small cadre of
hand-picked judges who are trying to interpret what the law
means,'' Pitts says.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that one of the industry's biggest
challenges is explaining to Congress how online music works.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say MP3 on the Hill, they say, `Oh, it's down the hall
on the right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
