<SLUG> BC-STRIP-DEPOT0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strip club can't use Home Depot-like sign
 &HT;    By Marc Caputo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ One of them sells shovels and saws. The other
offers strippers who sell exotic dances.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to confuse the services of the Home Depot and Adult
Depot, and a federal magistrate judge has decided to keep it that
way.
</P>
<P>
   At Home Depot's urging, Judge Lurana Snow ruled that Adult Depot
should stop imitating the home-maintenance store's signs and
mascot. Home Depot sued the X-rated store for trademark
infringement in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to rip off Home Depot's reputation for their profit
and the court saw through that,'' said Steve Levy, lawyer for the
Atlanta-based company that claims $30 billion in sales last year.
The company will not be reimbursed attorney's fees.
</P>
<P>
   Adult Depot's lawyer, Bruce Loren, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the ruling late last month, the Adult Depot
agreed to change its signs at its Boynton Beach and suburban Lake
Worth locations. Both have orange signs with white, stenciled
lettering that look similar to Home Depot's.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said the Adult Depot submitted a new sign design to Home
Depot last week. The sex store, which sells adult movies and toys,
will get to keep its name but the signs will change by mid-August,
Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Adult Depot also must scrap its imitation of Home Depot's
tool-clad mascot, Homer. The Adult Depot's Homer look-alike had a
sex toy strapped to his side in an advertisement for a pornography
star's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But Adult Depot's problems aren't over.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County wants to remove the strip club from its
location on Lake Worth Road west of Congress Avenue, saying it's
too close to homes.
</P>
<P>
   Club owners Edward Schultz and Fernando Carmona have fought the
county to a standstill; the two sides are trying to settle the case
by agreeing on a new spot.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Levy is happy that Adult Depot looks a little
less like the home-care store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want any confusion between the two,'' Levy said.
``They're not the same type of business by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
