u p BC-GOP-PLATFORM-BOS &LR;      07-27 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PLATFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLATFORM FAVORS AMENDMENT TO BAN ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A draft of the Republican Party's convention
platform retains an endorsement of a constitutional amendment that
would ban abortion, but adds a new section on women's health and
deletes some of the strident attacks on Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed platform was released Thursday night and was not
immediately available to most delegates who will vote on it. But
the document will be the subject of hearings for the next two days,
with the most likely fight coming over abortion. Overall, the
document seeks to mirror the tone set by the nominee-in-waiting,
George W. Bush, whose campaign was greatly responsible for its
content.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said for months that the anti-abortion plank should be
retained, so that is no surprise. By any measure, the platform is a
mostly conservative document, but the party is clearly reaching out
to moderates on some issues and has a much more muted tone in many
areas. The platform drops a call for the elimination of the
Department of Education and it says Republicans support ``a strong
federal role in environmental protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The new tone is by design, according to Senator Bill Frist of
Tennessee, a co-chairman of the platform committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are upbeat, optimistic, enthusiastic,'' Frist said as the
draft was handed out to reporters. Thus, the platform deletes
direct attacks on the Democrats and inserts appeals to women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the plank on affirmative action in 1996 said, ``We
scorn Bill Clinton's notion that any person should be denied a job,
promotion, contract or a chance at higher education because of
their race or gender.'' In the new platform, the plank has been
renamed ``equal access'' and there is no mention of scorn. Still,
the GOP principle on the issue is unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   In the section called ``right to bear arms,'' the 1996 platform
referred to Clinton's actions on gun control as ``strange.'' The
new platform deletes such attacks and adds an acknowledgment of the
recent spread of violence in the schools. ``With a special emphasis
upon school safety, we propose the crackdown on youth violence,''
the platform says.
</P>
<P>
   The new section on women's health, while not likely to mollify
supporters of abortion rights, is clearly aimed at women voters.
``Republicans are at the forefront in aggressively developing
health care initiatives targeted specifically at the needs of
women...and we are reaching out to under-served and minority female
populations.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform is titled ``Renewing America's Prosperity.
Together.'' In recounting how the economy has turned around in the
last eight years, the platform says: ``That wasn't magic. It took
honest and guts from a Congress that manages the nation's purse
strings.'' Just as the platform deletes the attacks on Clinton, it
does not give the president, or Vice President Gore, any credit for
the economy, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5051 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-ART-N     07-27 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PLATFORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP DRAFT PLATFORM KEEPS HARD LINE ON ABORTION BUT SOFTENS EDGES
ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., N.C., Tenn.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The proposed Republican platform would drop
several of the more hard-edged conservative positions adopted four
years ago _ like calling for the abolition of the Department of
Education _ and transform much of the document's tone to reflect
the ``compassionate conservatism'' of Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But it also reflects the continuing power of the party's
conservative base, most notably in its word-by-word reaffirmation
of the abortion plank, calling for a ban on abortion with no
exceptions and the appointment of judges who ``respect traditional
family values and the sanctity of innocent human life.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft of the platform was written under the guidance of Gov.
Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, the platform committee chairman, and
was distributed to members of the platform committee gathering here
Thursday night. It will be reviewed _ possibly rewritten _ and
voted upon by the 107-member platform committee over the next two
days. The full convention will consider the resulting product on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said Thursday night that he hoped the draft reflected
``a more uplifting view of the Republican Party, one that's more
inclusive, that attempts to build a winning team, that people can
rally around.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was also intended to reflect the Bush philosophy,
adding that he took the chairman's job ``because my friend the
governor asked me to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much he expected the committee to change this draft,
Thompson said, ``I hope not much, but I know some.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Backus, spokeswoman for the Democratic National Committee,
said Thursday that Republicans were simply putting ``compassionate
conservative wrapping paper'' around the same old conservative
dogma. She argued that the platform's changes were ``around the
margins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the American people wanted one sign that the Republican
Party had moved out of the 19th century,'' Backus said, ``it would
have been some understanding that American women want the right to
choose protected.''
</P>
<P>
   As written, the document is in large part a road map of the Bush
campaign's political imperatives in the general election campaign.
The section on immigration, for example, no longer demands a
constitutional amendment to deny automatic citizenship to the
children born of illegal immigrants, as it did four years ago.
Rather than calling for ``the official recognition of English as
the nation's common language,'' it declares, ``Another sign of our
unity is the role of English as our common language.'' The tone, in
general, is far more welcoming, reflecting Republicans' attempts to
reach out to Hispanics and other immigrant groups.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the document includes a careful appeal to women,
pledging the party's commitment to women's health issues, and to
the elderly, considered a critical swing vote this year.
</P>
<P>
   It promises to give Medicare ``a new lease on life'' by giving
each of its 39 million beneficiaries a choice of health plans, an
allusion to efforts to get more private insurance plans involved.
And it accuses the Clinton administration of treating ``Social
Security as a slogan rather than a priority,'' while touting Bush's
proposal to allow people to invest a portion of their payroll
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all these appeals to voters in the center, this is
hardly a rebuttal of conservative orthodoxy. The platform
reiterates a defense of ``the constitutional right to keep and bear
arms'' and argues that ``self defense is a basic human right.'' The
answer to gun violence, it argues, is stronger enforcement of
existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   The platform assails the Supreme Court's recent decision
overturning state laws barring what critics call ``partial birth''
abortion, asserting that the decision ``shocks the conscience of
the nation.'' And while Bush has said he would allow abortions in
the case of rape, incest and to save the life of the woman, the
platform remains unswervingly opposed. Bush and other Republican
leaders had promised the anti-abortion movement early on that the
abortion plank would not change.
</P>
<P>
   Republican aides said the document was intended to sound a far
less partisan tone than the 1996 platform, which is in keeping with
the Bush campaign's effort to present its candidate as ``a uniter,
not a divider.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the references are opaque: In a section titled
``Government for the People,'' the draft is apparently referring to
the impeachment of Clinton when it declares, ``At a time when the
nation felt betrayed by misconduct in high office, the Republican
Congress responded with gravity and high purpose. We applaud those
members who did their duty to conscience and the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform goes to great lengths, though, to try to build a
case against giving the Democrats any credit for the current
economic boom. It argues that the economy was in ``shambles'' under
President Carter, was saved by the Reagan and Bush administrations,
and was jeopardized anew by the election of the Clinton
administration in 1992, although that election occurred in a
recession. Only the ``honesty and guts'' of a Republican Congress
managed to erase the budget deficit and steady the economy for this
boom, the platform draft declares.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when that Republican Congress was still in full
cry, the platform called for the elimination of the Departments of
Commerce, Housing and Urban Development, Education and Energy. This
draft generally calls for ``downsizing'' of the ``mess'' in
Washington, where there are ``too many departments and agencies
with competing programs that waste resources and fail to deliver
the goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said the draft was written by the staff of the
Republican National Committee, the Bush campaign and his own
operation, under his guidance and that of his two co-chairs, Rep.
Sue Myrick of North Carolina and Sen. Bill Frist of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most scathing criticism in the draft comes in the
section on foreign policy, when the administration is assailed for
mishandling crises from the Balkans to Mexico: ``Reacting belatedly
to inevitable crises, the administration constantly enlarges the
reach of its rhetoric _ most recently in Vice President [Al) Gore's
`new security agenda' that adds disease, climate, and all the
world's ethnic or religious conflicts to an undiminished set of
existing American responsibilities. If there is some limit to
candidate Gore's new agenda for America as global social worker, he
has yet to define it,'' the draft declares.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for America to regain its focus,'' it adds.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore, responded, ``Sounds like
the Republicans are turning back the clock to the days of
isolationism and a head-in-the-sand view of the world. It's only
common sense to address these problems before they develop into
conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform draft also takes aim at Gore's environmental
activism, arguing that a Republican president will reduce harmful
emissions without ``forcing Americans to walk to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
