<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-GRASSHOPPERS-AR     07-27 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GRASSHOPPERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO TEXAS FARMERS' BURDENS, ADD THE GRASSHOPPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT15 and NYT16 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Texas _ With grasshoppers pinging off the windshield
like hailstones, Marvin Schrank mows through row after row of ripe
milo maize, swarms of the insects rolling in waves of dust just
ahead of his John Deere combine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those yellow hoppers have finished with the leaves and gone on
to eating the seed,'' Schrank said. ``They're hurting me now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of Schrank's grain field, his brother Alan shakes
the branches of a native peach tree and sends dozens of
grasshoppers skittering into the blazing afternoon sun. He points
to a green peach eaten halfway through to the pit, saying, ``Look
here what they done.''
</P>
<P>
   For Texas farmers and ranchers like the Schrank brothers _ whose
family has worked the same fields near here since the 1890s _ a
growing season marked by falling commodities prices and relentless
drought has, in the last few months, added yet another burden: a
costly infestation of grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst I've seen in my 31 years of working in Texas,''
said Cliff Hoelscher, an entomologist with Texas A&AMP;M University's
Agricultural Extension Service.
</P>
<P>
   Several warm winters in a row, combined with drought conditions
in much of Texas for the last three years, have created nearly
perfect breeding conditions for the 15 to 20 species of
grasshoppers commonly found in the state, Hoelscher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a cold winter or a wet spring, the eggs all hatch, and
all of the young grasshoppers are able to mature,'' he said. ``The
bigger they are, the more they'll eat.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 63 of the 254 counties in Texas have been affected,
Hoelscher said. And reports of infestations have come to his office
from New Mexico, Louisiana, Arkansas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit, Hoelscher said, are farmers and ranchers raising
cattle food: leafy green vegetation like hay, grain sorghum and
coastal bermuda grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll move into an area and strip 15 to 20 percent of the
available forage away in no time at all,'' he said. ``That's 15 to
20 percent more feed that ranchers have to buy to make up the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Though insecticides can help rid an area of the grasshoppers,
Hoelscher said, many of the insects will escape and move to an
adjacent unsprayed field. A natural enemy of the grasshoppers, the
entomophagous fungus, would help control their numbers, but it only
thrives in wet weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wet weather is something we haven't seen a lot of in Texas for
the last few years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Knutson, also an entomologist and a member of Texas A&AMP;M's
Extension Service, estimated that 21 million acres of pasture and
hay fields have been affected by grasshoppers in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant presence of grasshoppers might be eight to 10
insects per square yard,'' Knutson said. ``But we're seeing
incidents of 30 to 40 grasshoppers per square yard in some fields.
And that's causing us real problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Rich, of the Oklahoma Farm Bureau, said his state was
also suffering from the invasion of grasshoppers, but had not yet
calculated the financial damage. ``Some losses will be
significant,'' he said. ``I just don't know the numbers yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arkansas, Glenn E. Studebaker, an entomologist with the
Cooperative Extension Service at Little Rock, said: ``I wouldn't
call it a plague of locusts. We have some problem with grasshoppers
in southern Arkansas: soybeans in particular and some rice and some
pastureland. It's heavier than usual, but nothing like Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Knutson said, losses for this year alone have already
totaled at least $190 million in lost crops and treatment costs.
</P>
<P>
   Those treatment costs include spraying insecticides on infested
fields. And in that war, the area around the Schrank brothers' farm
_ about 100 miles southwest of Dallas _ is ground zero, said Steve
Watson, who runs a family-owned farm and ranch supplies store in
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had places out there that had hundreds of grasshoppers
per square yard,'' he said. ``We watched them take one 60-acre
field of coastal Bermuda grass from 2 and a half feet high down to
4 inches almost overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson sells insecticides to area farmers and ranchers, and
conducts many of the spraying operations himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to order 10 times more insecticide than I normally
would, and we've been working daylight to dark, seven days a week,
putting the stuff out in the fields, since early spring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get rid of them,'' Watson said. ``All you can do is
slow them down and try to protect your most valuable crops first.''
</P>
<P>
   But even keeping pace with the grasshoppers can be expensive, he
said. It costs $8 to $10 an acre to treat infected fields, he said,
and for an average-sized farm near this community of 3,000, that
can quickly add up to $6,000 to $10,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to spray twice or more, and then here will
come another batch of new grasshoppers flying in from somewhere
else,'' he said. Malathion and liquid Sevin are Watson's weapons of
choice, and he says that in the last few months he has killed
``billions'' of grasshoppers. ``I think, finally, we're gaining on
them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly. But Shauna Melde, who lives across a dusty county road
from the Schrank brothers, says she has had so many grasshoppers
that her sister began packing them in 5-gallon containers and
freezing them for fishing bait.
</P>
<P>
   Melde said her husband had tried spraying insecticide several
times in the last few days, but apparently with little effect.
</P>
<P>
   As she watched dozens of grasshoppers dancing across the
tattered remains of her front yard, she said: ``Look at them. They
really just seem to be enjoying it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
