<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-TRIALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL SCHOOLS ALLY TO STREAMLINE CLINICAL DRUG TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvard University Medical School and four other top US medical
schools, worried that private industry is taking over too much of
human research on new medical treatments, have formed an alliance
promising drug companies faster approval and completion of critical
clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Medical drugs are an exploding business. Pharmaceutical
companies spend $300 million to $500 million to develop a new drug,
in the hope that they will be first to discover a medication and
start selling it. The business is expected to become even more
competitive as scientists develop gene-based drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Given this, speed in getting products to market is critical.
Drug companies have increasingly turned to for-profit clinical
research organizations, private doctors' offices, and small
community hospitals to recruit patients and run trials rather than
university medical centers, which have laborious approval
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph B. Martin, dean of the Harvard Medical School, said
officials at the five institutions believe that they can speed up
that process without jeopardizing the safety of the participants.
The federal agency that oversees human research has approved the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the five academic medical centers _
Harvard-affiliated Massachusetts General and Brigham and Women's
hospitals, Washington University School of Medicine, the University
of Pennsylvania, Vanderbilt University, and Baylor College of
Medicine _ will run certain clinical trials jointly. They will
designate one institution as the lead reviewer, and that school's
Institutional Review Board will conduct a comprehensive review of
patient safety and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The other institutions will conduct abbreviated reviews and will
have access to the full review. Normally, drug companies must seek
full reviews and approval from IRBs at all academic medical centers
involved in a national clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are increasingly competing with studies that are being done
in the private sector,'' said Dr. Daniel Schuster, associate dean
of clinical research at Washington University in St. Louis. ``The
drug companies outsource these trials to clinical research
organizations and they decide where they can get the job done
fastest. If they can get it done in a private doctor's office more
quickly, that's where they go.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a decade ago academic medical centers conducted 90 percent
of the clinical trials paid for by drug companies, compared to 40
percent today, Schuster said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard wins less than 1 percent of the $20 billion to $25
billion that drug companies award in research grants each year,
said Dr. James Breitmeyer, president of the Harvard Clinical
Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Harvard to be offering more cutting-edge medications
to Boston patients,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Breitmeyer said the ``trials are getting done more often in
small storefront doctors' offices and small community hospitals and
solo practice settings. There's less bureaucracy but there's also
less intellectual scientific oversight and input.''
</P>
<P>
   Academic medical centers certainly want to win more research
dollars for their institutions, some of which are struggling
financially, but they also consider research one of their primary
missions.
</P>
<P>
   The five institutions plan to launch the project at Washington
University Sept. 15, when they will invite drug company executives
to meet medical school officials.
</P>
<P>
   Schuster said this is the first time the National Institutes of
Health has allowed such a relationship between academic
institutions in different regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
   He said that large private IRBs approve clinical trials within a
week, while academic medical centers typically require four to
eight weeks. While the centers involved in the partnership, called
the Multicenter Academic Clinical Research Organization, have tried
to reduce approval time to two to four weeks, Schuster does not
anticipate one-week turnarounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that unsettling,'' he said. ``It's almost like a rubber
stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan S. Bachenheimer, chief executive of BBK Patient Recruitment
in Newton, said that the medical centers ``are doing a very smart
thing'' but that speed is not the only factor for drug companies
choosing where to conduct a clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Location, she said, depends on where the patients go. If a drug
company is testing a new cold medication, those patients will
probably be found in doctors' offices, not university hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a research revolution,'' she said. ``This is a huge
industry and it's looking for efficiencies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
