<SLUG> BC-JAKES-RALLY0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evangelist taps financial, spiritual power
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few preachers can transform a talk on credit card debt
and mutual funds into a tent-revival-like sermon that leaves
thousands of women shouting in joy and waving their arms in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what Bishop T.D. Jakes did Thursday at the
Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' address marked the official opening of his three-day,
``Woman, Thou Art Loosed!'' conference, two different programs that
attracted tens of thousands of women to downtown Atlanta Thursday.
Thousands more _ perhaps a quarter-million people in all _ from
across Georgia and as far away as the Congo, Japan and Mexico are
expected to attend sessions today and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Jakes spoke about economic empowerment in the morning
and spiritual empowerment during an evening sermon at the Georgia
Dome. Yet for Jakes, who comes from a family of entrepreneurs, both
themes are intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   God, Jakes thinks, wants women to be loosed economically as well
as spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virtuous woman in the Bible wasn't an Aunt Bee who baked
biscuits and waited for Andy to come home,'' Jakes said. ``She was
an entrepreneur and a landowner.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the third year that Jakes, pastor of a mega-church in
Dallas, the Potters House, has held a conference in Atlanta. But
this year he comes with a twist in his offerings, a ``Woman, Thou
Art Loosed Plus'' conference that focuses on economics.
</P>
<P>
   As he did last year, Jakes also used his time here this week to
premiere a new play. Called ``Behind Closed Doors,'' the musical
drama explores issues of breast cancer and marital infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a point where I had to calm myself down because I
felt like I was in a church service, not a play,'' said Dawn Baah,
35, who traveled from London to hear Jakes and see the premiere of
his play Tuesday night. ``I left the place a changed woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes wants more women to become changed as business people as
well. He said too many church members possess spiritual principles
but little business sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I asked how many women in this room purchased a new outfit
within the last 30 days, hands would shoot up,'' Jakes said
Thursday during a morning session of his ``Plus'' conference at the
World Congress Center. ``But if I asked how many had a CD
(certificate of deposit) or a mutual fund, the numbers would
decline significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Many women, judging by the cheers, approve of Jakes emphasis on
economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spiritual part is fine but past that, life is life,'' said
Debra Zeilgler-Johnson, 44, from Kansas City, Mo. ``I gotta pay my
bills. I'm at a point where I need someone to take me to the next
level to show me what I need . . . He's there spiritually and
financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes is a savvy businessman who has used the popularity of his
message to create a cottage industry that includes the ``Woman Thou
Art Loosed'' revival, a best-selling book of the same name, a
special-edition Bible and a CD, ``Sacred Love Songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he still remembers the days when he and his wife, Serita,
had their utility bills cut off for lack of funds and his struggle
to get his first book published. He had to empty his savings
account to self-publish the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I have gone from welfare to Godfare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the center of Jakes' message remains his appeal to women's
hearts, not their purse strings. During his week-long visit to
Atlanta, Jakes bounced from radio and television appearances,
greeted by crowds of woman who say he has changed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Darleen Crockett, 40, waited three hours at a bookstore in
Underground Atlanta Tuesday for Jakes to sign his book. She was
deeply moved when the pastor waited for his wife in front of the
store, paused and then applauded as she entered building where fans
were waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love how he loves his wife,'' Crockett said. ``Every woman
wants a man to love her like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, at times, sounds mystified that he has become so popular.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of his popularity can trace its roots to a study
group he held at his Texas church where he discussed such issues as
incest and rape. Within a couple of months, hundreds of women were
attending the weekly sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the bleeding hearts of so many people in the pews
and outside the church doors, I felt like a paramedic,'' Jakes
said. ``It was important that I get there at the scene of the
crime. I took the risk. I was greatly relieved that they ran to me
and n
</P>
</TEXT>
