<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5064 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DORISMOND-SHOOTING     07-27 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DORISMOND-SHOOTING-ART-365(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY CLEARS DETECTIVE IN KILLING OF UNARMED OUTSIDE BAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo 14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A grand jury has declined to file criminal charges
against the undercover narcotics detective who fatally shot Patrick
M. Dorismond, an unarmed security guard, during a desperate,
two-minute brawl in March in front of a midtown Manhattan bar,
prosecutors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, said the
grand jury decided not to indict the detective, Anthony Vasquez,
after concluding that the shooting _ a single bullet fired from a
9-mm pistol, at a range so close that the barrel was touching
Dorismond's clothing _ was not intentional.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors also heard evidence that Dorismond had thrown the
first punch as a dispute with three detectives escalated into
disorder, and that Dorismond had seized and was twisting Vasquez's
shooting hand when the gun fired, Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, the son of Haitian immigrants and the father of two
young daughters, was the fourth unarmed black man to die at the
hands of police during a 13-month period. His death created a
public uproar and became an issue in the race for the U.S. Senate
before Mayor Rudolph Giuliani bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   It came just weeks after the acquittal of officers who had
killed another unarmed black man, Amadou Diallo, and Giuliani, who
called Dorismond no ``altar boy'' even as the investigation was
just starting, was widely criticized for allowing police officials
to release the dead man's juvenile criminal record and for failing
to meet with his family. The controversy intensified after
protesters clashed violently with police at Dorismond's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The case also brought scrutiny on the public risks inherent in
police buy-and-bust operations, in which teams of undercover
detectives randomly approach people on the street and try to buy
illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, 26, was not a drug dealer. He had completed a shift
as a 34th Street Partnership security guard an hour and a half
before he died. To police critics and to Dorismond's family, his
death was a symbol of a department whose aggressive tactics and
appetite for ever-climbing arrest statistics led detectives to draw
a young man into a scuffle that led to his killing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Morgenthau's office exercises considerable control over the
grand jury process, including the evidence heard and the charges
considered, and he acknowledged the political tension surrounding
the case Thursday. But the district attorney said the jurors had
acted conscientiously and fairly after reviewing 42 exhibits and
hearing from 24 witnesses, including Vasquez, during a four-week
session.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the public to accept its decision. ``Some people may be
disappointed that this investigation has not resulted in an
indictment,'' he said. ``I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added: ``The grand jury is not a forum for the
expression of political views or the resolution of policy disputes.
To allow it to be used for those purposes would simply layer an
injustice upon a tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, 30, could not be reached for comment Thursday night.
His lawyer, Philip Karasyk, issued a brief statement and then said
that Vasquez felt as if ``a tremendous weight has been lifted from
his and his family's shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no joy in this decision,'' he said. ``Only relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond's mother, Marie Rose Dorismond, and his father, Andre
Dorismond, assailed the grand jury's decision Thursday at an angry
news conference with the Rev. Al Sharpton. Alternately sobbing and
shouting, his mother called on God and President Clinton for help
and suggested the shooting had racist overtones. The three
detectives involved in the drug sting were Hispanic. Dorismond was
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help me, God,'' she said. ``Why did you create me black? Look
at me, I'm suffering now.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Thursday that Morgenthau's summary of the
investigation suggested that the police had acted almost without
fault. ``It is pretty hard to read this report and find something
to criticize the police officers for,'' he said. ``I think they
were acting under a very, very difficult set of circumstances. I
think it is clear from the report, and the report says quite
clearly, that the aggressor was Dorismond.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, speaking in a calm, almost restrained voice, offered
condolences to the Dorismond family and later said the shooting was
a tragedy for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great sympathy for his family,'' he said. ``But I also
have great sympathy for the police officers who were put through
what is a horrible experience, in which their jobs, their
liberties, their careers were put in jeopardy and they will
continue to be under question and review for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau's remarks Thursday, and a summary of the case for
Police Commissioner Howard Safir that prosecutors released to news
organizations, provided the most vivid picture to date of the
events that occurred shortly after midnight on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prosecutors' report, the commander of the
Midtown South Precinct had requested the help of narcotics
detectives after reviewing mounting evidence that the Bloods gang
was selling crack cocaine on Eighth Avenue between West 34th and
West 43rd Streets. And so for two nights, a team _ consisting of
Detectives Vasquez, Anderson Moran, and Julio Cruz _ was assigned
to the area. Moran posed as a drug buyer. His two peers served as
``ghosts,'' or backups.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after midnight on March 16, Morgenthau said, Moran saw
Dorismond and a companion, Kevin Kaiser, standing in front of the
Wakamba Cocktail Lounge at 543 Eighth Ave. (Kaiser has said that
Dorismond was waiting for a taxi.) With his ghosts watching, the
detective approached Dorismond and asked him if he had any
``krills,'' street slang for crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter immediately turned hostile. Morgenthau said
witnesses testified that Dorismond argued with Moran, using foul
language, and advanced on him as the detective backed away. The
other two detectives came to Moran's side, Morgenthau said, and the
three men began to walk backward as Dorismond continued to approach
and his friend, Kaiser, tried to restrain him.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau described a flash point: Dorismond broke free from
his friend and punched Moran, he said, and the dispute descended
into chaos. ``Everyone was swinging fists, pushing and grabbing at
each other in a general melee or brawl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said Vasquez told investigators that he heard either
Dorismond or Kaiser yell ``gun'' or ``get the gun,'' and, believing
that the brawl was about turn into a gunfight, the detective yelled
``police,'' stepped forward and reached into his pants to withdraw
a concealed pistol.
</P>
<P>
   As he did so, Morgenthau said, Dorismond grabbed the detective's
right hand and the weapon and began twisting. The gun fired,
blasting a bullet into the left side of Dorismond's chest,
perforating his aorta and killing him within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, Morgenthau said, ``did not intentionally pull the
trigger, and in fact does not know how the discharge came about.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Thursday's announcement means that Vasquez will not
face state criminal charges, the examination of the shooting is not
over, and he remains on modified duty, without a weapon, performing
police clerical work. Patrick E. Kelleher, the Police Department's
first deputy commissioner, said internal affairs officers would
review the evidence to see if he should face administrative
charges. Federal prosecutors in Manhattan are also investigating
the case for possible violations of federal criminal civil rights
laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
