<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5068 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GATES-TB-FUND-BOS &LR;      07-27 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-TB-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES FOUNDATION GIVES $44.7B TO FIGHT TB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft founder Bill Gates's philanthropic foundation has
decided to make the largest private donation ever for fighting the
spread of tuberculosis, awarding a $44.7 million grant to a group
of Harvard doctors and medical scholars guided by a vision of
social justice to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year grant, to be announced formally in the next few
days, will go to Harvard Medical School's program in infectious
disease and social change. The program, an outgrowth of the
nonprofit Partners in Health group, will use the money to treat
drug-resistant TB in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The effort will mark the first time any organization has tried
to eliminate the mutating strains of the deadly disease in an
entire Third World country.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a time when health specialists and Western
governments, most notably the Clinton administration, have grown
increasingly concerned that sicknesses of the developing world are
spreading to the most privileged because of a huge jump in global
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world now has to figure out whether it can contain
outbreaks of multiple drug-resistant TB,'' said Bill Foege, a
senior adviser to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Foege said the foundation was impressed by the work of Partners
in Health and its founding doctors, Paul Farmer and Jim Kim, on
controlling drug-resistant TB in Peru. Foege said the hope is that
the ``new demonstration project can then be taken to its logical
conclusion and expanded to other countries around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates, who attended Harvard for only one year before dropping
out, has earmarked $1.9 billion for global health projects in the
last two years. The foundation hopes to spend about $550 million a
year on international health.
</P>
<P>
   For Partners in Health, which began in a tiny Cambridge, Mass.
office 13 years ago, the Gates's largesse will broaden their
influence among global health policy makers. The group has long
been led by Farmer, Kim and Boston philanthropist Thomas J. White.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous step forward for us,'' said White, 80, who
has spent $3 million in recent years on fewer than 200
drug-resistant TB patients in Peru to prove that they _ and others
in poor countries _ could be cured. ``To go from $3 million to $45
million is pretty good. But what's really great is it means life
instead of death for a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Partners in Health's mantra has been called an
``option-for-the-poor health care,'' an approach that addresses a
breadth of problems for the needy. The organization, which employs
more than 300 people, plans to continue current programs in Haiti,
the Chiapas region of Mexico and Roxbury on the theory that the
Gates money will cover costs for the Peru program.
</P>
<P>
   In Haiti, if it secures additional funding, Partners in Health
hopes to expand in areas of women's health, water protection,
surgical services, and pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of controlling tuberculosis will clearly take up
more of its focus now.
</P>
<P>
   TB, which kills more people than any other infectious disease,
is a bacterium with wings, spread by a sneeze or a cough. The bug
develops resistance to the most common anti-TB drugs when a person
takes only part of antibiotic regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Multidrug-resistant TB, or MDR-TB, has multiplied in recent
years, including in the former Soviet states, where prisons have
become breeding grounds for the disease due to lack of funds for TB
treatment. In Russia's prisons, 25 percent of all inmates have
drug-resistant TB. And 30 percent of all Russian prisoners,
including those with TB, are released every year.
</P>
<P>
   As in other countries, a chief worry in Russia is the meeting
ground of HIV/AIDS and drug-resistant TB, a cocktail that spikes
the death rate exponentially when a person's depleted immune system
cannot fight the aggressive TB bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get MDR-TB under control now, it will simply
continue to grow,'' said Kim, the grant's author and principal
investigator. ``Once HIV and MDR-TB meet each other in other areas,
as it has been in South Africa and other places, we are going to
have a problem of TB that will be unmanageable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peru program's goal is to treat every drug-resistant TB
patient. Partners in Health's sister organization in Peru, Socios
En Salud, will be the main executing arm of the grant. It will
train hundreds of local health workers on proper diagnosis and
administration of the TB drugs. It is a complex task, involving up
to two years of taking the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard doctors also will explore two separate avenues of
treatment in Peru with an eye toward exporting the program to other
nations: developing state-of-the-art therapies to diagnose the
resistance almost overnight; and exploring less technical ways of
treating the disease by learning more about how resistance
develops.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Farmer and Kim decided to investigate drug-resistant TB
in Peru after one of their relief workers returned from there with
the bug and died. The group found an outbreak in the northern Lima
slum of Carabayllo and began to treat the sick.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year later, the World Health Organization said in a
publication: ``In developing countries, people with
multidrug-resistant TB usually die, because effective treatment is
often impossible in poor settings.''
</P>
<P>
   Partners proved it was possible in Carabayllo, thanks to White's
pocketbook: He gave about $12,000 a patient per year, an almost
unheard of sum for treatment of the poor in the developing world.
Since then, due largely to the program's success, the price of
treating such patients has fallen dramatically, to $400 to $4,000
per patient, depending on the mix of antibiotics. Overall, such
medicines have fallen by 90 percent in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said he hoped that the new Peru program, which will also
include the WHO and the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention as subcontractors, an arrangement that was perhaps
unthinkable not so long ago. The Task Force for Child Survival and
Development of Atlanta will coordinate the coalition and develop a
global strategy to fight drug-resistant TB.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the treatment of MDR-TB much more
straightforward and standardized around the world,'' he said. ``In
the process, we will bring down the price of drugs, bring down the
price of diagnostics. . . . So instead of waiting two months for a
culture result to come back, which is way too much time, we hope to
utilize new technology to give us the answers in a day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he said, ``the place to do this kind of research and
operation is a place where there are TB patients, a lot of TB
patients. We think Peru will be a good place to test new drugs, new
diagnostics and show under pressure, in a real live clinic, that we
can treat these patients.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
