<HEADER>
A5071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-GYM-MEN0728-COX     07-27 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYM-MEN0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veterans holding their own
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Blaine Wilson's pep talk to Jason Gatson was meant
to comfort his training partner, but it actually underscored the
pressure facing gymnasts at the U.S. Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is in first place, Gatson 19th entering tonight's finals.
Only the top 14 will advance to the Olympic trials in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it's not over,'' said Wilson, who has a commanding
1.2-point lead over Sean Townsend. ``We still have six more events.
With people falling left and right, all he has to do is be in the
top 14. And a lot of these guys haven't seen a trials like Boston.
I'm sure there's going to be a lot more missed routines there.''
</P>
<P>
   The four gymnasts with the top combined scores from here (40
percent) and Boston (60 percent) will make the Olympic team, plus
two others selected by coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Gatson was leading at nationals last year when he blew out his
knee on his high-bar dismount.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle he's here,'' said his coach Ron Brant, who
coaches at the U.S. Olympic Training Center in Colorado Springs.
``He was at the top and now has to fight back. It's tough in an
Olympic year.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Thornton of Augusta is in 13th place, and trying not only to
hang on, but to improve his position. Thornton had a tough time on
his first event, parallel bars, but regrouped. In 1996, he barely
advanced to the Olympic trials, then performed well and placed
ninth. Thornton was so encouraged that he stuck around four more
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to keep improving,'' said Thornton, who also
trains with Wilson and Gatson. ``I'll use this to motivate me and
keep plugging away.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, a 1996 Olympian, said he felt a little tired, ``But I
wasn't overly tired. I got to the point where I got so relaxed that
I let a couple of things go, which I shouldn't have.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely don't want to give away tenths of points.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1999 World Championships, Wilson finished one-thousandth
of a point out of third place in the all-around.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, he watched the scoreboard and knew that
two-time Olympian John Roethlisberger was only .4 behind after
three events.
</P>
<P>
   But Roethlisberger, who at age 30 would be one of the oldest
male gymnasts ever to compete for the U.S. team at the Olympics,
fell twice on floor exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointed? That's the understatement of the night,'' said
Roethlisberger, who is fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
