<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PENTAGON-CONVENTION-N     07-27 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PENTAGON, GOP CONVENTION IS CHANCE TO PUT ON A SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a policy prohibiting military involvement
in partisan politics, members of Congress and guests at the
Republican National Convention will have an exclusive viewing of
some of the Pentagon's latest hardware, including an aircraft that
the expected Republican vice-presidential nominee, Dick Cheney,
tried to kill when he was defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing what a spokesman on Thursday called ``a convenient
opportunity'' to display some of its latest equipment, the Pentagon
asked the armed services to ship _ at taxpayer expense _ weapons
and other equipment to the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard for
what amounts to a three-day military trade show, beginning
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, the only Republican in
President Clinton's Cabinet, approved the display after receiving a
written request earlier this month from Rep. Curt Weldon, a
Republican from suburban Philadelphia and senior member of the
House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen did so, officials said, only after the Pentagon was
assured that the hardware _ and more than 150 service members
accompanying it _ would not be used for any political activities.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the point, the assistant secretary of defense for
legislative affairs, John K. Veroneau, sent Weldon a letter
outlining certain conditions: in short, no photo opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the display will be a centerpiece of a series of events
organized by Weldon for about 100 Republican colleagues and their
families, who will be staying in old Navy billets at the shipyard
during the convention at the First Union Center, less than a mile
away. Included in the festivities, closed to the public, will be a
``block party'' fund-raiser by Weldon on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is awkward,'' said Charles Lewis, executive
director of the Center for Public Integrity, a nonprofit group in
Washington. ``All this sexy, multibillion-dollar hardware there to
impress delegates is very smarmy and probably inappropriate. If
there isn't a rule against this, it seems to me there ought to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's role has even raised hackles among some military
officers, who complained that, at best, it blurs the definition of
what constitutes political activity. ``To say this is not a
partisan event is borderline absurd,'' one officer said.
</P>
<P>
   Others at the Pentagon complained that the cost would have to
come out of their own budgets, at a time they face spot shortages
of money for readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those misgivings, some of the services now appear to
regard the display as a chance to do a little lobbying of their
own. ``There's not a lot of enthusiasm for this,'' another official
said, ``but if they're ordered to do it, they want to look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the aircraft to be displayed is the V-22 Osprey, which has
crashed three times in the past decade. It is a hybrid with rotors
that swivel so it can take off like a helicopter but cruise like a
turboprop commuter plane. The Osprey has been beset by controversy
over cost and mission as well as safety, and Cheney waged a long
and unsuccessful battle against it when he was in the Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the V-22, the Marines are sending an amphibious
vehicle and equipment for its chemical- and biological-attack
response teams. The Air Force plans to include an unmanned
surveillance aircraft, the Predator, as well as missiles and bombs
and story boards promoting its newest fighter, the F-22.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, not to be outdone, has mobilized a virtual armory of
equipment, including an Apache attack helicopter, its own unmanned
aircraft and its troubled theater missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania National Guard is contributing an M1-A1 tank,
an armored personnel carrier and two more helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Navy is sending only an aging Sea Sprite
helicopter from a nearby reserve unit, two surveillance vehicles
and a small riverine boat.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said Thursday that it was too soon to put a
cost on moving all the equipment to Philadelphia, though the Air
Force estimated that its share would be at least $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, spent much of a news
conference Thursday defending the display. Bacon said that the
events at the shipyard were an opportunity to provide what amounted
to a briefing to lawmakers _ without mentioning lobbyists and other
influential Republicans who might happen by _ but maintained that
the display was not itself partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that's contemporaneous with the Republican
National Convention,'' he said. ``It's not adjacent _ it's not
right on the grounds where the convention is being held. It's
nearby, but not on the grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also noted that Rep. Robert A. Brady, a Democrat whose
district includes the shipyard, supported the request, though he
did not sign Weldon's request to Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon's spokesman, Pete Peterson, said the congressman saw the
shipyard, which is in the process of being closed and turned over
for private development, as a convenient and secure location for
his colleagues during the convention. Weldon, he said, was also
eager to promote the shipyard's activities.
</P>
<P>
   So is Richard A. Goldbach, the chairman and chief executive of
Metro Machines, one of the largest military contractors at the
shipyard. His company is erecting a tent to highlight its work,
which includes ship rebuilding and demolition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pure and simple a promotion,'' Goldbach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS &LR;      07-27 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP, CITY OF PHILADELPHIA SEE DIFFERENT GOALS AT COMMON EVENT --
REPUBLICAN CONVENTION &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ With presidential running mates inspired by the
wide open spaces of the West, the Republican Party polished themes
for its national convention Thursday in a city that hopes to bury
its image as a tattered victim of urban decay in the North.
</P>
<P>
   Unionized electricians, who plug Democrats in every political
argument, plugged in equipment at the convention site while wearing
savvy T-shirts. ``Republican . . . for a week,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP put some of the final touches on the schedule for its
four-day convention, which starts Monday and features the
nomination of Texas Gov. George W. Bush to succeed President
Clinton. For instance, party officials said retired Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf, the Persian Gulf War commander, will speak to the
convention Tuesday via a video signal from the decks of the
battleship USS New Jersey on the Delaware River nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The 1991 war, in which troops from the United States and other
nations expelled the Iraqi army from Kuwait, is emerging as a
sub-theme of the convention. Wednesday, when voting by delegates is
expected to award Bush the presidential nomination, is the 10th
anniversary of Iraq's invasion of its neighbor nation.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, introduced this week as Bush's running mate, ran
the Pentagon as defense secretary during the Persian Gulf War,
which started six months after the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell, who was between Cheney and
Schwarzkopf in the military heirarchy as chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, will also address the convention.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texas governor's father, President Bush, reached the
height of his political popularity when he prosecuted the war
against Iraqi President Saddam Hussein. The former president will
be honored Tuesday as one of the Republican Party's three living
past presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush's campaign staff has prevailed on the party to
make the convention high-minded by muting the traditional insults
against Democrats, officials announced a convention feature that
will cast some sidelight onto Republican efforts to defeat Hillary
Rodham Clinton in New York's U.S. Senate election:
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Card, convention co-chairman and former secretary of
transportation, said Monday's emphasis on education issues will
include a speech by New York congressional candidate Joan Johnson.
She is seeking the seat being vacated by U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, who
is running for Senate against the first lady. If elected, Johnson
would be the first Republican black woman in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney have talked about soaking up their conservatism
from the frontier culture of their childhood home towns. Bush, born
in Connecticut, lived in Midland, Texas, until he became a
teen-ager and moved to Houston. Nebraska-born Cheney grew up in
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   They will be adored and sent into political battle from a
convention in a contrasting environment _ Comcast-Spectacor First
Union Center, a sports arena in South Philly.
</P>
<P>
   In a city known for ethnic diversity, blue-collar living and
Democratic loyalty, South Philly is known as the zone for
Italian-American traditions and cheese-steak sandwiches _
delicacies that pack enough cholesterol to probably send Cheney, a
survivor of three heart attacks, running the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, known as the City of Brotherly Love, now calls
itself ``the city that loves you back.'' The metropolis, slightly
smaller than Houston in population, wants the convention glow to
obscure national images of its slums, formerly high unemployment
rate and infamous clashes between citizens and police. So cheery
greeters and promotional literature told GOP visitors and others
Thursday about the city's cultural amenities, the financial
rejuvenation of its downtown sector and the growth of its hotel
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Around the convention hall Thursday, however, the most often
heard phrase from local workers was a simple regionalism: ``Yo.''
</P>
<P>
   As delegates started streaming in for preliminary meetings and
receptions, downtown Philadelphia sported bunting, special lighting
and promotional signs Thursday. Workers applied fresh paint and
made repairs at the subway stop closes to the convention site,
which serves as a basketball and hockey arena.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolic of the city's effort to put on a fetching face, workers
atop a crane placed new letters spelling out First Union Center on
the side of the building Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the convention hall, the name of Comcast, a
communications and cable TV company that manages the arena, loomed
large. ``Welcome to Comcast Country,'' said a sign over the
convention podium. And QVC, the shopping channel owned by Comcast,
was setting up a mobile studio from which to hawk convention
souvenirs on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The podium, still under construction Thursday, features three
video screens framed by a mixture of curved, dark and light woods _
a clash of modern media and a retro, Ethan Allen furniture look.
While some workers projected a color test pattern onto the video
screens, others hoisted nets full of balloons up to the ceiling for
use in the convention-closing celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The arena will accommodate the 4,150 GOP delegates and
alternates, hundreds of VIPs and volunteers and some of the 15,000
news media personnel on hand.
</P>
<P>
   An extensive round of receptions and parties is on tap at many
sites throughout the city. Dick Clark, who started his American
Bandstand TV show here, will provide the entertainment at two
parties. Frankie Avalon, Chubby Checker and Bobby Rydell, native
Philadelphians all, will sing.
</P>
<P>
   Getting down to official business Thursday, the Republican
National Committee _ similar to a board of directors _ voted to
overhaul the way the GOP presidential nominee is picked starting in
2004. But the plan must be adopted by the party Rules Committee and
then a majority of delegates before it can take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The commitee endorsed a plan to junk the chock-a-block schedule
of primaries that Bush endured in the spring and substitute an
orderly schedule in which small states vote in a group and large
states vote last. The proposal, known as the Delaware Plan, might
undercut New Hampshire's traditional first-in-the-land primary.
Bush has not endorsed it.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have scheduled myriad events, including marches,
rallies and a display at the Liberty Bell of thousands of shoes _ a
silent demonstration against gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the faction groups _ from gun safety advocates, and
abortion rights supporters to welfare and health cause supporters _
have formed into one coalition called the R2K Network.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers were setting up shop, bringing in food and water and
helping the 10,000 expected each day to find places to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the group are from the same organizations that virtually
shut down Seattle during the World Trade Organization talks last
year. But most of their literature promotes nonviolent disruptions
and one spokesman said all the groups have talked since Seattle and
have promised no property destruction. But R2K member David Levy
said it doesn't mean that some demonstrators won't stray.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia police commissioner John Timoney reassured his
citizens and the rest of the nation Thursday that his department
was ready to handle whatever happened, adding he has been working
with all the groups to try to ensure peace.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney has continued to deny his officers will use tear gas
unless there is an extreme situation and then only if he or two
deputy commissioners give the OK first. His officers will carry
pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said no peaceful disruptions _ such as human blockades _
will automatically be doused with pepper spray, nor will arrests be
automatic for protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffice it to say that when they (the officers) do react it
will be under the supervision of a sergeant, lieutenant or a
captain and then only in a team fashion,'' Timoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter Lisa Teachey contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY XXX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
