<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GASTRUCK-ACCIDENT0728     07-27 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASTRUCK-ACCIDENT0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fiery crash kills 1, shuts Florida Turnpike
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A gasoline tanker driver who authorities say
may have dozed at the wheel Thursday morning crashed the truck,
then tried to crawl out but got only a few feet before he was
engulfed in 2,000-degree flames.
</P>
<P>
   The tanker, containing 8,900 gallons of gasoline, burned for
more than two hours, shutting down Florida's Turnpike west of Boca
Raton at the heart of rush hour and delaying or rerouting tens of
thousands of drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Wayne Baynard, 39, of suburban Fort Lauderdale, who'd
been delivering gasoline since about 1 a.m. Thursday, was killed
about 6:20 a.m., the Florida Highway Patrol said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing the best we can under the circumstances,''
Baynard's wife, Elaine, said Thursday evening from her home.
Baynard had two daughters, 22 and 15, a son, 13, and a 4-year-old
grandson, his wife said. She said the danger of hauling gasoline
was often on her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like it, but he felt comfortable with his job,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the how the accident occurred, according to a Highway
Patrol report and FHP Lt. Sammie Thomas:
</P>
<P>
   Baynard was northbound on the turnpike when his Kenan Transport
truck drifted into the left lane, then veered sharply into the
right lane. The 2000 Mack truck struck the left rear panel of a
white 2000 Dodge pickup parked on the right shoulder. Alan Keith
Fox, 38, of Coral Springs had just climbed back into the truck
after fixing a flat tire.
</P>
<P>
   The pickup, its rear smashed, flew through the air, landing
about 20 feet away, while Baynard's tanker slid over on its side
and across the shoulder, coming to rest against two trees.
</P>
<P>
   Baynard's body was found about five feet from the cab; Thomas
said authorities surmise he survived the crash and tried to crawl
away, only to be consumed by the fireball.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tallon, an operations manager for the Tru-Green land-care
firm, came across the wreck seconds later. He pulled his 2000 Ford
pickup between the two vehicles and ran to the tanker. He heard the
engine racing and tried to find the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' he said, ``the thing just ignited. It sparked from
under the cab first. As soon as I saw the spark, I had to run
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallon, 51, said he was less than 10 feet away when he heard ``a
couple of small pops. There was fuel all over the ground. In a
couple of minutes, it was in flames.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Tallon's truck; the fire melted its front.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was eerily familiar for Tallon; several years ago
the exact same thing happened to him in Ohio. There he also was
unable to save the driver from a fiery death.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel kind of helpless,'' he said. ``You try to help
somebody. But when I saw the fire, I was alarmed for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   About 27 Palm Beach County firefighters and a dozen of their
vehicles were on the scene in minutes, but were driven back by the
flames, estimated at 2,000 degrees at their heart and 200 degrees
even 100 yards away. District chief Richard Lounsbury said
firefighters decided to let the fire burn, because it couldn't do
much more damage than it already had, and putting it out might just
make it spark up again unexpectedly. Also, firefighters believed
burning off the gasoline would do less environmental damage than
extinguishing the fire and letting the unburned gas soak into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Florida Department of Environmental Protection
came to the scene to test the ground. Firefighters also worried
about a natural gas line directly under the tanker, but said it was
three feet underground and well insulated and they decided it was
not in peril.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was finally doused about 8:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 a.m., firefighters were still spraying foam on the
smoldering wreck. The tanker, valued by the highway patrol at
$70,000, lay in two pieces between the two now-scorched trees.
</P>
<P>
   Baynard had been a trucker for 10 years and worked for Kenan
Transport for six years, his wife said. She said his assignment was
to deliver gasoline to individual service stations starting about 1
a.m. By 6 a.m. he would have delivered his third or fourth load,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Transportation records show Baynard has not
been involved in any accidents during the past year and his
employer has a good overall safety record, DOT Lt. Kenny Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
