<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JULY 28 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday, July 28. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT (Moved on Friday, July 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Friday,
July 14, about potential running mates for Vice President Al Gore
misstated the middle initial of Warren Christopher, who is leading
the search. It is M., not G.
</P>
<P>
   BC-UNIPHASE-EARNINGS-NYT (Moved on Wednesday, July 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on
Wednesday, July 26, about the quarterly financial performance of
the JDS Uniphase Corporation misspelled the name of its chief
executive. He is Jozef Straus, not Joseph Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-FARMING-NYT (Moved on Wednesday, July 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on
Wednesday, July 12, about technological advances in farming
misstated the altitude of Landsat satellites used to provide images
of fields for monitoring crop growth. They are 437 miles above the
earth, not 20,000 feet. The article also misstated the resolution
of the images. Each pixel represents roughly 1,000 square yards,
not 5 to 10 square yards.
</P>
