<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY ZIP SHOWS HE ISN'T CHEAP ON SPEED
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y., _ Before they even lined up for the 87th
running of the Sanford Stakes, Linda Rice was spotting D. Wayne
Lukas $1,941,000 and 13 years in experience. The colt she trains,
City Zip, was purchased for $9,000 last year as a yearling. His
colt, Yonaguska, was picked up for $1.9 million seven months ago as
a 2-year-old. Rice had a handful of important stakes races on her
resume; he had 13 Triple Crown victories and 20 national champions
on his.
</P>
<P>
   But it took only 1:10 3/5 of horse racing _ the time City Zip
clocked to win his second stakes race _ for Rice to show that
inexpensive does not mean slow and that inexperience is erased one
heat at a time. But up until the final yards of the six-furlong
sprint, Rice and City Zip were spotting Lukas and Yonaguska
lengths, too.
</P>
<P>
   After City Zip dueled the long shot Dancing Missile in a
blistering opening quarter mile in 21.03 seconds, Jose Santos put
the brakes on Rice's colt in such a dramatic way that the
36-year-old trainer thought they were out of the race. ``I was
nervous,'' Rice said. ``I thought we were in trouble, and it might
cost us the race.''
</P>
<P>
   But Santos, who was aboard City Zip 24 days ago in his Tremont
victory at Belmont, was confident that he knew his colt. ``Having
the rail forced me to use him on the pace early,'' Santos said.
``Moving toward the far turn, I decided to give him a little break
and took back.''
</P>
<P>
   The grinding down of gears allowed Yonaguska and Jerry Bailey to
gun wide around the turn and take a two-length lead. It looked like
enough for the undefeated son of Cherokee Run to grind down his
bargain basement rival just as he had done to City Zip in the Flash
Stakes last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I moved too soon,'' Bailey said. ``That middle move
tired him out. He was flat in the last furlong.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos, however, had plenty of run remaining in his horse. He
angled City Zip outside in the stretch and urged him with staccato
left-handed whips past the 3-5 favorite to the throaty delight of
the crowd of 15,668.
</P>
<P>
   When City Zip crossed the finish line a three-and-a-half-length
winner, his owners, Carl Bowling and Chuck Thompson, had won
$65,220 of the $108,700 purse, his backers had collected $8.40 on a
$2 bet and Rice had executed a giant upset in the Grade II race.
</P>
<P>
   Why had City Zip barely attracted cash in the sales ring?
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of imperfections,'' Rice said. ``You can
criticize his appearance, but you can't be critical of him as a
race horse.''
</P>
<P>
   She is very likely to face Yonaguska in the Hopeful on Sept. 2.
Lukas, the Hall of Fame trainer, took the loss in stride. ``I think
we compromised our chances with the big middle move,'' he said.
``But hey, that is why we run them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
