<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING FOR (POLITICAL) TIME ON CHINA TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Commerce Secretary William Daley laid down the
Clinton administration's strategy this past spring for forcing the
China trade bill through a reluctant Congress, he insisted
repeatedly that, win or lose, Congress had to vote before the
summer political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't want to be debating China during the heat of
the fall campaign,'' Daley said at the time. ``You do that and all
bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Daley has left the administration to head Al Gore's
presidential campaign and the China trade bill, having cleared the
House in May with seemingly unstoppable momentum, has become tied
up in the Senate's arcane maneuvering on the budget, efforts to
punish China for weapons proliferation, and general procedural
gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will adjourn on Friday for the summer having barely
begun to debate, much less vote, on the measure that Clinton
repeatedly called a national security priority and his top
remaining legislative goal.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Clinton administration and the Senate leadership expect
the bill to pass. The Senate voted 86-12 Thursday afternoon to open
a debate on China trade, overcoming a procedural hurdle to schedule
full consideration of the measure in early September. Nearly 70
senators are thought to support the bill itself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the fears Daley expressed last spring over the fate of the
China bill have come true: It has become a political football, held
hostage while the White House and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
clashed over annual appropriations bills and while Democrats
focused on unrelated legislative goals. Meanwhile, the political
needs of the Gore campaign sidelined Daley from the White House
lobbying campaign to pass the trade bill, leaving Steven Richetti,
a less prominent political hand, in charge of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients' bill of rights is simply not an important matter
compared to the possibility of nuclear stand-off in Asia,'' said
Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y., who has argued that the United
States could face a military confrontation with China if Congress
fails to approve permanent trade ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We _ and I mean the Democrats, the White House and the
Republicans _ simply do not recognize the weight of this matter,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that China remains one of
Clinton's foremost priorities. But since the bill passed the House,
the president and many of his top aides have been focused on other
issues that will shape his legacy, including brokering a Middle
East peace accord, rejecting Republican tax-cut initiatives and,
perhaps most of all, helping Gore become president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton allowed Daley, who headed the aggressive lobbying effort
on behalf of the China bill from January to June, to resign to take
over Gore's lagging campaign. Richetti, the deputy White House
chief of staff who was Daley's partner in shepherding the China
bill through the House, was left to see it through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Richetti said the prospects for passage were good in September,
despite earlier concerns that Democrats might have a hard time
voting for a trade measure staunchly opposed by labor so soon
before a tight election. He urged Lott to stop using the China bill
as a legislative negotiating lever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is wide bipartisan support for this,'' Richetti said.
``It's far too important a national security and economic issue to
be used as a bargaining chip for other matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Few fault Richetti's political skills or his attention to the
China trade issue. But several senators and business lobbyists who
support the China trade bill said Daley has been missed.
</P>
<P>
   Widely considered Clinton's best political strategist, Daley has
a no-nonsense style and, among Clinton administration officials, a
rare track record of working successfully with the Republican-led
Congress. He also demanded _ and was granted _ broad influence over
Clinton's schedule, arranging many public and private events to
show that the president had no higher priority than China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a sense of urgency in the House and then we lost it _
Daley leaving, the president had some other things, you had the
appropriations bills,'' said Thomas Donohue, president of the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce. ``We need to get that urgency back.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that while there is plenty of support for the measure in
the Senate, it will now be subject to intense political pressures
and a crowded legislative calendar in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official described the view that
Daley's departure signaled a downshift on the China bill as
``totally false.'' The official argued that the stall in the Senate
began even before Daley left and that the strategy put in place by
Daley and Richetti for dealing with those delays remained.
</P>
<P>
   They and several Senate Democrats put the blame squarely on the
Republican caucus and Lott, who exercises almost complete control
of the Senate's daily agenda. Despite overwhelming support from
their core constituency _ business _ Lott repeatedly refused to
schedule a firm date for a vote in June or July.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see the China vote as a tough one for Democrats
because it requires they offend core labor and environmental
constituencies, making a September vote politically appealing. ``I
think it's clear that the Republicans want to make it as difficult
as possible on the Democrats,'' said Tom Daschle, the Senate
minority leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
