<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEAMSTERS-MOVIES-BOS &LR;      07-27 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-MOVIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTER WHO DEALS WITH MOVIE STUDIOS SAID TARGET OF US PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY AND STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal grand jury investigating alleged extortion of
Hollywood movie makers by local Teamsters is probing the activities
of the Teamster official who negotiates contracts with studios that
film around New England, according to sources familiar with the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters Local 25 Organizer Louis DiGiampaolo, who accompanied
Governor Paul Cellucci on trade missions to Hollywood last year and
in 1997 to try to convince studio heads to film in Massachusetts,
is a focus of the federal investigation, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are looking into whether DiGiampaolo, 48, of
Tewksbury, has threatened to shut down film productions unless they
did business with Local 25, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   One movie executive told the Globe that DiGiampaolo has
intimidated television commercial producers by ordering them to
hire Teamsters when they shoot around Boston, even though
traditionally they're not required by contract to hire union
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Bruce Singal, who represents DiGiampaolo in the federal
investigation, said DiGiampaolo denies claims that he's tried to
force people to hire Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's absolutely not a target of any investigation based on
what we've been informed,'' Singal said.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported Tuesday that Teamsters Local 25 President
George Cashman, who also accompanied Cellucci on the Hollywood
trips and serves on the Massachusetts Port Authority board of
directors, is under scrutiny by federal investigators, according to
sources.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury is investigating allegations that James
Flynn, Local 25's transportation coordinator, has forced filmmakers
to hire a company he controls that rents wardrobe trailers and
leases other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said Wednesday that he would speak to Cashman about the
investigation and acknowledged to reporters that he knows of the
complaints from movie studios about Local 25, having mediated some
of the disputes. There was no word from Cellucci's office on
whether the conversation took place.
</P>
<P>
   A group of executives who produce television commercials also
complained to Cellucci in 1996 that the Teamsters were trying to
shut down their sets because they were refusing to hire Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci told the executives, according to one who attended the
meeting, that he was willing to mediate a compromise between them
and Cashman but they turned down the offer believing that it could
lead to their having to negotiate a contract with the Teamsters.
``We were looking for the governor to put his foot down with
Cashman, but he was unwilling to do that,'' the executive said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dr. Alvin F. Pouissant, a Harvard Medical School
professor and child psychiatrist, says a Teamster official
``threatened'' to shut down the filming of a public broadcast
special unless a Teamster driver was added to the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Pouissant said that the Teamster, whose name he could not
recall, believed that the special was one in a series of
productions that was being funded with millions of dollars in
funds. Pouissant said he repeated to the Teamster that the budget
for the show, ``Willoughby's Wonders,'' which was to help teach
coping skills to children, was $650,000, and all the money had come
from government grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't believe me. He kept threatening that they would put
up a picket line and shut down the production unless we hired a
Teamster driver,'' Pouissant recalled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   When Pouissant asked if he could hire a Teamster at a reduced
rate, the official said no, Pouissant said. The meeting broke up
with the official promising to take the matter up with his
superiors at Local 25. Later that day, the official called
Pouissant and told him that the union would allow the production to
proceed without a Teamster driver.
</P>
<P>
   The production won a New England Emmy in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a federal grand jury in Boston subpoenaed records from
Teamsters Local 25, located in Charlestown, detailing the union's
contracts with filmmakers of such hits as ``The Perfect Storm,''
``The Cider House Rules,'' ``Message in a Bottle,'' and ``Good Will
Hunting''.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, agents from the US Department of Labor,
Division of Labor and Racketeering, raided the Weymouth home of
James P. Flynn, the union's transportation coordinator on many
Hollywood hits shot locally.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are looking into allegations that Flynn forced
filmmakers to hire Location Connection, a company controlled by
Flynn that provides wardrobe trailers and sublets other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The company was formed in 1989 by Flynn and other investors,
including convicted Charlestown bank robber William Sheehan, who is
now deceased, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn has long had ties to organized crime. He was acquitted in
1986 of the gangland slayings four years earlier of Michael Donahue
and Brian Halloran, who had been cooperating against gangster James
``Whitey'' Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn has caused some dissension within Local 25 by allegedly
hand-picking his friends to work on movies filming locally, a
lucrative assignment that brings a driver $2,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Former Middlesex Sheriff John McGonigle, who was convicted of
extortion in 1995 for taking cash from underlings, was welcomed
into Local 25 after serving a 57-month prison term and recently
landed a job on the set of ``What's the Worst That Could Happen''
with Flynn's help, sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
