<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5103 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMNS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHILE YOU WERE SLEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time's up, people. We've got political conventions coming, with
running mates, protesters _ all the stuff you need to hold an
actual presidential election. No more pretending this campaign
isn't really happening. Duty calls.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months Al Gore has been campaigning like
crazy, unfazed by your inattention. His current message is that
George W. Bush would turn the country into another Texas, a place
Gore has been depicting as a sort of Burkina Faso with oil rigs.
This pitch might work slightly better if Gore himself had not spent
so many years as No. 2 to the former governor of Arkansas. But the
Democratic National Committee lent a hand the other day, somberly
issuing a traveler's warning that urged visitors to the Lone Star
State to update their immunization shots. Meanwhile, Bush has been
proceeding at a more leisurely pace _ being inclusive, bonding with
Dick Cheney and building his dream ranch house. This is going to be
the only presidential candidate in history who spends the campaign
working on his retirement home.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Washington, Bill Clinton gave a radio interview in which
he responded to a question on what the last eight years had done to
his marriage with the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I think it's been good for ours because I got to live
above the store. ... There's a swimming pool here, and Hillary and
I spent a lot of happy days out there just talking and reading. ...
We've probably had more time together in our time here that at any
point in our marriage. ... It's been wonderful for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else has occurred that was anywhere near that amazing.
However, these are some runner-up memorable moments:
</P>
<P>
   May 15 _ Reacting to criticism that Al Gore's campaign is
adrift, Tony Coelho tells The New York Times: ``When people say
`Maybe you've lost some traction,' they have no idea what we're
doing. ... Just watch us. Watch us go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   May 31 _ George W. Bush irritably tells a TV interviewer he has
read ``a lot more books than you give me credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   June 3 _ Nothing much happens in the presidential race, but over
in England, Queen Elizabeth invites Prince Charles' mistress to a
garden party.
</P>
<P>
   June 5 _ The New York state Republican Party sends out a
fund-raising letter calling Hillary Rodham Clinton ``a brash and
bombastic, devious and dangerous, selfish and self-promoting
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   June 6 _ Boosting his friend George W. Bush to reporters, Gov.
Gary Johnson of New Mexico recalls a conversation they had at a
conference on state government. ``George turns to me and says,
`What are they talking about?' I said, `I don't know.' He said,
`You don't know a thing, do you?' And I said, `Not one thing.' He
said, `Neither do I.' And we kind of high-fived.''
</P>
<P>
   June 14 _ Not to be outdone in humanizing the presidential
candidate of his choice, Gov. Gary Locke of Washington, a Democrat,
tells reporters that Al Gore is ``not only a great person, but he's
very funny. ... He is always picking up the phone to check on his
mom.''
</P>
<P>
   June 15 _ Pat Buchanan, Reform Party presidential hopeful,
campaigns in New York, attempting to broaden his base with a speech
opposing the U.N. war crimes tribunal. He also blames Hillary
Clinton for the recent sexual assaults in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   June 16 _ Tony ``Watch us go forward'' Coelho resigns.
</P>
<P>
   June 18 _ The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, tells a TV
interviewer that ``the House deserves a lot of credit for passing a
bill overwhelmingly, bipartisanly, to eliminate the death penalty.
We're going to bring that up in the Senate.'' Further questioning
reveals that the death penalty he has in mind is the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   June 28 _ Asked if the scandals in his administration are
hurting Gore's campaign, President Clinton says, ``a whole bunch of
this stuff was just garbage,'' and reminds reporters that the only
thing the vice president was ``implicated in is this
campaign-finance thing.''
</P>
<P>
   July 19 _ New York Republicans send out a new letter, accusing
Hillary Clinton of being ``ambitious, ruthless, scheming,
calculating, manipulative'' and ``an angry woman.''
</P>
<P>
   July 20 _ Al Gore accepts an invitation to debate George W. Bush
on the David Letterman show. ``We think this will pretty much
decide the election,'' says the show's executive producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-R-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT     07-27 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: YASSER ARAFAT'S MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (REPEATING for all needing.)  
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   And so it really comes down to this: Who is Yasser Arafat? Is he
Nelson Mandela, or is he Willie Nelson? That is, is he a man ready
for a historic compromise, or would he just prefer to sing the old
songs?
</P>
<P>
   What is striking is that after a two-week diplomatic slumber
party at Camp David with Arafat, U.S. officials say they still
don't know. But this is the key question now.
</P>
<P>
   The reason President Clinton was so frustrated with Arafat at
Camp David was not because he refused to accept every aspect of
Ehud Barak's offer for how to share Jerusalem. No one could have,
or should have, expected that. The Palestinian-Muslim claim to
Jerusalem is authentic, deep-rooted and heartfelt. The reason the
Americans were frustrated with Arafat was that he played
rope-a-dope. He came with no compromise ideas of his own on
Jerusalem. He simply absorbed Barak's proposals and repeated
Palestinian mantras about recovering all of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   What should Arafat have said? He should have told Barak that his
ideas for granting Palestinians an administrative presence in East
Jerusalem, autonomous control over the Arab neighborhoods there and
religious control over the Temple Mount were a huge leap forward
for an Israeli leader.
</P>
<P>
   But, he should have added, they didn't go far enough. The
Palestinians needed three things: First, they must have not simply
an administrative presence but a sovereign presence in East
Jerusalem, over which they have full control and can fly their flag
_ even if it is just one square block. It could be at Orient House
or in the Muslim Quarter. Second, they must at least share
sovereignty with the Jewish people over the sacred space of the
Temple Mount, which is the site of both the ancient Jewish temple
and two of Islam's holiest mosques. And third, the Palestinians
must have direct access from that sovereign Palestinian presence to
both the mosques on the Temple Mount and to the Palestinian state
in the West Bank, so they don't have to go through Israeli
checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Such a proposal would have been further than Barak was ready to
go, but it would have been a credible Palestinian counteroffer, and
it would have been the basis for a real negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Because we do know now who Ehud Barak is. ``Barak is engaged in
the most important historical event of the Zionist movement,''
remarked the Hebrew University philosopher Moshe Halbertal.
``Between the Mediterranean and the Jordan there are roughly 5
million Jews and 5 million Palestinian Arabs. You cannot have a
Jewish and democratic state without dividing this land, and those
who oppose that are dooming Israel to an apartheid state, which
might have secure borders, but might not be worth securing. Barak
is on a purely Zionist mission to bring Israel back into borders
where it can be Jewish, just, democratic _ and secure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't Arafat seize on that with a serious counteroffer? One
view in the U.S. camp is that the Palestinians still don't know who
they want to be when they grow up. They still prefer to whine and
play the victim. Another view says, hold on, Arafat knows he has to
engage, but he needed to show his people he could say no before he
says yes.
</P>
<P>
   My own view is a mix. I believe Arafat presides over a
decentralized, disenfranchised and dysfunctional national movement
that, against all odds, has managed to survive Arab regimes that
wanted to control it and Israeli governments that wanted to destroy
it. He survived all these years by bobbing, weaving, straddling and
never making an irrevocable decision. But now he is at the moment
of truth. He must do something he has never done before: clearly
define not just what the Palestinians want, but what they also
believe the Jews are entitled to, and then split the difference and
take responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   To do that he is going to have to rise above his personal
history and circumstances, and also enlist the backing of Egypt and
Saudi Arabia _ which represent the Muslim world, but which ran away
when Clinton asked them to help Arafat fashion and sell a
compromise on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late. Listen to Israel. Listen to the silence. It's
the Israeli silent majority already redrawing maps in their heads.
That is Barak's great achievement. But it has limits, and it will
be utterly wasted if Arafat and the Arabs can't muster the courage
to get their own people to do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0354 </DOCNO>
