<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROSE-BOS &LR;      07-27 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE'S FENWAY DREAM FADES AS HE HEADS FOR THE ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It could just as easily have been three years
ago, when Montreal general manager Jim Beattie was planning to
trade Pedro Martinez to the Red Sox and had his pick of the top two
Sox pitching prospects, Carl Pavano or Brian Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie chose Pavano, and Rose still had intact his dream of
pitching for the Olde Towne Team he'd grown up cheering for in
South Dartmouth, Mass. But while Rose, whose favorite player as a
kid was Roger Clemens, made it to Fenway Park, making his
big-league debut at the age of 21 before friends and family, it
turns out his term on Yawkey Way was short-lived, too.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Rose pitches in the big leagues _ and that could
be as soon as Sunday in Milwaukee _ it will be for the Colorado
Rockies, who acquired Rose and John Wasdin, along with second
baseman Jeff Frye and another local boy, Walpole's Jeff Taglienti,
in a seven-player deal Thursday in which the Sox received Cuban
defector Rolando Arrojo and infielder Mike Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Rose had some grand moments for the Sox, most notably when he
beat the Yankees twice in a span of six days last May, but the down
times outnumbered the good for the 24-year-old righthander, who had
elbow problems, clashed with the front office and pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan, and spent parts of each the last four seasons in
Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was home in Dartmouth when he received a call informing him
of the trade. He later spoke with Rockies general manager Dan
O'Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty startled and a little anxious,'' Rose said by
phone. ``This is a chance to get back to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan O'Dowd told me I was the guy they were really looking for
in the deal, and that they're excited I'm going over there. He
basically told me not to be scared about the ballpark and just use
my pitches. I'm just looking forward to pitching in the big leagues
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies had wanted Rose to pitch Saturday, taking Arrojo's
spot in the rotation, but he just pitched Tuesday in Pawtucket, so
he'll likely be bumped back to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to reflect on his time with the Sox, and whether he felt
the club had lost confidence in him, Rose said: ``I basically can't
answer that question now. I'm still a little startled about the
trade. One day maybe I'll sit down and talk about it. But I've been
advised by my agent, Jack Toffey, not to say anything more.''
</P>
<P>
   Toffey was a classmate of O'Dowd's at Rollins College. ``He's
sad he's leaving New England and the Red Sox,'' Toffey said, ``but
I think of change of scenery may be good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox and Rose had some conflicts over the condition of his
elbow two years ago, when the team refused to pick up the tab when
Rose sought a second opinion from another doctor. Then last summer
in Chicago, after Rose failed to cover first base, Kerrigan was
quoted as saying Rose had ``embarrassed'' the entire team on
national television and had him at the ballpark early the next day
for fielding drills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
