<HEADLINE>
ALBUM OF THE WEEK: `HEROES &AMP; VILLAINS' 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VARIOUS ARTISTS: ``Heroes &AMP; Villains: Music Inspired by the
Powerpuff Girls'' (Rhino/Cartoon Net).
</P>
<P>
   Those mutant X-Men are confronting all comers at the box office,
but there are champions much tougher than that movie's confused
adolescent, Rogue. The Powerpuff Girls, created by Craig McCracken
for the Cartoon Network, give young viewers a taste of unequivocal
female punch. Buttercup, Bubbles and Blossom talk like the
Chipmunks, chew gum, think fast and defeat baddies like the monkey
Mojo Jojo without mussing the bows in their hair.
</P>
<P>
   The show's hip kiddie feminism appeals to underground rockers.
For ``Heroes &AMP; Villains'' 11 bands united to create a Powerpuff
Girls episode in the recording studio. Better than just another
soundtrack, this disc boasts pert originals by Apples in Stereo,
Shonen Knife, Bis, Frank Black, Cornelius and others, linked to
tell a typical Powerpuff tale of chaos, bravado and ultimate
triumph. The precocious sound these bands cultivate has never had a
more appropriate niche. The Powerpuff Girls are a godsend to cute
pop bands, and to prepubescents everywhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
