<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5114 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     07-27 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRYE ROCKS THE BOAT, SO NOW HE'S A ROCKIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Large and small, old and young, veteran and
rookie. Let the word go forth to all who would work for the Boston
American League baseball club: Speak out and you are gone. Like
deposed leaders in the old Soviet Union, you are easily erased.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had been looking to dump Jeff Frye's contract for a
couple of years and his loss on the field is not a huge deal. But
can it be total coincidence that Frye was traded four days after
ripping Dan Duquette (over the Duke's treatment of Mike Staley)?
And is it really a good baseball/business decision when you unload
a 33-year-old infielder who's finishing a $2.5 million contract in
exchange for a 32-year-old guy who'll get $6.5 million next year?
</P>
<P>
   Either this guy Mike Lansing can really play, or the Duke was
really stung by Frye's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette must have majored in Machiavelli at Amherst. His
corporate mission statement dissent policy calls for zero
tolerance. Only yes-men need apply. Rock the boat and they'll start
fitting you for a body bag. Ask Roger Clemens, Mo Vaughn, Jose
Canseco, Mike Greenwell, Kevin Kennedy, Jim Leyritz, Butch Henry,
Flash Gordon, Luke Wrenn, Bob Schaefer, Mike Rizzo, Bill Madlock,
Gerald Perry, Steve August, Johnny Pesky, Sam Mele, Frank Malzone,
Jim Samia.
</P>
<P>
   Sox players knew something was coming down Thursday afternoon.
Tim Wakefield sat at a table in the clubhouse with Rich Garces and
said, ``I hear we made a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield listed the names. He had the principals down almost
perfectly. A few minutes later, the Sox bus arrived and Frye walked
into the clubhouse. He already knew. He had a brief meeting with
Sox manager Jimy Williams, then collected his bats and spoke with
Sox traveling secretary Jack McCormick about securing a flight to
Milwaukee. The Rockies play at County Stadium Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   A procession of teammates went to Frye's locker. Hugs all
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be taking any of my bats,'' said Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ha, they're all corked anyway,'' teased Frye.
</P>
<P>
   Frye had never been traded. Any regrets about popping off
against the Duke?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Sometimes you have to speak up. Every man in
this clubhouse appreciates what I did for Mike Stanley.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he think he was traded because of his rant?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``It's close to the trading deadline.
Teams are trying to make some moves. You'd have to ask Dan (we
would, but it's clear by now that Duquette doesn't care to give
fans any sincere answers). I'm probably the one that burned the
bridge, but these things happen sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Any advice for a young Boston player who wants to stick around?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you should conform and bite your tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox players know the score. Darren Lewis knows. Rod Beck knows.
Tim Wakefield knows. They know and they are concerned with the loss
of solid citizens who have helped the team in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders Nomar and Pedro Martinez were asked if they had any
concerns about Duquette trading Frye or other players for reasons
other than ``baseball decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' said Nomar. ``You don't know what's in the
works. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro said, ``This is part of baseball. You have to realize the
business part of baseball is larger than the game. We love the
game. They (management) don't. And that's the way it's supposed to
be. I'm an oldie now. I realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Business or bad blood, the timing of this trade left Williams
with only three bench players. That's right. Three. The Sox are
carrying 11 pitchers. Add nine players in the lineup and you get to
20. That should leave five pinch hitters, but Frye was flying to
Milwaukee and Jurassic Carl Everett (who this week issued the most
phony apology since Bobby Knight) was serving the third game of his
10-game suspension. The good news was that the immortal Izzy
Alcantara was batting cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   As baseball trades go, this might be a good one. We're going to
miss Frye's presence and life on Lansdowne certainly won't be the
same without Johnny ``Way Back'' Wasdin. The mind boggles at the
thought of the homers Way Back could surrender in the rarified air
of Colorado. As for Brian Rose, he never showed he was anything
more than a Triple A pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing can hit a little. Rolando Arrojo is the Sox' first Cuban
righty since Luis Tiant, and that one worked out pretty well. Rich
Croushore is no relation to Austin Croshere, coveted by the
Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Lansing, Arrojo, Ed Sprague, and Bernard Gilkey don't
offset Denny Neagle and David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe the Duke's not done. There could be another
trade. Some other Sox player might pop off between now and the
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0359 </DOCNO>
