<SLUG> BC-R-US-VIETNAM-TRADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN VIETNAM, A NEW, BUDDING LANDSCAPE FOR TRADE AND INVESTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Repeats to include graphics note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam _ Just a few weeks ago, foreign executives here
looked at Vietnam and saw a Communist backwater dabbling
halfheartedly in free enterprise and foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they see a budding market in a country that has signed an
agreement granting the United States, a former enemy, access to
almost every aspect of its economy.
</P>
<P>
   The change is largely due to that trade agreement, signed by
Washington and Hanoi officials nearly two weeks ago. Lawyers,
economists and business people are only beginning to make sense of
the new accord, a densely worded volume of diplomatic and legal
language. The consensus is that the agreement is the most
significant business development here since the country reopened to
foreign investment almost 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has changed the landscape completely,'' said Nigel Russell,
a lawyer who has worked for seven years in Vietnam advising
American and other foreign clients for Phillips Fox, an Australian
law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, subject to approval by Congress, would give
Vietnam the same ``most-favored nation'' status of low tariffs that
China enjoyed subject to annual reviews by Congress until it
secured permanent status this year. In return for gradually opening
its economy further to U.S. investment and exports, Vietnam
immediately gains improved access for its products in American
markets, with the average tariff on goods from Vietnam falling to 3
percent from almost 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very comprehensive agreement that will open a lot of
doors to U.S. business in Vietnam,'' said Frederick Burke, a lawyer
at Baker &AMP; Mackenzie at a briefing to the American Chamber of
Commerce here. The agreement also represents ``dramatic progress
for Vietnam in its integration into the global economic
community,'' he told the more than 100 people in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   That said, few people here are under the illusion that change
will come easily or that it will quickly reverse a recent exodus by
disenchanted foreign investors. Much will still depend on the
political will of Vietnam's elderly Communist rulers to enforce the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implementation is going to be a serious question,'' said
Anthony Salzman, who sells Caterpillar products in Vietnam. ``As an
American businessman, I'll be looking at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam has been experimenting with what it calls
``market-oriented'' reform since 1987. Since President Clinton
lifted the trade embargo in 1994, American companies have been
trying with mixed success to participate in that experiment, but it
took almost five years for the two nations to reach an agreement
formalizing terms for a trade and investment agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate impact of the agreement on Vietnam's economy would
be relatively small. The World Bank estimates that Vietnamese
exports to the United States would rise to $768 million a year,
compared with $504 million last year. Even in an economy as small
as Vietnam's, that would raise average incomes by less than 1
percent, the bank estimates. ``The real economic impact is not as
great as people expect,'' said Dinh Tuan Viet, an economist at the
World Bank's office here.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate beneficiaries are foreign textile and apparel
manufacturers with plants here, such as Nike and the lingerie maker
Triumph. U.S. tariffs on bras and underpants, for example, would
drop to zero from about 60 percent, contributing to what the World
Bank estimates would be a 1,500 percent increase in Vietnamese
clothing exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although Vietnamese workers would earn the wages from such a
boom, the country does not supply the raw materials for such
exports and so the broad economy would reap relatively little
economic benefit, says Viet at the World Bank. A greater benefit to
the economy, he said, would come from cuts in tariffs on processed
food, especially fish and shrimp products.
</P>
<P>
   More profound are the changes the agreement makes to Vietnam's
rules on foreign investment. Economists say these will not only
force the country to adopt international norms on accounting and
corporate governance, but accelerate economic reforms already under
way, especially the transfer of state-owned industry to
individuals. Last week, for instance, Vietnam opened a long-awaited
stock exchange in the hope of mobilizing private capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up the economy to a whole series of competitive
forces,'' said Wong Yit Fan, regional economist at Standard
Chartered Bank in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   For U.S. companies looking at Vietnam's market of 77 million
people, the agreement offers important concessions. It phases out
quotas on a range of American products from meat to motorcycles and
gradually cuts tariffs on everything from Maybelline mascara to
Motorola mobile phones. It establishes the right of U.S. accounting
and law firms to establish wholly owned subsidiaries in Vietnam and
over time opens the country to U.S. banks, insurers and health-care
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also protects intellectual property rights,
including software and semiconductor designs, and prohibits Vietnam
from applying different product standards on U.S. importers or from
charging foreign business higher fees for telephone calls,
utilities and air fares. Perhaps most tellingly, it seeks to
eliminate the regulatory caprice that is the subject of so many
foreign investor complaints. The agreement would oblige Vietnam to
end arbitrary application of rules on foreign companies. Any rules
would have to be promulgated well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Burke at Baker &AMP; Mackenzie said the agreement's significance was
amplified by nondiscrimination clauses in Vietnam's trade
agreements with other nations. That means companies from China,
Europe and Japan would also benefit from the new terms.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the agreement stops short in many areas. Vietnam
retained restrictions on trade in economically critical products
like oil, rice and gold, as well as politically sensitive products
such as publications and films.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also appears to do little to improve Vietnam's
Internet infrastructure. It mimics China's limits on foreign
involvement in telecommunications and does little to promote flows
of venture capital to fund the kind of high-technology start-ups
other developing nations have deemed crucial to taking part in the
so-called new economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
