<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROBLEM WITH CERTIFIED MAIL CAUSES DELAYS IN DELIVERY
</P>
<P>
   Local postmasters have acknowledged that a failure to assign
enough workers to move the mail and problems installing a computer
system for tracking certified mail have led to pileups of letters _
which include tax payments, legal documents like foreclosure
notices and court filings _ in postal warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, hundreds of taxpayers were sent notices
demanding penalties and interest for failing to make June property
tax payments on time before the city discovered what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   WITHOUT NAPSTER, THE SWAP GOES ON
</P>
<P>
   A decision by a judge to prohibit Napster from offering access
to songs whose copyrights are owned by the major record labels is
being viewed as a serious blow to those who had hoped to build a
business on the online trading of copyrighted music. But the
cultural phenomenon shows no signs of abating.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Napster asked a federal court to stay a preliminary
injunction, asserting it would effectively shut down the service.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCOM SHARES FALL ON WARNING
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom, the nation's second-largest long-distance company,
reported a 53 percent rise in second-quarter earnings, matching
Wall Street expectations. But the company also warned that sales
growth for the rest of the year would be at the low end of its
previous estimate, and WorldCom shares tumbled as much as 15
percent before recovering somewhat. Shares of WorldCom ended the
day down $5.4375, or 12 percent, at $39.3125.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ PLUNGES, BUT DOW CLIMBS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as concern about the results of technology
companies led investors to switch to old economy shares. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 145.49 points, or 3.7 percent, to 3,842.23,
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 2.80 points, to
1,449.62. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 69.65 points, or
0.7 percent, to 10,586.13.
</P>
<P>
   EX-FEDERATED CHIEF JOINS PENNEY
</P>
<P>
   Allen L. Questrom, who headed Federated Department Stores for
much of the 1990s and led Barney's out of bankruptcy, was named
chairman and chief executive of J.C. Penney, whose shares rose 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
   15 FROM BLAIR INDICTED IN FRAUD CASE
</P>
<P>
   D.H. Blair, a defunct Manhattan brokerage firm, and 15 of its
officers and employees were indicted on securities fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE GIANT PREPARES TO LOBBY
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom is considering ways to reduce the German
government's stake in the company as it prepares to wage a
behind-the-scenes political battle to win approval of its plan to
buy VoiceStream Wireless, said Ron Sommer, the company's chief
executive. The holdings could be lowered either through other
acquisitions, which would dilute the stake, or through a sale of
shares.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. REACHES DEAL ON WEB PRIVACY
</P>
<P>
   The government reached agreement with a group of Internet
advertisers on how they will glean information from Web surfers and
what they will do with it.
</P>
<P>
   FORD ATTRIBUTES CHANGE TO RESEARCH
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor said that its market research, not the gut instinct
of executives, prompted the company's decision to improve the gas
mileage of its sport utility vehicles by 25 percent over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   CASE AND LEVIN DEFEND MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case and Gerald Levin traveled to Washington to defend the
proposed merger of America Online and Time Warner against a rising
tide of criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
