<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PANEL LOOKS AT POSSIBLE REINS ON AOL TIME WARNER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Steve Case and Gerald Levin came to Washington on
Thursday to defend the proposed merger of America Online and Time
Warner Inc. against a rising tide of criticism that the new
colossus would be so anti-competitive that it would need to be
reined in by regulators even before its creation.
</P>
<P>
   As they have in the past, Case, chairman and chief executive of
AOL, and Levin, his counterpart at Time Warner, vowed to keep their
cable, broadcast and Internet systems open to rivals, and said it
would be against their business interests to discriminate against
other companies that relied on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been suggested that a combined AOL Time Warner might
somehow favor our content over that of competitors,'' Case said.
``Let me be very clear: AOL has never done anything like that, and
we never would _ because it would diminish our members' online
experience. For the same reasons, a combined AOL Time Warner would
build on our companies' demonstrated commitment to open access.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics and some commissioners suggested restrictions might
be necessary to force the company to honor its commitments. They
also noted that neither Case nor Levin would say precisely when
they would open AOL's instant messaging service to competing
systems, or when Time Warner would begin offering rival Internet
service providers access to its cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Case and Levin were the lead witnesses in a five-hour hearing
this afternoon at the Federal Communications Commission that
offered the first glimpse of the thinking at the agency's highest
ranks. The commissioners' questions and comments appeared to
confirm the conventional wisdom that the deal would not be blocked,
although it appeared possible that significant conditions would be
imposed to prevent the new company from shutting out competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Executives on both sides of the debate agree that its outcome
will shape the Internet landscape and its regulation for years to
come, laying down broad principles about Washington's role in
assuring that the marketplace remains both open and innovative.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer groups, along with the Walt Disney Co. , NBC and a
host of Internet service providers and telephone companies, have
raised concerns about the deal, coming in the midst of a digital
revolution that is slowly blurring the lines between telephones,
televisions and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They say that the convergence of these technologies makes it
dangerous to put too much control of the market in the hands of AOL
and Time Warner, which could give it the ability to shut the rivals
out of the developing areas like interactive television, instant
messaging and digital telephony services, and could slow Internet
connections between rival content providers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Critic after critic told the commissioners that there was no
reason for the government to trust promises by Case and Levin to
keep their system open. The critics reminded the commissioners that
America Online's instant messaging system does not work with
competing systems and that Time Warner had shut ABC off its cable
television systems earlier this year in the middle of a commercial
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``What remains is for their promises and policies to be refined
and codified as conditions to approving the deal,'' said William
Reddersen, executive vice president of BellSouth, which offers its
own high-speed Internet alternative over telephone lines. ``They
are saying trust me, in an area where they have not allowed their
systems to always be open in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney, another rival, has complained that AOL's 23 million
subscribers ``spend 85 percent of their time within its `walled
garden' rather than the Internet at large.'' That, Disney says,
demonstrates ``the extent of AOL's power and the ability to exclude
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richard D. Parsons, the president of Time Warner, dismissed
Disney's complaints as nothing more than ``a series of business
disputes that are being dressed up to be policy disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's money, that's what this is about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some commissioners suggested that they were uncomfortable
imposing regulations on a marketplace that was developing so
rapidly and unpredictably.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are faced with a merger that is born from a revolution that
is in its infancy, and the merger's great promise and possible
dangers rest principally in the future _ a future that changes
rapidly and often unpredictably,'' said Commissioner Michael
Powell. ``It is very difficult to grasp the effect of this
combination on consumers in markets that have barely emerged, or
have yet to be created even.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the prevailing view among lobbyists and government
officials is that it is far more likely that the Federal Trade
Commission, which is also reviewing the deal, will impose more
stringent conditions than the FCC But the trade commission's
authority is limited to interpreting antitrust laws and court cases
that give it less leeway than the communications commission,
particularly in cases involving so-called vertical integration
between a producer and distributor. The FCC, by contrast, has the
authority to do virtually anything it wants under federal
telecommunications law, which allows commissioners to approve the
deal if it serves a nebulous standard of promoting the ``public
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few of the commissioners at the FCC expressed some
concerns about the implications of a merger that combines the
world's largest Internet service company with the world's largest
media and entertainment conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposed merger is not only one of the largest in United
States history, but combines the control of conduit and content in
an unprecedented fashion, implicating issues that are at the core
of our democracy,'' said Gloria Tristani. ``It raises the specter
of barriers to the free flow in the marketplace of ideas that has
been the essence of our democracy. If the shelves in the
marketplace of ideas are stocked by too few hands, a kind of
digital imperialism may replace a well-informed citizenry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2233EDT &QL; 
