<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     07-27 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KID PITCHER WON'T FORGET HIS DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (also see BBN-METS-EXPOS) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In two months, nobody will remember this weird game
except for Grant Roberts. Played partly in a soft mist, the game
will recede into the mists of memory except for the kid pitcher who
made his major league debut, quickly and erratically.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ultimately happens with the Mets this season, they will
obsess on games in late September, when every hit, every error,
will receive, by definition, bonus frequent-flyer miles of terror.
By then, even the Mets' players will probably have forgotten
Thursday's noon game in the odd Walesian chill of July.
</P>
<P>
   Players kept leaving the field with blood dripping from them.
Four different Mets wound up patrolling right field. And somehow
the Mets managed to come back to win, 9-8, in the first game of a
doubleheader against the Montreal Expos, and they won the second
game, too, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   The most vivid memories of the first game will belong to
Roberts, age 22, who was called up to start because the Mets were
in a pitching crunch. His term with the club was scheduled to be
about as short as it could get: one game, in and out.
</P>
<P>
   This is his sixth season in professional baseball. A 5-5
won-lost record this year makes him something less than a pheenom.
But the Mets needed some innings, so here he was.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts arrived in New York at 12:30 a.m. Thursday. By his own
admission, he ``didn't sleep too well.'' Asked to be more specific,
he said, ``Just about minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody had left him a note telling him to report to Shea
Stadium at 9 a.m., which was fine with him, considering he wasn't
sleeping anyway. When he got to the clubhouse, nobody was there.
Wednesday's drenching rain had canceled a pregame practice, so he
had some more quality time by himself.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, the majority of the patrons were day campers, clusters
of blue T-shirts and green T-shirts and yellow T-shirts, who had
arrived on clunky yellow school buses. The campers were far less
likely to shower venom on any errant Mets than the firewater-fueled
alleged adults on your normal, rabid night game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was the big leagues. In his warm-ups, Roberts got the
impression the mound was somehow flatter than the one at Norfolk.
For whatever reason, Roberts walked the first batter, and then he
walked the second batter. Then he saw Bobby Valentine, the manager,
trotting out for a chat.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts did not know Valentine rarely visits the mound,
preferring to leave those machinations to his pitching coach. But
Valentine said Dave Wallace, the coach, had informed him that ``he
had done everything he could in the bullpen,'' so Valentine felt it
was incumbent on him to try to soothe the young pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me I looked real good in my uniform,'' Roberts
recalled later, a bemused smirk indicating he knew Valentine had
made a nice try.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also told Roberts that the mound was fine. The manager
did a lot of gesticulating, as if the two of them were sitting
around a coffee bar debating the meaning of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it was, it didn't work,'' Valentine admitted later.
</P>
<P>
   Now came the carnage. The third batter whacked a hard single
that bounced off the wet grass and hit a hydroplaning Derek Bell
smack on the chin, drawing blood. Bell trudged out of the game via
the bullpen. Bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero, batting a mere .355, lashed a line drive to
third, but Jose Vidro, hitting a sizzling .358, cleared the bases
with a double. By the time the young man left in the second inning,
he would hold an earned run average of 40.50 for his major league
career, all four outs of it. ``Maybe I was choking the ball,''
Roberts conceded later.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, he had plenty of company in the clubhouse. There
was Bell with three new stitches in his chin. Soon there was also
Melvin Mora, out of the game with blood dripping from a split nail
on his throwing hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were down, 7-2, and a few players told Roberts to pay
attention, that they were going to win this game. He was not about
to dispute them. When they tied the score, the players told Roberts
that he had ``slipped the big tuna hook, that I wasn't just a
little trout.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably deserved an `L,''' Roberts said, referring to a
loss. ``But I'm glad the team won.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first game, Roberts was ready to go back to Norfolk.
The Mets were activating their utility infielder Kurt Abbott and
needed a space on the roster. ``I don't think they saw the real
Grant Roberts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he is back here in September, the campers will be in school
and the games will seem so much more vital. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
