<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG12-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A sheepish grin spread across the face of
Nebraska football coach Frank Solich yesterday as he feigned
confusion about a sudden reversal in the way elite teams are
judged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always heard that defense wins championships. But I'm not
hearing that this year, with all we have back on offense,'' said
Solich, whose squad has been pegged, along with Florida State, as
the co-favorites to win college football's national championship
for the 2000 season. ``It seems like all the hype about us has
completely reversed itself since last year.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. The Nebraska team that finished last year
ranked third in the final Associated Press poll got there with a
stifling defense and survived a school-record 49 fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   With six defensive starters lost to graduation, it's the offense
that produced 469 yards _ with just one turnover _ in a 31-21 romp
over Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl that has caught the imagination
of preseason prognosticators. The Cornhuskers return nine offensive
starters, including quarterback Eric Crouch, the top two tailbacks
and four of five offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Even with last year's turnover problems, Nebraska averaged 34.3
points per game. That has proved to be sufficient to earn the
'Huskers a preseason nod as eventual national champions from
``Preview Sports'' and ``Texas Football'' magazines, among others.
The first AP college football poll will not be released until Aug.
5. But Crouch said during yesterday's Big 12 media day that such
faith in a once fumble-prone offense is well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen that most ratings that have us No. 1 or No. 2. But
I think we expect more of ourselves than anyone else could,'' said
Crouch, a junior who rushed for 889 yards and 16 touchdowns last
season. ``This year, we have much better leadership. Everyone is
focusing on each other and not themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Crouch stands as the personification of the turnaround.
After being told during 1999 fall drills that he would not start,
Crouch left the team. He returned three days later after meeting
with Solich. Eventually, he regained the starting spot, then
received all-conference recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch showed his supportive side yesterday, saying he believes
Nebraska's rebuilt defense will be strong enough to make a
national-title run because the Cornhuskers have ``a lot of great
players'' capable of filling the vacancies. Carlos Polk, an
all-conference middle linebacker, concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, I don't feel like we have any questions,'' said
Polk, the team's top returning tackler (83 tackles, 6.5 sacks).
``We're flattered to be the preseason No. 1, but we want to be the
postseason No. 1. If we play as hard as we can and leave it all on
the field, a national championship can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect the Cornhuskers to receive unbridled praise
from rivals despite being a unanimous pick of league coaches to win
the Big 12 North Division. Colorado coach Gary Barnett said
yesterday that the talent gap between Nebraska and their conference
brethren is thinner than outsiders realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they are overwhelming favorites,'' Barnett said.
``With 85 scholarships \Rper school\S ... in this conference, you
won't see anybody overwhelm anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the message Solich attempted to convey yesterday while
deflecting speculation that his offense should average more than 40
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything along the lines of trying to project this football
team as the best in our conference or one of the best in the nation
is premature,'' Solich said. ``When you go through the Big 12, you
play your share of tough teams. You can't count anything in terms
of national championships until you get into the season and see how
things go with injuries and how things unfold. You essentially have
the chance to lose a game every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Solich said he's comfortable with the heightened
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way, as a head coach, to control what the
expectations are,'' Solich said. ``There is a lot of optimism about
this team and the players are confident. That's a good thing. When
you have that, the expectations will be there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
