<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRICE-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>

(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By TIM PRICE c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram When Gold Nugget pulled a 16-1 upset in the
$250,000 Dallas Turf Cup six weeks ago at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie, owner Leland Cook got so excited about his horse that he
gave his cowboy hat the Frisbee treatment and let it fly from his
seat five floors up in the grandstand.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He got his hat back, but the people in Southern California might
think Cook still has lost his top when he shows up with Gold Nugget
and runs him in the $400,000 Eddie Read Handicap on Sunday at Del
Mar. Gold Nugget might have won a nice race in his own back yard at
Lone Star, but traveling to the West Coast and running in a Grade I
race like the Eddie Read is a totally different environment.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook, a Corsicana resident who owns Gold Nugget along with
his wife, Sue, isn't naive. He has secured the riding services of
jockey Alex Solis for this trip to California, and he has
videotaped races turned in by some of the horses he expects to run
against in the Eddie Read. So, he has a handle on what might be
ahead at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a light field,'' Cook said, ``as far as numbers go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only six or seven are in there against us. But all of them are
top-notch.''
</P>
<P>
   Top-notch is right, for the field should include Dark
Moondancer, Ladies Din, Falcon Flight, Sunshine Street and Chester
House. All of those horses have won stakes races in Southern
California or Europe in the past year, and all of them mark a big
improvement over the last group of Southern California horses Gold
Nugget raced against.
</P>
<P>
   That came in the Dallas Turf Cup, when Gold Nugget beat Southern
California shippers Northern Quest, Army Of One and Self Feeder.
Northern Quest hasn't competed since the Lone Star race. But Army
Of One and Self Feeder have come back, and their performances make
the Dallas Turf Cup look anything other than a key race.
</P>
<P>
   Army Of One ran fifth in an optional $100,000 claimer at
Hollywood. Self Feeder finished fourth, 81/2 lengths back, in the
Grade II Sunset Handicap. But he had finished second in a Grade I
before he left for Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those horses had something taken out of them by the Texas
heat. But that doesn't explain why Sultry Substitute ran a game
second in the Grade II Bel Air Handicap at Hollywood Park after
running third in the Grade III Lone Star Park Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the Dallas Turf Cup, this field likely won't let Gold
Nugget get away to an easy lead. Both Sunshine Street and Dark
Moondancer ran on the lead or close to it when Dark Moondancer won
the American Handicap at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it can be done. A horse named Caherdaniel won a
minor-stakes race at Retama Park, then was shipped to Del Mar for
his next start in the How Now Stakes, which he won in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse, just about every time we've stepped him up against
competition, he's answered the call,'' Cook said. ``He deserves
this chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Gold Nugget does come through?
</P>
<P>
   ``I may never find my hat again,'' Cook said, ``I'd throw it so
far and high.''
\Nsubheds:LATE SCRATCHES... \Nsubheds:Getting on track The
adjusting of the dirt main track racing surface will continue for
at least another year at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie. Lone Star
general manager Steve Sexton confirmed this week that track
management met with trainers before the end of the thoroughbred
season to plan changes to the track.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star added about 500 cubic yards of pine-tree mulch to the
track last year and added another 1,500 cubic yards this year, but
trainers still noticed ``impact-type soreness'' with their horses,
said Texas Horsemen's Partnership executive director Tommy
Azopardi.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton said Lone Star has a goal of having the new materials
onto the track before the start of the quarter horse season Sept.
21, but it might have to wait until after the 11-week season.
\Nsubheds:Significant victory The quarter horse season at Lone Star
is 55 days away, and one of the standout horses expected to race
this year in Grand Prairie is getting into form. Significant Speed,
who qualified last year to the Dash For Cash Futurity at Lone Star,
won the $152,911 Rainbow Derby last week at Ruidoso Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The win was big for the filly because she often lost her races
in the late stages last year. She led the All American Futurity
last year until A Delightful Dasher and Chicks Call Me collared
her. But in the Rainbow, A Delightful Dasher was fourth and Chicks
Call Me was even further back.
</P>
<P>
   ``She ran a giant race,'' said Weatherford resident Gus Barakis,
who owns Significant Speed. ``This year she's matured a lot. She's
just mentally tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Barakis said Significant Speed, trained by Sleepy Gilbreath and
ridden by Roy Baldillez, is scheduled to race next in the trials
for the All American Derby on Aug. 18. Her ultimate goal is the
Texas Classic Derby in November at Lone Star. \Nsubheds:Final
workout Gold Nugget, the Texas-bred champion turf horse at the
recently completed Lone Star thoroughbred season, got in his final
bit of work before his scheduled appearance at the Grade I Eddie
Read Handicap on Sunday at Del Mar. He covered five furlongs on the
main track in 593/5 seconds and galloped out another quarter mile
for a total time of 1:13.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Randy Mayfield said the colt made the trip Tuesday to
the San Diego area in good shape. He's being stabled at the barn of
Keith Desormeaux, who finished seventh in the trainer standings at
Lone Star and who has stalls at Del Mar.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON ... Heritage Of Gold faces key rematch at
Saratoga There was a time not too long ago when a rematch between
Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus and Preakness Stakes winner
Red Bullet looked to be the best thing since the hype preceding the
heavyweight boxing rematch between Lennox Lewis and Evander
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   But the second fight turned out to be blah. And Pegasus-Bullet
II won't even happen as long as Pegasus gets closer to his
syndicated breeding season, and as long as the Bullet continues to
develop ulcers in his digestive tract.
</P>
<P>
   A more than suitable replacement should come Sunday at Saratoga.
Heritage Of Gold vs. Beautiful Pleasure will be the rematch of the
year if both face each other as expected in the Grade I Go For Wand
Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Of Gold, last year's Horse of the Year at Lone Star
Park at Grand Prairie's thoroughbred season, was hardly noticed
when she ran third to Beautiful Pleasure in the Breeders' Cup
Distaff in November. But she drilled Beautiful Pleasure in the
Grade I Apple Blossom Stakes in April at Oaklawn Park.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Of Gold had the benefit of a race over the track a
month earlier at Oaklawn. But it was Beautiful Pleasure's season
debut, highly evident when she missed the start of the Apple
Blossom and gave away at least two lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Amoss, who trains Heritage Of Gold, knows there is no way
Beautiful Pleasure will blow a similar race again. Although
Heritage Of Gold has won two races at Churchill Downs since the
Apple Blossom, Beautiful Pleasure regained her championship form
when she won her starts in the Grade II Shuvee Handicap and Grade I
Hempstead Handicap at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I watched her race in the Hempstead, I knew we couldn't
make any mistakes in Heritage Of Gold's training,'' Amoss said.
``It still may not be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Amoss said Heritage Of Gold is scheduled to make two undisclosed
starts before she returns to Churchill for the Breeders' Cup on
Nov. 4.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
