u p BC-CHENEY-MANDELA-NYT &LR;      07-27 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-MANDELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY SLIPS IN EXPLAINING A VOTE ON FREEING MANDELA 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As he made the rounds of the television talk shows
Thursday morning, Dick Cheney confidently defended his votes in the
1980s against gun control, abortion rights and education spending,
but he slipped when he tried to justify his opposition to an
obscure resolution in 1986 that called on South Africa to release
Nelson Mandela from prison.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately pounced on the issue and vowed to use it
against the Republican ticket in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Today'' show, Cheney, the expected Republican vice
presidential nominee, said his vote was based on a disagreement
over whether economic sanctions against South Africa were the best
way to end apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate that we had at the time had to do with how we could
best pursue our policies in South Africa,'' Cheney said. ``Nobody
supported apartheid. We were all against it. But there was a big
debate over the best leverage we could use to get Nelson Mandela
free.
</P>
<P>
   ``One school of thought said that there should be sanctions
imposed on South Africa, that American companies should be
prohibited from operating in South Africa, that there shouldn't be
any trade with South Africa. The other school of thought said,
`Wait a minute,' that, in fact, the only good jobs that were
available to black South Africans were with American firms. If you
wanted a company that was going to provide opportunities and not
discriminate, you had to go to American firms, and the people that
would be hurt if we forced American firms out of South Africa were
those very people we were trying to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney then said, ``This notion that somehow I was opposed to
freeing Nelson Mandela is a typical Al Gore distortion of a record
_ a point he's trying to make because he doesn't want to talk about
real issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement over sanctions was a big issue in Congress in
1986, and Cheney's description of the two sides was accurate.
Before the year was out, Congress overrode President Ronald
Reagan's veto of a bill that imposed sanctions, the first time
Reagan had been rebuffed like that on a foreign-policy matter.
Cheney supported the president.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of sanctions never came up in the debate on the
Mandela resolution. The opposition to it was based on the belief of
the right wing of the Republican Party in the House that the
African National Congress, Mandela's party and the leading
political voice against apartheid, was dominated by communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This resolution is potentially a step toward a communist
dictatorship in South Africa,'' said Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., not
yet a member of the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., said: ``Let us look at the ANC and see
what it consists of exactly. Nineteen of the 30 members of the ANC
are known members of the South African Communist Party, and we
believe as many as 26.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists said Thursday they expected to use the
Mandela vote against the Republicans this fall, particularly in
commercials on radio stations popular with blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush has now said to the African-American community,
`I give you my person, my candidate for vice president, and my
person said no to Nelson Mandela when he was in prison,''' said
Mayor Dennis Archer of Detroit, co-chairman of the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Clyburn, D-S.C., the chairman of the Congressional
Black Caucus, said, ``I think at least Cheney ought to apologize to
President Mandela.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1986 resolution was nonbinding. It expressed the sense of
the House that Reagan should encourage the white government of
South Africa to release Mandela and other political prisoners, to
recognize the ANC as the political representative of South African
blacks and to begin negotiations that could lead to a settlement
with the black majority.
</P>
<P>
   It was offered by Democrats mostly to goad Republicans into
casting a vote that could embarrass them in an election year. It
came up under rules that prohibited amendments and required a
two-thirds majority for passage.
</P>
<P>
   The House debated it for less than an hour, and it was defeated,
245-177, shy of the 282 votes needed for a two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
   On the vote, 215 Democrats and 30 Republicans were in favor; 32
Democrats and 145 Republicans, including Cheney, were opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the fourth-ranking member of the Republican leadership
at the time, did not speak in the debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
