r s BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-T     07-27 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bud Selig is an intelligent, reasonable man. When the baseball
commissioner clearly and passionately talks about the problems
facing the sport, he makes a great deal of sense.
</P>
<P>
   Economic disparity between clubs is a serious issue, and
something must be done. The recommendations of the panel on
baseball economics make sense. Put a 50 percent tax on payrolls
above $84 million to rein in the free spenders like the Yankees.
Increase the sharing of local revenues to help out teams like the
Expos and the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   It all makes sense after a conversation with the commissioner.
Only a professional cynic wouldn't see the problems and acknowledge
the solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, of course, has a professional cynic. It's called the
Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   The union's response to the economic panel's report and
recommendations has been low key, but there have been enough hints
dropped to indicate that the players are not in total agreement
about either the problem or the solution.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which wasn't pleased that it had no representation on
the panel, is skeptical about the claims that 27 of the 30 clubs
lost money in the five-year period from 1995-99, or at least why
the losses occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be one enormous failure in the discussion,''
union chief Donald Fehr told Bloomberg News. ``You're looking at a
time period that began during or immediately after the strike. The
problems of many clubs may have been exacerbated or in some cases
occasioned by the labor dispute _ which was forced by the owners.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly possible to debate whether the owners or the
players were most responsible for the 1994 strike that wiped out
the World Series, but one thing is inarguable. The dispute was
caused by the owners' insistence on a salary cap to close the
gaping chasm between the payrolls of the haves and the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   There's no talk of a salary cap this time, but the 50 percent
tax on payrolls above $84 million could have a similar effect.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also suggested that clubs not receive a greater share
of revenue sharing unless they meet a minimum payroll of $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   A payroll range of roughly $40 million to $84 million might be
good for competitive balance, but anything that acts like a salary
cap will be met with hostility by the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they come out and say it's a salary cap or whether
they try to disguise it as something else, I know right now that's
not going to happen,'' said Rangers pitcher Rick Helling, a member
of the union board. ``We've looked at it every way you can look at
it, and it's not in the best interests of baseball from the
players' standpoint or the owners' standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The union also is extremely skeptical about the accounting
methods that show clubs continue to lose money every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see teams building new stadiums left and right, and you
see owners paying big franchise fees, and you wonder why would
anyone pay $200 million so they can lose $20 million every year,''
Helling said. ``These are smart businessmen, and they're not going
to give money away year after year like they claim they do.
Economically, it doesn't make any sense and yet every owner comes
out and claims they're losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Players Association does agree with some of the things
brought out in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely some positives there to it,'' Helling said.
``We've known since the last deal that revenue sharing was
something that needed to be fixed. I don't think it was or ever
will be a positive if the bigger-market teams are paying the
smaller-market teams and they're just putting it in their pockets.
We need to figure out some way to where they're using that to help
build their team.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, the union doesn't have a view of Selig as a
reasonable man with common-sense solutions. And that doesn't bode
well for a peaceful resolution when it comes time to bargain for a
new collective bargaining agreement for the 2002 season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
