<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-SANKS0728-COX     07-27 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SANKS0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A rebuilt Sanks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Two years ago, when his heart was about the only
thing heavier than his thighs, Georgia running back Jasper Sanks
nearly walked away from football.
</P>
<P>
   After a 1998 freshman season that included only 10 carries in
two games, Sanks says he was ready to leave Georgia. He had arrived
in Athens with enormous expectations, but he failed to live up to
them because of his bulging waistline and an injured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about quitting,'' Sanks said. ``I just thought maybe
it wasn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't worth it when he wasn't playing. Weeks before the 1998
Peach Bowl, Sanks said Bulldogs coach Jim Donnan told him that he
wouldn't play in the game because he had not earned the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like everybody was against me,'' Sanks said.
``Everybody was asking me, `How much do you weigh?' It was
embarrassing. I blame myself. I didn't prepare myself at all. I was
lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   `I TOOK A LOT OF THINGS FOR GRANTED'
</P>
<P>
   Sanks considered transferring to a smaller school but decided he
couldn't quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a lot of things for granted,'' he said. ``I was reading
all the magazines and listening to what people were saying about
me, about how good I was going to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that because of what I did in high school, I should
have been out there. I wasn't working. Every time my name came up,
they were saying, `Sanks is a bust. He's a bust.' It was like my
name was forgotten or buried.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from his career at Carver High School in
Columbus, where Sanks was named a Parade All-American as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``All freshmen think about going home or transferring at some
point,'' said his father, Joecephus Sanks. ``He was just going
through that phase. I tried to explain to him coming out of high
school that a lot was expected of him but that he just needed to
set his own goals. He had a typical freshman year, and I think it
might have affected him.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of Sanks' freshman season, Joe Tereshinski, the
program's assistant strength-and-conditioning coach, took the
player under his wing. They started working out together before the
1998 Peach Bowl, and then resumed the workouts after Sanks
underwent surgery for a hernia in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks lost about eight pounds before last season and emerged as
the Bulldogs' starting running back. Even though he was still
overweight and had shoulder problems, Sanks rushed for 896 yards,
the school's second-highest total in seven seasons. He ran for more
than 100 yards in three consecutive games, including a 156-yard
effort against LSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still disappointed last year,'' Sanks said. ``I wasn't
running with any confidence, and I was running timid. I was
worrying about making mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   MISTAKES ACT AS MOTIVATOR
</P>
<P>
   His sophomore season probably will be remembered most for two
critical mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Against fifth-ranked Florida, the Bulldogs trailed 16-14 in the
fourth quarter. Georgia drove deep into Florida territory, but
Sanks fumbled, and the Gators recovered at the 16-yard line.
Florida scored to take a 23-14 lead, and later added another
touchdown for a 30-14 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a month later, Sanks was the victim of a controversial
call in the Bulldogs' 51-48 overtime loss at Georgia Tech. With
nine seconds left in regulation, officials ruled that Sanks fumbled
at Tech's 2-yard line, even though replays showed that he was down
before the ball came loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two fumbles really tore me apart,'' Sanks said. ``I play
those two games over and over in my head every day. Not a day goes
by that I don't think about those fumbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of dwelling on the mistakes, Sanks says, he is using
them as motivation. He spent more than a month this summer working
with a personal trainer in Atlanta, swimming and sprinting to
improve his speed. He returned to Athens in early June to
participate in the team's voluntary conditioning program, and he is
taking Taibo classes to improve his flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   WORKOUT PAYS OFF
</P>
<P>
   Five days a week, Sanks runs at 6:30 a.m. He lifts weights at 11
a.m., and then runs again with his offensive linemen at 3 p.m. An
hour later, he runs passing routes with quarterbacks, receivers and
other running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jasper has worked really hard in the offseason,'' Donnan said.
``I think he understands what his kind of ability is. He is
motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard work seems to be paying off. Sanks has lost nearly 20
pounds since his freshman year and now weighs 218. His body-fat
percentage has dropped from 13 percent to 4 percent, and he has
shaved nearly two-tenths of a seconds off his 40-yard dash time,
from 4.67 to 4.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stopped feeling sorry for myself,'' Sanks said. ``I'm a
totally different person now as far as my work ethic. I grew up and
matured. I got serious.''
</P>
<P>
   EAGER AND READY TO GO
</P>
<P>
   His teammates have noticed. When preseason camp opens next
month, Sanks will battle redshirt freshman Bruce Thornton and
newcomers Albert Hollis and Musa Smith for the starting job. It is
Sanks' job to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said Jasper was slacking off last year and
that his focus wasn't there,'' Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter
said. ``But Jasper's been the same person the past three years. I
think the expectations were so high when he came in that we
expected Jasper to be the next Herschel Walker. That's the status
he was given.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had a difficult time handling that,'' Carter said.
``We've talked a lot the last several months. He knows that he's
made mistakes, and he's owned up to them. But Jasper has worked
hard since he's been here. He's going to blow them away this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Sanks watched the Baltimore Ravens choose former
Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis with the fifth pick of the NFL
Draft. Sanks and Lewis, a former Douglass High School star, were
considered the state's top two college prospects in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was a freshman All-American for the Vols in 1997, while
Sanks spent the year at Fork Union Military Academy in Virginia,
after he failed to qualify academically at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching Jamal in the draft really motivated me,'' Sanks said.
``Despite the rivalry people tried to make out between us, I always
respected him. He was determined and stayed focused, and all of it
paid off for him in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at Jamal's situation and contrast it with mine. He got
his chances early in his career. I'm going to get my chances later.
I can't wait to put the pads on again. I haven't felt this good
since high school. I'm hungry again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
