<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SALVAGED-HOUSE-2TAKES     07-27 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVAGED-HOUSE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN NOTEBOOK: THE RADICAL RANCH PITCHES ITS TENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ In the arc of a flashlight beam, Patrick McCue held up
a lump of caliche, a crusty calcium-rich soil, and set it against
the rough-edged earthen wall of his new house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we were, stumbling to get this stuff out of the way, and
we ended up making the house to look just like it,'' he said.
McCue, 40, a captain in the Phoenix Fire Department, whose fiery
red hair blends seamlessly into his sunburnt face, kicked a few
rocks out of the spot of light and set down a metal kitchen chair
for his wife, Marika, 37, who is a fire captain herself.
</P>
<P>
   It was about 10 p.m. and 100 degrees in the quiet neighborhood
sprawling around the base of Squaw Mountain, a jagged landmark. A
full moon was rising over a distant ridge. The only other light was
a sizzling spray of sparks bouncing off metal being welded nearby.
</P>
<P>
   After two grueling years of construction, day and night, the
McCue house is nearing completion on a work cycle squeezed between
shifts: 24 hours at the firehouse, followed by 48 hours on the
building site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done nothing social, we don't celebrate birthdays, our
families are upset with us, but who else is going to do the work?''
McCue said, shrugging broad swimmer's shoulders. ``It's a matter of
`Let's dig in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Five volunteers _ fellow firefighters and an architecture
student from Arizona State University _ were picking up tools and
tossing leftover Chuy's tacos in the trash, finishing, by hand and
in their off-duty hours, a radical work of residential
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The four-room, 2,400-square-foot McCue house is made from 75
percent salvaged material, including trusses rejected from a
ballpark, high-quality but scratched glass donated by a
house-building friend and surplus steel picked up at junkyards. The
walls are of poured earth, and the roof is a polyvinyl tent fabric,
hovering, lightweight and taut as a spider web. This is the first
American home to use tensile fabric in a starring role, according
to Ferrari, the French manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   In a day when architectural zing often comes with the ring of a
multimillion-dollar price tag, the McCue house shows that those of
modest means can still innovate. The desert's vistas have
challenged architectural pioneers for much of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The house was designed by Marwan Al-Sayed, an architect born in
Baghdad, with Mies Grybaitis, a glass artist. Curators at the
Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum in New York selected the
project while it was still in germination for inclusion in ``Design
Culture Now,'' an exhibition of groundbreaking work that is running
through Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with the sensuous quality of the house,'' said
Donald Albrecht, a curator. ``There are those adobelike walls of
the desert. Then the super-duper modern roof system. It's like
transplanting the ancient desert architecture of one culture and
adding it to the modern desert architecture of another.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has cost the couple more than the $300,000 they
budgeted to build their house, which they have scrappily financed
with short-term construction loans and a lot of overtime. And no
small human cost.
</P>
<P>
   If the house inspired design aficionados while still on paper,
it brought about more than a few extraordinary feats of communal
devotion at the site itself. Friends with no particular attraction
to avant-garde architecture quickly realized that this house was
going to be special. And they wanted to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the firefighters, the labor force included Terry
McCue, McCue's brother, who has done much of the welding. After an
accident on the site partly severed ligaments, tendons and nerves
in his wrist, he lost sensation in his hand but continues to work.
``If we could have escaped that, we would have been home free,''
McCue said, still shaken.
</P>
<P>
   McCue's mother is sewing translucent fabric to be used in place
of glass or paneling for the few interior doors _ more like shades,
really _ in the mostly open-plan house. His father has been
recording the project in photos for a book.
</P>
<P>
   For an experimental house, it is shaped simply: part monumental
earthwork, part railroad flat. Its rectangular mass _ 25 feet wide
and 100 feet long _ straddles the bed of a dried-out creek, or
wash, which can fill during a severe summer thunderstorm. The
18-inch-thick walls render the house solidly earthbound, while the
silvery two-ply tent roof sweeps as high as 14 feet overhead _ a
permanent cloud, tethered by rope and steel, giving luminous shade
to the interior. By day, the temperature drops _ if not
precipitously, at least notably _ as one steps out of the broiling
sunlight into the ever so slightly blue-tinged spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to reduce things to their purest level,'' said
Al-Sayed, 38, who received an architecture degree at Columbia
University and studied desert culture in the Sahara on a traveling
fellowship. ``Coming from the culture that I do, I'm especially
interested in issues of the earth and the sky and how to bring them
into the architecture. It's a different relationship to the
out-of-doors than you find in the classic American house, which is
a lot more internally oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   His plan was to make a house of substantial mass that was
flooded with light, and he drew inspiration from a line in an
Egyptian film he recalled: ``Mamam, Mamam, the moon is at the door.
Should I let her in or shut the door?''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sayed has given the house a name, the House of Earth and
Light, and Grybaitis, his collaborator and fiancee, has cast that
name into a green-glass illuminated cornerstone at the front of the
house. Although Al-Sayed spent more than 10 years in the New York
office of Tod Williams and Billie Tsien and was the project
architect for their expansion of the Phoenix Museum of Art, this
will be his first solo building.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going out on a limb with this house,'' said
Grybaitis, 32, who came to the United States from Australia four
years ago. ``In terms of our career, it was either going to be the
end or it was going to be the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   For the irrepressible McCues, the project was a response to
their frustration with the stiflingly standardized development
common in Phoenix. Indeed, seen from an airplane flying over the
flat-as-a-frying-pan landscape, many residential lots look more
like hotdog buns on a tray than houses. The McCues used to live in
one such ranchburger. And no sooner had they finished four years of
renovating it than McCue started saying to himself: ``Is this all
there is? I'm not happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple promptly sold the house and used the money to buy
land in Alta Vista, a small, iconoclastic neighborhood just east of
the golf course of the famed Biltmore Hotel, partly designed by
Frank Lloyd Wright. The neighborhood had its own architectural
pedigree, with three Wright houses, including a burned-out ruin
left standing, along with recent construction by Williams and
Tsien, and a copper-finned, drum-shape home by Will Bruder, also of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this neighborhood could accommodate something
different,'' said McCue, who is also an inventor and metal artist.
``And that anything we built wouldn't stick out like a sore
thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sayed met the McCues just about when he and Grybaitis decided
they had had enough of Phoenix. Al-Sayed had arrived in 1994 to
work on the museum. When the project was completed, he headed back
to New York, where an apartment he had renovated caused a stir,
centered on a sun court in the middle of its living room. It was a
glass canyon open to rain, snow and, probably, falling ash from
trash-burning. Then they met the McCues.
</P>
<P>
   It might be said that Al-Sayed's inspiration for the house was a
telephone pole. ``There are few bus shelters in Phoenix,'' the
architect said. ``And I started noticing how people would line up
in the shade of a telephone pole just to get out of the sun. Shade
is like water here. It's a precious commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   His idea was to design a house that took advantage of the
extraordinary light in Phoenix, while shading the inhabitants from
light's harsher effects. Thus, the tent, a roofing material that
had already proved itself viable in places like Denver
International Airport and the Haj Terminal of the King Abdul Aziz
International Airport in Jidda, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sayed came up with a layered system: the top skin of
fire-resistant polyvinyl material would deflect more than 80
percent of the radiant heat; a second skin of coated polyvinyl is
waterproof. When cleaning time comes, this firefighting couple will
just pull out the power hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, none of this technology was even available,''
said Al-Sayed, who even in the biblical heat of Phoenix was layered
in a long-sleeved shirt and an undershirt (a self-insulating trick
that his father taught him after years of working in Saudi Arabia).
</P>
<P>
   A soft light pierces the roof, making it possible to see the
shadows of birds and planes as they fly overhead. McCue and his
brother made the trusses from salvage recovered for $300 from
Phoenix's Bank One ballpark, with its high-tech retractable dome.
</P>
<P>
   If the roof aspires to near-weightlessness, the thick walls go
for bold monumentality. Originally, the architect considered the
ancient technique of rammed earth, but rejected it as too
labor-intensive and cavelike. He settled on poured earth, laced
with his own recipe of cement plus soil, which is sloughed into
wooden molds. It is an unforgiving medium and requires huge
forethought: every window and door opening, plumbing and electrical
passage, even the placement of switch plates, had to be determined
before the house was cast as a solid piece of earth.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the designers have made something surreal out of the
everyday. Al-Sayed counts Federico Fellini as an inspiration. What
could be more contradictory than fortress walls, a gossamer roof
and cast glass? But they all mesh seamlessly. The entry door is
more than eight feet tall, made of bottle-green glass cast by
Grybaitis, using a section of street grating as her mold.
</P>
<P>
   The entire slot-shape house is exposed upon entry, with the
living room off to the left. There, the solid masonry gives way to
wide glass windows on both sides, offering views, partly obscured
by the hilly terrain and Squaw Mountain. (Imagine Philip Johnson's
glass house, circa 1000 B.C.) To the right, the bedroom is partly
concealed by a glass container, which serves as a walk-in closet.
</P>
<P>
   The house is positioned with its narrow end facing west, to
minimize the full brunt of the sun. A six-foot overhang of roof
fabric shades the south side, lest the living room turn into a
sauna. A swimming pool for McCue, who races competitively, will lap
the exterior wall of their bedroom, an idea Al-Sayed borrowed from
a Moroccan hotel that was once a sultan's palace. He has included a
slot window at the foot of the bed for pool gazing.
</P>
<P>
   Between the open living room and the bedroom is a study, more
like a conversation pit, sunk into the concrete, with a low window
for peering out at the desert floor. Bookcases were molded directly
into the earthen walls.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced to haiku simplicity, the house nevertheless has endless
complexity and engrossing nuance, from its steel toggle light
switches, reminiscent of the early houses of Le Corbusier and other
modern pioneers, to the constantly fluctuating shadows of trusses,
which mark the passage of the day like sundials.
</P>
<P>
   At twilight, even those massive walls seem to prickle with
light: McCue has cut 300 discs of glass to fit deftly into the
holes left by dowels during the casting. Grybaitis taught her how
to use a glass drill.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot evening last week, McCue, one of the first women to
become a firefighter in Phoenix, was eager to move in at last.
``We've got to get it done,'' she said. They have been living with
their yellow Labrador in a horse trailer parked on the site. ``Some
nights, my ankles are hurting, my knuckles are dragging in the
dirt, and I think I can't do this any longer. But somehow we do
keep pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   When she and her husband finally move into their house, in two
weeks, there is no doubt how she will respond when the moon comes
calling. She will welcome it through the open glass door, the
windows, the pierced walls _ and most especially through the
diaphanous sheltering roof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
