<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MILLER0728-COX     07-27 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER0728-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller steps up to seat in Senate
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pledging to serve with the same bipartisan spirit
as his predecessor, former Georgia Gov. Zell Miller ascended
Thursday to a Senate seat he had first pursued 20 years ago, nearly
wrecking his political career.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a 68-year-old Democrat, becomes the 62nd senator from
Georgia. He succeeds Paul Coverdell, a leading light of the
Republican Party, who died in office July 18 after a massive
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Although the day belonged to Miller, Coverdell's absence hung
heavy in the Senate chamber. Colleagues continued their outpouring
of sorrow in speeches before the swearing-in, and Miller used his
brief remarks to pay tribute to the man with whom he once served in
the Georgia state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, I am a different man from Paul Coverdell,''
Miller said in his North Georgia twang. ``I have rarely been
accused of giving soft answers. And in my day, I suppose, I have
uttered more than my share of grievous words that have stirred up
anger. But I also have a commitment to getting things done for my
state and our nation, and a commitment to work with anyone
regardless of party who shares that commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Coverdell had a powerful faith in bipartisan progress,''
Miller continued, ``and I intend to keep that faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Miller cast his first Senate vote _ for the Department of
Defense appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   Miller remained without any Republican challengers Thursday, and
U.S. Rep. Bob Barr announced he will not challenge the former
governor.
</P>
<P>
   With Barr's announcement, all but one of Georgia's eight
Republican congressmen have indicated they will not run in November
for the remaining four years of the term to which Coverdell was
elected. The eighth representative, Jack Kingston of Savannah, is
said to be leaning against a bid.
</P>
<P>
   Barr was considered among the most likely to jump into the race
because he has the largest campaign account among the so-called G-8
Republicans, and he faces a potentially difficult battle to retain
his House seat in 2002 after re-districting.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Georgia congressional delegation, former Republican
Sen. Mack Mattingly remained coy about whether he would enter the
race. Reached at his home on St. Simons Island, Mattingly said he
would make a decision by next Friday, when qualifying ends.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential candidate mentioned among Republicans is Lewis
Jordan, former chief executive officer of ValuJet, now flying as
AirTran. Party officials like the fact that Jordan is wealthy
enough to help finance his campaign. Jordan has made no
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Any GOP candidate who waits until the last day of qualifying
would miss a golden opportunity by not declaring before next week's
Republican National Convention, which starts Monday. The
conventions are generally a great place to raise campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the newly appointed senator, will serve less than four
months before the Nov. 7 special election.
</P>
<P>
   He wasted little time preparing for that contest. Thursday
morning, before his swearing-in, he held a fund-raiser at a
Washington hotel that attracted much of the K Street lobbying
community.
</P>
<P>
   Several major Georgia companies, including Coca-Cola, Southern
Co. and AFLAC, were represented, along with a number of Democratic
senators, according to Georgia lawyer Keith Mason, a longtime
Miller adviser. The event raised about $200,000, Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have preferred it the way I used to do it, when I ran
a statewide race for $175,000 in 1974, by just going around and
seeing folks in courthouses and county squares,'' said Miller.
``But that has become part of it. If that is the price that one has
to pay, I'll do what I need to do to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller moved swiftly to put a campaign team in place, retaining
Tim Phillips, who ran Sen. Max Cleland's successful Senate race in
1996, to manage his campaign. Miller also brought in Charlie
Harman, former Sen. Sam Nunn's administrative assistant, to manage
his Senate transition team.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Begala, who along with James Carville engineered President
Clinton's 1992 election, wrote the outline of Miller's first Senate
speech. Both Carville and Begala will serve as informal advisers to
the campaign, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 of the 100 members of the Senate were present when
Miller, wearing a dark blue suit and a red tie, entered the chamber
for the swearing-in ceremony. Clutching a tan Bible given to him by
former Gov. Joe Frank Harris when Miller was sworn in as governor
in 1991, Miller was escorted to the dais by Cleland.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond (R-S.C.), the Senate president pro tem,
administered the oath at 11:05 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Miller received a standing ovation afterward, and senators from
both parties lined up to congratulate him. Senate Minority Leader
Tom Daschle (D-S.D.) pinned a gold insignia representing the Senate
onto Miller's lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) then took the floor to
welcome their newest member.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that we have heavy hearts still for our friend,
Senator Paul Coverdell,'' Lott said. ``But we appreciate the way in
which he has approached this position already. He is one of our
colleagues. He's a senator. We welcome him.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's arrival tips the balance the power a tad, giving the
Democrats 46 senators to the GOP's 54. If Miller were to win
election in November and the Democrats managed to net five more
seats, they would hold the majority in the upper legislative
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's rise to the Senate brings his political career full
circle. In 1980, an upstart Miller challenged the Democratic
establishment in Georgia and took on Sen. Herman Talmadge in the
Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a bitter, divisive contest, Miller spent the next 10
years rehabilitating his career before being elected governor in
1990. In floor remarks, Daschle hailed Miller as the elder
statesman of Georgia politics, chronicling a career that began in
1960 when he was elected to the state Senate and _ until this week
_ appeared to have ended when he left the governor's office in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   After his swearing-in, Miller said he hadn't had time to reflect
on the twists and turns of his political career. ``Twenty years is
a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he would make no policy statements until he had time
to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the new kid on the block and I understand that,'' Miller
said. ``You also know, if you know anything about me, that I will
come up with some ideas, and that I will make some decisions, and I
will not be a shrinking violet.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Miller, who accompanie
</P>
</TEXT>
