<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX MAKE SOME NOISE WITH DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES AND BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Mass. _ Taking advantage of the Colorado Rockies'
tumble from first to fourth place in three weeks, Red Sox general
manager Dan Duquette Thursday swooped in and acquired righthander
Rolando Arrojo and second baseman Mike Lansing for pitchers Brian
Rose and John Wasdin, minor league pitcher Jeff Taglienti, and
outspoken second baseman Jeff Frye.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, a 32-year-old Cuban defector whose reported age was
greeted with great skepticism by Duquette when he first arrived
here and signed with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, is expected to
arrive here sometime Friday and make his first start for the Sox
Sunday against the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We acquired him to stabilize our pitching and help us down the
stretch,'' Duquette said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that he'll follow in the footsteps of the last
great Cuban pitcher we had here _ El Tiante,'' Duquette said,
referring to Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo has had nowhere near the success Tiant enjoyed in the big
leagues. He won 14 games for the Devil Rays in 1998, slipped to
seven wins last season, when he had shoulder tendinitis, and was
5-9 (6.04 earned run average) for the Rockies this season. But,
like Tiant, Arrojo throws the ball from a half-dozen angles, and
when he's right, his slider can be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette succeeded in outbidding the Cleveland Indians for
Arrojo's services.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not certain when Lansing, 32, will report. An
infielder who originally came up as a shortstop with the Montreal
Expos and has played primarily second base in the big leagues,
Lansing told Colorado reporters he was in ``shock'' about the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing also has played sparingly at third base, leading to
speculation he could be used there by the Sox, who also have Jose
Offerman at second. Jimy Williams said that decision will be made
after Lansing arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing has another year on his contract for $6 million, plus a
$1.25 million buyout if his option is not picked up in 2002. The
Rockies will be paying part of Lansing's remaining salary this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lansing reminds me a lot of John Valentin,'' Duquette said,
referring to the Sox third baseman out for the season after
rupturing his patellar tendon. ``He hits a lot of doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansing has twice hit 40 or more doubles in a season. The
Rockies acquired Lansing from the Expos on Nov. 18, 1997, the same
day Duquette made his deal with the Expos for Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication how this deal might impact the Sox'
talks with the Phillies about first baseman Rico Brogna. The
Cardinals, with Mark McGwire expressing concern that he may miss
the rest of the season because of patellar tendinitis, have shown
some interest in acquiring Brogna on a ``rental'' basis for the
rest of this season. Brogna is eligible to become a free agent
after his $4.2 million contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   But talks between the Sox and Phillies intensified this week,
when the Phillies agreed to pay $500,000 of the $1.35 million left
on Brogna's salary. Among the players the Phillies are interested
in is infielder-outfielder Donnie Sadler, who interestingly did not
start in Pawtucket's game Thursday, though he entered as a
defensive replacement later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still talking to other clubs,'' said Duquette, who has
until Monday at midnight to make another trade, though waiver deals
are always possible after that date.
</P>
<P>
   The trade of Frye comes just four days after the second baseman
ripped Duquette for releasing popular veteran and team leader Mike
Stanley. Frye had missed essentially all of the last two seasons
after tearing the ACL in his knee during a spring-training rundown
drill in 1998, and had additional knee surgery last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's a coincidence that it happened shortly
after I spoke up about the general manager or it just so happens
it's the trading deadline,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   He said emphatically that he had no no regets about speaking
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's business,'' he said. ``I have to go to my new team, and
go do what I can do, play hard, and try to help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye left here Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last year of my contract, I think everybdoy pretty
much figured I wouldn't be back in Boston next year,'' he said.
``From that aspect, it gives me a fresh start. I'm not ready to
stop playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
