<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-SHEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTING OF CONDEMNED VERMONT SHEEP IS EXAMINED IN COURT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A judge in Brattleboro, Vt. listened to expert
testimony on the science behind the federal government's decision
to kill 350 Vermont sheep suspected of carrying a disease similar
to mad-cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   Judge J. Garvan Murtha of Federal District Court, did not make a
ruling, saying only that he would issue a written decision soon on
whether the Agriculture Department could seize and slaughter the
sheep over their owners' objections.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha listened to a full day of testimony on the tests that led
the government to announce that the sheep could be infected and
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Two experts on the pathology of mad-cow disease testified on
behalf of the sheep owners, saying they thought the test, a Western
blot, should be redone because it did not include the proper
controls and because its results were less than conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, said one of the experts, Shu Chen, an assistant
professor of pathology at Case Western Reserve University, ``I
would conclude this test needs to be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen suggested that improved methods and another laboratory be
used to confirm the results.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Rubenstein of the New York State Institute for Basic
Research, who ran the test, stood by his results.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are two flocks of dairy sheep brought to Vermont from
Belgium in the mid-1990s. The owners, Larry and Linda Faillace and
Houghton Freeman, say the sheep were never exposed to contaminated
feed and could not be carrying say the sheep were never exposed to
contaminated feed and could not be carrying mad-cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   The disease has sown fear in Europe, killing dozens of humans
and tens of thousands of cows. American agricultural authorities
have said they want to err on the side of caution. They have kept
the Belgian sheep under quarantine for two years. When tests
earlier this month on four sheep from Freeman's flock showed signs
of a disorder related to mad-cow disease, they quickly issued an
order to kill all the sheep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
