<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-CORNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNING AND NORTEL DECIDE NOT TO COMBINE OPTIC UNITS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ontario)  By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corning Inc. and Nortel Networks ended talks Thursday that would
have combined their fiber optic operations.
</P>
<P>
   If a merger had been completed, it would have given Corning
Inc., the world's largest manufacturer of optical fiber, a
relatively full line of the lasers and other components used in
making communications and data networks. Corning had been
negotiating to do so by acquiring Nortel Networks' fiber optics
unit, which would have vaulted Corning into a strong No. 2 position
behind JDS Uniphase as a supplier of such goods.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would also have helped Nortel Networks, , the largest
manufacturer of optical communications networks, pursue its policy
of outsourcing most component manufacturing in order to concentrate
on system design.
</P>
<P>
   For all the strategic sense the deal made though, the numbers
just did not add up. Nortel said Monday that its fiber optic
component, , which sells most of its parts to the company's own
businesses, have a sales value of $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Following JDS Uniphase's recent agreement to acquire SDL,
another optical component company, for $41 billion, the market
value of Nortel's component operations soared to more than $100
billion, more than Corning's total stock market value.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to put the businesses together without Nortel
ending up controlling a majority of Corning's stock _ at least 57
percent by some estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel could have accepted nonvoting stock shares or a variety
of other governance restrictions that would have given Corning room
to operate independently, but no acceptable approaches emerged in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, analysts said, it was unlikely that the two
companies could convince Wall Street or others in the industry that
Nortel would not be in control. That raised the specter of other
major equipment purchasers, like Lucent Technologies, Nortel's
biggest rival, cutting back on their business with Corning in order
to avoid helping Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in a written statement saying that Corning remained
committed to expanding its optical offerings, Roger Ackerman,
Corning's chairman and chief executive, pointedly concluded that
``our core value of independence'' was ``central to this
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Corning's independence was not the only hurdle. The price of
acquiring Nortel's components business would have led to near-term
declines in Corning earnings. After the announcement that the talks
had collapsed, relieved investors initially sent Corning shares up
as high as $275 on the New York Stock Exchange, up 6.6 percent from
Wednesday's close of $258. But shares later fell, closing down
$9.375, to $248.75.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel declined to comment on why the talks had ended. But John
Roth, president and chief executive of the Toronto-based
telecommunications giant, said that Corning would remain a key
strategic partner.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nortel fell $5.50 Thursday, to $78.50 in trading on
the Big Board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
