<SLUG> BC-CONSECO-CUTBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSECO, NEEDING TO PAY DEBT, PLANS JOB CUTS AT FINANCE ARM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind.)  (Eds.: In 11th graph, the word ``plus'' should be converted to the
symbol.)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conseco Inc., the troubled insurance and finance company, said
Thursday that it planned to cut 2,000 jobs from its Conseco Finance
operation and sell numerous assets as it seeks to raise cash to
meet debt payments coming due.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Wendt, the company's new chairman and chief executive, said
Conseco's new strategy would concentrate on raising cash to meet
debts at the holding company and on maximizing long-term economic
earnings, without regard to whether accounting rules would allow it
to show profits.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco, based in Carmel, Ind., had a long string of rising
profits under its founder and former chief executive, Steven
Hilbert. But the holding company that controlled the insurance
subsidiaries was left with a rising debt level and investors began
to doubt the quality of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company Thursday reported a loss of $404.7 million, or $1.25
a share, for the second quarter, compared with a profit of $213.3
million, or 64 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. The
latest loss included a large number of special items, including
writing down assets that were being sold and the $45 million
signing bonus given to Wendt. The company said that its operating
loss was $28.6 million, or 9 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco Finance, the former Green Tree Finance, had been put up
for sale by prior management, but the offers for the company were
not high enough and Wendt indicated he was now more interested in
operating it than selling it. He compared losing the finance
company, a leader in the financing of mobile homes, to losing one
of a person's two arms.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during a conference call with analysts if the finance unit
was still for sale, he replied, ``Everything is for sale,'' but
then added: ``My top priority is to sell the holding company. If
you know anyone who would like to buy that puppy, we can make a
really good deal for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the finance unit would be operated so that it would
become self-financing and a contributor of cash to the parent
company, rather than a drain on cash. He said the company now had
$300 million to prepay debts coming due in September and said that
when sales of assets were completed it would have the cash needed
to pay debt coming due this year and ``well into 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendt, who gained a large Wall Street following as chief
executive of GE Capital, a subsidiary of General Electric, also
announced that three people who had worked with him at GE Capital _
Paul Street, Mike Borom and Peter Keenoy _ had ``joined our team of
`restoration activists.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Conseco shares, which peaked in early 1998, just before Green
Tree was acquired, at $58.125, Thursday rose $1.625, to $9.50 in
New York Stock Exchange in trading before the company's
announcements were made.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco said it would sell its stake in Tritel, a wireless
telephone company, whose shares fell $1.6125, to $29.6125 in late
trading. It took a $47.6 million charge to write that stake down to
market value.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt said the company would also focus on restoring the ratings
of its insurance companies. A.M. Best has downgraded Conseco to a
rating of B plus plus, which is devastating in a market where
nearly every company has a rating of A or higher. Wendt said that
getting holding company debt down would be a primary part of his
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Until that happens, Wendt said, the company will look for what
he calls ``rented equity,'' in which other insurance companies
provide reinsurance to assure that Conseco's products are rated
highly enough to be able to sell new policies.
</P>
<P>
   At the finance unit, which Wendt said had ``been portrayed as
the demon in the Conseco house,'' the company plans to sell five
business units and cut costs by closing some offices. He said that
would lead to a loss of 2,000 jobs at the company. When the
restructuring is completed Conseco Finance will be able to grow
while spinning off cash to the parent, Wendt said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
