u p BC-CHENEY-RECORD-NYT &LR;      07-27 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-RECORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY QUIZZED REPEATEDLY ON HIS VOTING RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dick Cheney tried Thursday to beat back
questions about his conservative voting record, appearing on the
morning news programs of all three major networks as the Bush
campaign fought to keep from being defined by the second man on the
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush jumped into the debate, accusing the
Democrats of using a ``constant line _ vote for me, I'm going to
tear down the other person'' _ in attacking the record of his
running mate, whose service as defense secretary to Bush's father
followed 10 years in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretary Cheney brought people together and helped win a
war,'' Bush said, ``which stands in stark contrast to Vice
President Al Gore, who tends to divide people to create war.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke as Cheney, for a second straight day, was called on
to explain positions he took as a congressman from Wyoming,
including votes against the Equal Rights Amendment, gun control and
sanctions on South Africa's apartheid government.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have highlighted those stands to undercut Bush's
efforts to define himself as a ``different kind of Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   At times Thursday, Cheney shot back by pointing to
inconsistencies in Gore's own congressional voting record. At other
times, he defended his conservative views. And occasionally, he
turned to talk of legislative process.
</P>
<P>
   Asked, for instance, why he had voted against the Equal Rights
Amendment, he said Thomas P. O'Neill Jr., as the speaker of a
Democratic-controlled House, had brought it up for a vote under a
procedure ``that prohibited amendments of any kind _ we had to
accept or reject it.'' He said he had feared that the way it was
written would have required the drafting of women into the
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I didn't think that was a very good idea,'' Cheney said
on ``The Early Show'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later Bush made a brief appearance before
reporters, taking time out from practicing his acceptance speech
for his nomination next week, and maintained that he had not been
blindsided by Cheney's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I knew his votes,'' Bush said. ``But I also know his
record. What do you expect? I'm running against people who all they
do is spend time tearing people down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats kept up their efforts to use Cheney's record as a
way of tying Bush to a Republican establishment of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Cheney's selection has done is given us a rather vivid
picture of old guard Republicanism,'' said Mark Fabiani, a deputy
Gore campaign manager. And, Fabiani said, ``some of his past votes
are hard to explain away in any era.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty for Bush is that some of the stands of his
running mate cut right to the heart of the way he has been seeking
to define himself as a ``compassionate conservative.'' Bush has put
a heavy premium on education, for example, and Cheney voted against
the Head Start program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush regularly surrounds himself with members of minorities and
recently spoke at the convention of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People. Cheney voted against imposing
economic sanctions on the apartheid government of South Africa and
against a House resolution calling for Nelson Mandela to be freed
after 23 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning Cheney said on the NBC ``Today'' program that
``this notion that somehow I was opposed to freeing Nelson Mandela
is a typical distortion by Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the issue had been tied up in a debate over sanctions
against South Africa. He said he believed that forcing U.S.
companies out of South Africa would have left many blacks there
worse off, because ``any good jobs available to black South
Africans were with American firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Of domestic matters, Cheney argued that the 1980s, when he
served in the House, were a different era, when budget deficits
required votes to control spending. And he said his rise in
Congress up the leadership ladder of his party showed that he had
not been viewed as an extreme conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``So whatever the Democrats want to say about me now,'' he said,
``the fact of the matter was many Democrats, as well as all of the
Republicans, thought I was a reasonably respectable fellow in the
1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   On some issues, Cheney stood firm. When asked why he had been
one of only 21 House members to vote against a ban on so-called
cop-killer bullets, he said: ``I consistently voted against gun
control. I'm one of those people who believes that the solution to
our gun problem is to enforce existing laws, not impose new
restrictions on law-abiding citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed as to why in 1988 he voted against a ban on plastic guns
that can make it through airport security, a measure that was not
opposed by even the National Rifle Association, he said, ``Well,
obviously I wasn't in the pocket of the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   And on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' he tried to turn the
scrutiny to Gore, whose position on gun issues has changed since
his first years in Congress. ``At the same time that I was doing
that, casting those votes, Al Gore was receiving an A rating from
the National Rifle Association,'' Cheney said. ``He was pro-gun and
anti-gun-control.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his votes against creating the Department of Education
and against spending on Head Start, Cheney cautioned against the
assumption ``that anything that's got the word `education' on it is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look at the substance of it,'' he said. ``You've
got to analyze the legislation. The fact of the matter is that
education is primarily a state and local responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also answered questions about a Republican fund-raising
brochure from 1992 that had a picture of him as defense secretary
and promised large contributors the right to attend unspecified
government briefings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do any fund-raisers in the Pentagon,'' he said.
``Never did. I did brief people from time to time, but as a general
rule we stayed out of partisan politics in the Pentagon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
