<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
 
REPUBLICAN PUSH TO SHUFFLE PRIMARY CALENDAR CLEARS FIRST HURDLE By
ADAM CLYMER   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican National Committee voted on
Thursday to make the presidential nominating season last until May
by requiring big states to hold their primaries last. But the plan
faces a stiff fight in the national convention's rules committee on
Friday and perhaps on the convention floor next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's vote was 92-55. Most of the opposition came from big
states, like New York, California and Illinois, which would be
permitted to hold primaries or caucuses no earlier than the first
Tuesday in May. And while each state has three votes on the
national committee, and two on the rules committee, the bigger
states have more votes in the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argued that the new system, in which a majority of
delegates would be elected in May, would allow Republicans in all
states to cast votes that mattered. This year the nominations of
both major parties were settled in March, before many states had
voted.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Blackwell, a national committeeman from Virginia, argued
that if the party did nothing, states would continue to move their
primaries to the earliest possible date. That, he said, would
create a national primary, which could be won only by someone with
enough money to campaign everywhere at once, or by someone
``beloved by the media'' and favored with magazine covers and
television interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents argued that coming late would deprive them of
influence, and also warned that Democratic governors and
Democratic-controlled legislatures would refuse to shift primary
dates, thus forcing Republicans either to hold caucuses or to pay
for their own primaries. John Fleischman, executive director of
California's Republican Party, said this would cost the party $15
million to $20 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters like Richard Forsten, general counsel of the Delaware
party, argued that with the flexibility that the proposed rule
would give the Republican National Committee, such problems would
be worked out amicably. Though he did not mention it, the
Democratic National Committee has the authority to change
delegate-selection rules _ including primary dates _ between
elections and to grant waivers to states that want to break them.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican proposal's comparable flexibility, which its
advocates said was essential to make it work, runs counter to
Republican tradition, in which the rules are set once every four
years, at the national convention. And the idea of changing that
will stir hostility in the convention's rules committee.
</P>
<P>
   However the rules committee decides, the vote is likely to be
close enough for the losing side to take the issue to the floor, a
step that would require the signatures of 27 of the committee's 107
members. Both Fleischman, opposing the plan, and Tom Sansonetti of
Wyoming, chairman of the national committee's rules panel, which
produced it, said on Thursday that they were ready to go to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   That could be forestalled by the presidential campaign of Gov.
George W. Bush, which has been structuring the convention to make
it free of controversy. But the spectacle of politicians' arguing
about political calendars, rather than something so emotional as
abortion, might not seem harmful, especially if it took place on
Monday morning, when only a couple of cable networks were covering
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has had nothing to say about the proposal, although
recently his aides have said he has some ``concerns'' about it. Ari
Fleischer, a Bush campaign spokesman, said in Austin on Thursday
that ``he has no position on it.'' But Charles Black Jr., a veteran
Republican consultant in Washington who is an adviser to the
campaign, said he and several other advisers, acting on their own,
were trying to build opposition to the plan. Black said that
without any sign that Democrats would cooperate, adoption of the
proposal could let them pick their nominee by March and start
building campaign donations while Republicans continue to contest
their nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT &LR;      07-27 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMPTON GIVES BULLPEN A REST AND METS A SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Between games of a doubleheader Thursday, Pat Mahomes
asked Mike Hampton if Hampton was going to pitch nine innings.
Hampton, the Mets left-hander, said he would. ``He was true to his
word,'' Mahomes said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes had just thrown 4 2/3 innings, a season high for a New
York Mets reliever, but his effort had not prevented manager Bobby
Valentine from using three other relief pitchers to secure a 9-8
victory over the Montreal Expos in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' bullpen needed a rest, and Hampton was the man to
provide it. The Mets had lost both games he started on their recent
road trip, but this was a dire situation, and that, Hampton's
teammates have found, is when their No. 1 starter is at his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's a big-game guy,'' Mahomes said. ``No matter what
happens, it seems like every time there's a big game, he steps up
and does a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was outstanding Thursday, offering the Expos his usual
assortment of sinkers down and away and cut fastballs down and in,
to pitch the Mets to a 4-3 victory, completing a sweep. Hampton had
allowed three runs (two earned) on five hits through eight innings.
With rain coming down hard and Armando Benitez warming up in the
bullpen, he fought through a difficult ninth inning to secure the
complete game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get past the eighth,'' said Hampton, who walked only
one, ``it doesn't really matter how tired you are. Adrenaline will
push you another inning.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hampton knocked down a hard bouncer by Milton Bradley and
threw to first for the game's final out _ three batters after a
diving stop by Edgardo Alfonzo for the inning's first out _ it
concluded a bizarre day at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A nervous Grant Roberts was overwhelmed in his major league
debut, lasting only 1 1/3 innings and giving up six earned runs on
six hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Derek Bell left the first game when a ball smashed
off his chin in right field, then returned for the second game with
three stitches, only to be removed in the fifth inning when he felt
light-headed and sick. Shortstop Melvin Mora left the first game
when a ground ball struck his right index finger, cracking it open
and causing him to miss the second game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and the Expos combined for nine errors that did not
include two dropped pop-ups that were not scored errors. Third
baseman Lenny Harris had three of those errors in the second game,
but made up for it with a home run that took one hop and bounced
over the back wall of the right-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a minute I thought I was Robin Ventura, because I wasn't
making any errors,'' said Harris, who had only one error as
Ventura's replacement at third base before Thursday. ``Then I got
back to reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are still waiting for Benny Agbayani to do the same.
They continue to explore options for a more proven bat to put in
the everyday lineup, and Agbayani does not know if he will still
have a spot in the lineup or on the team after Monday's nonwaiver
trading deadline. Meanwhile, he continues to produce, going 4 for 5
in the first game and singling in the Mets' three-run rally in the
second inning of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani admitted the Mets were not optimistic coming off the
field after the top of the first inning of the first game. Roberts,
who walked the first two hitters and allowed hits to three of the
next four, had thrown 41 pitches in putting the Mets in a 4-0 hole.
Bell, a .300 hitter, had left the game, and Mike Piazza was resting
in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were probably thinking, `Aw, this is going to be a long day
_ what a way to start a game off, like this,''' Agbayani said.
``But you've got to play all nine innings to find out what's going
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and the bases loaded in the first inning, Agbayani
doubled to the base of the wall in left field, driving in two runs
to cut the Expos' lead in half. Montreal went ahead by 7-2 in the
second, but then Mahomes was on his way, blanking the Expos through
the sixth. By the time Turk Wendell came on for the seventh, the
Mets had closed to within one run of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   They tied it, then allowed the Expos to go ahead, 8-7. But with
two outs in the eighth, Joe McEwing doubled, Alfonzo walked and
Todd Zeile singled in the tying run. Facing the left-hander Steve
Kline, the left-handed-batting Matt Franco rapped the go-ahead
single to right, his third hit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine usually does not let Franco hit against left-handers;
Franco was 0 for 7 against lefties last year and 1 for 6 this
season. If the Mets had been trailing, Valentine said, he would
have brought his only remaining position player, Piazza, off the
bench. Catcher Todd Pratt then would have shifted to the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine let Franco hit, and Franco rewarded him, stroking
a 2-1 fastball to right for the decisive single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that's one thing in baseball that's kind of
overrated,'' Franco said. ``A guy like Randy Johnson's tough on
lefties, but he's tough on everybody. There's a lot of left-handers
in the league that can hit lefties.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco was back on the bench for the second game, but the Mets
still got most of their production from players not used to the
spotlight. Alfonzo and Piazza were 0 for 10 in the doubleheader,
but Agbayani, Harris and Jay Payton all had hits in both games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the entire team to win as many games as we need to
win,'' Valentine said. ``We've been relying heavily on Mike and
Fonzie, and tonight it worked without their offensive
contributions.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
