<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ROCKIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS OUTSLUG ROCKIES, 16-11
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Adrian Beltre hit a grand slam and had a career-high
six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but shortstop Alex Cora, who had one RBI in a month and
seven on the season, hit two homers, including a 396-foot,
three-run shot to the opposite field, and drove in a career-high
five runs.
</P>
<P>
   Guess where the Dodgers played?
</P>
<P>
   Correct. The only place such acts could take place, but
fortunately for the Dodgers, their two guys at the bottom of the
lineup pounded Colorado pitching for four hits apiece and drove in
11 runs as the Dodgers out-Coors Fielded the Rockies 16-11
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield had three RBI on three singles for the Dodgers
and Eric Karros had three hits. Colorado's Larry Walker went 4 for
4 with an upper-deck homer and tied a club record by scoring five
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a typical Coors day, it seems like to me, when you're
going to run out of pitchers or use everybody you have that's
available to try and win a ballgame,'' said Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson, who used five pitchers. ``It's never over until the last
guy makes an out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (54-47) tied season highs for runs and errors
(four), banged out a season-best 20 hits and won three of the four
games in the series to win for the eighth time in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, all was not splendid in the clubhouse afterward because the
expected happened. Rookie right-hander Eric Gagne, of whom the
organization thinks highly, was sent to Triple-A Albuquerque after
one of the worst outings of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Despite leads of 7-3 in the third inning and 11-7 in the fifth,
Gagne never made it far enough to qualify for the win. He allowed
eight runs (five earned) on a career-high 11 hits in 41/3 innings.
Gagne is 1-6 with a 5.74 ERA; his spot is taken by Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   It was an equally tough day for lefty Onan Masaoka, who pitched
two-thirds of an inning of perfect relief for his first win but was
also sent to Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give me 11 runs, it should be enough,'' Gagne, 24, said.
``I deserve (to go to the minors). I need some innings. We're in a
race and it's not about me, it's about the team. Valdes is going to
come in and do a good job. I didn't do the job and there's nothing
I can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gagne continues to struggle, Beltre turned things around
in this series. Not able to come up with the big hit in clutch
situations for the past month, he changed that here. Beltre had the
game-winning single Tuesday, and hit his second grand slam of the
season in the third inning Thursday as the Dodgers took a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get production out of your seventh and eighth hitter, it
makes the guys up front more relaxed so when we get guys on, now we
can wait for our pitch,'' Sheffield said. ``If he walks us, we can
wait for the next guy to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cora followed Beltre's slam with his first homer of the day to
put the Dodgers ahead 7-3. Gagne gave it all back in the third and
fourth innings, culminating with Todd Helton's two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the quintessential Coors Field game, and no sooner
had the Rockies tied it in the fourth than the Dodgers piled on
again. Beltre started it with an RBI single in the fifth, and Cora,
with one career homer coming in, hit a three-run homer off reliever
Giovanni Carrara.
</P>
<P>
   Cora added his fifth RBI with a double off the right-field wall
to cap a three-run sixth inning for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not after (Mark) McGwire, I'm after Sheff right now,''
Cora said jokingly. ``I know he's very happy because we had a talk
(Wednesday) before the game and he gave me a tip. He told me to
watch the game and try to learn, and he's one of the best hitters
in the game. My approach was different because of that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
