<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: THE PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN AS OEDIPAL ARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWELL RAINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We don't need Dad in this race,'' George W. Bush told The
Midland Reporter-Telegram back in 1978, when he was making an
unsuccessful run for Congress and being questioned about the views
of his already famous father. But in the world of oedipal politics,
keeping dad out of the campaign can be a difficult task, as Bush
and countless other famous sons have discovered over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, American campaigns sometimes seem to resemble one of
those men's-movement fables from ``Iron John'' in which the son can
achieve full masculine power only by vanquishing the father's
ghost. As a practical matter, of course, ghosts can be easier to
deal with than a living, meddling father or public suspicions about
paternal string-pulling. American voters seem to like political
dynasties _ up to that point where the romance of father-son
continuity seems to verge on something resembling royal
entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the few traits that Bush and Vice President Al
Gore seem to have in common is the dilemma of being a famous son.
Bush probably has the harder task in containing the offstage
presence of a very lively 76-year-old former president. But Gore's
candidacy is haunted, in a way, by the golden-throated ghost of
former Sen. Albert Gore Sr., who died in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, political scions from Herman (son of Ol' Gene)
Talmadge to George Wallace Jr. have labored to avoid the appearance
of being foisted on the public. In that respect, it was probably
less than helpful when the elder Gore, asked in 1992 about his
son's presence on the Democratic national ticket, said, ``We raised
him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, the father's reputation competes with the son's
reality. Albert Gore Sr. was a famous orator. The son turns to
stone at the teleprompter. Vice President Gore is accused of
pandering. Senior lost his Senate seat rather than alter his
opposition to the Vietnam War. The father had the advantage of an
impoverished Tennessee boyhood. Albert Gore Jr. used their
Tennessee farm as a summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, Bush faces the tougher, day-to-day threat of being
miniaturized by a living ex-president. The elder Bush inflicted
unintended collateral damage at a rally before the New Hampshire
primary by referring to his son as ``this boy.'' In a subsequent
interview with The New York Times, former President Bush and his
wife, Barbara, took what appeared to be a pledge of
non-interference.
</P>
<P>
   But family discipline seemed to break down during the process of
putting Dick Cheney on the ticket. Bush acknowledged ``kibitzing''
by his father, apparently code for days of lobbying by the former
president for his secretary of defense. A fatherly call to the
elderly Texas heart surgeon Denton Cooley about Cheney's health was
also made public.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush, in damage-control mode, said Thursday
that it was ``absolutely inaccurate'' to say he had driven the
choice of Cheney. But in fact the whole process took on a very
retro, Texas-elite, Bush-senior look. The psychological signal was
even more damaging, as if by pushing Cheney, the former president
was saying, Don't worry: when my son makes decisions, adults will
be in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Were John F. Kennedy alive, he could certainly identify with the
problem of paternal-assistance overload. Joseph P. Kennedy Sr.'s
bootlegger image and his reputation for being soft on Nazi Germany
made it essential to keep him in the background. But the old man's
public ambition to put a son in the White House and the jokes about
his not paying for a single vote more than necessary made that a
hard task. Indeed, the elder Kennedy's triumphal behavior at JFK's
inaugural was enough to make one wonder whose day it was _ at least
in Joseph Kennedy's mind.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fathers, there is, of course, a
counter-tradition in postwar presidential politics. Harry Truman,
Dwight Eisenhower, Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford, Jimmy Carter, Ronald
Reagan and Bill Clinton were all figures who were, in a political
sense, fatherless. Truman had made his bones in machine politics.
Eisenhower, through his war experience, entered elective combat
with the status of national father figure. It was impossible to
imagine the Supreme Allied Commander playing junior to any man,
even back in Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Johnson, Nixon and Reagan, pitied their fathers for
their weaknesses. Others, notably Carter, revered their fathers'
rectitude. Ford and Clinton were estranged by death and
circumstance from their biological fathers. All had, by the time
they ran for president, far surpassed the paternal example of
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor Gore is quite there yet. True, Gore now
outranks his father, but he is not yet perceived as having made the
step from scion to paterfamilias. That could argue for picking a
junior figure for a running mate. Bush has gone in the other
direction, putting a de facto father on the ticket at the urging of
his real father in Houston. Gov. Bush cites this as proof of his
inner security, and it may be. But he still has to worry that
voters will read it as a sign of a son not yet risen to full
autonomy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
