<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' DAT NGUYEN, COMING OFF LASER EYE SURGERY, HAS SIGHTS SET
ON STARTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Dat Nguyen's keen instincts just got
keener.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' second-year middle linebacker from Texas A&AMP;M
underwent laser eye surgery five months ago. He no longer needs to
wear contact lenses to find the ball carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: Dat Nguyen with both a ``nose'' ``and'' 20/20
vision for the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to squint to see what time it is anymore,''
saidNguyen, 24. ``I don't have to scramble to find my glasses in
the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Now with corrected vision, Nguyen can set his sights on winning
the starting middle linebacker job.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-10, the 1998 Lombardi Trophy winner has grown
accustomed to proving he's not too short to play this game.
</P>
<P>
   Randall Godfrey, the team's leading tackler last season, was
lost to free agency when he signed with the Tennessee Titans in
February. Nguyen automatically _ or so it seemed at the time _
would become Godfrey's successor after playing middle linebacker in
nickel packages as a 1999 rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to play all three downs,'' Nguyen said. ``When
you're a competitor, you never want to come off the field. I play
the game with a lot of love. But I'm still a young player, and I'm
still learning on the run. I'll do whatever I need to do to help
this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen's competition for the starting job is Barron Wortham, who
has made 55 NFL starts, including Super Bowl XXXIV for the
Tennessee Titans, and Chris Bordano, who has had 18 NFL starts with
New Orleans, including 12 starts last season.
</P>
<P>
   Wortham came to the Cowboys as a free agent from Tennessee,
following in the steps of strongside linebacker Joe Bowden. Bordano
came to the Cowboys from New Orleans in a trade for cornerback
Kevin Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie last season, Nguyen appeared in all 16 games, plus
the playoff loss to Minnesota, as a situational middle linebacker
on passing downs and a fierce tackler on special teams. His next
NFL start will be his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Dat will be able to play all three downs, without a
doubt,'' Cowboys linebackers coach George Edwards said. ``But I
also think that our having the luxury of experienced linebackers in
camp, he may not have to \Rplay all three downs\S. We'll take it
day-to-day, week-to-week, and see how things progress.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Cowboys explore their options, Nguyen keeps working to
get better at making the defensive calls, which the middle
linebacker must do, and making plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding the football and getting \Rthe ball carrier\S on the
ground is what Dat does best,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said.
``Dat's instincts are what separate him from the pack ... \Rand\S
I'm comfortable with him in there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards added: ``When the lights are on, Dat plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen is learning to be more of a conformist and play within
the scheme in the Cowboys' standard packages that are used on first
and second down. Last season, he seemed better suited for the
nickel packages, which allowed him to do what he does best: read
and react, find a way to make a play.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen shows up better in games than in practice drills. But he
still needs to use the Cowboys' five preseason games to nail down
the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I 100 percent comfortable at middle linebacker?'' Campo
asked. ``No, because we don't know 100 percent about the position.
We have a complete situation there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, born in a refugee camp in Arkansas to parents who left
Vietnam just before the end of the Vietnam War, knows something
about challenges and overcoming long odds. He's the only
Vietnamese-American player in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel you always have to prove yourself,'' Nguyen said. ``In
football, you have to want to get better every day. I know when I
make a mistake now before I've been told. I'm just more
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I'm fitting in more ... although I guess I still
stick out a little bit because I'm the only Asian guy out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he wants to be the only Cowboys' starting middle linebacker
when the season begins Sept. 3 against Philadelphia.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
