<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ATTACKS LAZIO'S TIES TO DISSIDENT AIDS GROUP
</HEADLINE>
  By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attacking her opponent as ``out of touch with the
mainstream,'' Hillary Rodham Clinton seemed to take some delight
Thursday in pointing to Rep. Rick Lazio's links to a dissident band
of scientists who contend that the human immunodeficiency virus
does not cause AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican candidate for Senate, wrote to federal
health officials earlier this year on behalf of the Group for the
Scientific Reappraisal of HIV/AIDS. The group is connected to two
scientists, Peter Deusberg and David Resnick, to whom the South
African president, Thabo Mbeki, also apparently turned earlier this
year in questioning the causes of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign aides said Thursday that he wrote to officials
with the Health and Human Services Department and the National
Institutes of Health on behalf of a constituent, who belonged to
the group. Molly Fullington, a spokeswoman for the Lazio campaign,
said the group was trying to secure federal financing to conduct
research on ``the underlying causes of AIDS and to fund holistic
approaches to treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she could not comment on whether Lazio knew of the
group's disputed belief. But, she said, ``Rick Lazio does not hold
their view that HIV does not cause AIDS,'' adding that ``he
believes it does.''
</P>
<P>
   The report of Lazio's advocacy of the dissident AIDS group was
first published Thursday in The New York Post. Clinton seized on
the report at a news conference to announce endorsements from two
gay and lesbian groups, the Human Rights Campaign and Empire State
Pride Agenda. ``It was a further piece of evidence as to why my
opponent doesn't get it,'' she said, urging him to engage in
debates statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the two organizations that announced their
support pointed to her advocacy of issues important to gay and
lesbian voters, from her support of hate-crimes laws to backing the
right of gay couples to be foster and adoptive parents. Clinton,
her backers said, has also supported the right of openly gay people
to serve in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a close call,'' Tim Sweeney, executive director of
Empire State Pride Agenda said in announcing his endorsement of
Clinton. ``He's not even Al D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   The gay community split over the question of D'Amato in the last
Senate race in New York, with the Human Rights Campaign backing
D'Amato over his Democratic opponent, Charles Schumer. But this
time, officials with the Human Rights Campaign said, there was no
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Lazio has had ample opportunity to support our issues,''
said the group's executive director, Elizabeth Birch. ``And time
and time again, he has come up short or come up empty.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton's invitation to debate, Lazio's aides welcomed
it. Michael Marr, a spokesman, described it as an opportunity to
highlight ``the difference between the candidate who has a real
record of legislative achievement and a candidate who has no such
record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-SAUTET-NYT &LR;      07-27 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SAUTET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAUDE SAUTET, 76, NOTED FRENCH FILM DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Claude Sautet, an award-winning director whose films focused on
the lives of the bourgeoisie, died July 22 in Paris. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was liver cancer, his producer, Alain Sarde, told
Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to choose subjects or anecdotes, if you will, that
are quite simple, to develop them simply, to film them simply and
to find multiple levels in relationships,'' he said in a 1996
interview with The Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   Sautet spent the early part of his career working in television
and as a screenwriter and script doctor. He first drew critical
attention as a director with ``Les Choses de la Vie'' (``The Things
of Life'') in 1969, a tragicomedy about a romantic triangle, with
Michel Piccoli and Romy Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   He himself acted in that film and several others, including
``Cesar and Rosalie'' (1972), about a divorced woman who becomes
involved with a wealthy man and a young artist.
</P>
<P>
   His credits also included ``Vincent, Francois, Paul and the
Others'' (1974); ``Une Histoire Simple'' (``A Simple Story''), with
Schneider, which was one of the nominees for the 1980 Oscar for
best foreign film; and ``Quelques Jours Avec Moi'' (``A Few Days
With Me'') in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Un Coeur en Hiver'' (``A Heart in Winter''), released in the
United States in 1993, was the story of a violin repairer (Daniel
Auteuil) who is better at his work than at his relationships with
people _ including a beautiful young violinist (Emmanuelle Beart)
with whom he falls in love. Sautet's film was praised by Janet
Maslin in The New York Times as ``a coolly elegant romance.'' The
film brought him a Cesar, the French equivalent of an Oscar, in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   He won another Cesar for his last film, ``Nelly and Monsieur
Arnaud'' (1996), with Beart and Michel Serrault, the story of a
young woman and her relationship with the reclusive elderly man who
unexpectedly chooses to become her benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Montrouge, a suburb of Paris, on Feb. 23, 1924, Sautet
first sought a career as a painter and sculptor before enrolling in
film school in Paris. He worked at a series of jobs, writing music
criticism and even serving as warden of a school for juvenile
delinquents, before finding work as a script doctor and directorial
assistant. His early efforts included several gangster films.
</P>
<P>
   Sautet said that the heart of his films, which often featured a
group of people supporting the main character, was drawn from, as
The Times of London put it, ``childhood experiences in an extended
family with a cafe as the center of community life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I also discovered the secret of loneliness of
people, of being lonely in a crowd,'' he said in the interview.
``One of the classic subjects is solitude.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I always try to create an imbalance, an edge to
friendship. You never know what's going to trigger the next moment.
My real subject is always uncertainty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
