<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FORD'S CLEAN AIR BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 28:
</P>
<P>
   The various industries responsible for much of the country's air
pollution _ the oil companies, the automakers, the big utilities _
have usually resisted federal clean air regulations, routinely
overestimating the costs of the regulations while underestimating
the ability of their engineers to satisfy them. In the 30 years
since the passage of the Clean Air Act, industry has rarely been
out in front of government.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, Ford Motor Co. reversed this paradigm with
the announcement that it would increase the average fuel economy of
its sport utility vehicles by 25 percent over the next five years.
It did so even though Congress recently rejected yet another effort
by environmentalists to tighten up fuel economy standards.
</P>
<P>
   The company's move deserves applause from anyone who worries
about carbon dioxide, a so-called greenhouse gas that is thought to
be a major contributor to global warming. Cars and trucks are
responsible for about one-third of the carbon dioxide produced in
the United States, and SUVs are responsible for a big chunk of
that. SUVs, pickup trucks and vans now account for half the
vehicles sold in America. This has been a boon for Detroit but not
for cleaner air, mainly because SUVs, which are officially classed
as light trucks, have been allowed to emit up to three times as
much pollution per mile as standard cars. They also consume about
one-third to one-half more fuel than ordinary cars.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Environmental Protection Agency began a crackdown
on SUVs, using the so-called tailpipe standards authorized by the
Clean Air Act. It issued new rules that will require SUVs to meet
the same emission standards that apply to ordinary cars and govern
pollutants like nitrogen oxide, a precursor to urban smog. At the
same time, the EPA required the oil companies to produce a
cleaner-burning gasoline to increase the efficiency of a car's
catalytic converter, the device that strips most pollutants from
auto exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   But the catalytic converter does nothing to decrease emissions
of carbon dioxide, the main greenhouse gas. The only way to reduce
carbon dioxide, short of installing an engine that does not use
fossil fuels, is to increase fuel efficiency. That is what Ford's
new strategy for its SUVs would do.
</P>
<P>
   While committing itself to more fuel-efficient SUVs, the company
remains opposed, along with other automakers, to legislative
efforts to increase fuel economy standards generally. These
standards have not significantly changed in nearly 20 years. Ford's
answer to what some see as an inconsistency is that it opposes
top-down regulation but will respond to consumer-driven market
forces. Ford says it is convinced that consumers are ready to
sacrifice a modest amount of engine power and size in exchange for
a cleaner SUV. It also argues that it has the technology to
increase the fuel economy of SUVs without increasing prices _ the
implication being that it will be able to do the same for other
cars if allowed to proceed at its own pace.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists on the whole were delighted. They noted that
if Ford can build SUVs that yield much better mileage per gallon,
other companies are sure to follow. If they do, William C. Ford
Jr., Ford's chairman and the great-grandson of Henry Ford, will
further solidify his reputation as the most adventurous executive
in an industry not previously known for environmental stewardship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
