<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ALM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALVIN ALM, 63, A LEADER IN ENVIRONMENTAL POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Colo.)   By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alvin L. Alm, a businessman and senior government
official who helped create environmental and energy policy in
Republican and Democratic administrations for four decades, died
July 24 at Georgetown University Hospital in Washington. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Alm was stricken at his home in nearby Falls Church, Va.,
apparently with heart failure, said Allen Moore, a colleague at
Chambers Associates, a public policy consulting firm where Alm was
president.
</P>
<P>
   As an expert in budgeting, economics, regulation and the other
fine details of environmental policy, Alm operated just under the
bureaucratic rank where public service translates into renown.
Although virtually every policy- maker in Alm's field knew of his
work, the influence of the jobs he held, like assistant secretary
of energy for environmental management and deputy administrator of
the Environmental Protection Agency, far exceeded his public name
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Alm spoke lightly of his many moves into and out of government,
once saying, ``I have to confess I am a recidivist.'' One reason he
came and went was that the most powerful figures in the federal
government called upon him at critical moments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when the EPA was in crisis during the Reagan
administration, with Administrator Anne Gorsuch's resignation under
pressure for her handling of the Superfund and other programs, Alm
returned for a second stint at the agency under William D.
Ruckelshaus, whom President Ronald Reagan had called back to
salvage the EPA's bruised reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Leroy Alm was born in Denver, graduated from the
University of Denver in 1960 and earned a master's degree in public
administration from the Maxwell Graduate School at Syracuse
University.
</P>
<P>
   He worked on environmental matters in the Washington bureaucracy
for several years and by 1970, when the modern environmental
movement reached full flower, held a crucial post as staff director
of the newly created White House Council on Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   He helped develop the landmark Clean Water Act of 1972 and moved
to the EPA, then in its infancy, as assistant manager for planning
and management. There, from 1973 to 1977, he helped devise the
system of water pollution permits that put the law into force.
</P>
<P>
   During the energy crisis of the late 1970s, he worked on energy
policy for the Carter administration and moved to the Energy
Department for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his long career, Alm took on some of the most
intractable of problems. His most recent tour in government was
from 1996 to 1998, as President Clinton's assistant secretary of
energy in charge of cleaning up the nation's nuclear weapons
complex, overseeing a program of about $6 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Outside government, he was chairman and chief executive of
Thermal Analytical Corp., an environmental testing concern, from
1985 to 1987; chief executive of another technical consulting
company, Alliance Technologies Corp., from 1987 to 1989; and senior
vice president of yet another, Science Applications International
Corp., from 1989 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s he was at the John F. Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard as a lecturer and head of a research program.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to the former Ronnie Elwell ended in divorce. He is
survived by a daughter, Jessica Alm of Boston; a sister, Carol
Birza of Denver; and his companion, Mary Clark of Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000727.0396 </DOCNO>
