<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-27 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5277 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-2NDLD-WRI     07-27 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ARISE ABOUT PROCESS OF BUSH CHOOSING CHENEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., N.Y., Pa.)   (SUBS 7th graf to clarify; ADDS 18th graf to 2nd take with Powell
turning Bush down on May 25)  
 (Eds: Additional information for this article was contributed by
ABC News under a joint reporting agreement between the network and
The Times.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Little more than two weeks ago, Dick Cheney
visited Sen. Bill Frist of Tennessee in his office on Capitol Hill,
and Frist made his pitch, explaining why his experience as a heart
surgeon who had managed life-and-death situations made him the
right man to accompany Gov. George W. Bush along the inevitably
rocky, tense road to Election Day and perhaps into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney apeared to listen intently. It was his job to supervise
the Texas governor's hunt for a running mate, and he had arranged
to meet Frist.
</P>
<P>
   Within several days, Bush flew to the Northeast and met twice
with Gov. George Pataki of New York, discussing a possible place
for Pataki on the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   For all this tantalizing activity, it now appears that Cheney
had at the time already emerged as a leading candidate _ and
perhaps the leading candidate _ for the slot he had been assigned
to help fill. Cheney and Bush had discussed the possibility July 3
at Bush's ranch near Crawford, about 90 miles north of here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cheney's own candidacy was moving along a track so secret
that some of the other politicians on the list of seemingly serious
prospects had no idea that Bush was settling on Cheney until they
learned it from newspaper and television reports less than 72 hours
before Bush formally announced his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Republicans who discussed the vice-presidential
selection with Bush over the past two weeks, among them Gov. Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania, said that the Texas governor had not let on
that he was considering the head of his search committee for the
post. He also did not inquire about how such a selection might
play, even as he reviewed with them the qualifications of other
potential candidates on his list.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the choice of Cheney was all but assured in the final
days of frenzied speculation among news organizations, days that
yielded some entirely unfounded reports: that Sen. John McCain of
Arizona might be a last-minute addition to Bush's short list; that
Bush was making a final, hopeful approach to Gen. Colin Powell.
Bush was really just running Cheney through his mind one last time.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is an immensely respected political veteran, and his
selection elicited praise from many Republicans. But the unusual
way in which the former defense secretary arrived at Bush's side at
a news conference here on Tuesday to announce the vice-presidential
selection has stirred concern among some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They have noted with alarm the attacks Democrats were able to
quickly muster on Cheney's conservative voting record in Congress,
and questioned whether the man in charge of screening the other
candidates for the job could possibly have received as thorough a
screening himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did they vet?'' a senior Republican strategist with
experience in national campaigns asked Thursday. ``That he went to
college? They really got their ears pinned back.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Cheney's ties to former President George Bush have
provoked renewed speculation about the influence of Bush's father
on his son's presidential campaign. In a telephone interview
Thursday that represented his first public comments on the search
process, President Bush said: ``What I see emerging is that the old
guy drove the choice. That is absolutely inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that he spoke regularly with his son about
the search and gave his opinions on various candidates, including
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   And when he was asked if he spoke directly to Cheney and urged
him to think about taking the job, Bush said, ``I cannot reveal
whether I did or didn't. Not wanting to obfuscate, but put this
down to obfuscation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please respect my age _ 76,'' he continued. ``I'm forgetful.''
Asked if that meant that he had forgotten whether he spoke with
Cheney, his response suggested that the two men had talked, perhaps
because Cheney was soliciting opinions about vice presidential
contenders and the former president knew many of these people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into what I talked to Dick Cheney or
anybody else about,'' President Bush said. ``You've got to put it
in the context of what Dick Cheney was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his son's advisers, the review of Cheney's
credentials and background materials was conducted somewhat outside
of the process that Cheney had established for the rest of the
field, and it proceeded at a much speedier pace. Within minutes
after Cheney's selection was announced on Tuesday, Democrats
produced a trove of extremely conservative votes from Cheney's
decade in Congress, and the barrage of questions about his record
that hit Cheney and the Bush campaign seemed to take them at least
partly by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during an interview on ABC's ``Good Morning America''
Thursday about several votes that he cast in opposition to gun
control, Cheney said, ``Well, I'd have to go back and dig into that
in detail.'' In a previous interview on CNN's ``Larry King Live,''
Cheney seemed a bit surprised by similar questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and his aides have declined to provide any
more than rudimentary details about the vetting of vice
presidential prospects, including Cheney, but said that all of them
had been carefully noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I knew his votes,'' Bush said during a brief news
conference at the governor's mansion here Thursday. ``But I also
know his record. What do you expect? I'm running against people who
all they do is spend time tearing people down. And they're going to
give it their level best trying to tear Dick Cheney down, but
they're not going to be able to do so.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush also suggested that most Americans already knew and
respected Cheney as a result of his role as defense secretary
during the Persian Gulf War. ``Secretary Cheney brought people
together and helped to win a war, which stands in stark contrast
with Vice President Al Gore, who tens to divide people to create
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his aides, Bush declined to be interviewed for this
article. Cheney did not respond to several requests for an
interview about the search process that were made through Bush's
aides.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with Republicans who spoke with Cheney and Bush
these past few weeks, including a number of men who were told they
were on the short list of potential vice presidential candidates,
suggest that they underwent a process that was different then the
one Cheney endured. It is these differences that account for the
murmurs of concern among some Republicans who have watched Cheney's
first few turbulent days as a candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   While Cheney took charge of reviewing financial histories and
interviewing candidates, Bush himself attended to that chore in
Cheney's case. While Cheney researched the voting records of the
other vice presidential prospects, the task of assessing Cheney's
political past fell to Joe Allbaugh, the campaign manager.
(Allbaugh also did not return a call for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   While other candidates began submitting their voluminous paper
work in mid-May, in some cases shipping boxes of documents to
Cheney, the examination of Cheney apparently began little more than
a week before Bush called him and offered him the job.
</P>
<P>
   And while at least 11 Republicans filled out an extraordinarily
detailed, 83-question form, including inquiries ranging from
plagiarism to recreational drug use, Bush's senior advisers were
unable to say if Cheney had taken the same formal step, though they
noted that Cheney's background had been reviewed when he was named
secretary of defense under President Bush. ``Secretary Cheney told
me he subjected himself to the same kind of scrutiny,'' Karen P.
Hughes, the campaign spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   But unexplained oddities about the vetting of Cheney lingered.
According to one Republican official, the name of his daughter,
Elizabeth Cheney, a lawyer, was on the return address of the
materials that another candidate received, and she helped place
calls late last week to round up the weekend phone numbers of other
vice presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Elizabeth Cheney's possible role in helping to
screen candidates, including her father, Hughes said that except
for Dick Cheney, Bush and Allbaugh, ``I am not able to discuss
others who were involved in the vetting process.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney said on ``Good Morning America'' that there was no
cause for concern about the unusual way in which he came to be
selected. Referring to Bush, he said: ``The fact of the matter is
that we spent a lot of time _ and again, remember my original
advice to him was, you know, we're going to find you a great
candidate, but I'd rather not be a candidate myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as we went through the process in terms of talking about
my health and my record and my business career and so forth, we
reviewed all those things between the two of us as we went forward
and before we made the decision, before he made the decision that
he wanted me to be a candidate,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the campaign of Vice President Al Gore has seemed
genuinely invigorated by the news of Cheney's selection. Aides to
the vice president were churning out reams of documents about
Cheney's legislative background literally from the moment Bush
concluded the formal announcement of Cheney's selection.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of what is arguably the most important political
decision Bush has made in his presidential campaign to date may
never be known. The lack of information has prompted questions
among some some Republicans about whether many of the politicians
whose names were publicly floated as possible running mates for
Bush were ever in serious contention.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge said in an interview that he had told aides on July 5 that
he did not want to be considered for the race; nonetheless, Bush
himself continued to encourage speculation that he was considering
Ridge when he campaigned with the Pennsylvania governor in
Pittsburgh a week later. Similarly, by the time Bush met with
Pataki on July 14 _ an encounter that his aides readily confirmed _
Cheney, who has a history of heart attacks, had completed a medical
examination in New York and reported to Bush that he had been given
a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ridge and Pataki are supporters of abortion rights, unlike
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who is a staunch opponent of abortion, had been pitching
in with the governor's presidential campaign from the beginning.
Last year, he helped Bush assemble the team of foreign policy
advisers for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it was natural that in mid-March, after Bush
effectively secured the Republican presidential nomination, he
asked Cheney if he wanted to be considered as a possible running
mate. Cheney said no, but, weeks later, agreed to supervise the
search process.
</P>
<P>
   Under his guidance, hundreds of letters were sent to Republican
officials to get their advice. At least 11 prospective candidates
received questionnaires and requests for documents.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who had been mentioned as potentially the
strongest running mate Bush could chose, Powell, explicitly told
Bush that he did not want the job. He did so during a private
moment with the governor on May 25, when Bush held a ceremony here
pledging support for Powell's national youth-mentoring program, an
aide to Powell said this week. Bush and his senior advisers never
raised the subject with Powell again, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was no hint yet that Cheney's professed resistance
to considering the job was softening, Bush's advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   But on June 27, just six days before Cheney visited Bush's ranch
and indicated a possible willingness to be Bush's running mate, his
name popped up during a gathering of former members of his father's
presidential administration at the Bush family compound in
Kennebunkport, Maine. Those present included President Bush; his
former national security adviser, Brent Scowcroft, and his former
director of presidential personnel, Chase Untermeyer.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer recalled that as these men and others sat around a
table on the back porch, Bush asked in a lighthearted manner who
they thought should be his son's vice presidential pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost in the sense of a parlor game, as if he were
asking, ``Who do you think will win the Masters?''' Untermeyer said
in one of two telephone interviews this week. He said the name that
came up most often was Ridge's.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Untermeyer said, someone brought up Cheney's
name, and someone else said he was not interested. According to
Untermeyer, Scowcroft then said that Cheney had recently indicated
to him that he might be willing to take the job after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression was that President Bush was very interested to
hear that and took it aboard as if it was an important fact to
know,'' Untermeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But Scowcroft and President Bush both made telephone calls to a
reporter Thursday to dispute the accuracy of that account.
Scowcroft said that before the Kennebunkport meeting, he had run
into Cheney and teased him about being the perfect vice
presidential prospect. Scowcroft said that he merely shared that
story with President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush said that he did not press the idea of Cheney on
his son. ``Am I high on Cheney?,'' the former president said.
``Absolutely. Was I high on others? Absolutely. Did I talk to
George when he called to go over stuff? Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Less then a week later, Bush revisited Cheney's initial
objections with him at the ranch, and Cheney began to budge.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11th, Hughes said, he got his medical examination. On
July 15 he and Bush informed Bush's senior advisers that he was in
the running, and his vetting began, according to Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 days later, the job was his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
