<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE LOSES ANOTHER ONE AS YANKEES FALL TO TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ There was no mistaking the dejection on David
Cone's face Thursday night, his mouth turned down, lips pursed,
sadness weighing on his eyes like anvils. It was the look of
helplessness, and it was the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's reputation is built on dominance, and the Minnesota Twins
were burying him. He is known for stubborn relentlessness, and as
Cone worked deeper into trouble, defeat must have felt inevitable
to him, on the eve of the three-month anniversary of his last
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Cone lost again, was pounded again, allowing nine hits, five
walks and eight runs in five-plus innings Thursday night, and he
remained in that long only because manager Joe Torre tried to wait
for the New York Yankees to come back and rescue the veteran
pitcher from the losing streak. But they were defeated, 9-3, their
four-game winning streak ending as Cone's won-lost record fell to
1-10, and it would seem that his place in the team's rotation is in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has been an ace pitcher most of his career, embracing the
responsibility that this entails, and there is no getting around
the fact that his troubles are dragging down the team. In Cone's
last 12 starts, the Yankees are 0-12; they are 32-19 in games
started by others during that same span.
</P>
<P>
   Only one pitcher in club history has made more starts with only
one victory to show for it: Fritz Peterson, who was 1-10 after 22
starts in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle, Andy Pettitte and Roger Clemens are permanent
members of the five-man rotation. Orlando Hernandez is working his
way back from the disabled list. Dwight Gooden is 3-0 with a 2.16
earned run average in three starts. The Yankees are entertaining
the idea of trading for another starting pitcher, in San Diego's
Matt Clement.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is scheduled to pitch again on Wednesday if nothing
changes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cone, 37, extracted some hope from his previous defeat. He felt
good about an adjustment he made to his pitching mechanics: he held
his hands near his right hip in the middle of his windup, rather
than raising his hands and then dropping them before throwing; this
made his motion more compact and seemed to help his control against
Tampa Bay in a game last Saturday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was relieved after six innings of that game, having thrown
just 94 pitches, and Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching coach, knew Cone
was angry about this. But Cone remained mute about that decision,
realizing he was not pitching well enough to complain, and focused
on his next start. Cone flipped the ball to Stottlemyre after
finishing his warm-ups Thursday night, and Stottlemyre patted him
on the shoulder. ``Let's go,'' Stottlemyre said, and Cone nodded.
</P>
<P>
   His fourth pitch of the game was smacked down the left-field
line for a double by Denny Hocking; Cristian Guzman bounced Cone's
ninth pitch for a single, to score Hocking. Cone tries to analyze
his starts as objectively as possible and can be brutally honest
with himself, to the point where it probably hurts him; Cone is not
superstitious, does not blame fate. Still, he cannot comprehend why
trouble hits him in speed-of-light fashion, why it seems he cannot
get away with any mistakes, the way other pitchers do. Cone stops
short of saying it is bad luck, but he wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked Matt Lawton on four pitches, and Ron Coomer singled
home the Twins' second run. Cone, rushing in his delivery, fell
behind David Ortiz, three balls and no strikes, and walked him.
Bases loaded, still nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   He was missing badly by now, his fastball and slider straying,
and when he threw two balls out of the strike zone to Corey Koskie
_ 2-0 _ the phone in the Yankees' bullpen rang and Jason Grimsley
started warming up.
</P>
<P>
   There were two fly balls, and another run scored. Jacque Jones,
the Twins' No. 8 hitter, stepped out of the batter's box a couple
of times and Cone appeared to be incensed by this; after Jones
struck out to end the inning, Cone walked over and spoke to the
umpire Gregory Gibson pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   Cone threw 36 pitches in that first inning, 21 in the second, a
staggering toll for a pitcher rarely given a chance to throw more
than 100 pitches anymore. He got through the third inning easily,
retired the first hitter in the fourth and appeared to gather some
sort of rhythm, sometimes peeking at the radar gun readings posted
on the face of the upper deck in left field. His fastball was
hitting 88 mph. Cone dropped his arm angle to throw a rare sidearm
slider to Chad Moeller, Minnesota's ninth-place hitter: a sliver of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone went on to walk Moeller. He walked Hocking, as well,
and when Lawton laced a breaking ball into the left-field corner,
the bullpen coach Tony Cloninger reached down and held his hand on
the bullpen phone, anticipating the call that came a second later,
after both of Minnesota's runners scored.
</P>
<P>
   Cone glanced at the bullpen as he departed the mound at the end
of the fourth, to see if somebody was warming up to relieve him.
Minnesota led, 5-0, but when the Yankees scored three runs in the
top of the fifth, Torre stayed with Cone; he believes that if only
Cone can end his losing streak, then at least bits of his old
confidence will be restored.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked Ortiz to lead off the bottom of the fifth, Grimsley
got up for the third time and sat down for the third time when Cone
held the Twins scoreless in the half-inning. But Cone's pitch count
was 106 after five innings, and when Jones singled to lead off the
sixth, Grimsley got up one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Moeller lifted a high pop with the runner moving, and there was
confusion between second baseman Jose Vizcaino and left fielder
Paul O'Neill and the ball fell between them. Hocking hit a double
and the runners charged around the bases. That was all. The
Yankees' infielders gathered around Cone at the mound. Not one
appeared to say anything before Cone handed the ball to Torre.
</P>
</TEXT>
