<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-EXECUTE-DNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNA TESTS BEING SPONSORED IN CASE THAT LED TO EXECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Seeking to learn if an innocent man was put to death
four years ago, The Boston Globe and three other news organizations
said this week that they would underwrite new DNA tests on evidence
from a 1981 Georgia murder case.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Ellis Wayne Felker, was executed in 1996 for the rape
and murder of a 19-year-old college student, Evelyn Joy Ludlam. If
DNA tests prove his innocence, it would be the first time the
technology exonerated an inmate who had been put to death.
</P>
<P>
   DNA evidence has cleared eight convicts awaiting execution, and
next week in Texas a man sentenced to 99 years in prison for the
rape of a 16-year-old girl is likely be pardoned on the strength of
new DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that only DNA testimony with its reliability could
prove that a person was wrongfully executed,'' said Ben Bradlee
Jr., The Globe's deputy managing editor for projects. ``This has
never been tested, but if it could be proven, it would
significantly alter the terms of the death-penalty debate in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   A Georgia judge cleared the way for the investigation earlier
this month, when he agreed to turn over evidence from Felker's case
to The Globe. After the decision, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
joined the Globe in offering to pay for the DNA tests, and The
Macon Telegraph and CBS's ``60 Minutes'' news magazine are now
petitioning to gain access to the evidence. The cost of the tests
has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Scheck, co-director of the Innocence Project, an advocacy
group at the Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law at Yeshiva
University in New York that assists inmates protesting their
innocence, said this was the first instance of a court granting the
public access to evidence for DNA testing after the inmate's
execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all other cases, they've denied access because they were
afraid it would prove there was an unlawful execution,'' Scheck
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly R. Burke, the district attorney in Houston County, where
Felker's case was originally tried, opposed the move, saying: ``If
I thought I had a legal basis to stand on, I'd be fighting this. I
think it's a colossal waste of time. I believe the DNA evidence is
going to have degraded such that when it gets to the lab, the
scientists are going to look at it and say, `Sorry, we can't test
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``What proved Wayne Felker did it wasn't just one piece of
evidence. There were a lot of different things that went into the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Ludlam was raped and strangled, her eyes and mouth
covered with duct tape, and her body dumped in a creek, where it
lay for two weeks. Felker was convicted of the crime after
investigators found hair matching his on the victim. He was found
guilty in 1983, and sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   Felker received national attention in 1996, when the Supreme
Court heard his challenge of a law limiting the federal appeals
process for death row inmates in an effort to hasten executions.
The court ruled unanimously against him, and he was put to death
one month later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
