<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PENNEY-CEO-NYT &LR;      07-27 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNEY-CEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLED J.C. PENNEY NAMES A NEW CHAIRMAN AND CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Allen L. Questrom, who headed Federated Department
Stores for much of the 1990s and led Barneys New York Inc. out of
bankruptcy, was named chairman and chief executive of J.C. Penney
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, who have knocked three-quarters of the market value
off Penney in the last two years, pushed the stock up 16 percent,
betting that Questrom can lift the sagging fortunes of the company,
one of the nation's largest department store chains.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the company has lost focus, losing to nimbler
competitors like Kohl's and Target, and has struggled to wrest
itself from an insular and plodding culture that left too much
power in the hands of store managers. That has led to serious
inventory problems, including slow distribution of newer,
hot-selling merchandise and overstocked shelves of unpopular
products.
</P>
<P>
   Penney's chief executive, James E. Oesterreicher, who said in
May that he would resign, and Vanessa Castagna, the chief operating
officer, who was hired last year from Wal-Mart Stores, were both
considered possible successors at one point.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Questrom, 60, said that he expected to stay at
Penney for at least five years, though he is leaving Barneys New
York after just over a year. At Barneys New York, Questrom will
remain chairman and help lead a search for a new chief executive.
At Penney, he said that he planned to immerse himself in the
company's operations for a few months before letting anyone know
his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of impressions, but I hesitate to share those
until I get to talk to people,'' Questrom said. ``Little companies
are nimble, and as they get larger, they have to go back and
refocus.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they expected Questrom, who begins at Penney on
Sept. 15, to take a number of steps this year, perhaps closing
stores, announcing a major inventory write-off, or trimming the
number of vendors and brands in Penney stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best possible outcome of this company's executive
search, frankly,'' said George Strachan, an analyst at Goldman
Sachs, who raised his rating on the stock. ``He's got a lot of
charisma and is very decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Church, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, applauded
the move but said he did not expect Penney to show quick
improvement. ``I don't consider it to be tremendously undervalued,
given its earnings prospects'' in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Penney shares gained $2.375, to close at $17.25.
</P>
<P>
   At Barneys, Questrom had an unusual compensation package that
granted him about 15 percent of the company's equity, depending on
vesting and other requirements, in return for a three-year
employment contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-27-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
